//www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/sustainable-packaging/multipack-cups-made-plants</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/partnering-planet">http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/partnering-planet</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/wastewater">http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/wastewater</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/water">http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/water</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/energy">http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/energy</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/green-building">http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/green-building</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stonyfield.com/sites/default/files/attachments/green-building-scrapbook-6-12-09.pdf">http://www.stonyfield.com/sites/default/files/attachments/green-building-scrapbook-6-12-09.pdf</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1500, 'default', 134, '<h1 align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>Interface Sustainability Review</strong></span></h1>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Introduction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	Interface was founded in 1973 and is now a worldwide leader in design, production and sales of environmentally responsible modular carpet for the commercial, institutional, and residential market. It sells in 110 countries and has manufacturing facilities on four continents. It is currently the world’s leading producer of soft-surfaced modular floorcoverings. In 1994 Ray Anderson wanted to pursue a new vision for Interface-a vision that incorporated sustainability in all of its dimensions: “people, process, product, place and profit”.<a href="#_edn1" name="_ednref1" title="">[i]</a>&nbsp;Interface’s strategic frame for sustainability is called: “7 Fronts of Mount&nbsp;Sustainability: ‘The’ mountain to climb”, and is comprised of the following key elements:&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Eliminating Waste&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		Emitting Benign Emissions</li>\n	<li>\n		Using Renewable Energy</li>\n	<li>\n		Closing the loop</li>\n	<li>\n		Using Resource-Efficient Transportation</li>\n	<li>\n		Sensitizing Stakeholders</li>\n	<li>\n		Redesigning Commerce</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Awards, frameworks and accomplishments</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards 2012:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012 Screw Business As Usual Award - Interface and Ray Anderson (from Richard Branson and Virgin Unite)</li>\n	<li>\n		Interface''s Urban Retreat Wins Best of NeoCon Silver - Modular Carpet Category</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards 2011:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Popular Science selects Raw™ from InterfaceFLOR for 2011 “Best of What’s New” award</li>\n	<li>\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Bronze Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Permian" by InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Bronze Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Raw" by InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Silver Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Red Carpet Collection" by InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Silver Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Silurian" and "Matrix" by InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Gold Award for Sustainable Products - "Striation" by InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Jim Blanchard Award - Ray Anderson, Interface, Inc.</li>\n	<li>\n		Best of NeoCon 2011 Silver Winner Carpet: Modular (Tile) -- Luxe at Work - Striation™, Smithfield Stripe™, Finsbury Square™ and Silurian™ by InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Eric Nelson Named CARE Person of the Year -- InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Citigroup''s Citi Realty Services (CRS) Global Environmental Vendor of the Year Award - InterfaceFLOR</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards 2010:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe, Sustain Magazine Award for Environmental Manufacturing</li>\n	<li>\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe, Lean and Green Award for Sustainable Logistics Innovation</li>\n	<li>\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe, Shelf Mills, Environmental Index Benchmark Bronze Award from Business in the Community (BITC)</li>\n	<li>\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe received Big Tick Award for Climate Change at the Business in the Community (BITC) Yorkshire &amp; Humber Awards</li>\n	<li>\n		Ray Anderson received the 2010 ASID Design for Humanity award from the American Society of Interior Design</li>\n	<li>\n		Ethical Corporation recognizes Ray Anderson with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the Responsible Business Awards 2010 in London</li>\n	<li>\n		Interface, Inc. Listed Among Top Rated Companies for Sustainability 2010 in the Southeast by GreenBusiness WORKS</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards 2009:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		ReSoul™ Collection Named to Top 100 Products for 2009 - InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Center for Companies That Care Award 2009 - InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Awarded The California Gold Fit Business Award 2009 for being a pioneer in worksite wellness</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards 2008:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2008 CalRecycle Sustainable Business Award from California Integrated Waste Management Board - Bentley Prince Street</li>\n	<li>\n		Floor Focus magazine "Top 250 Designers Survey" - #1 in Green Kudos, Green Leaders, Product Kudos -- InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Floor Focus magazine "Top 250 Designers Survey" - #1 in Overall Business Experience, Quality, Performance and Value -- InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Best Places to Work in Los Angeles (2008) by the Los Angeles Business Journal - Bentley Prince Street</li>\n	<li>\n		Waste Reduction Awards Program (W.R.A.P.) Environmental from the State of California EPA &amp; Integrated Waste Management Board - Bentley Prince Street</li>\n	<li>\n		2008 Max Award (Georgia State University, Robinson College) for Marketing Excellence for the video concept for ReEntry® 2.0 / Reprise™ Collection - InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Achievement Award for “Emerging Technologies in Materials, Processes and Applications” for the technology to separate and recycle nylon 6,6 fiber through ReEntry 2.0 - InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		United Way of West Georgia 2008 Peoples Award for Most Employee Contributions from a Single Company – InterfaceFLOR</li>\n	<li>\n		Queen''s Awards for Enterprise Sustainable Development</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Listings/Index:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012:&nbsp; Promotion to the Global Challenges Index (GCX)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Rankings</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		October 2012: pioneer in green business practices in Atlanta, Atlanta, USA, Charlote Business Journal</li>\n	<li>\n		2009: listed #1 on the Green Leaders list in the 2009 Floor Focus Top 250 Design Survey</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Frameworks</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Climate Disclosure Project</li>\n	<li>\n		Greenhouse Gas Protocol Corporate Standard</li>\n	<li>\n		Landfill Methane Outreach Program (LMOP)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainable Activities</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Biodiversity/Site</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		All of the Interface factories have been certified to conform to ISO 14001, the international standard for environmental management systems. ISO 14001 minimizes the environmental impacts of operations and sustains a continuous improvement</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Water</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		In 2011, the company used 4.54 liters of water per square meter of carpet which corresponds to a 84.21% reduction from 1996’s numbers</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Energy&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></h3>\n<p>\n	Improved energy efficiency: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Total energy use is down 43% per unit of product since 1996</li>\n	<li>\n		Building energy management systems have been applied to monitor, understand and reduce the use of energy</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Renewable energy</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Percentage of total energy used in 2010 is 30% renewable energy, 66% Natural gas, Brown electricity (electricity produced from coal or gas) 3%, and propane 1%</li>\n	<li>\n		30 percent of the energy use at all Interface’s factories comes from renewable resources – 28% from green electricity and 2% from landfill gas</li>\n	<li>\n		In 2000, installation of a 5 kW photovoltaic array at Interface factory in Scherpenzeel, The Netherlands, and a 17kW photovoltaic array at Interface factory in LaGrange, Georgia</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Launched Landfill Methane Outreach Program (LMOP): a voluntary assistance program launched by US EPA to encourage companies to use landfill gas as an energy resource</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Interface also purchased Renewable Energy Credits (RECs) from Green-e certified renewable energy projects to support the development of green power markets</li>\n	<li>\n		2003 – Partnered with the City of LaGrange, Georgia to use methane gas from a local landfill as a renewable fuel source for the Interface factory in LaGrange</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Greenhouse Gas Emissions Reduction:</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Implementation of employee programs to help address their emissions and selling carbon neutral products through the Cool Carpet™ program, one of the first in the world</li>\n	<li>\n		Interface® calculates its global greenhouse gas emissions using the <u>greenhouse gas protocol corporate standard</u>, allowing to analyze and report the emissions reductions</li>\n	<li>\n		Reduction of greenhouse gas emissions from all global manufacturing operations by 35% from 1996 baseline through diverse strategies including process efficiencies, energy efficiencies (such as lighting and equipment replacement), fuel switching, and use of renewable energy</li>\n	<li>\n		Life cycle assessment to measure the footprint of products for the Cool Carpet program. Discloser of annual inventory and progress on this site and through the&nbsp;climate disclosure project</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Materials</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Mission Zero® journey program is a program designed and launched by Interface in 1994 with the aim of making the company fully sustainable, and eliminating all the company’s negative impact on society and the environment</li>\n	<li>\n		Quality Utilizing Employee Suggestions and Teamwork (QUEST) began in 1995 as a program to drive waste reduction efforts at the factories. It’s an employee-led system to define and eliminate waste and communicate the accomplishments, recognizing efforts and measuring progress to let employees know that their contributions matter. Using cross-functional teams of employees with shared goals allows for different perspectives and ideas to surface. Inviting new thinking and allowing permission to fail creates an abundance of positive risk takers&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		Through a process called ReEntry, in 2007 Interface became the first carpet manufacturer to allow for a maximum amount of post-consumer materials to be recycled into new products with minimal contamination. Current technologies allow Interface to manufacture product with 64-75% total recycled content. The ReEntry process allows Interface to determine the best option for processing products such as recycling, repurposing, downcycling and upcycling</li>\n	<li>\n		Waste reduction efforts have resulted in a 76% decrease in total waste to landfills from the carpet factories since 1996</li>\n	<li>\n		Interface has achieved a 41% reduction in waste cost per unit, resulting in $438 million in calculated avoided waste costs since it began in 1994</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Sample Reduction Programs</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Shifting from physical samples, leveraging Simulated Sample Technology (SIMS) to create virtual pictures of room designs and produce printed, highly realistic, product images.&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		The zerolandfill™&nbsp;program is one innovative solution to this problem where interface donate old&nbsp;<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Waste.aspx" title="Click to Continue &gt; by Text-Enhance">carpet samples</a>&nbsp;to artists and art educators for projects and educational materials&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		Cool blue program: radical change in the way machines are designed. The set of assumptions is reversed to: abundant materials being impure, inconsistent and variable over time. Interface has developed a machine under the Waste to Energy program that\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				is able to work with any thermoplastic (i.e., any plastic that melts -- over 70&nbsp;percent&nbsp;of plastic production is thermoplastic)</li>\n			<li>\n				tolerates up to 30&nbsp;percent&nbsp;“contamination” with materials not intended for use in carpet tile backing (e.g., nylon carpet fiber)</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Transportation/Air Quality</span></h3>\n<p>\n	Mapping and reducing the global transportation footprint has led to create and partner with innovative programs that address transportation-related impacts from product shipping to business travel and more.</p>\n<h4>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;"><em>Internal Transportation Programs</em></span></h4>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Trees for Travel™ – Program designed to track and neutralize the carbon emissions from employee business Air Travel. Interface has planted more than 118,000 trees to neutralize the carbon emissions from business related air travel since this program started in 1997</li>\n	<li>\n		Cool Fuel™ – Program to track and offset carbon emissions from company cars. Using money received from corporate fuel card rebates, Interface purchases certified carbon offsets to balance the carbon emissions of corporate fleet. Interface has purchased 2.4 million gallons of Cool Fuel and retired over 27,000 metric tons of certified carbon offsets as a result of this program</li>\n	<li>\n		Cool CO<sub>2</sub>mmute™ – Program offering Interface employees the opportunity to neutralize the emissions from their daily commutes and personal travel. Interface matches employee contributions to purchase tree plantings that neutralize carbon emissions from their commutes. Nearly 45,000 trees have been planted since this program began in 2002</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;"><em>Transportation Efficiency Initiatives</em></span></h4>\n<p>\n	Interface has developed innovative strategies to reduce transportation emissions including internal policies, shipping guidance and incentives to choose more efficient alternatives.</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Interface U.S. sales force drives Partial Zero Emission Vehicles&nbsp;(PZEV) from Subaru of America</li>\n	<li>\n		Several Interface locations provide incentives to encourage employees to carpool or take public transportation</li>\n	<li>\n		The employees of Interface in the UK are rewarded with cash&nbsp;for selecting company cars with lower emission levels</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Partnerships:</span></h3>\n<p>\n	<em>Partnership with U.S. EPA &amp; UNEP</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		U.S. EPA’s SmartWay™ Partnership started in 2003 to reduce transportation emissions</li>\n	<li>\n		Interface U.S. is a member of the U.S. EPA’s&nbsp;green power partnership&nbsp;(GPP), a voluntary initiative aimed at increasing the use of renewable energy. Both companies have been included in the Green Power Leadership Club – a recognition reserved for partners who exceed their renewable energy commitment by a significant margin</li>\n	<li>\n		Actively engaged in various climate-related partnerships including: United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) Climate Neutral Network, Chicago Climate Exchange, U.S. EPA Climate Leaders, The Climate Group, Pew Center on Global Climate Change Business Environmental Leadership Council (BELC), and the World Resource Institute’s Climate-Safe Business Network</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<em>Partnership with Subaru </em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Innovative Partnership with Subaru of America – Interface and Subaru work together to make the fleet carbon neutral in the U.S. Subaru offsets the carbon footprint for the first 60,000 miles of the company cars by purchasing and retiring carbon offsets</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<em>Memberships in various projects</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Interface is a member of the&nbsp;carbon disclosure project, through which it discloses publicly the details of its greenhouse gas inventory and climate strategy</li>\n	<li>\n		member of the&nbsp;presidential climate action project (pcap): the project is responsible for the development of policy recommendations on climate change and energy security</li>\n	<li>\n		member of zero co2 emissions commitment, the clinton global initiative</li>\n	<li>\n		interface is also a part of bio-mimicry guild, a group dedicated&nbsp;to inventing and discovering nature inspired materials to use in products to replace petro-chemical</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainability Governance</span></h2>\n<p>\n	The Company has adopted the Corporate Governance Guidelines to provide a framework for the governance of Interface. It ensures that the strategic management team they have established carries out the best practices available. The Board of Directors ensures that Interface continues to be successful by designating committees to handle specific duties. There are three standing committees: the Nominating and Governance Committee, the Compensation Committee and the Audit Committee.</p>\n<p>\n	One of the Vice President out of 10 council members is also designated for the sustainability program of the company.</p>\n<p>\n	In order for Interface to achieve its vision and mission, the company has created an ECO Dream Team to achieve sustainability. The Eco Dream Team is comprised of members who help the company create an environmental roadmap. The team consists of eleven members and each one has a certain expertise that they contribute to the Eco Dream Team. It is composed of authors, activists, scientists and entrepreneurs.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Challenges and Future Goals </span></h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Mission Zero® commitment, Interface<sup>®</sup>&nbsp;has set a goal to source 100% of energy needs from renewable sources and reduce the waste to Zero by 2020</li>\n	<li>\n		Sourcing Raw Materials for Closed Loop Products</li>\n	<li>\n		Achieving Zero Footprint</li>\n	<li>\n		Sustaining an Engaged Culture</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">&nbsp;Best practices, Success Drivers</span></h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		44% of total raw materials used in production are recycled</li>\n	<li>\n		Getting Employees Involved – QUEST Program: Quality Utilizing Employee Suggestions and Teamwork (QUEST) began in 1995 as a program to drive waste reduction efforts. It’s an employee-led system to define and eliminate waste and communicate the accomplishments of company, recognizing efforts and measuring progress to let employees know that their contributions matter. After launching this program, company is succeeded to reduce 54% of scarp yarn</li>\n	<li>\n		Cool blue Program changing the way machines are designed to take into account the future nature and amount of resources available</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and prepared by Binod Dahal for Sustainable Silicon Valley</em></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sources</strong></span></h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Interface-Story.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Interface-Story.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Company/Mission-Vision.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Company/Mission-Vision.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Waste.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Waste.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/InterfaceFLOR-News.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/InterfaceFLOR-News.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Challenges.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Challenges.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/blog/going_green/2012/10/interface-crew-charlotte-lindsay-james.html?page=all">http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/blog/going_green/2012/10/interface-crew-charlotte-lindsay-james.html?page=all</a></li>\n	<li>\n		http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/10/19/rage-against-machines-revolutionizing-industrial-design</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Results/Pages/responses.aspx">https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Results/Pages/responses.aspx</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.climateactionproject.com/plan/">http://www.climateactionproject.com/plan/</a> <a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability.aspx</a> (Sustainability) <a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Company/History.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Company/History.aspx</a> (History of Interface) <a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Investor-Relations/Annual-Reports.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Investor-Relations/Annual-Reports.aspx</a>(Annual Reports)</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Investor-Relations/Corporate-Governance.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Investor-Relations/Corporate-Governance.aspx</a> (Corporate Governance)</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Manufacturing.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Manufacturing.aspx</a> (Manufacturing, Recycled Materials)</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx">http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx</a> (Awards)</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="https://www.interfaceflooring.com/sustain/ReEntry.pdf">https://www.interfaceflooring.com/sustain/ReEntry.pdf</a> (ReEntry Program)</li>\n</ul>\n<div>\n	<br clear="all" />\n	<hr align="left" size="1" width="33%" />\n	<div id="edn1">\n		<p>\n			<a href="#_ednref1" name="_edn1" title="">[i]</a> For more information:&nbsp; <a href="http://www.lagrangenews.com/view/full_story/15264482/article-Environmental-hero-remembered#ixzz29UFx2Ujv">LaGrange News - Environmental hero remembered</a></p>\n	</div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, '');
</span></h2>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia’s goal is to move from an “opportunistic” to a “strategic” approach to sustainability when it comes to measuring the Eco-elements of its business</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia is striving to provide hard data relative to such areas as its carbon footprint, the amount of Eco friendly fabric in its products, how much product the company recycles, and much more</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Important aspects of green design lies in the materials used in the product,&nbsp; green materials usage that define how Eco-friendly they really are. Patagonia is on the leading edge of these green initiatives.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia wants to reach a goal of 50,000 pledges for the “Common Threads Initiative”</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Best practices, Success Drivers</span></h2>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Over the past 20 years the Company has given about $40 million in cash and in-kind donations to environmental causes</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia has helped launch the North American business philanthropies, the Conservation Alliance and 1% For The Planet, and the European Outdoor Group’s Association for Conservation</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Company has worked to restore the “five dam busters” from Maine to California as part of their “Our Common Waters Campaign”</p>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and prepared by Pallavi Kalale for Sustainable Silicon Valley</em></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sources</strong></span></h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://business.transworld.net/94208/news/patagonia-wins-sustainability-lifetime-achievement-award/">http://business.transw