Sustainable Activities\n\n	The sustainability actions are either concerning the core services offered by eBay or its internal organization. Most of the internal organization actions are locally managed and assessed.\n\n	Biodiversity/site\n\n	Local:\n\n	\n		Community gardens:\n		\n			\n				Organic community garden created by the Omaha (NE) Green Team: 70 employees gardeners worked 40 plots in 2010, and there is a waiting list to get a plot\n		\n	\n	\n		Volunteering:\n		\n			\n				Salt Lake City team was recognized the most dedicated corporate group at Tree Utah , having assisted with tree planting initiatives, restoration of wetlands annual fundraising efforts for several years\n			\n				Participation in Salt Lake City Earth Fest and Live Green Eco Fair\n			\n				47 employees from Swiss offices partnered with World Wildlife Fund to remove invasive plants and protect endangered species native to the Valaise region of Switzerland\n		\n	\n\n\n	Water\n\n	No publicly available information.\n\n	Energy\n\n	\n		Renewable energy in the USA:\n		\n			\n				Announced in Spring 2012 the Topaz data center in South Jordan, Utah, the first wholly owned data center, awarded LEED® Gold status by the USGBC, creates power thanks to a solar array. It will produce 924,013 kilowatts hours (kWh) of clean electricity annually, &nbsp;which is equivalent to offsetting 702 tons of greenhouse gas emissions or planting 136 acres of pine forest. It is anticipated to pay for itself in 4 years\n			\n				Three solar arrays (665 kW in South Jordan, 650 kW in San Jose, 100 kW in Denver)and 500 kW Bloom Fuel cell installation in &nbsp;San Jose bring total renewable energy capacity to almost 2 Megawatts. That’s about 11% of eBay total US data center electricity demand. In 2013 eBay will open the first US data center that uses 100% renewable energy as primary power at their Utah site\n			\n				Less energy used to cool the data centers: minimum of 76% of energy going to computers in Arizona, and 95% in other states, against an industry average of 57%\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		Energy efficient buildings in the USA and Germany:\n		\n			\n				Fall 2011: announced a new employee center in Draper (Utah) to be built and operated to LEED® Gold standards thanks to minimal construction waste, sustainable and locally-sourced building materials, high-efficiency heating and &nbsp;lighting, easy access to transit and green cleaning and landscaping practices. The facility will be opening in spring 2013.\n			\n				The site in Germany in 2010 was powered 100% with hydropower electricity and extended their renewable energy contract through 2012. When their new server room was constructed, they made sure to use the most efficient cooling system available and even increased the temperature to require less cooling system energy\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		Lobbying:\n		\n			\n				Work with Republican State Senator Mark Madsen and others to pass Senate Bill 12, a new piece of legislation that allows power-intensive utility customers like eBay to buy and transmit renewable power in Utah\n		\n	\n\n\n	Materials\n\n	Global:\n\n	\n		eBay reusable box pilot made from environmentally friendly materials: free reusable boxes provided to eBay sellers and buyers. Could protect nearly 4,000 trees, save 2.4 million gallons of water and conserve enough energy to power 49 homes for a year. This idea won the 2011 grand prize winning idea at the eBay Innovation Expo, as well as the eBay Green Team’s Big Green Idea contest. 100,000 boxes have been given away and 1,500 have been registered and reused. It resulted in the conservation of almost 7,000 gallons of water, an amount of energy sufficient to power 13 homes for a week, and reduced greenhouse gas emissions equivalent to taking 18 cars off the road for a week\n	\n		Partnership with USPS\n\n\n	Local:\n\n	\n		USA: Omaha (Nebraska) Green Team:\n		\n			\n				switch from plastic bottles to cans in the PayPal vending machines.\n			\n				the green team and the local Workplace Resource’s group partnered to provide employees with stainless steel flatware, ceramic coffee cups and reusable tumblers in break rooms and cafes\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		USA: StubHub Green Team in Connecticut:\n		\n			\n				No more disposable cups\n			\n				Greening of local events and community outreach programs in partnership with the local CARE team\n			\n				Changed out their bathroom products for more environmentally friendly ones\n			\n				Enacted green education initiatives, and started a test group to rid the office of Post-It Notes entirely\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		USA: Headquarters in San Jose:\n		\n			\n				Workplace resource’s group launched in 2010 the Zero Waste for Green Space program, aiming at zero waste going to the Landfill. Most trashcans were replaced with recycling and compost cans and the San Jose campuses now have a diversion rate over 95% (program in partnership with Republic Services)\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		Israel:\n		\n			\n				Biodegradable kitchenware\n			\n				Double-sided printers\n			\n				Bike sharing program\n			\n				Drastic reduction of trash going to landfills&nbsp;\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		eBay Canada:\n		\n			\n				All branded goods are either made of recycled materials, can be recycled, or are reusable. Their office pens are made of 65% organic materials directly from renewable energy developers\n		\n	\n\n\n	Transportation/Air Quality\n\n	Local:\n\n	\n		Omaha employees biked over 9,880 miles last year and were certified a Bronze level Bike Friendly Business by the League of American Bicyclists\n	\n		Preferred parking program for environmentally friendly cars in Salt Lake City\n	\n		In Israel, subsidized leasing program for Hybrid cars and bike racks\n	\n		In Switzerland: bikes available to commute to train stations, coordination of lunch&nbsp;deliveries with existing local schedules to minimize driving of providers. Alternative commute program\n	\n		In Bern (Switzerland) used by 70% of employees\n\n\n	Global:\n\n	\n		Website giving greener driving tips and services: http://green.ebay.com/greenteam/blog/Introducing-eBay-Green-Driving/8536\n\n\n	Partnerships:\n\n	\n		Shows and events in San Jose (e-waste sale, electric car showcase, etc.)\n	\n		Work with Net Impact to help them advance an entrepreneurial sustainability culture\n	\n		Writing of “Making Your Impact at Work” guide in 2009\n	\n		Organization of creative reuse competition\n\n\n	Sustainability-related services:\n\n	\n		Largest marketplace for used, refurbished and vintage goods\n	\n		Created two specialized websites to buy/sell sustainable products (socially and environmentally respectful):\n		\n			\n				green.ebay.com since 2009: inviting users to join the “Green Team” (300,000 members today)\n		\n	\n	\n		Maintain a blog giving green tips to users on what to buy, how to use products and what to do to be greener\n	\n		Offer a specialized platform to sell pre-owned electronics ebay instant sale\n\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	The sustainability program at eBay started with 40 employees at the San Jose site in 2007, when they formed the first Green Team. Today, employees forming the Green Team is made of 2,500+ employees in 25 countries. eBay’s sustainability program uses a bottom-up process: each site is coming up with ideas and actions it implements. All members of the extensive Green Team also collaborate on a few global projects.\n\n	eBay contributors to the Green ebay website\n\n	\n		Annie Lescroart Senior Manager, Sustainability Communications\n	\n		Caitlin Bristol Manager, eBay Green + Sustainability\n	\n		Danielle Huffaker Merchandising Manager\n	\n		Dean Nelson Senior Director, Global Foundation Services\n	\n		Gaurav Rekhi Product Manager, Social Innovation\n	\n		Jill Primost Sustainable Commerce\n	\n		Kevin Wolfley eBay Green Canada\n	\n		Lori Duvall Director of Operational Sustainability\n	\n		Lorin May Head of EU Charity &amp; Sustainability\n	\n		Pat Kohl Facility Operations Manager\n	\n		Siddharth Sanghvi GM, Sustainable Commerce\n	\n		JD Norton Community Manager\n\n\n	Guest contributors to the Green ebay website\n\n	\n		Brad Berman Hybrid &amp; Electric Vehicle Expert\n	\n		Danna Crawford eBay Seller\n	\n		Gabrielle Maguire 2011 Climate Corps Fellow\n	\n		Sheena Matheiken Founder, The Uniform Project\n	\n		The Inside Source eBay''s Digital Media Destination\n	\n		Zem Joaquin eBay Eco Lifestyle Expert\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals \n\n	\n		Use frameworks to make the sustainability policy more consistent at the corporate scale and to compare actions to an objective scale&nbsp;\n	\n		Establish a system to measure results of sustainability actions in terms of savings (resource, energy, CO2, money)\n	\n		Publish a Sustainability Report\n	\n		Partner with assessment firms and programs\n\n\n	Best practices, Success Drivers\n\n	Internal actions:\n\n	\n		Aggressive data center efficiency program yielding &gt; 50% improvement in transaction efficiency since 2008\n	\n		Involved a large number of people from diverse offices around the globe, rewarding&nbsp;them for their local collective efforts\n	\n		Took advantage of the creativity of each one in the firm. Reduced costs and expanded impact of the sustainability effort by engaging regular eBay employees and internet users and visitors into green teams (more than 300,000 members in the&nbsp;online community)\n	\n		Adapted each office sustainability policy to its situation, opportunities and needs\n	\n		Communicated through a Blog on the green teams’ actions, using a platform and&nbsp;tone less formal and likely to appeal to eBay users, getting them to join the global green team\n\n\n	Core business/services:\n\n	\n		“Belief that people are good and when offered the tools, resources and knowledge, they shop in ways that are better for the planet”, stated on ebay website&nbsp;\n	\n		More than 100 billion worth of reused products have been sold on eBay since 1998\n\n\n	Researched and prepared by Caroline Nowacki for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources:\n\n	\n		http://green.ebay.com/greenteam/ebay/blog/Engaging-People/25\n	\n		http://green.ebay.com/greenteam/blog/eBay-Green-Team-2010-Year-in-Review/4467\n	\n		http://green.ebay.com/greenteam/about/\n	\n		http://green.ebay.com/greenteam/blog/eBay-and-Dell-Recognized-for-Data-Center-Efficiency-Leadership/8527\n	\n		http://specials.kenan-flagler.unc.edu/kicse/ORIG%20Shared%20Documents/Measuring%20Sustainability.pdf\n	\n		https://www.cdproject.net/CDPResults/CDP-G500-2011-Report.pdf\n\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '125', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/ebay', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/125', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/125'),
(680, 'Diverting Waste', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Local News &amp; Developments&nbsp;\n\n	The Sunnyvale City Council has voted 7-0 to ban foam food containers. &nbsp;The ordinance will make it illegal for retail food service vendors to distribute foam containers for food or liquid. To learn more and also find a list of vendors that supply alternatives to foam food containers visit&nbsp;http://sunnyvale.ca.gov/Departments/EnvironmentalServices/FoamFoodContainers.aspx\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n\n	Core Knowledge\n\n	Thinking about how you manage the materials you use on a daily basis is a big step towards developing sustainability within your organization. &nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n\n	Success Stories\n\n	Currently researching\n\n\n	Tools &amp; Resources\n\n	Plastic Film Recycling\n\n	\n		Does your company see a lot of plastic film? The plastic&nbsp;grocery&nbsp;bag is a commonly seen plastic film, but much of the plastic wrap in product packaging is the same material, PE or&nbsp;polyethylene, and there is a large market for it''s recovery. &nbsp;Visit&nbsp;http://www.plasticbagrecycling.org/02.0/&nbsp;for a calculator to determine the financial benefit of collecting this material, information on who will buy it and helpful strategies to ensure you get the most bang for your buck.&nbsp;\n	\n		Paper recycling and procurement\n	\n		The Environmental Paper Network (EPN) provides a&nbsp;compressive toolkit to guide your business to responsible paper usage. &nbsp;They provide&nbsp;tools&nbsp;for everything your company would need from start to finish including: model paper policies, an&nbsp;environmentally&nbsp;sound paper hierarchy, how to efficiently use your paper and even resources to help your suppliers verify the fiber content in their paper.&nbsp;Visit&nbsp;http://www.whatsinyourpaper.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=7&amp;Itemid=68&nbsp;to get started. &nbsp;Also check out their applications for purchasers at&nbsp;http://environmentalpaper.org/purchaser-apps/, which includes a&nbsp;calculator to measure and report the environmental benefits and savings with responsible paper procurement.\n	\n		For making responsible paper purchases visit&nbsp;http://canopyplanet.org/EPD/&nbsp;for a great tool that ties in with the Paper Step (http://www.whatsinyourpaper.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=view&amp;id=57&amp;Itemid=62) from the Environmental Paper Network. &nbsp;You can search for paper based on types (printing, tissue,&nbsp;gift wrap, notepads, etc.) along&nbsp;with&nbsp;a variety of other fields like: ancient forest friendly, recycled content and brand name. &nbsp;\n	\n		Finding value with your waste stream\n	\n		The By-Product Synergy (BPS) Network matches under-valued waste or by-product streams from one facility to potential users at another facility to create new revenues or savings with potential social and environmental benefits.&nbsp; This US Business Council for Sustainable Development (USBCSD) program takes it a step above a normal waste exchange by covering the technical, policy and financial hurdles&nbsp;to ensure the BPS effort is maximized.&nbsp; The diversity of businesses within their program also increases the possibilities by opening up synergies between industries that may have not otherwise become connected.&nbsp; In addition to materials they work to identify transportation, space, logistic and other resource synergies.&nbsp; To learn more and get involved visit http://bps-hub.org/.\n	\n		Staying ahead of the game in waste reduction\n	\n		The Northern California Recycling Association (NCRA) is a non-profit organization&nbsp;committed&nbsp;to promoting, expanding and&nbsp;institutionalizing&nbsp;recycling. &nbsp;This is a great group to get involved with to stay abreast in the recycling &amp; composting industry. &nbsp;They offer many classes, training, networking meetings and conferences. &nbsp;As stated on&nbsp;their site you are probably already benefiting from their work. &nbsp;If you are interested in staying ahead of the curve in managing your waste check out&nbsp;http://ncrarecycles.org\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '61', NULL, 'topics/materials/diverting-waste', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/61', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/61'),
(727, 'Compare companies', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	Sustainable Silicon Valley just completed a review of the sustainability practices of 15 leading companies in sustainability. Here are the three Sustainability Trends SSV observed:\n\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Multiplication of sustainable transportation initiatives\n\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; New reusable and fully recyclable packaging\n\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cradle-to-cradle product design\n\n	Reducing the CO2 emissions of employees’ commutes\n\n	The Google buses are among the most well known companies’ transportation initiatives, but apart from it being a multi-occupancy vehicle, did you know that their shuttle used biodiesel and transported over 4,500 employees everyday?&nbsp; In addition to this Shuttle program, Google has created GFleet: a car-sharing program composed of energy-efficient vehicles including electric plug-ins. These two initiatives have resulted in a net annual saving of more than 5400 metric tons of CO2.\n\n	Microsoft has also created one of the world’s largest private bus systems, called the “Connector”, for its Seattle’s campus, WA, and their drivers follow a 5-minute “low or no idle” rule to help reduce emissions. But apart from these private solutions, partnering with other public or private systems is a good alternative. Microsoft also subsidizes regional public transportation. HP enables employees to take advantage of WageWorks and use pretax income to pay for public transport costs. HP also encourages carpooling options, notably through a partnership with rideshare.org in the San Francisco Bay Area.\n\n	Reusable and fully recyclable packaging\n\n	Sustainable Packaging is also a hot topic in which companies such as eBay, Coca-Cola, SAP, and HP are innovating.&nbsp; For example, eBay crowd-sourced through a contest, a solution of reusable boxes made from environmentally friendly materials. Making it available to its buyers and sellers has resulted in the conservation of almost 7,000 gallons of water, an amount of energy sufficient to power 13 homes for a week, and a reduced greenhouse gas emissions amount equivalent to taking 18 cars off the road.&nbsp;\n\n	Coca-Cola’s PlantBottle program is another example and the first ever fully recyclable PET bottle made partially from plant-based materials. It led to a reduction of approximately one-third of the petroleum-based material that was traditionally used to make PET bottles.&nbsp;\n\n	Cradle-to-Cradle product design\n\n	A final trend observed in companies such as HP, Cisco or Patagonia, is the effort to help customers efficiently recycle their old products.&nbsp; HP’s worldwide ink cartridge recycling Planet Partner program provides customers with an easy and free way to recycle their old cartridges.&nbsp; HP recycles the old cartridges and collects PET plastic to create new HP Original Ink Cartridges.&nbsp; This program reduced HP’s Carbon Footprint by 33%, decreased their water use by up to 89%, and lowered their fossil fuel depletion by 62%.&nbsp;\n\n	Patagonia’s worldwide recycling initiative, called the Common Threads Recycling Program, actually asks its customers not to buy what they do not need! It offers customers to repair their Patagonia gear, find a home for gear no longer needed and buy it back from customers, and finally recycle worn out gear into new fiber and fabric.\n\n	The complete reviews of the 15 companies will be on EcoCloud by the end of January 2013, don’t forget to check it out!\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	More information on companies'' websites:\n\n	\n		Google Commute:&nbsp;http://www.google.com/green/efficiency/oncampus/#commuting\n	\n		Ebay reusable box:&nbsp;http://thebox.ebay.com/ws/eBayISAPI.dll?EbayGreenBox\n	\n		Microsoft:&nbsp;http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/misc/09-06connectorFS.aspx\n	\n		Coca-Cola Plant Bottle Program:\n	\n		http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/plantbottle.html\n	\n		Patagonia:&nbsp;http://www.patagonia.com/us/common-threads/\n	\n		HP Cartridge Recycling Program:&nbsp;http://www.hp.com/sbso/product/supplies/cartridge-recycling.html\n	\n		SAP:&nbsp;http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/materials-used\n\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '109', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/109', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/109'),
(791, '13. Photobioreactor Sculptures', 'The world needs energy. Why not make energy from an investment in art. I would like to build sculpture that grows energy from primordial algae.  The sculpture manifests this by becoming A photobioreactor which is a closed or semi-closed system in which light and nutrients are supplied to the system in an attempt to maximize algal biomass. Nutrients can be in the form of pollutants,so the sculpture can facilitate bio-remediation. It also consumes CO2, reducing greenhouse gases.The algae can than be used to generate biodiesel. The biodiesel could be used to run machinery and vehicles etc.\n\nAs an alternative to energy production the Photobioreactor sculpture could also be used to produce Spirulina blue green algae as a food supplement.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '108', 716, 'solutions/view/108', 'admin/solutions/edit/108', 'admin/solutions/delete/108'),
(793, '15. SustainTheFuture.org – Community Garden Network Program (STF-CGN)', 'In a nutshell a Community Garden Network (CGN) is a locally organized community effort focused on maximizing local produce production, harvesting, and food distribution through networks within the community to eliminate hunger, encourage healthy nutrition, self-sustenance, and community bonding.  Challenges each community face as it attempts to start-up a CGN are \n\nEnrollment of private, public, and residential gardens\n Volunteer engagement, mobilization, related Incentive strategies to ensure participation\nPlanning strategies for ensuring all produce is picked and distributed and nothing goes to waste\nSponsor engagement and food distribution partnerships to ensure produce is delivered \n Frictionless sharing of best practices, tools, models\nThe STF-CGN mission is to create a reusable county wide model & operational framework (w/tools) for implementing community based agriculture, healthy eating, and self-sustenance as a building block for the planet.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '110', 692, 'solutions/view/110', 'admin/solutions/edit/110', 'admin/solutions/delete/110'),
(799, '16. TRASH on your BACK™ Challenge  - What''s your trash impact?', 'For 1 week try carrying all of your garbage with you, wherever you go – to explore how much refuse your lifestyle produces and how to cut back. Imagine a "Challenge" sponsored by local communities where people from across the nation carry their trash with them for 5 days to understand how their consumption habits personally impact the planet! \nWe would like to learn if local challenges like this could lead the world to greener habits, more sustainable practices on the planet, greater scientific awareness, the power of consumerism, greener product development and innovation in the marketplace, while accelerating economic recovery & improving our health all at the same time. Create the thinking around the possibility of becoming a ZERO-WASTE Nation and change behaviors to make it happen?? We believe it''s possible if we\n\n buy less & throw away less \n change purchasing habits to prioritize less waste \n educate about the amount of waste we individually generate\n', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '111', 720, 'solutions/view/111', 'admin/solutions/edit/111', 'admin/solutions/delete/111'),
(800, '17. BIOS-FINS', '40% of all energy consumed is through building operation.  The greatest sustainable solutions for the planet will come in the form of building systems.  The BIOS-FIN system was designed with this in mind.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '112', 716, 'solutions/view/112', 'admin/solutions/edit/112', 'admin/solutions/delete/112'),
(667, 'SAP', ' \n	&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\n\n	SAP Sustainability Review\n\n	January 2013\n\n	Introduction\n\n	SAP is a German software corporation that innovates business management software, applications and services. They started an organized and broad sustainability effort in 2009. Their sustainability efforts are detailed in comprehensive online sustainability reports including GRI and UN Global Compact indexes. In addition, SAP partners with organizations such as the Sustainability Consortium, Carbon Disclosure Project, and Business for Social Responsibility.\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012\n\n	Sustainability Awards\n\n	\n		2012 Technology Innovation Award by Ventana Research for SAP’s innovative approach and market introduction of SAP for Automotive Cloud and SAP for Utilities Cloud. (http://www.sap.com/news-reader/index.epx?pressid=19535)\n	\n		SAP’s Palo Alto building was awarded by the City of Palo Alto with the Green Business Leader Award for achieving major strides in improving building energy efficiency\n	\n		BCA Greenmark Award 2012 Gold for SAP’s office building in Singapore\n	\n		Two 2012 Social Innovation Awards in recognition of SAP’s Sustainability Report presented by JustMeans\n	\n		PR&nbsp;News'' 2012 CSR Awards\n	\n		SAP’s Shea-Butter video http://www.sap-tv.com/video/7334 has won the intermedia-globe GOLD Award in the category Public Relations: Human Relations and Values\n	\n		SAP was recognized as a leader in a Sustainability Leadership Report by BrandLogic, which measures real performance vs. perceived sustainability progress, showing the importance of &nbsp;sustainability communications\n\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	\n		FTSE4Good (since 2007) - Link\n	\n		Dow Jones Sustainability Index (SAP leads the software industry for the sixth consecutive year) - Link \n	\n		Global Challenges Index (among the first 100 firms selected when the index was founded in 2007) - Link\n	\n		Global 100 (Corporate Knights Inc. and Innovest Strategic Value Advisors ranking) - Link NASDAQ OMX CRD Global Sustainability 50 Index - Link&nbsp;\n	\n		Oekom Prime Rating - Link\n	\n		Inclusion in the Greenpeace Cool IT Leaderboard - Link\n	\n		Inclusion in the Ethibel PIONEER and Ethibel EXCELLENCE Investment Registers - Link\n	\n		STOXX® Global ESG Leaders - Link\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		&nbsp;# 8 in 2012 global Newsweek''s "Green Rankings" (Link2012) - #20 in 2011 global rankings (Link2011)\n	\n		Among top 50 of Interbrand''s "Best Global Green Brands 2012" ranking - Link\n	\n		Inclusion in the Greenpeace Cool IT Leaderboard - Link\n	\n		SAP Canada has been selected as one of Canada’s 50 Best Employers for 2013\n	\n		The U.S Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) recognized SAP America as one of the Top 20 Tech and Telecom green power users for its purchase of electricity generated from renewable sources\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		Sustainability reports according to GRI guidelines and published on Internet since 2008 (Level C in 2008, accredited by KPMG since 2009, level A+ since 2010 report)\n	\n		Measured its scope 3 emissions (upstream and downstream emissions included) for the first time in 2011, working with the WRI to develop a new standard\n	\n		UN Global Compact member since 2000. “Communications On Progress” conform to the three requirements of UN Global Compact and published in 2005, and then each year from 2007 to today\n\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	\n		Biodiversity protection with green roofs, ground sealing, rainwater infiltration, planting hayfields, and sustainable landscaping\n\n\n	Water\n\n	\n		Run-off water for irrigation and toilets in Germany\n	\n		Waterless washroom fixtures, installed pressure reduction valves and reduced flush toilets in offices in Brazil, Canada, India, Israel, Singapore, Switzerland, and the United States\n\n\n	Energy\n\n	Total energy increase from 845 GWh in 2010 to 860 GWh in 2011, but:\n\n	\n		+ 23 electric cars in the corporate car fleet =&gt; increase of fuel consumption non proportionate to the increase in the number of cars\n	\n		7% decrease in office electricity usage in 2011 compared to 2010: improved lighting, cooling and heating systems; “smart buildings” tracking the use of electricity and managing it\n	\n		LEED gold and platinum certifications in some countries, ISO 14001 standards in others\n	\n		Investment in renewable energies: 47% of total electricity usage in 2011, compared to 45% in 2010 an 16% in 2009\n	\n		50% of headquarters’ energy is from renewable sources thanks to electricity bought from a local hydro production.\n	\n		Increase from 52% to 65% of server virtualization of entire IT landscape. Desktop virtualization has helped reduce the number of PCs per employee\n	\n		Facility management software improving energy and carbon management in 350 facilities worldwide: energy usage breakdown and comparison of facilities efficiency around the world\n	\n		Optimization of system configurations to lower power usage within data centers\n	\n		Avoided costs of a quarter billion US dollars since 2008 related to Greenhouse Gas emissions reductions\n\n\n	Materials\n\n	\n		Reduction of packaging for products: Blu-Ray discs for greater data storage, downloading of software and handbooks instead of hard copies\n	\n		Reduction of number of pages printed per employee thanks to: double-sided printing, scanning instead of copying (e.g. for expense reports), reducing number of printers, increasing employee awareness using a printing tracker on the SAP software\n	\n		Results were 2% reduction in pages printed (goal was 5% for 2011)\n\n\n	Transportation\n\n	\n		Use of Cisco services for teleconferences to reduce the number of business trips\n\n\n	Partnerships around sustainability (engaging suppliers)\n\n	80% comes from downstream emissions (use of products) so 3-step policy focusing on product use:\n\n	\n		Work with hardware providers to help increase hardware efficiency\n	\n		Benchmark of hardware provider products available to customers to optimize the energy efficiency of their servers\n	\n		High-efficiency data center management knowledge, experienced and shared with clients\n\n\n	Sustainability-related products and services\n\n	\n		Energy-efficient software thanks to streamlined databases and in-memory solutions: up to 60% electricity saved with SAP NetWeaver® Process Integration technology\n	\n		Work with CDP to include energy and carbon management applications:\n		\n			\n				Sustainability map for EcoHub solution marketplace of green IT solutions and services.\n			\n				CDP Reporter Services, supporting an organization’s carbon management and disclosure process and includes a range of programs such as Investor CDP, CDP Supply Chain and CDP Water Disclosure.\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		Simpler software design, running on fewer servers to require less energy\n	\n		Software solutions that help SAP customers create more sustainable businesses and address the following challenges: energy management, sustainable supply chain, operational risk management, sustainable workforce, and sustainability reporting and analytics.\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals \n\n	\n		Long-term goal is to reach the firm’s carbon emissions level of 2000 in 2020, which is half 2007 emissions\n	\n		How to reduce energy and resource use while business activities are growing?\n		\n			\n				Main sources of increase in 2011 were business flights and corporate cars\n			\n				Solutions for these are telepresence technologies and its operability with regular video-conference, online meeting platforms and webcams; employees alternatives to driving, integration of more energy-efficient cars into the firm’s fleet\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		Target of 54% of electricity coming from renewable energies through renegotiation of electricity contracts this year\n	\n		Continued reduction of printing materials, including customer training materials\n\n\n	Best practices, Success Drivers\n\n	As recalled Peter Graf, Chief Sustainability Officer and Executive VP of Sustainability Solutions, at the WEST Summit, the key to make a business care about sustainability is to tie sustainability issues to its core business, to the way it creates value.\n\n	\n		The corporate strategy itself became sustainable instead of developing a separate sustainability strategy\n	\n		Sustainability and Innovation have been adopted as key values and integrated into every aspects of the business: solutions offered to clients, operations of the firm, social investments. It created a direct link between sustainable growth and profitability\n	\n		Innovative and sustainable solutions were developed in all five key categories of products (applications, analytics, mobile, cloud, database)\n	\n		Sustainability challenges were underlined in terms of:\n		\n			\n				Risk: potential disruption to the business model because of significant changes in the economic, environmental or social circumstances\n			\n				Profitability: opportunity for profit through market-leading sustainability software solutions and cost-savings by applying best practices inside SAP operations\n			\n				&nbsp;Brand and Employee Engagement: staying relevant to the most forward-thinking minds in the industry as a company focused on innovation\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Researched and prepared by Caroline Nowacki for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources:\n\n	SAP sustainability report (http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com) and its various titles:\n\n	Awards: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/recognition\n\n	Materials: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/materials-used\n\n	Data Centers and Energy: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/data-center-energy\n\n	Total Energy Consumed: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/total-energy-consumed\n\n	Renewable energies: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/renewable‐energy\n\n	CDP partnership and reports: https://www.cdproject.net/en-­‐US/Programmes/Pages/CDP-Reporter-Services.aspx\n\n	Benchmark ofproviders: http://www.sap.com/solutions/benchmark/power‐benchmarks.epx\n\n	Water: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/total-water-withdrawal\n\n	Solutions: Netweaver: http://scn.sap.com/people/holger.faulhaber/blog/2011/06/06/sap‐netweaver-73‐goes‐green\n\n	Sustainability Governance: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/management-approach-economic-environmental-and-social-performance\n\n	Sustainability progress: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/our-progress\n\n	UN Global Compact: http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/un-global-compact\n\n	Indexes:https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Results/Pages/CDP-Global-500-Report-2011.aspx?PageID=5\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '114', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/sap', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/114', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/114');
\n\n	Symantec faced challenges in reducing the CO2 emissions due to the expansion of data centers.\n\n	\n		Develop a GHG emissions reduction approach through the implementation of a global environmental management system (EMS)\n	\n		Obtain LEED and ENERGY STAR certifications at all owned or long-leased facilities\n	\n		Achieve an industry standard Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE) of 1.7 or better for all owned or long leased facilities\n	\n		Identify metrics and measurement criteria to track success and outcomes of strategic partnerships\n\n\n	Best practices, Success Drivers\n\n	\n		The success driver for Symantec is the active Green Team located around the world who been implementing various efforts contributing towards a giant target of CO2 reduction\n	\n		GHG emissions decreased four percent from our 2008 baseline due to increased data accuracy, real estate consolidation, reductions in air travel, and data center/lab efficiencies\n	\n		Achieved the first LEED Certification for a Symantec building in India, bringing the total number of LEED certified facilities to 18 (88 percent of all Symantec owned or long-leased facilities)\n	\n		Achieved annual ENERGY STAR renewal for 12 facilities, (62 percent of all Symantec owned or long-leased facilities)\n\n\n	Researched and prepared by Juhi Jain for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources\n\n	\n		http://ethisphere.com/wme/\n	\n		http://www.symantec.com/about/news/release/article.jsp?prid=20110531_01\n	\n		http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/10/16/green-rankings-2011.html\n	\n		http://www.symantec.com/content/en/us/about/media/environmental_policy_statement.pdf\n	\n		http://www.symantec.com/corporate_responsibility/topic.jsp?id=environmental_performance#man4\n	\n		http://www.symantec.com/theme.jsp?themeid=green_it\n	\n		http://www.symantec.com/corporate_responsibility/topic.jsp?id=the_world\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '132', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/symantec', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/132', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/132'),
(717, 'Stonyfield', ' \n	Stonyfield Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Stonyfield is a company that produces organic yogurt, smoothies, ice cream and milk. The Company focuses on implementing the best practices to develop an organic, sustainable and environmentally friendly business. Stonyfield started as a little farming school in 1983 that taught sustainable agricultural practices. By 1987 Stonyfield began building their plant and since then the Company has been recognized for their sustainable, eco-friendly achievements. Their Yogurt Works office is located in Londonderry, New Hampshire, and the company has about 500 employees.\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012\n\n	Sustainability Awards\n\n	\n		Institute of Packaging Professionals AmeriStar Award, 2011— Plant-based PLA Form-Fill-Seal Plastic Multipack Yogurt Cup\n	\n		Nutrition Business Journal Sustainability Award, 2010\n	\n		Responsible Packaging Award— For reducing weight and material use for yogurt cups, 2010\n	\n		Edison Awards— Finalist, The Green Award, 2010\n	\n		New Hampshire Business Review— Best Green Business, 2010\n	\n		Environmental Protection Agency’s 2009 SmartWay Excellence Award\n	\n		Treehugger.com Best of Green— Best Practices by a Big Food Brand 2009\n	\n		EPA Clean Air Excellence Award 2009\n	\n		NH Business Review— Best Environmentally Friendly Business 2009\n	\n		NEEP Northeast Energy Efficiency Partnership’s Business Leader award 2008\n	\n		NH Division of Economic Development Business Resource Center\n	\n		“Innovation Rocks!” Award Winner, Recycling Program, 2008\n	\n		Working Mother magazine’s Best Green Companies for America’s Children, 2008\n	\n		National Wildlife Federation’s National Conservation Achievement award in Corporate Leadership, 2006\n	\n		EPA and US DOE Green Power Leadership Award, 2006\n	\n		EPA Business, Industry and Professional Organizations Environmental Merit Award, 2006\n	\n		Global Green USA’s Green Cross Millennium Award for Corporate Environmental Leadership, 1999\n	\n		National Award for Sustainability (Atmosphere and Climate) from the President’s Council on Sustainable Development and Renew America, 1999\n	\n		Robert Rodale Environmental Achievement Award, 1998\n	\n		Climate Wise Achievement Award from the Environmental Protection Agency, 1998\n	\n		Corporate Environmental Steward Award from the Council on Economic Priorities, 1990\n\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	\n		First for profit company to register its greenhouse gas emissions with the State of New Hampshire''s voluntary registry in 2003\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		Greenbiz.com listing on “Top 10 Greenest Companies,” 2007\n	\n		Inc. magazine Green 50 includes Stonyfield CE-Yo Gary Hirshberg, 2006\n\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	Corporate office in Londonderry, NH is built to LEED silver certification standards, but did not receive verification from USGBC\n\n	\n		Built to silver LEED certification standards\n	\n		Oriented towards the south so it stays warm in winter and cool in summer\n	\n		External solar shades on south-facing windows block the hot summer sun\n	\n		Solar collectors preheat cold incoming water\n	\n		Double-glazed windows\n	\n		Energy efficient lighting, timers, daylight sensors, motion sensors\n	\n		HVAC on automatic, digital control, cafeteria has demand-controlled ventilation\n	\n		Energy recovery wheel transfers heat and moisture to incoming or outgoing air depending on time of year\n	\n		Tile is made from post-industrial waste\n	\n		Wood floors were harvested following Forest Stewardship Council Guidelines\n	\n		Recycled bottles, sawdust and bathroom stalls used for desk and table materials\n	\n		Walls painted with non-toxic, low VOC paint\n	\n		Waterless urinals, dual flush toilets\n\n\n	Water\n\n	\n		Reuse wash water in multiple cycles in plant as part of production process, where it is safe\n	\n		Low-flow water fixtures in office building\n	\n		Porous pavement in parking structures to recharge the ground water\n	\n		Teach employees awareness of conserving water\n	\n		For each cup of yogurt, 17% less wastewater in 2008 than 2007\n	\n		Water: cut overall plant wastewater volume by 5% annually for 10 years\n\n\n	Energy\n\n	\n		First manufacturer in the US to offset the carbon impact of its facility energy use\n	\n		Used 19% less energy in 2008 than 2007 and saved half a million dollars\n	\n		Plant-wide energy monitoring system used in order to identify ways to reduce energy use\n	\n		Turning off equipment and lights when not needed, adjusting temperature to the season\n	\n		Efficient motors, high efficiency lighting (fluorescent lights, daylight sensors)\n	\n		Measure energy per unit yogurt produced, emissions from transportation\n	\n		One of New Hampshire''s largest solar electric systems on the roof\n	\n		Solar hot water system that heats water for their plant office before is enters the domestic water heater\n	\n		Anaerobic digester that treats their wastewater and generates biogas to power the digester\n	\n		Has been offsetting carbon emissions for ten years by investing in wind energy, farm methane recovery and reforestation\n\n\n	Materials\n\n	\n		Switched from #2 plastic to #5 plastic because it is more lightweight and therefore uses less energy to be produced, more is recycled because not all #2 plastic products can be recycled\n	\n		Partnership with Preserve to turn recycled yogurt cups into toothbrushes\n	\n		Can send cups to Stonyfield to be recycled\n	\n		Multipacks are made from 93% plant based PLA plastic, made from corn, 43% less carbon\n	\n		Smoothie bottles are made from HDPE #2 which is made from sugar cane\n	\n		Reduced packaging by 1 million pounds\n	\n		Recycled 91% of building materials by diverting demolition and construction debris\n	\n		Wastewater treatment plant to pretreat wastewater on-site\n	\n		Zero Waste: recycling rate up 24% since 2006; recycling and reuse on average saved $150,000 per year\n	\n		Sustainable Packaging: Reduced packaging by almost 1 million pounds per year and saved $780,000 per year\n\n\n	Transportation\n\n	\n		Transportation and Distribution: Saved over $7.6 million between 2006 and 2010; reduced CO2 emissions by 46% between 2006 and 2010 while growing the business\n\n\n	Partnerships around sustainability\n\n	\n		Preserve\n	\n		US National Organic Standards\n	\n		Coulee Region Organic Produce Pool (CROPP) Initiative\n	\n		The Rural Education Center, nonprofit teaching rural and homesteading skills with an emphasis on organic food production\n	\n		Oxfam America\n	\n		Earth Force\n	\n		Union of Concerned Scientists to raise awareness on Global Warming\n	\n		Climate Counts\n	\n		SHFT Los Angeles\n	\n		Reverb\n\n\n	Governance\n\n	Stonyfield Farm’s Director of Natural Resources and President/CEO have developed specific indicators to indicate the importance of moving the company “up the continuum of sustainability.” Employee engagement was also seen as crucial to support the use of the roadmap for Green Business and indicators developed. Stonyfield chose five mission areas and developed indicators corresponding to them: Employee Well-being, Family Farms and Sustainable Agriculture, Environment, Profitability and Quality.\n\n	Developing Environmental Indicators was challenging and resource intensive but really helped the firm improve its sustainability. The environmental indicators were grouped into four main categories: Resource Use, Pesticides and Toxics, Global Warming, and Acidification.\n\n	\n		Stonyfield’s Mission Action Program (MAP): MAP is a company-wide program developed to engage employees in achieving their environmental mission. MAP was formed in 2006 to address the environmental burdens of the company in nine different areas: Green Chemistry, Milk, Facility Greenhouse Gas Emissions, Sustainable Ingredients, Water, Zero Waste, Transportation and Distribution, Sustainable Packaging and Stonyfield Walking Our Talk (SWOT)\n	\n		Under the MPA process, each team must complete an annual Action Plan that sets long-term and near-term goals, and outlines the steps on how to achieve these goals. The CEO, COO and VP of Natural Resources must approve the Action Plan. To achieve the annual MAP goals, the team members have a portion of their compensation linked to such objectives.\n		\n			\n				Facility Greenhouse Gas Emissions (the Energy Team): the team focuses on eliminating GHG from the facility by using renewable sources of power, energy efficiency and sequestration. The group represents the Marketing, Natural Resources, Research and Development, Purchasing, Procurement, Operations and Engineering&nbsp;\n			\n				Milk Team: they develop the best practices to minimize impacts from production and transportation of the milk. The team represents Natural Resources, Purchasing, and Communications\n			\n				Sustainable Ingredient Team: they ensure that the company makes the right decisions in purchasing the ingredients. The team represents the Purchasing, Natural Resources, Supply Chain and Logistics and Quality\n			\n				Water Team: it was officially formed in 2011 and they reduce the overall water consumption while maintaining quality\n			\n				Green Chemistry Team: formed in 2011, the team identifies chemicals that reduce or eliminate human health risks, environmental toxicity and greenhouse gas impacts\n			\n				Transportation and Distribution Team: the team develops the best practices to minimize emissions from the transportation of finished products\n			\n				Zero Waste Team: this team eliminates waste and maximizes recovery of materials. The group represents the Engineering, Natural Resources, Shipping, Warehouse, Quality, Supply Chain and Material Handling\n			\n				Sustainable Packaging Team: this team creates the most environmentally sustainable product packaging possible\n			\n				Stonyfield Walking Our Talk Team (SWOT): SWOT conducts all of the events, activities and purchases that are consistent with the company’s mission and values\n		\n	\n	\n		Under MAP, each team has specific goals that will help achieve Stonyfield’s mission areas. Such goals are as followed:\n		\n			\n				Align with the International Panel on Climate Change’s recommendation to globally reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 80% from 2000 levels by 2050\n			\n				Cut overall plant wastewater volume by 5% annually for 10 years\n			\n				To have zero waste by 2017 (no waste going to a landfill or incinerator)\n			\n				To achieve 100% sustainable packaging by 2015\n		\n	\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals \n\n	\n		To achieve 100% sustainable packaging by 2015\n	\n		Reduce normalized GHG emissions 75% by 2015\n	\n		Reduce absolute GHG emissions by 40% by 2014\n	\n		Reduce solid waste per ton by 25% by 2012\n	\n		Have zero waste by 2017\n	\n		Cut overall plant wastewater volume by 5% annually for 10 years\n	\n		A 20-year stretch of zero discharge from the waste treatment plant sewer by 2030\n	\n		Efficiency: Cut amount of energy use per ton of yogurt, 50% by 2012\n\n\n	Best practices, Success Drivers\n\n	\n		Have-A-Cow Program\n	\n		Profits for the Planet\n	\n		Support for organic farmers\n\n\n	Researched and Prepared by Katie Chansler for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources\n\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/about-us/our-mission\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/about-us/our-mission/awards\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-roadmap-green-business/our-carbon-footprint\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-roadmap-green-business/environmental-milestones\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/sustainable-packaging\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/sustainable-packaging/multipack-cups-made-plants\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/partnering-planet\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/wastewater\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/water\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/energy\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/healthy-planet/our-practices-farm-table/our-yogurt-works-facility/green-building\n	\n		http://www.stonyfield.com/sites/default/files/attachments/green-building-scrapbook-6-12-09.pdf\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '133', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/stonyfield', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/133', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/133'),
(718, 'Interface', ' \n	Interface Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Interface was founded in 1973 and is now a worldwide leader in design, production and sales of environmentally responsible modular carpet for the commercial, institutional, and residential market. It sells in 110 countries and has manufacturing facilities on four continents. It is currently the world’s leading producer of soft-surfaced modular floorcoverings. In 1994 Ray Anderson wanted to pursue a new vision for Interface-a vision that incorporated sustainability in all of its dimensions: “people, process, product, place and profit”.[i]&nbsp;Interface’s strategic frame for sustainability is called: “7 Fronts of Mount&nbsp;Sustainability: ‘The’ mountain to climb”, and is comprised of the following key elements:&nbsp;\n\n	\n		Eliminating Waste&nbsp;\n	\n		Emitting Benign Emissions\n	\n		Using Renewable Energy\n	\n		Closing the loop\n	\n		Using Resource-Efficient Transportation\n	\n		Sensitizing Stakeholders\n	\n		Redesigning Commerce\n\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments\n\n	Sustainability Awards 2012:\n\n	\n		2012 Screw Business As Usual Award - Interface and Ray Anderson (from Richard Branson and Virgin Unite)\n	\n		Interface''s Urban Retreat Wins Best of NeoCon Silver - Modular Carpet Category\n\n\n	Sustainability Awards 2011:\n\n	\n		Popular Science selects Raw™ from InterfaceFLOR for 2011 “Best of What’s New” award\n	\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Bronze Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Permian" by InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Bronze Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Raw" by InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Silver Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Red Carpet Collection" by InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Silver Award in Modular Carpet Category -- "Silurian" and "Matrix" by InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		IIDEX NeoCon Canada Gold Award for Sustainable Products - "Striation" by InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Jim Blanchard Award - Ray Anderson, Interface, Inc.\n	\n		Best of NeoCon 2011 Silver Winner Carpet: Modular (Tile) -- Luxe at Work - Striation™, Smithfield Stripe™, Finsbury Square™ and Silurian™ by InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Eric Nelson Named CARE Person of the Year -- InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Citigroup''s Citi Realty Services (CRS) Global Environmental Vendor of the Year Award - InterfaceFLOR\n\n\n	Sustainability Awards 2010:\n\n	\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe, Sustain Magazine Award for Environmental Manufacturing\n	\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe, Lean and Green Award for Sustainable Logistics Innovation\n	\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe, Shelf Mills, Environmental Index Benchmark Bronze Award from Business in the Community (BITC)\n	\n		InterfaceFLOR Europe received Big Tick Award for Climate Change at the Business in the Community (BITC) Yorkshire &amp; Humber Awards\n	\n		Ray Anderson received the 2010 ASID Design for Humanity award from the American Society of Interior Design\n	\n		Ethical Corporation recognizes Ray Anderson with a Lifetime Achievement Award at the Responsible Business Awards 2010 in London\n	\n		Interface, Inc. Listed Among Top Rated Companies for Sustainability 2010 in the Southeast by GreenBusiness WORKS\n\n\n	Sustainability Awards 2009:\n\n	\n		ReSoul™ Collection Named to Top 100 Products for 2009 - InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Center for Companies That Care Award 2009 - InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Awarded The California Gold Fit Business Award 2009 for being a pioneer in worksite wellness\n\n\n	Sustainability Awards 2008:\n\n	\n		2008 CalRecycle Sustainable Business Award from California Integrated Waste Management Board - Bentley Prince Street\n	\n		Floor Focus magazine "Top 250 Designers Survey" - #1 in Green Kudos, Green Leaders, Product Kudos -- InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Floor Focus magazine "Top 250 Designers Survey" - #1 in Overall Business Experience, Quality, Performance and Value -- InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Best Places to Work in Los Angeles (2008) by the Los Angeles Business Journal - Bentley Prince Street\n	\n		Waste Reduction Awards Program (W.R.A.P.) Environmental from the State of California EPA &amp; Integrated Waste Management Board - Bentley Prince Street\n	\n		2008 Max Award (Georgia State University, Robinson College) for Marketing Excellence for the video concept for ReEntry® 2.0 / Reprise™ Collection - InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Achievement Award for “Emerging Technologies in Materials, Processes and Applications” for the technology to separate and recycle nylon 6,6 fiber through ReEntry 2.0 - InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		United Way of West Georgia 2008 Peoples Award for Most Employee Contributions from a Single Company – InterfaceFLOR\n	\n		Queen''s Awards for Enterprise Sustainable Development\n\n\n	Listings/Index:\n\n	\n		2012:&nbsp; Promotion to the Global Challenges Index (GCX)\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		October 2012: pioneer in green business practices in Atlanta, Atlanta, USA, Charlote Business Journal\n	\n		2009: listed #1 on the Green Leaders list in the 2009 Floor Focus Top 250 Design Survey\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		Climate Disclosure Project\n	\n		Greenhouse Gas Protocol Corporate Standard\n	\n		Landfill Methane Outreach Program (LMOP)\n\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	\n		All of the Interface factories have been certified to conform to ISO 14001, the international standard for environmental management systems. ISO 14001 minimizes the environmental impacts of operations and sustains a continuous improvement\n\n\n	Water\n\n	\n		In 2011, the company used 4.54 liters of water per square meter of carpet which corresponds to a 84.21% reduction from 1996’s numbers\n\n\n	Energy&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n	Improved energy efficiency: &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\n\n	\n		Total energy use is down 43% per unit of product since 1996\n	\n		Building energy management systems have been applied to monitor, understand and reduce the use of energy\n\n\n	Renewable energy\n\n	\n		Percentage of total energy used in 2010 is 30% renewable energy, 66% Natural gas, Brown electricity (electricity produced from coal or gas) 3%, and propane 1%\n	\n		30 percent of the energy use at all Interface’s factories comes from renewable resources – 28% from green electricity and 2% from landfill gas\n	\n		In 2000, installation of a 5 kW photovoltaic array at Interface factory in Scherpenzeel, The Netherlands, and a 17kW photovoltaic array at Interface factory in LaGrange, Georgia\n\n\n	Launched Landfill Methane Outreach Program (LMOP): a voluntary assistance program launched by US EPA to encourage companies to use landfill gas as an energy resource\n\n	\n		Interface also purchased Renewable Energy Credits (RECs) from Green-e certified renewable energy projects to support the development of green power markets\n	\n		2003 – Partnered with the City of LaGrange, Georgia to use methane gas from a local landfill as a renewable fuel source for the Interface factory in LaGrange\n\n\n	Greenhouse Gas Emissions Reduction:\n\n	\n		Implementation of employee programs to help address their emissions and selling carbon neutral products through the Cool Carpet™ program, one of the first in the world\n	\n		Interface® calculates its global greenhouse gas emissions using the greenhouse gas protocol corporate standard, allowing to analyze and report the emissions reductions\n	\n		Reduction of greenhouse gas emissions from all global manufacturing operations by 35% from 1996 baseline through diverse strategies including process efficiencies, energy efficiencies (such as lighting and equipment replacement), fuel switching, and use of renewable energy\n	\n		Life cycle assessment to measure the footprint of products for the Cool Carpet program. Discloser of annual inventory and progress on this site and through the&nbsp;climate disclosure project\n\n\n	Materials\n\n	\n		Mission Zero® journey program is a program designed and launched by Interface in 1994 with the aim of making the company fully sustainable, and eliminating all the company’s negative impact on society and the environment\n	\n		Quality Utilizing Employee Suggestions and Teamwork (QUEST) began in 1995 as a program to drive waste reduction efforts at the factories. It’s an employee-led system to define and eliminate waste and communicate the accomplishments, recognizing efforts and measuring progress to let employees know that their contributions matter. Using cross-functional teams of employees with shared goals allows for different perspectives and ideas to surface. Inviting new thinking and allowing permission to fail creates an abundance of positive risk takers&nbsp;\n	\n		Through a process called ReEntry, in 2007 Interface became the first carpet manufacturer to allow for a maximum amount of post-consumer materials to be recycled into new products with minimal contamination. Current technologies allow Interface to manufacture product with 64-75% total recycled content. The ReEntry process allows Interface to determine the best option for processing products such as recycling, repurposing, downcycling and upcycling\n	\n		Waste reduction efforts have resulted in a 76% decrease in total waste to landfills from the carpet factories since 1996\n	\n		Interface has achieved a 41% reduction in waste cost per unit, resulting in $438 million in calculated avoided waste costs since it began in 1994\n\n\n	Sample Reduction Programs\n\n	\n		Shifting from physical samples, leveraging Simulated Sample Technology (SIMS) to create virtual pictures of room designs and produce printed, highly realistic, product images.&nbsp;\n	\n		The zerolandfill™&nbsp;program is one innovative solution to this problem where interface donate old&nbsp;carpet samples&nbsp;to artists and art educators for projects and educational materials&nbsp;\n	\n		Cool blue program: radical change in the way machines are designed. The set of assumptions is reversed to: abundant materials being impure, inconsistent and variable over time. Interface has developed a machine under the Waste to Energy program that\n		\n			\n				is able to work with any thermoplastic (i.e., any plastic that melts -- over 70&nbsp;percent&nbsp;of plastic production is thermoplastic)\n			\n				tolerates up to 30&nbsp;percent&nbsp;“contamination” with materials not intended for use in carpet tile backing (e.g., nylon carpet fiber)\n		\n	\n\n\n	Transportation/Air Quality\n\n	Mapping and reducing the global transportation footprint has led to create and partner with innovative programs that address transportation-related impacts from product shipping to business travel and more.\n\n	Internal Transportation Programs\n\n	\n		Trees for Travel™ – Program designed to track and neutralize the carbon emissions from employee business Air Travel. Interface has planted more than 118,000 trees to neutralize the carbon emissions from business related air travel since this program started in 1997\n	\n		Cool Fuel™ – Program to track and offset carbon emissions from company cars. Using money received from corporate fuel card rebates, Interface purchases certified carbon offsets to balance the carbon emissions of corporate fleet. Interface has purchased 2.4 million gallons of Cool Fuel and retired over 27,000 metric tons of certified carbon offsets as a result of this program\n	\n		Cool CO2mmute™ – Program offering Interface employees the opportunity to neutralize the emissions from their daily commutes and personal travel. Interface matches employee contributions to purchase tree plantings that neutralize carbon emissions from their commutes. Nearly 45,000 trees have been planted since this program began in 2002\n\n\n	Transportation Efficiency Initiatives\n\n	Interface has developed innovative strategies to reduce transportation emissions including internal policies, shipping guidance and incentives to choose more efficient alternatives.\n\n	\n		Interface U.S. sales force drives Partial Zero Emission Vehicles&nbsp;(PZEV) from Subaru of America\n	\n		Several Interface locations provide incentives to encourage employees to carpool or take public transportation\n	\n		The employees of Interface in the UK are rewarded with cash&nbsp;for selecting company cars with lower emission levels\n\n\n	Partnerships:\n\n	Partnership with U.S. EPA &amp; UNEP\n\n	\n		U.S. EPA’s SmartWay™ Partnership started in 2003 to reduce transportation emissions\n	\n		Interface U.S. is a member of the U.S. EPA’s&nbsp;green power partnership&nbsp;(GPP), a voluntary initiative aimed at increasing the use of renewable energy. Both companies have been included in the Green Power Leadership Club – a recognition reserved for partners who exceed their renewable energy commitment by a significant margin\n	\n		Actively engaged in various climate-related partnerships including: United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) Climate Neutral Network, Chicago Climate Exchange, U.S. EPA Climate Leaders, The Climate Group, Pew Center on Global Climate Change Business Environmental Leadership Council (BELC), and the World Resource Institute’s Climate-Safe Business Network\n\n\n	Partnership with Subaru \n\n	\n		Innovative Partnership with Subaru of America – Interface and Subaru work together to make the fleet carbon neutral in the U.S. Subaru offsets the carbon footprint for the first 60,000 miles of the company cars by purchasing and retiring carbon offsets\n\n\n	Memberships in various projects\n\n	\n		Interface is a member of the&nbsp;carbon disclosure project, through which it discloses publicly the details of its greenhouse gas inventory and climate strategy\n	\n		member of the&nbsp;presidential climate action project (pcap): the project is responsible for the development of policy recommendations on climate change and energy security\n	\n		member of zero co2 emissions commitment, the clinton global initiative\n	\n		interface is also a part of bio-mimicry guild, a group dedicated&nbsp;to inventing and discovering nature inspired materials to use in products to replace petro-chemical\n\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	The Company has adopted the Corporate Governance Guidelines to provide a framework for the governance of Interface. It ensures that the strategic management team they have established carries out the best practices available. The Board of Directors ensures that Interface continues to be successful by designating committees to handle specific duties. There are three standing committees: the Nominating and Governance Committee, the Compensation Committee and the Audit Committee.\n\n	One of the Vice President out of 10 council members is also designated for the sustainability program of the company.\n\n	In order for Interface to achieve its vision and mission, the company has created an ECO Dream Team to achieve sustainability. The Eco Dream Team is comprised of members who help the company create an environmental roadmap. The team consists of eleven members and each one has a certain expertise that they contribute to the Eco Dream Team. It is composed of authors, activists, scientists and entrepreneurs.\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals \n\n	\n		Mission Zero® commitment, Interface®&nbsp;has set a goal to source 100% of energy needs from renewable sources and reduce the waste to Zero by 2020\n	\n		Sourcing Raw Materials for Closed Loop Products\n	\n		Achieving Zero Footprint\n	\n		Sustaining an Engaged Culture\n\n\n	&nbsp;Best practices, Success Drivers\n\n	\n		44% of total raw materials used in production are recycled\n	\n		Getting Employees Involved – QUEST Program: Quality Utilizing Employee Suggestions and Teamwork (QUEST) began in 1995 as a program to drive waste reduction efforts. It’s an employee-led system to define and eliminate waste and communicate the accomplishments of company, recognizing efforts and measuring progress to let employees know that their contributions matter. After launching this program, company is succeeded to reduce 54% of scarp yarn\n	\n		Cool blue Program changing the way machines are designed to take into account the future nature and amount of resources available\n\n\n	Researched and prepared by Binod Dahal for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources\n\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Interface-Story.aspx\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Company/Mission-Vision.aspx\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Waste.aspx\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/InterfaceFLOR-News.aspx\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Challenges.aspx\n	\n		http://www.bizjournals.com/charlotte/blog/going_green/2012/10/interface-crew-charlotte-lindsay-james.html?page=all\n	\n		http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/10/19/rage-against-machines-revolutionizing-industrial-design\n	\n		https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Results/Pages/responses.aspx\n	\n		http://www.climateactionproject.com/plan/ http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability.aspx (Sustainability) http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Company/History.aspx (History of Interface) http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Investor-Relations/Annual-Reports.aspx(Annual Reports)\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Investor-Relations/Corporate-Governance.aspx (Corporate Governance)\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Sustainability/Our-Progress/Manufacturing.aspx (Manufacturing, Recycled Materials)\n	\n		http://www.interfaceglobal.com/Newsroom/Awards.aspx (Awards)\n	\n		https://www.interfaceflooring.com/sustain/ReEntry.pdf (ReEntry Program)\n\n\n	\n	\n	\n		\n			[i] For more information:&nbsp; LaGrange News - Environmental hero remembered\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '134', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/interface', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/134', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/134');
