(736, 'Entry Criteria', ' \n	\n		\n			About\n		\n			Entry Criteria\n		\n			How To Enter\n		\n			Review Process\n		\n			Finalists\n		\n			My Solutions\n		\n			View Expert Profiles\n	\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			Click Here to ENTER A Solution&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			Click Here to VIEW Your Solutions\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			Call for Solutions\n			Competition\n		\n			\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			&nbsp;\n	\n\n\n	Entries will be submitted online and will be reviewed by:\n\n	\n		\n			\n				\n			\n				\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Solutions should:\n\n	\n		Exhibit clarity of solution design, be game-changing, implementable and scalable\n	\n		Be a part of an integrated strategy dealing with key social, economic, environmental, policy and cultural issues\n	\n		Be bold, visionary and tangible, focusing on a well-defined need of critical importance\n	\n		Be regionally specific yet globally applicable, and backed up by a solid plan and the capability to move the solution forward\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '45', NULL, 'showcase-of-solutions-for-planetary-sustainability/entry-criteria', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/45', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/45'),
(737, 'Review Process', ' \n	\n		\n			About\n		\n			Entry Criteria\n		\n			How To Enter\n		\n			Review Process\n		\n			Finalists\n		\n			My Solutions\n		\n			View Expert Profiles\n	\n\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		\n	\n		\n			Review Process Overview\n		\n			\n				The judging of solutions will occur after the submission deadline (January 31, 2013), and will be completed by the end of February 2013.\n			\n				Every submitted solution will be judged by experts from academic, research, business and venture communities, including experienced professors, engineers, entrepreneurs, angel and venture investors, environmental experts and other professionals.\n			\n				Solutions will also be reviewed by members of the public through a crowd-sourcing approach.\n		\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			The submissions will be judged in the following focus areas:\n		\n			\n				Resources\n			\n				Human Systems\n			\n				Enterprise\n			\n				Regional\n			\n				Industry\n			\n				Earth Systems\n		\n		\n			&nbsp;\n	\n	\n		Within these focus areas each solution will be judged for meeting the following&nbsp; solution requirements:\n	\n		\n			Ratings in each category will range from 0-5\n		\n			0 - indicating inability to meet the basic criteria\n		\n			1-2 - promising solution, could use more evidence\n		\n			3-4 - strong solution with good potential for breakthrough impact\n		\n			5 - outstanding solution with high potential for breakthrough impact\n	\n	\n		\n			Creativity - Original Technology, Innovative Application\n	\n	\n		Assessing the extent to which the work introduces a new or significantly improved solution/technology in an affordable, replicable and sustainable manner\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		\n			Approach - Problem Identification, Problem Analysis, Plan for Success\n	\n	\n		Assessing how well solutions are able to identify the problem being addressed, and how well solutions are analyzed. Additionally, assessing the short, medium and long term plan for implementation and plan to measure success of the solution\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		\n			Goals - Game Changing\n			\n				\n					Multiple Categories (solution integrates a number of elements)\n				\n					Mitigation Strategy (solution helps reduce future global warming or pollution)\n				\n					Adaptation Strategy (solution helps humanity adapt to affects of global warming already in progress)\n				\n					Scalable (solution can be widely adopted so that impact will be significant)\n				\n					Reasonable Risk, Feasibility (solution is feasible to implement, may require legislation or investment or political will)\n				\n					Ecosystem of Solutions (solutions bring together elements that re-enforce one another, creating an ecosystem of solutions that generate a positive impact in a regenerative manner)\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Solution descriptions should include plans for assessing achievement of these goals.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	\n		\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Click Here to ENTER A Solution&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Click Here to VIEW Your Solutions\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Call for Solutions\n				Competition\n			\n				\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				&nbsp;\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '43', NULL, 'showcase-of-solutions-for-planetary-sustainability/review-process', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/43', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/43'),
(934, 'residential-solar-systems', ' \n	Residential Solar Systems: where do we stand?\n\n	By Lise Bilhaut\n\n	I recently attended a presentation by Rick Devlin, from SunStar Energy Inc, and organized by the Humanist Community in Silicon Valley on December 9th, 2012. The presentation, entitled "Solar Power in California" targeted individuals interested in installing a PV system on their roofs. Because of the rapid evolution of costs and regulation of PV, it was very useful to be given current information and numbers regarding those small residential systems. Here is a brief summary:\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Having a PV system makes sense if:\n\n	\n		your residential electricity bill is more than $80/month (or your total consumption is above 6000 kWh per year [[1]])\n	\n		you have at least 6 hours of direct sunlight per day on your roof. The best orientation in California is SSW, but other orientations are worth to consider.\n\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Several incentives and credits are currently in use:\n\n	\n		Federal Investment Tax Credit : 30% off the full system (the same applies for business with the advantage of accelerated depreciation)\n	\n		The California solar initiative gives a rebate of $200/kW [[2]]. "PG&amp;E targets to have 764.8 MW of solar generating capacity by 2016 on January 9th 2013, the target has been completed at 95%, with a total amount of 727.6 MW" [[3]]!\n\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Typically, for a 5 kW AC residential system, the cost is $14,700 net after the rebate and tax credit (for a $22,000 initial cost).\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unfortunately, the regulation in place doesn''t encourage over-producing, since PG&amp;E pays very little for excess electricity (3-4 cent/kWh). Right now, a good installer will dimension your system so it compensates your electricity consumption over a year.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Solar is highly leveraged in PG&amp;E territory [[4]] for two reasons:\n\n	\n		The residential tiered usage, which means the more power you use, the more it costs you (from 12 c/kWh up to 34 c/kWh) [[5]]\n	\n		The Time-of-Use rate, by which PG&amp;E credits more during afternoons, which is when solar produces most (the summer baseline peak rate is $29c/kWh whereas the off-peak rate is only $10c/kWh)[[6]].\n\n\n	During the discussion, other interesting points were raised by Rick Devlin and other presentation attendees:\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We need to realize grid parity has been reached, and apparently has been reached for 10 years in California.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; People are not aware that the cost of PV panels dropped by 25% over the last 5 years. Although SolarWorld won its case [[7]], this doesn''t necessarily mean that the cost of PV panels is going up.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the high profile failure of Solyndra, a lot has been said about subsidies to renewable energy and solar energy in particular. However, as shown by a report from Environmental Law Institute, government subsidies are five times higher for fossil fuel than renewable energy! [[8]]\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The cost of electricity will rise - the historical trend being above 4% per year [[9]]. A PV system, once installed, is a very safe investment, with very little risk and low maintenance cost.\n\n	For my part, I would like to see some federal or state regulation to stimulate photovoltaic electricity over-production. Furthermore, we should never forget that the cleanest (and cheapest!) energy is the one that you don''t spend: if you have a bill of $200/month, the first step would be to reflect on your consumption and see if it could be reduced!\n\n	References:\n\n	\n		\n			[[1]] http://sunstarenergy.com/Issolar.html\n	\n	\n		\n			[[2]]see here (http://www.gosolarcalifornia.ca.gov/csi/rebates.php ) for the current applicable rebate level\n	\n	\n		\n			[[3]] http://www.pge.com/myhome/saveenergymoney/solarenergy/csi/csiprogramstatistics/index.shtml\n	\n	\n		\n			[[4]] contrary to the area under the City of Palo Alto Utilities, which offers cheaper rates\n	\n	\n		\n			[[5]] http://pge.com/\n	\n	\n		\n			[[6]] http://www.pge.com/tariffs/tm2/pdf/ELEC_SCHEDS_E-6.pdf\n	\n	\n		\n			[[7]] http://www.forbes.com/sites/toddwoody/2012/10/10/u-s-hits-chinese-solar-manufacturers-with-higher-tariffs/\n	\n	\n		\n			[[8]]"Subsidies to fossil fuels [...] totaled approximately $72 billion over the [2002-2008] period, representing a direct cost to taxpayers. Subsidies for renewable fuels, a relatively young and developing industry, totaled $29 billion over the same period. Almost half of the subsidies for renewables are attributable to corn-based ethanol, the use of which, while decreasing American reliance on foreign oil, raises considerable questions about effects on climate." on page 3 of the report (http://www.elistore.org/Data/products/d19_07.pdf)\n	\n	\n		\n			[[9]] http://www.lee.org/blog/2008/07/23/historical-electric-rates/\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '142', NULL, 'topics/energy/renewables/solar/residential-solar-systems', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/142', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/142'),
(767, 'Leed-program', ' \n	\n		Application of LEED rating program for Energy Efficiency\n\n\n	By Jyothsna Giridhar\n\n	The ‘idea’ of energy efficiency gained popularity during the energy crisis of 1970s. A lot of studies were undertaken on existing energy conserving technologies and research &nbsp;was carried out on viable energy efficient strategies and alternatives for production and consumption of energy. An average of 30% of the energy produced in United States is consumed by building operations and maintenance (USGBC, 2009). Efforts to make buildings more energy efficient gained more patronization from the 1990s with the development of various green building rating systems, starting with the BREEAM rating system, followed by HQE and LEED.\n\n	LEED is one of the preferred rating systems in the US. LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) is a voluntary consensus based rating system developed by the USGBC. The first version of LEED was launched in 1998. It aims to evaluate building performance based on five categories: Sustainable Sites, Water Efficiency, Energy and Atmosphere, Materials and Resources and Indoor Environmental Quality, wherein, it aims to simultaneously address resource conservation and healthy built environment. Within LEED there are various rating systems to address the requirements of various building typologies. The various rating systems are listed below:\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED NC (New Construction): Facilities where the owner is the primary occupant.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED CS (Core and Shell): Facilities where the tenant is the primary occupant.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED for Homes\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED for Schools\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED Neighborhood Development\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED CI (Commercial Interiors): Tenant spaces in multi tenant office buildings.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LEED EB (Existing Buildings) addresses the requirements of buildings one year or older and which seeks to gain a LEED rating.\n\n	This article focuses on how LEED addresses energy efficiency for new and existing buildings.\n\n	Energy efficiency and LEED\n\n	Reducing building energy use has a direct impact on running costs of the building, resources spent on energy production and CO2 emissions into the atmosphere. Building orientation, massing, envelope, design of building services, operation and maintenance, usage pattern of occupants, amongst other factors, have a great impact on building energy performance.\n\n	The LEED rating system assesses energy performance of facilities based broadly on the following criteria.\n\n	Commissioning and retro-commissioning of building systems\n\n	This requirement seeks to ensure that the installation, calibration and performance of building systems are as per the project team’s requirements and satisfies the design intent. Systems to be commissioned includes HVAC systems, lighting and daylighting systems, domestic hot water systems, renewable energy systems installed within the site, at the minimum.\n\n	For retrofitting projects commissioning would address space temperature, space pressurization, building envelopes (caulking, sealing), primary HVAC systems, AHUs, control systems, lighting systems including all fixtures and their controls, and water systems.\n\n	Building Performance\n\n	Building performance improvement for new buildings is demonstrated through simulation comparison to ASHRAE baseline as spelt out in Appendix G of ASHRAE 90.1 2007. Alternatively buildings less than 20000 sqft are required to comply with ASHRAE Advanced Energy Design Guide, and buildings 20,000 to 100,000 Sqft are required to comply with Advanced Buildings Core Performance Guide.\n\n	Existing buildings demonstrate performance improvement through energy star rating. A minimum rating of 60 is compulsory. The energy Star Portfolio Manager Tool could be utilized for this.\n\n	Buildings Operations and Maintenance\n\n	Operations and maintenance of building systems impact energy performance of the facility in a big way. Existing buildings can take measures to monitor and maintain systems. Additionally educating the operations &amp; maintenance staff on the building systems and their maintenance is recommended.\n\n	Performance Measurement\n\n	Performance measurement in terms of emission reduction and running cost comparison of the retrofitted building to pre-retrofitting period is given weightage under LEED for Existing Buildings.\n\n	Other measures include:\n\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Elimination of CFCs and HCFCs in the facility: While it is mandatory under LEED to eliminate CFC usage, HCFC usage elimination in the facility is preferred.\n\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Installation of onsite renewable energy source\n\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Investment on offsite renewable energy source to offset the facility’s annual energy consumption (New Build).\n\n	LEED Credits\n\n	The following table shows the various LEED credits under the Energy and Atmosphere section of LEED NC.\n\n	\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit\n			\n			\n				\n					Title\n			\n			\n				\n					Points\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					NC\n			\n			\n				\n					CS\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Prerequisite 1\n			\n			\n				\n					Fundamental Commissioning of Building Energy Systems\n			\n			\n				\n					-\n			\n			\n				\n					-\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Prerequisite 2\n			\n			\n				\n					Minimum Energy Performance\n			\n			\n				\n					-\n			\n			\n				\n					-\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Prerequisite 3\n			\n			\n				\n					Fundamental Refrigerant Management\n			\n			\n				\n					-\n			\n			\n				\n					-\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Credit 1\n			\n			\n				\n					Optimize Energy Performance\n			\n			\n				\n					1-19\n			\n			\n				\n					1-21\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Credit 2\n			\n			\n				\n					Onsite Renewable Energy\n			\n			\n				\n					1-7\n			\n			\n				\n					1-7\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Credit 3\n			\n			\n				\n					Enhanced Commissioning\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Credit 4\n			\n			\n				\n					Enhanced Refrigerant Management\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n			\n				\n					1\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Credit 5\n			\n			\n				\n					Measurement and Verification\n			\n			\n				\n					3\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					EA Credit 6\n			\n			\n				\n					Green Power\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	The following table shows the various LEED credits under the Energy and Atmosphere section of LEED EB\n\n	\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit\n			\n			\n				\n					Title\n			\n			\n				\n					Points\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Prerequisite 1 \n			\n			\n				\n					Energy Efficiency Best Management Practices\n			\n			\n				&nbsp;\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Prerequisite 2 \n			\n			\n				\n					Minimum Energy Efficiency Performance\n			\n			\n				&nbsp;\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Prerequisite 3 \n			\n			\n				\n					Fundamental Refrigerant Management\n			\n			\n				&nbsp;\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit 1\n			\n			\n				\n					Optimize Energy Efficiency Performance\n			\n			\n				\n					1 to 18\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit 2.1\n			\n			\n				\n					Existing Building Commissioning—Investigation and Analysis\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit 2.2\n			\n			\n				\n					Existing Building Commissioning—Implementation\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit 2.3\n			\n			\n				\n					Existing Building Commissioning—Ongoing Commissioning\n			\n			\n				\n					2\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit 3.1\n			\n			\n				\n					Performance Measurement—Building Automation System\n			\n			\n				\n					1\n			\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					Credit 3.2\n			\n			\n