(1, 'Tesla Motors begins Model S production', 0, 'live', 'Tesla-Motors-begins-Model-S-production', '<p>\n Electric car company&nbsp;Tesla Motors Inc.&nbsp;said revenue fell and losses widened in the second quarter of this year.</p>\n<p>\n The company is in a key transition period, shifting from deriving its revenue from sales of just a few thousand Roadster sports cars and development work for other automakers to manufacturing and selling its Model S, Tesla’s first full production vehicle.</p>\n<p>\n The automaker just began selling the Model S, an all-electric five-passenger hatchback that has received rave reviews from the automotive press.&nbsp; Chief Executive Elon Musk said the company had been manufacturing just five cars a week but not has doubled production and is “ramping methodically.”</p>\n<p>\n “We are maintaining our revenue guidance of $560 [million and] $600 million and our Model S volume projection of 5,000 units for 2012. We expect to deliver approximately 500 vehicles to customers in Q3 with the balance delivered in Q4,” he said in a letter to shareholders.</p>\n<p>\n The car sells for between $50,000 to more than $100,000 depending on trim level and options. <a href="http://funk.latimes.com/bin/latimes.pl?state=fmsqh1.1.1&f=doc&p_u_all=#h8">Tesla</a> builds the Model S at a factory in Fremont, Calif., where it plans to also make the Model X, an electric SUV built on the same platform and sharing much of the technology, starting late next year.</p>\n<p>\n For the quarter, Tesla said its losses ballooned to $105.6 million, or 89 cents a share, from $58.9 million, or 53 cents, in the same period a year earlier.&nbsp; Revenue dipped to $26.7 million from $58.2 million.&nbsp; Prior to the release of its results, Tesla shares closed down 89 cents, or 3%, to $28.95.</p>', 'Tesla Motors expects losses as production ramps up at their new facility in Fremont.', 659, 1342824300),
(3, 'Ocean Conservation?  There''s an app for that!', 1, 'live', 'o', '<p>\n Technology helps us to solve problems every day. Just think of how many types of tech you use before you even finish your breakfast: alarm clock, light switch, electric toothbrush, iPhone, toaster, coffee pot -- all before you even really wake up!</p>\n<p>\n Over time technology has evolved to become an integral part of our every move, I for one cannot live without my Suunto D-3 dive-watch.</p>\n<p>\n Technology is meant to answer questions, meet needs, and solve problems. Whether it is making toast or <a href="http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-space-shuttle-endeavour-arrival-lax-pano,0,1751501.htmlstory" target="_hplink">exploring outer space</a>; when we find ourselves facing challenges we apply technology to deliver smarter, faster, easier solutions.</p>\nSo queuing up the next obvious question -- Can we apply our vast reservoirs of technology to create solutions for ocean conservation? Why yes we can!</p>\n<p>\n Just a few years ago the idea of using a phone to teach you about ocean conservation would have seemed like science fiction, however there certainly are some promising signs we have evolved past our imaginations -- you know the saying "there''s an app for that!" One such handy app <a href="http://www.oceanconservancy.org/our-work/rippl-mobile-app.html" target="_hplink"><strong>Rippl </strong></a>(recently released for iPhone) helps you build "green habits" by sending you helpful tips and reminders on how your actions impact the oceans. The app, which was created by the<a href="http://www.oceanconservancy.org/" target="_hplink"> Ocean Conservancy</a>, uses technology to <a href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/francesca-koe/oceans-climate-change_b_1696776.html" target="_hplink">bring ocean awareness </a>into our daily routines.</p>', 'Now an app helps you build "green habits" by sending you helpful tips and reminders on how your actions impact the oceans.', 4, 1348635600),
(4, 'Cradle-to-Cradle Inspiration', 1, 'live', 'cradle-to-cradle-inspiration', '<p>Material flow in a cradle-to-cradle economy means that there is no "waste." Outputs from one process become inputs to another, by design. Attendees at the June SSV Materials Management event heard presentations from expert practitioners from the Cradle to Cradle Products Innovation Institute, Adobe, Speciality Solid Waste and US EPA on how Silicon Valley companies and cities are bringing this transformational (and profitable) vision to reality.</p>\n\n<p>Bridgett Luther of the <a href="http://www.c2ccertified.org/" target="_blank">Cradle to Cradle Products Innovation Institute</a> gave a very inspiring and hopeful talk and she has kindly provided her PowerPoint slides for all to enjoy, which also describe their new push to get as many products certified as possible and not being harmful to health or planet. Anyone out there working on non-toxic fire retardants?</p>', 'Attendees at the June SSV Materials Management event heard presentations from expert practitioners from the Cradle to Cradle Products Innovation Institute, Adobe, Speciality Solid Waste and US EPA.', 8, 1349067600),
(5, 'Apply for Architectural Advisory Committee', 1, 'live', 'Apply-for-Architectural-Advisory-Committee', '<div>\n One seat is available on Redwood City''s Architectural Advisory Committee, to be appointed by the Planning Commission.</div>\n<div >\n Qualifications:&nbsp;</div>\n<ul>\n <li >\n  Members of the Architectural Advisory Committee are required to be licensed architects or landscape architects, residing or working in the City of Redwood City or its sphere of influence (as described in the City''s General Plan).</li>\n <li >\n  Have a strong desire and willingness to work diligently on behalf of the community</li>\n</ul>\n<div>\n <br />\n The application deadline is 5 pm, Monday, November 12, 2012. You can apply online by going to<a href="http://www.redwoodcity.org/clerks"  rgb(17, 85, 204); " target="_blank">www.redwoodcity.org/clerks</a>, or call&nbsp;<a href="tel:650-780-7220"  rgb(17, 85, 204); " target="_blank" value="+16507807220">650-780-7220</a>&nbsp;to request an application.</div>\n<div >\n The final appointment is expected to be made later this year. Applicants meeting the professional qualifications will be invited for oral interviews. This seat will expire on May 31, 2016.</div>', 'One seat is available on Redwood City''s Architectural Advisory Committee, to be appointed by the Planning Commission', 4, 1350584160),
(6, 'Apply now for 2013 Leadership Santa Clara program', 1, 'live', 'Apply-now-for-2013-Leadership-Santa-Clara-program', '<p>Applications are now being accepted for Leadership Santa Clara 2013, a course beginning in January that prepares individuals interested in becoming community leaders.</p>\n<p>\n Sessions are generally held on the second Thursday of each month from February through June, with two additional sessions in January and an evening graduation ceremony/reception in mid-June. Classes are held at a variety of Santa Clara business locations, offering students an opportunity to visit a range of local organizations. Class sessions begin at 8:30 a.m. and conclude at 4:30 p.m.</p>\n<p>\n Top-notch speakers cover a wide range of topics including governance, business climate, transportation, media, diversity, arts and culture, environment, volunteerism, health care and human/community services. Full days are devoted to public safety and education. Skill-building sessions focus on working with the media, public presentation skills, team building, meeting management, and ethics.</p>\n<p>\n Tuition is $750, and students may have up to 90% of their tuition covered by their employer. Scholarships are available.</p>\n<p>\n For more information, call Leadership Santa Clara Program Coordinator Scott Summerfield at 925-249-9320, email him at <a href="mailto:smmrfld@aol.com">smmrfld@aol.com</a>, or contact the City Manager''s Office at 408-615-2210. Application for the 2013 Leadership Santa Clara session is posted at <a href="http://santaclaraca.gov/index.aspx?page=1070">http://santaclaraca.gov/index.aspx?page=1070</a>.&nbsp;<br />\n &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n Contact:<br />\n Dan Beerman<br />\n (408) 615-2228</p>', 'Applications are now being accepted for Leadership Santa Clara 2013, a course beginning in January that prepares individuals interested in becoming community leaders.', 27, 1350599220),
(7, 'Planning Commission Study Session', 1, 'live', 'Planning-Commission-Study-Session', '[FC Press Release] The Foster City Planning Commission will hold a Study Session on Thursday, November 1, 2012 regarding the 15-Acre site adjacent to City Hall.\n<p>\n The Study Session, which begins at 7:00 pm, will take place in the Foster City Fire Department, EOC Room, 1040 East Hillsdale Boulevard, Foster City.&nbsp; Please follow the link below to view the Study Session Notice for this meeting.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n Please contact the Community Development Department at 650-286-3225 with any questions.</p>', '[FC Press Release] The Foster City Planning Commission will hold a Study Session on Thursday, November 1, 2012 regarding the 15-Acre site adjacent to City Hall.', 27, 1350536400),
(8, 'Triton event - Fall Floral Festival', 1, 'live', 'Triton-event---Fall-Floral-Festival', '<p>Join us for a beautiful night of flowers, art, music, fine hors d''oeuvres and wine!\n</p>\n<p>\n Where: Triton Museum of Art, 1505 Warburton Ave., Santa Clara, CA 95050</p>\n<p>\n When: Saturday, October 20, 2012, 6:30 pm - 8:30 pm</p>\n<p>\n Tickets: $50.00</p>\n<p>\n This year''s event will feature a special world premier performance by Alla Breve, Peninsula Women''s Chorus''s small ensemble, who will debut their own special interpretation of a work of visual fine art. Noted composer Frank Ferko was commissioned to write a composition based upon a painting by artist Ryan Reynolds: Alma Submerged. Reynolds is a professor of Art at Santa Clara University and one of the up and coming artists of our region. This is a special opportunity to hear a world premier performance that merges the talents of the artist, the composer, and the celebrated Alla Breve of the Peninsula Women''s Chorus.</p>\n<p>\n Can''t come Saturday night? Come Sunday, October 21 from 11:00 am to 5:00 pm to view the beauty for $5.00/person.<br />\n For more information on the event or to buy tickets, visit the event website.</p>\n<p>\n <br />\n Thank you to our in-kind catering sponsors:<br />\n Catered Too!<br />\n Parsley, Sage, Rosemary &amp; Thyme Catering&nbsp;<br />\n the Party Helpers<br />\n Restaurant O Catering</p>', 'Join us for a beautiful night of flowers, art, music, fine hors d''oeuvres and wine!', 27, 1350600120),
(9, 'Narnia - The Musical: featuring students from throughout SM County', 1, 'live', 'Narnia---The-Musical-featuring-students-from-throughout-SM-County', 'The nonprofit Bay Area Educational Theater Company invites you to their joyous interpretation of one of the most beloved childhood stories of all time: C. S. Lewis'' Chronicles of Narnia.\n<h4>Narnia - The Musical</h4>\n Fridays, November 2 &amp; November 9: 7:30 pm&nbsp;<br />\n Saturdays, November 3 &amp; November 10: 2:00 pm<br />\n Sundays, November 4 &amp; November 11: 2:00 pm<br />\n School Groups Special Show Dates:&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\n Friday, November 2, 2012&nbsp; 10:00am<br />\n Thursday, November 8, 2012&nbsp; 6:00pm (benefits charity)<br />\n &nbsp;Location: Cañada College Main Stage Theater, 4200 Farm Hill Blvd., Redwood City<br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n Tickets and more information: <a href="http://www.bayareaetc.org">www.bayareaetc.org</a> or email <a href="mailto:tickets@bayareaetc.org">tickets@bayareaetc.org</a> or <a href="mailto:narnia@bayareaetc.org">narnia@bayareaetc.org</a><br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n<p>Four children from our world find a portal that leads them into the magical land of Narnia, where brave mythical creatures and intelligent talking animals live unhappily in a perpetual winter imposed by the evil White Witch. The children embark on a quest with the great lion ruler of Narnia, King Aslan, to defeat the White Witch and bring life and joy back to the land while discovering courage, selflessness and wisdom within themselves.</p>\n<p>Narnia bursts with song, from the excitement of the opening number, "Aslan''s on the Move," to the beauty of "Narnia (You Can''t Imagine)," you and your children''s spirits will soar with all the good Narnians.</p>\n<p>\n Featuring Bay Area performers ages 6-18 representing dozens of San Mateo County schools (as well as some theater-loving adults!).</p>', 'The nonprofit Bay Area Educational Theater Company invites you to their joyous interpretation of one of the most beloved childhood stories of all time: C. S. Lewis'' Chronicles of Narnia.', 27, 1351049640),
(10, 'Survey from SM County Parks', 1, 'live', 'Survey-from-SM-County-Parks', '<p>San Mateo County Parks is undertaking a strategic planning process to ensure that our vision for our park system remains relevant and sets priorities for the next five years.</p>\n<p>\nAs we look forward to 2018, we would like to hear from you about your experience in our parks and how you would like to use our parks in the future. In addition, we hope that you will take a few minutes to rank your priorities for our parks over the next five years.</p>\nCompleting the survey takes approximately five minutes, and can be found at: <a href="https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/SMCParks2018">https://www.surveymonkey.com/s/SMCParks2018</a><br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nPlease complete the survey by October 28, 2012.<br />\n&nbsp;<br />', 'San Mateo County Parks is undertaking a strategic planning process to ensure that our vision for our park system remains relevant and sets priorities for the next five years.', 27, 1351141200),
(11, 'Redwood City Needs Park Ambassadors!', 1, 'live', 'Redwood-City-Needs-Park-Ambassadors!', 'Park Ambassadors are park lovers who are dedicated to keeping the parks safe, clean, and fun for everyone. Park ambassadors also help to spread the word about Stulsaft Park''s new dogs off-leash pilot program.<br/>\nAnyone can be a Park ambassador, just stop by the Community Activities Building at 1400 Roosevelt to sign up and pick up a Park Ambassador button to make it official!&nbsp; Email Jacob Hodgdon for more info. <a href="mailto:jhodgdon@redwoodcity.org">jhodgdon@redwoodcity.org</a>', 'Park Ambassadors are park lovers who are dedicated to keeping the parks safe, clean, and fun for everyone. Park ambassadors also help to spread the word about Stulsaft Park''s new dogs off-leash pilot program.', 27, 1351642440),
(12, 'Winter Spare the Air Season Begins November 1', 1, 'live', 'Winter-Spare-the-Air-Season-Begins-November-1', '<p>The Air District is announcing the beginning of the Winter Spare the Air season on November 1, making it illegal to burn wood, manufactured firelogs or any other solid fuel, both indoors and outdoors, when a Winter Spare the Air Alert is called.</p>\n<p>\n The Air District calls Winter Spare the Air Alerts when weather conditions trap pollution close to the ground and air quality is forecast to be unhealthy. The Winter Spare the Air season runs from November 1, 2012, through February 28, 2013.<br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n <a href="http://www.baaqmd.gov/Divisions/Communications-and-Outreach/News-Media-and-Features.aspx">http://www.baaqmd.gov/Divisions/Communications-and-Outreach/News-Media-and-Features.aspx</a></p>\n<p>\n Sent by:</p>\n<p>\n Bay Area Air Quality Management District<br />\n 939 Ellis Street<br />\n San Francisco, CA 94109<br />\n (415) 771-6000<br />\n &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n &nbsp;</p>', 'The Air District is announcing the beginning of the Winter Spare the Air season on November 1, making it illegal to burn wood, manufactured firelogs or any other solid fuel, both indoors and outdoors, when a Winter Spare the Air Alert is called.', 27, 1352174160),
(13, 'Free Film on Threats to California Forests', 1, 'live', 'Free-Film-on-Threats-to-California-Forests', '<p>There''s a free film being shown on Monday night at the Downtown Library, sponsored by the Sierra Club, about the condition and threats to our forests in California.</p>\nOur Beautiful California Forests.... Under Siege!<br />\nMonday, November 5, 2012 - 6:15 - 8:30 PM<br />\nRedwood City Library, 1044 Middlefield Road<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nSponsored by Sierra Club<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nDiscover the changes that are occurring to our magnificent Sierra Nevada forests and how you can help to protect these magnificent forests. Come and get motivated about how we can each make a big difference.<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nA light meal and dessert is included.<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nThere is no charge to attend, but RSVP via email to Karen Maki, <a href="mailto:karen.maki@lomaprieta.sierraclub.org">karen.maki@lomaprieta.sierraclub.org</a> or sign up online at Meetup.com.<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\n&nbsp;(sent by)<br />\n&nbsp;<br />\nMalcolm Smith<br />\nPublic Communications Manager<br />\nCity of Redwood City, California<br />\nOffice:&nbsp; 650.780.7305<br />\nEmail:&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="mailto:malcolm.smith@redwoodcity.org">malcolm.smith@redwoodcity.org</a><br />\nWeb:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.redwoodcity.org">www.redwoodcity.org</a><br />', 'There''s a free film being shown on Monday night at the Downtown Library, sponsored by the Sierra Club, about the condition and threats to our forests in California.', 27, 1352174700),
(14, 'November - Carbon Monoxide Awareness Month', 1, 'live', 'November---Carbon-Monoxide-Awareness-Month', '<p>\n Redwood City Fire Department Advisory - November is Carbon Monoxide Awareness Month&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n Contact:<br />\n Jim Palisi, Fire Marshal<br />\n Redwood City Fire Department</p>\n<p>\n 650-740-0827</p>\n<p>\nRedwood City, CA - As the colder weather starts to settle in and the use of fossil fuel heating increases, the Redwood City Fire Department reminds residents that November is Carbon Monoxide Awareness month.</p>\n<p>\n &nbsp;<br />\n Carbon monoxide (CO) is a colorless, odorless gas that is produced from heaters, fireplaces, furnaces, and many types of appliances and cooking devices. Each year, CO claims the lives of an average of 480 people, and sends more than 20,000 people to emergency rooms, nationwide. In Redwood City, there have been incidents of CO poisoning in recent years from in-house heating and furnaces, which have been life-threatening and nearly disastrous.&nbsp;<br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n The best way for homeowners to stay protected from CO is to have a carbon monoxide alarm installed on every floor and outside each sleeping area. A recent study found that nearly nine in 10 California households did not have a CO alarm. Combination CO/smoke alarms are available.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n As of July 1, 2011, state law requires owners of single family homes with attached garages or fossil fuel sources for heating to install carbon monoxide alarms in every California home.&nbsp; In addition, all other dwelling units, like apartments, are required to have an alarm by January 1, 2013.<br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n California''s Carbon Monoxide Month is intended to help educate homeowners about the law and to encourage them to install a carbon monoxide alarm. CAL FIRE / Office of the State Fire Marshal are teaming up with fire departments across the state, as well as other State agencies to spread the word about the dangers of CO and how to keep families and friends safe.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />\n &nbsp;<br />\n For more information on carbon monoxide visit the CAL FIRE website at <a href="http://www.fire.ca.gov">www.fire.ca.gov</a> or visit the website for the California Department of Public Health at <a href="http://www.cdph.ca.gov">www.cdph.ca.gov</a>. Visit the Redwood City Fire Department''s web page at <a href="http://www.redwoodcity.org/fire">www.redwoodcity.org/fire</a>.&nbsp;<br />\n &nbsp;<br />', 'Redwood City, CA - As the colder weather starts to settle in and the use of fossil fuel heating increases, the Redwood City Fire Department reminds residents that November is Carbon Monoxide Awareness month.', 27, 1352440800),
(15, 'Silicon Valley Power LED Bulb Contest', 1, 'live', 'Silicon-Valley-Power-LED-Bulb-Contest', '<p>Silicon Valley Power is holding a contest using old, inefficient bulb(s) to create a cool art project.<p>\n<p>\n Got a creative side and some old, incandescent bulbs? Want to win free LED light bulbs for your home? Silicon Valley Power is holding a contest to using old, inefficient bulb(s) to create a cool art project. The user who submits the most popular project wins free ENERGY STAR® LED light bulbs for their home. Up to a $200 value!<br />\n Entries are being accepted through December 7th and can be posted to SVP''s LED bulb contest Facebook page.</p>\n<p>\n The contest is open to all SVP residential customers.</p>', 'Silicon Valley Power is holding a contest using old, inefficient bulb(s) to create a cool art project.', 27, 1352778660),
(16, 'Holiday Book Talk: Gift Book Suggestions', 1, 'live', 'holiday-book-talk-gift-book-suggestions', '<p>\n Learn about great new books for adults and kids!<br />\n Date: 11/19/2012 6:30 PM - 7:45 PM<br />\n Cost: Free<br />\n Location: Central Park Library- Redwood Room<br />\n 2635 Homestead Road<br />\n Santa Clara, California 95051</p>\n<p>\n Jenn Ramage from Random House, Children''s Librarian Erin Ulrich, and Adult Services Librarian Mary Boyle, share their recommendations for new books to read and to gift this holiday season.<br />\n There will be a free raffle - the prize is a bag of newly released books! Please provide your name and email address at the event to sign up for raffle.<br />\n The event is free and open to the public.<br />\n This event is presented by the Foundation and Friends of the Santa Clara Library in partnership with the Santa Clara City Library and Random House.<br />\n Click here for the event flyer. <a >http://santaclaraca.gov/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=8058</a></p>\n<p>\n (Sent by)</p>\n<p>\n Web Manager <a href="mailto:webmanager@santaclaraca.gov">webmanager@santaclaraca.gov</a></p>', 'Learn about great new books for adults and kids!', 27, 1352872800),
(17, 'California Best Buildings Challenge', 1, 'live', 'California-Best-Buildings-Challenge', 'USGBC works with regional industry leaders in the high tech, biotech, and financial sectors, to develop the California Best Buildings Challenge, to leverage California’s culture of innovation and propel the green building movement forward worldwide.\n\nThe Challenge is part of a larger initiative, the Road to Greenbuild, which builds momentum and excitement in the region culminating in Greenbuild, the largest industry conference worldwide that will occur in San Francisco in November 2012 (35,000 attendees expected).\n\n Learn more about the event at http://ow.ly/fmgx0', '', 669, 1353045600),
(19, 'Silicon Valley Water Awards', 1, 'live', 'Silicon-Valley-Water-Awards', 'The application/nomination period for the 2013 Silicon Valley Water Conservation Awards is open until February 15, 2013.\n\nGo to www.waterawards.org for more details.\n\nRecognizing the primacy of water to the health and economic vitality of our region and the environment, the Silicon Valley Water Conservation Awards are presented to organizations, agencies, businesses and individuals whose programs and leadership have advanced water conservation in Silicon Valley (San Mateo County, Santa Clara County and Alameda County from Hayward South.) Our coalition of 20 organizations represents a diverse cross-section of respected parties concerned about water conservation and the need for a strategic response, both to droughts and to a new era of water scarcity. The goal of the Awards is to raise awareness and celebrate outstanding achievements in water conservation through best practices, efficiency and innovation.\n \nThis years award categories are:\nGovernment Agency / Water Utility\nBusiness\nOrganization\nGreenscape Management\nEducation\nWater Champion\n\nMark Your Calendars!\nThe 2013 Awards Ceremony will be held on World Water Day, March 22nd, 2013. Go to www.waterawards.org for more details.\n\nHosted by the Silicon Valley Water Conservation Coalition including the following organizations:\nActerra\nBay Area Water Supply and Conservation Agency\nCity of Cupertino\nCity of Hayward\nCity of Mountain View\nCity of Palo Alto\nCity of Redwood City\nCity of Sunnyvale\nClean Water Action\nCalifornia Native Plant Society\nJoint Venture: Silicon Valley Network\nPurissima Hills Water District\nSanta Clara County Creeks Coalition\nSanta Clara Valley Water District\nSierra Club Loma Prieta Chapter\nSilicon Valley Leadership Group\nSustainable San Mateo County\nSustainable Silicon Valley\nTuolumne River Trust\nWholly H2O', '', 11, 1353736800),
(21, 'Bay Area inspector wins prestigious awards', 0, 'live', 'bay-area-inspector-wins-prestigious-awards', 'The California Air Pollution Control Officers Association has recognized the outstanding accomplishments of Bay Area Air Quality Management District inspector Sal Rueda, as the recipient of the 2012 Rodney Swartzendruber Outstanding Inspector Award.\n\nThe award is given each year by CAPCOA''s Enforcement Managers'' Committee to three inspectors who work for the state''s 35 air quality management districts. It recognizes inspectors who consistently demonstrate outstanding performance and who make significant contributions that benefit air pollution control efforts in an exemplary way.\n \n http://www.baaqmd.gov/Divisions/Communications-and-Outreach/News-Media-and-Features.aspx\n\n(Sent by) \n\nBAAQMD webmaster@baaqmd.gov', 'The California Air Pollution Control Officers Association has recognized the outstanding accomplishments of Bay Area Air Quality Management District inspector Sal Rueda.', 4, 1353909600),
(22, 'Shoreline Regional Park Community Transportation Study community meeting scheduled', 1, 'live', 'shoreline-regional-park-community-transportation-study-community-meeting-scheduled', 'A community meeting to review and to comment on the preliminary transportation strategies identified to address the traffic impacts associated with anticipated development and employment growth in the City’s North Bayshore Area will be held on:\n\nWednesday, December 5, 20127:00 pm -- 9:00 pm Mountain View Public LibraryCommunity Room585 Franklin Street\n\nMembers of the public are encouraged to attend and comment on the long-term transportation strategies identified through the Shoreline Regional Park Community Transportation Study process.\n\nContact the Public Works Department at (650) 903-6311 or email public.works@mountainview.gov for additional information.', 'Community meeting to review and to comment on the preliminary transportation strategies identified to address the traffic impacts associated with anticipated development and employment growth in Mountain View', 4, 1353996000),
(23, 'Transportation Meeting @ City of Mountain View 12/5, 7-9 pm', 1, 'live', 'Transportation-Meeting-@-City-of-Mountain-View-12/5--7-9-pm', 'The City of Mountain View is holding a meeting on Wed. 12/15 from 7-9pm to invite public input into their study of transportation in the North Bayshore area in preparation to a final report to the City Council in early 2013. Please come if you want to learn more or make recommendations. The final report will be going to the City Council at the end of January 2013.', '', 9, 1354274943),
(24, 'The Nature of Materials with the Northern California Recycling Association', 1, 'live', 'The-Nature-of-Materials-with-the-Northern-California-Recycling-Association', 'Another very informative class put on by the Northern California Recycling Association.  This one-day class covered four major sectors in the recycling industry: plastic, paper, glass and metal.  Patty Moore from Moore Recycling Associates spoke on the recyclers’ viewpoint on plastics, covering the different types of plastics, expelling some common myths and presented some trends for the coming future in plastics recycling.  Susan Kinsella from Conservatree explored the manufacturing process and the properties of the many types of paper, the challenges facing the industry today and how the current paper recycling model isn’t the most effective for the varying paper sectors.  Phil Ross from Glass Industry Consulting Inc. presented glass from the manufacturing perspective, explaining the various types, their properties as well as highlighting the precise chemistry involved and how recycling adds to its complexity.  Scott Rubenstein from Alco Metals spoke on the business model they utilize in recycling metals, reviewing the metals they work with, the importance of understanding your markets and some issues that arise in their sector.  Like the Introduction to Recycling course put on by NCRA, this class provides a wealth of information from industry experts and is recommend for anyone from concerned citizens to business owners and career recyclers. Check out the Northern California Recycling Associations Website for their next great class.  www.ncrarecycles.org  \n\nHere are some interesting points to consider: \n\n• The plastic film recycling stations in front of grocery stores collects more then just plastic grocery bags; it is recycling for all Polyethylene (PE) plastic films.  Plastic film is not usually recycled from curbside but rather ends up in a landfill after more valuable materials are separated.  Collect your plastic film for the next trip to the store and get it back into the loop.  See plasticbagrecycling.org\n• The energy needed to produce a typical canvas bag is roughly equivalent to the energy needed to make 120 plastic bags, so you would need to re-use your canvas bags 120 times to start seeing a savings in energy.  With citywide bag bans, stores are no longer required to provide plastic film recycling to their customers, often taking away a main resource for plastic film recycling.  Are reusable bags and plastic bag bans a robust solution?  How many reusable bags do you have and are they all getting used?  What other considerations are there for the plastic ban?  How many bags actually get recycled and what is their downstream effect on the environment when they are not recycled?  \n• About 90% of manufactured office paper has no recycled content, yet its manufacturing is the hardest on the environment compared to other types of paper.  To make office paper from recycled content you need the left over scraps from its manufacturing (pre-consumer recycling) or segregated office paper of the same quality (post-consumer recycling).  Recycled office paper cannot be made from old corrugate cardboard, old newspaper and unlikely from shredded office paper due to contaminants that usually end up in the mix (e.g. staples, tape, plastics). For these reasons, office paper that is put in mixed paper recycling is essentially lost to office paper mills.  Even if offices were to keep their office paper separate, will their recycling service pick it up separately and then recycle it separately? Should offices plan recycling services accordingly?\n• Glass can theoretically be recycled an infinite number of times.  Manufactures want recycled glass but need consistent supply.  Precise measurements of glass components are needed to achieve desired product; making it difficult to recycle mixed color glass.  Color separated glass is a highly desirable feedstock for manufactures.', 'This one-day class covered four major sectors in the recycling industry: plastic, paper, glass and metal.', 695, 1354666320),
(25, 'Best Time for Tree Trimming', 1, 'live', 'Best-Time-for-Tree-Trimming', 'Did you know that right now is the best time to trim or prune trees?\n\nEach year the Wildlife Center of Silicon Valley receives a significant number of baby birds and squirrels who have been injured or orphaned by tree trimming and sadly many of them do not survive. In California, the winter season is the best time to trim or prune trees because by this time of the year, bird and squirrel babies have reached an age of self-sufficiency. Spring is the height of nesting season and also a time where trees are directing their energy into producing new growth.\n\nExceptions to the rule are when there are dead or diseased branches that may cause injury. These can be removed any time of the year. If trimming is required out of the winter season, be sure to check the area for nests before you cut. Cutting down or disturbing an active nest is in violation of California Department of Fish and Game Code sections 3503 and 3503.5.\n\nSquirrels nest twice a year from February to May and then again from July to September. If you see a big clump of leaves and twigs caught in the junction of two branches, it probably belongs to a squirrel. \n\nBird nests are smaller and harder to find. In the spring, look for a dark spot tucked among the smaller branches. If you ever find a nest with an egg or babies, always leave it alone. Under the Migratory Bird Treaty and the Endangered Species Act, it is illegal to harm or remove the nests of migratory and native birds, and most songbirds.', '', 165, 1355447811),
(26, 'Coexisting with Our Wild Neighbors', 1, 'live', 'Coexisting-with-Our-Wild-Neighbors', 'Because our valley provides excellent homes for many species of wildlife, chances are, you’ve encountered hummingbirds, opossums, and other wildlife in your neighborhood, your backyard, or at the office.\n\nAs human development progressively encroaches on wildlife habitat and open space, interactions between humans and wild animals become more common and inevitable. People turn to lethal control to remove "offending" or “nuisance” animals, despite the fact that many conflicts between people and wildlife can be mitigated by simple changes in human behavior. Please see below for five things you can do to help wildlife:\n\n1. Dispose of food in the proper trash receptacles. \n2. Pick up litter (plastic soda pack rings, glass, fishhooks, etc.) that might harm wildlife wherever you see it. Report illegal garbage dumps and pollution. \n3. Support open space initiatives that will preserve wildlife habitat.\n4. Plant native species in your garden and avoid chemicals (sprays and fertilizers) that will harm wildlife. \n5. Feed pets and other animals, such as stray or feral cats, during the daylight hours only and away from human activities. Remove food and water at the end of each day. Do not leave bowls out at night.\n\nFor additional information to prevent potential problems and help us coexist with our wild neighbors, visit www.wcsv.org/coexisting/.', '', 165, 1355448105),
(27, 'Holiday Tips', 1, 'live', 'Holiday-Tips', 'Enjoy hot drinks in a reusable mug, use a timer for string lights, have a marked recycling container at your holiday party, compost left-over food, and be aware of Winter Spare the Air Days (when wood burning is prohibited). \n\nLeft over cooking grease? Pour it from the pan to a can. Let cool or hardened, then scrape into the regular garbage. Grease should never be poured down the drain because it causes build up in the sanitary sewer line.\n\nBe a green Santa: wrap gifts in paper destined for the recycled bin (newspaper comics, old calendar pictures, and magazine pages), bring your own shopping bag, and reduce car trips by taking transit or carpooling with family and friends.\n\nMake a resolution to put your mailbox on a diet. Take control of junk mail. It’s easy, start here: https://sanjose.catalogchoice.org/', '', 165, 1355448261),
(28, 'Prevent Water Pollution During the Wet Season (and always)', 1, 'live', 'Prevent-Water-Pollution-During-the-Wet-Season-(and-always)', 'When rain water flows over impervious surfaces like paved streets and parking lots, it can collect debris, chemicals, sediment and other pollutants that go directly into our storm water systems. Any water that goes into the storm drain is untreated and flows straight to our local watersheds.\n\nCheck your vehicles for leaks! Even a small leak can have a big impact.  One gallon of oil can contaminate 1,000,000 gallons of water. \n\nIf you see litter, pick it up before the rain washes it down the gutter. Once litter gets into our water ways it is nearly impossible to clean it up.', '', 165, 1355448515),
(29, 'Job Opportunities', 0, 'live', 'Job-Opportunities', 'Here are some really exciting job opportunities in the area of Sustainability at Global Footprint Network!\nhttp://www.footprintnetwork.org/en/index.php/GFN/page/job_opportunities/', 'The Global Footprint Network provides tools and programs that can help countries thrive in a resource-constrained world. See the link to learn more about opportunities in Oakland and Geneva.', 669, 1355523948),
(31, 'Rainwater harvesting the How To for Businesses and Home Owners', 1, 'live', 'rainwater-harvesting-the-how-to-for-businesses-and-home-owners', 'It''s winter and hopefully more rain is still to come! Help us save our precious potable water by installing rainwater barrels or cisterns. See below for some resources to aid you in doing this and for rebate programs available now! Businesses and homeowners can install them! \n<strong>Rainwater Harvesting Local Incentives:</strong> \n\nSome Cities have Rebates - check your utility to see if they are available. Some cities that have rebates are: \n<a href="http://www.cityofpaloalto.org/gov/depts/pwd/stormwater/rebates/cisterns.asp?BlobID=14858">Palo Alto Rainwater Business and home Incentive Program</a>: Install a rainwater cistern and receive a rebate of 15 cents per gallon \n<a href="http://www.ci.millbrae.ca.us/index.aspx?page=231">City of Millbrae Rainwater Harvesting Rebate Program</a> \nThese programs have sold out for this year but get on their mailing lists to be advised of future rebates: <a href="http://sfwater.org/index.aspx?page=178">SF PUC Rainwater Program</a>; \n<a href="http://www2.oaklandnet.com/Government/o/PWA/o/EC/s/CreeksandWatershed/OAK025822">Oakland Free Rain Barrel Program</a> \nFor other locations see: <a href="http://www.harvesth2o.com/incentives.shtml">Residential Rainwater and Water Conservation Incentives by State</a> \n<strong>Other Resources: </strong> <a >Bay Area Stormwater Management Agencies Association (BASMAA) Rain Barrels and Cisterns Brochure </a>\n\n<a href="http://sfwater.org/index.aspx?page=178">SF PUC Rainwater Program</a>- has a calculator to help you size your rainwater system, a how-to video, and instructional brochures and handouts. \n\nFrom: <a href="http://www.WhollyH2O.org">www.WhollyH2O.org</a> See: <a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater-stormwater/rainwater-res.html">Rainwater Harvesting - Resources for Residential Users</a> \n<a href="http://www.arcsa.org/content.asp?pl=6&contentid=6">American Rainwater Catchment Systems Association</a> \n\nA NOTE ABOUT PERMITTING: Some systems don''t require permits! In the current updated plumbing code that is in effect on an emergency basis code includes rainwater harvesting under Chapter 17 and allowance for unpermitted tanks has been raised from 250 gallons to 5000. For installing a cistern for irrigation or toilet flushing, a plumbing permit or building permit might be required. \nThe long delayed updated California State residential and commercial greywater plumbing code was approved by the California Building Standards Commission on an emergency basis on August 4 and will remain effective for 180 days, while the Department of Housing and Community Development (HDC) holds public hearings. For more information on the revised code and to read all of the guidelines, go to the <a href="http://www.hcd.ca.gov/codes/shl/graywater_emergency.html">HDC website</a> and check out <a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/daily-stream/item/428-update-on-the-california-residential-and-commercial-graywater-code-rewrite.html">this blog</a> on <a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org">http://www.whollyh2o.org</a> \nThese systems can be decorative and functional! \n<a href="http://www.scvurppp-w2k.com/workshop_june_17_2009/Krupp-Mills_College-Rainwater_Harvesting.pdf">Check out Mills College Rainwater Harvesting System</a>', 'It''s winter and hopefully more rain is still to come! Help us save our precious potable water by installing rainwater barrels or cisterns. See below for some resources to aid you in doing this and for rebate programs available now! Businesses and homeowners can install them!', 11, 1355895900),
(34, 'Invitation to Enter Call for Solutions (closes 1/31/2013)', 0, 'live', 'invitation-to-enter-call-for-solutions-closes-1312013', 'Collectively, human beings and our industrial society are destroying the life support systems of the planet. This is not inevitable. Human genius and creativity can be used to heal and repair and even strengthen these systems. Sustainable Silicon Valley and our partners, including NASA Ames Research Center, Silver Spring Networks and Microsoft are collaborating on a conference that will be held in Silicon Valley on May 23, 2013 to explore in-depth, solutions that can yield planetary sustainability. \n\nInvitation to Action \nWe invite you to share your solutions by Jan. 31, 2013 that can contribute to planetary sustainability. Do you have a technology, policy or behavior-changing proposal that is scalable and game-changing? If so, please enter the Call for Solutions. Your idea will be posted on the EcoCloud website to stimulate dialog with other concerned people around the world. The most promising solutions will be selected as finalists to be presented at the conference on May 23, 2013. Winners will be selected for special recognition by a panel of distinguished experts from a wide range of fields. We are especially interested in approaches that span domains (such as energy and water). The conference will include time for match-making among solution inventors and potential funders and integrators with the goal of creating ecosystems of solutions, and building momentum for implementation and action.\n\nWhat are Planetary Life Support Systems?\nPlanet Earth is made up of many interwoven systems that create an environment conducive to life. For example, rich soils, full of microorganisms and communities of insects and invertebrates, make it possible for trees, grasses and other plants to grow. The soil absorbs water and releases it slowly, to reduce floods and withstand dry seasons. Tree roots hold the soil in place to resist erosion from wind and rain. Larger animals graze on the plants and keep those populations in check. Predators and disease keep the plant-eating animals from over-grazing, yielding a dynamic equilibrium among species. \n\nThese systems affect each other. For example, plant canopies help keep the surface temperatures of the earth comfortable for living creatures. They serve as the lungs of the planet, breathing in carbon dioxide and breathing out oxygen. The atmosphere around the planet moderates storm intensity and precipitation patterns. As human industry burns forests to clear them for agriculture and burns fossil fuels for energy, we have changed the chemistry of the atmosphere, adding huge amounts of carbon dioxide, methane and other gases that create a green house effect, warming the surface temperature of the oceans and land and creating changes in precipitation and other weather patterns that have resulted in catastrophic storms, floods, droughts, heat waves, and wind that cause damage to crops, property and lives. \n\nThe chemistry of the oceans are changed as they absorb huge quantities of carbon dioxide, becoming more acidic and less hospitable to the microscopic life forms that are the base of the aquatic food chain. Over fishing and extensive pollution from plastic waste and toxic chemicals, such as agricultural run-off, also is threatening the health and productivity of the oceans.\n\nMany other systems allow the basis for human agriculture and civilization to exist and flourish. It is up to us to invest in the health and well-being of these systems over the long-term, and not just extract resources for short term use and profit. Self-restraint through social norms, the rule of law, taxes on “externalities”; technology that can reuse and recycle resources and generate energy from sun and wind; and, cultivation of a culture of conservation are some of the ways that humanity can shift towards truly sustainable civilization. Now is the time. Join us at WEST Summit 2013.', 'Humans and industrial society are destroying the life support systems of the planet. This is not inevitable. Human genius and creativity can be used to heal, repair and strengthen these systems. Join SSV, NASA Ames Research Center, Silver Spring Networks & Microsoft at the WEST Summit on 5/23/2013 to explore solutions for planetary sustainability.', 9, 1356917520),
(35, 'Applied Materials Increases Purchase of Clean Renewable Energy', 1, 'live', 'Applied-Materials-Increases-Purchase-of-Clean-Renewable-Energy', 'Silicon Valley Power (SVP), the City of Santa Clara''s municipal electric utility, announced today that Applied Materials, Inc., the global leader in providing manufacturing solutions for the semiconductor, flat panel display and solar photovoltaic industries, will increase its purchase of clean renewable energy to match 100% of the electricity used at its Santa Clara headquarters. Applied Materials began purchasing green power in 2007 and is now SVP''s largest purchaser of Santa Clara Green Power, a renewable energy program that provides 100 percent clean wind and solar power resources.\n\nWith an annual renewable power commitment of 45 million kilowatt-hours, the company''s Santa Clara facility is now a Leadership Club member of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency''s (EPA) Green Power Partnership for its Santa Clara headquarters. Applied Materials'' green power commitment to 100% of its electricity use at its headquarters represents a five-fold increase over last year.\n\n"Applied Materials continues to demonstrate its leadership in sustainability, and we are proud to have the company as a long-term and active partner in the Santa Clara Green Power program," said Larry Owens, Division Manager of Silicon Valley Power.\n\nUsing EPA calculations, Applied Materials'' clean power commitment is projected to help avoid more than 31,132 metric tons of carbon dioxide-equivalent emissions, a key greenhouse gas, which is equal to the annual greenhouse gas emissions from 6,104 passenger cars, or the carbon sequestered annually by more than 6,638 acres of pine or fir forests. With its commitment, the company''s purchase of Santa Clara Green Power is now the equivalent of more than the annual output of 14 large-scale wind turbines.\n\n"Conventional electricity usage is the nation''s single largest industrial source of greenhouse gas emissions in the U.S.," said Blaine Collison, Director of EPA''s Green Power Partnership. "By increasing its commitment to purchase green power, Applied Materials will reduce its carbon footprint and help advance the market for cleaner, renewable resources."\n\n"Applied Materials is honored to be recognized as a corporate leader in using energy responsibly throughout our business to reduce impacts to the environment and in minimizing greenhouse gas emissions by giving preference to renewable energy sources," said Phil Naughton, Corporate Energy Manager at Applied Materials. "We are proud to be making this investment to help grow our business responsibly and in a sustainable fashion."\n\nAbout Applied Materials\nApplied Materials, Inc. (Nasdaq:AMAT) is the global leader in providing innovative equipment, services and software to enable the manufacture of advanced semiconductor, flat panel display and solar photovoltaic products. Our technologies help make innovations like smartphones, flat screen TVs and solar panels more affordable and accessible to consumers and businesses around the world. Learn more at www.appliedmaterials.com.\n\nAbout Silicon Valley Power\nSilicon Valley Power is the trademark adopted for use by the not-for-profit electric municipal utility of Santa Clara, CA serving residents and businesses for over 100 years. SVP provides power to more than 50,000 customers, including Applied Materials, Intel, Owens Corning and Yahoo!, at rates 15 to 45 percent below neighboring communities.\nVisit siliconvalleypower.com for more information.\n\nAbout Santa Clara Green Power\nSanta Clara Green Power is a voluntary renewable energy program offered by Silicon Valley Power to all of its residential, commercial and industrial customers as a way to support energy generated from 100 percent clean wind and solar power resources at a low additional cost of 1.5 cents per kilowatt-hour. Santa Clara utility customers can enroll in Santa Clara Green Power by signing up through the secure website at www.siliconvalleypower.com/green or by calling 408.244.SAVE (7283).\n\nContact:\nLarry Owens\nSilicon Valley Power\nPhone: 408.621.5873\nEmail: LOwens@SantaClaraCA.gov  \n\nDan Beerman\nCity of Santa Clara\nTel: 408.615.2228', 'Applied Materials Increases Purchase of Clean Renewable Energy from Silicon Valley Power Company, joins Leadership Club of the U.S. EPA''s Green Power Partnership.', 27, 1357738800);
