(21, 4, 0, 0, 0, 1359167400, 1359174600, 'Plug and Play Tech Center 440 N. Wolfe Road, Sunnyvale, CA', 'Innovation in Clean Energy: The Story of Battery, Solar and Fuel Cell', 'In his famous new book The Third Industrial Revolution, social scientist Jeremy Rifkin depicts us an attractive future blueprint of human society, in which abundant clean energy is produced and consumed in a decentralized manner thanks to the solar panels, wind turbines, and fuel cells installed in households and corporate buildings—all of these enabled by the advancements in material and energy technology.\n\nRegister at : http://chainnewmaterial-erec.eventbrite.com/?rank=20#', ''),
(22, 838, 0, 0, 0, 1361381400, 1361403000, 'Santa Clara Valley Water District 5700 Almaden Expressway San Jose, CA 95118', 'Commercial, Industrial, and Institutional Recycled Water Use Workshops', 'The WateReuse Industrial Reuse Committee Presents\nCommercial, Industrial, and Institutional Recycled Water Use Workshop\nFee: $175\n\nTo register for the workshop, visit:\nwww.watereuse.org/conferences/california/industrial\n\nJOIN BUSINESS OWNERS, PLANT ENGINEERS, UTILITY MANAGERS, CONSULTANTS and other industry experts to learn how to save money and make your facility "green" with recycled water.\n\nIn this one-day workshop, you''ll find out how to maximize recycled water use in cooling\nand manufacturing, overcome challenges and banish any doubts about the value\nof this important resource. Long used for landscape irrigation, high-quality recycled\nwater is now successfully used throughout the country for a variety of process and\ninternal applications.\n\nThe workshop will also allow businesses, utilities and consultants to meet together\nto see how we can assist each other to improve the reliability of our local water\nsupplies. Along with technical presentations highlighting case studies of successful\nindustrial uses, you''ll also hear about the progress made by the California Department\nof Water Resources’ CII Task Force and their new manual of best management\npractices for sustainable use of water in the CII sector.\n\nCo-Sponsored by: SCSC (Southern California Salinity Coalition)', '');
