(838, 'default', 63, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean and Carey Chen</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Water Lead</author>\n<h3>\n	<b>January 2012</b></h3>\n<p>\n	<i>For a more detailed &amp; and up to date review of new metrics, refer to our</i> <a href="http://sustainablesv.org/EcoCloud/WaterMetricsFrameworksReport.pdf" target="_blank">Water Metrics Report</a><i> </i><i>and the</i> tables on <a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/metrics-reporting" target="_blank">EcoCloud Water Metrics</a></p>\n<h2>\n	Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) – Water Performance Indicators</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/Pages/default.aspx">https://www.globalreporting.org/Pages/default.aspx</a><br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> GRI produces and continuously updates a "comprehensive sustainability reporting framework" that is one of the most used reporting framework in the world. The G3 Guidelines are made up of two parts. Part 1 features guidance on how to report. Part 2 features guidance on what should be reported, in the form of Disclosures on Management Approach and Performance Indicators. There are three water indicators:</p>\n<p>\n	1) Total water withdrawal by source</p>\n<p>\n	2) Water sources significantly affected by withdrawal of water</p>\n<p>\n	3) Percentage and total volume of water recycled and reused</p>\n<p>\n	As of early November 2011, 3000+ organizations around the world have adopted the GRI framework, resulting in 7,600+ GRI sustainability reports.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> For-profit corporations, NGOs, non-profit organizations, universities, gov’t agencies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> GRI<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> Standardized reporting format that gives guidelines and boundaries to the process of sustainability</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> first version of Sustainability Reporting Guidelines released in 2000 (currently in process of developing v.4)<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> financial reporting, sustainability reporting, water metrics, water-performance indicators</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Continuous update/refinement of framework, sector-specific metrics, combo of quantitative and qualitative metrics, standardized framework <span class="font-size-2"><strong>• improves caparability</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Lengthy process to generate a report, leading to significant resource commitment and GRI report adopters tend to be larger corporations with sufficient financial and HR means; metrics beget metrics – reports often run hundreds of pages, making it difficult to summarize and parse info; annual reporting timeframe may be too long for timely decision-making; voluntary audit of reports.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Sustainability Programs</strong></span>: The G3 sustainability Performance Indicators are organized into 3 categories: <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/resourcelibrary/G3-EconomicIndicatorProtocols.pdf">Economic</a>, <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/resourcelibrary/G3-Environment-Indicator-Protocols.pdf">Environmental</a> and Social ( <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/resourcelibrary/G3-Labor-Indicator-Protocols.pdf">Labor</a>, <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/resourcelibrary/G3-Human-Rights-Indicator-Protocols.pdf">Human Rights</a>, <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/resourcelibrary/G3-Society-Indicator-Protocols.pdf">Society</a> and <a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/resourcelibrary/G3-Product-Responsibility-Indicator-Protocols.pdf">Product Responsibility</a> subcategories)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> financial-reporting, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics, water-performance-indicators</p>\n<h2>\n	CDP - Water Disclosure</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/water.aspx">https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/water.aspx</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> "CDP Water Disclosure provides critical water-related data from the world’s largest corporations to inform the global market place on investment risk and commercial opportunity. Companies targeted are the:</p>\n<p>\n	largest 500 companies globally (the FTSE Global Equity Index Series)</p>\n<p>\n	largest 100 Australian companies (the ASX 100)</p>\n<p>\n	largest 100 South African companies (the JSE 100)</p>\n<p>\n	The 2011 report includes data from 354 financial institutions with assets of US$43T.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> business organizations, institutional investors, government</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> CDP, with companies disclosing relevant info on a voluntary basis.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> report published every November<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> financial reporting, sustainability reporting, water metrics, Best Management Practices , finance</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Continuous refinement of water questionnaire; integration with GRI and GHG Protocol; combination of quantitative and qualitative metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Voluntary nature may skew resulting aggregate data; findings are only for the largest companies in the world or companies with the HR means to dedicate resources to project</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Sustainable Programs</strong></span> Carbon disclosure &amp; information on climate change for large investors, cities, corporations, public entities; Global Corporations climate change impacts within supply chain</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> financial-reporting, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics, Best-Management-Practices, finance</p>\n<h2>\n	Institute for Supply Management (ISM) Sustainability and Social Responsibility Metrics and Performance Criteria (Document)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.ism.ws/Files/SR/Metrics.pdf">http://www.ism.ws/Files/SR/Metrics.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> List of sustainability and CSR Metrics and performance criteria (5 pages) for "(1) supply organization, (2) entity and (3) supply base (e.g., first tier and beyond, transportation services, etc.)"; <a href="http://www.ism.ws/">ISM website</a> includes best practices, guides, "How-tos", and links to green purchasing websites about sustainability, energy, water, and CSR related to supply management</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> supply professionals and management</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Institute of Supply Management (ISM); "largest" supply management professional association; ISM''s mission is to lead the supply management profession through its standards of excellence, research, promotional activities, and education<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> last updated on February 16, 2011<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> financial reporting, sustainability reporting, water metrics, Best Management Practices</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> emphasis on supply chain management; more resources maybe available to members only</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> criteria document list only; serves as guide only</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> financial-reporting, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics, Best-Management-Practices</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(839, 'default', 70, '<p data-mce-style="text-align: center;">\n	<b>by Mary Kean and Carey Chen</b></p>\n<p data-mce-style="text-align: center;">\n	January 2012</p>\n<p>\n	<i>For a more detailed &amp; and up to date review of new metrics, refer to our</i> <a data-mce-="" href="http://sustainablesv.org/EcoCloud/WaterMetricsFrameworksReport.pdf" target="_blank"><i>Water Metrics Report</i></a><i>&nbsp;</i><i>and&nbsp;the</i> tables on <a data-mce-="" href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/metrics-reporting" target="_self">EcoCloud Water Metrics</a></p>\n<h2>\n	Climate Resilience Evaluation &amp; Awareness Tool (CREAT)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <b><a data-mce-="" href="http://water.epa.gov/infrastructure/watersecurity/climate/creat.cfm">Climate Resilience Evaluation &amp; Awareness Tool (CREAT)</a></b><br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> " EPA has developed CREAT, a software tool to assist drinking water and wastewater utility owners and operators in understanding potential climate change threats and in assessing the related risks at their individual utilities. CREAT provides users with access to the most recent national assessment of climate change impacts for use in considering how these changes will impact utility operations and missions"<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> water/wastewater utility owners and operators</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> United States. Environmental Protection Agency<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Dec 17, 2010<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> Adaption, drought, rain, precipitation, flooding, water quality, water supply, changes in supply, snowpack, water utilities guidance, models and tools</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Contains info at regional and local levels; provides suggested adaptation strategies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Too narrow in scope; CREAT is only for drinking water and wastewater utility owners and operators; meant to be a stand-alone risk assessment tool – does not allow integration with other tools</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Adaption, drought, rain, precipitation, flooding, water-quality, water-supply, changes-in-supply, snowpack, water-utilities-guidance, models-and-tools</p>\n<h2>\n	For More Climate Change Resources Related to Water:</h2>\n<p>\n	<a data-mce-="" href="http://cf.valleywater.org/Water/Where_Your_Water_Comes_From/Water%20Supply%20and%20Infrastructure%20Planning/Climate%20Change/portal.cfm">Santa Clara Valley Water District Climate Change Portal</a></p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(841, 'default', 37, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Water Lead</author>\n<p style="margin-top: 0.19in; margin-bottom: 0.19in;">\n	<font size="3"><strong><font color="#808080">March 22, 2012</font></strong></font></p>\n<p style="margin-top: 0.19in; margin-bottom: 0.19in;">\n	<font size="3">This section&nbsp;summarizes the evaluation of water management tools, metrics and frameworks to help businesses and organizations measure and improve water cost, environmental impacts and implement best management practices. This includes detailed reviews of online and downloadable tools, standards, guidance, software, certification schemes, and case studies of organizations who have used them.</font>Our methodology is organized into 3 categories by project type, purpose, and audience.</p>\n<p style="margin-top: 0.19in; margin-bottom: 0.19in;">\n	See our <span class="font-size-2" style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong><a href="http://sustainablesv.org/ECDocs/WaterMetricsFrameworksReport.pdf" target="_blank">Water Metrics Report(March 2012).pdf</a></strong></span>&nbsp;for a more detailed review of these resources.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://sustainablesv.org/ECDocs/Water_Metrics_Summary_All.pdf">Table 1: Summary of All Water Metrics</a><br />\n	<a href="http://sustainablesv.org/ECDocs/Water_Metrics_Summary_CII.pdf">Table 2: Summary of CII Water Metrics</a><br />\n	<a href="http://sustainablesv.org/ECDocs/Water_Metrics_Summary_ResidentialBuilding.pdf">Table 3: Summary of Residential and Building Owner Water Metrics</a><br />\n	<a href="http://sustainablesv.org/ECDocs/Water_Metrics_Summary_Utilities.pdf" target="_self">Table 4: Summary of Water Metrics for Utilities</a></p>\n<table cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">\n	<colgroup>\n		<col width="86*" />\n		<col width="83*" />\n		<col width="87*" />\n	</colgroup>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td colspan="3" height="14" width="100%">\n				<p align="center">\n					<span class="font-si