(866, 'default', 62, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean, PE\n<p>\n	<b>January 2012</b></p>\n<p>\n	This "Water Metrics and Tool" section includes water metric guidelines, tools (excel, interactive maps, online tools), and reports about water accounting, risk evaluation, benchmarking, measuring and certification systems. See the section on <a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/water-management-software-it" target="_self">Water Management Software / I</a>T for specific software applications regarding water and energy.</p>\n<p>\n	<i>For a more detailed &amp; up to date review of each item, refer to</i> <a href="http://sustainablesv.org/EcoCloud/WaterMetricsFrameworksReport.pdf" target="_blank"><i>Water Metrics Report (pdf)</i></a><i> </i><i>and a quick reference on the tables accessible</i> on <a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/metrics-reporting" target="_blank">EcoCloud Water Metrics</a></p>\n<h2>\n	The Alliance for Water Stewardship (AWS) Certification Program</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.allianceforwaterstewardship.org/">http://www.allianceforwaterstewardship.org/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool or Metric:</strong></span> certification standard for water managers (under development)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> AWS is working with water authorities, companies, local communities and environmentalists to establish a voluntary freshwater stewardship certification program; This program will include an "eco-label" and require quantification of water use, discharge, and impacts; Standard will based on: 1) International standards, 2) Verification to determine whether these standards have been met., 3) A global brand demonstrates compliance with or support for water stewardship.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> standard to apply to utilities and organizations (businesses, CII); Used by water managers companies, &amp; communities; international; North American Chapter started 2011</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> AWS; A non-profit; Board orgs include: The Nature Conservancy, The Water Stewardship Australia, Pacific Institute, WWF, Water Witness Int’l, European Water Partnership, Water Environment Federation, Int’l Water Mgmt Institute, UN CEO Water Mandate, CDP.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> promote responsible use that is both socially beneficial and environmentally sustainable</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> formed in 2008; working on certification program<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, certification</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> represents various stakeholders (as of July 2011: The Nature Conservancy, WWF, Water Stewardship Australia, Water Witness International, the Water Environment Federation, the Pacific Institute, the European Water Partnership, CDP, the International Water Management Institute (IWMI), UN’s CEO Water Mandate)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> aims to reward water users/managers who "take significant steps to minimize their water use and impacts", but could lead to conflict of interest and bias; lacks specifics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, certification</p>\n<h2>\n	American Water Works Association (AWWA) Water Conservation Measurement Metrics Guidance Report</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.awwa.org/files/Publications/Streamlines/2010/030210/AWWA%20Metrics%20Guidance%20Report%20Jan-22-2010%20Final%20_3_.pdf">http://www.awwa.org/files/Publications/Streamlines/2010/030210/AWWA%20Metrics%20Guidance%20Report%20Jan-22-2010%20Final%20_3_.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The purpose of the report is to identify and characterize a set of water use and conservation metrics for public water supply utilities. These metrics could be used as measurement tools to evaluate the effects of water efficiency programs over time in a single utility. Some metrics can also be used to compare water use and conservation effects across different utilities. This report provides guidance on standardized methods of calculating specific metrics and describes their advantages and limitations.</p>\n<p>\n	The report includes data from seven U.S. water utilities.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> public water supply utilities</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> AWWA</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> January 2010<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics, water-conservation</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> detailed water use accounting; methodology appears to be sound; metrics developed with conservation as end goal; provides pro and con of each selected metric</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> may need larger pilot study to further demonstrate metrics’ usefulness</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	Energy Index Development for Benchmarking Water and Wastewater Utilities Report (AWWA Research Foundation)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.waterrf.org/ProjectsReports/PublicReportLibrary/91201.pdf">http://www.waterrf.org/ProjectsReports/PublicReportLibrary/91201.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description :</strong></span> This 190 page report sets out to review , assess, and develop energy metrics <span class="font-size-2"><strong>•</strong></span> that allow comparison of energy use among water and wastewater treatment plants through a scoring method.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> water utilities, wastewater treatment plant operators; water consultants</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> AWWA Research Foundation dedicated to drinking water research;<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> 2007<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> water energy, benchmarking, wastewater, water-metric, energy-metric</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> well-researched, academic approach; applicable to existing plants</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> TBD</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Sustainable Programs</strong></span>: Over $460 million in research, more than 1000 projects in the health, infrastructure, management, treatment technologies, and water resources for water utilities</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> water-energy, benchmarking, wastewater</p>\n<h2>\n	(In Progress) Aquawareness – European Water Stewardship Program (EWS)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.ewp.eu/activities/water-stewardship/">http://www.ewp.eu/activities/water-stewardship/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool or Metric:</strong></span> Certification and Assessment framework using indicators to indentify risks/impacts to business and water ecosystem. The final system (expected 2013) will include the EWS standard (glossary and guidelines, case studies of best management practices), inspection and certification system (checklists, ranking system), and communication guidelines.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> Voluntary system to assess/certify and communicate about Sustainable Water Management by an organization, industry, agricultural user, or urban area. The certification system will include assessing a water user’s performance on-site and within the referring river basin. The draft certification as of December 2011 consists of 4 sustainable water management principles and 53 indicators which are ranked. These 4 principles area: 1) achieve and maintain sustainable water quantity 2) biological/chemical sustainability (toxicity of chemicals), 3) restore/preserve "high conservation value areas" (sensitive ecosystems), 4) equitable/transparency water governance</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> EWS System implementation pilot studies will include industries, agriculture, and urban areas to be used by CII<b>,</b> public authorities, agricultural users, &amp; inter-governmental agencies in Europe</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> EWP, a non-profit organization; structured to include cross-sectoral organizations to give water one common "voice" in Europe. Partners include government, innovators, water utilities, and researchers on multiple cross-collaboration projects.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> Water Stewardship Program objectives are to provide an evaluation of the strong/weak points of the water management on-site, and identify the response strategy that will have the highest impact on the referring watershed and to stimulate the reality of a third party certification system. EWP’s aquawareness objectives are (1) create a common vision for water in Europe with widely accepted principles for sustainable water management, (2) set sights on changing behavior and practices, (3) shape and integrates water into policy and strategy agendas, (4) create a water saving and efficiency culture among private, industrial, business and agricultural users, (5) support the shift from supply to demand management through information, education and training.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> established in 2008; Developed draft indicators 2008-2011; Pilot Programs (2010-2012) and full implementation expected 2013.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, public policy, case studies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> EWS good for identification of water strategies at the operational level; in line with and complementary to other environmental certification schemes, raise awareness;; unites various stakeholders across Europe; provides uniform framework and vision for many countries; supports education and training effort</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations: EWS</strong></span> checklists &amp; list of indicators not available on website (Dec 2011); Vision 2030 may be too long-term to be effective for timely actions now</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Sustainable Programs:</strong></span> Includes a vision 2030 for Europe Water multiple public-private collaboration projects around sustainable water management <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/environment/water/blueprint/index_en.htm">Europeon Commission Environment’s water blueprint</a>, <a href="http://www.europe-innova.eu">INNOWATER</a> (collaboration to identify and implement innovative water technology (3 year project 2010-2012), and <a href="http://www.stream-project.eu/about-stream">STREAM</a> project communication project between research and policy on Aquatic management research.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, certification public-policy</p>\n<h2>\n	Beverage Industry Environmental Roundtable (BIER)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://bieroundtable.com/water_stewardship.html">http://bieroundtable.com/water_stewardship.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool or Metric</strong></span><b>:</b> Sector specific water use guidelines; benchmarking; water footprinting guidelines (in development; Dec 2011)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The mission of the roundtable is to define a common framework for stewardship, drive continuous improvement practices and performance, and inform public policy in the areas of Water Conservation and Resource Protection, Energy Efficiency, and Climate Change Mitigation. Annual quantitative and qualitative benchmarking is completed on select aspects of the BIER-developed World Class Water Stewardship in the Beverage Industry. Results are consolidated, patterned, and collectively analyzed at Roundtable meetings. To date, the benchmarking has included data from over 1,100 beverage facilities, including breweries, distilleries, wineries, and bottling sites. A working group has been formulated to continually improve benchmarking processes and methodologies.</p>\n<p>\n	Current BIER members include: American Beverage Association, Anheuser-Busch InBev, Bacardi Limited, Beam Global Spirits &amp; Wine, Brown-Forman Corporation, Carlsberg Group, The Coca-Cola Company, Diageo, Diversey, Groupe Danone, Ecolab, Heineken, MillerCoors, Molson Coors Brewing Company, Nestlé Waters, New Belgium Brewing Company, Ocean Spray Cranberries, Pernod Ricard and PepsiCo.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> beverage industry companies and supporting partners</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> BIER</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> first convened in 2006<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> powerful coalition of companies may lead to significant changes; gov’t engagement</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Trade group ploy or something "real"? Does not use LCA approach in water accounting</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	CA Commercial, Institutional, and Industrial (CII) State Task Force Report including Case Studies, and Metrics</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.cuwcc.org/2column.aspx?id=16620">http://www.cuwcc.org/2column.aspx?id=16620</a><br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> State Task force developing alternative best management practices (BMPs) for Commercial, Industrial, and Institutional (CII) water users include metrics, best management practices, case studies, and water saving potentials.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Facility Managers, consultants, regulators, and anyone who is interested in water best management practices and possible reductions in water use in CII; will include actual case studies of success stories of CII that completed reductions in water use or potable water use and utilized innovative technologies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> CII Task Force as appointed by the State Legislature; Coordinated by CA Department of Water Resources with input from multi-stakeholder group including regulators, utilities, researchers, consultants, and representatives from CII organizations<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> To be completed by April 2011 and presented to State Legislature<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, water metrics, water conservation, case studies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> TBD</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> TBD</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-metrics, water-conservation, case-studies</p>\n<h2>\n	The California Water Sustainability Indicators Framework</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.waterplan.water.ca.gov/docs/meeting_materials/workshop/08.24.11/CWP_SIF_Draft_Framework_Jul20_11.pdf">http://www.waterplan.water.ca.gov/docs/meeting_materials/workshop/08.24.11/CWP_SIF_Draft_Framework_Jul20_11.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Framework is composed of a cycle of process steps that build upon each other. The cycle begins with defining what is meant by sustainability and other terms and completes one cycle by informing policy and decision‐making. The process is intended to be part of a cycle of adaptive learning and action. The indicators and the process of developing, analyzing, and interpreting them are not intended to stand alone, so links are described with regional planning, ecosystem services, and water footprint. Process could be used by others to implement water sustainability initiatives and be used to guide public policy.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> water authorities, water managers and users, companies, communities</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> The California Water Plan, part of CA DWR; Participating stakeholders include: CA Dept of Water Resources, EPA, Water Plan’s Statewide Water Analysis Network, Sustainable Water Resources Roundtable, State Agency Steering Committee, Water Plan Public Advisory Committee, Regional Forums, Tribal Advisory Committee, and Federal Agency Network.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> draft dated July 20, 2011<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, sustainability reporting, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> starts from fundamentals (e.g. definition of sustainability, etc.); detailed and summary reports; linked to ecological footprints; scenario planning</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> applicability to other regions; project scope too wide?</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	Ceres Aqua Gauge</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.ceres.org/issues/water/aqua-gauge/aqua-gauge">http://www.ceres.org/issues/water/aqua-gauge/aqua-gauge</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Ceres Aqua Gauge provides a framework and tool for assessing corporate water risk management. It is an Excel-based tool that "allows investors to scorecard a company''s water management activities against detailed definitions of leading practice. The tool also benefits companies by giving them a resource to inform and strengthen their own water management strategies."<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Investors (incl. 1) Portfolio managers and analysts, 2) governance specialists, and 3) financial and ESG data providers) and business organizations</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Ceres<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Released in October 2011<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, benchmarking, financial, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Flexible – Allows for both rapid and more comprehensive analysis; continuously updated to reflect advances in water management practices and ongoing stakeholder feedback; simple, clear one-page scorecard</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Primary aim is to provide a quick guide to engage equity investors, which means the underlying methodology may not be as rigorous or comprehensive; mostly qualitative questions in assessment</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, financial, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	Corporate Water Gauge (CWG)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.sustainableorganizations.org/Water-Gauge-FAQs.pdf">http://www.sustainableorganizations.org/Water-Gauge-FAQs.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> CWG is a context-based water metric that consists of (1) a spreadsheet-based measure of water use that compares the water consumption of an organization or facility with an allocation of available renewable water supplies relative to volume of water, per employee, or per revenue, (2) a GIS technique for measuring and allocating renewable water supplies in watersheds, and (3) a consulting service for teaching and/or assisting with the use of the whole package. A context-based metric expresses the sustainability performance in the form of numerical quotients; focus on site and enterprise level metric and reporting;<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Any organization with one or more sites that uses water and has data on their water sources; Corporate sustainability managers, plant or facility managers, environmental managers; Applicable globally and different industrial sectors</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Center for Sustainable Organizations co-developed with Acer GeoAnalytics (Vermont)<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> v3.5 released in March 2011<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Context-based metrics (Company’s impact on renewable water resources)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> May not have data on related water sources and sinks and their respective volumes; Conflict of interest? It provides consulting service and fee-based workshops; seems to be more concerned with finding faults with GRI</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	Global Environmental Management Initiative (GEMI) Water Sustainability Tool</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.gemi.org/water/overview.htm">http://www.gemi.org/water/overview.htm</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool or Metric:</strong></span> GEMI online water sustainability planner</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> GEMI’s free online Water Sustainability Tool contains five core analytical stages, or modules, all with a focus on a company’s value chain. These include:</p>\n<p>\n	Module 1: Water Use, Impact, and Source Assessment</p>\n<p>\n	Module 2: Business Risk Assessment</p>\n<p>\n	Module 3: Business Opportunity Assessment</p>\n<p>\n	Module 4: Strategic Direction and Goal Setting</p>\n<p>\n	Module 5: Strategy Development and Implementation</p>\n<p>\n	GEMI is currently developing the GEMI Local Water Tool that aims to be a follow-up tool to WBCSD’s Global Water Tool for action planning.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations (corporate and operational staff)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> GEMI including 30 companies from various sectors; chaired by WBCSD members and industries<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> identify water risks; generate corporate/facility water strategy</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Released in 2002<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, water risks, water accounting</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Roadmap for corporate strategy; case studies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Does not provide a method or calculator to measure or quantify water use, impacts, and risks (mostly qualitative questions)</p>\n<p>\n	online water calculators and rules of thumb that can be downloaded as excel spreadsheets (residential and fluid flow/; pump, etc); general <a href="http://www.gemi.org/sd/">GEMI online sustainability planner</a>; The <a href="http://www.gemi.org/toolmatrix"><u>GEMI Solution Tools Matrix™</u></a> is an interactive, web solution for users around the world to access the +30 free, solutions-based tools for organizations/industry for EHS and sustainability</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, water risks, water-accounting</p>\n<h2>\n	GEMI Water Sustainability Planner</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.gemi.org/waterplanner/">http://www.gemi.org/waterplanner/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool or Metric:</strong></span> GEMI online water sustainability planner</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> GEMI’s Collecting the Drops: A Water Sustainability Planner is a free online calculator segregated into three Modules that guides a facility user through:</p>\n<p>\n	Module 1: preparing a facility water block diagram and water balance in comparison to the availability of water in the region;</p>\n<p>\n	Module 2: web based interactive water risk evaluation questionnaire (watershed, supply reliability, efficiency, compliance, supply economics, and social context) and the identification of factors that may pose a risk on the operation’s ability to produce.</p>\n<p>\n	Module 3: Case study examples of how GEMI members have identified opportunities to efficiently manage water resources are also provided.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations (corporate and operational staff)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> GEMI including 30 companies from various sectors; chaired by WBCSD members and industries<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> Generate information that can be used to create short and long term water management strategies, identify water risks; output used to develop corporate/facility water strategy</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Released in 2007<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> Best Management Practices; water calculator, case studies<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Roadmap for both long-term and short-term corporate strategy; can be used by specific facilities for information on water use needs/risks; case studies water management strategies; can create an account for specific facilities; some industries case studies same as San Francisco Bay Area industries<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> no mention of its relationship to GEMI’s other water tools; can’t add risk questions or modify; not many specific CA case studies (Dec 2011); no quantifiable results; rudimentary assessment of relative risks<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Sustainable Programs:</strong></span> online water calculators and rules of thumb that can be downloaded as excel spreadsheets (residential and fluid flow/; pump, etc); general <a href="http://www.gemi.org/sd/">GEMI online sustainability planner</a>; The <a href="http://www.gemi.org/toolmatrix"><u>GEMI Solution Tools Matrix</u><b>™</b></a> is an interactive, web solution for users around the world to access the +30 free, solutions-based tools for organizations/industry for EHS and sustainability. <span class="font-size-2"><strong>•<br />\n	Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, water-calculator, case-studies</p>\n<h2>\n	Global Water Footprint Standard</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.waterfootprint.org/?page=files/home">http://www.waterfootprint.org/?page=files/home</a> (main website)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The water footprint here is defined as "the amount of freshwater used in the goods and services consumed or used in production." The main website has pdf documents on how water footprints can be calculated for individual processes and products, as well as for consumers, nations and businesses; there is a water footprint calculator for individuals; actual examples of different kinds of water footprints; examples of measures that can contribute to water footprint reduction</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Water footprint accounting is targeted for the following groups of stakeholders:</p>\n<p>\n	A consumer or group of consumers (online calculator)</p>\n<p>\n	Province, river basin, i.e. a geographically delineated area</p>\n<p>\n	Nation</p>\n<p>\n	Business</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Water Footprint Network; Founding partners include: WWF, UNESCO-IHE Institute for Water Education, WBCSD, Univ of Twente, Water Neutral Foundation, International Finance Corp., and the Netherlands Water Partnership<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> First published in November 2009 (131 page report). Current version came out in February 2011.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> The Global Water Footprint Standard aims to make all water footprints comparable in order to help relevant stakeholders improve water management.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Good tool for "big picture" strategic planning purposes; easily understood by non-technical audiences; Best for water use assessments, as opposed to water quality; identifies hotspots linking corporate water use and source water data</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Generic, aggregated blue-green-grey water footring figures are misleading; Grey water footprint deemed ineffective by many companies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	Global Water Tool (WBCSD)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.wbcsd.org/work-program/sector-projects/water/global-water-tool.aspx">http://www.wbcsd.org/work-program/sector-projects/water/global-water-tool.aspx</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool/Metric Description:</strong></span> Tool includes two parts: 1) Free, Excel-based tool for companies and organizations to map their water use and assess risks relative to their global operations and supply chains; 2) online and GIS mapping system that plots site location with external water datasets and special viewing via google earth interface.<br />\n	Outputs include GRI water indicators, inventories of water consumption/efficiency; downloadable charts with company and watershed data and GSI geographic maps<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Companies and organizations operating in multiple countries who need to better understand the water issues in their operations and that of their extended supply chain; "More than 300 corporations have used the tool which has been regularly updated with improved datasets and functionalities."</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> World Business Council for Sustainable Development (WBCSD)<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> , map water use at an industry and assess and communicate water risks relative to water availability in facility operations and supply chain</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Launched in 2007, last updated in 2011<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths: free</strong></span> of charge; easy to use; Effective at identifying water risk "hot spots"; emphasis on geographic locations; Linked to GRI, CDP, Water, Bloomberg, and DJSI water reporting indicators; includes supply chain; rough measurement of water use and efficiency; can enter water related data for supplies and staff presence;</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Does not assess water quality/discharge related risks; doesn’t assess impacts; only rough estimates of risk; must hand enter data into excel worksheet unless you write a macro to transfer data</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices</p>\n<h2>\n	The Green Grid</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/news/2011/03/08/green-grid-rolls-out-data-center-metrics-water-energy-reuse">http://www.greenbiz.com/news/2011/03/08/green-grid-rolls-out-data-center-metrics-water-energy-reuse</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Green Grid is an IT industry sustainability group that develops metrics to track data center sustainability efforts. The Green Grid also acts as a standards setting organization with tools such as the Data Center Maturity Model that helps determine how resource-efficient data centers are. Newly developed metrics in 2011 include:</p>\n<p>\n	(1) WUE, or Water Usage Effectiveness</p>\n<p>\n	(2) ERE, or Energy Reuse Effectiveness</p>\n<p>\n	(3) DCcE, or Data Center Compute Efficiency<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> business orgs, data center sustainability managers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> GreenBiz.com<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> March 08, 2011<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, water energy, benchmarking, water metrics, energy metrics, data center sustainability</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Addresses important niche of data center operation, frequent updates, alliances with gov’t orgs, NGOs, and trade assoc</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> TBD</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-energy, benchmarking, water-metrics, energy-metrics, data- center-sustainability</p>\n<h2>\n	Hospital Energy Benchmarking Guidance</h2>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: blue; font-size: 105%; font-weight: bold"><b><span class="font-size-2"><strong>• </strong></span></b></span><strong>Website</strong>: <a href="http://hightech.lbl.gov/documents/healthcare/lbnl-2738e.pdf">http://hightech.lbl.gov/documents/healthcare/lbnl-2738e.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> Describes an energy benchmarking framework for hospitals.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> business orgs, hospital operation and building sustainability managers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL)<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> October 2009<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> water energy, benchmarking, hospital energy benchmarking</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Addresses energy benchmarking in hospitals, metrics address energy use through heating, cooling, water, air, and others.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> TBD</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> water-energy, benchmarking, hospital-energy-benchmarking</p>\n<h2>\n	(In Progress) ISO 14046, Water footprint</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.iso.org/iso/isofocusplus_bonus_water-footprint">http://www.iso.org/iso/isofocusplus_bonus_water-footprint</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The proposed Standard will deliver principles, requirements, and guidelines for a water footprint metric of products, processes and organizations, based on the guidance of impact assessment as given in ISO 14044. It will develop a water accounting inventory methodology and requirements for impact assessment (for screening and detailed assessments). It will define how the different types of water sources (e.g. ground, surface, gray, etc.) should be considered, how the different types of water releases should be considered, and how the local environmental conditions (dry areas, wet areas) should be treated. For products, it will apply the life cycle approach and will be based on the same product system as specified in ISO 14040 and ISO 14044. At the organization level, it will consider the guidance given by ISO 14064 for GHG.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations; use at multiple organizational levels from facility to regional</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> International Standard Organization<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> In development; at the stage of preliminary work item (Dec 2011)<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Addresses communication with respect to water footprinting</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> No methodology for calculating offsets or compensation</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-foot-print; water-metics</p>\n<h2>\n	Life Cycle Analysis (LCA)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> no one protocol/website has been adopted to complete a life cycle analysis; some information on life cycle assessment is available through <a href="http://lcinitiative.unep.fr/sites/lcinit/default.asp?site=lcinit&amp;page_id=2F3B97E2-1697-4CD5-9D7E-D3CAD7214482">UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> An analytical method which measures the environmental sustainability of products (including water use/discharge and other environmental factors) through all parts of the value change</p>\n<p>\n	1) <a href="http://lcinitiative.unep.fr/sites/lcinit/default.asp?site=lcinit&amp;page_id=2F3B97E2-1697-4CD5-9D7E-D3CAD7214482">UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative</a>, a global non-profit professional society has information on general life cycle assessments, methodologies, and lifecycle database registry; has a working group on resources LCA (including water)</p>\n<p>\n	2) <a href="http://www.pacinst.org/reports/corporate_water_accounting_analysis/corp_water_accounting_exec_sum.pdf">Corporate Water Accounting</a>, the CEO Mandate Report (2010) has a comparison of this method versus 3 other water accounting methods<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Businesses/organizations which use water; particularly those with long supply chains</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative, a global non-profit professional society</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative: provide industries with framework to measure and compare environmental products regarding freshwater use and depletion; develop a multi-criteria assessment scheme within the LCA framework that allows industries to benchmark performance of products, facilities, and processes on freshwater resources, human health, and biodiversity protection</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> UNEP/SETAC Life cycle initiative: August 2007 created<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics, database</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> well-suited to cross-media environmental assessments; mature science based assessing water quality impacts; starting point for assessing risks; situates water in a broader context of sustainability</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> no universally accepted method of water use impacts; data often not available; results difficult to communicate to stakeholders; doesn’t typically calculate impacts at local receiving water bodies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Programs:</strong></span> LCA can be applied to water, energy, materials, GHG, and other sustainability areas</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics, life-cycle-assessment</p>\n<h2>\n	Strategic Water Management in the Minerals Industry</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.minerals.org.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/17595/Water_strategy_book.pdf">http://www.minerals.org.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/17595/Water_strategy_book.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> strategic framework structured around 4 issues:</p>\n<p>\n	1) Water Value: guidance on how to reflect the true value on water in decision making</p>\n<p>\n	2) Strategic water planning guidance</p>\n<p>\n	3) Implementation: guidance on site water management plans and balances to improve operational performance</p>\n<p>\n	4) guidance on engaging stakeholders</p>\n<p>\n	Member companies produce up to 85 per cent of Australia''s mineral output including precious metals, base metals, light metals and iron ore, as well as energy materials such as coal.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> mining companies; corporate managers and planners; mine managers and environmental personnel that are responsible for water management</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Australian Ministerial Council on Mineral and Petroleum Resources (MCMPR) and the Minerals Council of Australia (MCA).</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> Aim is to promote a strategic approach to water management at mining and processing sites so that water is more efficiently managed and valued as a vital business, community and environmental asset.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> framework development begun in 2005<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> coalition of companies may lead to significant changes; gov’t engagement; aligns with GRI</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Trade group ploy – activities are entirely funded by MCA member companies? Mostly qualitative assessment and metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	UK Federation House Commitment to Water Efficiency</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.fdf.org.uk/waterefficiency.aspx">http://www.fdf.org.uk/waterefficiency.aspx\\#item1</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> Developed in partnership between FDF and former government-funded body Envirowise, the Federation House Commitment (FHC) sets out a process for food and drink manufacturing companies to work in a systematic way towards improving their water efficiency.</p>\n<p>\n	There are currently 54 active signatories across 245 sites in the UK.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> food and drink manufacturers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Food and Drink Federation</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> 2007, with annual progress report<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> coalition of companies may lead to significant changes; gov’t engagement; strategic framework can be applied to other global companies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Trade group ploy or something "real"?; water use does not take into account water embedded in products</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	UN Water Footprint, Neutrality and Efficiency (WaFNE) Umbrella Project</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Metric or Tool:</strong></span> building a website to host different tools &amp; methodologies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.unep.fr/scp/water/WAFNE.htm">http://www.unep.fr/scp/water/WAFNE.htm</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Project aims to produce methodologies and guides through the refinement of water accounting/footprint and water neutrality management tools. It will apply the above concepts in selected industries and selected geographical locations. Includes <a href="http://www.unep.fr/shared/publications/pdf/DTIx1411xPA-WaterFootprint.pdf">Water Footprint and Corporate Water Accounting for Resource Efficiency Report</a> (183 pgs)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations, public authorities</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> UN Environment Programme<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span> enhance water efficiency and water quality management through the refinement and pilot testing of several accounting methods and supporting management tools</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Timeframe = 10/2009 – 2012/2013<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Partnerships with other UN water-related initiatives, Water Footprint Network, UNEP/SETAC Life Cycle Initiative, and GRI.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Only three years in project duration – limited impact (there is not even a dedicated website to the project)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking</p>\n<h2>\n	Veolia – Water Impact Index</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.veoliawaterna.com/north-america-water/ressources/documents/1/10975,Water_Impact_Index-White_Paper.pdf">http://www.veoliawaterna.com/north-america-water/ressources/documents/1/10975,Water_Impact_Index-White_Paper.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> According to Veolia, it is "the first indicator enabling a comprehensive assessment of the impact of human activity on water resources. It is a tool that can help cities and companies plan long-term projects and better understand sustainable approaches to ensure long-term water supplies and healthy water ecosystems."</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations, public authorities</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Veolia Water North America<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> July 2010<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Index integrates other variables in addition to volume, including resource stress, water quality and competing consumption needs with existing volume-based water measurement tools; considers both direct and indirect influences of an activity; LCA approach</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Developed by water utility – potential bias</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	WaterSense Label and Certification</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tool or Metric: Certification of Products</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.epa.gov/WaterSense/about_us/what_is_ws.html">http://www.epa.gov/WaterSense/about_us/what_is_ws.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The program seeks to help consumers make smart water choices that save money and maintain high environmental standards without compromising performance. Products and services that have earned the WaterSense label have been certified to be at least 20% more efficient without sacrificing performance. To date \\[2010 Report\\], WaterSense has helped consumers save a cumulative 125 billion gallons of water and over $2 billion in water and energy bills. By the end of 2010, reductions of 16.7 billion kWh of electricity and 6 million metric tons of carbon dioxide were achieved through the use of WaterSense labeled products.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> business organizations, consumers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> US EPA</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> program created in June 2006<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, policy, label</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> simple way to help consumer make informed decisions; independent certification ensures integrity</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> voluntary program on consumer products, could be looking into expanding program scope</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, policy, label</p>\n<h2>\n	Water Stewardship Australia</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.nwc.gov.au/publications/distilled-e-newsletter/2010/distilled-edition-51-june-2010/water-stewardship-australia">http://www.nwc.gov.au/publications/distilled-e-newsletter/2010/distilled-edition-51-june-2010/water-stewardship-australia</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The organization leads the initiative to develop responsible water management standards for the largest of all Australian water users in the agribusiness, manufacturing, mining and infrastructure sectors.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations, public authorities, consumers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Australia’s National Water Commission<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> 2007<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water policy planning, policy</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> various water tools available free of charge, publications on water research</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> water metrics and reporting would be the next step</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-policy-planning, policy</p>\n<h2>\n	WWF/DEG Water Risk Filter</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/issues_doc/Environment/ceo_water_mandate/7th_Working_Conference_Copenhagen_2011/Copenhagen-Verberne.pdf">http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/issues_doc/Environment/ceo_water_mandate/7th_Working_Conference_Copenhagen_2011/Copenhagen-Verberne.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Water Risk Filter uses the newest available scientific data sets with global coverage and company specific information to quantify all relevant water risks (physical, regulatory and reputational). A mitigation toolbox, providing a well-structured overview of potential mitigation responses and related case studies, will also be part of the online tool.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations, public authorities, consumers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Australia’s National Water Commission<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> anticipated early 2012<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, financial</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> input data seem comprehensive (GIS, WRI database, industry &amp; country data sets, etc.)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> provides go/no-go investment decision, but does not seem to provide recommendations for action</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, financial</p>\n<h2>\n	(In Progress) World Resource Institute''s Aqueduct Alliance</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://insights.wri.org/aqueduct/how-it-works">http://insights.wri.org/aqueduct/how-it-works</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> Aqueduct "provides a comprehensive and credible metric for measuring geographic water risks. It consists of a global database and interactive mapping tool that enable companies to quantify and map water risks at a local scale, worldwide." 21 indicators in three categories (access &amp; growth constraints, cost risks, and disruption potential) are aggregated to determine the overall water risk.</p>\n<p>\n	Funders by invitation: Goldman Sachs, Bloomberg, Dow, Talisman Energy, United Technologies, Coca-Cola, Dutch gov’t<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business and government</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<u>Modeled data:</u> hydrologic modeling by ISciences;</p>\n<p>\n	<u>Spatial data:</u> compiled by research or international organizations;</p>\n<p>\n	<u>Observations:</u> recorded from monitoring stations;</p>\n<p>\n	<u>Official statistics</u> reported by local and national governments;</p>\n<p>\n	<u>Global water stress maps:</u> provided by The Coca-Cola Company</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Aqueduct Alliance launched in August 2011. In depth basin-level water risk mapping will be released in early fall 2011.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> Flexible – Allows customization of Water Risk Atlas based on different sectors or risk profiles; periodic update of data sources; identifies increasingly water-stressed locations throughout the world</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> The success all hinges on Aqueduct’s global database of water risk information, which is highly dependent on data sources; data integrity and availability may vary greatly among regions</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics</p>\n</author>', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default');
INSERT INTO `page_chunks` (`id`, `slug`, `page_id`, `body`, `parsed`, `type`, `sort`, `class`) VALUES
(876, 'default', 82, '<p>\n	<b>by Mary Kean and Carey Chen</b></p>\n<p>\n	<b>January 2012</b></p>\n<p>\n	<i>For a more detailed &amp; and up to date review of new metrics, refer to our</i> <a href="http://sustainablesv.org/EcoCloud/WaterMetricsFrameworksReport.pdf" target="_blank"><i>Water Metrics Report</i></a><i> </i><i>and the</i> <a href="Audience%20-%20Finance.docx" target="_blank"><i>tables</i></a> on <a href="../metrics-reporting"><i>EcoCloud Water Metrics</i></a></p>\n<p>\n	This section includes organizations and resources relating to strategic planning and vision of organizations and policy related elements to implement sustainable water initiatives and frameworks.</p>\n<h2>\n	Aquawareness</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.ewp.eu/aquawareness/">http://www.ewp.eu/aquawareness/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> Visionary system developed to guide sustainable water management programs and organizations projects. EWP’s aquawareness objectives are (1) create a common vision for water in Europe with widely accepted principles for sustainable water management, (2) set sights on changing behavior and practices, (3) shape and integrates water into policy and strategy agendas, (4) create a water saving and efficiency culture among private, industrial, business and agricultural users, (5) support the shift from supply to demand management through information, education and training.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> CII<b>,</b> public authorities, agricultural users, &amp; inter-governmental agencies in Europe</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> EWP, a non-profit organization; structured to include cross-sectoral organizations to give water one common "voice" in Europe. Partners include government, innovators, water utilities, and researchers on multiple cross-collaboration projects.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> established in 2008;.<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, public policy, case studies<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> EWS good for identification of water strategies at the operational level; in line with and complementary to other environmental certification schemes, raise awareness;; unites various stakeholders across Europe; provides uniform framework and vision for many countries; supports education and training effort<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Vision 2030 may be too long-term to be effective for timely actions now</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Other Sustainable Programs:</strong></span> Includes Aquawareness- European Water Stewardship Project (See EcoCloud water metrics and tools section); Europe Water multiple public-private collaboration projects around sustainable water management <a href="http://ec.europa.eu/environment/water/blueprint/index_en.htm">Europeon Commission Environment’s water blueprint</a>, <a href="http://www.europe-innova.eu">INNOWATER</a> (collaboration to identify and implement innovative water technology (3 year project 2010-2012), and <a href="http://www.stream-project.eu/about-stream">STREAM</a> project communication project between research and policy on Aquatic management research.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, public-policy, case-studies</p>\n<h2>\n	Business Roundtable Water Brief for Business</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://waterbrief.businessroundtable.org/About/">http://waterbrief.businessroundtable.org/About/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> interactive educational website; Through the S.E.E. Change: Water Brief For Business, the Roundtable can perform and raise the awareness of member CEOs and motivate them to look seriously at how their companies use and affect water resources and what role they can play in addressing the water challenge. Where companies determine that a strategic business case exists for investment in sustainable water use, S.E.E. Change can provide the tools and framework for designing and implementing a sustainable water initiative.</p>\n<p>\n	Business Roundtable is an association of chief executive officers of leading U.S. companies with over $6 trillion in annual revenues and more than 14 million employees.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> business organizations</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Business Roundtable includes over 35 companies (various industrial sectors)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> September 2005<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topic:</strong></span> CII, Best Management Practices, water metrics</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> collection of powerful CEOs and companies</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> lack of specifics – no list of metrics, mostly generalized text on strategy; only engages <u>after</u> companies decide to invest in sustainable water use</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-metrics</p>\n<h2>\n	California Energy Commission</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/process/water/">http://www.energy.ca.gov/process/water/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Energy Commission''s process energy office is dedicated to providing resources to help water professionals control energy costs associated with delivering water and wastewater within he state of California. "Energy represents the largest controllable cost of providing water or wastewater services to the public. California water and wastewater agencies spend more than $500 million each year on energy costs. "</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> CII, public authorities, agricultural users, water/energy professionals</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> CA Energy Commission<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> last updated in January 2009<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, public policy, water energy</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> info for various sectors, wealth of research papers, articles, etc.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> does not seem to be updated frequently, difficult to navigate to find specific info</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, public-policy, water-energy</p>\n<h2>\n	CEO Water Mandate (UN)</h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.unglobalcompact.org/Issues/Environment/CEO_Water_Mandate/">http://www.unglobalcompact.org/Issues/Environment/CEO_Water_Mandate/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> The Mandate is "public-private initiative designed to assist companies in the development, implementation and disclosure of water sustainability policies and practices." The CEO Water Mandate covers six elements: Direct Operations; Supply Chain and Watershed Management; Collective Action; Public Policy; Community Engagement; and Transparency. UNEP Water Footprint, Neutrality &amp; Efficiency ( <a href="http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/issues_doc/Environment/ceo_water_mandate/5th_Working_Conference_NYC_2010/Sonnemann.pdf">WaFNE</a>) Project complements the CEO Water Mandate effort.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span> Business organizations, with engagement with UN agencies, NGOs, specialized water institutes, inter-governmental organizations, and public authorities</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> UN Global Compact<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Objective:</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> launched in July 2007; convenes two working conferences each year<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span> Best Management Practices, public policy</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span> influential collection of international stakeholders that draw attention to water sustainability issues; develops and disseminates research in areas related to water issues (e.g. human rights)</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span> Endorsement can be viewed as marketing ploy; difficult to measure progress; corporate driven – special interest bias</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags:</strong></span> Best-Management-Practices, public-policy, reporting</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(887, 'default', 85, '<p class="bread_crumb">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	A framework allows you to understand the relationship between sustainability''s 3Es (environment, equity, and economy).</p>\n<p>\n	One of the most helpful sustainability frameworks comes from economist Herman Daly.</p>\n<p>\n	Often the 3Es of sustainability are depicted as three equal, interlocking circles.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/Ll7mUXZ8DJYFOgFazl4sN2pv5FfzvG2umniQAdUW1z2wwKc1SjqwUbE4Ap9TXbsOOcrP3zQj3o52BdFQI0fVFa5BAjyz*1eR/SSV_Framworks_snapshot.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-left" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/Ll7mUXZ8DJYFOgFazl4sN2pv5FfzvG2umniQAdUW1z2wwKc1SjqwUbE4Ap9TXbsOOcrP3zQj3o52BdFQI0fVFa5BAjyz*1eR/SSV_Framworks_snapshot.jpg?width=120" width="120" /></a></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>What frameworks are currently in use to benchmark progress?</strong></p>\n<div id="page_note">\n	<p>\n		<span class="font-size-2">Suparna Vashisht, SLF Program Manager, Sustainable Silicon Valley, gave a presentation called <strong><a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/sites/default/files/dms/ssv-presentation-031810.pdf" target="_blank">Sustainabilty Frameworks: Guidelines, Protocols, and Registries</a>&nbsp;</strong>in March 2010</span></p>\n	<p>\n		<span class="font-size-2">based on the <strong><a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/sites/default/files/dms/ssv-sustainability-frameworks-whitepaper.pdf" target="_blank">whitepaper</a></strong>&nbsp;researched and compiled by Suparna Vashisht&nbsp;for Sustainable Silicon Valley</span></p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>EcoCloud™ members:</b> This is a collaborative site. You are invited to add content to this page. All contributed content is subject to moderation. <a href="/page/getting-started#contributor_howto">Get started</a></p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(890, 'default', 84, '<h3>\n	Grassroots, Online Calculators, &amp; Collaboration Resources<span class="c1"><strong>.</strong></span></h3>\n<h3>\n	<b>by Mary Kean and Carey Chen</b></h3>\n<h3>\n	<b>January 2012</b></h3>\n<p>\n	<i>For a more detailed &amp; and up to date review of new metrics, refer to our</i> <a href="http://sustainablesv.org/EcoCloud/WaterMetricsFrameworksReport.pdf" target="_blank"><i>Water Metrics Report</i></a><i> </i><i>and the</i> tables on <a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/metrics-reporting" target="_self">EcoCloud Water Metrics</a></p>\n<p>\n	This section includes resources, organizations, and websites that are geared to improve collaboration, communication among peer groups so that organizations and businesses can implement water and energy frameworks and benchmarking projects. Also included are water and energy calculators primarily aimed at consumers in order to raise awareness amongst and educate consumer''s best practices</p>\n<h2>\n	<span class="c2"><strong>A Single Drop (ASD)</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.singledrop.org/">http://www.singledrop.org/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span>"ASD is a non-profit organization building the capacity of self-reliant partnerships to plan, implement, and manage community-driven clean water and sanitation solutions through sustainable organizational strategies, WASH education, and appropriate technologies."</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span>Public authorities (esp. local gov''ts), community planners, subject matter experts with technical know-how of water-related solutions</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Blue Planet Network<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> Founded in 2004<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span>Best Management Practices, social entrepreneurship</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span>directly engages local communities, emphasis on developing countries</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span>community-driven, which is highly dependent on organizational capability of each community; requires experts, partners, and staff to build up partnerships to be self-reliant</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags: </strong></span>Best-Management-Practices, social-entrepreneurship</p>\n<h2>\n	<span class="c2"><strong>Calculators: Online Water and CO2 / Energy Calculators</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span>Below is a list of websites that include CO2 emissions calculators primarily aimed at consumers; for a more complete analysis of these - see the Excel spreadsheet on EcoCloud. The overall objective is to raise awareness amongst and educate consumer''s best practices.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span>consumers, business orgs, communities, government</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags: </strong></span>CO2-calculator, water-energy-calculator</p>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<strong>Name</strong></p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<strong>Website</strong></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					Carbon Calculators ( list of carbon calculators)</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.co2list.org/files/calculators.htm">http://www.co2list.org/files/calculators.htm</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					Carbonrally (social media challenges lower carbon use)</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.carbonrally.com">http://www.carbonrally.com</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					CoolClimate</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					coolclimate.berkeley.edu</p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					The Infinite Power of Texas Renewable Energy Educational Campaign</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.infinitepower.org/calculators.htm">http://www.infinitepower.org/calculators.htm</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					Wholly H2O (list and description of calculators)</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/calculators.html">http://www.whollyh2o.org/calculators.html</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					SBA Energy Saving Calculators</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.sba.gov/content/energy-saving-calculators-energy-star">http://www.sba.gov/content/energy-saving-calculators-energy-star</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					Water Neutral Offset Calculator</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.waterneutral.org/calculator2.asp">http://www.waterneutral.org/calculator2.asp</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					WECalc (Water-Energy-Climate Calculator)</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://wecalc.org/calc/">http://wecalc.org/calc/</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					Water-Energy Measure Calculator (WEMC)</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://doe2.com/download/Water-Energy/WaterSavingMeasures-Calculator-v3.pdf">http://doe2.com/download/Water-Energy/WaterSavingMeasures-Calculator-v3.pdf</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					Energy Cost Calculator for Electric and Gas Water Heaters</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/femp/technologies/eep_waterheaters_calc.html">http://www1.eere.energy.gov/femp/technologies/eep_waterheaters_calc.html</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					River Network''s water-energy calculators (showerhead, community, toilet, water heating, and new water source impact tool)</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top">\n				<p>\n					<a href="http://www.rivernetwork.org/water-energy-toolkit-understanding-carbon-footprint-your-water">http://www.rivernetwork.org/water-energy-toolkit-understanding-carbon-footprint-your-water</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<h2>\n	<span class="c2"><strong>Peer Water Exchange (PWX)</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://peerwater.org/">http://peerwater.org/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span>PWX acts as a Web-based water sector''s clearinghouse, the global marketplace to select, fund, manage, and track the impact of all water and sanitation projects efficiently, collaboratively, and transparently. "PWX is a platform, process, and human network for funding, soliciting, selecting, managing, and evaluating water projects worldwide. It is a participatory decision-making system to oversee thousands of grassroots water and sanitation projects worldwide efficiently, effectively, and transparently."</p>\n<p>\n	"Today, we partner with 73 members (e.g. implementer, funders, analysts), working in 23 countries. We showcase $25+ million of water and sanitation projects on behalf of our members and have directly funded nearly $1.5 million of projects. "</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span>Business organizations, NGOs, philanthropists, grassroots project organizers and implementers</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Source:</strong></span> Blue Planet Network<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Date:</strong></span> launched in 2006<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Topics:</strong></span>Best Management Practices, social entrepreneurship</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Strengths:</strong></span>scalable, map-driven, low cost field-level work, transparent</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Limitations:</strong></span>Web-based application may not be practical for projects in far-flung locations</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags: </strong></span>Best-Management-Practices, social-entrepreneurship</p>\n<h2>\n	<span class="c2"><strong>Free PGE Water and Energy Classes &amp; Resource Center</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Website:</strong></span> <a href="http://www.pge.com/pec/classes/index.jsp">http://www.pge.com/pec/classes/index.jsp\\#classresults</a> For a complete list of current PGE classes offered in energy, water, and solar<br />\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Description:</strong></span> PGE offers classes throughout the year in topics of water, energy, green building, HVAC, solar, etc. Course length varies: 1 hr to 5 days. Classes are online or at PGE training centers, primarily in San Francisco Bay Area. Many materials and resources are available online and at the <a href="http://www.pge.com/pec/resourcecenter/">PGE Energy Center library</a>located in San Francisco which can be checked out by any resident in PGE Service area.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Target Audience (User):</strong></span>consumers, public authorities, water and energy professionals; Some of the classes are introductory and some are for experienced professionals.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2"><strong>• Tags: </strong></span>energy-efficiency-classes, water-classes, green-building</p>\n<table border="1" cellspacing="0" class="MsoNormalTable" width="100%">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr class="c3">\n			<td valign="top" width="40%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					High Performance Residential Hot Water Systems</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top" width="59%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					<a href="http://www.pge.com/mybusiness/edusafety/training/pec/classes/index.jsp?reqType=detail&amp;ID=5204&amp;db=PEC5204.csv&amp;pageTitle=Class%20Details%20and%20Registration&amp;postback=yes">http://www.pge.com/mybusiness/edusafety/training/pec/classes/index.jsp?reqType=detail&amp;ID=5204&amp;db=PEC5204.csv&amp;pageTitle=Class%20Details%20and%20Registration&amp;postback=yes</a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr class="c7">\n			<td class="c4" valign="top" width="40%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					Smart Grid Fundamentals</p>\n			</td>\n			<td class="c6" valign="top" width="59%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					<a href="http://www.pge.com/mybusiness/edusafety/training/pec/classes/index.jsp?reqType=detail&amp;ID=5055&amp;db=PEC5055.csv&amp;pageTitle=Class%20Details%20and%20Registration&amp;postback=yes"><span class="c5">http://www.pge.com/mybusiness/edusafety/training/pec/classes/index.jsp?reqType=detail&amp;ID=5055&amp;db=PEC5055.csv&amp;pageTitle=Class%20Details%20and%20Registration&amp;postback=yes</span></a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr class="c8">\n			<td valign="top" width="40%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					The PG&amp;E Pacific Energy Center: Twenty Years of<br />\n					Educating and Serving Building Professionals</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top" width="59%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					<a href="http://www.pge.com/mybusiness/edusafety/training/pec/classes/index.jsp?reqType=detail&amp;ID=5151&amp;db=PEC5151.csv&amp;pageTitle=Class%20Details%20and%20Registration&amp;postback=yes"><span class="c5">http://www.pge.com/mybusiness/edusafety/training/pec/classes/index.jsp?reqType=detail&amp;ID=5151&amp;db=PEC5151.csv&amp;pageTitle=Class%20Details%20and%20Registration&amp;postback=yes</span></a></p>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr class="c9">\n			<td valign="top" width="40%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\n					Save Water and Energy in Foodservice</p>\n			</td>\n			<td valign="top" width="59%">\n				<p class="MsoNormal">\