(912, 'default', 56, '<p>\n	<img alt="vr_corridors_thumb.jpg" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/56/0" /></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Light Rail Without the Rails</b></p>\n<p>\n	Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) is a system of busing that in many ways emulates light rail, but without the expense or permanence of tracks.&nbsp; Features include dedicated lanes, priority crossing through lights, at-level boarding, pre-boarding ticket purchasing and, in some cases, on-board wi-fi.&nbsp; Curitiba, Brazil made the concept known, but many places in the U.S. (including Eugene, OR, Los Angeles, CA, Las Vegas, NV, and Boston, MA) have adopted it as well, with great success.&nbsp; Now the issue is front and center right here in Silicon Valley as communities along a proposed BRT line up El Camino Real from the HP Pavilion in San Jose to the Palo Alto Transit Center are considering whether to support the effort or not.</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Here in Silicon Valley:&nbsp; Sunnyvale’s Choice--Rejected</b></p>\n<p>\n	On May 22, 2012, Sunnyvale City Council voted 4 to 3 not to go forward with pursuing BRT for El Camino Real. &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Sunnyvale has long pursued more public transportation. When the light rail was being extended, downtown Sunnyvale lost out to Mountain View so that the rail lines brush through on the north side of the city before heading up to Moffet Field and on to Mountain View’s Castro St.&nbsp; The plan for the El Camino Corridor route (which is one of three routes planned by the Valley Transportation Association under the name “Valley Rapid”&nbsp; <a href="http://www.valleyrapid.org/what_is_valley_rapid/">http://www.valleyrapid.org/what_is_valley_rapid/</a>) would have offered service at 10 minute intervals and take many of the current 522 route buses off the streets (and out of the car lanes).&nbsp; It would also have taken away the parking lanes along El Camino and create bike lanes in order to make the space for the dedicated lanes in the middle of the roadway.&nbsp; This removal of parking space had some people and businesses worried, but there are only 300 spaces in Sunnyvale along El Camino as opposed to thousands of off-street spaces.&nbsp; The parking is in general underutilized anyway along El Camino, being a dangerous and undesirable place to park.&nbsp; Bicycle advocates welcomed the addition of the bike lanes along bicycle-unfriendly El Camino, and environmentally the plan could remove 4,555 metric tons of greenhouse gas annually.</p>\n<p>\n	While not as intensive as installing rails and electric overhead wires, the project would still have been a huge one.&nbsp; However, funding for the Valley Rapid projects is financed by the Santa Clara County Measure A half-cent sales tax and federal funds, so Sunnyvale would not have been paying for its development.&nbsp; As a comparison, light rail would cost $100 million per mile to build, whereas BRT rings in at $8-$13 million per mile and is expected to cost less to operate.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(935, 'default', 15, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean </author><author class="title">&nbsp;EcoCloud Water Lead</author>\n<p>\n	If you live in Australia, Hawaii or a developing nation with limited or no access to urban water infrastructure systems, the chances are that you are already quite familiar with decentralized water management. For the rest of us, a decentralized water infrastructure is defined as:</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		mimicking the natural hydrologic cycle</li>\n	<li>\n		locating water management at the community or household level</li>\n	<li>\n		locating water recovery at the community or household level</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	This differs from the centralized model of managing urban water at higher (e.g. regional) levels. What once was the realm of “alternative lifestyles” has now become mainstream as water supplies are endangered by overdrafts cause by overpopulation in water poor geographic areas and misuse of available water resources.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Our goal in the Decentralized Water section is to identify practices that will bring water use in line with water supply, in part, by focusing on what type of water is needed at point of use. In other words, it has been our practice in the United States to use energy-intensive water transported and cleaned to potable standards for end uses that do not necessitate potable water. Let’s be smarter water stewards by using the right water for the right job.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	A clear example is flushing toilets with energy-intensive potable water, when water treated to lesser standards, such as minimally treated rainwater and graywater, is perfectly appropriate to flush urine and feces through pipes to a wastewater treatment plant. Employing these largely untapped water sources also brings the user further in line with the natural hydrologic system by using rainwater onsite, keeping it from becoming stormwater that picks up pollutants from sidewalks and streets carrying them down storm drains into natural waterways.</p>\n<p>\n	<b><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/KGOxkW7x5V3CkHT8Y639fC0mu0PT-BF7ujeYVOjK-LTtx9tm2LsU*GuVgwPi5tQkWjzpGSWSnEKpPUjmtg73zZsbXb4FHrxW/WaterArmsEarth2.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-center" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/KGOxkW7x5V3CkHT8Y639fC0mu0PT-BF7ujeYVOjK-LTtx9tm2LsU*GuVgwPi5tQkWjzpGSWSnEKpPUjmtg73zZsbXb4FHrxW/WaterArmsEarth2.jpg" width="260" /></a>&nbsp;</b></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Issues in implementing decentralized water include:</b></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		identify all potential sources for water supply</li>\n	<li>\n		identify water end use needs and practices</li>\n	<li>\n		establish baseline water use</li>\n	<li>\n		create a water budget</li>\n	<li>\n		consider water supply costs and roi</li>\n	<li>\n		know state and local laws and ordinances</li>\n	<li>\n		create an integrated management plan that takes all water uses, sources and treatment into account</li>\n	<li>\n		maximize potential for decentralized energy gain</li>\n	<li>\n		integrate systems to capture, infiltrate, use, and reuse water on-site (rain, gray, storm, black water management)</li>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<b>&nbsp;</b><b>Potential Tactics for Decentralized Water Management:</b></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		rainwater harvesting</li>\n	<li>\n		graywater harvesting</li>\n	<li>\n		earthworks for onsite retention and infiltration</li>\n	<li>\n		raingardens</li>\n	<li>\n		permeable pavement</li>\n	<li>\n		onsite or localized blackwater treatment</li>\n	<li>\n		compost toilets</li>\n	<li>\n		urine diversion for plant food</li>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<b>&nbsp;</b><b>Where to find the information you need to match water supply sources with water end use:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Efficiency:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/efficiency.html">http://www.whollyh2o.org/efficiency.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Rainwater Harvesting (RWH):</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="https://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater.html">http://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Graywater:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.oasisdesign.net/greywater/">http://www.oasisdesign.net/greywater/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.greywateraction.org/greywater-recycling/">http://www.greywateraction.org/greywater-recycling/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/graywater.html">http://www.whollyh2o.org/graywater.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Stormwater:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="https://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater/overview.html">https://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater/overview.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://cfpub.epa.gov/npdes/home.cfm?program_id=6">http://cfpub.epa.gov/npdes/home.cfm?program_id=6</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Blackwater:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/blackwater.html">http://www.whollyh2o.org/blackwater.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.livingmachines.com/">http://www.livingmachines.com/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Low Impact Development:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.epa.gov/owow/NPS/lid/">http://www.epa.gov/owow/NPS/lid/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Audits:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.awwa.org/Resources/WaterLossControl.cfm?ItemNumber=48055">http://www.awwa.org/Resources/WaterLossControl.cfm?ItemNumber=48055</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.swfwmd.state.fl.us/conservation/audits/wateraudits.htm/">http://www.swfwmd.state.fl.us/conservation/audits/wateraudits.htm/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Water Budgets:</b></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater/rainwater-res/item/66-water-budgeting.html/">http://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater/rainwater-res/item/66-water-budgeting.html/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://waterbudget.sustainablesources.com/">http://waterbudget.sustainablesources.com/</a></p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(940, 'default', 14, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Water Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Recycled water is water that has been used, treated, and distributed for beneficial reuse within the community.</b> Recycled water (sometimes known as reclaimed water) is a sustainable, high-quality water supply – it reduces our dependency on imported water and preserves our drinking water supply for current and future generations. Half of the water supply in Santa Clara County is imported from the Sierra Nevada and the Sacramento/San Joaquin River Delta, and restrictions on these limited supplies continue to tighten. Recycled water is used in lieu of potable water to irrigate food crops and landscaping, cool buildings, flush toilets and urinals, and contribute to industrial processes. Recycled water is used all over the world; in Southern California, it undergoes further treatment and is used to supplement drinking water<br />\n	supplies.</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Recycled water is available in Silicon Valley.</b> Recycled water is available in portions of San Jose, Santa Clara, Milpitas, Sunnyvale, Mountain View, Palo Alto, and Gilroy. The South Bay Water Recycling program operates the largest system in Silicon Valley, providing recycled water to over 600 customers through 120 miles of dedicated pipelines in San Jose, Santa Clara, and Milpitas. To find out how you can access this source of recycled water, see <a href="http://ecocloud1.ning.com/page/connecting-to-the-sbwr-system">Connecting to the SBWR System</a>.</p>\n<p style="text-align: center">\n	<img alt="recycle_water.gif" class="pyro-image alignment-none" height="109" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/52/0" width="113" /></p>\n<p>\n	<b>Recycled water has a long track record of successful use in cooling towers.</b> Since 1998, South Bay Water Recycling customers have successfully used recycled water in lieu of potable water for cooling. Current customers include public institutions, power plants, manufacturing facilities, and datacenters. <a href="http://www.valleywater.org/Services/RecycledWater.aspx" target="_blank">Learn More...</a></p>\n<p>\n	Click the <b>Tools</b> tab for information on the recycled water piping in the Bay Area, including a map.</p>\n<p>\n	More Information:</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.epa.gov/region9/water/recycling/">Water Recycling and Reuse</a> by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency<br />\n	(EPA)</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.epa.gov/region9/waterinfrastructure/">Pacific Southwest Sustainable Water Infrastructure Program</a>, U.S. EPA</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.epa.gov/owm/waterinfrastructure/pdfs/guidebook_si_energymanagement.pdf">Ensuring a Sustainable Future: An Energy Management Guidebook for<br />\n	Wastewater and Water Utilities</a>, U.S. EPA</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://water.epa.gov/scitech/climatechange/index.cfm">Climate Change and Water</a>, an overview of relevant web pages from the<br />\n	U.S. EPA and SCVWD''s <a href="http://cf.valleywater.org/Water/Where_Your_Water_Comes_From/Water%20Supply%20and%20Infrastructure%20Planning/Climate%20Change/portal.cfm" target="_blank">Climate Change Portal</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default');
