(974, 'default', 11, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	A smart grid delivers electricity from suppliers to consumers using digital technology with two-way communications to control appliances at consumers'' homes to save energy, reduce cost and increase reliability and transparency. It overlays the electrical grid with an information and net metering system, and includes smart meters. Such a modernized electricity network is being promoted by many governments as a way of addressing energy independence, global warming and emergency resilience issues.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/5OM0RmqMuKYR1O*FVPxIAtscwANb31x8ig9CufA7z2zjgEsWIn2CKjrYSATGDZlJ1VaHzsDnJSKKTU*YsFg4vYytKJOZF8tf/articleImage_smartGrid.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-full" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/5OM0RmqMuKYR1O*FVPxIAtscwANb31x8ig9CufA7z2zjgEsWIn2CKjrYSATGDZlJ1VaHzsDnJSKKTU*YsFg4vYytKJOZF8tf/articleImage_smartGrid.jpg?width=750" width="750" /></a></p>\n<p>\n	The smart grid is made possible by applying sensing, measurement and control devices with two-way communications to electricity production, transmission, distribution and consumption parts of the power grid that communicate information about grid condition to system users, operators and automated devices, making it possible to dynamically respond to changes in grid condition.</p>\n<p>\n	A smart grid includes an intelligent monitoring system that keeps track of all electricity flowing in the system. When power is least expensive the user can allow the smart grid to turn on selected home appliances such as washing machines or factory processes that can run at arbitrary hours. At peak times it could turn off selected appliances to reduce demand.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(987, 'default', 59, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><strong>2011 – The Year of Electric Cars</strong></span></p>\n<div>\n	<p style="text-align: center;">\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		The year of the electric car has finally arrived. With manufacturers rushing to get their energy efficient vehicles out of production and into the hands of the customer this year, and with the Government offering compelling tax rebates on electric vehicles, there are many signs that indicate that this might turn out to be an year of extraordinary choices for a car buyer who is looking at saving energy, reducing cost, going green and helping the environment.</p>\n	<div style="margin: 4px; width: 33%; float: right;">\n		<p>\n			<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/kbATeGh8amypQhnLPekQ1ODiCtHwvUu9BPw6Dn-L1cmDLyTm40xmfbLVv7tjzl9hrZacR5YnWCu4m2LP91CzUk4ttfD853aw/EV_Article.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-right" height="138" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/kbATeGh8amypQhnLPekQ1ODiCtHwvUu9BPw6Dn-L1cmDLyTm40xmfbLVv7tjzl9hrZacR5YnWCu4m2LP91CzUk4ttfD853aw/EV_Article.jpg?width=750" width="208" /></a><em><span style="font-size: 12px;">Lithium-ion battery,&nbsp;</span></em><em><span style="font-size: 12px;">The New&nbsp;Electric &nbsp; Power Plant</span></em></p>\n	</div>\n	<p>\n		Manufacturers like Nissan have already been gearing up for a mass introduction of electric vehicles by showing up models to the public in various Auto Expo shows last year, offering test drives, getting public feedback and advertising in media. All these activities will now culminate into an exciting launch as many of these new electric car models are expected to hit the showrooms this year. The new EVs start from a price of around $32,780 (the Leaf''s price) and go up to $87,400 (the Fisker Karma plug-in hybrid). The cost of these cars could be offset with federal and state rebates and tax credits. To find out more about what kinds of rebates apply to you locally, please visit the following resource:</p>\n	<p>\n		<a href="http://www.driveclean.ca.gov/">http://www.driveclean.ca.gov</a></p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>&nbsp;</b></p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(989, 'default', 60, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<div id="page_note" style="text-align: center;">\n	<span class="font-size-3"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></div>\n<div style="text-align: center;">\n	<span class="font-size-3"><strong>Local Energy Efficiency Programs</strong></span></div>\n<div style="text-align: center;">\n	<span class="font-size-5" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>San Jose’s Green Vision Clean Energy Showcase</b></span></div>\n<div style="text-align: center;">\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div id="page_note">\n	<p style="text-align: center;">\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/GlokkNAOsMQafMTnHQgw*8NBcCSVx*8ezE0wbPcMlIgeDb6rvQjs0OTxFg0isgV8X5nWlH0B0o2d21M0O35RCQLMBI89YAG5/CIMG0661.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-left" height="144" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/GlokkNAOsMQafMTnHQgw*8NBcCSVx*8ezE0wbPcMlIgeDb6rvQjs0OTxFg0isgV8X5nWlH0B0o2d21M0O35RCQLMBI89YAG5/CIMG0661.jpg?width=750" width="194" /></a>San Jose is one of the 25 cities participating in DOE’s Solar America communities Program. San Jose’s vision over the next 15 years is to achieve the following goals and to reduce the carbon footprint in the city by more than half: create 25000 clean Tech jobs as the world center of Clean Tech innovation, reduce per capita Energy use by 50%, receive 100% of our electrical power from clean renewable sources, build or retrofit 50 million square feet of green buildings and replace 100% of our streetlights with smart zero-emission lighting.</p>\n	<p>\n		One of the special projects funded is the San Jose Clean Energy Showcase - a Green Vision Education and Demonstration Center that acts as the hub of providing information on solar technologies and innovative financing options and allows the community to gain hands-on experience with solar technologies.</p>\n	<p>\n		The San Jose Clean Energy Showcase brings cutting edge technologies and innovations in the area of renewable energy to the footsteps of residents, educating them about energy efficiency and use of renewable sources in their homes. The showcase is a live, hands-on, instructional experience for existing and potential home owners to learn about the benefits of using clean energy while experiencing and learning about various clean energy options available in the market today, and by directly talking to and learning more with company representatives available in the showcase.</p>\n	<div>\n		Participants in the clean energy showcase include various companies that are leaders in their renewable energy domains (example solar or wind technology companies). The clean energy showcase also brings together schools and colleges like SJSU School of Art and Design and the San Jose Public Art department.</div>\n	<div>\n		Following are some of the participants and the projects that are demonstrated to the public:</div>\n	<ol>\n		<li>\n			<b>Windspire Energy</b> – Off Grid vertical axis wind turbine.</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Schuco / Sunwater Solar</b> – An off-grid roof-mounted Solar thermal system</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Sunpods</b> – A factory built solar array utilized for both on and off-grid solar energy projects by Sunpods. Includes a turnkey electric vehicle charging station and car.</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Cool Roof Display</b> – Lawrence Berkley National Lab Heat Island Group</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Silicon Valley Energy Watch and New Avenue Homes -</b> New Avenue EcoHome featuring energy efficiency technologies</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>City of San Jose Public Art Program/ San Jose State University/ Qcells</b> - Off grid thin film photovoltaic shading structure with interactive elements</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Burnham Energy/ Stion/ Fresco</b> - Grid-tied high-efficiency thin film array</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Nanaosolar/ Real Good Solar/ Sunlink</b>&nbsp; - Grid-tied High efficiency thin-film photovoltaic array</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Cromasun</b> – A high performance solar collector for powering industry and air conditioning systems</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Sopogy</b> – Off-grid Micro Concentrating Solar Power Collector</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Akena solar (Westinghouse Solar)/ San Jose Fire department/ SMA America</b> - Two grid tied systems side by side arrays demonstrating photovoltaic modules utilizing traditional inverters vs. micro inverters</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Armageddon Energy –</b> Grid tied, light weight Solar Clover photovoltaic array</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>Sunpower</b> - Grid tied array showcasing Sunpower’s T5 photovoltaic commercial roof tiles.</li>\n		<li>\n			<b>US Solar &amp; Wind Synergies</b> – Off-grid LED streetlights with wind turbine, photovoltaic module and battery storage</li>\n		<li>\n			Off-grid photovoltaic modules with electric car plug-in capability and battery storage</li>\n	</ol>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p style="text-align: center;">\n		<span style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>Highlights from Solar Energy Efficiency Fair – April 30th</b></span></p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Home efficiency through State rebates Energy Workshop by Solar City -</b> This talk highlighted steps that homeowners can take to increase home energy efficiency before actually installing any solar PVs and also described preferred ways to get your home audited for energy efficiency. Solar City via an agency called BPI certifies houses and buildings by using a DOE certified software that simulates the energy utilized in a house using various factors like Latitude, Longitude, Air flows, etc, and calculates potential gains for homeowners in terms of energy savings as well as rebates upon installing energy efficient measures. For example, existing attic and crawl space leakages are detected, duct systems are inspected as potential leak sources, blower door tests are performed, and a 3 hour energy evaluation is done to determine the current energy efficiency of your home, followed by home energy improvement suggestions that a home owner may be interested in. After the workshop interested home-owners could enroll for discounted energy evaluation sessions with Solar City and BPI.</p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Go Solar and Save Workshop by Real Good Solar and Sunpower -</b> This talk highlighted the rebates and incentives that homeowners are entitled to when they install Solar PVs in their homes. A representative from Freedom Solar, a vendor agency of Sunpower, spoke about how to decrease our energy bill, how to calculate payback times on installing a solar PV panel, how to get inspections done, permit conditions, how to get certified contractors, typical rates, and various other aspects of interest to home owners potentially seeking to install Solar PV panels. Various important trivia was shared. For example a $150 per month electricity bill means you will save by installing solar PV. &nbsp;Or that with the current AB 920 legislation, home owners can expect changing rates (12 cents per 2KwH from 8.5 cents per 2 KwH last year), pay off period on smaller systems is typically 25 years while larger system installations have faster payback rates.</p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Solar Hot Water Workshop by Schucco</b></p>\n	<div id="page_note">\n		This workshop highlighted the benefits of using Solar Hot Water in homes. For example typical thermal collectors are at about 75 gallons capacity and save 70% of your energy. Schuco also had an actual exhibit and demonstration of their Solar Hot Water equipment installed in a model home and an expert was available to explain and answer any questions around the solar hot water equipment’s installation, use and maintenance. The equipment shown in the demo uses a Glycol Antifreeze that flows through the pump and heats up the water. Costing around $12,000, there is also a $3000 rebate and a 30% tax credit that can be claimed. Vendors like Apollo Systems support both Solar PV and Thermal installations, and provide a monitoring system to the home owner to detect that systems are working. An interesting use of this technology can be applied in your Pools by using a radiant system that costs $10,000 with a 30% rebate.</div>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Workshop by Firefighters Association <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/r3RyWpafVZifH*gJEFAgAaJx07f1HrX-rb43hS8atKEz4SocfZmmAfF4KJOqMPx0Glhsw164iQzE3zkEoFoYFTwdEqXT4l0g/CIMG0655.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-right" height="162" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/r3RyWpafVZifH*gJEFAgAaJx07f1HrX-rb43hS8atKEz4SocfZmmAfF4KJOqMPx0Glhsw164iQzE3zkEoFoYFTwdEqXT4l0g/CIMG0655.jpg?width=750" width="217" /></a></b></p>\n	<div id="page_note">\n		The workshop explained about “Setbacks” that are installed in the San Jose Fire code now so as to allow spaces in the roof of homes for fire-fighters to climb up and shut down any fires caused due to overheating of Solar PV panels. Around 600V of electricity continuously flows in a typical micro-inverter type PVs installed at the roof of your home, and an accidental fire caused due to a PV is harder to put out, simply because there is no wire that can be disconnected. There was a live demo by firefighters as they made people aware of precautions to take when installing or cleaning PVs on your rooftops.</div>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>SJSU - Students showcasing college projects</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Finally, a lot of innovative real life projects in progress were showcased by students of SJSU. For example the picture illustrates the bike-bud project that uses solar panels in an innovative way, promoting not only solar panels but also the healthy activity of biking in the community.</p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>EcoCloud™ members:</b> This is a collaborative site. Please add your own case studies here. When your page is ready, add a link to the list at left. All contributed content is subject to moderation. <a href="/page/getting-started#contributor_howto">Get started</a></p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-simple', 1, 'default'),
(993, 'default', 67, '<h2>\n	Legal and Economic issues include:</h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Labeling items as sustainable (or "green")</li>\n	<li>\n		Pricing issues</li>\n	<li>\n		Legal responsibility for disposal</li>\n	<li>\n		others</li>\n</ul>\n<div id="page_note">\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>EcoCloud™ members:</b> This is a collaborative site. We really appreciate any ideas or suggestions you may have regarding this EcoCloud sector. Please email <a href="mailto:ecocloud@sustainablesv.org">ecocloud@sustainablesv.org</a> with your ideas.</p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(999, 'default', 69, '<h2>\n	What is SunShares?</h2>\n<img alt="svlg_email_icon_v2.jpg" class="pyro-image alignment-right" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/54/0" style="float:right" />\n<div>\n	Silicon Valley Leadership Group has some good news for making home solar installation understandable and affordable.</div>\n<div>\n	Homeowners want to lower their utility costs and use solar to create clean energy but often are confused by the complexity of the process. Researching options is time-consuming and installing upgrades one home at a time is inefficient for contractors and costly to consumers. Developed by the City of San Jose as part of the Department of Energy''s Solar America Cities initiative, SunShares is a first-of-its-kind solar group-buy model that companies and local governments can replicate for highly attractive terms for employees to put solar power on their homes.</div>\n<div>\n	SunShares makes it easy for your employees to save money, cut energy use, and reduce their carbon footprint. The Program groups consumers and leads them through the process to secure a range of financing options that make going solar and increasing home comfort more affordable than ever. City employees were able to get 40% off the market price for installation costs, and subsequent programs with eminent Bay Area companies have seen discounts of approximately 15-20%. Through SunShares, the Leadership Group is seeking to aggregate member company employees throughout the Bay Area. If you’re looking for a great employee engagement program or a corporate social responsibility initiative, SunShares is both! Contact us at <a href="mailto:SunShares@svlg.org" target="_blank">SunShares@svlg.org</a></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Key Takeaways</strong></div>\n<div>\n	<ul>\n		<li>\n			SunShares aggregates the buying power of employee groups, providing access to more affordable solar energy and reducing return on investment time for homeowners</li>\n		<li>\n			Helps employees take advantage of state incentives through the California Solar Initiative, federal tax credits, and the benefits of net energy metering through local utilities</li>\n		<li>\n			Demonstrates strong corporate leadership by enabling employees to generate clean renewable energy for their homes while expanding organizational commitment to employee benefit programs</li>\n	</ul>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1022, 'default', 78, '<div id="xf_navigation">\n	<ul>\n		<li style="list-style: none; display: inline;">\n			<p>\n				<br />\n				<strong>Adaptation in Response to Climate Change</strong></p>\nBy <author class="name">Ursula Syrova</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Sustainability Lead</author>\n			<p>	<br />\n				Adapting to the effects of climate change is a hot topic now as efforts to mitigate against it are clearly not going fast enough. There is no exact picture of what the Bay Area in California will be facing, but the educated likely expectations are rising sea (and bay) levels, which will endanger development at the water''s edge, and decreased snow pack, which will endanger water supplies. More extreme weather also seems likely.</p>\n			<p>	<br />\n				The good news is that communities all around the bay are beginning to address these issues through development and land use policies, but these are big issues that effect everyone and there has to be collaboration and coordination.</p>\n			<p>	<br />\n				The Joint Policy Committee has provided the following two documents to highlight efforts currently underway:</p>\n			<p>\n				<span style="color: #0000ff;"><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/-k5gXZvd1w4ExmVs-1jyE5yhW0TaXmSmlouV4-AsY*AAv7T5Nd-elxqXZGhUqttAuQcYxcHEm3G2YyzjcsrdY5ozt1T8yRMT/CEProjectFactSheetFeb2012.doc" target="_self"><span style="color: #0000ff;">Bay Area Climate and Energy Resilience Project</span></a></span></p>\n			<p>\n				<span style="color: #0000ff;"><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/GdRPMa1VClvUVcklBNqnsZgMmaZw4udzfBsQhjBH6-bF-am93cnKi*25-7pCvIK6TpNALMqqdyuHArUYJWyMoCpXb7KGLT9V/BayAreaClimateAdaptMap1.doc" target="_self"><span style="color: #0000ff;">Bay Area Climate &amp; Energy Adaptation/Resilience Map</span></a></span></p>\n			<p>\n				&nbsp;</p>\n		</li>\n	</ul>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>', '', 'html', 1, 'default');
