(1030, 'default', 94, '<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: center;">\n	&nbsp;<b>$ &amp; Sustainability- A Success Story of Marrying the Two Greens</b></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Akraya, Inc., a Silicon Valley-based professional staffing and consulting firm is the living proof that a choosing corporate sustainability is not only an environmentally responsible but also a frugal decision. We owe much of the success of&nbsp; the company’s extraordinary green efforts to a fateful encounter Akraya CEO, Amar Panchal, had while waiting for his car at a local auto body shop. Amar happened upon a certified green business brochure, and immediately decided to learn more about how to decrease Akraya’s carbon footprint. Already long-interested in sustainability, Amar got his management team on board with his green initiative and thus, the “Green Earth, Green Akraya Program” was born.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	The first step in the program was to become a <b><i>Bay Area Certified Green Business</i></b> (BACGB). To achieve this, the Akraya staff learned in-depth about the required processes and how it benefited the environment. Using the BACGB Green Business Standards Checklist as a guide, the Akraya team made a to-do list to bring the business’ operations into compliance with the green business standards. The list addressed areas like resource conservation, recycling and pollution prevention. We introduced new recycling and waste management procedures, cut back on our natural resource consumption, and gave the employee break room a “green remodel”. The new employee break room was equipped with a new water filter machine that replaced plastic water bottles, several recycling containers, environmentally-friendly products and a poster with water conservation tactics. Plastic utensils and paper plates were replaced with permanent cutlery and plates and employees were asked to wash their own dishes.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	There was an adjustment period as employees became accustomed to the new ways of doing things around the office, but Akraya overcame these difficulties by taking the time to explain to staff why they were doing this, and shared data about how energy, water, and paper preservation can help the environment. In this way staff members were involved in the process and that helped them understand the implications instead of just making these things mandatory.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	As part of the resource conservation efforts, light bulbs were replaced with eco-friendly LED-certified bulbs and newly installed cubicle glass panels ensured that we maximize using natural sunlight instead of electricity. To prevent air pollution, we joined the Bay Area Air Quality Management District’s <b><i>Spare the Air Program</i></b> and introduced a new commute plan that allowed employees to work from home during rush hours when the air pollution report so advised.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	The company also incorporated the eco-friendly values into its formal office procedures. In addition to implementing a <b><i>Green Orientation</i></b> for new employees and a <b><i>Green Employee Policy</i></b>, the company premiered the <b><i>Green Akrayan of the Quarter</i></b>, a green competition that takes a playful &amp; fun approach to teach employees about how to incorporate green values into their everyday lives.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Becoming a Bay Area Certified Green Business in early 2009 and providing employees with a comprehensive eco-friendly education was just the beginning. Akraya reached out to its suppliers and encouraged and educated them about corporate sustainability as well. As a result of these measures, Akraya was commended by the city of Sunnyvale, CA for being a poster child of local small green businesses and going above and beyond the green standards. Acterra.org also awarded Akraya with the Climate Hero of Silicon Valley Award in March 2009.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	The changes made as a result of Akraya’s Green Earth, Green Akraya Program also contributed to the company’s bottom line. By eliminating plastic products like utensils and water bottles, Akraya cut back on plastic waste generation by 70%. Paper consumption decreased by 50% due to double sided printing and reusing previously printed paper as scrap paper as well as eliminating paper towels. Akraya also significantly reduced its office supply orders due to a central office supply station set-up by the printer that replaced individual office supplies on each desk. Since we also changed our office temperature settings to lower during winter and higher during summer and battle temperature changes using eco-friendly ways (like wearing a sweater in the office during winter or closing some of the shades to help keep the office cool during the summer), we were able to reduce our energy consumption as well. Our computers are set to stand-by mode if we leave the desk for longer than 5 minutes and the light is motion controlled; these small tricks also helped lower our electricity bill.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	In 2010, Akraya sought to extend its Green Earth, Green Akraya Program to the local community. Akraya partnered with the Northern California Minority Supplier Development Council and PG&amp;E to become a speaker at PG&amp;E’s <b><i>Diverse Suppliers Go Green Workshop</i></b> <b><i>Series.</i></b> At these panel discussions, Akraya educated large groups of diversity suppliers about the competitive advantages of going green, how the green certificate program works, and also shared useful tips on how to involve internal staff in the process. Through the increased visibility from these workshops, Akraya developed valuable relationships with diversity suppliers and opened a new platform for mentoring other diversity businesses in the procedures of becoming green, which in turn led to new business opportunities.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	From great press to an impact on the bottom line, Akraya has seen firsthand how many bonus benefits can stem from investing in eco-friendly changes in your office. Akraya leadership hopes to reach beyond its direct circle of influence to continue spreading the importance of green education and the notion that committing to environmental sustainability is quite the worthwhile investment.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1038, 'default', 96, '<h2>San Jose State University Uses Control System to Reduce Wastewater and Improve the Use of Recycled Water</h2>\n<p> </p>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><b>A Cooling Tower Case Study</b></p>\n<p>SAN JOSE STATE UNIVERSITY (SJSU) Central Plant (Plant) provides steam heating, chilled water cooling, and electrical distribution for approximately five million square feet of urban university building space. The facility uses a forced draft cooling tower for the production of chilled water. Since 1999 SJSU has enjoyed the cost benefits and the challenges of using recycled water for cooling tower make up.</p>\n<p>Additionally the campus community strives to be a good steward of the earth. By conserving water, using recycled water for non-potable uses such as cooling, and lowering sewer discharge, they were able to attain this more nebulous goal.</p>\n<h3>Problem</h3>\n<p>The existing cooling tower treatment control was setup conservatively to ensure that fluctuations in recycled water chemistry would not disturb operation of the system. Conductivity was controlled at a fixed rate, and adjusted to accommodate wet chemistry results, chlorine was fed to keep a sufficient residual to handle biological growth, and corrosion inhibiter was controlled by using a trace dye in the product. Since the control method was not precise, the chemical usage was programmed within a range, and it was never exact. More chemicals were being used than needed, thus providing the Plant with more frequent discharge to sewer because they were using the ideal water chemistry for the maximum cycles in the tower.</p>\n<h3>Goals</h3>\n<p>SJSU had a dual goal with this project:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Reduce the Plant''s flow to the sanitary sewer.</li>\n<li>Improve the efficiency of recycled water use in the cooling system.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Solution</h3>\n<p>SJSU has access to an on campus well or recycled water. They evaluated which was more cost effective. A computer based modeling program determined the program control limits for the cooling tower using both recycled water and well water. The modeling program determined that the Plant could run the cooling water system at a maximum of six cycles with the new control using either recycled water or well water; keeping the sewer flow the same regardless water source.</p>\n<p>When operational costs are compared, there is a cost benefit to having better automation regardless of water source. Because recycled water has a lower unit cost, the plant is better off using recycled water than using well water, as shown in the figure below:</p>\n<p><img src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/7AEjcO4sPF7DdT9mlG4EiRgaoFBimYtnAX4bkGLzM4gUWfcBLA4sr14TaHaEnrzDYc5bGl*QQpIXJW-A7PaYoFVgOpfPq56r/SJSU_Program_Comparison.png?width=721" /></p>\n<p>SJSU purchased a controller to improve their ability to monitor the Plant. It accurately traces the active polymer used in the process for scaling control. This allows the Plant to measure the proportional amount of product fed to the system, and the amount of active polymer remaining in the water. With the new technology, they no longer need to carry artificially high residual polymers to compensate for changes in tower loading. Conductivity is controlled and run at higher levels, and significant changes in make up water quality are automatically monitored. Bio-control is improved by measuring active biological growth in the tower basin with a color sensitive dye.</p>\n<p>The new controller increased the number of cycles of concentration in the cooling tower from between two and three to up to between five and six, drastically reducing the campus’ industrial waste water discharge to the sanitary sewer.</p>\n<h3>Results</h3>\n<p>Since installing the new control technology in October 2006, the plant has reduced blowdown and sewer flow by an average of 60%, (14,700 gallons per day). They are meeting their goal of reducing the daily sewer flow and have realized a significant cost savings. Additionally, operators have more information about system performance which helps to improve the reliability of the cooling water system and minimize maintenance costs.</p>\n<p>The new system benefits exceed performance and cost benefit expectations in some unanticipated ways. Previously the makeup water contained more chlorine than was necessary to maintain system performance. By actively controlling the chlorine feed base on biological growth, chlorine use dramatically decreased. With reduced chlorine residual, other treatment chemicals are less likely to be consumed by the oxidizer. This coupled with the active polymer control has significantly reduced the cost of water treatment at the Plant.</p>\n<h3>Return on Investment Analysis</h3>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td width="50%">Modification cost (includes purchase of equipment, installation and annual maintenance package)</td>\n<td>$11,545</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Chemical Savings Realized</td>\n<td>$ 1,345/month</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Recycled Water Cost Savings Realized</td>\n<td>$ 78/month</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Sewer Cost Savings Realized</td>\n<td>$ 1,185/month</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Total Operational Cost Savings</td>\n<td>$2,608/month</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><b>Time to Payout: 135 days - 0.37 years</b></p>\n<hr />\n<p>Thanks to Chris Nordby of SJSU and Chris Buchholz of Nalco for their assistance in preparing this case study.</p>', '', 'html', 1, 'default'),
(1072, 'default', 80, '<img alt="wrappingpaper.jpg" class="pyro-image alignment-left" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/67/0" style="float: left; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; " />\n<p>\n	<strong>Thinking and Acting with Sustainability in Mind During the Holidays</strong></p>\n<p>\n	In late December every year, MORE is the operative word for most of us and society in general it seems, and that includes creating a lot more waste (waste generation goes up at least 25% during this time of year). &nbsp;Resisting the siren call of advertising and cultural pressure can be challenging during the holidays, but making different choices as you go along is always worthwhile.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>For a super sustainable holiday gift idea</strong>, how about <a href="https://www.sustainablesv.org/civicrm/contribute/transact?reset=1&amp;id=1" target="_self">giving Sustainable Silicon Valley a donation</a>? We have a wish list if you want ideas or have something you could re-gift to us. Tax-deductible, too!</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Some basic goals for the holidays:</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Vote with your dollars:</strong> Think outside the big box store and look for something local, fair trade, sustainably produced. &nbsp;<a href="http://www.calrecycle.ca.gov/RecycleStore/" target="_blank">CalRecyle</a>&nbsp;has some great items made with recycled content to get you thinking.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Wrap it with re-use:</strong> &nbsp;Use fabric, use decorative bags, use interesting boxes. &nbsp;<a href="http://www.recycleworks.org/resident/giftsandpackaging.html#gifts" target="_blank">RecycleWorks</a>&nbsp;has many great ideas for gifts and wrapping.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Wrap it with recycling:</strong>&nbsp;That metallic wrapping paper sure is pretty, but it can''t be recycled. &nbsp;Let go of the glam when buying wrapping paper, and if you feel like it, try getting the paper off of gifts you receive somewhat intact so you can use it again. &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>More inspiration for less-is-more holidays:</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Make enjoying and honoring the world around you part of your holidays: <a href="http://wilderness.org/content/green-holiday-ideas-make-your-holidays-easy-earth" target="_blank">The Wilderness Society</a>&nbsp;has brought together many great ideas for gift giving, decorating and even eating during the holidays.</p>\n<p>\n	As the <a href="http://sierraclub.typepad.com/" target="_blank">Sierra Club</a>&nbsp;says, ''tis the season for consumption, and they have many ideas to help rein it all in, including a good one that is easy to forget--bring your own bag to every store, not just the grocery store.</p>\n<p>\n	Feeling economically constrained but still want to embrace your eco values? &nbsp;Here are some <a href="http://sierraclub.typepad.com/greenlife/2011/11/going-green-on-a-tight-budget-deals-and-bargains.html" target="_blank">budget friendly tips</a>&nbsp;for that, too.</p>\n<p>\n	If you are ready to think completely outside the box, there are many gifts that support worthy causes, such as the <a href="https://www.nrdcgreengifts.org/" target="_blank">Natural Resources Defense Council</a>, which offers gift-versions of support for various causes.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
