(1216, 'default', 93, '<p>\n	<strong>Santa Clara Valley Water District</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	The Santa Clara Valley Water District (District) in California is a water wholesaler for all of Santa Clara County and offers water conservation and water recycling programs for the areas’ 15 cities, 1.8 million residents and 200,000 commuters. While the primary goal of water recycling programs and water conservation programs is to use water more efficiently thereby reducing the demand for potable water, water conservation and water recycling save energy (and consequently reduce air pollution because energy production generates air pollutants) by reducing flow through California’s energy-intensive water supply chain. In 2007 the District was the first agency in the state to complete an analysis to estimate the energy saved (and air pollutant emissions reduced) by the District’s water conservation and water recycling programs. The District recently updated this analysis and developed a District-specific water-energy-air pollution model to incorporate the complexities of the District’s water supply system. The District’s water recycling programs and water conservation programs have been in operation since FY 92-93 and have saved 547,000 acre-feet of potable water. The model’s whole systems approach for quantifying water-related energy use provides water supply planners with an overview of the energy intensity of different water supply scenarios.</p>\n<p>\n	For FY 92-93 through FY 08-09, the District has saved approximately 2.67 billion kilowatt-hours (kWh) of energy, which represents a financial savings of approximately $347 million and is equivalent to the annual electricity required for over 412,000 households. Through saving energy the District eliminated the emissions of approximately 625 million kg of carbon dioxide (over the FY 92-93 through FY 08-09 time span), the equivalent of removing over 115,000 passenger cars from the roads for one year. The District also reduced the emissions of several other air pollutants due to the energy saved by its water conservation and water recycling programs: reactive organic gases (39,361 kg), carbon monoxide (564,349 kg), nitrogen oxides (275,610 kg), sulfur oxides (26,259 kg), and particulate matter smaller than 10 microns (48,560 kg). The new report includes an expanded section regarding recycled water, including the energy saved (and air pollutant emissions reduced) from the use of advanced treated recycled water, which the District will be producing within the next three years.</p>\n<p>\n	For more information about Santa Clara Valley’s energy water savings see the latest <a href="http://www.valleywater.org/" target="_blank">Watts to Water Report</a> published in May 2011 on Santa Clara Valley Water District website (put in search terms “energy and water” to find the pdf).</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default');
