(1221, 'default', 35, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Water Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	Water conservation, which relies on a thorough cost-benefit analysis to develop program details and rebate levels, is widely considered the most cost-effective option in any water supply portfolio.</p>\n<p>\n	<img class="align-left" height="132" src="http://api.ning.com/files/RKlq075fWQGPbcV3qh1TGjNP-XX2f2UuOdCX*baeqKqQ5-LgAS2wPfOH3qvanx8ioKEflTqsZlaIBUs-KU3gVbF-fNlgwUmJ/waterconservation.jpg?width=115" width="117" />Water conservation programs reduce demand on existing water and energy supplies, helping to lessen the costs and environmental impacts of developing additional supplies. In addition to helping to meet long-term water reliability goals, the District’s programs also help meet short-term demands placed on supply during critical dry periods as well as during a regulatory drought. These programs also protect the South Bay salt-marsh habitat and the endangered species that live there by reducing freshwater effluent released from wastewater treatment facilities.</p>\n<p>\n	In November 2009, Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger signed the historic water conservation bill, S.B. 7, at the SCVWD campus. This bill mandates the long-term goals of reducing per-capita urban water use by 20 percent by the year 2020. SCVWD’s water conservation program resulted in nearly 50,600 acre-feet of water savings in FY 09/10. <a href="http://www.valleywater.org/EkContent.aspx?id=2991">http://www.valleywater.org/EkContent.aspx?id=2991</a></p>\n<h3>\n	Water Conservation Resources from Bay Area organizations</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Bay Area Green Business Program</li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			The <a href="http://www.greenbiz.ca.gov/">Bay Area Green Business Program</a> is a partnership of environmental agencies and utilities that offers assistance and incentives to participating businesses to conserve energy and water, minimize waste, prevent pollution, and shrink their carbon footprints.</p>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		East Bay Municipal Utility District</li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			<i>WaterSmart Guidebook: Water Use Efficiency Plan and Review Guide for New Businesses</i> . A 242 page guidebook in PDF format, providing information on water-saving technologies for the commercial, industrial and institutional sectors.</p>\n		<p>\n			<a href="http://www.ebmud.com/for-customers/conservation-rebates-and-services/commercial/watersmart-guidebook">www.ebmud.com/for-customers/conservation-rebates-and-services/commercial/watersmart-guidebook</a></p>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Santa Clara Valley Water District <a href="http://www.valleywater.org/Programs/ConservationForBusinesses.aspx">http://www.valleywater.org/Programs/ConservationForBusinesses.aspx</a></li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			Information on rebates and Water Conservation Programs in the Bay Area</p>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Wholly H20</li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			<a href="http://www.whollyh2o.org/">Wholly H2O - California''s Integrated Water Reuse Management Center</a> is a catalyst for sustainable, integrated water management in California. Wholly H2O uses locally-adapted solutions for water efficiency, (re)use of rain, storm, gray, and black water.</p>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	Other Water Conservation Resources</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.cuwcc.com/">California Urban Water Conservation Council (CUWCC)</a></li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			CUWCC is a partnership of environmental agencies and utilities offering assistance and incentives that verifies participating businesses conserve energy and water, minimize waste, prevent pollution and shrink their carbon footprints.</p>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.stopwaste.org/home/index.asp">StopWaste</a></li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			A public agency serving Alameda County that offers programs, education and assistance on source reduction and recycling.</p>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.bayfriendlycoalition.org/">Bay Friendly Landscaping and Gardening</a></li>\n	<li style="list-style-type: none; display: inline; list-style-image: none">\n		<p>\n			A program of StopWaste, Bay Friendly offers workshops, classes and resources for a sustainable approach to landscaping and gardening for residents, landscape professionals and public agencies.</p>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<div id="page_note">\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1226, 'default', 97, '<p>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: #003366;"><b>Clean Energy Strategy Part of Santa Clara University’s Business Continuity Plan - Phase One of Smart Microgrid Project Complete&nbsp;</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	In 2006 Santa Clara University (SCU) conducted an energy strategy study as part of the university’s business continuity plan and its aim to become carbon-neutral by 2016.</p>\n<p>\n	“We looked at the next 20 years and what we needed to accomplish to ensure we had energy reliability,” said Joe Sugg, Assistant Vice President, University Operations at SCU. The university needed guaranteed energy reliability, some influence over the cost of energy, a move to green energy, and (to develop) the capability to operate with the grid down for extended periods of time.</p>\n<div style="float: right; width: 33%; margin: 4px;">\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSf6QtTUKGrLb3cCd5YyHErYQPkie3ewZCZUi3-mlQZIFvh**wPbhe7Ds1y2q06UGjnjouY6NkrNKVDPVoHFEyi-/8603_cut1.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-full" height="400" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSf6QtTUKGrLb3cCd5YyHErYQPkie3ewZCZUi3-mlQZIFvh**wPbhe7Ds1y2q06UGjnjouY6NkrNKVDPVoHFEyi-/8603_cut1.jpg" width="200" /></a><em><span style="font-size: 12px;">Joe Sugg, Assistant VP Operations SCU with SSV Executive Director Marianna Grossman testing a new prototype wind generator</span></em></div>\n<p>\n	“We knew we would need distributed generation capability on campus and a way to control our demand on campus and when our distributed energy was used. We also needed to be able to maintain continuity with the grid when it was up so we could take advantage of it.”</p>\n<p>\n	A smart microgrid became the necessary infrastructure to make it possible. A smart box will instantaneously sense any drop in supply, such as when cloud cover affects solar generation, and react accordingly by automatically reducing demand to match available generation.</p>\n<p>\n	In 2010 - the first phase of the project, SCU installed sub-meters into 14 buildings and integrated the smart microgrid’s onsite alternative energy sources, including solar. Phase 2 will connect the entire campus to the campus microgrid, and is expected to be completed ahead of schedule in December 2011.</p>\n<p>\n	SCU is currently producing 1 Megawatt (MW) from solar, 2 MW from diesel as standby energy, and generating biogas using garden waste. The university is also testing a new wind generator sited on the same roof as the university’s bank of solar panels and is in a product queue for a Bloom fuel cell that will generate an additional 1 MW.</p>\n<p>\n	According to Joe Sugg, the wind generator operates efficiently at low wind speeds; starting production at 2 mph. Energy from the generator currently is fed into a battery that is used to charge the university’s electric vehicles, and is not part of the microgrid.</p>\n<div style="float: right; width: 33%; margin: 4px;">\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSeMzwSmyu8zIA5ypizrtSBq55sSkiiKdPyCUkaY2xRXLQYC7keMqCb6q3sJJWM9cA7E7-YURRIABd3hrMAWOsbM/IMG_8678.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-left" height="213" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSeMzwSmyu8zIA5ypizrtSBq55sSkiiKdPyCUkaY2xRXLQYC7keMqCb6q3sJJWM9cA7E7-YURRIABd3hrMAWOsbM/IMG_8678.jpg?width=750" width="330" /></a><em><span style="font-size: 12px;">Monitoring the system and reviewing energy savings</span></em></div>\n<p>\n	While SCU expects to see savings of around 20% from on-campus energy generation and from reduced consumption, the real benefits are energy and cost reliability, simplified building management, and reduced CO<sub>2</sub>.</p>\n<p>\n	“We know the cost of solar electricity for the next 20 years, and we like the price,” said Joe Sugg.&nbsp;Distributed energy is not only the answer to SCU’s energy needs, but for the region overall, he says.</p>\n<p>\n	“I imagine our microgrid as one among hundreds. Our 3 MW generation capacity in combination with other smart microgrids becomes a powerful force in the Valley. “Silicon Valley Power” will be able to produce significant energy and carbon load savings.”</p>\n<p>\n	In 20-30 years from now, says Sugg, Long haul transmission of power from Nevada to California will be prohibitive. “It will not be an option.“</p>\n<div style="margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; border: 1px solid #CCCCCC; padding: 4px;">\n	<p>\n		SCU’s current system allows it to control HVAC systems and temperatures. A Trane environmental control system in conjunction with an Energy Management System from Serious Energy, processes server information to automatically monitor and adjust the optimum server room temperature. As a result SCU’s server room now operates at 85 degrees compared with 65 degrees previously.</p>\n	<p>\n		The smart microgrid, when complete, will encompass the entire campus and enable the university to instantly turn off lights and equipment in any building, ration electricity during prolonged power outages all from one computer.</p>\n	<p>\n		SCU is collaborating with Sustainable Silicon Valley and SSV partners - Cisco and Serious Energy.</p>\n</div>\n<div id="page_note">\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1236, 'default', 27, '<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">The EcoCloud™ site contains articles written by experts and advisors on a variety of sustainability topics.</span></p>\n<h4>\n	<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/water">Water</a></h4>\n<p style="margin-left: 10px;">\n	<span style="font-size:12px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif; ">EcoCloud exists to provide resources to water professionals, businesses and governments, with information and case studies&nbsp;to allow implementation of water projects and to connect with others in their region to implement their water projects.&nbsp; The EcoCloud team has focused on providing utilities, commercial, industrial, and institutional (CII) users, and water professionals, the case studies, metrics, tools, and frameworks to complete projects.</span></span></p>\n<h4>\n	<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/energy">Energy</a></h4>\n<p style="margin-left: 10px;">\n	<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif; ">Energy the key aspect or resource that allows earth’s various systems, including human cultural systems, industries and economies to survive adapt and grow. &nbsp;It is a natural capital that we as humans harness, convert and make use of in our daily lives.</span></p>\n<h4>\n	<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/materials">Materials</a></h4>\n<p style="margin-left: 10px;">\n	<span style="font-size:12px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif; ">The Materials Flow Cycle i</span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif; ">s the underlying indicator of direct human impacts on the environment due in part to human consumption.&nbsp;This impact is reduced by not only consuming less but by also making the full cycle of production, use, and disposal more sustainable. The diagram below describes the conventional flow of material resources through supply, production, consumption, and disposal or recycling.</span></span></p>\n<h4>\n	<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/transportation">Transportation</a></h4>\n<p style="margin-left: 10px; ">\n	<span style="font-size:12px;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif; ">According to the Environmental Defense Fund, roughly 20% of our greenhouse gas emissions in the U.S. come from transportation.&nbsp; Much of our country has grown up around the automobile, which was considered a clean tech option when it started to replace horse transport in New York City, but the downsides of the technology have made themselves known and as climate change and population growth become more urgent issues we need to start reducing our reliance on our cars. &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<h4>\n	<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/systemic">Systemic</a></h4>\n<p style="margin-left: 10px;">\n	<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif; ">Sustainability is the ability to endure. A sustainable system operates without need to draw on another system. Examples include healthy wetlands and forests. For human culture, sustainability means the potential for long-term support of people and their lifestyles. This has impact on environmental, economic, and social dimensions, which affect choices, behaviors, and costs.</span></p>\n\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1237, 'default', 87, '<p>\n	<span class="font-size-4"><strong>Successes -&nbsp;Where Green Can Meet Green</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Many companies are doing great work in their pursuit of ways to make operations more environmentally sustainable while also realizing financial benefit. &nbsp;Here we share some of those stories with you, while encouraging you to submit your own.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Case Studies:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/systemic/success-stories/akraya" target="_self"><strong>Akraya</strong> saves money and wins awards as a small green certified business</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/systemic/success-stories/air-products"><strong>Air Products</strong> makes use of recycled water&nbsp;in its Air Separation Unit</a> in Santa Clara, realizing great savings in the process.</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/systemic/success-stories/san-jose-state-university" target="_self"><strong>San Jose State University</strong> saves money using recycled water in their cooling towers</a></li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/systemic/success-stories/santa-clara-university" target="_self"><strong>Santa Clara University</strong> created a micro-grid</a> with on-site renewable energy production to realize significant energy cost savings and increased energy reliability.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1238, 'default', 95, '<p>\n	<a href="http://www.airproducts.com/">Air Products</a> is a provider of industrial gases. This case study describes how they converted to the use of recycled water at their facility in Santa Clara, CA.</p>\n<h2>\n	<strong>Air Products Turns Purple</strong></h2>\n<div style="float: right; width: 33%; padding: 25px;">\n	<img alt="Original grey water pipe" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/jyyrxk2K-1BeTKPwoM-03MXR7GKUk66kUWoqzX-StsfuXkQUyu5EBHffIgnzxp4SyHfQUmm2nG-Xr2bYyL3u*jo8R42YCe0B/AirProductsFig1.jpg?width=225" />\n	<p>\n		<i>Above: Original water pipe pumping potable water through the water cooling towers. This pipe will remain as a backup to be used in the case that recycled water is not accessible. Below: Air Products’ Erick Hawkins next to a new water pipe, distinguished by the purple, that will pump recycled water through the water cooling towers starting on May 21, 2010.</i></p>\n	<p>\n		<img alt="Purple pipe with recycled water utility water" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/1swj2CP2zdtILYvmPbnfeXZLHi0AoswkoJrBVhmm3VDq*SJx9GNjme6gXftriqRSSzKK8oyCaBdRGKzsrvonb*fpLCYNd2n*/AirProductsFig2.jpg" /></p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	Two pipelines connect to the sides of a large Air Products water cooler; on the left, a normal grey pipe that will soon shut off, and on the right, a light purple pipe already filled with six gallons of water and ready to be turned on. Air Products is the newest partner to the South Bay Water Recycling (SBWR), and on May 21st, SBWR’s system will begin to pump millions of gallons of recycled water per year into its Santa Clara Air Separation Unit. This program not only frees up 62 million gallons of drinking water for residents per year and takes the strain off of the Bay Delta ecosystem; it exemplifies how this private company plans to use sustainable principles profitably while creating partnerships within the community.</p>\n<p>\n	Air Products became interested in linking with the City of Santa Clara to recycle water at one of the quarterly meetings that the city hosts to share innovations and opportunities for industries in the area. At the meeting, a guest speaker presented on the recycled water program, its environmental and financial benefits, and the current map of its impact. Air Products’ Erick Hawkins and Luke Charpentier noticed the Air Separation Unit’s proximity to the well-established SBWR pipeline. Hawkins comments, “we were so close to the pipeline that it just made sense.” After taking interest and applying for the Recycled Water Service, Air Products went through the formalized process of confirming water suitability, cost-benefit analysis, environmental analysis, and permitting.</p>\n<h3>\n	<strong>Water Suitability</strong></h3>\n<p>\n	The Santa Clara Air Separation Unit separates air into pure liquid and gaseous argon, oxygen, and nitrogen distributed through a gas pipeline and by a ground fleet. The site uses water to cool the components involved in the process. After the water acquires heat from the equipment, it travels back to the water tower where it is cooled by evaporation. The cool water is them pumped back into the system to remove heat. Water is lost through evaporation, requiring water to be added to maintain the level in the tower. Second only to energy use, water is one of the most critical parts of this process, pumping up to 65 million gallons of water per year.</p>\n<p>\n	Air Products had to ensure that the recycled water was suitable for this use. The metals used in the water separation equipment are susceptible to corrosion, and the water that runs through it must be chemically compatible to ensure that it will not foul the equipment. SBWR provided reports on its recycled water quality in comparison to potable water. SBWR also supplied water samples that Air Products sent to independent analysts to confirm the water makeup. Air Products, through its partnership with G.E. Water Technology, found that the chemical makeup of the recycled water, while higher in Ammonia than the potable water, only required small changes to maintain the quality and neutralize the pH of the water. While this change attached an extra cost to water maintenance, Hawkins concludes that overall, the decision would both be “much cheaper and better for the environment.”</p>\n<h3>\n	<strong>Cost-Benefit Analysis</strong></h3>\n<p>\n	The financial benefits were clear. Recycled water is half of the cost of potable, accumulating nearly $100,000 per year in water savings for Air Products. The construction cost for the Air Products portion of the project were such that they met Air products required pay-back period. The City of Santa Clara played a major role in getting the new source of water to Air Products. The city conducted a project in parallel with the Air Products work, in which a new pipeline was extended 1300 feet to Air Products fence line. The city applied for stimulus funding through the U.S. Department of the Interior. The recycled water system was one of 60 projects on the west coast funded by the Bureau of Reclamation’s Title 16 Program. In addition to conducting its portion of the project, the city was extremely helpful in working with Air products in the design and approval stages of the project. “I can’t stress enough to how much the city helped us,” Hawkins comments.</p>\n<h3>\n	<strong>Partnerships</strong></h3>\n<p>\n	Air Products’ overall goals in the project were to pursue green initiatives and to network within a sustainable community of businesses. Its partnership with SBWR has achieved both of these goals by strengthening the green business and practice in the community. The recycled water project is one of many different environmental steps that Air Products has made internationally in its commitment to green business. In addition to connecting to the growing corporate culture of sustainable action, the formalized process that the Santa Clara Air Separation Unit has created serves as a model for other communities and projects with similar intentions. Branches in other areas, including Air Products’ Santa Fe Springs branch, have been looking into establishing their own recycled water systems. In addition, this project provides a model for success for local companies. The extension of the recycled water pipeline down Norman Street also provides a highly cost-effective opportunity for any neighboring companies to switch to recycled water.</p>\n<p>\n	Charpentier comments that partnering with SBWR creates a “new chapter as far as networking with a community.” Air Products’ participation within Sustainable Silicon Valley has reflected a desire for collaboration with South Bay industry towards a sustainable, environmentally conscious corporate movement.</p>\n<hr />\n<p>\n	Prepared by Elaina Marshalek – Sustainable Silicon Valley, May 10, 2010</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1239, 'default', 23, '<p>\n	<img alt="pedestrians_first.png" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/55/0" style="float: left; margin: 10px; width: 280px; " /></p>\n<p>\n	According to the Environmental Defense Fund, roughly 20% of our greenhouse gas emissions in the U.S. come from transportation.&nbsp; Much of our country has grown up around the automobile, which was considered a clean tech option when it started to replace horse transport in New York City, but the downsides of the technology have made themselves known and as climate change and population growth become more urgent issues we need to start reducing our reliance on our cars.&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	This issue goes far beyond people making different choices, because in most cities in the U.S. those choices don’t realistically exist.&nbsp; Even the greenest commuter is going to hesitate at a quadrupling their travel time in order to take the bus.&nbsp; Appreciating that fact, many cities and communities are working multi-modal enabling into their sustainability plans in order to reduce auto dependence for meeting needs of transportation to work, services, and entertainment.&nbsp; In fact, as cities in California are required to establish Climate Action Plans and make goals for reduced GHG emissions, there is no away to avoid the transportation piece.&nbsp; Alternative fuel vehicles are helping to some extent, but as communities move forward with broad sustainability plans, the single passenger car needs to be phased out—for space, for health, and for the climate.</p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	There are a number of established tools that enable multimodal transport, and this site will be examining each one in turn:</p>\n<br />\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Transit Oriented Development</li>\n	<li>\n		Bicycling</li>\n	<li>\n		Ride Sharing</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/transportation/bus-rapid-transit" target="_self">Bus Rapid Transit</a></li>\n	<li>\n		Congestion Pricing</li>\n	<li>\n		Highway Removal</li>\n	<li>\n		Traffic Calming</li>\n	<li>\n		Road Diet</li>\n	<li>\n		Price of Parking</li>\n	<li>\n		Parking Reform</li>\n	<li>\n		Incentivizing/improving public transportation</li>\n	<li>\n		Satellite work offices/work from home</li>\n</ul>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1325, 'default', 16, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Introduction</strong></p>\n<p>\n	A microgrid is a local electric infrastructure network consisting of energy generation, energy storage and energy distribution that can operate independent of the traditional centralized grid. It is a miniaturized replica of the macro electric grid that can be connected or disconnected with the macro-grid, so that it can operate either as the main grid’s endpoint when connected to it, or can take over the responsibility of generating and providing electricity to its local domain when it isolates itself from the main grid.</p>\n<p>\n	Local sources of electricity generation that the microgrid employs include renewable resources like solar energy in the form of photovoltaic systems (PV), wind energy in the form of wind-power systems, fuel cells based systems and various other alternate sources of energy. These local and small scale power generation technologies, also known as Distributed Energy Resources (DER), usually produce electricity in the range of 3kW to 10,000 kW and offer alternatives or enhancements to the traditional electric power systems. DG (Distributed Generation) looks at integrating various DER within the grid.</p>\n<p>\n	The generated energy in a microgrid can also be stored within the microgrid, leading to highly reliable electric power that can be provided on demand while allowing isolation from the main grid. This energy storage concept finds various applications, from individual energy backup clusters that are able to provide emergency electricity services in case of blackouts to military “backpacks” of self-contained electrical infrastructure, to a new form of consumer’s convenience where energy can be precisely controlled per consumer’s demand leading to its efficient usage, and where the consumer has choice to sell back extra electricity to the grid, or to voluntarily choose between microgrids that provide electricity at affordable costs since generation is local.</p>\n<p>\n	From an efficiency-perspective microgrids also offer an added benefit of being able to utilize by-product heat that is generated from local generation sources like micro-turbines into local processes for space heating in buildings. This concept of combining heat and power (CHP) finds good use in urban infrastructure like green buildings which can now be designed efficiently to take into account such capabilities of the microgrid that they are a part of.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Background</b></p>\n<p>\n	In the United States, the microgrid concept started in the 1990s, as a response to the government’s concern about the reliability of national electricity transmission. Formulated as a solution to relieve stress on an overtaxed electricity grid, the microgrid concept was born and fully started taking shape in 2002 with various government funded research organizations. Funding for this research came from the government, specifically from the DOE and California Energy Commission in the form of the <b>Consortium for Electric Reliability Technology Solutions</b> (CERTS). <a href="http://certs.lbl.gov/">CERTS</a> included various national specialists and researchers like Bob Lasseter who pioneered the microgrid concept and engineered solutions that allowed distributed generation (DG) to connect to the grid at a single point and operate 24/7. With excellent researchers in the foray, it was simply a question of time before real life micro grids would become a reality.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Microgrids in action today</b></p>\n<p>\n	After years of deliberation and thorough research, DOE has today started providing funding to Universities, school districts, hospitals, laboratories, industrial parks, military basis, national businesses, and prisons, for deploying microgrid technology. For instance, the Sacramento Municipal Utility District (<a href="https://www.smud.org/en/about-smud/contact-us/visit-smud.htm" target="_blank">SMUD</a>) bases it system on the original CERTS research when it operates a 310-kilowatt base load microgrid. SMUD’s microgrid comprises 3 100 kW reciprocating generators with a 120 ton CHP system from <a href="http://www.tecogen.com/">TecoGen</a> and a 10 kW photovoltaic (PV) system. Along with generation, the project also plans to integrate storage technology, for example, a 500 kW zinc-bromine flow battery. Integral to the SMUD project is the utilization of CHP systems that can double the system’s efficiency. Waste-heat from the 3 generators powers the absorption chiller system that in turn powers the air conditioning.</p>\n<p>\n	Another example is collaboration between Chevron Energy Systems, Satcon Power Systems and PG&amp;E for decreasing peak load, alleviating grid congestion and reducing carbon footprint by integrating microgrid technology within the Santa Rita prison. This microgrid is based off a 1.2 MW solar array. Other partners like Chevron are adding several 2 kW wind turbines and a battery to the microgrid system. During outages, the project plans to reuse energy stored in clean sodium-sulfur battery.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Tomorrow’s Drivers</b></p>\n<p>\n	CERTS in collaboration with <a href="http://certs.aeptechlab.com/">AEP</a> today helps define and test the microgrids model by looking at large scale integration of DER with the grid. In conjunction, smart grid development is driven by <a href="http://www.nist.gov/smartgrid/index.cfm">NIST</a> (National Institute of Science and Technology) which is responsible for defining similar interoperable standards for the smart grid, in collaboration with <a href="http://smartgrid.epri.com/">EPRI</a> (Electric Power Research Institute) and <a href="http://www.enernex.com/">Enernex</a>. Interoperable standards between these two approaches, coupled with various <a href="http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/freeabs_all.jsp?arnumber=4596703">IEEE standards</a> for islanding and energy-storage will further help bring in the microgrid concept as an integral part of the smart grid evolution for tomorrow.</p>\n<p>\n	Lower costs will also help drive microgrid deployment. While costs per kWh for centralized generation is increasing because of feedstock efficiency (CHP) and regulatory issues, the cost per kWh for distributed generation (DG) using microgrids has been falling because of low cost wind and solar, low cost storage and sensor networks to enable microgrids. All these factors together can help drive microgrid development and deployment for the future.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<b>References</b></p>\n<p>\n	1) <a href="http://certs.lbl.gov/certs-der-pubs.html">http://certs.lbl.gov/certs-der-pubs.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	2) “<a href="http://energy.gov/oe/downloads/why-two-grids-can-be-better-one-how-certs-microgrid-evolved-concept-practice">Why two grids can be better than one – How the CERTS Microgrid Evolved from Concept to Practice</a>” by Elizabeth McGowan, U.S. DOE, May 2011</p>\n<p>\n	3) <a href="http://der.lbl.gov/presentations/microgrid-smart-grid-activities-smud">Microgrid and Smart Grid activities at SMUD</a>, presented by Mark Rawson, Senior Research Project Manager, SMUD, 2010 Microgrid Symposium</p>\n<p>\n	4) “<a href="http://nanomarkets.net/market_reports/report/microgrid_markets_and_opportunities/">Microgrid Markets and Opportunities</a>” – Chapter One Report, May 2010, by NanoMarkets.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1328, 'default', 57, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author> <span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><strong>Green Data Centers</strong></span></h3>\n<div>\n	<h3>\n		<span class="font-size-5" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><strong>Best Practices for Making the Data Center Energy Efficient</strong></span></h3>\n</div>\n<div style="text-align: center;">\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<p>\n		Data Centers can consume up to 100 to 200 times as much of electricity as standard office spaces and so are prime targets for energy efficient design.</p>\n	<p>\n		This article provides an overview of best practices for an energy-efficient data center design and walks through some of the strategies that can be deployed in Information Technology (IT) systems and their environment, data center air management, cooling and electric systems, on-site generation and heat recovery.</p>\n	<p>\n		<span class="font-size-3" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><strong>Information Technology (IT) Systems</strong></span></p>\n	<p>\n		In a typical data center, IT equipment load can account for over half of the facility’s energy use. Use of energy efficient equipment will significantly reduce the load, which will also downsize the equipment required to cool them.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Efficient Servers</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Purchase servers equipped with energy-efficient processors and look for products that include variable fan speed. Servers that meet Energy Star efficiency requirements will be on average 30% more efficient than standard servers. Install power monitoring software on servers that can detect and direct certain servers to go idle or in low power.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Storage Devices</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Upgrade from traditional methods to thin-provisioning which will maximize storage capacity utilization by drawing from a common pool of purchased storage on an as-need basis. It will also allow for extra physical capacity to be installed when data approaches capacity threshold. Take superfluous data offline and consolidate storage drives into a Storage Area Network.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Network Equipment</b></p>\n	<p>\n		On newer generations of network equipment, look for active energy management measures like idle state logic, gate count optimizations and memory access algorithms to reduce energy usage based on variance of network demand. Ethernet network efficiency can also be substantially reduced by quickly switching the speed of network links to the amount of data that is currently transmitted.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Power Supplies</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Consider one power supply per rack instead of one per server. Integrated rack mounted power supplies operate at higher load (70%) as compared to individual power supplies (20% - 25%) which vastly improves power supply efficiency. Today it is possible to find power supplies with 95% efficiency which can also help lower the data center’s electricity bill.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Consolidation</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Consolidation happens through hardware-location and virtualization.</p>\n	<p>\n		Hardware Location – Equipments with similar heat load densities and temperature requirements should be grouped together. This allows cooling systems to be directed to the least energy-intensive set points on each location.</p>\n	<p>\n		Virtualization – Enable running multiple independent virtual operating systems on a single computer in order to drastically reduce the number of servers and thereby reduce the server power and size of necessary cooling equipment.</p>\n	<p>\n		<span class="font-size-3" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>Air Management</b></span></p>\n	<p>\n		Air management in a data center deals with things like minimizing or eliminating mixing between cool air supplied to equipment and hot air rejected from equipment. An effective air management system that minimizes bypass of cool air around rack intakes and recirculation of heat exhaust back into rack intakes can reduce operating costs, reduce heat related failures and increase the data center’s power density.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Implement Cable Management</b></p>\n	<p>\n		A poorly laid out cable system will obstruct and interfere with the distribution of cooling air. A minimum effective height of 24 inches should be provided for raised floor installations. There should be a clear and persistent cable managing strategy employed in the center.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Aisle Separation and Containment</b></p>\n	<p>\n		<b><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/CabR*RoJFfgdIv9d2XSZ4YgVmX4T5ZRg-Wedf9DP0T2hzyu1goIHKaXEQ2JTfG0yLyknHy-0sOcLVSGEGNX0AIEDZLdgAhW9/Aircirculation.png" target="_self"><img class="align-center" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/CabR*RoJFfgdIv9d2XSZ4YgVmX4T5ZRg-Wedf9DP0T2hzyu1goIHKaXEQ2JTfG0yLyknHy-0sOcLVSGEGNX0AIEDZLdgAhW9/Aircirculation.png?width=750" width="750" /></a></b></p>\n	<p>\n		<b>&nbsp;</b>&nbsp;Data center equipment should be laid out in rows of racks with alternating cold (rack intake) and hot (rack exhaust) aisles as this increases the cooling capacity of the system. Equipment with non standard exhaust directions must be addressed in some way (shrouds, ducts etc) to achieve the designed front-to-back airflow. Cable openings in raised floors and ceilings should be sealed. The hot air does not mix with cold air as per design and this can allow reuse of the exhaust heat.</p>\n	<p>\n		Use flexible plastic barriers such as plastic supermarket refrigeration covers to seal the space between tops of the racks to greatly improve hot aisle/cold aisle isolation. Use VSD (Variable Speed Drives) or other speed-control based fans to take maximum advantage of this optimization.</p>\n	<p>\n		Use overhead or under-the-floor air distribution systems. For overhead systems, diffusers should be located directly in front of racks, above the cold aisle. Under-the-floor air distributions systems usually have maintenance issues when wanting to change wiring etc and so must be very carefully planned.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Cooling Systems</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Cooling Systems should always keep in mind initial and future loads, and part and low-load conditions, as the need for digital data is always expanding.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Direct Expansion (DX) Systems</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Use packaged DX air conditioners as cooling equipment for smaller data centers. Also look for packaged inexpensive rooftop units. Several manufacturers also offer units with multiple and/or variable speed compressors to improve part-load efficiency. Also investigate newer energy efficiency cooling options that are integrated within the CRAC.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Air Handlers</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Better performance and efficiency can be achieved by utilizing specifically designed central air handler systems. Centralized systems today offer more advantages than traditional distributed systems. The following two pie charts elaborate on the differences between using centralized vs. distributed air handling systems in two fairly large data centers in terms of the electricity consumption distribution.</p>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n	<p>\n		<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/gmwAYGqjORKInCZEgFY4FVUEYr4NgHqDz3cI2dloTFEOGc0AcnkI-LsPhr3JxnnUA4ruVpGiM0fxOIEbwnJDwN5EquodnT-u/dcpiecharts.png" target="_self"><img class="align-center" height="287" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/gmwAYGqjORKInCZEgFY4FVUEYr4NgHqDz3cI2dloTFEOGc0AcnkI-LsPhr3JxnnUA4ruVpGiM0fxOIEbwnJDwN5EquodnT-u/dcpiecharts.png?width=750" width="610" /></a></p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Low Pressure Drop Air Delivery</b> A low-pressure drop design (‘oversized’ ductwork or a generous under floor) is essential to optimizing energy efficiency by reducing fan energy and facilitates long-term build out flexibility. Ducts should be as short as possible in length and sized significantly larger than typical office systems, since 24-hour operation of the data center increases the value of energy use over time relative to first cost. Periodic manual air flow balancing is more cost effective than implementing an automated air flow balancing scheme.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>High Efficiency Chilled Water Systems</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Use high efficiency VFD equipped water cooled chillers with an appropriate condenser water reset. Condensed water and chilled water pumps should be selected for the highest pumping efficiency at typical operating conditions, rather than at full load condition.</p>\n	<p>\n		A medium-temperature, as opposed to low-temperature, chilled water loop design using a water supply temperature of 55°F or higher improves chiller efficiency and eliminates uncontrolled phantom dehumidification loads (refer to “Humidification” and “Controls” sections). Higher temperature chilled water also allows more water-side economizer hours, in which the cooling towers can serve some or the entire load directly, reducing or eliminating the load on the chillers.</p>\n	<p>\n		The condenser water loop should also be optimized; a 5°F to 7°F approach cooling tower plant with a condenser water temperature reset pairs nicely with a variable speed chiller to offer large energy savings.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Free Cooling</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Most nights and during mild winter conditions, the lowest cost option to cool data centers is an air-side economizer; however, a proper engineering evaluation of the local climate conditions must be completed to evaluate whether this is the case for a specific data center.</p>\n	<p>\n		Due to the humidity and contamination concerns associated with data centers, careful control and design work may be required to ensure that cooling savings are not lost because of excessive humidification and filtration requirements, respectively.</p>\n	<p>\n		For data centers with active humidity control, a dew-point temperature lockout scheme should be used as part of the air-side economizer control strategy.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Thermal Storage</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Thermal storage is a method of storing thermal energy in a reservoir for later use, and is particularly useful in facilities with particularly high cooling loads such as data centers.</p>\n	<p>\n		In climates with cool, dry nighttime conditions, cooling towers can directly charge a chilled water storage tank; using a small fraction of the energy otherwise required by chillers. A thermal storage tank can also be an economical alternative to additional mechanical cooling capacity.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Humidification</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Low-energy humidification techniques can replace traditional electric resistance humidifiers with an adiabatic approach that uses the heat present in the air or recovered from the computer heat load for humidification. Ultrasonic humidifiers, evaporative wetted media and micro droplet spray are some examples of adiabatic humidifiers.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Controls</b></p>\n	<p>\n		A center-wide control system should be programmed to maximize energy efficiency. VSD should be deployed on CRAC and CRAH units. For raised floor installations, fan speed should be controlled to maintain an under-floor pressure set point. Variable air volume delivery systems should be installed. There is no need to tightly control humidity (a legacy approach).</p>\n	<p>\n		On the chilled water plant side, variable flow pumping and chillers equipped with variable speed driven compressors should be installed to provide energy-efficient operation during low load conditions.</p>\n	<p>\n		<span class="font-size-3" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>Electrical Systems</b></span></p>\n	<p>\n		Like cooling systems, consider initial and future loads, and part and low-part conditions when designing and selecting equipment for data center’s electrical system.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Power Distribution</b></p>\n	<p>\n		The electrical power distribution path consists of the utility service, switchboard, switchgear, alternate power sources (i.e. backup generator), paralleling equipment for redundancy (i.e. multiple UPS and PDU), and auxiliary conditioning equipment (i.e. line filters, capacitor bank).</p>\n	<p>\n		Operating efficiencies can be controlled and optimized through thoughtful selection of these components.</p>\n	<p>\n		Buy UPS systems for your data centers that have efficiency between 90% to 95%. Redundancy in particular requires design attention; operating a single large UPS in parallel with a 100% capacity identical redundant UPS unit (n+1 design redundancy) results in very low load factor operation.</p>\n	<p>\n		The following figure shows a typical UPS efficiency curve for 100 kVA capacity and greater.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/BhX1r4VBfPZdwrxs4jHjQFQnUmouM3lghk9yTN1Bl2eeGP7lkdTJeyEAnn4ZemS1bV6wxR7OMtJIPSuGOnG2OQgXWZSnuEtw/UPSGraph.png" target="_self"><img class="align-center" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/BhX1r4VBfPZdwrxs4jHjQFQnUmouM3lghk9yTN1Bl2eeGP7lkdTJeyEAnn4ZemS1bV6wxR7OMtJIPSuGOnG2OQgXWZSnuEtw/UPSGraph.png?width=750" width="750" /></a></b></p>\n	<p>\n		Line interactive systems often provide enough power conditioning for servers at a higher efficiency than typical double conversion UPS systems. New technologies currently being proven on the market, such as flywheel systems, should also be considered. Such systems eliminate replacement and disposal concerns associated with conventional lead-acid battery based UPS systems.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>DC Power</b></p>\n	<p>\n		One way to reduce the number of times power needs to be converted is by utilizing a DC power distribution. This has not yet become a common practice and, therefore, could carry significantly higher first costs, but it has been tested at several facilities.</p>\n	<p>\n		A study done by Lawrence Berkeley National Labs in 2007 compared the benefits of adopting a 380V DC power distribution for a data-com facility to a traditional 480V AC power distribution system. The results showed that the facility using the DC power had a 7% reduction in energy consumption compared to the typical facility with AC power distribution.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Lighting</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Zone based occupancy sensors throughout a data center can have a significant impact on reducing the lighting electrical use. Careful selection of an efficient lighting layout (e.g. above aisles and not above the server racks), reduced lamps and ballasts will reduce not only the lighting electrical usage but also the load on the cooling system.</p>\n	<p>\n		<span class="font-size-3"><strong><span style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);">Other opportunities</span></strong></span></p>\n	<p>\n		<b>On-Site Generation</b></p>\n	<p>\n		To reduce first costs, on-site generation equipment should replace the backup generator system. It provides both an alternative to grid power and waste heat that can be used to meet nearby heating needs or harvested to cool the data center through absorption or adsorption chiller technologies.</p>\n	<p>\n		An option is to use Co-generation plants, involving the use of a heat engine or power station to simultaneously produce electricity and useful heat. The waste heat produced by the generator can be used to run an absorption chiller which provides cooling to the data center.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Use of Waste Heat</b></p>\n	<p>\n		Waste heat can be used directly or to supply cooling required by the data center through the use of absorption or adsorption chillers, reducing chilled water plant energy costs by well over 50%. Adsorption chillers generally restart more quickly and easily compared to absorption chillers. While adsorption chillers have been in production for more than 20 years, they have only recently been introduced in the U.S. market.</p>\n	<p>\n		The direct use of waste heat for low temperature heating applications such as preheating ventilation air for buildings or heating water will provide the greatest energy savings.</p>\n	<p>\n		<b>Source:</b> <em>Best Practices Guide for Energy-Efficient Data Center Design</em>, Revised March 2011 edition, U.S. Department of Energy, Federal Energy Management Program.</p>\n</div>\n<div style="background: rgb(208, 208, 208); margin-top: 10px;">\n	<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;">\n		<strong>Other Recent Topics:</strong></div>\n	<div>\n		<a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/topics/energy/efficiency/benchmarking">Benchmarking Energy for Buildings</a></div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default');
