(1337, 'default', 103, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author> <author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<p>\n	In this section, we provide timely articles on trends in the Energy community and industry, including statistics on usage and production.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1344, 'default', 104, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author>, <author class="title">EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: #000080;"><b>U.S. Renewable Energy Usage and Production 2010</b></span></h3>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-3" style="color: #000000;">Dec 10th 2011</span></h3>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Renewable Energy Usage and Consumption</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	In 2010, renewable energy consumption in the U.S. was 8.049 quadrillion Btu, which was slightly more than 8% of the total energy consumed by the nation. The largest contributions in this 8% share of renewable energy come from biomass energy (53%) followed by hydro energy (31%), wind energy (11%), geothermal energy (3%) and solar energy (1%), as shown in the figure below.</p>\n<p>\n	<b><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/If60mtgyoRqp2tEasW071AP8W5FReLQK8Zitcw8JIKg-Fv2klks9UIG56CodC0Sq8CWohq057IfV6q7KQ0UKhepXy15KO7fs/EnergyConsumption2010.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-center" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/If60mtgyoRqp2tEasW071AP8W5FReLQK8Zitcw8JIKg-Fv2klks9UIG56CodC0Sq8CWohq057IfV6q7KQ0UKhepXy15KO7fs/EnergyConsumption2010.jpg" width="550" /></a></b></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Comparing Renewable Energy Consumption Trends with 2009</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/u-s-renewable-energy-usage-and-production" target="_self">Renewable energy consumption in 2009</a>was slightly less at 7.744 quadrillion Btu .The main drivers behind the increase in 2010 are consumption increases in biofuels and wind, of amounts of 288 trillion Btu and 203 trillion Btu respectively. These increases were partially offset by a decrease in conventional hydro-power by an amount of 160 trillion Btu. As a whole, renewable energy consumption rose by 6% from 2009 to over 8 quadrillion Btu in 2010, growing faster than the total energy consumption increase of 4% in the same period.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Comparing Renewable Energy Consumption Trends with 2006</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	From 2006, changes in renewable energy consumption and usage patterns in the U.S. have been significant, as depicted in the two figures shown below. Changes from 2006 to 2010 show an increase in wind power usage from 4% to 11%, an increase in biomass usage from 49% to 53%, and a decrease in the share of conventional hydroelectric from 43% to 31%. The figures also show that while both Geothermal and Solar have been growing quantitatively (in Btu usage) over this period, their shares have remained constant at 3% and 1% respectively. Overall, between 2006 and 2010, renewable energy consumption in the U.S. has quantitatively grown by more than 2000 quadrillion Btu, with increased share of wind energy and biomass energy consumption.</p>\n<p>\n	<b><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/QNlRtrWHNPhLA5dFDrhpOmvMKwQXCYIL5A08urWy9MqvtkrKZWFeRyJYqs1cR9EbAEfO6x8ulamT7xnCKTTCClWy-LiDUi-Y/REComparison20062010.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-center" height="362" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/QNlRtrWHNPhLA5dFDrhpOmvMKwQXCYIL5A08urWy9MqvtkrKZWFeRyJYqs1cR9EbAEfO6x8ulamT7xnCKTTCClWy-LiDUi-Y/REComparison20062010.jpg" width="619" /></a></b></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Increase in Biofuel Consumption</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	Increases in Biofuel consumption from 2006 to 2010 are largely from ethanol consumption which has more than doubled to over 1 quadrillion Btu during this period. This increase has happened because of two Government regulations; First, in the <a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/femp/regulations/eisa.html">Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA)</a>Clean Air Act section, the US EPA has issued an increase in demand target volume from 13.19 billion gallons to 13.95 billion ethanol equivalent gallons of bio-fuels in 2010, and secondly, the EPA has also now permitted the blending of motor gasoline with 15% ethanol (E15), raising this blending ratio from the recent 10% limit. The E15 blending is applicable to light-duty vehicles manufactured from 2001 and later. An 85% mix of ethanol (E85) also holds potential growth for the market. Biodiesel, on the other hand showed a decrease in consumption from 2009, due to the expiration of biodiesel blender tax credit and its late renewal in 2010.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Sector-wise Consumption of Renewable Energy</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	Interestingly, out of all the renewable energy consumed, only about half of the renewable consumption is for the electric power sector at 4000 trillion Btu. This market share has in fact decreased from 55% in 2006 to 50% in 2010, dropping by around 2% from 2009. This is followed by a steady share of 2249 Btu of consumption in industrial sector. Transportation sector’s consumption of renewable energy on the other hand has doubled during this period (from 475 trillion Btu in 2006 to 1098 trillion Btu in 2010, an increase from 7% to 14%) due to an expansion in biofuel consumption. Residential and commercial sectors had smaller but stable market shares.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Electricity Generation</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	Out of a total of 4,120 billion kWh of total energy produced in the U.S. in 2010, renewable energy generated 4425 billion kWh, or around 10% of the total energy produced. While total energy production increased by 4% between 2009 and 2010, renewable energy grew by only 2% in the same period, due to a net decrease of 16 billion kWh of conventional hydropower because of low water availability. With California’s exception, thirty seven U.S. states experienced losses in hydropower generation. The states of California, New York, Oregon, Texas and Washington provided more than half of the total renewable energy produced between 2009 and 2010.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Wind Generation</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	Wind generation increased by 21 billion kWh to 95 billion kWh from 2009 to 2010, providing 2% of total U.S. energy with the majority of increase of 6 billion kWh coming from Texas alone. Wind capacity expanded in 21 other states, while 2 states – Delaware and Maryland had wind capacity for the first time. Since 2006, wind generation has more than tripled, from 11,329 MW in 2006 to 37,889 MW in 2010.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Solar Generation</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	From 2006, when Solar had central station capacity in just 2 states, this sector has expanded to 15 states with capacity of 888 MW, with 4 new states in 2010. The largest share is from California (460 MW) followed by Nevada (137 MW), Florida (125 MW), Colorado (33 MW) and North Carolina (33 MW).</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><b>Growth Factors for Renewables</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	Factors contributing to the growth of renewables in the period from 2009 to 2010 were:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The federal <a href="http://dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=US13F">Production Tax Credit (PTC)</a> provided a 2.2 cent/kWh credit for wind and 1.1 cent/kWh credit for all remaining technologies like biomass, geothermal and hydroelectric.</li>\n	<li>\n		The <a href="http://dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=US02F">energy Investment Tax Credit (ITC)</a>, which is worth 30% of expenditures, was also available in lieu of PTC to eligible systems.</li>\n	<li>\n		The U.S. treasury grant program was also available under <a href="http://www.opencongress.org/bill/111-h4853/show">H.R.4853</a> providing a grant of 30 percent of the basis of property for wind, geothermal, biomass and other energy sources. The grant was 10 percent of the basis of property for geothermal heat pumps, micro turbines, and certain combined heat and power (CHP) facilities.</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/repi/">Renewable Production Initiative (REPI)</a> also provided a 2.2 cents/kWh incentive for new eligible facilities in operation.</li>\n	<li>\n		Renewable Portfolio Standards or mandates in 37 states.</li>\n	<li>\n		Lower cost of silicon used in crystalline silicon-PV installations.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Despite the effects of recession, competition from low natural gas prices and reluctance of utilities to enter Power Purchase Agreements (<a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/femp/financing/power_purchase_agreements.html">PPA</a>) with wind, renewable capacity grew in 2010 by 3%, or 4,019 MW. These trends indicate that the generation and consumption of renewable energy will be on the growth path in the U.S. in the foreseeable future.</p>\n<p>\n	<b>Source:</b> <a href="http://www.eia.gov/renewable/annual/preliminary/">http://www.eia.gov/renewable/annual/preliminary/</a></p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1345, 'default', 105, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author>, <author class="title">EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4"><b><span style="color: #003366;"><span class="font-size-5"><span class="font-size-4">U.S. Renewable Energy Production and Usage 2009</span></span></span></b></span></h3>\n<h3>\n	April 18th 2010</h3>\n<p>\n	Renewable energy consumption for generating electricity in the U.S. stands at 8% of the total energy consumed. The largest contributions come from hydro (35%) followed by wood (24%), bio-fuels (20%) and wind (9%).</p>\n<p>\n	<b><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/RHlZFMTJmWenn2lgW7FJqz*A1M5FQieZxPG2NfC16fXfklEkgwmAEmE7RBxYe4sm-kw6f801H7itENcidM2bthBkHLLqZM-k/us_energy_consumption_by_energy_sourcesmall.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-center" height="274" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/RHlZFMTJmWenn2lgW7FJqz*A1M5FQieZxPG2NfC16fXfklEkgwmAEmE7RBxYe4sm-kw6f801H7itENcidM2bthBkHLLqZM-k/us_energy_consumption_by_energy_sourcesmall.jpg" width="463" /></a></b></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	U.S. is also one of the largest producers of renewable energy, closely following China. The largest production share comes from hydro (66%) followed by wind (17%), wood (9%), biomass waste (4%), geothermal (4%) and solar (0.2%). In 2009, the highest year over year growth in renewable energy was for Wind, up 28% from 2008.</p>\n<p>\n	Despite this growth in production, only 53% of this total renewable energy produced is actually consumed for generating electricity. A 66% contribution of Hydropower in renewable energy production for example translates only to 35% contribution towards electricity generation (53% usage of 66% production) as Hydropower gets diverted to other uses.</p>\n<p>\n	Overall, renewable energy production increases by around 8% yearly, contributing to around 8% of demand and around 10% of electricity generation in the U.S. This is an indication of the strong growth to be expected with using renewable sources.</p>\n<p>\n	According to US EIA, consumption of renewable sources for electricity will grow up to 17% of total electricity generation by 2035, in large part due to tax credits, policies like RPS (Renewable Portfolio Standards) and how RECs (Renewable Energy Certificates) are used between providers and different states. Any deterrents to this growth will come from the cost of building renewable energy power plants and infrastructural investment required to connect remotely based renewable power plants.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1346, 'default', 106, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author>, <author class="title">EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: #003366;"><b>U.S. photovoltaic (PV) industry hits a record high in 2009</b></span></h3>\n<p>\n	The U.S. Photovoltaic (P.V) industry has been hitting record highs. According to a US-EIA report released in Jan 2011, the PV industry shipped nearly 1.3 peak gigawatts of cells and modules, representing a 30 percent year to year growth from the previous year. A major factor for this is thought to be Federal Stimulus funding coupled with significant manufacturing cost reductions.</p>\n<p>\n	<img class="align align-center" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/RHlZFMTJmWcr90IuVNrWLpKF1CFISm3hFR5wW4bZr71LW2ymDKn*q34-m7kC3WwF9x4GnX0uaTXDFLCnenIlh-3hvGUe-yPl/PVmodulesShipments2009.jpg" width="575" /></p>\n<p>\n	While demand for solar cells/modules increased greatly, overall profit margins decreased significantly from the previous year. This is probably due to many new companies entering this market, and the diversification of activities of existing companies. For example, in 2009, 43 companies were involved in module and/or cell manufacturing, 49 designed modules or systems, 34 developed prototype modules, 26 developed prototype systems, 54 were involved in wholesale distribution, 23 were involved in retail distribution, while 42 installed PV systems. Innovation will clearly be a differentiator in the PV market.</p>\n<p>\n	All 3 forms of PVs (Crystalline Silicon, Thin-Film and Concentrator) show excellent growth, with PV cells and modules increasing for the 6<sup>th</sup> consecutive year and reaching a record of 1,282,560 peak kilowatts in 2009. Electricity generation, which consists of both grid-connected and remote or dispersed applications, continues to be the predominant end use for PV cells and modules. In 2009, PV cell and module shipments to the electricity generation market totaled 593,308 peak kilowatts, or nearly 99 percent of domestic shipments. At the same time, exports of PV cells have also shown a 47 percent growth in 2009 from the previous year, and exceeded domestic shipments in 2009, accounting for about 53 percent of total shipments. Thus PV demand continues to be on the rise both within and outside of the U.S.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1347, 'default', 107, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Dominika Kurzeja</author>, <author class="title">EcoCloud Energy Content Developer</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-5"><strong><span style="color: #000080;"><span class="font-size-4">Wind Energy Trends in the US and Germany </span></span></strong></span></h3>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4"><strong><span style="color: #000080;">A Comparison of Key Elements</span></strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	Dec 11th 2011</p>\n<p>\n	Germany is often called the wind energy kingdom; the country’s wind energy industry is one of the largest worldwide. In 2007 Germany was the largest wind power generator in the world and currently it stands at the number three position, exceeded by China and the U.S. But what exactly is the driving force behind its success? What is so different about Germany’s wind energy industry compared to the US?</p>\n<p>\n	The boom started in 1991 by the introduction of a law that committed electricity supply companies to purchase the produced wind energy for a defined price along with continuous Governmental support for research and development. As a result of this political decision, by the end of 2007 Germany had more than a third of total installed wind capacity worldwide<span style="color: #000000;">[i]</span>. In addition Germany was able to become a worldwide leader in wind power engineering.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-3" style="color: #000080;"><strong>Financials</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	The most obvious difference between Germany and the US is the pricing model. In Germany the price for energy is fixed by law. <a href="http://www.wind-works.org/articles/fl_ElectricityFeedLaws.html">In this model</a>, utilities are mandated by legislation to provide access and a fixed price for electricity that is normally based on cost plus normal profit margin. One major factor for determining the price is the year of installation. For example: a wind energy converter installed in 2009 shall receive 9.2 €ct/kWh for the first five years, and after that the tariff decreases to 5.02 €ct/kWh for the next 15 years<a href="#_edn2" title="">[ii]</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	In the US the price for sale of power is negotiated through a Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) with a buyer (typically, a utility). Depending on various factors like location, capacity and duration of the PPA the sales price ranked between 3 $ct/kWh and 7.5 $ct/kWh in 2008<a href="#_edn3" title="">[iii]</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	One major advantage of the German model is the high investment security for wind energy operators, which means lower risks and therefore more investments. On the other hand, the US model is more flexible as operators can choose between the duration of their PPA and taking the long-term development of the energy price into account.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-3" style="color: #000080;"><strong>Interconnection</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Wind farms that deliver power into the grid are required to submit an interconnection request. This process includes a feasibility study, system impact study and a facility study.</p>\n<p>\n	Depending on the region, the generation queue is long and it occurs frequently that wind energy operators in the US need to wait couple of years in order to start delivering power. Moreover the wind farm owner is responsible for the cost of transmitting the energy from the wind farm to the interconnection point.</p>\n<p>\n	In Germany the system operator is mandated by legislation to interconnect any renewable energy source to his grid<a href="#_edn4" title="">[iv]</a>. This process only takes couple of weeks. Furthermore the system operator is responsible to provide an interconnection point directly to the wind farm, which means lower costs for the wind energy operator.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-3"><strong><span style="color: #000080;">Infrastructure </span></strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Wind energy farms are often concentrated in areas with high wind energy. These areas are not attractive for people to live. So after the wind energy is harvested, it must be transported to the population centers. Since few people live in the high-wind areas, the electricity grid is weak. As a result of this there is a high supply of wind energy, but not sufficient capacity for incorporating the energy into the grid. This bottleneck-problem is more pronounced in the US. With over 312 Million<a href="#_edn5" title="">[v]</a> people and 9.83 million km<sup>2</sup> the US<a href="#_edn6" title="">[vi]</a> is the third or fourth largest by total area. The density of population is 33.7/km<sup>2</sup>. In Germany the density of population stands at 230 inhabitants per square kilometer, with 82 Million<a href="#_edn7" title="">[vii]</a> people and 357.000 km<sup>2</sup>. Because of the higher density the infrastructure in Germany is more developed and the grid can incorporate more renewable energy.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-3"><strong><span style="color: #000080;">Grants</span></strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	In Germany there are several grants available on the national and European level. State-of-the-art projects can be eligible for low-interest financing. The development and demonstration of innovation is eligible for non-refundable grants up to 30% of the total investment costs. There are non-refundable grants available for research and development up to 50% of the total project costs. Furthermore the guaranteed Feed-in Tariff, which is financed by the German power consumer eventually, is a subsidy.</p>\n<p>\n	During the recession in 2009-2010 the US government initiated the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act 2009, which, among other things, extended the federal tax credit for the production of electricity from wind facility through the end of 2012. This Production Tax Credit (PTC) has been the major financial support mechanism for wind energy, which rewards the wind energy facility with 2.2 $ct per kWh for 10 years<a href="#_edn8" title="">[viii]</a>. In lieu of the PTC wind energy facilities could apply for a cash grant for 30% <a target="_self">[ix]</a>of the cost of the renewable energy facility, if the facility was placed in service in 2009 and 2010 or if construction began in 2009 or 2010 and it is placed in service before 2013. The application for the cash grants must have been submitted until the end of September 2011. That means that the primary financial support mechanisms for wind energy are going to expire by the end of next year.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.emerging-energy.com/" target="_blank">IHS Emerging Energy Research</a> forecasts, that without the PTC installations could collapse from an annual peak of 10.5 GW in 2012 to as low as 1.5 GW in 2013.</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-3" style="color: #000080;"><strong>Conclusion</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	As of today Germany ranks third with more than 27 GW total installed capacity behind the leader China with 44 GW and the US with 40 GW<a href="#_edn10" title="">[x]</a>, although China and the US are significantly larger countries than Germany. Consequent and reliable legislation, predictable financing and a developed infrastructure are the key to Germany''s successful and sustainable development of wind energy. Recently, the starting signal for commercial offshore wind energy farms has been given. It remains to be seen, which strategy will pay off.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><strong><span class="font-size-3">References:</span></strong></span></p>\n<div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><span style="color: #3366ff;"><a target="_blank"><span style="color: #3366ff;">[i]</span></a></span> <a href="http://www.gwec.net/index.php?id=90" target="_blank">GWEC: Global Wind 2007 Report</a></span></p>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref2" title="">[ii]</a> <a href="http://www.bmu.de/files/english/pdf/application/pdf/eeg_2009_en_bf.pdf">Renewable Energy Sources Act (EEG) 2009, Section 29</a></span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref3" title="">[iii]</a> Pramod Jain, <i>Wind Energy Engineering,</i> The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc. 2011</span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref4" title="">[iv]</a> <a href="http://www.bmu.de/files/english/pdf/application/pdf/eeg_2009_en_bf.pdf">Renewable Energy Sources Act (EEG) 2009, Section 5</a></span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref5" title="">[v]</a> <a href="http://www.census.gov/population/www/popclockus.html">"U.S. POPClock Projection"</a>. U.S. Census Bureau.</span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref6" title="">[vi]</a> <a href="https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/us.html">"United States"</a>. The World Factbook. CIA. 2009-09-30. Retrieved 2010-01-05</span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref7" title="">[vii]</a> <a href="http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/cache/ITY_OFFPUB/KS-EI-11-001/EN/KS-EI-11-001-EN.PDF">Key Figures on Europe</a>. Belgium: European Union. 2011. p. 37</span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref8" title="">[viii]</a> <a href="http://dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=US13F">DSIRE – Renewable Energy Production Tax Credit (PTC)</a></span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref9" title="">[ix]</a> <a href="http://dsireusa.org/incentives/incentive.cfm?Incentive_Code=US53F&amp;re=1&amp;ee=1" target="_self">DSIRE – U.S. Department of Treasury – Renewable Energy Grants</a></span></p>\n	</div>\n	<div>\n		<p>\n			<span class="font-size-3"><a href="#_ednref10" title="">[x]</a> <a href="http://www.wind-energie.de/infocenter/statistiken/international/welt-top-5-laender-installierte-leistung-2010">Bundesverband Windenergie e.V.</a></span></p>\n	</div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1348, 'default', 101, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author>, <author class="title">EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<h4>\n	May 1st 2012</h4>\n<p>\n	<span><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/s2sZbafeBpVgtE83ASSYv7gVTO-AwajJiyu-RAXcWiXnmHhVagGs9ybUXxl51OTphmXMeVMrxY-J-S-lBS4UGt1iVIH6lM9v/LBNLDC.png" target="_self"><img class="align-left" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/s2sZbafeBpVgtE83ASSYv7gVTO-AwajJiyu-RAXcWiXnmHhVagGs9ybUXxl51OTphmXMeVMrxY-J-S-lBS4UGt1iVIH6lM9v/LBNLDC.png?width=252" width="252" /></a><span class="font-size-2">At Silicon Valley’s annual Earth Day event on April 27<sup>th</sup>, Sustainable Silicon Valley presented the event “Green Data Centers: Economics and Operations” that was hosted by SAP and featured speakers from prominent companies like GE, SAP, Vantage Data Centers, Yahoo and LBNL. The two hour long program brought in data center expertise and experience from different perspectives and functionalities lik</span></span><span style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif; font-size: 12pt; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; mso-ansi-language: EN-US; mso-fareast-language: EN-US; mso-bidi-language: AR-SA;"><span class="font-size-2">e engineering design, software and IT operations, environmental strategies, and energy management programs. The audience was treated to valuable insights in data center energy optimizations as the distinguished speakers described state of the art best practices for data centers that were being pursued by their companies, and explained various strategies that have resulted in considerable economic savings and highly efficient PUEs for their data centers.</span></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span>The session started with the first speaker - <strong>Jonathan Koomey</strong>, consulting professor at Stanford University. Describing studies that were carried out in 2005 to measure how much of electricity was being used holistically in data centers in the U.S, the data revealed that data center electricity use had moved up to 1.5% of the total electricity consumed in the U.S. and had doubled in the last 5 years. A more recent analysis indicated a curb in this trend, as the electricity usage has not doubled recently, and is at 1.3% of the world and 2% of the U.S. electricity usage. From a high level perspective, key principles for ensuring energy efficiency in data centers were elucidated; Accurately evaluate your inventory like servers and other infrastructure, conti</span><span class="font-size-2" style="font-family: arial,helvetica,sans-serif;">nuously measure and benchmark your energy usage, focus on the total cost by designing efficient management hierarchies that can combine diverse operations like IT and facilities under a common cost control scheme, and start with a clean approach of design principles whenever possible to create a highly efficient data center. Data centers can be categorized into three types for easier understanding – high performance computing centers, in house data centers for companies, and the efficient cloud computing centers. Download presentation <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/zOxOn5w0LZVmAW3T1JpmuaywID0W6WC1Lvo-zjb123zGt-DLLjHospqGv2URo2egfVEDvHySOD0RnW5CKDKdn4NTJudlfbsw/KoomeyforSSVvantageSAPeventv2.pdf" target="_self">here</a></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span>The next speaker, <strong>Jennifer Fraser</strong>, Director of Engineering and Construction at Vantage Data Center, spoke from the perspective of client engagement in delivering a highly efficient data center designed upon sound engineering principles that achieve highly efficient PUEs. A key concept followed in Vantage Data Center is to understand the client’s requirements in terms of their IT, network infrastructure, engineering and cost requirements to come up with a more efficient design. Showing their LEED certified V2 facility in Santa Clara which has two 55MW substations allowing a client’s definition to be integrated at inception and the ability to expand from 9MW to 18MW in a very short time, Jennifer explained their emphasis on pre-engineered solutions and modular structures for clients. Techniques for managing density requirements (Watts/sq-foot) and utilizing outside air for cooling were described. Their critical mission is to keep everyone’s business online and a lot of infrastructure is in place to achieve this. A new tier 3 data center being designed by Vantage in Washington targets a PUE of 1.25 and will be capable of surviving natural disasters like earthquakes. All of their data centers are Platinum LEED certified and they report annualized PUEs of 1.12.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span>Next up was <strong>Brenda Riconscente</strong>, Regional Manager at GE representing mission critical applications. Brenda introduced and explained GE’s “ecoimagination” concept. Data centers today have individual control systems in different sections like power generation, power quality, electrical distribution, cooling, IT (AC systems) and facilities (lighting and security systems). GE’s ecoimagination solution combines all of these separate controls and integrates them into an easy to use front-end for efficiently managing data center operations. The architecture, design and resulting benefits of this system were then explained during this session. Check out GE presentation <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/L2qQFWBlV7V1xTXerj6EqvxXAeNYxRzpZV7yKQOBEaaDVxZ2So4M81gIVICEbituodwiOgEwdusXmwvFm55htiTI-mVyeG4U/BrendaRiconscenteSustainableGreenDataCenter2012.pdf" target="_self">here</a>.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span><strong>Gil Perez</strong>, Global VP for Sustainability Management and Strategy at SAP, representing the IT/Software aspect of data center optimization next threw a unique perspective into the session series by explaining how software contributes to carbon emissions, and how SAP implements methodologies that reduce IT consumption, minimize e-waste, reduce software complexity and improve hardware efficiency. Entire SAP systems that include servers, storage and network are power benchmarked with solutions that SAP co-develops with their partners. Gil also explained how virtualization as a technique is very useful in achieving high efficiency and showcased SAP’s NetWeaver platform. Download presentation <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/s2sZbafeBpUwaENLjQHFL9Ngh*Kzs-6lWEPqfJCrhBhyBXvV3YZaw8flP3Nw12JWRD6q8w9CCd4MccZNIeXGEPmEnvd*7TDK/PresentationGilPerezApril27th.pdf" target="_self">here</a>.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span>The next speaker was <strong>Christina Page</strong>, Global Director, Energy and Sustainability Strategy at Yahoo. Introducing Yahoo’s busy cloud computing platform that manages millions of users, data and service requests continuously, Christina took the discussion to a broader perspective about climate change and investing in large scale values, directions and solutions that can influence energy usage in data centers. Starting with a clean sheet for new data center design a couple of years ago where it re-evaluated design and metrics, the company today looks towards addressing factors like volatility in electricity prices by engaging in creative solutions that look at alternative renewable sources of energy production that could be beneficial to data centers. Yahoo’s long term goal is to reduce their MMT CO2 levels by committing to a downward trend for CO2 emissions that continue till 2050. The presentation can be downloaded <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/kBXneao3pCZZ4-B2i5jqORrkn8c8CgNZwa-pdJH6nsUdIz5ZM3g6Jqg50wOwDt07LV0ptNC5OAmPtmCWyl438DO98aQWHUs3/ChristinaPage_SSVevent.ppt.pdf" target="_self">here</a>. </span></p>\n<p>\n	<span>The last speaker for the event was <strong>Dale Sartor</strong>, Head Building Technologies, Applications Team at Lawrence Berkeley National Labs (LBNL). Explaining how power is lost as it is carried forth in various stages from raw material to delivery resulting in just 15% of the actual energy utilized at a data center, he emphasized opportunities available at every stage of the transmission process that can be utilized to optimize the flow. We could have on site generation and reduce transmission losses, utilize waste heat for productive purposes, increase voltage distribution, use uninterruptable power supply systems, reduce the number of AC-DC-AC flows in the system, and use various retrofitting applications to improve the energy efficiency of data centers. Mentioning that many data centers are outdated today with some having PUEs of 4, he cited best practices deployed at LBNL to achieve high efficiencies. LBNL has improved PUEs of their super computer data center from 1.4 to 1.28, while their enterprise data center has shown improvements from 1.65 to a value between 1.42 and 1.49. More can be learnt by downloading the LBNL presentation <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/hcqR2dDVLrF7qWoUFDGPC7PAPnEHUvKtsS*xyFrKGE8fP-Ore8XhMlmZS5UAB*wPQ6i-sYXKQFxqNi5LFGIn2MybwE*y*80Z/DaleSartorSustainableSiliconValley27Apr12.pdf" target="_self">here</a></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span>The speaker sessions concluded with enough time for the audience and participants to exchange information and ideas. In all, the Green Data Center event hosted by Sustainable Silicon Valley was informative, educational and provided valuable insights to the audience from these distinguished speakers representing various departments of their companies.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<strong><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/0LkAJB3pYofya9o6qUfSXwG9LLG6GQZSAyAL0tdw8X19W3WHn2CRxv5tM09kQVxbxZ2HeGuh4i2Zne9vaOy06BWhSqWsvzVW/AbouttheSpeakers.pdf" target="_self">About the Speakers</a></strong></p>\n<p>\n	<strong><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/sXf2Uvvj91vpjobgDnm2VbgAcWffYQEBQh9y9DoMR6RaCuuAlTzXpEUkeYDYgyReX92maOyllJFm1bUnidZZFbcqn4v5hE7M/Green_data_centers__20120427.pdf" target="_self">Event Agenda</a></strong></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #003366;"><strong>Speaker Presentations</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/q1pFLgiZZQt2Okb7NKD9XsvGvykoQwbtDx6TNEBZF53FlLeZgo6Tl7EJgJyI9Eya2P*nu8rZdU50jev1KjAxfVpU4FzMqfK4/BrendaRiconscenteSustainableGreenDataCenter2012.pdf" target="_self">GE ecoimagination presentation by BrendaRiconscente</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/UbSgRBJXnch-W8Skqwaf*NfXLZZktSBFsnmUk7KgK650duCYJ*2umkRmFDDy13*U5U-Xtjm2JW5EnlSuH2zuuL52Bpry9wzK/ChristinaPage_SSVevent.ppt.pdf" target="_self">Green and Greener presentation by Christina Page Yahoo</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/uEJKzE33jF5BgmMYjmJKJUbDYbsUazQKFehTAUkKOrcuVer553goJAEWZdiKNJ-5jWtqSsZCbUEbgyGhS8a6GRToe6kOOQoB/DaleSartorSustainableSiliconValley27Apr12.pdf" target="_self">Saving Energy in Dta Centers presentation by Dale Sartor LBNL</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/RdmFX6dG0mvjZXNRNojEtvc5mXYSw2Vt-fZ4mHSqstFhUoYdJMa1QTnC7C-wS7DmNgBhHv873*cqVpeTAYn8ngY4JvHIHH6w/KoomeyforSSVvantageSAPeventv2.pdf" target="_self">Capturing Efficiency in Data Center presentation by Jonathan Koomey Stanford</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/0O2xtKCJCOA*2BMuF5OL0lxJyNKszPxWa8BhA0FoLBMONnvu6lACTPFfImehq95IiBjaA1k3GIzF4834*fgtBNf4txPPF9*J/PresentationGilPerezApril27th.pdf" target="_self">Sustainable IT Operations presentation by Gil Perez SAP</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1349, 'default', 102, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author>, <author class="title">EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-4"><strong><span style="color: #000080;">CleanTech Open Global Forum 2011</span></strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-2">Dec 18<sup>th</sup> 2011</span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/content/home/index" target="_self">CleanTech Open</a> is the world’s largest clean technology business competition for clean tech entrepreneurs. This annual event in the U.S. that was started in 2006 seeks to discover, promote and reward the most promising and upcoming clean tech entrepreneur companies of today, by mentoring and training these companies and providing opportunities for Venture Capital <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/content/sponsors/2011sponsors">funding</a>of up to $250,000. Since its inception, this program has resulted in the creation of more than $300 Million of private capital by its alumni companies and has led to more than 2500 clean tech jobs in the market.</p>\n<p>\n	The clean tech open business competition of 2011 focused on key clean tech innovation and business ideas in the areas of Renewable Energy, Energy Efficiency and Smart Power, Green Grid and Energy Storage among other clean tech <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/content/competition/category_description">categories</a>. The <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/entry_list/2011/1">participants</a> for both the <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/content/competition/business/index">National Business Competition</a> and the <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/content/competition/ideas/index">Global Ideas Competition</a> included startups that had invested themselves in creating unique business opportunities in one of the key categories listed for the competition. After being evaluated all year long for their business viabilities and success probabilities, the 2011 event culminated into a 2 day <a href="http://www.cvent.com/events/cleantech-open-2011-global-forum/event-summary-d19f80c6f1db438889384f7894ef46bf.aspx">Cleantech Open 2011 Global Forum</a> event held in San Jose on November 15<sup>th</sup> and 16<sup>th</sup> 2011, where <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/entry_list/2011/2">regional and category finalists</a>had to compete by pitching their ideas to the judges and where the final winners of the 2011 competition were announced.</p>\n<p>\n	The grand prize of $250,000 went to <a href="http://www.atmrcv.com/">Atmosphere Recovery Inc</a>, the winner of the Renewable Energy category, for developing unique laser-based gas analyzer systems that enables advanced energy process control and efficient manufacturing. The runners up included <a href="http://www.indowwindows.com/">Indow Windows</a>, the winner of Energy Efficiency category, which manufactures thermal-window inserts that press into place on insides of window frames and improve performance at fractional prices, and <a href="http://www.pkclean.com/">PK Clean</a>, a company that incorporates a unique catalytic de-polymerization process that converts various forms of wastes into useful forms of energy.</p>\n<p>\n	National category winners also included <a href="http://www.gridmobility.com/">GridMobility</a>, the winner of Smart Power category, whose proprietary signal technology catalyses smart-grid growth by enabling business, industry and consumers to choose electricity sources based on personal preferences, and <a href="http://www.wholetrees.com">Whole Tree Structures</a>, winner of the Green Building category, that manufactures structural building systems made from round timber which is the waste product of sustainably managed forests.</p>\n<p>\n	Other notable participants included <a href="http://www.arcticsand.com">ArticSand</a> – an MIT spinout delivering power conversion with a 10X reduction in circuit size and cutting power losses by 75%, <a href="http://www.enovativegroup.com">Enovative Kontrol Systems</a> that develops patented controls for water heating efficiency systems, <a href="http://www.hm3e.com">HM3 Energy</a> that uses proprietary biomass torrefaction technology to convert woody biomass into energy-dense briquettes, <a href="http://www.KeystoneTowerSystems.com">Keystone Tower Systems</a> that use on-site welded steel towers for next generation wind turbines, and <a href="http://www.sheerwind.com">Sheerwind Inc</a> that uses proprietary technology to accelerate and concentrate wind to produce cheaper electricity than natural gas. A complete list of finalists can be found <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/entry_list/2011/1">here</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	Click <a href="http://www.pitchengine.com/zingpr/cleantech-open-announces-winners-of-2011-national-business-competition-and-global-ideas-competition">here</a> for a complete list of winners and announcements for the 2011 CleanTech Open competition. For general questions as a future participant to the CleanTech Open competition, check this <a href="http://www.cleantechopen.com/app.cgi/content/competition/business/faq">link</a>.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1350, 'default', 100, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4"><strong><span style="color: #000080;">Benchmarking</span></strong></span><span class="font-size-4"><strong><span style="color: #000080;"> Energy for Buildings</span></strong></span></h3>\n<h4>\n	<span class="font-size-2">Jan 2<sup>nd</sup> 2012</span></h4>\n<p>\n	Benchmarking energy means measuring the energy consumed by a building, using a standard set of tools like the <a href="http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?c=evaluate_performance.bus_portfoliomanager" target="_self">Portfolio Manager</a>, and comparing these measurements against a relevant set of energy consumption data using a program like <a href="http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?c=home.index">Energy Star</a>. Energy benchmarking in CA is currently mandated for certain non-residential buildings of size greater than 10,000 sq. ft. which are sold, leased or refinanced.</p>\n<p>\n	The <a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/ab1103/">legislation</a> for energy benchmarking for CA buildings calls for a mandatory disclosure of energy benchmarking data by buildings within a certain timeframe. This is primarily enforced by <a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/ab1103/documents/ab_1103_bill_20071012_chaptered.pdf">AB 1103</a> – the Commercial Building Benchmarking Law that was signed by the Governor in 2009 and it currently applies to non-residential buildings. This bill is now <a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/2010publications/CEC-400-2010-004/CEC-400-2010-004-SD2.pdf">regulated</a> by the CEC and it mandates that by the end of 2011, CA based Utilities like PG&amp;E are able to provide energy consumption data per request from their customers as a first phase of implementation. The second phase for implementing the same law requires that by 2012, non-residential building owners will have to disclose benchmarking data for the refinancing, sale or lease to the market for an entire building.</p>\n<p>\n	The timeframes for implementing benchmarking criteria (as defined in AB 1103) are separately established by <a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/ab1103/documents/2011-09-12_workshop/2011-09-12_Assembly_Bill_531.pdf">AB 531</a> which provides for the CEC to establish the <a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/2010publications/CEC-400-2010-004/CEC-400-2010-004-SD2.pdf">schedule</a> to implement AB 1103 through a CA non-residential building energy use disclosure program.</p>\n<p>\n	Accordingly the requirement for implementing AB 1103 is that by 2012 buildings with 50,000 square feet area should disclose their energy benchmarking data; that by Jan 2013 buildings with areas between 10,000 and 50,000 square feet should disclose their benchmark data, and that finally by July 2013 buildings with areas between 5,000 to 10,000 square feet should disclose their energy benchmark data. AB 1103 also mandates that buildings that are eligible to receive Energy Star scores from 1 – 100 must also disclose their final scores to the market.</p>\n<p>\n	The energy benchmarking process is itself carried out by following <a href="http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?c=evaluate_performance.bus_portfoliomanager_benchmarking">certain steps</a> as outlined by the Portfolio Manager. The energy performance rating resulting from this process utilizes certain building variables affecting energy consumption like Building Size, Space Type, Weather, Hours of Operation, Occupancy and Plug Load. Once a building has its energy benchmarking data, it also sets itself up for periodic energy audits to measure changes in energy consumption patterns over periods of time.</p>\n<p>\n	Utilities like PG&amp;E now provide Automated Benchmarking Service (ABS) for their customers which create Portfolio Manager Accounts for users and allow them to view energy consumption data and benchmarking results online. Similarly the City of San Francisco is also active in disseminating information about energy benchmarking strategies that it plans to carry out through <a href="http://www.sfenvironment.org/downloads/library/ECBWebinarFlyerAug30.pdf">webinars</a> in collaboration with Utilities like PG&amp;E, as well as by establishing detailed <a href="http://www.hansonbridgett.com/~/media/Files/Publications/San%20Franciscos%20Energy%20Performance%20OrdinanceSpotlighting%20Commercial%20Building%20Energy%20Use.ashx">ordinances</a> that describe the practicalities of dealing with benchmarking data from commercial buildings in San Francisco. The city’s goal is to reduce energy consumption by 50% over the next 20 years by identifying potential savings, engaging tenants, and leading by example in public facilities.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, '');
