(1359, 'default', 39, 'By <author class="name">Cheryl Weiden</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Content Creator</author>\n<p>\n	Feb 3rd 2012</p>\n<p>\n	Water and energy, both necessary for life, are linked. Large amounts of water are needed for electricity generation; for example in the process of generating electricity from coal, water is used for extraction, processing, fuel conversion and cooling. Similarly a large amount of electricity is needed for extraction, treatment, and distribution of water. Up to now water and energy issues have been considered independently, but the increasing scarcity and cost of each will demand that they be considered together.</p>\n<p>\n	A <a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/npdZjvbyYBn2jLi0hJNj0o3-ZW-mwzNuohFn120GFRiQuKhjjv8vKi3t33o*xt5UcdJqI3J3asjH0WCxPGaRrmPSIUt0EViP/feature3.pdf" target="_self">study</a> found that water requirements for electricity generation vary greatly depending on the primary energy source and the conversion and cooling technologies used. The biggest users are bioenergy from dedicated energy crops, hydroelectric facilities and thermoelectric facilities using once through cooling. Waste based facilities, solar photovoltaic, wind turbines and thermoelectric facilities using dry cooling use the least water.</p>\n<p>\n	Major water efficiencies can be achieved using technologies that target water efficiencies. Dry cooling and coal gasification can decrease California’s projected 2020 scenario for annual freshwater withdrawal and consumption by 66%; and by adding more water efficient technologies such as solar photovoltaic, wind and waste based bioenergy a 90% reduction is projected.</p>\n<p>\n	The study concluded:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Water efficient electricity generation requires the right mix of primary energy sources, conversion technologies and cooling technologies. Utilities must plan to invest in such water efficient technologies as wind, solar photovoltaic and coal gasification.</li>\n	<li>\n		Policies that encourage water conservation can make a big impact. Such polices may include:</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	- Issuing conservation credits to power utilities that implement programs to reduce water use.</p>\n<p>\n	- Co-locating water treatment plants and power plants to facilitate the use of reclaimed water.</p>\n<p>\n	Further study is needed on the full life cycle of electricity generation including the construction of the power plant to understand the full water requirements of electricity generation.</p>\n<p>\n	Issues to be considered in the integration of water and electricity planning include:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		The transition to more water efficient means of electricity generation must be accomplished in a manner that will not compromise energy reliability.</li>\n	<li>\n		In addition to the impacts of water on electricity generation, planning must include other environmental impacts such as habitat, ecosystems and biodiversity.</li>\n	<li>\n		Impacts on water resources may be regional as seen in the bioenergy sector. For example some areas that have plenty of water may be more viable for production of dedicated energy crops.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Source: “<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/1izA7qarrQc15KDtMR666LdaLrjOF3FsHIsjrqz9ICSAnnAKH4-5yOvZjay8ayT1-t8Kv12GBEFDswqcjKpp7f9t5J08q0Fp/feature3.pdf" target="_self">California’s Energy-Water Nexus: Water Use in Electricity Generation</a>”</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1360, 'default', 50, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><strong>California to get 33% of energy from Renewable Resources by 2020</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	<strong><i>New SBX 1 2 Energy Bill introduced</i></strong></p>\n<p>\n	Governor Jerry Brown of California on Tuesday 04/12/2011 signed SBX 1 2, a historic legislation which requires one third or 33% of California’s electricity to come from renewable resources like solar, wind and geothermal by December 31st 2020. This is the highest target of renewable energy utilization for generating electricity that has been set for any state in the U.S. today.</p>\n<p>\n	SBX 1 2 increases California’s previous target as specified in bill AB32 of achieving 20% of its electricity from renewable resources to a new target of 33% by 2020. Governor Brown in his signing message said that this new bill would help stimulate investments in green technologies in California, creating new jobs, improving local air quality, promoting energy independence and reducing green-house gas emissions.</p>\n<p>\n	The SBX 1 2 bill requires that the amount of electricity generated per year from eligible renewable energy resources be increased to an amount that equals at least 20% of the total electricity sold to retail customers in California per year by December 31, 2013, and 33% by December 31, 2020.</p>\n<p>\n	At the same time, the bill requires that the PUC, by January 1, 2012, establishes the quantity of electricity products from eligible renewable energy resources to be procured by each retail seller for specified compliance periods, sufficient to ensure that the procurement of electricity products from eligible renewable resources achieves 25% of sales by December 31, 2016, and 33% of retail sales by December 31st 2020, and that retail sellers procure not less than 33% of retail sales in all subsequent years.</p>\n<p>\n	This means that the biggest retail sellers of California - Pacific Gas and Electric Company, San Diego Gas and Electric, and Southern California Edison, would have to begin procuring electricity from eligible renewable energy producers in the manner, quantities and timelines as required by this law.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	The passing of this bill sets California on an aggressive target of increasing its reliance on renewable energy resources and this is bound to have a positive cascading effect on green technologies and environment sustainability in the coming years in the state.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1363, 'default', 51, '<p>\n	By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead and Cary Chen, EcoCloud Energy Content Developer</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="color: #000080;"><strong><span class="font-size-4">Energy Tools Evaluation Report</span></strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	<span style="color: #808080;"><strong>Feb 18th 2012&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	This section summarizes the evaluation of various Energy tools which are used today to manage energy demand, control energy cost and consumption, improve energy reliability and minimize environmental impacts.</p>\n<p>\n	Our methodology categorizes the energy tools in two categories:</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>By Audience</strong></p>\n<p>\n	The basis of our categorization of energy tools by audience is the users of various energy performance metrics as defined by the <a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/buildings/commercial_initiative/performance_metrics_tiers.html">Commercial Building Initiative</a> run by the Office of Energy Efficiency &amp; Renewable Energy (EERE) and by the <a href="http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/buildings/tools_directory/">Building Energy Software Tools Directory</a>of the Department of Energy (DOE).</p>\n<table border="2" cellspacing="0" id="my_table1" style="width: 291px; height: 246px;" width="337">\n	<colgroup>\n		<col width="223" />\n	</colgroup>\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl65" height="19" style="text-align: left;" width="223">\n				<span class="font-size-4" style="color: #000080;"><strong>Tools - By&nbsp;Audience</strong></span></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/MJPE62FEMzkTUXujuOtxQ-0LoDDFHyieg68g3G5lIKPrT-G7Ee*YfVphwWCDqpP*S-ryNcPAtFBf1eN*etZYv8SMJL5k5Jjx/EnergyToolsByAudienceArchitectsBuilders02182012.pdf" target="_self">Architects and Builders</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/z-9oJyVpAMxM3OvHgBc7LXg1tOAOG8uL3lZZmwV6F1243hnezHt4O0YxH215hBExEh8ENRYjUKjbrJVV8t1D7tfDF3xtSHuo/EnergyToolsByAudienceAuditors02182012.pdf" target="_self">Auditors</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/1DMazCIX9zLjVig7WLHfOBkJEPWIylo94fHo7ueJ6F6yr1*BWWUf-3aJgE-cjDbsT9f3KPuqVO4hjiXnC9KgQiGfDXyI7vUi/EnergyToolsByAudienceCorporations02182012.pdf" target="_self">Corporations</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/z-9oJyVpAMz2ItsxVgcLXP3k-OsTWmhbqobi5uGIDJsbEzRMQ4f6K3*DpSeUOstjaCNkBv6XSDot7EjKro34OuU*CUBpaJXd/EnergyToolsByAudienceEngineersandEnergyProfessionals02182012.pdf" target="_self">Engineers and Energy Professionals</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/3bDhQZLbS5RZpYnmCq2iPQAdtt*rVx*VEwHuCXClEvpMMunaWAIF-fq03xq3HaXs5CWFzqxV3SPACOer-noVPCh75qdJA2lI/EnergyToolsByAudienceFacilityManagers02182012.pdf" target="_self">Facility Managers</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/YV8Q6Js1C61FMiSHx1PNQMhhKNg2C1kf46MDh1dZC6X*qTpAZC75C4MB79esKaIa1747jFa2RhPqmc7abvWW6ZBacHCo0po7/EnergyToolsByAudienceBuildingandResidentialHomeOwners02182012.pdf" target="_self">Building and Residential Owners</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/YV8Q6Js1C60vlUn-XegyW4ET6sc36aZ8bnGMX*OJ2llDrib5H3qGDQUy2iMzjUF7ROSxQTX4fxjsEf219oVq7JGsMgPfcrc0/EnergyToolsByAudienceResearchersandStudents02182012.pdf" target="_self">Researchers and Students</a></td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n			<td class="xl66" height="19" style="text-align: left;">\n				<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/8W0tjY-8qtJg5oit2yP04ExOxAI1y9Z5yPzmT-OoUxHIug4SNakgnFGzHfvDvRzYSPUx