(1364, 'default', 54, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<h3 class="Standard">\n	<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><strong><span class="font-size-4"><strong><span>Solar Technology&nbsp;Innovations and Highlights</span></strong></span></strong></span></h3>\n<h4 class="Standard">\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>Solar Power Assets&nbsp;- Building The Solar</b></span><span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b> Highway to Energy Independence</b></span></h4>\n<p class="Standard">\n	<span class="font-size-1" style="color: rgb(128, 128, 128);"><strong>Posted April 17, 2011 by Anuradha Munshi</strong></span></p>\n<p class="Standard" style="text-align: left;">\n	<em><a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/8z0jZEFVwDvwEmV7XukV8XkCwAmnUzHQujfUqab--Bd3LKLDZ6fmzfcLQFJydIayNcHnlhKIW8-nKU-oJAXjBCDUGRwgjIVA/hpp1.png" target="_self"><img class="align-left" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/8z0jZEFVwDvwEmV7XukV8XkCwAmnUzHQujfUqab--Bd3LKLDZ6fmzfcLQFJydIayNcHnlhKIW8-nKU-oJAXjBCDUGRwgjIVA/hpp1.png" width="216" /></a><strong>Solar Power Assets (SPA) is planning to deploy rapid, massive, low-cost and innovative Solar Electricity generating facilities in order to create Solar Highways, Solar Rivers and Solar Farms.</strong></em></p>\n<p class="Standard" style="text-align: left;">\n	SPA will generate low cost solar energy by sequentially stringing and deploying highly efficient solar PV modules along public roadways and waterways. It will focus on lowering solar generation and installation costs by eliminating energy transmission losses and by providing automated installation and deployment methods to drive overall solar costs down to $2Wp.</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	SPA will utilize vast corridors including rights of way that are already available for solar energy generation and transmission (e.g. on highways, aqueducts), creating what it calls “Solar Rivers”, “Solar Highways” and “Solar Farms”. Energy transmission losses will be reduced with the help of an innovative proprietary power transmission backbone, the Cumulative Transmission Line (CTL).</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/K-XUvcAylbfPVIPjjYsLbVxeV9uQkb1hk9ernwIRyjmEheB*h*W1bPG5-kqXRoXbF0gKv*xdOWssQ2aq-Rc20Jq3*1CFKPXG/hpp2.png" target="_self"><img class="align-left" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/K-XUvcAylbfPVIPjjYsLbVxeV9uQkb1hk9ernwIRyjmEheB*h*W1bPG5-kqXRoXbF0gKv*xdOWssQ2aq-Rc20Jq3*1CFKPXG/hpp2.png" width="258" /></a>SPA wants to start its mission with California by collaborating with key departments in California State Government. Over 55,000 miles of California''s Roadways can be utilized to generate up to 6GW of solar power, while over 2600 miles of waterways in CA can generate 7GW of solar energy. SPA believes that by focusing on lowering installation costs, it will introduce faster time to energy generation, eliminate high power transmission lines and ultimately drive down solar electricity power generation costs to match or beat fossil fuel electricity cost within three years.</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	<strong>About Solar Power Assets</strong></p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	Solar Power Assets, LLC is a self-funded startup incorporated in June 2007 focused on providing sound energy alternatives that are lower in cost and reduce dependency on conventional energy sources.</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div style="background: rgb(208, 208, 208); margin-top: 10px;">\n	<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;">\n		<strong>Other Recent Topics:</strong></div>\n	<div style="margin: 0px 5px 4px 4px; float: left;">\n		<img align="left" class="align" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/RHlZFMTJmWcr90IuVNrWLpKF1CFISm3hFR5wW4bZr71LW2ymDKn*q34-m7kC3WwF9x4GnX0uaTXDFLCnenIlh-3hvGUe-yPl/PVmodulesShipments2009.jpg" width="190" /></div>\n	<div>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/topics/energy/trends/solar-pv-industry-2009">U.S. photovoltaic (PV) industry hits a record high in 2009</a> According to a US-EIA report released in Jan 2011, the PV industry shipped nearly 1.3 peak gigawatts of cells and modules, representing a 30 percent year to year growth from the previous<a href="/page/solar-pv-industry" style="text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt;</a></div>\n	<div style="clear: both;">\n		&nbsp;</div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1365, 'default', 55, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-6" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><strong>Wind Power Growth</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/LvRj9FrP3mc6Er*DiNTc*BfNNAyy*5yPKpyteSU*8PZSR*FIFPP7Yw09e34231QNZf*n76AZlaoi5DQWgsWe4eQpdJGeWa8X/WindGenerationVsCapacity.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align align-center" height="283" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/LvRj9FrP3mc6Er*DiNTc*BfNNAyy*5yPKpyteSU*8PZSR*FIFPP7Yw09e34231QNZf*n76AZlaoi5DQWgsWe4eQpdJGeWa8X/WindGenerationVsCapacity.jpg" width="415" /></a></p>\n<p>\n	As shown in the diagram above, Wind power in the U.S. has been the fastest growing renewable source of generating electric power for several years now. This has been possible due to incentives like wind generators being eligible for Federal production and investment tax credits. The passage of the 2005 Energy Policy Act (EPACT2005) has allowed interest-free financing via Clean Renewable Energy Bonds (CREBs) to be available to government entities investing in wind energy. The 2002 and 2008 Farm Bills (Section 9006, under Title IX) also contain various provisions for grant and loan guarantee for wind projects to farmers, ranchers, and other rural businesses.</p>\n<p>\n	Such federal incentives for wind energy have been meaningful and timely, and the numbers speak for themselves. In 2009, generation from wind power increased 33.5 percent over 2008, bringing the share of total generation to 1.9 percent. This followed year-over-year generation gains of 49.3 percent in 2006, 29.6 percent in 2007, and 60.7 percent in 2008. Wind capacity in 2009 totaled 34,296 megawatts (MW), as compared to 24,651 MW in 2008. Clearly there are lots of opportunities for growth and investment in this area.</p>\n<div>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<div style="background: rgb(208, 208, 208); margin-top: 10px;">\n	<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;">\n		<strong>Other Recent Topics:</strong></div>\n	<div style="margin: 0px 5px 4px 4px; float: left;">\n		<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/Bgfb5y4m2h2A9W1hN23GTN5Oa1PqkK24MFE*dGs3Gt7qqPHadWLQNTqaw*kJyDV0VqYEvFnLkQnmaUucBe7uRMmOzugWS9In/WindTurbinePic1.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-left" height="162" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/Bgfb5y4m2h2A9W1hN23GTN5Oa1PqkK24MFE*dGs3Gt7qqPHadWLQNTqaw*kJyDV0VqYEvFnLkQnmaUucBe7uRMmOzugWS9In/WindTurbinePic1.jpg" width="219" /></a></div>\n	<div>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/topics/energy/trends/wind-energy-trends-in-the-us-and-germany"><span class="font-size-4">Wind Energy Trends in the U.S. and Germany - A Comparison of Key Elements</span>.</a>&nbsp; Germany is often called the wind energy kingdom; the country’s wind energy industry is one of the largest worldwide. In 2007 Germany was the largest wind power generator in the world and currently it stands at the number three position, exceeded by China and the U.S. But what exactly is the driving force behind its success? What is so different about Germany’s wind energy industry compared to the US?<a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/page/wind-energy-trends-in-the-us-and-germany" style="text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt;</a></div>\n	<div style="clear: both;">\n		&nbsp;</div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1366, 'default', 58, '<p>\n	<author class="name">By Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author></p>\n<h3>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>Solar Industry – Dealing with Toxic Wastes</b></span></h3>\n<p class="Standard">\n	As solar energy rapidly emerges and proliferates into the fabric of our society, little thought is being given to the environmental impacts of producing and eventually recycling solar PV panels. Disturbing global trends seem to be emerging; in 2008 it was reported that a Chinese solar plant was regularly dumping extremely toxic Silicon Tetrachloride on a nearby farmland.</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	Today, competition and time to market drive many companies involved in this nascent but very highly promising area of Solar energy. As a result, the solar PV industry is rapidly evolving new materials and processes to increase cell efficiency and reduce production costs. Unfortunately many of these technologies and processes use toxic, explosive, corrosive or potentially carcinogenic materials like Cadmium and Selenium, while other products use materials that have not been completely tested.</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	Over the years, academia and industry have researched new materials and processes for generating electricity based off solar. While progress is made at increasing the rate of efficiency of utilization of solar energy, the same is not always true when considering mitigation of environmental impacts of these materials and processes.</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/kZQbTWHrz7P4O3wmRlvqS1M*knN5DyepXxDt-oZeTMOgC8J1Re9RSkN-MdDAy6wBF2TkiZHXTj8HLwhs-c9GP9Gm5qI4Tggf/solarcellefficiencies.png" target="_self"><img class="align-center" height="331" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/kZQbTWHrz7P4O3wmRlvqS1M*knN5DyepXxDt-oZeTMOgC8J1Re9RSkN-MdDAy6wBF2TkiZHXTj8HLwhs-c9GP9Gm5qI4Tggf/solarcellefficiencies.png?width=750" width="560" /></a></p>\n<p class="Standard" style="text-align: center;">\n	Best Research–Cell Efficiencies - courtesy of National Renewable Energy Laboratory</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	Emerging thin-film and nanotechnology-based cells are known to pose health and environment dangers. For example the process of sawing c-Si wafers creates a significant amount of waste silicon dust called Kerf that could cause respiratory problems to workers while polluting air and water. Similarly the use of Silane gas is known to be explosive and the industry reports several accidents per year. Silicon Tetrachloride and Sulphur Hexafluoride are two other very toxic and potent chemicals used in Solar PV production that can be very hazardous, going so far as to create acid rains at worst. At the other end of the spectrum the question of dealing with recycling of these toxic solar PV panels as they end their life cycle in 20-25 years is left largely unanswered.</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	Silicon Valley Toxics Coalition (SVTC) a 25 year veteran organization believes that the following measures and policies will help in effectively turning this trend:</p>\n<ol>\n	<li>\n		<div>\n			Research, reduce and eliminate use of toxic materials during production – In particular, usage of the following toxic materials should be phased out and discouraged - cadmium, lead, mercury, brominated flame retardants, chromium, along with Sulphur Hexafluoride, Hydrogen selenide, arsenic and phosphine.</div>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<div>\n			Extended Producer Responsibility – Ensure that Solar PV manufacturers are responsible for lifetime impacts of their products. This includes sharing responsibility for safely recycling the solar PV panels that companies produce once these panels reach end of life.</div>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<div>\n			Ensure proper testing of new and emerging materials and processes and take a precautionary approach. For example, standards that measure environmental impacts need to be deployed as part of the production and test release cycle.</div>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<div>\n			Expand the recycling technology and design products for easy recycling – Companies need to look at safer ways of recycling solar panels, especially those that already have toxic substances, to minimize polluting the environment.</div>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<div>\n			Create green jobs that protect worker health and safety and protect community health and safety.</div>\n	</li>\n</ol>\n<p class="Standard">\n	Reference:</p>\n<p class="Standard">\n	A Silicon Valley Toxic Coalition White Paper <i>– Towards a Just and Sustainable Solar Energy Industry, 2009 </i></p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1369, 'default', 12, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	One of nature''s principles of sustainability is to rely mostly on renewable energy. We can get renewable solar energy directly from the sun or indirectly from moving water, wind and biomass. Other forms of renewable energy are geothermal and tidal.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div style="margin-bottom: 5px;">\n	<strong>Recent Articles:</strong></div>\n<div style="background: rgb(208, 208, 208); margin-top: 10px;">\n	<div style="margin: 0px 5px 4px 4px; float: left; padding: 5px">\n		<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/Bgfb5y4m2h2A9W1hN23GTN5Oa1PqkK24MFE*dGs3Gt7qqPHadWLQNTqaw*kJyDV0VqYEvFnLkQnmaUucBe7uRMmOzugWS9In/WindTurbinePic1.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-left" height="162" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/Bgfb5y4m2h2A9W1hN23GTN5Oa1PqkK24MFE*dGs3Gt7qqPHadWLQNTqaw*kJyDV0VqYEvFnLkQnmaUucBe7uRMmOzugWS9In/WindTurbinePic1.jpg" width="219" /></a></div>\n	<div>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/topics/energy/trends/wind-energy-trends-in-the-us-and-germany"><span class="font-size-4">Wind Energy Trends in the U.S. and Germany - A Comparison of Key Elements</span>.</a> Germany is often called the wind energy kingdom; the country’s wind energy industry is one of the largest worldwide. In 2007 Germany was the largest wind power generator in the world and currently it stands at the number three position, exceeded by China and the U.S. But what exactly is the driving force behind its success? What is so different about Germany’s wind energy industry compared to the US?<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/topics/energy/trends/wind-energy-trends-in-the-us-and-germany" style="text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt;</a></div>\n	<div style="clear:both">\n		&nbsp;</div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<div style="background: rgb(208, 208, 208); margin-top: 10px;">\n	<div style="margin: 0px 5px 4px 4px; float: left; padding: 5px">\n		<img align="left" class="align" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/RHlZFMTJmWcr90IuVNrWLpKF1CFISm3hFR5wW4bZr71LW2ymDKn*q34-m7kC3WwF9x4GnX0uaTXDFLCnenIlh-3hvGUe-yPl/PVmodulesShipments2009.jpg" width="190" /></div>\n	<div>\n		<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/topics/energy/trends/solar-pv-industry-2009">U.S. photovoltaic (PV) industry hits a record high in 2009</a> According to a US-EIA report released in Jan 2011, the PV industry shipped nearly 1.3 peak gigawatts of cells and modules, representing a 30 percent year to year growth from the previous<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/topics/energy/trends/solar-pv-industry-2009" style="text-decoration: none;">&gt;&gt;</a></div>\n	<div style="clear:both">\n		&nbsp;</div>\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1370, 'default', 53, 'By <author class="name">Anuradha Munshi</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Energy Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span class="font-size-4" style="color: rgb(0, 51, 102);"><b>Clean Energy Strategy Part of Santa Clara University’s Business Continuity Plan - Phase One of Smart Microgrid Project Complete&nbsp;</b></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	In 2006 Santa Clara University (SCU) conducted an energy strategy study as part of the university’s business continuity plan and its aim to become carbon-neutral by 2016.</p>\n<p>\n	“We looked at the next 20 years and what we needed to accomplish to ensure we had energy reliability,” said Joe Sugg, Assistant Vice President, University Operations at SCU. The university needed guaranteed energy reliability, some influence over the cost of energy, a move to green energy, and (to develop) the capability to operate with the grid down for extended periods of time.</p>\n<div style="margin: 4px; width: 33%; float: right;">\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSf6QtTUKGrLb3cCd5YyHErYQPkie3ewZCZUi3-mlQZIFvh**wPbhe7Ds1y2q06UGjnjouY6NkrNKVDPVoHFEyi-/8603_cut1.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-full" height="400" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSf6QtTUKGrLb3cCd5YyHErYQPkie3ewZCZUi3-mlQZIFvh**wPbhe7Ds1y2q06UGjnjouY6NkrNKVDPVoHFEyi-/8603_cut1.jpg" width="200" /></a><br/><em><span style="font-size: 12px;">Joe Sugg, Assistant VP Operations SCU with SSV Executive Director Marianna Grossman testing a new prototype wind generator</span></em></div>\n<p>\n	“We knew we would need distributed generation capability on campus and a way to control our demand on campus and when our distributed energy was used. We also needed to be able to maintain continuity with the grid when it was up so we could take advantage of it.”</p>\n<p>\n	A smart microgrid became the necessary infrastructure to make it possible. A smart box will instantaneously sense any drop in supply, such as when cloud cover affects solar generation, and react accordingly by automatically reducing demand to match available generation.</p>\n<p>\n	In 2010 - the first phase of the project, SCU installed sub-meters into 14 buildings and integrated the smart microgrid’s onsite alternative energy sources, including solar. Phase 2 will connect the entire campus to the campus microgrid, and is expected to be completed ahead of schedule in December 2011.</p>\n<p>\n	SCU is currently producing 1 Megawatt (MW) from solar, 2 MW from diesel as standby energy, and generating biogas using garden waste. The university is also testing a new wind generator sited on the same roof as the university’s bank of solar panels and is in a product queue for a Bloom fuel cell that will generate an additional 1 MW.</p>\n<p>\n	According to Joe Sugg, the wind generator operates efficiently at low wind speeds; starting production at 2 mph. Energy from the generator currently is fed into a battery that is used to charge the university’s electric vehicles, and is not part of the microgrid.</p>\n<div style="margin: 4px; width: 33%; float: right;">\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSeMzwSmyu8zIA5ypizrtSBq55sSkiiKdPyCUkaY2xRXLQYC7keMqCb6q3sJJWM9cA7E7-YURRIABd3hrMAWOsbM/IMG_8678.jpg" target="_self"><img class="align-left" height="213" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/mlko*j5vwSeMzwSmyu8zIA5ypizrtSBq55sSkiiKdPyCUkaY2xRXLQYC7keMqCb6q3sJJWM9cA7E7-YURRIABd3hrMAWOsbM/IMG_8678.jpg?width=750" style="width: 277px; height: 163px;" width="330" /></a><em><span style="font-size: 12px;">Monitoring the system and reviewing energy savings</span></em></div>\n<p>\n	While SCU expects to see savings of around 20% from on-campus energy generation and from reduced consumption, the real benefits are energy and cost reliability, simplified building management, and reduced CO<sub>2</sub>.</p>\n<p>\n	“We know the cost of solar electricity for the next 20 years, and we like the price,” said Joe Sugg.&nbsp;Distributed energy is not only the answer to SCU’s energy needs, but for the region overall, he says.</p>\n<p>\n	“I imagine our microgrid as one among hundreds. Our 3 MW generation capacity in combination with other smart microgrids becomes a powerful force in the Valley. “Silicon Valley Power” will be able to produce significant energy and carbon load savings.”</p>\n<p>\n	In 20-30 years from now, says Sugg, Long haul transmission of power from Nevada to California will be prohibitive. “It will not be an option.“</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div style="padding: 4px; border: 1px solid rgb(204, 204, 204); margin-right: 10px; margin-left: 10px;">\n	<p>\n		SCU’s current system allows it to control HVAC systems and temperatures. A Trane environmental control system in conjunction with an Energy Management System from Serious Energy, processes server information to automatically monitor and adjust the optimum server room temperature. As a result SCU’s server room now operates at 85 degrees compared with 65 degrees previously.</p>\n	<p>\n		The smart microgrid, when complete, will encompass the entire campus and enable the university to instantly turn off lights and equipment in any building, ration electricity during prolonged power outages all from one computer.</p>\n	<p>\n		SCU is collaborating with Sustainable Silicon Valley and SSV partners - Cisco and Serious Energy.</p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1379, 'default', 36, 'By <author class="name">Mary Kean</author><author class="title">, EcoCloud Water Lead</author>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	California’s water supply chain, or the route water follows as it is pumped and/or conveyed from its source, treated to drinking water standards, distributed, used, and treated to wastewater standards, is energy intensive. More specifically, water-related energy consumption in the state represents approximately 15%-20% of all energy consumed in California. For example, the State Water Project alone, a 444-mile long aqueduct transporting San Francisco Bay-San Joaquin Delta water to Southern California, consumes 2%-3% of all electricity in the state because of the high elevations and long distances over which water must be pumped and conveyed. Thus, a reduction in flow through the water supply chain brought about by an alternative water supply source/demand management tool such as water conservation or water recycling will decrease energy use.</p>\n<p>\n	See EcoCloud’s review of <a href="http://ecocloud-sv.com/topics/water/tools-metrics-reporting">tools</a>&nbsp;including water/energy for more info.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/gODaOqhwx3YYIE9JRHDq1qCPsdBZ0UDdrSviX7av4g11KbrtByLHOKFM5fOZ4RXEfdq0v193z0jcwryXOJPmARFXR3MnYz67/energywater.png" target="_self"><img class="align-left" height="240" src="http://api.ning.com:80/files/gODaOqhwx3YYIE9JRHDq1qCPsdBZ0UDdrSviX7av4g11KbrtByLHOKFM5fOZ4RXEfdq0v193z0jcwryXOJPmARFXR3MnYz67/energywater.png" width="197" /></a></p>\n<p>\n	For more information on the Water/Energy Nexus, visit:</p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://cwee.ucdavis.edu/">UC Davis Center for Water Energy Efficiency</a><br />\n	<a href="http://www.cal-wec.org/">Cal-Wec</a> – CA Water Energy Coalition<br />\n	<a href="http://www.theclimatechangeclearinghouse.org/">The Climate Change Clearinghouse</a><br />\n	<a href="http://www.energy.ca.gov/2005publications/CEC-700-2005-011/CEC-700-2005-011-SF.PDF">CEC 2005- Calfornia''s Water Energy Relationship</a><br />\n	<a href="http://www.ncsl.org/?tabid=18025">NCSL - Summary of Water/Energy Nexus Statutes</a><br />\n	<a href="http://www.physorg.com/news188151770.html">Researchers to test renewable-energy system at local treatment plant</a> <br />\n	<a href="http://collab.waterrf.org/Workshops/WaterEnergySustainabilitySummit/Northern%20California%20Workshop%20Presentations/Forms/AllItems.aspx">Northern California Water/Energy Summit Presentations</a><br />\n	<a href="http://collab.waterrf.org/Workshops/WaterEnergySustainabilitySummit/WaterEnergy%20Wiki%20Search/Forms/AllPages.aspx">Water/Energy Issues Wiki</a><br />\n	<a href="http://ntlm.waterrf.org/search/allresults.aspx?k=energy">Link to WaterRF energy projects</a><br />\n	<a href="https://www.whollyh2o.org/water-energy-nexus.html">https://www.whollyh2o.org/water-energy-nexus.html</a><br />\n	<br />\n	<br />\n	<a href="http://www.valleywater.org/">Watts to Water Report</a> by Santa Clara Valley Water District</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default');
