(1486, 'default', 125, '<p align="center">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p align="center">\n	<strong style="font-size: 18px; ">EBAY Sustainability Review</strong></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Introduction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	eBay is the world’s largest online marketplace (more than 100 million active users in 2011), connecting individual buyers and sellers, as well as small businesses. eBay had 27,770 employees end of 2011, including 18,720 in the USA, and facilities in 30 countries. eBay does not publish a sustainability report.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Awards, frameworks and accomplishments</span></h2>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size: 14px; ">Sustainability Awards:</span></h2>\n<p>\n	<em>National:</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2010: <a href="http://www.justmeans.com/2010-Social-Innovation-Awards-Justmeans-FT/11613.html">Social Innovator Award</a> for Best Employee Engagement Strategy, given by Just Means and The Financial Times</li>\n	<li>\n		2010: <a href="http://www.globalgreen.org/press/167">Sustainable Design Award</a> for the organizational design of the Green Team initiatives, given by Global Green USA</li>\n	<li>\n		2012: eBay and Dell have been selected to win a Green Enterprise IT award by <a href="http://uptimeinstitute.com/">Uptime Institute</a>, a global organization that provides thought leadership, certification, education and professional services for the global data center industry</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<em>Local:</em></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012: Modular Data Center Product Deployment award received jointly&nbsp; for Project Mercury data center in Phoenix, AZ</li>\n	<li>\n		The WPR team in San Jose recently received a BOMA (Building Owners and Managers Association) <a href="http://www.boma-sv.org/events/emerald-awards.html">Emerald Award</a> for Single Tenant Recycling as a result of the Zero Waste Program</li>\n	<li>\n		Bronze level for a bike-friendly business given by the League of American Bicyclists to the Omaha office, making it one of the first companies in Nebraska to receive this designation</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Listings/Index</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Calvert Social Index</li>\n	<li>\n		FTSE4Good</li>\n	<li>\n		Domini400</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Rankings</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked 104 in 2011 Newsweek’s Green Ranking of US companies (among first 100 in 2009)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Frameworks</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2011 Carbon Disclosure Leadership Index: 63/100; Performance: C</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"> INSERT INTO `page_chunks` (`id`, `slug`, `page_id`, `body`, `parsed`, `type`, `sort`, `class`) VALUES
(1499, 'default', 133, '<p align="center">\n	<strong style="font-size: 18px; ">Stonyfield Sustainability Review</strong></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Introduction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	Stonyfield is a company that produces organic yogurt, smoothies, ice cream and milk. The Company focuses on implementing the best practices to develop an organic, sustainable and environmentally friendly business. Stonyfield started as a little farming school in 1983 that taught sustainable agricultural practices. By 1987 Stonyfield began building their plant and since then the Company has been recognized for their sustainable, eco-friendly achievements. Their Yogurt Works office is located in Londonderry, New Hampshire, and the company has about 500 employees.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Institute of Packaging Professionals AmeriStar Award, 2011— Plant-based PLA Form-Fill-Seal Plastic Multipack Yogurt Cup</li>\n	<li>\n		Nutrition Business Journal Sustainability Award, 2010</li>\n	<li>\n		Responsible Packaging Award— For reducing weight and material use for yogurt cups, 2010</li>\n	<li>\n		Edison Awards— Finalist, The Green Award, 2010</li>\n	<li>\n		New Hampshire Business Review— Best Green Business, 2010</li>\n	<li>\n		Environmental Protection Agency’s 2009 SmartWay Excellence Award</li>\n	<li>\n		Treehugger.com Best of Green— Best Practices by a Big Food Brand 2009</li>\n	<li>\n		EPA Clean Air Excellence Award 2009</li>\n	<li>\n		NH Business Review— Best Environmentally Friendly Business 2009</li>\n	<li>\n		NEEP Northeast Energy Efficiency Partnership’s Business Leader award 2008</li>\n	<li>\n		NH Division of Economic Development Business Resource Center</li>\n	<li>\n		“Innovation Rocks!” Award Winner, Recycling Program, 2008</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Working Mother</em> magazine’s Best Green Companies for America’s Children, 2008</li>\n	<li>\n		National Wildlife Federation’s National Conservation Achievement award in Corporate Leadership, 2006</li>\n	<li>\n		EPA and US DOE Green Power Leadership Award, 2006</li>\n	<li>\n		EPA Business, Industry and Professional Organizations Environmental Merit Award, 2006</li>\n	<li>\n		Global Green USA’s Green Cross Millennium Award for Corporate Environmental Leadership, 1999</li>\n	<li>\n		National Award for Sustainability (Atmosphere and Climate) from the President’s Council on Sustainable Development and Renew America, 1999</li>\n	<li>\n		Robert Rodale Environmental Achievement Award, 1998</li>\n	<li>\n		Climate Wise Achievement Award from the Environmental Protection Agency, 1998</li>\n	<li>\n		Corporate Environmental Steward Award from the Council on Economic Priorities, 1990</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Listings/Index</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		First for profit company to register its greenhouse gas emissions with the State of New Hampshire''s voluntary registry in 2003</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Rankings</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Greenbiz.com listing on “Top 10 Greenest Companies,” 2007</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Inc.</em> magazine Green 50 includes Stonyfield CE-Yo Gary Hirshberg, 2006</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainable Activities</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Biodiversity/Site</span></h3>\n<p>\n	Corporate office in Londonderry, NH is built to LEED silver certification standards, but did not receive verification from USGBC</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Built to silver LEED certification standards</li>\n	<li>\n		Oriented towards the south so it stays warm in winter and cool in summer</li>\n	<li>\n		External solar shades on south-facing windows block the hot summer sun</li>\n	<li>\n		Solar collectors preheat cold incoming water</li>\n	<li>\n		Double-glazed windows</li>\n	<li>\n		Energy efficient lighting, timers, daylight sensors, motion sensors</li>\n	<li>\n		HVAC on automatic, digital control, cafeteria has demand-controlled ventilation</li>\n	<li>\n		Energy recovery wheel transfers heat and moisture to incoming or outgoing air depending on time of year</li>\n	<li>\n		Tile is made from post-industrial waste</li>\n	<li>\n		Wood floors were harvested following Forest Stewardship Council Guidelines</li>\n	<li>\n		Recycled bottles, sawdust and bathroom stalls used for desk and table materials</li>\n	<li>\n		Walls painted with non-toxic, low VOC paint</li>\n	<li>\n		Waterless urinals, dual flush toilets</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Water</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Reuse wash water in multiple cycles in plant as part of production process, where it is safe</li>\n	<li>\n		Low-flow water fixtures in office building</li>\n	<li>\n		Porous pavement in parking structures to recharge the ground water</li>\n	<li>\n		Teach employees awareness of conserving water</li>\n	<li>\n		For each cup of yogurt, 17% less wastewater in 2008 than 2007</li>\n	<li>\n		Water: cut overall plant wastewater volume by 5% annually for 10 years</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Energy</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		First manufacturer in the US to offset the carbon impact of its facility energy use</li>\n	<li>\n		Used 19% less energy in 2008 than 2007 and saved half a million dollars</li>\n	<li>\n		Plant-wide energy monitoring system used in order to identify ways to reduce energy use</li>\n	<li>\n		Turning off equipment and lights when not needed, adjusting temperature to the season</li>\n	<li>\n		Efficient motors, high efficiency lighting (fluorescent lights, daylight sensors)</li>\n	<li>\n		Measure energy per unit yogurt produced, emissions from transportation</li>\n	<li>\n		One of New Hampshire''s largest solar electric systems on the roof</li>\n	<li>\n		Solar hot water system that heats water for their plant office before is enters the domestic water heater</li>\n	<li>\n		Anaerobic digester that treats their wastewater and generates biogas to power the digester</li>\n	<li>\n		Has been offsetting carbon emissions for ten years by investing in wind energy, farm methane recovery and reforestation</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Materials</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Switched from #2 plastic to #5 plastic because it is more lightweight and therefore uses less energy to be produced, more is recycled because not all #2 plastic products can be recycled</li>\n	<li>\n		Partnership with Preserve to turn recycled yogurt cups into toothbrushes</li>\n	<li>\n		Can send cups to Stonyfield to be recycled</li>\n	<li>\n		Multipacks are made from 93% plant based PLA plastic, made from corn, 43% less carbon</li>\n	<li>\n		Smoothie bottles are made from HDPE #2 which is made from sugar cane</li>\n	<li>\n		Reduced packaging by 1 million pounds</li>\n	<li>\n		Recycled 91% of building materials by diverting demolition and construction debris</li>\n	<li>\n		Wastewater treatment plant to pretreat wastewater on-site</li>\n	<li>\n		Zero Waste: recycling rate up 24% since 2006; recycling and reuse on average saved $150,000 per year</li>\n	<li>\n		Sustainable Packaging: Reduced packaging by almost 1 million pounds per year and saved $780,000 per year</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Transportation</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Transportation and Distribution: Saved over $7.6 million between 2006 and 2010; reduced CO2 emissions by 46% between 2006 and 2010 while growing the business</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Partnerships around sustainability</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Preserve</li>\n	<li>\n		US National Organic Standards</li>\n	<li>\n		Coulee Region Organic Produce Pool (CROPP) Initiative</li>\n	<li>\n		The Rural Education Center, nonprofit teaching rural and homesteading skills with an emphasis on organic food production</li>\n	<li>\n		Oxfam America</li>\n	<li>\n		Earth Force</li>\n	<li>\n		Union of Concerned Scientists to raise awareness on Global Warming</li>\n	<li>\n		Climate Counts</li>\n	<li>\n		SHFT Los Angeles</li>\n	<li>\n		Reverb</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Governance</span></h2>\n<p>\n	Stonyfield Farm’s Director of Natural Resources and President/CEO have developed specific indicators to indicate the importance of moving the company “up the continuum of sustainability.” Employee engagement was also seen as crucial to support the use of the roadmap for Green Business and indicators developed. Stonyfield chose five mission areas and developed indicators corresponding to them: Employee Well-being, Family Farms and Sustainable Agriculture, Environment, Profitability and Quality.</p>\n<p>\n	Developing Environmental Indicators was challenging and resource intensive but really helped the firm improve its sustainability. The environmental indicators were grouped into four main categories: Resource Use, Pesticides and Toxics, Global Warming, and Acidification.</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<strong><em>Stonyfield’s Mission Action Program (MAP): </em></strong>MAP is a company-wide program developed to engage employees in achieving their environmental mission. MAP was formed in 2006 to address the environmental burdens of the company in nine different areas: Green Chemistry, Milk, Facility Greenhouse Gas Emissions, Sustainable Ingredients, Water, Zero Waste, Transportation and Distribution, Sustainable Packaging and Stonyfield Walking Our Talk (SWOT)</li>\n	<li>\n		Under the MPA process, each team must complete an annual Action Plan that sets long-term and near-term goals, and outlines the steps on how to achieve these goals. The CEO, COO and VP of Natural Resources must approve the Action Plan. To achieve the annual MAP goals, the team members have a portion of their compensation linked to such objectives.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Facility Greenhouse Gas Emissions (the Energy Team): </strong>the team focuses on eliminating GHG from the facility by using renewable sources of power, energy efficiency and sequestration. The group represents the Marketing, Natural Resources, Research and Development, Purchasing, Procurement, Operations and Engineering&nbsp;</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Milk Team:</strong> they develop the best practices to minimize impacts from production and transportation of the milk. The team represents Natural Resources, Purchasing, and Communications</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Sustainable Ingredient Team:</strong> they ensure that the company makes the right decisions in purchasing the ingredients. The team represents the Purchasing, Natural Resources, Supply Chain and Logistics and Quality</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Water Team:</strong> it was officially formed in 2011 and they reduce the overall water consumption while maintaining quality</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Green Chemistry Team:</strong> formed in 2011, the team identifies chemicals that reduce or eliminate human health risks, environmental toxicity and greenhouse gas impacts</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Transportation and Distribution Team:</strong> the team develops the best practices to minimize emissions from the transportation of finished products</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Zero Waste Team:</strong> this team eliminates waste and maximizes recovery of materials. The group represents the Engineering, Natural Resources, Shipping, Warehouse, Quality, Supply Chain and Material Handling</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Sustainable Packaging Team:</strong> this team creates the most environmentally sustainable product packaging possible</li>\n			<li>\n				<strong>Stonyfield Walking Our Talk Team (SWOT):</strong> SWOT conducts all of the events, activities and purchases that are consistent with the company’s mission and values</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Under MAP, each team has specific goals that will help achieve Stonyfield’s mission areas. Such goals are as followed:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Align with the International Panel on Climate Change’s recommendation to globally reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 80% from 2000 levels by 2050</li>\n			<li>\n				Cut overall plant wastewater volume by 5% annually for 10 years</li>\n			<li>\n				To have zero waste by 2017 (no waste going to a landfill or incinerator)</li>\n			<li>\n				To achieve 100% sustainable packaging by 2015</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Challenges and Future Goals INSERT INTO `page_chunks` (`id`, `slug`, `page_id`, `body`, `parsed`, `type`, `sort`, `class`) VALUES
(1507, 'default', 136, '<p align="center">\n	<strong><span style="font-size:18px;">Patagonia Sustainability Review</span></strong></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<strong style="font-size: 16px; ">November 2012</strong></p>\n<h1>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Introduction</span></h1>\n<p>\n	Patagonia, Inc. is a Ventura, California based clothing company, focusing mainly on high end outdoor clothing such as Alpine Climbing, Fly Fishing, Rock Climbing, Skiing, Surfing, Trail Running and Snowboarding. It was founded by Yvon Chouinards in 1972 in Ventura, California. It is a privately held retail company with retail stores in the USA and abroad and employing around 1,500 people. Patagonia’s founder is a green-living pioneer and his company’s strategy includes being one of the greenest/cleanest and environmentally savvy companies.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012</span></h2>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards</span></h2>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Lifetime Achievement Award for leading sustainable businesses: The Sustainable Business Council</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010: "Gear of the Year" awards for its use of lightweight and recycled materials: National geographic adventure</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2008: ''Eco Brand of the Year'' award at the Volvo Ecodesign Forum during the ISPO Trade Show in Munich</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2008: 2nd Annual Rock/Creek Environmental Stewardship Award: Rock/Creek</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006: Patagonia, Environmental Sustainability: For its unique commitment to developing sustainable business practices: Business Ethics 18th Annual Awards</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Listings/Index</span></h3>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; May 24, 2012: Los Angeles Times: Outdoor retailer Patagonia puts environment ahead of sales growth</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sustainability index: Patagonia is working with 40 clothing companies, such as Walmart, to put green buying directly into the hands of consumers</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Rankings</span></h3>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia was the first major clothier to make fleece jackets out of recycled bottles</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nearly a third of the power for its headquarters and adjoining child-care center comes from solar</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia ranked 7.8/10 for its green cloth rating as the cotton used was sourced organically</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Frameworks</span></h3>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By joining B Corporation, Patagonia is striving to build the best company by meeting&nbsp; “rigorous, independent, and transparent standards of social and environmental performance.”</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainable Activities</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Biodiversity/Site</span></h3>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia also demonstrates their environmental consciousness in the design and construction of their facilities. An example is their Reno Nevada Service Center which employs green design and technologies to initially achieve a LEED Silver and then later Gold certification</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Materials</span></h3>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia commits to buy sustainable wool from Ovis XXI, while this organization certifies that the product comes from responsible producers that are keeping and restoring their natural grasslands, and keeps instructing them along with The Nature Conservancy</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, Patagonia launched a worldwide recycling initiative called the Common Threads Recycling Program. The Common Threads Recycling Program relies on both Patagonia and its customers to accomplish reducing, reusing and repairing, and recycling. It allows customers to bring back any Patagonia clothing with the special Common Threads label on it and put it into the store’s recycling bin. Patagonia then ships the clothing to refurbishment centers around the world where the fabric is processed and turned into a new Patagonia product. This reduces the amount of virgin material used for Patagonia’s products</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduce- Patagonia makes useful gear that lasts long, the consumer is asked not to buy what they don’t need.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Repair- The company helps repair the customers Patagonia gear, the consumer pledges to fix what is broken.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reuse- Patagonia helps find a home for gear that is no longer needed, the consumer sells it back to Patagonia through the Common Threads Initiative or passes it on to someone who does need it.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Recycle- Patagonia will take back gear that is worn out and recycle it into new fiber or fabric, the consumer pledges to keep stuff out of landfills.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reimagine- together “reimagine a world where we take only what nature can replace.”&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia works with bluesign standard since 2000 to evaluate and to reduce resource consumption and to screen raw materials, including dyes and finishes, used in the supply chain. Bluesign Technologies, based in Switzerland, audits the energy, water and chemical usage of its system partners and helps them achieve continuous, long-term environmental improvement. This includes screening of chemicals, which are assigned to one of three categories: blue, safe to use; gray, special handling required; and black, forbidden under the standard. The bluesign standard helps factories eliminate black chemicals and find equivalent alternatives</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Partnerships around sustainability (engaging suppliers)</span></h3>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia Inc. has teamed with <strong>The Nature Conservancy Argentina</strong> and <strong>Ovis XXI</strong> to promote the conservation of natural grasslands and their surrounding environment</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>The Organic Exchange</strong> is an organization that helps promote education about and use of organic materials in clothing and industry, primarily organic cotton. Patagonia has supported this organization since its establishment in 2002, and Patagonia was one of the first companies to switch to entirely organic cotton</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Founded in 1989 by Patagonia, <strong>the Conservation Alliance</strong> encourages outdoor sporting goods stores to contribute monetarily to environmental causes. With over 170 members, 100% of the proceeds go directly to environmental organizations</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia commits 1% of their total sales or 10% of their profits, whichever is more, to environmental groups. Since 1985, when the program was first started, Patagonia has donated $25 million to over 1,000 organizations</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia co-founded 1% for the planet, an alliance of businesses which, like Patagonia, commit at least 1% of their total sales to the environment.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia often features their environmental campaigns in their catalogs and advertisements. Many of their recent campaigns include work with preventing oil drilling in the Alaska Wildlife Refuge, "Ocean As A Wilderness", and "Don''t Dam Patagonia"</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia is collaborating with Earth justice and renowned photographer Florian Schulz to protect the Arctic wilderness.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia supports Oceans as Wilderness campaign to help to see what lives under the Earth''s seas, how the vast schools of tuna are like herds of buffalo, how bottom trawling is like clear-cutting an entire forest to get at a single tree</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to large global initiatives, Patagonia also supports several smaller initiatives such as the World Trout Initiative, Environmental Internships, and the Organic Exchange:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Developed in 2005, the World Trout Initiative works to protect the endangered fish of the world through grants to organizations that protect threatened fish. The mission of the World Trout Initiative is to “identify the individuals and groups that protect native fish, to tell their story and to support their conservation efforts by placing money into the hands of the actual groups protecting the fish”</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; A unique program that Patagonia started in 1993 is their Environmental Internships program. A Patagonia employee can take a leave of absence with full pay and benefits to volunteer within an environmental non-profit of their choice for up to two months. Employees can work anywhere in the country on any project they want</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.25in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Gulf Crisis Response- <strong>Patagonia’s Response to the Gulf Oil Spill in 2010</strong>. Patagonia''s employees, while working with the Louisiana Bucket Brigade, walked door-to-door in communities across southeastern Louisiana’s coastal parishes surveying residents about the public health, cultural and financial impacts they’d felt from BP’s April 2010 oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico. A total of 70 Employees, worked for 7 Weeks with 7 Communities</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Company has also paired up with several groups to address the challenges with sustainability and social responsibility. Some of those groups are the Outdoor Industry Association’s Eco-Index, the Corporate Responsibility Working Groups and the European Outdoor Group’s Social Responsibility Working Group</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Founded by Patagonia in 2007, Freedom to Roam is a self-supporting coalition of business, government, and conservation groups working together to conserve wildlife corridors across North America. Its goal is to create, restore and protect wild ways or corridors between habitats so animals can survive.</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability-related products and services</span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>The Footprint Chronicles</strong>: This interactive website lets a customer follow a specific piece of clothing through its entire journey from production to recycle. The website is meant to give customers a glimpse into what Patagonia is doing, and leaves an open forum for customers to comment and try to make the process even better. The point of the website is to show customers the good and the bad side of Patagonia, and open up to suggestions for how they can improve the processes that are still hurting the environment</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Governance</span></h2>\n<p>\n	As part of their Corporate Responsibility (CR) efforts, Patagonia takes responsibility for the impact of their activities on communities and the environment. Patagonia makes sure that their products are produced under safe and legal humane working conditions. The company itself does not make the products; it merely sells them through retail stores, but the products that are being sold are made from sustainable, organic materials from factories that efficaciously promote sustainability</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To ensure the sustainability of the goods they sell, Patagonia examines every factory that is used to make their products because they want to make sure the factories are aligned with their values, goals, and mission. Patagonia selects the factories based on four factors: quality, business factors, environment and social performance</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Social/Environmental Responsibility team screens all new factories for social and environmental compliance with local law under the terms and conditions of the Patagonia Code of Conduct. The SER staff visits the factories regularly to assess compliance and follow up with training for specific concerns.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The director of SER works with the Sourcing and Quality departments to determine where to place the products, and he has full veto power over the choosing of a new factory. The SER team not only works with the Quality and Sourcing departments, but with the Production Department as well. All three teams work together, and each team’s director has an equal say in sourcing decisions</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia has yet to publish a Corporate Social Responsibility report or a Sustainability Report that follows the guidelines of the GRI. But Patagonia is committed to Corporate Responsibility by initiating their own reports and publishing them online. Some of those publications are the social audit report results and a list of factories, which are available online. The factory list reports all the factories that produce Patagonia’s products. The social audit report reports on the clothes produced through the Fair Labor Association</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Challenges and Future Goals INSERT INTO `page_chunks` (`id`, `slug`, `page_id`, `body`, `parsed`, `type`, `sort`, `class`) VALUES
(1508, 'default', 135, '<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>The Coca-Cola Company’s Sustainability Review</strong></span></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Introduction:</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	The Coca-Cola Company is the world’s largest non-alcoholic beverage producer and supplier.&nbsp; They have approximately 146,200 employees worldwide, distribute over 3,500 beverages, operate in over 200 countries, and maintain 275 bottlers worldwide.&nbsp; Their sustainability efforts are detailed in the “2011-2012 GRI Report” and a few external publications.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Awards, Frameworks, and Accomplishments:</strong></span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Awards and Recognitions: </strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>July 2012</u>: “Innovation in Small Projects Award”, the International Water Association, Asia Pacific Region. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2012/07/innovative-water-recovery-system-wins-award.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>November 2010</u>: Responsible CEO of the Year Award to Mubtar Kent, Corporate Responsibility Magazine. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/11/muhtar-kent-recipient-of-responsible-ceo-of-the-year-award.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>August 2010:</u> Greener Package Award for Sustainable Innovation, PlantBottleä Packaging. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/08/plantbottle-packaging-wins-greener-package-award-for-sustainable-innovation.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>August 2010:</u> Environmental Certificate, Coca-Cola Brazil’s bottling partner Leão Junior, 9<sup>th</sup> Latin American Conference on the Preservation of the Environment. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/08/coca-cola-brasils-bottling-partner-leao-junior-recognized-with-environmental-merit-certificate.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>August 2010:</u> Environmental Excellence Award 2010, The Coca-Cola Export Corporation Pakistan Branch, National Forum for Environment &amp; Health (NFEH). <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/08/coca-cola-wins-environment-excellence-award-in-pakistan.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>July 2010:</u> 2009 – 2010 Environmental Responsibility Award "Ghiis Jáa," Coca-Cola Peru. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/07/coca-cola-peru-is-recognized-with-the-2009-2010-environmental-responsibility-award-ghiis-jaa.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>May 2010:</u> Gold Award, PlantBottleä Packaging, DuPont Awards for Packaging Innovation. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/05/the-coca-cola-company-plantbottle-packaging-receives-prestigious-global-award.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>November 2009</u>: 2009 CSR Award, Coca-Cola China, AmCham Shanghai Corporate Social Responsibility Conference and Awards</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>October 2009</u>: Citizen of Gold Award, Learning to Achieve program with Junior Achievement, Latin American Center for Development (CELADE), Uruguay</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>October 2009</u>: iTOi and Mode Selection Awards, Manantial premium water, Colombia</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>September 2009</u>: LEED Gold Environment Certificate, Global Innovation and Technology Center, The U.S. Green Building Council (USGBC), China. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2009/09/coca-cola-china-complex-awarded-leed-gold-environment-certificate-1.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>September 2009</u>: River Guardian Award, Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper (UCR).</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>May 2009</u>: Corporate Social Responsibility Awards, Coca-Cola India. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/news20090520_golden_peacock.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>May 2009</u>: Green Choice Award, <em>Natural Health Magazine. </em><a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2009/05/cheers-natural-health-magazine-selects-coca-cola-for-green-choice-award.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>January 2009</u>: Gold Medal for International Corporate Achievement in Sustainable Development, World Environment Center <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2009/01/company-receives-2009-world-environment-center-gold-medal-for-international-corporate-achievement-in.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>January 2009</u>: Red Dot Award, Product Design 2008, for innovative recycling bin made of recycled PET, Red Dot Competition</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>June 2008</u>: Sustainable Packaging Award for creation of lightweight Coca=Cola contour bottle, The Coca-Cola Company and Ardagh Glass, Starpack Awards</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>June 2008</u>: Water Care Award, Coca-Cola South Africa’s Leak Repair Project, Mail &amp; Guardian’s Greening the Future Awards</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>April 2008</u>: Green Save Award for outstanding and unique environmental conservation efforts in the Atlanta metropolitan area, <em>Atlanta Business Chronicle</em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2008</u>: “Alliance of the Year” Award, USAID</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>February 2008</u>: Golden Peacock Award for water management initiatives, Coca-Cola India, World Council for Corporate Governance</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>December 2007</u>: National Award for Excellence in Water Management for the most “Water Efficient Unit,” Coca-Cola India, Confederation of Indian Industry (CII).</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>December 2007</u>: Named Strategic Partners in Poland’s Responsible Business Forum, Coca-Cola Poland Services (CCPS) and Coca-Cola HBC Polska (CCHBCP), Responsible Business Forum (FOB)</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>November 2007<strong>:</strong></u> Asia Society Leadership Award</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>September 2007</u>: Finalist, Water Stewardship Initiatives, Coca=Cola China, Secretary of State’s 2007 Award for Corporate Excellence (ACE)</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>May 2007</u>: Bronze Star for Best Use of Innovative Materials, Chaudfontaine 0.51 RGB environmental friendly transparent label (first time compatible with reusable bottle), Starpack Industry Awards</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2007:</u> Corporate Social Responsibility Award, Mexican America Legal Defense and Education Fund.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>February 2007</u>: Bhagidari Award, Coca-Cola India water conservation and environmental management, Delhi government</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2007:</u> Product Innovation Best Ideas on Social Responsibility Issues, Coca-Cola Spain, <em>Actualidad Economica</em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CSR Excellence Awards for “Continuous Commitment”, “Environment” and “Human Resources,” Coca-Cola Greece. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2010/02/coca-cola-greece-receives-three-prestigious-awards-for-social-responsibility-in-the-community-and-wo.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Listings/Index: </strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>July 2007:</u> FTSE4Good Index of Socially Responsible Companies</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Rankings: </strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2010</u>: 50 Most Admired Companies, FORTUNE. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/exit.html?redirect=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/mostadmired/2010/index.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>October 2009</u>: 1s place, Corporate Reputation Ranking, Coca-Cola Chile, Hill and Knowlton-Captiva and <em>La Tercera</em> newspaper</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>October 2009</u>: 2<sup>nd</sup> place, Corporate Responsibility, Coca-Cola Argentina, ComunicarSE NGO</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>October 2009</u>: Best Reputation Company in Bolivia, Coca-Cola Bottling Partner Embol, Captura Consulting</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>September 2009</u>: No. 2, <em>Newsweek </em>Green Rankings, <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2009/09/company-makes-newsweeks-green-rankings.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>August 2008</u>: Most Socially Responsible Company 2008, Coca-Cola Nigeria Limited, Social Enterprise Reports and Award (SERA)</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>August 2008</u>: Food and Beverages Most Socially Responsible Company in Nigeria 2008, Coca-Cola Nigeria Limited, Social Enterprise Reports and Award (SERA)</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>June 2008</u>: “Best Corporate Brand License of the Year” for innovative merchandise made from “reclaimed, recycled and repurposed” materials, The Coca-Cola Company, Licensing Industry Merchandisers’ Association (LIMA)</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>February 2008</u>: One of Ten “Most-Admired” Companies in Germany, The Coca-Cola Company, <em>Manager Magazine</em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>December 2007</u>: Philanthropist of the Year, Coca-Cola Ukraine, World of Child, Ukrainian Fund of Philanthropists and Ukraine 3000</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>December 2007</u>: World’ Most Accountable Corporations, One World Trust 2007 Global Accountability Report. <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/news_20071203_most_accountable.html">Learn more »</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>December 2007</u>: No. 2 2007 Corporate Responsibility Study, Coca-Cola Mexico, <em>Excélsior, </em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>November 2007:</u> No. 2 India’s Most Respected Fast Moving Consumer Goods Company, <em>BusinessWorld</em> in conjunction with the Indian Market Research Bureau</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>November 2007:</u> No. 7 Most Respected Multinational Corporation in India, Coca-Cola India, <em>BusinessWorld</em> in conjunction with the Indian Market Research Bureau</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>September 2007:</u> World’s Most Respected Companies Survey, <em>Barron’s</em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>July 2007:</u> Food and Beverage Industry Category, Best EthicalQuote Progress and Best Reported Performance Categories</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>July 2007:</u> No. 2 Leaders Across All Sectors for Best Reported Performance, EthicalQuote.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>April 2007:</u> No. 4 Most Respected Companies, Coca-Cola India, <em>Business World</em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2007:</u> No. 8 America’s Most Responsible Companies Consumer Index</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2007:</u> Best Sustainability Initiative, eKOfreshment program, Zenith International Publishing Beverage Innovation Awards</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2007</u>: Green End User of the Year (small projects), eKOfreshment compression (used in coolers and vending machines), Cooling Industry Awards</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>March 2007:</u> No. 3 Beverage Industry Category, America’s Most Admired Companies Survey, <em>Fortune Magazine</em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>February 2007:</u> Ethical Brand Awards: No 1 in the United States, No. 3 in Spain, No. 8 in France, five-country study by market research group GfK NOP</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>January 2007:</u> “Global 100,” unranked list of the world’s most sustainable corporations</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2007:</u> Best Companies of the Year, Coca-Cola Spain, <em>Dirigentes. </em></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2007:</u> Best Professional Ethics, 3<sup>rd</sup> Place, Coca-Cola Spain, <em>Actualidad Economica</em></p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Frameworks: </strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Project</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Global Reporting Initiative</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainable Actions</strong></span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Water (Reduce, Recycle, and Replenish)</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company is becoming more efficient in their water use by reducing the amount they use per liter of product even as they increase their production volume</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Estimate they replenish (offset) approximately 23% of water used in their finished products</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, the company used 294.5 billion liters of water to make 130 billion liters of product, a water use ratio of 2.26 liters per liter of product (16% reduction from 2004)</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company wants to treat all the wastewater from their manufacturing processes. By the end of 2010, they achieved a 93% alignment</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By the end of 2010, 100% of the 200 Company owned plants achieved compliance with their wastewater treatment and discharge standards and now use on-site, municipal or government approved wastewater treatment plants</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To date, 370/950 system-wide plants have completed source vulnerability assessments.&nbsp; And 269 of those plants have begun implementing source water protection plants based on those assessments.&nbsp; The assessments inventory risks to water resources that supply their facilities and the surrounding communities</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Assessments covered six main areas of potential water risk:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Efficiency of water use</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Compliance with wastewater standards</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Watershed Sustainability</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Water Supply Reliability</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Social and Competitive Context</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Supply Economics</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; 2008 Risk Assessment Update:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 44% of water-related risks were derived from growing and competing demands on water, coupled with inadequate government policy and action, which affected water quality and quantity</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 24% of their risks were economic and came from rising water acquisition and discharge fees</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 15% of their risks were due to a lack of full compliance with internal wastewater treatment requirements</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 17% of their risk were sociopolitical in nature and came from local government and community engagement around local/global water challenges</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prior to 2010 water use division: 78% municipal, 21% surface/ground, and 1% other water/rainwater</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 system: 52% ground/surface, 47% municipal, and practically no other water/rainwater is used</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company states that they were able to achieve their successes in water sustainability by:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Using ionized air instead of water to rinse product packages prior to filling.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reusing treated wastewater for landscape irrigation and truck washing.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Advanced monitoring of water use and efficiency.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company’s bottling partners have engaged in 320 community water projects in 86 countries, 96 of the projects are educational programs. The projects have 4 objectives:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Improve access to water and sanitation</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Protect watersheds</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide water for productive use</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Educate/Raise Awareness about water issues.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Water Footprinting</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; A product water footprint is the total volume of freshwater consumed, directly and indirectly, to produce a product</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The Coca-Cola Company is investing in water footprint assessments in order to have a better understanding how of they indirectly use water in their supply chain, particularly sustainable agriculture</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; They have partnered with the Water Footprint Network since 2008, supporting its development and methodology</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; For the past two years, they have collaborated with The Nature Conservancy on 3 water footprint studies:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Coca-Cola in a 0.5-liter PET bottle produced by Coca-Cola Enterprises, Inc. in the Netherlands</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Beet sugar supplied to Coca-Cola bottling plants in Europe.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; Minute Maid orange juice and Simply Orange produced for North America</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Energy</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company has developed several measures to reduce greenhouse gas emissions:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; With the help of their partnership with WWF and research within their company the company was able to develop 10 high-return, low-risk energy best practices for bottling partners to implement by 2012 and a site through which they can document their progress</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; At their Ireland-based concentrate manufacturing facility, Ballina Beverages, a new combined heat and power plant went online.&nbsp; The plan captures heat from electricity generation and diverts it to heating and hot water systems.&nbsp; The plant’s operation is showing 17% lower carbon dioxide emissions</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Investing in clean energy:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The company has installed solar panels at facilities in Macon, Georgia and Coachella, California.&nbsp; They are working on installing solar panels at 4 more North American facilities</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; They have begun construction on a landfill gas-powered co-generation system at their Atlanta syrup branch</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; The 6.3 megawatt combined heat and power system will use biomethane from a nearby landfill as its primary fuel.&nbsp; They expect it to reduce Coca-Cola Refreshments carbon footprint by approximately 20,400 tons each year</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, they organized a Sustainable Refrigeration Summit, which brought together a variety of companies to explore a more rapid adoption of HFC-free refrigerants. This led to The Consumer Goods Forum’s pledge to start phasing our HFC refrigerants by 2015</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Along with World Climate Ltd., they co-organized a panel discussion on a carbon-free economy</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Increasing their energy efficiency:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Through their improvement of their energy efficiency ratio to 0.45 megajoules per liter in 2010 the company was able to avoid $163 million in energy costs for 2010. That is a 1% improvement over their 2009 ratio and 14% over their 2004 ratio</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Global manufacturing emissions in 2010 were 2% lower than 2009 while increasing unit case volume by 5%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, Coca-Cola reduced emissions in developed companies by 1% compared to 2009</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; More efficient cooling equipment:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Approximately 45% of their company-owned coolers now have energy management devices which results in an estimated 16% decrease in energy consumption by the cooler fleet</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By the end of 2010, 100% of their new glass-door coolers and 95% of their new vending and fountain machines were 40% more efficient</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By August 31, 2011 the company had installed around 400,000 HFC-free coolers</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, around 15% of their new cold-drink equipment purchases were HFC-free</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cutting emissions and energy use in developing countries:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The new facilities that the company builds in developing countries meet the energy efficiency standards that the company holds for the rest of the facilities.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; For example, their operations in Turkey are the most efficient in their system, with a ratio of 0.26 megajoules per liter</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; They have LEED certified facilities being build in Brazil and established in China</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Materials (Sustainable Packaging)</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduced the weight of their 20-oz PET plastic bottle by more than 25%</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduced 30% of the weight of their 12-oz aluminum can</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduced the weight of their 8-oz glass bottle by more than 50%</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, the company saved $90 million through a reduction of packaging waste</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of 2011, the company recovers around 36% of the bottles and cans they have in market</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Developed the first-ever fully recyclable PET bottle made from plant based material, PlantBottleä</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca – Cola works towards a zero-waste vision by:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Designing resource efficient packaging</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Eliminating waste for landfills</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Using recycled and renewable materials.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 Coca-Cola System Global Packaging Mix:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; PET: 54%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Aluminum: 12%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Refillable Glass: 11%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Fountain: 11%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Refillable PET: 7%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Glass: 1%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Other: 4%</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In developing markets, the company works with industry and government to advance informal collection systems to make them formal systems that recover packaging material and provide sustainable jobs</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In developed markets, the company supports ways to organize comprehensive material recovery systems through industry</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Support the market for RPET by supporting the creation of goods made from the material</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PlantBottleä Packaging:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; More than 50% of The Coca-Cola Company’s beverage volume is delivered in bottles made from PET</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; PlantBottleä is a fully recyclable PET bottle made partially from plant materials</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; The company has discovered a way to manufacture one of the two primary ingredients in PET from plant-based material and is working on the other one</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company invested in 7 bottle-to-bottle facilities that strive to increase their capacity for using recycled material</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Transportation</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	Developed a Climate Friendly Fleet:</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company powers the fleet with a mix of fuels that include electricity, natural gas, diesel-electric hybrids, bio-diesel, and conventional fuels</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company believes that their electric hybrid fleet in North America, of 700 or more trucks, could potentially reduce greenhouse gas emissions by around 30%</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca-Cola Hellenic has avoided 954 tons of carbon dioxide emissions since 2009 through the employment of a Safe and Eco-Driving Program along with maximum fuel consumption, route management systems, trained drivers, and performance monitoring</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca – Cola Refreshments is working to increase the number of electric trucks they deploy. They currently have 2 operating in Bronx, NY and six Navistar eStar electric trucks in Los Angeles, New York City, San Francisco and Washington D.C.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Along with training drivers to use techniques that are more energy efficient and reduce emissions</p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Partnerships Around Sustainability</strong></span></h3>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Safe Water for Africa Program</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; As part of the Replenish Africa Initiative (RAIN), Coca-Cola’s 6 year $30 million commitment to provide access to safe drinking water for communities in Africa, the company joined Diageo plc, WaterHealth International and the International Finance Corporation in laundhcing the Safe Water for Africa Program in May 2011</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The program will bring WaterHealth International’s WaterHealth Centers to more communities in Africa.&nbsp; The centers treat locally available water in accordance with the World Health Organization’s standards.&nbsp; The water is then made available to residents for a nominal usage fee and eventually the fees cover the cost of the center and maintenance, making the community sustainable</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>The Latin America Water Fund Partnership</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; FEMSA Foundation, a partner of one of Coca=Cola’s largest bottlers in Latin America along with The Nature Conservancy and Inter-American Development Bank created this Partnership that will manage all water funds in Latin America</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; The water funds are in essence trust funds dedicated to the conservation of watersheds</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By achieving the stewardship of 32 water funds, the partnership intends to conserve at least 800,000 hectares of protected natural areas and an additional 20,000 hectares of key ecosystems</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; It is projected that by 2015, more than 12 million people will have better access to water and at least 1200 rural families will increase their annual income</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Partnership with the World Wildlife Fund (WWF)</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2007, The Coca-Cola Company launched a transformational partnership with WWF, which established a join commitment to conserve 7 of the most important river basins spanning Asia, Europe, Africa, and the Americas. In each basin they address 4 central challenges:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 1. Better governance and management</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 2. Resource protection</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 3. Conservation in balance with development</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\n	§&nbsp; 4. Biodiversity Protection</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Partnership with the UNDP</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2006, the company joined the UNDP in launching Every Drop Mattersä, which is an effort to address water related challenges in communities across Eastern Europe and Eurasia.&nbsp; The program helps to improve sanitation and water quality, install rainwater-harvesting systems and educate residents about water stewardship. The company made a $23.75 million commitment to support the project through 2014</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>2030 Water Resources Group (WRG)</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In partnership with other businesses and governmental organizations, The Coca – Cola Company helped from this group in 2007 to contribute new insights to the increasingly urgent issue of water scarcity</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of the group’s work, several governments facing water shortages (e.g. India, Jordan, and Mexico) have engaged in more dialogue on water security, water management, and policy reform</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Its new goal is to support governments as they engage in water analysis, convene multistakeholder collaborations and undertake public-private partnerships</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Aqueduct Alliance</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The Coca-Cola Company has joined this group, which is a group of leading water experts from the private and public sectors, NGOs and academia</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; This alliance is a program of the World Resources Institute seeking to measure, map, and report on global water risk in order to form a global database of water risk information</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The company will support this group by providing their own extensive global database of water risk information</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>National Clean Fleets Partnership</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2011, Coca-Cola Refreshments (CCR), the North American owned bottling operations, announced a membership with the National Clean Fleets Partnership.&nbsp; The partnership intends to help large companies reduce diesel and gasoline use by incorporating alternative vehicles, alternative fuels, and other fuel-saving measures</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Partnership with Thailand’s Pathum Thani Province</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, the Thailand Institute of Packaging and Recycling Management for Sustainable Environment, an industry organization that Coca-Cola is part of, partnered with the Pathum Thani Province as part of a project that aims to develop a more effective integrated waste management program</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Partnership with The Regional Initiative for Inclusive Recycling (Brazil)</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; A 4-year effort to transform the recycling market in Latin America by improving the socioeconomic status of recyclers and their families; ensuring that recycling cooperatives thrive in a competitive market; supporting public policy that allows recycling cooperatives to become part of local waste management systems.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Ocean Conservancy</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The company has partnered with this group for 16 years and has supported them by providing funding, in-kind support, and volunteer assistance to help clean up the seas and investigate marine pollution</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Co-hosted a workshop that helped design the <em>Fifth International Marine Debris Conference</em></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2011, helped the Ocean Conservancy launch <em>Trash Free Seas Alliance – </em>a cooperative group of businesses, NGO’s, and scientific institutions working toward a goal of eliminating ocean trash</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainability Governance</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	The Board of Directors is elected by shareowners to oversee the long-term health and the success of the business. The Board serves as the ultimate decision-making body, except for matters reserved to the shareowners. There are seven standing committees under the direction of the Board of Directors (Audit, Compensation, Directors &amp; Corporate Governance, Executive, Finance,</p>\n<p>\n	Management Development, and Public Issues and Diversity Review). Currently there are seventeen serving members in the Board of Directors.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Board of Directors established the Public Issues and Diversity Review Committee to aid the Board in its responsibilities regarding Coca Cola’s positions on corporate social responsibility and public issues that affect the shareowners, the Company, business community, and the general public. The Committee shall consist of no fewer than three members of the Board of Directors, which it currently consists six members including the chairman</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Public Issues and Diversity Review Committee evaluates social, political and environmental trends, issues and concerns that could affect the Company’s business activities and performance</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Audit Committee has oversight of environmental policies and performance as well</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Office of Sustainability with Chief Sustainability Officer, Beatriz Perez</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; VP, Corporate Social Responsibility, John Reid</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Global Director, Women’s Economic Empowerment, Charlotte Oades</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; VP, Sustainability Strategy and Communication, Abby Rodgers</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; VP, Environment and Water, Jeff Seabright</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Director, Corporate External Affairs</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Senior Management and Board of Directors, several organizations were implemented to address sustainability such as the Technical Stewardship Organization, the Environment and Water Resources Department, the Environmental Advisory Board (EAB), and the Coca-Cola Environmental Council (CCEC)</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Technical Stewardship Organization</strong>- is responsible for environmental matters, including water resources, as well as product quality, scientific and regulatory affairs and business process excellence</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Environment and Water Resources Department</strong>- resides in the Technical Stewardship Organization and it is responsible for setting environmental strategy across business operations, developing environmental standards and programs, and managing performance</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Environmental Advisory Board(EAB)-</strong> a panel of experts from government, nongovernmental organizations and academia provides counsel to management on environmental issues, the views of external stakeholders, and environmental policies, programs and performance</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Coca-Cola Environmental Council (CCEC)-</strong> the CCEC consists of senior representatives from the Company and bottling partners. The Council promotes environmental management across the business system by sharing best practices and developing and validating environmental standards</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Challenges and Future Goals</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Water</u></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: Assess the vulnerability of the quality and quantity of water sources for each of our bottling plants and implement a locally relevant water resource sustainability program by the end of 2012.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2012, improve water efficiency by 20% compared with a 2004 baseline.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2020, safely return to nature and to communities an amount of water equal to what we want to use in our finished beverages and their production.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Energy</u></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: Grow our business but not our system-wide carbon emissions in our manufacturing operations through 2015 compared with our 2004 baseline.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2015, reduce emissions from our manufacturing operations in developed countries by 5% compared to our 2004 baseline.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: As of 2015, all new cold-drink equipment will be HFC-free, with an interim goal of being 50% HFC-free by 2012.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>Sustainable Packaging</u></p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2015, improve packaging material efficiency per liter of product sold by 7% compared with a 2008 baseline.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2015, recover 50% of the equivalent bottles and cans’ used annually.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: Source 25% of our PET plastic from recycled and renewable material by 2015.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Best Practices / Success Drivers</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PlantBottleä Packaging: <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/plantbottle.html">PlantBottle Webpage</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ionized Air: <a href="http://www.google.com/patents/US5265298">Patent</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><em>Compensation Tied to Company Performance: </em></strong></p>\n<p>\n	The compensation programs are designed to reward employees for producing sustainable growth consistent with the Company’s 2020 Vision, to attract and retain world-class talent and to align compensation with the long-term interests of shareowners. The Coca-Cola Company believes that as an employee’s level or responsibility increases, so should the proportion of performance-based compensation. As a result, the executive compensation programs are closely tied to performance</p>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and Prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley</em></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sources</strong></span></h2>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/TCCC_2010_2011_GRI_Report.pdf">http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/TCCC_2010_2011_GRI_Report.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/TCCC_2010_2011_GRI_Report.pdf">http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/TCCC_2010_2011_GRI_Report.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/ourcompany/awards_recognition.html?awardSection=corp_responsibility">http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/ourcompany/awards_recognition.html?awardSection=corp_responsibility</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2011/05/new-chief-sustainability-officer.html">http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2011/05/new-chief-sustainability-officer.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/plantbottle.html">http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/plantbottle.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://www.google.com/patents/US5265298">http://www.google.com/patents/US5265298</a></p>\n<p>\n	For further information regarding compensation discussion and analysis can be found on the following link: <a href="http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/21344/000130817912000055/lcocacola_def14a.htm">http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/21344/000130817912000055/lcocacola_def14a.htm</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, '');
