(1509, 'default', 137, '<h1 align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>IBM Sustainability Review</strong></span></h1>\n<h1 align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></h1>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Introduction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	Charles Ranlett Flint founded the International Business Machine Corporation, or IBM in 1911. With 433,362 employees, $116.4 billion in assets, and over 300 national and international locations IBM is a very large company that makes and applies technology to improve the world.&nbsp; Its employees create and integrate hardware, software, and services with the goal of creating a “smarter planet”.&nbsp; It established corporate policies of providing a safe and healthy workplace (1967), protecting the environment (1971), and conserving natural resources and energy (1974).&nbsp; From 2007-2011, IBM has spent $106.9 million in capital and $508.5 million in operating expenses to construct, maintain, and improve the infrastructure for environmental protection and to manage its worldwide environmental programs.</p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability Awards</span></h3>\n<p>\n	2012:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		European Union Code of Conduct for Data Centers Award: for technologies used to improve data center energy efficiency</li>\n	<li>\n		EPA Climate Leadership Award</li>\n	<li>\n		World Environment Center’s Gold Medal for International Corporate Achievement in Sustainable Development</li>\n	<li>\n		Vermont Governor’s Award for Environmental Excellence</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2011:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (to IBM Global Real Estate Operations)</li>\n	<li>\n		Corporate Energy Management International Award from AEE (Association of Energy Engineers)</li>\n	<li>\n		Institute for Supply Management Awards for Excellence in Supply Management</li>\n	<li>\n		Business and The Environment Award (from DECISION magazine in the UK)</li>\n	<li>\n		China Sustainability Award</li>\n	<li>\n		Canadian Industry Program for Energy Conservation Leadership Award (IBM Canada)</li>\n	<li>\n		Distinction Award (in the category of Energy Efficiency)(IBM Canada)</li>\n	<li>\n		Vermont Governor’s Awards for Environmental Excellence (IBM Burlington)</li>\n	<li>\n		Best Overall Energy Project in New England Award (from the New England Chapter of the Association of Energy Engineers) (IBM Burlington)</li>\n	<li>\n		Excellence in Environmental Engineering Award (from the American Academy of Environmental Engineers)</li>\n	<li>\n		Smith Seal of North Carolina Sustainable Business award--Lifetime Achievement for Large Organization</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2010:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (IBM Systems and Technology Group)</li>\n	<li>\n		Most Valuable Pollution Prevention Award (from National Pollution Prevention Roundtable)</li>\n	<li>\n		Class of Excellence Wastewi$e Label Award in the Hong Kong Awards for Environmental Excellence program (IBM Hong Kong)</li>\n	<li>\n		Excellence Award in the Environment Excellence category (IBM’s Corporate Service Corps)</li>\n	<li>\n		Vermont Governor’s Awards for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2009:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (IBM Research)</li>\n	<li>\n		Vermont Governor’s Awards for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention</li>\n	<li>\n		Sustainable Development Award (IBM Canada from the regional Chamber of Commerce)</li>\n	<li>\n		Industrial Energy Technology Conference Energy Awards</li>\n	<li>\n		Most Valuable Pollution Prevention Award (IBM Burlington, Vermont)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2008:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		ECOFIRA INNOVACION Award</li>\n	<li>\n		Environmental Affairs Excellence Award (IBM East Fishkill)</li>\n	<li>\n		Top Winner in the Green IT Report</li>\n	<li>\n		Gold Medal at the British Computer Society Project Excellence Awards in the IT Industry Awards category</li>\n	<li>\n		Vermont Governor’s Award for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2007:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (IBM Systems and Technology Group)</li>\n	<li>\n		Environmental Excellence Award</li>\n	<li>\n		Green IT Initiative of the Year</li>\n	<li>\n		Technology Award (IBM Canada from American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-Conditioning Engineers)</li>\n	<li>\n		Most Outstanding Demonstration of Packaging Waste Management in Australia</li>\n	<li>\n		SmartWay Excellence Award (from US EPA)</li>\n	<li>\n		Most Valuable Pollution Prevention Award (IBM Burlington, Vermont)</li>\n	<li>\n		Vermont Governor’s Award for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention (IBM Burlington)</li>\n	<li>\n		New York State Environmental Excellence Award (IBM East Fishkill)</li>\n	<li>\n		U.S. Environmental Protection Agency SmartWay Excellence Award</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Listings/Index</span></h3>\n<p>\n	2012:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Standard &amp; Poors list: AA-</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2011:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Dow Jones Sustainability Index (since 2005)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2008:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Gold Rating under the Corporate Responsibility Index (from St. James Ethics Centre, Australia)</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked AA+ from Climate Protection Office of the Tokyo Government</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2007</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Silver Star rating in the Corporate Responsibility Index (submitted by IBMAustralia)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Rankings</span></h3>\n<p>\n	2012:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 among US Companies in Newsweek’s Green Rankings</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #4 in the global ranking of Newsweek’s Green Rankings</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2011:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in Newsweek’s Green Rankings</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in the November 2011 Supercomputing Green500 List (from Green500.org)</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #6 in Computerworld’s Top 12 Green IT Vendors</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2010:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in Newsweek’s Green Rankings</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in the November 2010 Supercomputing Green 500 List (from Green500.org)</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in all-around performance in Gartner/World Wildlife Fund’s “Low-Carbon and Environmental Leadership Findings Report”</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2009:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in IDG’s Computerworld’s annual Top Green-IT Vendors ranking</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 Supercomputing Green 500 List</li>\n	<li>\n		Top 20 companies in the Sustainable Business 20 List: The World’s Top Sustainable Stocks</li>\n	<li>\n		Top 5 in Newsweek magazine’s Green Rankings</li>\n	<li>\n		Top Rating in Bank Sarasin’s sustainability analysis</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2008:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 on Climate Change Strategies in Ceres Report</li>\n	<li>\n		Gold level ranking in the Business in the Community Environment Index</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in Best 50 Corporate Citizens in Canada</li>\n	<li>\n		Included in Sustainable Business 20 List: The World’s Top Sustainable Stocks</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	2007:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #12 on US EPA’s Fortune 500 List of Green Power Partners for 2007</li>\n	<li>\n		Gold Rating in Corporate Responsibility Index (IBM Australia)</li>\n	<li>\n		Gold Rating U.K. Business in the Community</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #1 in the IT sector by the MERCO index (Spanish Corporate Responsibility Index)</li>\n	<li>\n		Ranked #4 on Climate Counts scorecard of corporate leadership on climate change</li>\n	<li>\n		Top Ten Best Green Outsourcers of 2007</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Frameworks</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		LEED Gold Certification (Lab in Foster City, CA)</li>\n	<li>\n		Carbon Disclosure Project\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Disclosure Rating = 83</li>\n			<li>\n				Highest Disclosure Rating within sector</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Global Reporting Initiative rating of A</li>\n	<li>\n		Using OneReport</li>\n	<li>\n		IBM’s Global Environmental Management System conforms to ISO 50001 Standard on Energy Management Systems</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainable Activities</span></h2>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Biodiversity/Site</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		IBM Smarter Building Software maximizes the energy and environmental performance of buildings.&nbsp; It monitors equipment that consumes energy, manages the maintenance activities, and then reports the data using IBM software</li>\n	<li>\n		Match building lighting and occupancy schedules and install more efficient lighting systems</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Water</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2011: 646 TCMs of water were conserved through:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				On-site water reuse</li>\n			<li>\n				Wastewater and groundwater recycling projects</li>\n			<li>\n				Groundwater monitoring at all manufacturing and development locations</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Goal: average annual water conservation savings equal to 2% IBM’s annual water use at microelectronics manufacturing operations</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Energy</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Saved 523,000 MWh of electricity: 7.4% of total energy</li>\n	<li>\n		175,000 metric tons of CO2 avoided</li>\n	<li>\n		Doubled the computing capacity of its data centers in 3 years w/o increasing power consumption</li>\n	<li>\n		Use renewable energy\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Working to further the availability and affordability of renewable energy</li>\n			<li>\n				Wind farm management</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Materials</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Health Protection:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Prohibited CFCs, Class I and II ozone-depleting substances, Trichloroethylene, ethylene-based glycol ethers and dichloromethane</li>\n			<li>\n				Of 3,233 metric tons of EPCRA-listed chemicals, more than 84% was treated for recycling or for energy recovery</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Product Recycling:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				35% total weight of plastic resins were resins that contained between 25 and 100% recycled materials</li>\n			<li>\n				Processed 37,950 metric tons of end-of-life products and product waste and send only 0.4% of total to landfills/incineration</li>\n			<li>\n				Offered product take-back programs in Europe since 1989</li>\n			<li>\n				Included product recovery in annual corporate environmental report since 1995</li>\n			<li>\n				78% nonhazardous waste recycled</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Product Packaging Design:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Saved 780 metric tons of packaging materials with their 24 packaging redesign projects</li>\n			<li>\n				IBM Packaging guidelines (developed in 1990) lay out the methods, processes, and designs that should be used in order to reduce packaging volume and to promote the use of packaging materials that are reusable, recyclable, and/or contain recycled materials&nbsp;</li>\n			<li>\n				Use corrugated cardboard box instead of outer wooden crates for shipment overseas</li>\n			<li>\n				Eliminated the individual corrugated carton packaging for each part of the option package of IBM System x server</li>\n			<li>\n				Past Power System server chassis packaging strengthened so it could be reused for final delivery of product</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Voluntary Environmental Goal for Packaging Materials:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Requirement for responsible sourcing of paper and paper/wood-based packaging in 2002--supplies must be procured from suppliers who sustainably manage their forests</li>\n			<li>\n				Investigated bio-based materials</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Hazardous Materials\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Management program tracks the hazardous waste management performance of locations worldwide</li>\n			<li>\n				Voluntary environmental goal</li>\n			<li>\n				Recycle some of the hazardous waste: in 2011, IBM generated 7,700 metric tons of hazardous waste.&nbsp; 44% was recycled and 36% was sent to landfills.&nbsp; Of the waste sent to the landfills, 85% was sludge from industrial wastewater treatment plants which (by government regulations) needed to be disposed of in hazardous waste landfills</li>\n			<li>\n				In 5 years, the hazardous waste generation has decreased by 36%</li>\n			<li>\n				Report the releases of chemicals into the environment\n				<ul>\n					<li>\n						0.4% chemicals released into the air</li>\n					<li>\n						Goal: year-to-year reduction in releases of EPCRA reportable chemicals to the environment</li>\n				</ul>\n			</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Transportation/Air Quality</span></h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2011: conserved 6.4 million gallons of fuel</li>\n	<li>\n		Offers Cognos and Sterling Transportation Management Software Solutions to help companies optimize their transportation systems (increase container/truck capacity, optimize routing, improving timely deliveries, reduce fuel use, and decrease emissions)</li>\n	<li>\n		Electrical vehicles: integrating into electricity grid and battery development</li>\n	<li>\n		Flexible work programs (work-at-home and mobile employees)</li>\n	<li>\n		Support public transport (shuttles from locations to mass transit stations, and “loaner” cars for business trips during the workday &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		Set guidelines for smaller engines with lower car emission levels</li>\n	<li>\n		Online meetings and instant messaging to cut down on traveling</li>\n	<li>\n		2011: conserved 6.4 million gallons of fuel</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Partnerships around sustainability (engaging suppliers)</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Governmental:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				United States Environmental Protection Agency’s ENERGY STAR, SmartWay, Design for Environment, and WasteWise programs</li>\n			<li>\n				European Union Code of Conduct for Energy Efficient Data Centers</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		NGOs:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Charter membership in World Wildlife Fund’s Climate Savers program</li>\n			<li>\n				Membership in Center for Climate and Energy Solutions</li>\n			<li>\n				Work with and support The Conservation Fund, the Environmental Law Institute, and the World Environment Center</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Partnerships with other companies:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Founding member of the GridWise Alliance: organization representing a large range of the energy supply chain with the goal of making the electric grid more sustainable</li>\n			<li>\n				IBM and WEC formed the Innovation in Environmental Sustainability Council, which explores how changes in business process and technology can solve challenges to materials, energy, water, infrastructure, and logistics</li>\n			<li>\n				Eco-Patent Commons: allows for global businesses to share their innovations that support sustainable development</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Sustainability-related products and services</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Designing energy-efficient products that use high-efficiency power supplies\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Providing clients with energy-efficient solutions</li>\n			<li>\n				Offers Cognos and Sterling Transportation Management Software Solutions to help companies optimize their transportation systems (increase container/truck capacity, optimize routing, improving timely deliveries, reduce fuel use, and decrease emissions)</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainability Governance</span></h2>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		IBM’s Board of Directors is responsible for supervising the overall company’s affairs: it usually consists of 10 to 14 directors and it currently stands at 14 members.</li>\n	<li>\n		It has delegated authority to four committees:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				The Audit Committee</li>\n			<li>\n				The Executive Compensation and Management Resource Committee</li>\n			<li>\n				The Executive Committee</li>\n			<li>\n				The Directors and Corporate Governance Committee\n				<ul>\n					<li>\n						The Directors and Corporate Governance Committee review IBM’s environmental programs and performance annually</li>\n					<li>\n						The Committee was formed in 1993 and it established responsibility for reviewing IBM’s position and practices on issues such as corporate responsibility and environmental protection</li>\n				</ul>\n			</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		The Corporate Environmental Affairs staff:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Establishes the company’s worldwide environmental affairs strategy, EMS requirements, and monitoring of its implementation</li>\n			<li>\n				Environmental programs are implemented by professionals at manufacturing, development, and research</li>\n			<li>\n				Environmental staff at headquarters of major IBM geographic organizations oversees local performance</li>\n			<li>\n				IBM employees within operating units serve as team leaders for environmental matters</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Mechanisms to measure effectiveness include:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Professional Self-Assessment Program</li>\n			<li>\n				Environmental Performance Database</li>\n			<li>\n				Corporate Internal Audits</li>\n			<li>\n				ISO 14001 surveillance audits</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		IBM formalized corporate policies in 1967, 1971 and 1974 to provide a safe and healthful work place, protect the environment, and conserve energy and natural resources</li>\n	<li>\n		IBM established a strong worldwide Environmental Management System: EMS\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				IBM first established EMS in 1997 to identify and effectively manage the potential environmental impact of IBM’s operations</li>\n			<li>\n				It respects the standard ISO 14001</li>\n			<li>\n				The registration of EMS verifies that IBM executes the same EMS no matter where in the world it does business</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Over the past five years IBM has spent over $508.5 million in operating expenses for environmental protection and to manage its environmental programs. In 2011 IBM saved about $139.1 million worldwide in environmental costs</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Challenges and Future Goals INSERT INTO `page_chunks` (`id`, `slug`, `page_id`, `body`, `parsed`, `type`, `sort`, `class`) VALUES
