(1585, 'default', 144, '<p>\n	<strong><u>Adobe – Green Buildings and Sustainability Measures&nbsp;</u></strong></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>By Anuradha Munshi</strong></p>\n<p>\n	Adobe has been innovating in the LEED green building movement for the past decade. It owns seven buildings in the U.S., all of which have achieved EPA Energy STAR label with an average rating of 99 out of a possible 100. Six of the seven buildings are LEED Platinum certified in the Existing Buildings category, while the seventh is LEED Platinum certified in the Commercial Interiors category.</p>\n<p>\n	How has Adobe achieved and maintained this level of energy efficiency in its buildings? Described below are some of the features that Adobe deploys for its green buildings, along with some key sustainability measures.</p>\n<p>\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Lighting Upgrades </u></strong>- Adobe has continuously upgraded all lighting at its office buildings and garages as more efficient versions of lighting have become available in the industry. Starting with florescent lamps Adobe first upgraded its lighting infrastructure. Today as LEDs have decreased in cost with higher efficiency, the facilities crew has once again swapped all bulbs for LEDs. Adobe finds that this simple yet effective move helps achieve a high degree of energy efficiency.</p>\n<p>\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Intelligent Sensors</u> </strong>– Efficiency by the lighting infrastructure is complimented by installing intelligent motion sensors, daylight sensors, and other controls to turn off lamps and VAV boxes in work spaces and to power down monitors, task lamps, and other accessories when they not in use. For example daylight controlled lighting and timer sensitive motion detectors are used to control and monitor lighting in offices, resulting in its optimum usage.</p>\n<p>\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Monitoring and Control</u></strong> – Lighting upgrades and sensor equipment are further accompanied by software based intelligent monitor and control systems that monitor and control the buildings’ electricity and gas use, CO2 emissions, water use, indoor climate (temperature, humidity and airflow). Energy use in Adobe is tracked by building, floor and even by individual clusters of desks called “neighborhoods”. This holistic measurement and control is critical for Adobe in maintaining desired levels of energy efficiency in its buildings.</p>\n<p>\n	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Commissioning </u></strong>– Once the infrastructures are in place, continuous tweaking and fine tuning follows. Commissioning, or the process of continuous monitoring, fine tuning and upgrading, has been addressed early on in Adobe by their Facilities team. For example their HVAC changed from basic hourly timing or current weather conditions to well-placed motion sensors tied to VAV boxes. Similarly tying motion sensors to HVAC alone saved 300,000 kWh per year for Adobe. Moving a thermostat from ceiling to head level in an IDC closet (intermediate distributed closet) yielded better efficiencies. The key point is the process of constant experimentation and improvisation.</p>\n<p>\n	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Open office space </u></strong>– Adobe adopts an open office design that eliminates hard walls and makes use of natural lighting wherever possible. This has resulted in lower energy usage. Two rows of lights closest to the windows are operated by daylight activated sensors.&nbsp; Also when no motion is detected for 15 minutes all the lights shut off, and switching them back on is a manual task that people avoid. This saves energy and also does not make them want to use light unnecessarily in the first place.</p>\n<p>\n	6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Energy Generation </u></strong>– The Company has delved into different ways of generating sustainable energy of its own. At its San Jose campus, 20 vertical axis wind turbines (called “Windspires”) on the 6<sup>th</sup> floor patio generate clean energy from the natural wind tunnel configuration provided by the Adobe Towers. Adobe has also installed 12 100 kW Fuel Cells by Bloom Energy on its 5<sup>th</sup> floor parking garage. The fuel cells deliver about 30% of the electricity used at Adobe’s headquarters. The fuel cells however create CO2 and Adobe purchases RECs (Renewable Energy Certificates) to achieve carbon neutrality.</p>\n<p>\n	7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Water Conservation</u></strong> – Adobe has installed low-flow showerheads, low-flow hands-free faucets, waterless urinals and dual high-efficiency flush models with devices that adjust the volume according to the length of the user’s stay. Additionally their landscaping features drought tolerant native plants. Evapotranspiration controllers are used to adjust the amount of water used for irrigation based on current precipitation, humidity, temperature and wind conditions as determined wirelessly from the local weather station.</p>\n<p>\n	8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Solid Waste and Recycling </u></strong>– Adobe achieves nearly zero waste diversion rates. The office discourages excess usage of paper and other materials. Printers default to 2-side copies.&nbsp; Paper purchases are down by 60%. Bathrooms use compostable roll-style paper towels, bottled water dispensers are no longer used, coffee machines use beans in bulk packaging, and recyclers have been installed for shrink wraps and disposable pens, while all electronic waste is recycled. Dual “side-saddle” waste baskets at every desk allow first pass separation of recyclables into compost and non-compost articles. Shipping, packaging and distribution are controlled and monitored.&nbsp; All such measures go a long way for Adobe in controlling its solid waste disposal and encouraging recycling.</p>\n<p>\n	9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Supporting Sustainable and Local Agriculture</u></strong> – Cafeterias use organically grown food from local regions, even including food from the offices’ owned edible terrace gardens. Wood and other materials for furniture and design come from approved sources by the Forest Stewardship Council.</p>\n<p>\n	10.&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong><u>Encouraging sustainable transportation</u> </strong>- Adobe provides free Caltrain passes to its employees, thereby encouraging mass transit. Monthly vouchers for other transit systems are also offered. Bicycle commuting is encouraged by providing weather shelters bicycle racks inside the garage, with gear lockers and showers at each building, while Electric charging stations are available for guests and employees free of cost. As a result of these measures, 24% of the total Adobe population commutes on public transit (compared to 4% average for the county of Santa Clara).</p>\n<p>\n	For more information about Adobe’s sustainability measures please refer to the document here.</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1586, 'default', 139, '<p>\n	<strong><u>Smart Grids and the future</u></strong></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>By Anuradha Munshi</strong></p>\n<p>\n	A smart grid is an intelligent infrastructure of the electricity network that builds itself up in a bidirectional and decentralized manner, unlike the traditional centralized top down electricity network that is in place today.&nbsp; This modern electricity network offers the advantages of utilizing locally available Distributed Generation (DGs) (which could be driven by renewable sources of energy like Solar and Wind energy) coupled with a fast and modern bi-directional interconnection network that allows near real time fault tracking and control. The smart grid improves grid reliability and operational efficiency <a href="http://www.cnt.org/news/media/isgi-summary-of-benefits-and-issues-6-08.pdf"><strong>[1]</strong></a>, and introduces a platform on which retailers can create and offer new products and services that give electricity consumers greater choice and flexibility in energy consumption and in creating value for end users.</p>\n<p>\n	Architecturally the smart grid can be constructed as a network of smaller units of smart grids called micro-grids, each of which consists of a local distributed generation source and transmission mechanisms that interconnect it to the network. In the event of a national emergency (like a natural disaster), these micro grids can decouple from the main grid and can act as self-sufficient sources of electricity for long periods of time.</p>\n<p>\n	In this article we look at a couple of specific applications of the smart grid. The first application allows the smart grid to act as a peer to peer electricity network and help facilitate transactions where the consumer turns into a prosumer (or a producer and consumer of electricity). The second application allows a smart grid cluster of micro-grids to decouple itself from the main network in times of emergency.</p>\n<p>\n	As a decentralized model, a smart grid allows two methods of prosumer participation. The first model assumes that the utility has higher prominence in deciding or controlling electricity transactions between buyer and seller. This is the principle behind net-metering or the feed-in-tarrif (FiT) model today. The second model is the true peer-to-peer model <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/10/24/electricity-ebay-our-future"><strong>[3]</strong></a> where all participants have equal status and can deal directly with each other for electricity buying and selling. In this case, transactions, pricing, and demand response capability in the smart grid are implemented via specialized software and hardware that enable this peer to peer relationship to exist. This model represents how eBay or the stock market or any peer-to-peer transactional network works today.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	There is an interesting pilot project called <strong>PowerMatchingCity</strong> <a href="http://www.ecn.nl/docs/library/report/2011/m11002.pdf"><strong>[4]</strong></a> in Netherlands that explores this very concept with the smart grid. Working on a cluster of 25 sample homes that are equipped with communication devices that help facilitate peer to peer electricity transactions, this pilot project makes use of a technology called PowerMatcher, a real time software that uses the concepts of Smart Agents to balance and get real-time quotes on electricity pricing that buyers and sellers can then negotiate upon and trade surplus electricity with each other.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">PowerMatcher uses the concepts of Agents to help facilitate prosumer electricity transactions in a decentralized manner </span><a href="http://www.powermatcher.net/get-technical/powermatcher-technology/basic-structure-and-agent-roles/" style="font-size: 12px;"><strong>[5]</strong></a><span style="font-size: 12px;">. The Auctioneer agent is the main entity responsible for the price forming process as it collects bids from buyers and prices from sellers. Concentrator agents represent other micro grids connections as a combined price-bid number to the concentrator agent.</span></p>\n<p>\n	A larger scale project called EcoGrid <a href="http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/"><strong>[6]</strong></a> has been implemented in Bornholm, a Danish island. This project covers about 28,000 customers and utilizes a peer to peer smart grid model that is based on 50% renewable mix. The results of this project <a href="http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/images/Documents/121218ecogrid%20eu%20-%20guide%20to%20the%20large-scale%20project_dec_update.pdf"><strong>[7]</strong></a> have been very positive in fine tuning algorithms to implement a functional peer to peer model and also in verifying grid stability – responses for smaller production/consumption units (micro grids) are much faster than traditional larger units.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt="ecogrid" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/149/500" width="500" /></p>\n<p>\n	The above figure is a representation of the EcoGrid microgrid implementation in Bornholm, taken from <a href="http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/images/Documents/121218ecogrid%20eu%20-%20guide%20to%20the%20large-scale%20project_dec_update.pdf"><strong>[7]</strong></a>.</p>\n<p>\n	As a second application of the Smart Grid, consider Sandy – the well-known U.S. “superstorm” of 2012 that was known to have wreaked havoc on the entire North Eastern U.S. Utility infrastructure. What is perhaps not that known is that during this outage a couple of Universities like Princeton and New York Universities that had implemented micro-grids interconnected to the traditional grid were able to isolate themselves and independently survive for a couple of days <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/12/05/how-microgrids-build-resiliency-extreme-weather"><strong>[8]</strong></a>. Similarly the 9.0 magnitude earthquake that hit Japan in 2011 allowed the Sendai 1 MW Microgrid <a href="http://systemstechnologies.wordpress.com/2011/11/12/a-microgrid-that-wouldn%E2%80%99t-quit/"><strong>[9]</strong></a> at Tohoku Fukushi University to isolate and operate independently for a couple of days during this time. Both of these events bear testimony to the fact that a transition to micro grids will allow larger clusters to go independent during times of emergency. Micro grids are today largely implemented by the military and universities, which is quite like the pattern of how the Internet started.</p>\n<p>\n	Some states like Connecticut today have started policy programs to support micro grids as responses to major storms and outages that have affected them. Internationally, some countries are also promoting micro grid growth in countries where grid reliability is poor. For example Greenpeace <a href="http://www.renewable-energy-technology.net/grid-storage/greenpeace-india-unveils-report-create-microgrids-network"><strong>[10]</strong></a> in India is extolling a bottoms-up distributed renewables strategy to export surplus solar energy via micro grids from the Indian state of Bihar. It is these countries that offer a very large market for micro grid growth and expansion. Another concept that is very applicable to developing nations is remote micro grids, or micro grids that operate when there is no utility grid. Such micro grids can serve as the baseline of a new scalable infrastructure that smartly delivers humanitarian services to the poor.</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>References:</strong></p>\n<p>\n	[1] - <a href="http://www.cnt.org/news/media/isgi-summary-of-benefits-and-issues-6-08.pdf">http://www.cnt.org/news/media/isgi-summary-of-benefits-and-issues-6-08.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	[2] - <a href="http://www.geni.org/globalenergy/library/technical-articles/transmission/green.venturebeat.com/how-microgrids-will-change-the-way/index.shtml">http://www.geni.org/globalenergy/library/technical-articles/transmission/green.venturebeat.com/how-microgrids-will-change-the-way/index.shtml</a></p>\n<p>\n	[3]- <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/10/24/electricity-ebay-our-future">http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/10/24/electricity-ebay-our-future</a></p>\n<p>\n	[4] - <a href="http://www.ecn.nl/docs/library/report/2011/m11002.pdf">http://www.ecn.nl/docs/library/report/2011/m11002.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	[5] - <a href="http://www.powermatcher.net/get-technical/powermatcher-technology/basic-structure-and-agent-roles/">http://www.powermatcher.net/get-technical/powermatcher-technology/basic-structure-and-agent-roles/</a></p>\n<p>\n	[6] - <a href="http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/">http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/</a></p>\n<p>\n	[7]- <a href="http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/images/Documents/121218ecogrid%20eu%20-%20guide%20to%20the%20large-scale%20project_dec_update.pdf">http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/images/Documents/121218ecogrid%20eu%20-%20guide%20to%20the%20large-scale%20project_dec_update.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	[8] - <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/12/05/how-microgrids-build-resiliency-extreme-weather">http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/12/05/how-microgrids-build-resiliency-extreme-weather</a></p>\n<p>\n	[9] - <a href="http://systemstechnologies.wordpress.com/2011/11/12/a-microgrid-that-wouldn%E2%80%99t-quit/">http://systemstechnologies.wordpress.com/2011/11/12/a-microgrid-that-wouldn%E2%80%99t-quit/</a></p>\n<p>\n	[10] - <a href="http://www.renewable-energy-technology.net/grid-storage/greenpeace-india-unveils-report-create-microgrids-network">http://www.renewable-energy-technology.net/grid-storage/greenpeace-india-unveils-report-create-microgrids-network</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1589, 'default', 143, '<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Adobe - Green Buildings and Sustainability Measures</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">Adobe has been innovating in the LEED green building movement for the past decade. It owns seven buildings in the U.S., all of which have achieved EPA Energy STAR label with an average rating of 99 out of a possible 100.Six of the seven buildings are LEED Platinum certified in the Existing Buildings category, while the seventh is LEED Platinum certified in the Commercial Interiors category.How has Adobe achieved and maintained this level of energy efficiency in its buildings? Described are some of the features that Adobe deploys for its green buildings, along with some key sustainability measures. <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/topics/energy/featured-case-studies/adobe-case-study-green-buildings">Read full Adobe Case Study here</a></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong style="font-size: 14px;">NetApp - Greening its Data Centers</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">In today’s world of high performance computing, servers and IT equipment are typically housed in data centers that are constantly consuming large amounts of electricity as they run in the background to provide processing power to companies. The high amounts of power consumed along with inefficiencies in data center designs leads to the overconsumption and the wastage of electricity as a resource.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">To address these issues, leading data storage and solutions providers like NetApp have deployed various measures that help reduce power consumption and increase data center efficiencies. Many of NetApp’s solutions for greening their data centers and achieving high energy efficiencies and lower Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE) have today become industry best practices in the quest for sustainability.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">How has NetApp achieved these low Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE) values in its data centers? What are some of the innovative features that are deployed to achieve high energy efficiencies in its data center operations? This case study from Sustainable Silicon Valley highlights NetApp’s solutions and best practices for achieving a high degree of efficiency in its data centers.&nbsp;<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/WBJi6nS9cs-sxYqZ9lrBJha7WOt17pv-KyNOHlloeruRPz5iRzUFbGLQ78*VclHbp0d2W5AQ5R7kQd9TeTllUYp-Gb4obIfj/NetAppCaseStudyMay2012bySSV.pdf" target="_self">Read full NetApp Case Study here</a></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Green Programs and Initiatives by eBay</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">Sustainability as a goal demands that we maintain our natural environment and create conditions that permit the fulfilling of social, economic and other requirements of present and future generations. To environmentalists all over the world this concept is well understood. But what does sustainability mean to large corporations?</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">To a company like eBay which facilitates online transaction of goods, sustainability means different things at different levels. At an operations and business model level, it means introducing green programs in its model of online trading, partnering with green companies and so forth. At an infrastructural level, it means making its data centers more efficient and optimizing its offices and facilities. At a corporate level, it means lending voice to green movements.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:12px;">How does eBay deploy strategies that help drive green programs in its operational, infrastructural and corporate levels? How does it blend these initiatives within its existing culture? This case study from Sustainable Silicon Valley holistically examines various methodologies that eBay has adopted which lead it on the path of sustainability.&nbsp;<a href="http://api.ning.com:80/files/ywlhRv3zJjuGCfQGdjeVOqZGLMWqzagnOkoB2nBnNdaJ7Y5PXqpQLHyMUOuRMtHs4f8SKCf7w6klrYdyEk-XFRImXlX2wx6x/eBayCaseStudyJune2012bySSV.pdf" target="_self">Read full eBay case study here</a></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1590, 'default', 141, '<p style="">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>LEDs vs. Florescent vs. Incandescent Lighting </strong></span></p>\n<p style="">\n	<strong>By Daniel Degu</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Background</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">Texas Instruments, General Electric, Monsanto, and Hewlett Packard all played a significant role in the evolution of LEDs—light-emitting diodes. Commercialized during the 1960’s, LEDs have the ability to revolutionize the efficiency, appearance, and quality of lighting.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">LEDs proved a powerful but limited light source that seemed destined to remain the go to lighting source for niche applications such as traffic lights, exit signs, car brake lights and dashboard displays for the next several decades. But thanks to rapid evolution of these highly efficient, long lasting powerhouses in the past decade, LEDs are now providing quality white light while significantly reducing commercial and residential energy consumption, operating expenses and maintenance costs and concerns (</span><a href="http://www.jpm-digital.org/jpm/20121112#pg32" style="font-size: 12px;">Bloom, 2012</a><span style="font-size: 12px;">).</span></p>\n<p>\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Checking The Facts</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">The </span><a href="http://energy.gov/sites/prod/files/guide_to_energy_efficient_lighting.pdf" style="font-size: 12px;">U.S. Department of Energy</a><span style="font-size: 12px;"> estimates that rapid adoption of LED lighting in the U.S. by 2027 could:</span></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Deliver savings of about $265 billion.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Avoid 40 new power plants.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduce lighting electricity demand by 33% in 2027.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Drive 190 terawatt-hours of electricity savings per year</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">According to market research firm </span><a href="http://www.strategies-u.com/articles/2012/06/the-worldwide-market-for-leds-market-review-and-forecast-2012.html" style="font-size: 12px;">Strategies</a><span style="font-size: 12px;"> </span><a href="http://www.strategies-u.com/articles/reports/high-brightness-led2.html" style="font-size: 12px;">Unlimited</a><span style="font-size: 12px;">:</span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:39.0pt;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LED sales are projected to grow from $340 million in 2007 to $7.3 billion by 2014 – 44% increase.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:39.0pt;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The worldwide high-brightness LED market grew from $11.3 billion in 2010 to $12.5 billion in 2011 – 9.8% increase.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:39.0pt;">\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Approximately 50% of smartphone displays are expected to be OLEDs (Organic LEDs) by 2016.</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt="Flo-vs-LED" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/large/150" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>What Does This Mean?</strong></p>\n<p>\n	That''s roughly the annual output of 24 large power plants, or enough electricity to light 95 million homes, representing $15 billion in cost savings annually by 2030, as well as the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 246 million metric tons of carbon between now and 2030 (<a href="http://www.jpm-digital.org/jpm/20121112#pg32">Bloom, 2012</a>).</p>\n<p>\n	LEDs are as much as 80 percent more energy-efficient than the incandescent, halogen, fluorescent and high intensity discharge light sources they replace. In general, the LED lights offer a much longer life than the compact fluorescent lamps (CFLs). They can last up to 10 times longer than CFL and 60 times longer than incandescent lamps. Sporting long, 25,000- to 50,000-hour life spans, compositions free of hazardous materials such as lead or mercury, and offering durable and reliable operation. On average, CFLs— compact fluorescent lights— normally contain about five milligrams of mercury. If not discarded properly, the mercury could lead to water contamination (<a href="http://www.greenzer.com/face-off_5">Greenzer, 2009</a>).</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Incandescent vs. CFLs vs. LEDs. </strong></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">LEDs emit light in a specific direction, whereas an incandescent or fluorescent bulb emits light — and heat — in all directions. For direct lighting applications LED lighting uses both light and energy more efficiently.</span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<img alt="Incan-vs-CFL-vs-LED" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/large/151" /></p>\n<p>\n	Source: <a href="http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?c=lighting.pr_what_are">Energy Star: Learn about LEDs</a></p>\n<p>\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Case Studies</strong></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Please click the following links for reading more on the case studies.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37283">Bournemouth Airport to save 72% on car park lighting costs by switching to LED</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	<a href="http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37283"><img alt="Bouremouth-airport" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/152/350" width="350" /></a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37058">Target Signs converts six billboards to digital with Watchfire Digital Outdoor</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	<img alt="target-signs" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/153/250" width="250" /></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37059"> Spark solar-wind hybrid LED street light SPL-96 project in Russia</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.25in;">\n	<img alt="spark-solar-hybrid-led" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/154/250" width="250" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Conclusion</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">If the environment alone is not a good enough reason to change ones way of life, in terms of energy consumption, it is important to know that upgrading to LEDs helps companies and consumers economically and environmentally. While fluorescent lights have been reliable in the past, today LEDs remain the future of indoor and outdoor lighting.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">References</strong></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">Bloom (2012). Bright light of the future: LEDs take new focus.&nbsp;</span><span style="font-size: 12px;">Retrieved from http://www.jpm-digital.org/jpm/20121112#pg32</span></p>\n<p>\n	Department of Energy (2010). Guide to Energy Efficient Lighting. Retrieved from http://energy.gov/sites/prod/files/guide_to_energy_efficient_lighting.pdf.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">Energy Star (2012). Learn about LEDs. Retrieved from </span><a href="http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?c=lighting.pr_what_are" style="font-size: 12px;">http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?c=lighting.pr_what_are</a><span style="font-size: 12px;">.</span></p>\n<p>\n	Greenzer. (2009). Green face-off: CFL vs LED. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.greenzer.com/face-off_5">http://www.greenzer.com/face-off_5</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">LEDs Magazine (2012). Spark solar-wind hybrid LED street light SPL-96 project in Russia. Retrieved from </span><a href="http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37059" style="font-size: 12px;">http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37059</a><span style="font-size: 12px;">.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">LEDs Magazine (2012). Target Signs converts six billboards to digital with Watchfire</span></p>\n<p>\n	Digital Outdoor. Retrieved from <a href="http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37058">http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37058</a>.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">LEDs Magazine (2013). Bournemouth Airport to save 72% on car park lighting costs by switching to LED. Retrieved from http://ledsmagazine.com/casestudies/37283.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">Strategies Unlimited (2010). The Market for High-Brightness LEDs in Lighting Applications 2010. Retrieved from </span><a href="http://www.strategies-u.com/articles/reports/high-brightness-led2.html" style="font-size: 12px;">http://www.strategies-u.com/articles/reports/high-brightness-led2.html</a><span style="font-size: 12px;">.</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">Strategies Unlimited (2012). The Worldwide Market for LEDs Market Review and Forecast 2012. Retrieved from </span><a href="http://www.strategies-u.com/articles/2012/06/the-worldwide-market-for-leds-market-review-and-forecast-2012.html" style="font-size: 12px;">http://www.strategies-u.com/articles/2012/06/the-worldwide-market-for-leds-market-review-and-forecast-2012.html</a><span style="font-size: 12px;">.</span></p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, '');
