(1591, 'default', 21, '<table border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="15" width="100%">\n	<tbody>\n		<tr>\n			<td style="vertical-align: top;">\n				<h2>\n					SSV Vision &amp; Mission</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" height="172" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td style="vertical-align: top;">\n								<img class="ajT" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/u/1/images/cleardot.gif" /><strong>Vision:</strong>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">Sustainable Silicon Valley (SSV) envisions a healthy environment, a vibrant economy and a socially equitable community, in our region and throughout the world.</span></p>\n								<p>\n									<strong>Mission:</strong><br />\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">As a consortium of companies, governmental entities, academic and research institutions and non-profit organizations, we work together to achieve this vision through collaboration and innovation, bringing solutions from Silicon Valley’s inventors, entrepreneurs and enterprises to solve problems and create resilience in our region and in regions around the world.</span></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<h2>\n					<br />\n					SSV Board, Staff and Volunteer</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" height="70" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									SSV is a non-profit organization. It consists of <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/content/ssv-board-advisory-council" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">SSV Board &amp; Advisory Council</a>, <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/content/ssv-staff-and-volunteers" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">staff and volunteers</a>.</p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<h2>\n					<br />\n					EcoCloud</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" height="112" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									A project of Sustainable Silicon Valley (SSV) in conjunction with public and private sector partners, EcoCloud is a virtual space where you can connect with Silicon Valley business leaders, industry experts, researchers and policy makers--striving to make our enterprises and our region more ecologically, equitably, and economically sustainable.</p>\n								<p>\n									See here for <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/about-ecocloud">details.</a></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<h2>\n					<br />\n					EcoCloud Members</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" height="117" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php//register"><img alt="joinecocloud" class="right" height="31" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/43/0" width="106" /></a>EcoCoud community is open to anyone interested in sustainability. Its members mainly come from individual members and institutional partners.</p>\n								<p>\n									See here for <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/participants" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">member details.</a></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n			<td style="vertical-align: top;">\n				<h2>\n					How To Use The Site</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">Welcome to EcoCloud™! We hope you will enjoy exploring this site and collaborating with other EcoCloud™ members. Before you start, please be sure to read the <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/terms-of-use">Terms of Use</a>, and to ensure harmonious relationships with other EcoCloud™ members, take a look at our <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/behavior-guidelines" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">Behavior Guidelines.</a></span></p>\n								<p>\n									&nbsp;</p>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">More details can be found <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/how-to-use-the-site" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">here</a>.</span></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<h2>\n					<br />\n					Terms Of Use</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" height="154" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">All members of this site agree to the terms of use set forth in this page, in addition to the Terms of Service available through the link in the webpage footer.</span></p>\n								<p>\n									&nbsp;</p>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">All members are encouraged to use basic courtesy and best practices as described in <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/behavior-guidelines" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">Behavior Guidelines.</a> Failure to do so can result in remedial action at the discretion of the site moderators, up to and including cancellation of site membership.</span></p>\n								<p>\n									&nbsp;</p>\n								<p>\n									For more, please see <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/terms-of-use">details here</a>.</p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<p>\n					&nbsp;</p>\n				<h2>\n					Behavior Guidelines</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">EcoCloud™ serves the sustainability community by providing a respectful venue for communication and collaboration. The site should improve communications, foster involvement, and help further sustainability goals in Silicon Valley. The tone of discussion is intended to be professional and helpful. EcoCloud™ provides a venue for sharing news, providing thought leadership, collaborating on projects, and sending inquiries to other members of the community.</span></p>\n								<p>\n									&nbsp;</p>\n								<p>\n									<span style="font-size:12px;">The members of EcoCloud™ are our greatest asset and must be treated with respect. Site members should work together to maintain a high level of value and ensure that participation is rewarding and satisfying for all members. Toward that end, EcoCloud™ members are encouraged to use the following guidelines: <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/behavior-guidelines" onclick="window.open(this.href, '''', ''width=1000,height=600,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=no,dependent=no''); return false;">more ...</a></span></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n				<p>\n					&nbsp;</p>\n				<h2>\n					Contact Us</h2>\n				<table bgcolor="#eeeeee" border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="1" height="118" width="470">\n					<tbody>\n						<tr>\n							<td>\n								<p>\n									<span class="font-size-2"><strong><span style="font-family: verdana,geneva;">We want to hear from you!</span></strong></span></p>\n								<p>\n									<a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/administrative/contact-us"><img alt="contact" class="right" height="31" src="{{ url:site }}files/thumb/44/0" width="67" /></a><span class="font-size-2" style="font-family: verdana,geneva;">Please <a href="http://www.sustainablesv.org/ecocloud/index.php/administrative/contact-us">contact us</a> for more information about how to participate in EcoCloud™ in order to help your organization and the entire Bay Area region become more sustainable. </span></p>\n							</td>\n						</tr>\n					</tbody>\n				</table>\n			</td>\n		</tr>\n	</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1650, 'default', 22, '<div id="xf_navigation">\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<h4 style="text-align: -webkit-auto; margin-top: 7px; font-size: 12pt; ">\n	<em>Welcome to the materials page. &nbsp;<span style="font-size: 12pt; ">Our goal is to connect you with the knowledge &amp; resources you need to develop sustainable practices in your materials management. &nbsp;We are working to compile the best information available and describe our findings. &nbsp;Allowing you to focus on implementing the changes that will move your business, local government agency or community organization forward. &nbsp;</span></em></h4>\n<h2>\n	How our site works</h2>\n<h4>\n	Our team constantly researches topics regarding sustainable materials management giving you a head start in implementing change</h4>\n<h4>\n	We have organized our research into 6 sections to clarify our findings</h4>\n<h4>\n	The site is collaborative, we look forward to your questions and constructive feedback to increase the site''s effectiveness</h4>\n<h4>\n	Each section includes</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<h4>\n			core knowledge&nbsp;explaining fundamental principles&nbsp;</h4>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<h4>\n			success stories to inspire and foster innovation&nbsp;</h4>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<h4>\n			tools to help you get the job done&nbsp;</h4>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<h4>\n			news &amp; developments so you stay in the loop</h4>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>\n	&nbsp;</h2>\n<h2>\n	By reaching this site you are taking an important step towards sutainability. Just incase you need a little more of a push, here is a quick run down of reasons why you will want to move forward to develop a better understanding of your materials and processes.&nbsp;</h2>\n<h3 style="text-align: left; ">\n	&nbsp;</h3>\n<h3>\n	Save money&nbsp;</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		More than $231 million back into Walmart U.S. in 2011 by increaseing recycling revenue and decreasing disposal expenses</li>\n	<li>\n		Research by consultancy McKinsey, found European manufacturers could save $630 billion a year by 2025 if they moved towards greater resource efficiency and reduced their reliance on increasingly rare and costly raw materials</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	Reduce Green House Gas Emmissions</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Safeway prevents the release of 37,518 metric tons of CO<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;in 2011 by shipping produce items from warehouses to stores in reusable plastic containers instead of cardboard boxes</li>\n	<li>\n		Apple reduced its iPhone packaging by 42%, allowing them to fit 80% more product into each airline shipping container to reduce air transportation</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	Brand Image &amp; Coporate Responsibility</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		method ranked as the 7th fastest growing company in America by INC. 500 in 2006. &nbsp;Also one of the first companies to be cradle to cradle certified in 2009 with 37 certified products at launch. &nbsp;Coincidence?</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	Adapting to Legislation</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		AB341 to reduce GHG emissions by diverting commercial solid waste to recycling efforts and to expand the opportunity for additional recycling services and recycling manufacturing facilities in California</li>\n	<li>\n		EPA workgroup writes paper "Sustainable Materials Management: The Road Ahead," presenting their ideas to move future legislation towards accelerating a life-cycle consideration of materials and more producer responsibility</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div style="margin-top: 7px; font-size: 12pt; text-align: center; ">\n	<img alt="Materials Flow Cycle" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/large/145" /></div>\n<div style="float: left; margin: 7px;">\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div id="page_note">\n	<p>\n		&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, 'default'),
(1653, 'default', 129, '<p>\n	Gamification is a fun and competitive approach to engage users and solve problems. Gamification uses game-thinking and game mechanics such as points, badges, challenge levels, rewards and leaderboards to incentivize. Green gamification is one method to engage and motivate others and employees in corporate sustainability efforts. Many gamification strategies utilize the social web to calculate metrics, like household energy use, and reward users for their relative performance. &nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Gamification Websites and Applications:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.practicallygreen.com/">Practically Green</a>: Putting your green actions to work can be tracked and automatically estimated showing your impact and savings accompanied by a score. Using a dashboard, your points are accrued and you can move up in Green level.</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="https://www.myenergy.com/">My Energy</a>: Understand your power bill and compare it with similar homes, friends and neighbors</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="https://leafully.com/">Leafully</a>: The activities on Leafully help you save energy and show you how much you are giving back to the environment.</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="http://www.greenisuniversal.com/play/one-small-act/">One Small Act</a>: An app that gives suggestions of small, eco-friendly actions that a user can set goals and track their progress with points.</li>\n	<li>\n		<a href="https://www.beeminder.com/">Beeminder</a>: Commit to a goal with a money pledge and track your progress using a yellow brick road feature. If you go off track, your pledged money stays with the company.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>Presentations: How is It and How it Works</strong></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		SSV: Gamification</li>\n	<li>\n		SSV: Increasing Participation</li>\n</ul>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1654, 'default', 142, '<h1>\n	Residential Solar Systems: where do we stand?</h1>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">By Lise Bilhaut</span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">I recently attended a presentation by Rick Devlin, from SunStar Energy Inc, and organized by the Humanist Community in Silicon Valley on December 9</span><sup>th</sup><span style="font-size: 12px;">, 2012. The presentation, entitled "Solar Power in California" targeted individuals interested in installing a PV system on their roofs. Because of the rapid evolution of costs and regulation of PV, it was very useful to be given current information and numbers regarding those small residential systems. Here is a brief summary:</span></p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Having a PV system makes sense if:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">\n		your <strong>residential electricity bill is more than $80/month</strong> (or your total consumption is above 6000 kWh per year [<a href="#_ftn1" name="_ftnref1" title="">[1]</a>])</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">\n		you have <strong>at least 6 hours of direct sunlight per day</strong> on your roof. The best orientation in California is SSW, but other orientations are worth to consider.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Several incentives and credits are currently in use:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">\n		Federal Investment Tax Credit : 30% off the full system (the same applies for business with the advantage of accelerated depreciation)</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">\n		The California solar initiative gives a rebate of $200/kW [<a href="#_ftn2" name="_ftnref2" title="">[2]</a>]. "PG&amp;E targets to have 764.8 MW of solar generating capacity by 2016 on January 9th 2013, the target has been completed at 95%, with a total amount of 727.6 MW" [<a href="#_ftn3" name="_ftnref3" title="">[3]</a>]!</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Typically, for a <strong>5 kW AC residential system, the cost is $14,700 net after the rebate and tax credit</strong> (for a $22,000 initial cost).</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Unfortunately, <strong>the regulation in place doesn''t encourage over-producing, since PG&amp;E pays very little for excess electricity</strong> (3-4 cent/kWh). Right now, a good installer will dimension your system so it compensates your electricity consumption over a year.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Solar is highly leveraged in PG&amp;E territory</strong> [<a href="#_ftn4" name="_ftnref4" title="">[4]</a>] for two reasons:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">\n		The residential tiered usage, which means the more power you use, the more it costs you (from 12 c/kWh up to 34 c/kWh) [<a href="#_ftn5" name="_ftnref5" title="">[5]</a>]</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 40px;">\n		The Time-of-Use rate, by which PG&amp;E credits more during afternoons, which is when solar produces most (the summer baseline peak rate is $29c/kWh whereas the off-peak rate is only $10c/kWh)[<a href="#_ftn6" name="_ftnref6" title="">[6]</a>].</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	During the discussion, other interesting points were raised by Rick Devlin and other presentation attendees:</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; We need to realize <strong>grid parity has been reached</strong>, and apparently has been reached for 10 years in California.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; People are not aware that the <strong>cost of PV panels dropped by 25% over the last 5 years</strong>. Although SolarWorld won its case [<a href="#_ftn7" name="_ftnref7" title="">[7]</a>], this doesn''t necessarily mean that the cost of PV panels is going up.</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Following the high profile failure of Solyndra, a lot has been said about subsidies to renewable energy and solar energy in particular. However, as shown by a report from Environmental Law Institute, <strong>government subsidies are five times higher for fossil fuel than renewable energy!</strong> [<a href="#_ftn8" name="_ftnref8" title="">[8]</a>]</p>\n<p>\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The cost of electricity will rise - the historical trend being above 4% per year [<a href="#_ftn9" name="_ftnref9" title="">[9]</a>]. <strong>A PV system, once installed, is a very safe investment, with very little risk and low maintenance cost</strong>.</p>\n<p>\n	For my part, I would like to see some federal or state regulation to stimulate photovoltaic electricity over-production. Furthermore, we should never forget that <strong>the cleanest (and cheapest!) energy is the one that you don''t spend</strong>: if you have a bill of $200/month, the first step would be to reflect on your consumption and see if it could be reduced!</p>\n<p>\n	<strong>References:</strong></p>\n<div>\n	<div id="ftn1">\n		<p>\n			[[1]] http://sunstarenergy.com/Issolar.html</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn2">\n		<p>\n			[[2]]see here (http://www.gosolarcalifornia.ca.gov/csi/rebates.php ) for the current applicable rebate level</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn3">\n		<p>\n			[[3]] http://www.pge.com/myhome/saveenergymoney/solarenergy/csi/csiprogramstatistics/index.shtml</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn4">\n		<p>\n			[[4]] contrary to the area under the City of Palo Alto Utilities, which offers cheaper rates</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn5">\n		<p>\n			[[5]] http://pge.com/</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn6">\n		<p>\n			[[6]] http://www.pge.com/tariffs/tm2/pdf/ELEC_SCHEDS_E-6.pdf</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn7">\n		<p>\n			[[7]] http://www.forbes.com/sites/toddwoody/2012/10/10/u-s-hits-chinese-solar-manufacturers-with-higher-tariffs/</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn8">\n		<p>\n			[[8]]"Subsidies to fossil fuels [...] totaled approximately $72 billion over the [2002-2008] period, representing a direct cost to taxpayers. Subsidies for renewable fuels, a relatively young and developing industry, totaled $29 billion over the same period. Almost half of the subsidies for renewables are attributable to corn-based ethanol, the use of which, while decreasing American reliance on foreign oil, raises considerable questions about effects on climate." on page 3 of the report (http://www.elistore.org/Data/products/d19_07.pdf)</p>\n	</div>\n	<div id="ftn9">\n		<p>\n			[[9]] http://www.lee.org/blog/2008/07/23/historical-electric-rates/</p>\n	</div>\n</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1673, 'default', 146, '<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<h1>\n	<span style="font-size:28px;">Transformational Results From Using Integrated Reporting</span></h1>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<div>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">With the recent update of SAP’s preliminary <a href="http://www.sapsustainabilityreport.com/quarterly-update" style="font-size: 16px;">sustainability results for 2012</a> and the impending release of their first ever Integrated Report&nbsp;for 2012,&nbsp;we sat down to speak with SAP’s Chief Sustainability Officer Dr. Peter Graf. Dr. Graf talks about how <strong>Integrated Reporting</strong></span><span style="font-size: 14px;">&nbsp;</span><strong style="font-size: 14px;"><a href="http://www.theiirc.org/">&lt;IR&gt;</a></strong><span style="font-size: 14px;">&nbsp;is transformational in driving integrated thinking not only for the company’s sustainability strategy but also for the overall corporate strategy. From his experience, he believes &lt;IR&gt;</span><span style="font-size: 14px;">&nbsp;is important for any company interested in driving sustainability into the heart of their business.</span></div>\n<p>\n	<img alt="Peter Graf" class="pyro-image alignment-none" src="{{ url:site }}files/large/171" style="float: left; margin: 10px;" /></p>\n<p>\n	<strong>What would you like to tell us about &lt;IR&gt; and SAP’s sustainability strategy?</strong></p>\n<div>\n	<strong>Peter Graf</strong>: Integrated Reporting &lt;IR&gt; needs to be seen as part of the wider strategy that SAP had embarked on when we made sustainability a strategic priority to the business back in 2009. At that point, we had separate strategies: A sustainability strategy, a product strategy, a go-to-market strategy, a people strategy, etc. It became clear that even if we executed our sustainability strategy very successfully we would still only represent one of the many different aspects of the business competing for attention from our senior management.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	So when the &lt;IR&gt; initiative started with the IIRC, we initially thought that an integrated report would be a great way to describe an integrated strategy -- once you have one. In other words, our belief was that we first had to put a lot of work into getting everyone on board and only then be able to articulate an integrated strategy, which would eventually lead to an integrated report.. We then recognized that we were wrong.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>How it works:</strong></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>PG:</strong>&nbsp;An integrated report combines elements of what you would put into an annual report with things you would put into a sustainability report. This combination is more than just the sum of the data in both reports: The real value of an integrated report is to actually explain the interdependencies between your financial performance indicators and your non-financial performance indicators.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	Toward the middle of 2012, while talking to people who actually engage in &lt;IR&gt;,I learned that one shouldn’t wait until everyone is convinced of an integrated strategy that would flow into an integrated report. Instead, we recognized that the creation of the integrated report itself is the required catalyst to drive integrated thinking and an integrated strategy. That was an extremely valuable recognition.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Looking forward:</strong></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>PG:</strong>&nbsp;We are currently in the final preparations of our integrated report for 2012 which will be our first time ever. The expectations are high because SAP has always had so much recognition for its sustainability reports in the past. Our report has been acknowledged by readers at many different publications and we’ve received many awards as one of the top sustainability reports in the world. So we hope many people will take a look at our integrated report as well.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Impact of &lt;IR&gt; within the company:</strong></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>PG:&nbsp;</strong>The experience of creating an integrated report leads to a whole variety of different conversations throughout the company. In line with what &lt;IR&gt; is about, those conversations were about the long-term view of the business and how practicing sustainability and related non-financial indicators actually help us understand how we can be more financially successful in the future. This led to conversations with our investor relations team, with our finance and administration organizations, with HR and many other teams – conversations on a very different and more strategic level.</div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>Recommendation for businesses setting up a sustainability strategy:</strong></div>\n<div>\n	&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	<strong>PG:</strong> I would recommend to anybody trying to move from having a sustainability strategy to a more sustainable corporate strategy to consider using the creation of an integrated report as the catalyst to drive integrated thinking. In other words, even if you don’t think your company is ready for an integrated report yet, I’d rather try it sooner than later because of the level of strategic engagement integrated reporting produces within your organization.</div>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	(<em>This interview has been edited to group together but is otherwise as-told-to Aswathy Dayanand</em>)</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1674, 'd1abb', 146, '<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:20px;">You might also want to read :</span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.theiirc.org/">What is IIRC and &nbsp;&lt;Integrated Reporting&gt;?</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="https://www.globalreporting.org/Pages/default.aspx">What is Global Reporting Initiative?</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.coca-colacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/downloads/2012-sustainability-report.pdf">Coca-Cola 2011/2012 GRI Report</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.microsoft.com/about/corporatecitizenship/en-us/reporting/key-performance-indicators/">Microsoft and GRI</a></p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 2, ''),
(1684, 'default', 148, '<p align="center">\n	<strong style="font-size: 18px; ">Cisco Sustainability Review</strong></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Introduction</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Founded in 1984, Cisco designs and sells networking solutions related to the information and communication technology industry to public sector organizations, enterprise business, commercial customers, and consumers. Cisco’s headquarters are located in San Jose, California and they have more than 475 offices in more than 165 countries and more than 66,000 employees globally. They state their mission as “To shape the future of the internet by creating unprecedented value and opportunity for customers, employees, investors, and partners.”&nbsp;&nbsp; They apply their goal of innovation and their mission to their sustainable practices and goals as well.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Awards, Listings, and Frameworks</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Awards and Recognitions</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012: Cool IT Challenge (#2), Greenpeace International</li>\n	<li>\n		2012: Best Corporate Citizenship Award to Cisco China, 21<sup>st</sup> Century Business Herald</li>\n	<li>\n		2012: Outstanding Corporate Citizenship Award to Cisco China, China Philanthropy Times under the Minister of Civil Affairs</li>\n	<li>\n		2012: Outstanding CSR Case Studies Award to Cisco China, China Philanthropy Times under the Minister of Civil Affairs</li>\n	<li>\n		2012: Outstanding Corporate Leader of 2012, Sustainability Roundtable, Inc.</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>January 2011</u>: Green Business Award, Cisco Lawrenceville, Gwinnett Clean and Beautiful</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2011:</u> Silver “Green Binnie” Award, Cisco Boxborough, MassRecycle</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Best Green Business Award, Gwinnett County</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Greater Austin Business Award, for environmental responsibility, Austin Texas Chamber of Commerce</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Best Green PR Campaign, PR News, Cisco Canada</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Outstanding waste reduction efforts recognition, California Waste Reduction Awards Program (WRAP)</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Silicon Valley Water Conservation Award, California</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Gold LEED Certification, Cisco Building 14, Bangalore, India</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Buildy Award, for smart building and connected infrastructure innovations,&nbsp;BuilConn</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Best of Interop Green Award, for Cisco Energywise, Las Vegas Interop and Best of Interop Japan &nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Gold Quill Award, for video series that inspired employees to think and act in environmentally sustainable ways, International Association of Business Communicators.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Rankings</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<u>2012: 50 Best Green Global Brands (#11), Interbrand</u></li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2012: World’s Most Ethical Companies, Ethisphere Institute</u></li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2012: Gartner Supply Chain 25 (#8), Gartner</u></li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2011:</u> America''s Top 10 Greenest Companies&nbsp;(#8), Forbes</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: One of America’s 10 Greenest Companies, Forbes</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Green Power Purchasers (#6), US EPA List</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Listings</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<u>2012: Dow Jones Sustainability World and North America Indices, Dow Jones and SAM</u></li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2012: FTSE4Good Index Series, FTSE International and Ethical Research Services</u></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Frameworks</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012: Global Reporting Initiative</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2012</u>: Carbon Disclosure Project, Carbon Performance Leadership Index (CPLI)</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: Clinton Global Initiative</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: UN Global Compact</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: UN Millennium Development Goals</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>2010</u>: World Economic Forum</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainable Actions</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Biodiversity/Site</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Cisco built new green data centers in the Research Triangle Park, North Carolina in early FY 2012</li>\n	<li>\n		By the end of FY 2012, 26 Cisco facilities had LEED certifications (17 are Gold or Platinum status)</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco developed the “Cisco Connected Workplace”, a new space organization with mobile desktops to prevent the use of fix cubicles, which are vacant 35% of the time at Cisco. In a “Cisco Connected Workplace”, 140 employees work comfortably where 88 would work in a traditional workplace design. The goal is to improve productivity, employee satisfaction, increase user density in the building, and save real estate costs\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				By the end of FY12, Cisco Connected Workplace represented 19.5% of Cisco’s Total Office Space.</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has a 20.4 acre parcel of land that is a protected habitat for the burrowing owl and a rare plant species (Congdon’s Tarplant)\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Cisco developed and implemented a wetland migration plan that created 0.77 acres of wetlands in the habitat preserve area and established a 5-year monitoring and maintenance program</li>\n			<li>\n				Implementing a burrowing owl mitigation plan that required preconstruction surveys and the installation of 12 artificial burrows in the habitat preserve\n				<ul>\n					<li>\n						Locating grazing cattle in this habitat preserve as a method of weed abatement and soil compaction to help facilitate wetlands establishment.</li>\n				</ul>\n			</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Partnered with Bon Appétit Management Company as their “Farm to Fork” program promotes local farming and supports sustainable farming and harvesting techniques</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Water</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Cisco uses irrigation controllers at San Jose main campus, recycled water for irrigation, installed variable-frequency drives in their cooling towers and two way valves for bathroom fixtures, converted decorative fountains into landscaped beds for drought-resistant plants, utilized a water harvesting system at their Bangalore, India campus to capture rainwater for filtering and use, and replaced turf with planter beds that require little water</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY12 Cisco integrated a new Sustainability Information System that greatly improved their ability to track water consumption data for a majority of their real estate operations.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				In FY 2012, Cisco was able to collect water use data for 71% of their total real estate portfolio by area</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Energy</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		100% of Cisco’s contract manufacturers, 93% of global transport providers, and 80% of their component suppliers responded to the CDP 2012 survey</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco is phasing into the SIS (sustainability information system) and has incorporated Source 1 and Source 2 data and anticipates adding Scope 3 in the next phase</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has designed a way to use a company network as a center for energy intelligence: the Cisco EnergyWise System. Cisco has installed over 5,000 EnergyWise compliant power distribution units and has identified over $5 million energy savings potential</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco’s average (gross) electricity emission factor for both its global facilities and data centers are 14% and 15% lower than the global average, respectively\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Due to the fact that Cisco has located the majority of its facilities in grid locations where low-carbon to no-carbon grid electricity is available</li>\n			<li>\n				Through their energy reduction strategy Cisco estimates that in FY 2012 they conserved around 15.6 million kWh of energy and avoided 7,300 metric ton CO2 emissions through a $1.6 million investment in energy conservation projects</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY 2011 and 2012 Cisco installed solar PV systems at two data centers\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				These systems produced 270,000 kWh of electricity, saved Cisco $16,000 and avoided 170 metric ton of CO2e of GHG emissions</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY 2012, Cisco purchased 457 million kWh of Renewable Energy Certificates (RECs) by Green-e and 94 million kWh through various European green power suppliers</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco is working to get its most efficient products qualified with the U.S. EPA Energy Star program</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY12, started a project to install a 425 kW cogeneration system on its campus in Bedfront Lakes, UK.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				System is expected to reduce GHG emissions by more than 704 metric tonne of CO2 per year</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco Green Data Center – Allen, Texas\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Uninterruptable power supply (UPS) room uses rotary flywheels, which require little energy to be kept in motion</li>\n			<li>\n				Cooled by an air-side economizer design that reduces the need for mechanical chilling by using ambient air when the outside temperature is low</li>\n			<li>\n				A lagoon captures water to irrigate the drought-resistant landscape plants</li>\n			<li>\n				Solar cells on the roof generate 100 kW of power for the office spaces in the building</li>\n			<li>\n				LEED Gold certification renewed in FY 2012</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco Green Data Center, Research Triangle Park, North Carolina\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Select Features: Chimney rack hot-air isolation for improved cooling efficiency, 100kW solar photovoltaic cells on building roof, LED exterior lighting, reclaimed water use in cooling towers, occupancy sensors integrated with lighting and temperature controls, and landfill diversion during construction.</li>\n			<li>\n				Designed to achieve a Power Usage Effectiveness of 1.35 at full load</li>\n			<li>\n				Achieved a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) – NC Gold Certification</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco’s Bangalore data center has received one of the highest-rated Platinum LEED ID+C scores in the world (96 points)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Materials</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Deployed sustainability criteria in business scorecards for all contract manufacturers, logistic partners, and preferred component suppliers</li>\n	<li>\n		Provide sustainability training to supplier-facing employees</li>\n	<li>\n		Most of their documentation vendors are Forest Stewardship Council certified</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco connects customers with their take-back suppliers who bring trade-in products back to Cisco where they can be refurbished, resold, or reused if possible</li>\n	<li>\n		More than 99% of the electronics sent to their e-scrap recyclers are recycled</li>\n	<li>\n		In their packaging initiatives, Cisco reduced 757,000 pounds of paper and plastic usage and increased the overall packaging efficiency rates for some of their Catalyst 3750 products by 6.7%\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				In total, reduced 466 metric ton of corrugated cardboard, plastic, and paper in their shipment in FY 2012</li>\n			<li>\n				Cisco products use recyclable polyethylene bags for protection and accessory kits subassembly consolidation</li>\n			<li>\n				All mechanical parts greater than 100 grams are made of one material, for ease of separation later on</li>\n			<li>\n				Plastic parts greater than 25 grams are designed with material coding so they can be easily identified at the recycler</li>\n			<li>\n				All plastic parts are free of metal inlays and can be separated with common tools, improving recyclability.</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco Technical Migration and Exceptional Pick-Up Program: Cisco has trade-in programs where customers can bring back used technology to Cisco and will receive a discount on their new purchases in return\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Customer can set up appointment with Cisco to have their old electronics picked up for recycling/reuse&nbsp;</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY 2012, Cisco reused over $286 million of Cisco equipment, calculated at standard cost</li>\n	<li>\n		Take-Back and Recycle program focuses on Cisco products that do not qualify for a trade-in program. Cisco also takes back competitor equipment that consumers have replaced with new Cisco products\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				These objects go to a Cisco-approved recycling site</li>\n			<li>\n				Cisco tries to use an “eco-pack” packaging solution for high-volume products that has been shown to reduce total packaging weight by up to 2% compared to single-packaging option, which makes a difference on high volume shipments</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has an internal waste program, eBin/Lab Scrap Program, at the San Jose campus\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				eBins’s are plastic rolling bins provided to employees in their lab where materials are collected for recycling.&nbsp; The employee makes an appointment with the recycler to have the waste picked up in exchange for a new bin</li>\n			<li>\n				Cisco Data Center Server Recycling Program serves data centers in 12 countries, when data is no longer needed at one center it is offered to other Cisco data centers for possible reuse</li>\n			<li>\n				San Jose campus diverted 713 metric tons of food waste that would have been sent to a landfill in FY 2012</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Transportation</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Cisco encourages employees to use mass transit systems by allowing eligible employees to use pre-tax money to purchase their mass-transit passes</li>\n	<li>\n		By the end of 2011, Cisco had installed 23 EV charging stations</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco is working towards replacing physical travel by using Cisco remote collaboration products such as TelePresence, WebEx, and MeetingPlace\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Worldwide use of TelePresence has stayed steady at just under 50% based on an 8-hour day</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY 2012, air-travel emissions have dropped more than 30% compared to FY 2007</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has contributed towards saving 4415 gallons of fuel, $11,204 in fuel costs, and 23,622 pounds of CO2e in GHG emissions as a result of their EV stations</li>\n	<li>\n		In FY 2012, Cisco started a bike-sharing program at its Research Triangle Park location, North Carolina</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has provided employees with products such as Remote Collaboration and Cisco Virtual Office in order to reduce the amount of commuting they do</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Partnerships Around Sustainability</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Planet Skin Institute (Cisco and NASA)\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Global non-profit research and development organization that aims to improve the lives of people around the world by developing risk and resource management decision services</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		U.S. EPA’s Green Power Partnership.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				As of July 2012, Cisco was listed 16<sup>th</sup> among the National Top 50 and 11<sup>th</sup> among Fortune 500 companies</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Participated in the development of the Greenhouse Gas Protocol Scope 3 and GHGP Product accounting standards led by the World Resources Institute and the World Business Council for Sustainable Development</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainability-Related Services</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		In FY 2012, about 96% of new products incorporated design-for-environment principles through the product requirements template</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has implemented company-wide information and training events such as Virtual Earth Day and video-on-demand classes</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has an internal, quarterly newsletter that summarizes Cisco’s environmental activities for their employees called Think Green</li>\n	<li>\n		Sponsors civil councils that allow employees to volunteer in their local communities on social or environmental related programs</li>\n	<li>\n		Once a year, Cisco employees can bring in used electronics to have them recycled using the same vendors and processes used in Cisco’s business</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco is working to cut the power used by its Application-Specific Integrated Circuits (ASICs) used in most Cisco products. In lab tests, these modifications to the circuit have been shown to reduce energy consumption by 10 – 30%</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco products such as TelePresence and Webex foster virtual communication and collaboration.</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco data center virtualization technologies significantly reduce the number of data center components.</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has included a requirement that their power supplies be at least 85% efficient.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainability Governance</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Tae Yoo – Cisco’s Senior Vice President of Corporate Affairs\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Handles business surrounding the CSR report</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Sustainable Business Practice Team</li>\n	<li>\n		Global Energy Management and Sustainability Team</li>\n	<li>\n		Eco-Board is an executive level forum to ratify strategy and goals, share best practices, and provide opportunities for employee education, awareness, and engagement</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Challenges and Future Goals</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal</u>: Partner with suppliers to identify and realize sustainability improvements in FY 2013</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal</u>: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to complete Cisco’s supplier sustainability survey in FY 2013</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal:</u> Get 100% of preferred suppliers to report their GHG emissions to the CDP in FY 2013</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal</u>: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to have goals in place to reduce their GHG emissions and report their progress towards goals in FY 2015</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal</u>: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to report Cisco’s share in their GHG emissions by end of FY 2015&nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal</u>: Get 100% of manufacturing partners to publish a CSR in FY 2013</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal</u>: Get 75% of logistics providers to publish a CSR report in FY 2013</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal:</u> 100% of Cisco’s supplier managers will complete web-based training on sustainability in FY 2013</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal:</u> Roll out EnergyWise- enabled power distribution units in Cisco engineering labs worldwide</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal:</u> Expand the quantity and usage of installed EV charging stations</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal:</u> Incorporate Scope 3 (air travel data) data into the SIS system</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Goal: Move all GHG emissions, air travel, and sustainability data to a new, enterprise-wide sustainability information system (SIS)</u></li>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;<u>Challenge</u>: Prevent electricity emission factors from increasing as Cisco grows in energy markets where low carbon and no-carbon electricity is not readily available</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Best Practices/Success Drivers</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		<u>Cisco’s ISO 14001 certified cites are audited by an independent third party</u></li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco has used dematerialization projects to identify and remove unnecessary items associated with their shipment of products\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				<u>Pointer card (directs people to web link) to replace accessory kits</u></li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Getting suppliers engaged with sustainability practices (i.e. completing CSR, reporting to CDP)</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco EnergyWise System</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco Connected Workplace</li>\n	<li>\n		Cisco Virtual Office</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and Prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley</em></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>References</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.cisco.com/web/about/citizenship/reports/pdfs/CSR-Report-2012-Full-Report.pdf">http://www.cisco.com/web/about/citizenship/reports/pdfs/CSR-Report-2012-Full-Report.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://csr.cisco.com/pages/csr-awards-2012">http://csr.cisco.com/pages/csr-awards-2012</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, '');
