(1687, 'default', 150, '<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>INTEL</strong> <strong>sustainability</strong> <strong>Review<br />\n	November</strong> <strong>2012</strong></span></p>\n<h2>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Introduction</span></h2>\n<p>\n	Intel Corporation is a multinational semiconductor chip maker corporation headquartered in Santa Clara, California, USA. Intel is the world''s largest semiconductor manufacturer. Intel has offices located worldwide with over &nbsp;100,000 employees.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Awards,</strong> <strong>frameworks</strong> <strong>and</strong> <strong>accomplishments</strong> <strong>as</strong> <strong>of</strong> <strong>Nov.</strong> <strong>2012</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	In the past year, Intel has received numerous &nbsp;recognitions for corporate responsibility efforts at the local, national, and global level.</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Awards</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012 U.S. State Department ACE Award (Nov). Intel was recognized in 2012 by the State Department with the Award for Corporate Excellence Award for our CSR achievements in Vietnam.</li>\n	<li>\n		2008-2012 : Intel named &nbsp;a Green Power Partner of the Year by U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) for voluntary efforts to address climate change through renewable energy purchases, leadership, overall strategy, and impact on the green power market.</li>\n	<li>\n		2012 (Dec) : Intel was one of four companies recognized by FTSE4Good for leadership in CSR at the Sir Mervyn Pedelty Award ceremony at the London Stock Exchange.</li>\n	<li>\n		2009 : InfoWorld Green 15 for identifying cost savings and pushing the limits of free cooling in data centers</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Rankings</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		2012: Corporate &nbsp;Knights: #18 in the global 100 ranking of the most sustainable corporations in the world. Intel has been in the top 100 for eight years in a row</li>\n	<li>\n		2012 (Oct): Intel was ranked #7 in Newsweek’s Green Ranking for the largest 500 U.S. companies, and #35 in the Newsweek global green ranking</li>\n	<li>\n		2011: #1 of Forbes’ America’s Greenest Companies for the third year in a row: recognized as the largest voluntary purchaser of green power in the U.S. and for its commitment to environmental responsibility</li>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;2012: Intel was ranked #3 on Corporate Responsibility magazine’s 100 Best Corporate &nbsp;Citizens</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Listings</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		2012: Ethisphere’s &nbsp;World’s &nbsp;Most &nbsp;Ethical &nbsp;Companies</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		2012 Good Company Index: grade B. Also present in the 2011 list (index created in 2011)</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		2012: Dow Jones Sustainability World and North American indexes for the 14th consecutive year</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		&nbsp;2010: #2 overall and top technology company in the Maplecroft Climate Innovation Index, which measures U.S. companies on carbon management and climate-related innovation</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>F</strong><strong>r</strong><strong>a</strong><strong>meworks</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		GRI: 2012 level A+ self-declared. Intel has used GRI guidelines in its CSR report since 2003.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainable</strong> <strong>Actions/Initiatives</strong></span></p>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Biodiversity/Site</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Intel has adopted a policy to design all new buildings to a minimum LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) Silver level. Through the end of 2011, Intel also achieved certification for a total of 18 buildings across five sites in Arizona, Costa Rica, China, Israel and Malaysia. Intel is exploring certification for another 14 existing buildings in Arizona, India, Israel, Mexico, Oregon, and Vietnam.</li>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;<a href="http://www.intel.com/">Intel is</a> the first semiconductor or industrial technology company to achieve &nbsp;LEED certification from the U.S. Green Building Council (USGBC) for an entire manufacturing complex (its American campus in Ocotillo, AZ, obtained a silver LEED certification in 2011.).</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel built its first Green building for R&amp;D center at Haifa, Israel. This building&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; achieved LEED gold certification and has the following features:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				50% of the building footprint covered by a Green Roof to reduce heat island and provide thermal insulation. Use of reflecting materials, shades, and landscaping</li>\n			<li>\n				The facade includes reflective panels to maximize daylight penetration, providing natural lighting levels to more that 75% of the occupied areas</li>\n			<li>\n				Internal Technologies\n				<ul>\n					<li>\n						Lighting fixtures’ controlled system enables each fixture to be dimmed separately.</li>\n					<li>\n						Individual light and thermal comfort is controlled via Building&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management System.</li>\n					<li>\n						Each worker will be allowed to adjust his ambient air comfort and overhead lighting from his or her personal computer.</li>\n					<li>\n						A glazing surface area has been reduced on East/South/West facades</li>\n				</ul>\n			</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Implemented a green plan for Intel’s Developer Forum (IDF), the company’s largest event and developed a green events handbook to apply to other Intel events throughout the year.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="margin-left:2.25pt;">\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Water</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	Since 1998, Intel has invested more than $100 million in water conservation programs in its global facilities. To date, these efforts have saved over 40 billion gallons of water-enough for roughly 400,000 U.S. homes for one year.</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Arizona presents unique water use challenges due to its hot, arid climate and fast growing metropolitan areas. Intel used some methods to overcome these challenges for its campus in Ocotillo, AZ over the past decade. These include:</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Chandler RO Recharge Facility - Intel used an advanced reverse osmosis water treatment facility to treat process wastewater from its semiconductor manufacturing. This process wastewater is treated to drinking water standards and returned to the underground aquifer to replenish the groundwater supply.</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		POTW Effluent Reuse Program – Intel’s Ocotillo campus takes back a portion of Chandler’s treated effluent from its POTW for use in mechanical systems&nbsp;(i.e., scrubbers, cooling towers), landscape watering, and farm (forage crop) irrigation.</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Internal Water Reuse Projects – Advanced facilities systems that reclaim process and facilities wastewater. This reclaimed wastewater is supplied to facility equipment where most other industries would use fresh city water.</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Conserving 66 percent of its site wide water, saving approximately 5 million gallons of fresh water each day,</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Retaining 100 percent of captured storm water on-site,</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Partnering with the City of Chandler to divert non-potable water from the city’s waste water plant to the complex to use for 100 percent of the irrigation water and 95 percent of the cooling tower water. As a result, Intel reuses up to 75% of its water on this site.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n	On the &nbsp;Israel campus, measures related to water include:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Indigenous plants and controlled computerized irrigation reduce water usage by 55% at mid- summer. A 31% reduction of water usage and related sewage is achieved by efficient urinals, dual flush water closets, and low-flow faucets and showers</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Gardens are watered by an automatic irrigation system using recycled&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; water. A HVAC condensate water drain, collected at a rate of 5300 gallon/day during summer, is sufficient as the sole source of irrigation</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Paving of internal roads and pavements offset by developing the adjacent public area with plants</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Energy</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Green power production and purchase:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Since 2008, Intel has been the largest voluntary purchaser of green power in the U.S., according to the U.S. EPA.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Intel announced &nbsp;it would purchase more than 1.3 billion kilowatt hours a year of renewable energy certificates, making it the single-largest corporate purchaser of green power in the US. at the time. Intel purchases Renewable Energy Certificates (or RECs) generated from the production of wind, solar, geothermal, low-impact hydro, and biomass sources</li>\n			<li>\n				In 2011 Intel increased its green power usage by 75 percent, from approximately 1.4 billion kilowatt-hours (kWh) to more than 2.5 billion kWh – equal to &nbsp;85 percent of its U.S. electricity use</li>\n			<li>\n				In February 2012, Intel announced it would increase its purchase to 2.8 billion kWh, equivalent to 88 percent of its U.S. energy use</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		In addition to purchasing green power, Intel hosts a total of &nbsp;15 solar systems on multiple locations in Oregon, New Mexico, Arizona, California, India, Israel, and Vietnam that total more than five megawatts hour (MWh) per year. These projects consist of ground and roof- mounted solar arrays, in addition to solar support structures in the parking lots</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel’s campus in Arizona uses 26 percent less energy than comparable&nbsp;&nbsp; semiconductor complexes</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel’s &nbsp;LEED certified building in &nbsp;Israel (including a data center and a high-energy consumer) has a heating system based on heat recovery from the DC water-cooled condensers. Recovered heat is also used for preheating of the domestic hot water supply to the kitchen and gym showers. There is no conventional fuel-powered boiler heating system</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Intel works on empowering energy consumers and accelerating the development of renewable energy, smart grids, and buildings:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Intel serves on the board of the Green Grid, a global consortium founded in 2007 made of companies dedicated to energy efficiency in business computing ecosystems.</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel founded and co-chairs Digital Energy Sustainability and Solutions Campaign (DESSC), a coalition of ICT companies, NGOs, and trade associations dedicated to promoting the adoption of public policies that will enable ICT be effectively applied to improving societal energy efficiency and to reduce carbon emissions.</li>\n	<li>\n		“Solar kiosks” are located at each of Intel''s solar sites to educate employees and visitors about the company''s green power efforts, along with showing real-time information on electricity generated from these systems</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel has developed a social networking platform called “Planet Blue,” which is helping increase employee awareness of its commitment to green power. This platform provides opportunities for employees to collaborate on sustainability projects</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel also created a residential solar energy discount program for employees to leverage its green power leadership beyond the organization''s boundaries</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Transportation/Air</strong> <strong>Quality</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		A carpool policy is implemented</li>\n	<li>\n		Bicycle Storage (for 40 units) with showers and changing rooms for the bicyclists’ benefit are located in the underground parking area</li>\n	<li>\n		Site located at a walking distance from main transportation stations, such as a train station, a central bus station, and a city bus</li>\n	<li>\n		The quantity of fresh air in the offices of Intel in Israël is controlled by a CO2 monitoring system to save cost and improve ventilation</li>\n	<li>\n		Only low-emitting (low-VOC) paints, adhesives, and sealers are applied in Intel’s new offices</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Material</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	Intel strives to minimize the environmental impact of the products at all phases in their life cycle: <strong>development,</strong> <strong>p</strong><strong>r</strong><strong>o</strong><strong>duction,</strong> <strong>use,</strong> <strong>and</strong> <strong>ultimate</strong> <strong>disposal.</strong></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	Concerning Intel’s site in Israël:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		10% - 20% of all supplies in this building made up of recycled material</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Forest Stewardship Council certified wood make up 50% of the wood used in the building (doors, finishes, furniture)</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Construction waste is recycled or reused (parking lot asphalt is reused on site; soil and aggregates were reused at adjacent construction site: steel, wood, cardboard, organic materials, etc. to meet the target of keeping 50% of the construction waste from having to be disposed of)</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		As a prerequisite, a recycling program for non- hazardous waste was&nbsp; implemented during the building’s life-cycle</li>\n	<li style="margin-left: 5.6pt; ">\n		Products with a smaller ecological footprint</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;">Partnerships around sustainability</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Through the Intel Involved program, Intel employees donate their time at local schools and nonprofits around the world. &nbsp;Over the past five years, Intel employees have donated more than five million hours of service in their local communities, including volunteering for environmental projects. &nbsp;For example, employees taught elementary school classes on environmental stewardship and recycling. One group of employees volunteered as mentors for the Tech challenge at the San Jose Tech Museum, helping students showcase their solutions for cleaning up junk in space.</li>\n	<li>\n		At the Ocotillo plant, a new process to grow algae thanks to the carbon dioxide emissions coming from the boilers at the plant is being developed. The idea first came from an Intel team, and now <a href="http://alti.asu.edu/research/algae/">Arizona State University’s (ASU) Laboratory for Algae Research and Biotechnology</a> (LARB) has helped them create a small pilot model on the roof of the plant. Captured boiler emissions feed algae that is cropped and burned in bio-reactors until reactors get to their maximum capacity.</li>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;Intel works with other organizations, customers, and businesses to find and lead industry-wide environmental initiatives. These programs help minimize the footprint of the computing industry and encourage environmentally responsible computing and business practices.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;">Sustainability-related products and services</span></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		&nbsp;Intel founded a Collaborative Research Institute for Sustainable Connected Cities</li>\n	<li>\n		Created a cross-functional collaborative team to share best practices and inspire planners to expand the effort to other events.</li>\n	<li>\n		Developed a green event handbook, “The Blue Guide to Being Green,” which has over 70 tools to help planners through a step-by-step sustainable event process.</li>\n	<li>\n		Educated event program owners through webinars and a newly created mentorship program that provides one-on-one support.</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Governance</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Intel employees are encouraged to find ways to innovate sustainability in their jobs and are recognized by Intel Environment Excellence Awards.</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel created the Sustainability in Action program through which employees can apply in advance for funding for their innovative sustainability projects.</li>\n	<li>\n		Since 2008, Intel has linked a portion of every employee’s variable compensation from front- line employees to our CEO to the achievement of environmental sustainability metrics</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Challenges</strong> <strong>and</strong> <strong>Future</strong> <strong>Goals</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Intel has set some ambitious new sustainability goals:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		By 2020, Intel wants to reduce direct greenhouse gas emissions by 10 percent per chip. (note : Intel has set 2020 goals across all key environmental issues – &nbsp;water, waste, product energy efficiency)</li>\n	<li>\n		Intel Corporation set itself a goal to reduce its global-warming greenhouse gas footprint by 20% by 2012 from 2007 levels.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Best</strong> <strong>practices,</strong> <strong>Success</strong> <strong>Drivers</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	Intel innovates in sustainability, for example with the production of Algae to create biofuel on the roof of its Arizona plant.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	Intel is active in the community and helps its employees be green, before encouraging them to train and inform other persons in the civil society.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and prepared by Pallavi Kalale for Sustainable Silicon Valley</em></p>\n<p>\n	<br />\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sources</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://www.intel.com/Assets/PDF/Intel-Awards-Recognitions.pdf">www.intel.com/Assets/PDF/Intel-Awards-Recognitions.pdf</a> <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/04/04/intel-reaps-cost-and-energy-savings-smarter-greener-events">http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/04/04/intel-reaps-cost-and-energy-savings-smarter-greener-</a> <a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/04/04/intel-reaps-cost-and-energy-savings-smarter-greener-events">events</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://blogs.intel.com/csr/2010/05/earth_day_at_intel/">http://blogs.intel.com/csr/2010/05/earth_day_at_intel/</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/05/16/intel-slashes-emissions-misses-water-and-waste-targets">http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/05/16/intel-slashes-emissions-misses-water-and-waste-targets</a> <a href="http://blog.calyptusgroup.com/2012/06/21/intel-sustainability-inside">http://blog.calyptusgroup.com/2012/06/21/intel-sustainability-inside</a> <a href="http://www.intel.com/content/www/ie/en/corporate">http://www.intel.com/content/www/ie/en/corporate</a><a href="http://www.intel.com/content/www/ie/en/corporate-responsibility/sustainability-initiatives-and-policies.html"> responsibility/sustainability-initiatives-and-</a> <a href="http://www.intel.com/content/www/ie/en/corporate-responsibility/sustainability-initiatives-and-policies.html">policies.html</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/corporate-responsibility/sustainability-initiatives-and-">http://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/corporate-responsibility/sustainability-initiatives-and-</a><a href="http://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/corporate-responsibility/sustainability-initiatives-and-policies.html">policies.html)</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://www.intel.com/technology/epa/index.htm">http://www.intel.com/technology/epa/index.htm</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<u>Environmental</u> <u>P</u><u>r</u><u>o</u><u>t</u><u>e</u><u>ction</u> <u>Agency</u> <u>N</u><u>a</u><u>tional</u> <u>T</u><u>o</u><u>p</u> <u>2</u><u>5</u> <u>a</u><u>s</u> <u>o</u><u>f</u> <u>April</u> <u>8</u><u>,</u> <u>2008.</u> <a href="http://www.epa.gov/greenpower/toplists/top50.htm">www.epa.gov/greenpower/toplists/top50.htm)</a> <u>download.intel.com/.../3-Intels_First_Designed_and_Built_Green_Bu...</u></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://www.epa.gov/region9/waterinfrastructure/.../Intel-Ocotillo-Arizona.p">www.epa.gov/region9/waterinfrastructure/.../Intel-Ocotillo-Arizona.p...)</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:5.6pt;">\n	<a href="http://www.gizmag.com/intel-goes-green-power-purchase/8732">http://www.gizmag.com/intel-goes-green-power-purchase/8732)</a> <u>download.intel.com/.../3-Intels_First_Designed_and_Built_Green_Building-1.pdf</u> <a href="http://www.epa.gov/greenpower/awards/winners.htm">http://www.epa.gov/greenpower/awards/winners.htm</a> <a href="http://newsroom.intel.com/community/intel_newsroom/blog/2011/04/21/intels-arizona-campus-takes-the-leed">http://newsroom.intel.com/community/intel_newsroom/blog/2011/04/21/intels-arizona-campus-</a> <a href="http://newsroom.intel.com/community/intel_newsroom/blog/2011/04/21/intels-arizona-campus-takes-the-leed">takes-the-leed</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, ''),
(1688, 'default', 151, '<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n<p align="center">\n	<br />\n	<strong><span style="font-size:18px;">ADOBE’s Sustainability Review</span></strong></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<p style="text-align: left; ">\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Introduction</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Adobe is a software company that specializes in digital marketing and digital media solutions that help businesses meet online publishing challenges. Adobe''s headquarter is located in San Jose, California.&nbsp;The company originated in Palo Alto, California in 1982. As of 2011, Adobe has 9,022 employees working in their offices around the world. 4,982 of those employees are located in the United States and Canada, and the other 4,040 are located in other countries. There are currently 26 Adobe offices in operation around the world. The company reports to the Carbon Disclosure Project and outlines their sustainability efforts in their Corporate Social Responsibility reports. According to their company website, their mission statement is:</p>\n<p>\n	“At Adobe, we believe a creative world sustains itself, we continue to strive to exceed industry certification standards and maximize efficiency with cutting-edge technology all while empowering employees to create a culture of environmental sustainability, it is adobe living its values”</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Awards/Frameworks and Accomplishments</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Awards</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	National:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2005 Environmental Project of the Year Award, Association of Energy Engineers</p>\n<p>\n	Local:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design– Existing Building Platinum certification, Adobe West Tower corporate headquarters, USGBC</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 First place award for Landscape Maintenance, Medium Commercial Maintenance Category, California Landscaping Contractors Association, San Francisco Bay Area Chapter</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Green Business of the Year, Santa Clara League of Conservation Voters</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Preservation Design Award in recognition of Outstanding Achievement in the Field of Historic Preservation for the Rehabilitation of the Baker and Hamilton Building in San Francisco, California Preservation Foundation</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2005 Best Overall, Comprehensive Energy Management, State of California, Flex Your Power</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Commendations for Green Business status, City of San Jose</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Green Building of the Year for Corporate Headquarters and International Earth Awards Silicon Valley Chapter, Building Owners and Managers Association</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2004 Building of the Year for Corporate Headquarters Buildings for Silicon Valley, BOMA Western Region</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Green Building Certification, Santa Clara County</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Certified Green Business, Association of Bay Area Governments</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Rankings</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012, 2011, 2010 World''s most ethical companies by Ethisphere – <a href="http://ethisphere.com/wme/">link</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Number 14 in 2011 and 2012 Newsweek Green rankings among US companies (<a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2011/10/16/green-rankings-2011-america-s-greenest-companies-photos.all.html">Link 2012</a> – <a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/topics/green-rankings.html">link</a>2011) <a href="http://ethisphere.com/wme/">http://ethisphere.com/wme/</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 Number 20 on the Goodness 500 list in the area of Corporate Social Responsibility for donations, equality, and the environment – <a href="http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html">link</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 Ranked &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; number 20 on the Corporate Social Responsibility Index of the top 50 Socially Responsible Companies in the United States by the Boston College Center for Corporate Citizenship and Reputation Institute – <a href="http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html">link</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Index</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Leadership Index S&amp;P 500, years 2011 (score 73) and 2012&nbsp; (score 93) - <a href="https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Results/Documents/2012-CDLI-CPLI/CDP-SP500-cdli.pdf">Link</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Frameworks</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Project - <a href="http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html">http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainable Activities</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Biodiversity/Site</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Total of 10 LEED certified buildings</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Increase of about 4% since 2008</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Jose building matched the highest score from the United States Green Building Council in 2010</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012 CSR Report says that 45% of all Adobe buildings are LEED certified and 43% are Platinum certified</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; First to achieve 3 Platinum-Level Certifications for Energy and Environmental Design Excellence</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Retrofitting Adobe Offices with energy-efficient equipment and installing monitors that instantly meter power usage at all our sites around the globe</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All janitorial products satisfy the American Society for Testing and Materials Cleaning Stewardship for Community Building Standards and meet the Green Seal Cleaning Products Standards &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Jose Location</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Waterless Urinals</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Garage Exhaust Fan</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Real-time electric meters</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Water</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Per the 2012 CSR report, the San Jose Office reduced their domestic water use by 53% and irrigation water was reduced by 93%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Francisco Location was able to reduce water by 48%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Overall increase in water recycling</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reducing hours fountains on site are running</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Energy</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wind turbines and Bloom energy fuel cells in California to power their offices and receive renewable energy credits</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bloom Boxes inexpensively convert natural, bio-gas into electricity and Adobe plans to reduce their carbon footprint by 121.5 million pounds over the<br />\n	next ten years</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Verifiable emissions reduction credits from their use of Windspire wind turbines and biogas plants</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Jose Office has also installed IBIS smart floor technology, enabling a 35% reduction in energy use compared to other floors.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From 2001 to 2010, the San Jose location was able to reduce their electricity by 27% and their natural gas by 16%</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The San Francisco office reduced electricity by 26% and natural gas by 29%</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Materials</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal to increase the amount of digital downloads to decrease the need for packaging</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal to reduce the amount of packaging per unit that is sold in stores</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have a greater influence on the manufacturing process, agreements with third parties in order to increase material efficiency</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lean Print Software optimizes document layouts and manages toner output to reduce resource consumption</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From 2008 to 2010, 5% decrease in the amount of software sold as hard goods and 5% increase in the amount sold electronically</p>\n<p>\n	Waste reduction:</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012 CSR report 98% of garbage was diverted from the landfill through recycling and composting</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Francisco diverted about 95% to be recycled</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe has agreements with their distributors to recycle</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In their offices in California, Adobe has switched paper dining and kitchen products to ones that are biodegradable</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kitchen grease is recycled and composting is a significant component in the kitchens</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The city of San Jose contributed to this effort when they switched to mixed recycling</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe calculates that their work to recycle saves about $198,000 in landfill fees after equipping office spaces with the appropriate supplies to effectively recycle</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Posters are located in break rooms to educate employees on their efforts so that everyone can benefit further from what is being done</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Accounts for e-waste and monitors it</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Air Quality/Transportation</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012 CSR Report total business miles travelled per year increased to 79.3 million miles from about 48.8 million miles</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Purchased enough credits to offset all scope 1 and 2 emissions</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Partnerships</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Electronics Industry Citizenship Coalition since 2006</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; UN Global Compact Ten Principles</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Follows the Code of Conduct and works with their suppliers to meet these standards and has begun using a Green Product Purchasing Policy. Adobe''s Supply Chains Operations Team participates in EICC working groups to continuously refine the codes.</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 exhibit in San Jose Tech Museum to teach about<br />\n	environmental technology</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 SIMS Recycling partnership to develop processes to recycle and dispose of technology-related software, ewaste</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cushman and Wakefield facilities management for world-scale energy monitoring and control</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PG&amp;E Energy Efficiency Programs</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainability Related Services</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use of Adobe® Acrobat® and LiveCycle® software for electronic document exchange and electronic workflows helps companies cut paper use and significantly increase efficiencies</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe Connect™ software is used by companies and individuals to host live and interactive web meetings, virtual classes, and on-demand presentations. Adobe also makes an internal use this product</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Governance</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Information available about Adobe''s sustainability efforts can be found in the Corporate Social Responsibility reports</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reports linked to the Carbon Disclosure Project</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Environmental Sustainability Council consisting of employees and experts that are representatives in areas such as facilities, operations, the supply chain,<br />\n	and IT</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Report back to the CSR department to contribute to the overall sustainability goals of Adobe</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Green Team of employees began in 2008 and is used to educate and empower employees</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Organization of events throughout the month of April 2012 to celebrate Earth Day and sustainable lifestyles &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Opportunities for employees to learn about solar power and receive a discount on solar panels</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Developing an employee-run garden</p>\n<p style="margin-left:1.0in;">\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe plans to expand its Green Team to all 12 major<br />\n	sites by 2015</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Challenges and Future Goals</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; “Create change” in the business, new software and pressing<br />\n	environmental issues</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Achieve net zero energy consumption by 2015 in their owned facilities in<br />\n	the United States</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduce the amount of packaging used per unit by 40% by 2012 and 80%<br />\n	by 2015</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Expand their employee-led green team to all of their 12 major sites by 2015</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure that third parties are sustainably minded</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Work on reducing emissions from travel of employees</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Best Practices/Success Drivers</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Green Team driving employees</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Technology allowing Adobe to cut down on emissions</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management of waste on site</p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED certification at multiple locations</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Proposed Case Studies Demonstrating Best Practices</strong></span></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; IBIS Smartfloor Technology– <a href="https://docs.google.com/a/sustainablesv.org/viewer?a=v&amp;pid=gmail&amp;attid=0.1&amp;thid=13824a7f849376cb&amp;mt=application/pdf&amp;url=https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=97763a74e4&amp;view=att&amp;th=13824a7f849376cb&amp;attid=0.1&amp;disp=safe&amp;realattid=f_h3vt9c4b0&amp;zw&amp;sig=AHIEtbQ2MlTPfBU5u13PVhn2_aAqjjtlBg">link</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Certification– <a href="http://www.usgbc.org/News/PressReleaseDetails.aspx?ID=2783">link</a></p>\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Material Waste Management– <a href="https://docs.google.com/a/sustainablesv.org/viewer?a=v&amp;pid=gmail&amp;attid=0.2&amp;thid=13824a7f849376cb&amp;mt=application/pdf&amp;url=https://mail.google.com/mail/u/0/?ui=2&amp;ik=97763a74e4&amp;view=att&amp;th=13824a7f849376cb&amp;attid=0.2&amp;disp=safe&amp;realattid=f_h3vt9c561&amp;zw&amp;sig=AHIEtbSOnqBviV-0Xu2o-2YmHoexa9T8lw">link</a></p>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and Prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley</em></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sources</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html">http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf">http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf">http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf">http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-facilities.html">http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-facilities.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-emissions.html">http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-emissions.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-waste-management.html">http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-waste-management.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/awards.html">http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/awards.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/product-resource-reduction.html">http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/product-resource-reduction.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-csr-brief-env-sust.pdf">http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-csr-brief-env-sust.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/2011-adobe-csr-data-summary.pdf">http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/2011-adobe-csr-data-summary.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/2009-csr-summary.pdf">http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/2009-csr-summary.pdf</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.thedailybeast.com/topics/green-rankings.html">http://www.thedailybeast.com/topics/green-rankings.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	&nbsp;</p>\n', '', 'wysiwyg-advanced', 1, '');
