(1691, 'default', 153, '<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>Google Sustainability Review</strong></span></p>\n<p align="center">\n	<span style="font-size:18px;"><strong>November 2012</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Introduction</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Google is the creator of a popular link-based search engine and has also expanded into the arena of tech-based gadgets including tablets and mobile operating systems. The company has 34,111 employees as of Quarter 2 in 2012 and 70 offices in 40 countries. The company was created by two Stanford students in 2005 and strives to make the search process both smarter and faster to enhance consumer’s web experience, and to design internet tools helpful to businesses.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainable Actions</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Biodiversity/Site</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	Food-related actions:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Google orders the food for their campuses from local sources that are within 200 miles of their offices\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Purchase poultry and produce from small farms and work to educate rising farmers on how to grow their foods organically</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Community Supported Agriculture (CSA) program allows Google employees to buy fresh, seasonal produce that is delivered directly to a Google campus</li>\n	<li>\n		Google purchases coffee from four local roasters all of whom buy from Fair Trade certified growers</li>\n	<li>\n		Google Green Seafood program helps ensure that the company purchases species caught locally and through independently managed fisheries that use environmentally responsible catch practices</li>\n	<li>\n		Many campuses have edible gardens that allow employees to grow herbs for their own cooking</li>\n	<li>\n		20% of food waste from their cafes is recycled and in Europe, the Middle East, and Africa it is recycled to produce bio-diesel or electricity\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				The rest of the waste is composted</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Waste reduction activities:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Google recycles 100% of the electronic equipment that leaves their data centers</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Data Driven Purchasing</em>: Google analyzes what is popular in their cafes and determines the amount of each ingredient to buy accordingly. This helps eliminate waste and provide a nice diverse variety of food at each meal</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Using Real Dishes and Silverware: </em>In Cafes employees use non-disposable dishes and silverware.&nbsp; There are micro-kitchens throughout the campuses that provide a location for employees to drop off their dishes if they chose to eat in their office space</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Composting and Recycling:</em> Throughout the campus there are marked recycling and compost bins and the to-go containers and utensils that are provided by Google are compostable as well</li>\n	<li>\n		<em>Donating Unused Food: </em>Any untouched, edible, and leftover food goes to local shelters in Google’s communities</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	Buildings construction and management:</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Only use building materials that have the lowest levels of VOCs and formaldehyde possible. Exclude any materials that contain mercury and lead\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Require vendors to be transparent about their product ingredient information at every point in the supply chain</li>\n			<li>\n				In North America, require that vendors share their information through the Pharos Project, an open source materials evaluation system. This allows all other Pharos members to be informed on product choices&nbsp;</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Purchase EnergyStar-rated (or overseas equivalent) office equipment and use sophisticated building control technologies to ensure systems are only on when needed</li>\n	<li>\n		Use LEED certification program and Living Building Challenge as well as their own program creation of “Sustainable Pursuit” (based on LEED framework and popular board game, Trivial Pursuit) to guide their building performance</li>\n	<li>\n		Have 14 LEED certified projects and more in the works as well as one Green Start certification (Australia’s LEED equivalent).&nbsp; The SF office has made the HVAC system more efficient and this helped the office achieve the LEED Gold certification.\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Received City of Mountain View’s first ever LEED platinum certification and first published LEED project certification for commercial interiors in Argentina</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Cradle to Cradle carpet usage: carpet Google uses is sent back to manufacturer where it is used in the supply stream so it does not end up in landfill</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainability Related Services</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		To conduct a single search on Google their servers use about 1kJ of energy, resulting in the emission of 0.2g of CO2.&nbsp; To put this into context, 100 searches on Google have about the same carbon footprint as one hour on a laptop (assuming it’s a 30W laptop)</li>\n	<li>\n		One minute of streaming on YouTube emits 0.11g of carbon dioxide.&nbsp; To put this into context, the footprint of a DVD (manufactured, packaged, and delivered) has about the equivalent footprint of 72 hours on YouTube (assume footprint of DVD is 3kg CO2)</li>\n	<li>\n		The carbon impact of using Gmail for a year is about 1.2 kg CO2.&nbsp; To put this into context, drinking a 750 ml bottle of wine and then placing a note in it and tossing it into the ocean emits more carbon than using Gmail for a year (assumes the carbon footprint of wine is about 2 kg CO2 per liter)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Water</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Use recycled municipal wastewater for applications such as toilet flushing and landscape watering</li>\n	<li>\n		In Hyderabad, India and Sydney, Australia water recycling programs are implemented.&nbsp; In India, about 380,000 gallons of waste water are treated and reused annually in non-potable systems</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Energy</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	In 2007, Google committed to being carbon neutral</p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Purchase high-quality carbon offsets (entire operation is in-house)\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Landfill gas capture: capture and destroy methane gas released from decomposing waste</li>\n			<li>\n				Agricultural methane capture: capture methane gas that is produced at farms from decomposing animal wastes and process it into usable products</li>\n			<li>\n				Forestry projects: Prevent the destruction of existing forests and develop new ones</li>\n			<li>\n				Reduce emissions from their operations\n				<ul>\n					<li>\n						Brought the facility (data centers) overhead energy usage down from 1.4 to 0.5 per watt of IT computer energy</li>\n					<li>\n						In Zurich, Switzerland, a chilled beam heating, ventilation and cooling (HVAC) system uses significantly less energy to regulate building temperature while also occupying less space than conventional equipment</li>\n				</ul>\n			</li>\n			<li>\n				Purchase renewable energy to power their operations\n				<ul>\n					<li>\n						Power Purchase Agreements: Long-term, large-scale contracts to buy energy from renewable sources energy production site. The aim is to drive down the cost of clean power. 30% of energy used by Google is from renewable sources</li>\n				</ul>\n			</li>\n			<li>\n				All carbon offset projects are third-party verified</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Total capacity of all Google’s renewable energy project investments is over 1.7GW.&nbsp; They are expected to generate 4.5 billion kWh annually – far more electricity than Google consumes</li>\n	<li>\n		Solar Power production in Mountain view: Google has installed 9,200 solar panels over its corporate headquarters in the last year. 1.7MW solar installation supplies approximately 30% of their peak energy consumption on the buildings it covers and Google has implemented a building management system that monitors and controls campus-wide energy use &nbsp;</li>\n	<li>\n		Set aside $10 million for a program to speed development of plug-in electric cars and $20 million for wind and solar companies (through Google.org)</li>\n	<li>\n		Google data centers use a very small portion of global energy, Stanford consulting professor Jonathan Koomey estimates that the data centers use between 1.1% and 1.5% of global electricity\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Added temperature monitoring, optimized air vent tiles, increased temperature and humidity settings on CRAC’s, blocked off the ends of cold aisles with curtains, added 48” extensions to all CRAC air returns, added a new CRAC controller, and put blanking plates and side panels to block cold air passing through empty rack spaces.</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:14px;"><strong>Transportation</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Google has built a green transportation system composed of biodiesel shuttles and the largest corporate electric vehicle-charging infrastructure in the country\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				About 4500 Google employees who commute to the SF Bay Area office use the shuttle</li>\n			<li>\n				Shuttles include wifi</li>\n			<li>\n				Google is the first company with a corporate coach fleet to exceed the EPA’s 2010 bus emission standards; the fleet runs on 5% biodiesel and has filtration systems that eliminate many harmful emissions such as nitrogen oxide</li>\n			<li>\n				The biodiesel shuttles and GFleet result in a net annual savings of more than 5400 metric tons of CO2</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		Google created a car-sharing program for the Google employees who commute to work called GFleet that also includes plug-in vehicles</li>\n	<li>\n		The GFleet is composed of Chevrolet Volts, Nissan LEAFs, Misubishi iMiEVs, Ford Focus Electrics, Ford Transit Connect Electrics, and a Honda Fit EV</li>\n	<li>\n		Google donates to an employee’s favorites charities based on how often they walk or bike to work. Each time an employee does so they receive a digital stamp that eventually translates to dollars that Google donates to the charity of the employee’s choosing. An employee can donate up to $140 a quarter and in 2011, 2000 employees took advantage of this opportunity</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Partnerships Around Sustainability</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Google has collaboration with Coulumb Technologies to build the largest corporate EV charging infrastructure in the United States.&nbsp; They have over 400 vehicle chargers and the latest fast charging level 2 chargers</li>\n	<li>\n		Google has invested in:\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Recurrent Energy: large scale photovoltaic projects in California</li>\n			<li>\n				Clean Power Finance: financing for rooftop solar</li>\n			<li>\n				SolarCity: solar for thousands of residential rooftops</li>\n			<li>\n				Brightsource: concentrated solar power at scale</li>\n			<li>\n				Atlantic Wind Connection: a superhighway for clean energy transmission</li>\n			<li>\n				Alta Wind Energy Center: harnessing winds of the Mojave</li>\n			<li>\n				Shepard’s Flat: one of the world’s largest wind farms</li>\n			<li>\n				Peace Garden Wind Farms: opening up more financing for wind</li>\n			<li>\n				Photovoltaics in Germany: investing in clean energy overseas</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Sustainability Governance</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Google’s management team oversees the Company’s best interests and makes sure that sustainability in strongly implemented</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	The management team consists of:</p>\n<ul style="margin-left: 40px; ">\n	<li>\n		<strong>Executive Officers</strong> (6 members)</li>\n	<li>\n		<strong>Senior Leadership</strong> (15 members)</li>\n	<li>\n		<strong>Board of Directors</strong> (10 members). The Board of Directors establishes Corporate Governance guidelines to provide effective objectives for the business and stockholders. Under the Board of Directors,\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				The <u>Leadership Development and Compensation Committee</u> was established to oversee Google’s compensation programs, supports business objectives and incorporates the corporate governance principles</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Google believes that the <strong>Business Operations and Corporate Development team</strong> is at the heart of their <u>business strategies</u>. Under the Business Operations and Corporate Development team,\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				<strong>The Energy and Sustainability Team</strong> strives to make Google a leader in sustainability and clean energy by focusing on the Company’s operations system. <u>The Energy and Sustainability Team implements sustainability</u> by creating innovative technologies, and developing the best business practices</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n	<li>\n		<u>Google’s Chief Sustainability Officer works closely with the Executive Officers </u>to insure that the company focuses on the environmental aspect and reduction in energy costs. The Chief Sustainability Officer and the team focuses on the environmental impacts from Google, “greening offices” such as in “energy efficiency, sustainable design, healthy interiors, and on greening the electricity coming from their offices.”\n		<ul>\n			<li>\n				Google has Real Estate &amp; Workplace Services Green Teams</li>\n		</ul>\n	</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Challenges and Future Goals</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		Goal: Eliminate 100% of known toxins from Google’s buildings</li>\n	<li>\n		Goal: Pledged fifty megawatts of renewable energy by 2012</li>\n	<li>\n		Challenge: How to feasibly use only renewable energy for their data centers? Electric grid is currently the most feasible method for their needs</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>Best Practices/Success Drivers</strong></span></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		GFleet</li>\n	<li>\n		Data Driven Purchasing to reduce food waste</li>\n	<li>\n		Local engagement: purchase of local produce and work with farmers toward organic agriculture</li>\n	<li>\n		In North America, require their vendors to use Pharos Project, an open source materials evaluation system. This allows all other Pharos members to be informed on product choices</li>\n	<li>\n		Green Data Centers (lower temperature, new architecture, recycling of servers)</li>\n</ul>\n<p style="text-align: center; ">\n	<em>Researched and prepared by Caroline Nowacki and Natasha Patel</em></p>\n<p>\n	<span style="font-size:16px;"><strong>References</strong></span></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.divinecaroline.com/22277/44799-meet-google-s-chief-sustainability-officer#ixzz21g3Q9PLt">http://www.divinecaroline.com/22277/44799-meet-google-s-chief-sustainability-officer#ixzz21g3Q9PLt</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/">http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/#/datacenters/infographics">http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/#/datacenters/infographics</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/#/intro/infographics-1">http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/#/intro/infographics-1</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/references.html">http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/references.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/green/energy/investments/">http://www.google.com/green/energy/investments/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/about/company/products/">http://www.google.com/about/company/products/</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/food-for-green-thought.html">http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/food-for-green-thought.html</a></p>\n<p>\n	<a href="http://www.google.com/green/efficiency/oncampus/#eating">http://ww