(656, 'Water', ' By Mary Kean, EcoCloud Water Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	EcoCloud exists to provide resources to water professionals, businesses and governments, with information and case studies to allow implementation of water projects and to connect with others in their region to implement their water projects.&nbsp; The EcoCloud team has focused on providing utilities, commercial, industrial, and institutional (CII) users, and water professionals, the case studies, metrics, tools, and frameworks to complete projects.\n\n	Former California Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger has called for a 20% reduction in per capita use of water by 2020 .&nbsp; To meet that need, the EcoCloud™ team seeks to apply the principles of Industrial Ecology to Integrated Urban Water Management &amp; Water Conservation Projects by investigating opportunities for systems thinking, efficiency, waste reduction, and closed-loop processes both at the planning stages and implementation.&nbsp; Some of the key EcoCloud™ focus areas include recycled utility water, decentralized water management, conservation (efficiency), and the energy/water connection. Urban water management and water conservation projects need to take into account the entire water cycle.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n	Image: ActewAGL Education Website\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	EcoCloud is seeking cutting edge examples of water projects especially in the Silicon Valley and Bay Area – if you have implemented a project or used an innovative tool, contact us at&nbsp;ecocloudcontent@sustainablesv.org\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '13', NULL, 'topics/water', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/13', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/13'),
(6, 'Tesla Motors begins Model S production', 'Tesla Motors expects losses as production ramps up at their new facility in Fremont.', NULL, NULL, 'blog', 'blog:post', 'blog:posts', '1', NULL, 'blog/2012/07/tesla-motors-begins-model-s-production', 'admin/blog/edit/1', 'admin/blog/delete/1'),
(4, 'Cradle-to-Cradle Inspiration', '\n	Cradle-to-Cradle Materials Management\n\n	Material flow in a cradle-to-cradle economy means that there is no "waste." Outputs from one process become inputs to another, by design. Attendees at the June SSV Materials Management event heard presentations from expert practitioners from the Cradle to Cradle Products Innovation Institute, Adobe, Speciality Solid Waste and US EPA on how Silicon Valley companies and cities are bringing this transformational (and profitable) vision to reality.', NULL, NULL, 'blog', 'blog:post', 'blog:posts', '4', NULL, 'blog/2012/10/cradle-to-cradle-inspiration', 'admin/blog/edit/4', 'admin/blog/delete/4'),
(5, 'Ocean Conservation?  There''s an app for that!', '\n	by Francesca Koe, NRDC\n\n	Just a few years ago the idea of using a phone to teach you about ocean conservation would have seemed like science fiction, however there certainly are some promising signs we have evolved past our imaginations -- you know the saying "there''s an app for that!" One such handy app Rippl (recently released for iPhone) helps you build "green habits" by sending you helpful tips and reminders on how your actions impact the oceans. The app, which was created by the Ocean Conservancy, uses technology to bring ocean awareness into our daily routines.', NULL, NULL, 'blog', 'blog:post', 'blog:posts', '3', NULL, 'blog/2012/09/o', 'admin/blog/edit/3', 'admin/blog/delete/3'),
(960, 'How To Enter', ' \n	\n		\n			About\n		\n			Entry Criteria\n		\n			How To Enter\n		\n			Review Process\n		\n			Finalists\n		\n			My Solutions\n		\n			View Expert Profiles\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		\n			&nbsp;\n		\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Click Here to ENTER A Solution&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; \n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Click Here to VIEW Your Solutions\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Call for Solutions\n				Competition\n			\n				\n			\n				&nbsp;\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n	\n		How to Enter:\n	\n		\n			Register a user account by filling out a brief online form on EcoCloud website\n		\n			Use the online form to Enter Your Solutions\n		\n			Read and consent to the Terms and Conditions Agreement\n		\n			Submit solution: statement of problem, summary of the solution, supplemental materials, videos and pictures\n	\n	\n		\n			Rules for Submitting\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Only electronic submissions of solutions will be accepted\n			\n				Read and consent to the Terms and Conditions Agreement\n			\n				Submit a solution\n		\n	\n	\n		Categories Overview:\n	\n		\n			\n				Resources\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						Examples of Resources: Energy, Water, Materials, Information\n					\n						How available resources can be used for the current generation while not over-exploiting and depleting them for the future generations\n					\n						Solutions could demonstrate dramatically reduced resource use, green chemistry, materials substitution, de-materialization (substituting services for products)\n					\n						Integrated solutions that address multiple resources (such as water/energy/information) and that demonstrate systemic benefits\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n				\n					&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Human Systems\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						Examples of Human Systems: Communications, Culture &amp; Engagement, Human Behavior Change, Invention &amp; Innovation, Knowledge Development &amp; Transfer, Markets, Policies &amp; Regulation\n					\n						How current corporate and national strategies for managing resources can lead to environmental and social problems, such as depletion of key resources, destruction of habitat, overfishing, degradation of soil fertility.\n					\n						Solutions should take into account the connection between resources, ecosystems and society and not consider them as separate entities.\n					\n						Rebuilding community and economic vitality while restoring ecosystem health, for clean water, biodiversity and reuse of resources.\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Enterprise\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						Examples of Enterprise: Customers, HR/Engagement, Leadership/Strategy, Metrics/Financial Models/Legal, Operations, Product/Service Design, Stakeholders/Community/Infrastructure, Supply Chain\n					\n						How current corporate and national strategies for managing resources can lead to environmental and social problems, such as depletion of key resources, destruction of habitat, overfishing, degradation of soil fertility.\n					\n						Solutions should take into account the connection between resources, ecosystems and society and not consider them as separate entities.\n					\n						Rebuilding community and economic vitality while restoring ecosystem health, for clean water, biodiversity and reuse of resources.\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Regional Resilience\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						Solutions that improve use of resources (water, energy, materials, information) on a regional basis.\n					\n						Infrastructure such as smart micro grid integrating renewable energy and advanced efficiency and demand management; recycled water systems; smart transportation and land use planning that provides alternatives to single occupancy vehicles, especially for commuting; and cradle-to-cradle materials management. One name for this is EcoDistricts.\n					\n						Multi-generational solutions that facilitate interactions among old and young, school systems that integrate service and vocational learning and connect students with adults in the community.\n					\n						Walkable communities that combine arts, business, sports, shopping, residential and work areas and are pedestrian, transit and bicycle friendly.\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Industry Sectors\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						Examples of Sectors: Education, Finance/Insurance/Investment, Food/Agriculture, Healthcare, Manufacturing/Supply Chain, Transportation\n					\n						Transformation of supply chains and impact of industry on ecological health of the areas where they do business.\n					\n						Accounting for risk and costs associated with climate change and disruption to commerce from severe weather, sea level rise and catastrophic storms.\n					\n						Strategies for helping customers minimize environmental costs of using and disposing of products.\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Earth Systems\n		\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						The planet can be considered a system of systems that support living organisms, including human beings and human civilization.\n					\n						Civilization relies on surplus value from nature (agriculture to provide food; hydrological cycle to provide water; atmosphere to provide relative climate stability; energy from the sun and from fossil fuels; minerals; lumber; oceans for food and transportation, etc.)\n					\n						Nature provides free services such as pollination, on which at least 30% of human food production relies. The salinity of the ocean affects currents and moderates temperatures for large inhabited areas of the planet.\n					\n						Burning fossil fuels (coal, oil and natural gas) and burning or clear-cutting forests has lead to acceleration in green house gas emissions levels, which is leading to warming and acidification of the oceans, warming of the earth''s atmosphere and disruption to the precipitation and weather patterns on which human agriculture and urbanization have depended.\n					\n						Sea level rise and destruction of wetlands is leading to increased flooding and will continue to intensify as the oceans continue to warm.\n					\n						Solutions in this area will address how to rapidly scale technology and/or behavior change to dramatically reduce GHG emissions and rebuild carbon fixing resources such as land-based forests and kelp forests.\n					\n						Solutions may also address monitoring and modeling capabilities to help determine impacts from human activities or from other factors such as forest fires.\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '46', NULL, 'showcase-of-solutions-for-planetary-sustainability/how-to-enter', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/46', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/46'),
