(776, 'About Us', ' \n	\n		\n			\n				\n					SSV Vision &amp; Mission\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								Vision:\n								\n									Sustainable Silicon Valley (SSV) envisions a healthy environment, a vibrant economy and a socially equitable community, in our region and throughout the world.\n								\n									Mission:\n									As a consortium of companies, governmental entities, academic and research institutions and non-profit organizations, we work together to achieve this vision through collaboration and innovation, bringing solutions from Silicon Valley’s inventors, entrepreneurs and enterprises to solve problems and create resilience in our region and in regions around the world.\n							\n						\n					\n				\n				\n					\n					SSV Board, Staff and Volunteer\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									SSV is a non-profit organization. It consists of SSV Board &amp; Advisory Council, staff and volunteers.\n							\n						\n					\n				\n				\n					\n					EcoCloud\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									A project of Sustainable Silicon Valley (SSV) in conjunction with public and private sector partners, EcoCloud is a virtual space where you can connect with Silicon Valley business leaders, industry experts, researchers and policy makers--striving to make our enterprises and our region more ecologically, equitably, and economically sustainable.\n								\n									See here for details.\n							\n						\n					\n				\n				\n					\n					EcoCloud Members\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									EcoCoud community is open to anyone interested in sustainability. Its members mainly come from individual members and institutional partners.\n								\n									See here for member details.\n							\n						\n					\n				\n			\n			\n				\n					How To Use The Site\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									Welcome to EcoCloud™! We hope you will enjoy exploring this site and collaborating with other EcoCloud™ members. Before you start, please be sure to read the Terms of Use, and to ensure harmonious relationships with other EcoCloud™ members, take a look at our Behavior Guidelines.\n								\n									&nbsp;\n								\n									More details can be found here.\n							\n						\n					\n				\n				\n					\n					Terms Of Use\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									All members of this site agree to the terms of use set forth in this page, in addition to the Terms of Service available through the link in the webpage footer.\n								\n									&nbsp;\n								\n									All members are encouraged to use basic courtesy and best practices as described in Behavior Guidelines. Failure to do so can result in remedial action at the discretion of the site moderators, up to and including cancellation of site membership.\n								\n									&nbsp;\n								\n									For more, please see details here.\n							\n						\n					\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n				\n					Behavior Guidelines\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									EcoCloud™ serves the sustainability community by providing a respectful venue for communication and collaboration. The site should improve communications, foster involvement, and help further sustainability goals in Silicon Valley. The tone of discussion is intended to be professional and helpful. EcoCloud™ provides a venue for sharing news, providing thought leadership, collaborating on projects, and sending inquiries to other members of the community.\n								\n									&nbsp;\n								\n									The members of EcoCloud™ are our greatest asset and must be treated with respect. Site members should work together to maintain a high level of value and ensure that participation is rewarding and satisfying for all members. Toward that end, EcoCloud™ members are encouraged to use the following guidelines: more ...\n							\n						\n					\n				\n				\n					&nbsp;\n				\n					Contact Us\n				\n					\n						\n							\n								\n									We want to hear from you!\n								\n									Please contact us for more information about how to participate in EcoCloud™ in order to help your organization and the entire Bay Area region become more sustainable. \n							\n						\n					\n				\n			\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '21', NULL, 'about-us', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/21', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/21'),
(607, 'Transportation', ' \n	\n\n	According to the Environmental Defense Fund, roughly 20% of our greenhouse gas emissions in the U.S. come from transportation.&nbsp; Much of our country has grown up around the automobile, which was considered a clean tech option when it started to replace horse transport in New York City, but the downsides of the technology have made themselves known and as climate change and population growth become more urgent issues we need to start reducing our reliance on our cars.&nbsp; &nbsp;\n\n	This issue goes far beyond people making different choices, because in most cities in the U.S. those choices don’t realistically exist.&nbsp; Even the greenest commuter is going to hesitate at a quadrupling their travel time in order to take the bus.&nbsp; Appreciating that fact, many cities and communities are working multi-modal enabling into their sustainability plans in order to reduce auto dependence for meeting needs of transportation to work, services, and entertainment.&nbsp; In fact, as cities in California are required to establish Climate Action Plans and make goals for reduced GHG emissions, there is no away to avoid the transportation piece.&nbsp; Alternative fuel vehicles are helping to some extent, but as communities move forward with broad sustainability plans, the single passenger car needs to be phased out—for space, for health, and for the climate.\n\n	\n	There are a number of established tools that enable multimodal transport, and this site will be examining each one in turn:\n\n\n	\n		Transit Oriented Development\n	\n		Bicycling\n	\n		Ride Sharing\n	\n		Bus Rapid Transit\n	\n		Congestion Pricing\n	\n		Highway Removal\n	\n		Traffic Calming\n	\n		Road Diet\n	\n		Price of Parking\n	\n		Parking Reform\n	\n		Incentivizing/improving public transportation\n	\n		Satellite work offices/work from home\n\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '23', NULL, 'topics/transportation', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/23', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/23'),
(608, 'Systemic', ' Sustainability is the ability to endure. A sustainable system operates without need to draw on another system. Examples include healthy wetlands and forests.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	For human culture, sustainability means the potential for long-term support of people and their lifestyles. This has impact on environmental, economic, and social dimensions, which affect choices, behaviors, and costs.\n\n	Sustainable environments are built on healthy ecosystems. An ecosystem is a interconnection of producers and consumers of a material or resource. We learn about sustainability by studying earth systems and conservation biology. To create a sustainable world we must adjust human consumption of resources, by applying principles of economics.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '25', NULL, 'topics/systemic', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/25', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/25'),
