(563, 'Smart Grid', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	A smart grid delivers electricity from suppliers to consumers using digital technology with two-way communications to control appliances at consumers'' homes to save energy, reduce cost and increase reliability and transparency. It overlays the electrical grid with an information and net metering system, and includes smart meters. Such a modernized electricity network is being promoted by many governments as a way of addressing energy independence, global warming and emergency resilience issues.\n\n	\n\n	The smart grid is made possible by applying sensing, measurement and control devices with two-way communications to electricity production, transmission, distribution and consumption parts of the power grid that communicate information about grid condition to system users, operators and automated devices, making it possible to dynamically respond to changes in grid condition.\n\n	A smart grid includes an intelligent monitoring system that keeps track of all electricity flowing in the system. When power is least expensive the user can allow the smart grid to turn on selected home appliances such as washing machines or factory processes that can run at arbitrary hours. At peak times it could turn off selected appliances to reduce demand.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '11', NULL, 'topics/energy/smart-grid', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/11', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/11'),
(564, 'Renewables', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	One of nature''s principles of sustainability is to rely mostly on renewable energy. We can get renewable solar energy directly from the sun or indirectly from moving water, wind and biomass. Other forms of renewable energy are geothermal and tidal.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Recent Articles:\n\n	\n		\n	\n		Wind Energy Trends in the U.S. and Germany - A Comparison of Key Elements. Germany is often called the wind energy kingdom; the country’s wind energy industry is one of the largest worldwide. In 2007 Germany was the largest wind power generator in the world and currently it stands at the number three position, exceeded by China and the U.S. But what exactly is the driving force behind its success? What is so different about Germany’s wind energy industry compared to the US?&gt;&gt;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n	\n		\n	\n		U.S. photovoltaic (PV) industry hits a record high in 2009 According to a US-EIA report released in Jan 2011, the PV industry shipped nearly 1.3 peak gigawatts of cells and modules, representing a 30 percent year to year growth from the previous&gt;&gt;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '12', NULL, 'topics/energy/renewables', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/12', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/12'),
(566, 'Energy-Water Nexus', ' By Cheryl Weiden, EcoCloud Content Creator\n\n	Feb 3rd 2012\n\n	Water and energy, both necessary for life, are linked. Large amounts of water are needed for electricity generation; for example in the process of generating electricity from coal, water is used for extraction, processing, fuel conversion and cooling. Similarly a large amount of electricity is needed for extraction, treatment, and distribution of water. Up to now water and energy issues have been considered independently, but the increasing scarcity and cost of each will demand that they be considered together.\n\n	A study found that water requirements for electricity generation vary greatly depending on the primary energy source and the conversion and cooling technologies used. The biggest users are bioenergy from dedicated energy crops, hydroelectric facilities and thermoelectric facilities using once through cooling. Waste based facilities, solar photovoltaic, wind turbines and thermoelectric facilities using dry cooling use the least water.\n\n	Major water efficiencies can be achieved using technologies that target water efficiencies. Dry cooling and coal gasification can decrease California’s projected 2020 scenario for annual freshwater withdrawal and consumption by 66%; and by adding more water efficient technologies such as solar photovoltaic, wind and waste based bioenergy a 90% reduction is projected.\n\n	The study concluded:\n\n	\n		Water efficient electricity generation requires the right mix of primary energy sources, conversion technologies and cooling technologies. Utilities must plan to invest in such water efficient technologies as wind, solar photovoltaic and coal gasification.\n	\n		Policies that encourage water conservation can make a big impact. Such polices may include:\n\n\n	- Issuing conservation credits to power utilities that implement programs to reduce water use.\n\n	- Co-locating water treatment plants and power plants to facilitate the use of reclaimed water.\n\n	Further study is needed on the full life cycle of electricity generation including the construction of the power plant to understand the full water requirements of electricity generation.\n\n	Issues to be considered in the integration of water and electricity planning include:\n\n	\n		The transition to more water efficient means of electricity generation must be accomplished in a manner that will not compromise energy reliability.\n	\n		In addition to the impacts of water on electricity generation, planning must include other environmental impacts such as habitat, ecosystems and biodiversity.\n	\n		Impacts on water resources may be regional as seen in the bioenergy sector. For example some areas that have plenty of water may be more viable for production of dedicated energy crops.\n\n\n	Source: “California’s Energy-Water Nexus: Water Use in Electricity Generation”\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '39', NULL, 'topics/energy/energy-water-nexus', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/39', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/39'),
(567, 'Energy Policy', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	California to get 33% of energy from Renewable Resources by 2020\n\n	New SBX 1 2 Energy Bill introduced\n\n	Governor Jerry Brown of California on Tuesday 04/12/2011 signed SBX 1 2, a historic legislation which requires one third or 33% of California’s electricity to come from renewable resources like solar, wind and geothermal by December 31st 2020. This is the highest target of renewable energy utilization for generating electricity that has been set for any state in the U.S. today.\n\n	SBX 1 2 increases California’s previous target as specified in bill AB32 of achieving 20% of its electricity from renewable resources to a new target of 33% by 2020. Governor Brown in his signing message said that this new bill would help stimulate investments in green technologies in California, creating new jobs, improving local air quality, promoting energy independence and reducing green-house gas emissions.\n\n	The SBX 1 2 bill requires that the amount of electricity generated per year from eligible renewable energy resources be increased to an amount that equals at least 20% of the total electricity sold to retail customers in California per year by December 31, 2013, and 33% by December 31, 2020.\n\n	At the same time, the bill requires that the PUC, by January 1, 2012, establishes the quantity of electricity products from eligible renewable energy resources to be procured by each retail seller for specified compliance periods, sufficient to ensure that the procurement of electricity products from eligible renewable resources achieves 25% of sales by December 31, 2016, and 33% of retail sales by December 31st 2020, and that retail sellers procure not less than 33% of retail sales in all subsequent years.\n\n	This means that the biggest retail sellers of California - Pacific Gas and Electric Company, San Diego Gas and Electric, and Southern California Edison, would have to begin procuring electricity from eligible renewable energy producers in the manner, quantities and timelines as required by this law.&nbsp;\n\n	The passing of this bill sets California on an aggressive target of increasing its reliance on renewable energy resources and this is bound to have a positive cascading effect on green technologies and environment sustainability in the coming years in the state.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '50', NULL, 'topics/energy/energy-policy', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/50', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/50'),
(571, 'Microgrids', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Introduction\n\n	A microgrid is a local electric infrastructure network consisting of energy generation, energy storage and energy distribution that can operate independent of the traditional centralized grid. It is a miniaturized replica of the macro electric grid that can be connected or disconnected with the macro-grid, so that it can operate either as the main grid’s endpoint when connected to it, or can take over the responsibility of generating and providing electricity to its local domain when it isolates itself from the main grid.\n\n	Local sources of electricity generation that the microgrid employs include renewable resources like solar energy in the form of photovoltaic systems (PV), wind energy in the form of wind-power systems, fuel cells based systems and various other alternate sources of energy. These local and small scale power generation technologies, also known as Distributed Energy Resources (DER), usually produce electricity in the range of 3kW to 10,000 kW and offer alternatives or enhancements to the traditional electric power systems. DG (Distributed Generation) looks at integrating various DER within the grid.\n\n	The generated energy in a microgrid can also be stored within the microgrid, leading to highly reliable electric power that can be provided on demand while allowing isolation from the main grid. This energy storage concept finds various applications, from individual energy backup clusters that are able to provide emergency electricity services in case of blackouts to military “backpacks” of self-contained electrical infrastructure, to a new form of consumer’s convenience where energy can be precisely controlled per consumer’s demand leading to its efficient usage, and where the consumer has choice to sell back extra electricity to the grid, or to voluntarily choose between microgrids that provide electricity at affordable costs since generation is local.\n\n	From an efficiency-perspective microgrids also offer an added benefit of being able to utilize by-product heat that is generated from local generation sources like micro-turbines into local processes for space heating in buildings. This concept of combining heat and power (CHP) finds good use in urban infrastructure like green buildings which can now be designed efficiently to take into account such capabilities of the microgrid that they are a part of.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Background\n\n	In the United States, the microgrid concept started in the 1990s, as a response to the government’s concern about the reliability of national electricity transmission. Formulated as a solution to relieve stress on an overtaxed electricity grid, the microgrid concept was born and fully started taking shape in 2002 with various government funded research organizations. Funding for this research came from the government, specifically from the DOE and California Energy Commission in the form of the Consortium for Electric Reliability Technology Solutions (CERTS). CERTS included various national specialists and researchers like Bob Lasseter who pioneered the microgrid concept and engineered solutions that allowed distributed generation (DG) to connect to the grid at a single point and operate 24/7. With excellent researchers in the foray, it was simply a question of time before real life micro grids would become a reality.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Microgrids in action today\n\n	After years of deliberation and thorough research, DOE has today started providing funding to Universities, school districts, hospitals, laboratories, industrial parks, military basis, national businesses, and prisons, for deploying microgrid technology. For instance, the Sacramento Municipal Utility District (SMUD) bases it system on the original CERTS research when it operates a 310-kilowatt base load microgrid. SMUD’s microgrid comprises 3 100 kW reciprocating generators with a 120 ton CHP system from TecoGen and a 10 kW photovoltaic (PV) system. Along with generation, the project also plans to integrate storage technology, for example, a 500 kW zinc-bromine flow battery. Integral to the SMUD project is the utilization of CHP systems that can double the system’s efficiency. Waste-heat from the 3 generators powers the absorption chiller system that in turn powers the air conditioning.\n\n	Another example is collaboration between Chevron Energy Systems, Satcon Power Systems and PG&amp;E for decreasing peak load, alleviating grid congestion and reducing carbon footprint by integrating microgrid technology within the Santa Rita prison. This microgrid is based off a 1.2 MW solar array. Other partners like Chevron are adding several 2 kW wind turbines and a battery to the microgrid system. During outages, the project plans to reuse energy stored in clean sodium-sulfur battery.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Tomorrow’s Drivers\n\n	CERTS in collaboration with AEP today helps define and test the microgrids model by looking at large scale integration of DER with the grid. In conjunction, smart grid development is driven by NIST (National Institute of Science and Technology) which is responsible for defining similar interoperable standards for the smart grid, in collaboration with EPRI (Electric Power Research Institute) and Enernex. Interoperable standards between these two approaches, coupled with various IEEE standards for islanding and energy-storage will further help bring in the microgrid concept as an integral part of the smart grid evolution for tomorrow.\n\n	Lower costs will also help drive microgrid deployment. While costs per kWh for centralized generation is increasing because of feedstock efficiency (CHP) and regulatory issues, the cost per kWh for distributed generation (DG) using microgrids has been falling because of low cost wind and solar, low cost storage and sensor networks to enable microgrids. All these factors together can help drive microgrid development and deployment for the future.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	References\n\n	1) http://certs.lbl.gov/certs-der-pubs.html\n\n	2) “Why two grids can be better than one – How the CERTS Microgrid Evolved from Concept to Practice” by Elizabeth McGowan, U.S. DOE, May 2011\n\n	3) Microgrid and Smart Grid activities at SMUD, presented by Mark Rawson, Senior Research Project Manager, SMUD, 2010 Microgrid Symposium\n\n	4) “Microgrid Markets and Opportunities” – Chapter One Report, May 2010, by NanoMarkets.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '16', NULL, 'topics/energy/smart-grid/microgrids', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/16', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/16'),
