(610, 'SCVWD Study', ' \n	Santa Clara Valley Water District\n\n	\n	The Santa Clara Valley Water District (District) in California is a water wholesaler for all of Santa Clara County and offers water conservation and water recycling programs for the areas’ 15 cities, 1.8 million residents and 200,000 commuters. While the primary goal of water recycling programs and water conservation programs is to use water more efficiently thereby reducing the demand for potable water, water conservation and water recycling save energy (and consequently reduce air pollution because energy production generates air pollutants) by reducing flow through California’s energy-intensive water supply chain. In 2007 the District was the first agency in the state to complete an analysis to estimate the energy saved (and air pollutant emissions reduced) by the District’s water conservation and water recycling programs. The District recently updated this analysis and developed a District-specific water-energy-air pollution model to incorporate the complexities of the District’s water supply system. The District’s water recycling programs and water conservation programs have been in operation since FY 92-93 and have saved 547,000 acre-feet of potable water. The model’s whole systems approach for quantifying water-related energy use provides water supply planners with an overview of the energy intensity of different water supply scenarios.\n\n	For FY 92-93 through FY 08-09, the District has saved approximately 2.67 billion kilowatt-hours (kWh) of energy, which represents a financial savings of approximately $347 million and is equivalent to the annual electricity required for over 412,000 households. Through saving energy the District eliminated the emissions of approximately 625 million kg of carbon dioxide (over the FY 92-93 through FY 08-09 time span), the equivalent of removing over 115,000 passenger cars from the roads for one year. The District also reduced the emissions of several other air pollutants due to the energy saved by its water conservation and water recycling programs: reactive organic gases (39,361 kg), carbon monoxide (564,349 kg), nitrogen oxides (275,610 kg), sulfur oxides (26,259 kg), and particulate matter smaller than 10 microns (48,560 kg). The new report includes an expanded section regarding recycled water, including the energy saved (and air pollutant emissions reduced) from the use of advanced treated recycled water, which the District will be producing within the next three years.\n\n	For more information about Santa Clara Valley’s energy water savings see the latest Watts to Water Report published in May 2011 on Santa Clara Valley Water District website (put in search terms “energy and water” to find the pdf).\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '93', NULL, 'topics/water/energy-water-connection/scvwd-study', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/93', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/93'),
(573, 'Solar', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	Solar Technology&nbsp;Innovations and Highlights\n\n	Solar Power Assets&nbsp;- Building The Solar Highway to Energy Independence\n\n	Posted April 17, 2011 by Anuradha Munshi\n\n	Solar Power Assets (SPA) is planning to deploy rapid, massive, low-cost and innovative Solar Electricity generating facilities in order to create Solar Highways, Solar Rivers and Solar Farms.\n\n	SPA will generate low cost solar energy by sequentially stringing and deploying highly efficient solar PV modules along public roadways and waterways. It will focus on lowering solar generation and installation costs by eliminating energy transmission losses and by providing automated installation and deployment methods to drive overall solar costs down to $2Wp.\n\n	SPA will utilize vast corridors including rights of way that are already available for solar energy generation and transmission (e.g. on highways, aqueducts), creating what it calls “Solar Rivers”, “Solar Highways” and “Solar Farms”. Energy transmission losses will be reduced with the help of an innovative proprietary power transmission backbone, the Cumulative Transmission Line (CTL).\n\n	SPA wants to start its mission with California by collaborating with key departments in California State Government. Over 55,000 miles of California''s Roadways can be utilized to generate up to 6GW of solar power, while over 2600 miles of waterways in CA can generate 7GW of solar energy. SPA believes that by focusing on lowering installation costs, it will introduce faster time to energy generation, eliminate high power transmission lines and ultimately drive down solar electricity power generation costs to match or beat fossil fuel electricity cost within three years.\n\n	About Solar Power Assets\n\n	Solar Power Assets, LLC is a self-funded startup incorporated in June 2007 focused on providing sound energy alternatives that are lower in cost and reduce dependency on conventional energy sources.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		Other Recent Topics:\n	\n		\n	\n		U.S. photovoltaic (PV) industry hits a record high in 2009 According to a US-EIA report released in Jan 2011, the PV industry shipped nearly 1.3 peak gigawatts of cells and modules, representing a 30 percent year to year growth from the previous&gt;&gt;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '54', NULL, 'topics/energy/renewables/solar', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/54', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/54'),
(574, 'Wind', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	Wind Power Growth\n\n	\n\n	As shown in the diagram above, Wind power in the U.S. has been the fastest growing renewable source of generating electric power for several years now. This has been possible due to incentives like wind generators being eligible for Federal production and investment tax credits. The passage of the 2005 Energy Policy Act (EPACT2005) has allowed interest-free financing via Clean Renewable Energy Bonds (CREBs) to be available to government entities investing in wind energy. The 2002 and 2008 Farm Bills (Section 9006, under Title IX) also contain various provisions for grant and loan guarantee for wind projects to farmers, ranchers, and other rural businesses.\n\n	Such federal incentives for wind energy have been meaningful and timely, and the numbers speak for themselves. In 2009, generation from wind power increased 33.5 percent over 2008, bringing the share of total generation to 1.9 percent. This followed year-over-year generation gains of 49.3 percent in 2006, 29.6 percent in 2007, and 60.7 percent in 2008. Wind capacity in 2009 totaled 34,296 megawatts (MW), as compared to 24,651 MW in 2008. Clearly there are lots of opportunities for growth and investment in this area.\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	\n		Other Recent Topics:\n	\n		\n	\n		Wind Energy Trends in the U.S. and Germany - A Comparison of Key Elements.&nbsp; Germany is often called the wind energy kingdom; the country’s wind energy industry is one of the largest worldwide. In 2007 Germany was the largest wind power generator in the world and currently it stands at the number three position, exceeded by China and the U.S. But what exactly is the driving force behind its success? What is so different about Germany’s wind energy industry compared to the US?&gt;&gt;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '55', NULL, 'topics/energy/renewables/wind', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/55', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/55'),
(575, 'Case Studies', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	Solar Industry – Dealing with Toxic Wastes\n\n	As solar energy rapidly emerges and proliferates into the fabric of our society, little thought is being given to the environmental impacts of producing and eventually recycling solar PV panels. Disturbing global trends seem to be emerging; in 2008 it was reported that a Chinese solar plant was regularly dumping extremely toxic Silicon Tetrachloride on a nearby farmland.\n\n	Today, competition and time to market drive many companies involved in this nascent but very highly promising area of Solar energy. As a result, the solar PV industry is rapidly evolving new materials and processes to increase cell efficiency and reduce production costs. Unfortunately many of these technologies and processes use toxic, explosive, corrosive or potentially carcinogenic materials like Cadmium and Selenium, while other products use materials that have not been completely tested.\n\n	Over the years, academia and industry have researched new materials and processes for generating electricity based off solar. While progress is made at increasing the rate of efficiency of utilization of solar energy, the same is not always true when considering mitigation of environmental impacts of these materials and processes.\n\n	\n\n	Best Research–Cell Efficiencies - courtesy of National Renewable Energy Laboratory\n\n	Emerging thin-film and nanotechnology-based cells are known to pose health and environment dangers. For example the process of sawing c-Si wafers creates a significant amount of waste silicon dust called Kerf that could cause respiratory problems to workers while polluting air and water. Similarly the use of Silane gas is known to be explosive and the industry reports several accidents per year. Silicon Tetrachloride and Sulphur Hexafluoride are two other very toxic and potent chemicals used in Solar PV production that can be very hazardous, going so far as to create acid rains at worst. At the other end of the spectrum the question of dealing with recycling of these toxic solar PV panels as they end their life cycle in 20-25 years is left largely unanswered.\n\n	Silicon Valley Toxics Coalition (SVTC) a 25 year veteran organization believes that the following measures and policies will help in effectively turning this trend:\n\n	\n		\n			Research, reduce and eliminate use of toxic materials during production – In particular, usage of the following toxic materials should be phased out and discouraged - cadmium, lead, mercury, brominated flame retardants, chromium, along with Sulphur Hexafluoride, Hydrogen selenide, arsenic and phosphine.\n	\n	\n		\n			Extended Producer Responsibility – Ensure that Solar PV manufacturers are responsible for lifetime impacts of their products. This includes sharing responsibility for safely recycling the solar PV panels that companies produce once these panels reach end of life.\n	\n	\n		\n			Ensure proper testing of new and emerging materials and processes and take a precautionary approach. For example, standards that measure environmental impacts need to be deployed as part of the production and test release cycle.\n	\n	\n		\n			Expand the recycling technology and design products for easy recycling – Companies need to look at safer ways of recycling solar panels, especially those that already have toxic substances, to minimize polluting the environment.\n	\n	\n		\n			Create green jobs that protect worker health and safety and protect community health and safety.\n	\n\n\n	Reference:\n\n	A Silicon Valley Toxic Coalition White Paper – Towards a Just and Sustainable Solar Energy Industry, 2009 \n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '58', NULL, 'topics/energy/renewables/case-studies', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/58', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/58');
