(576, 'Recycled', ' By Mary Kean, EcoCloud Water Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Recycled water is water that has been used, treated, and distributed for beneficial reuse within the community. Recycled water (sometimes known as reclaimed water) is a sustainable, high-quality water supply – it reduces our dependency on imported water and preserves our drinking water supply for current and future generations. Half of the water supply in Santa Clara County is imported from the Sierra Nevada and the Sacramento/San Joaquin River Delta, and restrictions on these limited supplies continue to tighten. Recycled water is used in lieu of potable water to irrigate food crops and landscaping, cool buildings, flush toilets and urinals, and contribute to industrial processes. Recycled water is used all over the world; in Southern California, it undergoes further treatment and is used to supplement drinking water\n	supplies.\n\n	Recycled water is available in Silicon Valley. Recycled water is available in portions of San Jose, Santa Clara, Milpitas, Sunnyvale, Mountain View, Palo Alto, and Gilroy. The South Bay Water Recycling program operates the largest system in Silicon Valley, providing recycled water to over 600 customers through 120 miles of dedicated pipelines in San Jose, Santa Clara, and Milpitas. To find out how you can access this source of recycled water, see Connecting to the SBWR System.\n\n	\n\n	Recycled water has a long track record of successful use in cooling towers. Since 1998, South Bay Water Recycling customers have successfully used recycled water in lieu of potable water for cooling. Current customers include public institutions, power plants, manufacturing facilities, and datacenters. Learn More...\n\n	Click the Tools tab for information on the recycled water piping in the Bay Area, including a map.\n\n	More Information:\n\n	Water Recycling and Reuse by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency\n	(EPA)\n\n	Pacific Southwest Sustainable Water Infrastructure Program, U.S. EPA\n\n	Ensuring a Sustainable Future: An Energy Management Guidebook for\n	Wastewater and Water Utilities, U.S. EPA\n\n	Climate Change and Water, an overview of relevant web pages from the\n	U.S. EPA and SCVWD''s Climate Change Portal.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '14', NULL, 'topics/water/recycled', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/14', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/14'),
(577, 'Decentralized', ' By Mary Kean &nbsp;EcoCloud Water Lead\n\n	If you live in Australia, Hawaii or a developing nation with limited or no access to urban water infrastructure systems, the chances are that you are already quite familiar with decentralized water management. For the rest of us, a decentralized water infrastructure is defined as:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		mimicking the natural hydrologic cycle\n	\n		locating water management at the community or household level\n	\n		locating water recovery at the community or household level\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	This differs from the centralized model of managing urban water at higher (e.g. regional) levels. What once was the realm of “alternative lifestyles” has now become mainstream as water supplies are endangered by overdrafts cause by overpopulation in water poor geographic areas and misuse of available water resources.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Our goal in the Decentralized Water section is to identify practices that will bring water use in line with water supply, in part, by focusing on what type of water is needed at point of use. In other words, it has been our practice in the United States to use energy-intensive water transported and cleaned to potable standards for end uses that do not necessitate potable water. Let’s be smarter water stewards by using the right water for the right job.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	A clear example is flushing toilets with energy-intensive potable water, when water treated to lesser standards, such as minimally treated rainwater and graywater, is perfectly appropriate to flush urine and feces through pipes to a wastewater treatment plant. Employing these largely untapped water sources also brings the user further in line with the natural hydrologic system by using rainwater onsite, keeping it from becoming stormwater that picks up pollutants from sidewalks and streets carrying them down storm drains into natural waterways.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Issues in implementing decentralized water include:\n\n	\n		identify all potential sources for water supply\n	\n		identify water end use needs and practices\n	\n		establish baseline water use\n	\n		create a water budget\n	\n		consider water supply costs and roi\n	\n		know state and local laws and ordinances\n	\n		create an integrated management plan that takes all water uses, sources and treatment into account\n	\n		maximize potential for decentralized energy gain\n	\n		integrate systems to capture, infiltrate, use, and reuse water on-site (rain, gray, storm, black water management)\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;Potential Tactics for Decentralized Water Management:\n\n	\n		rainwater harvesting\n	\n		graywater harvesting\n	\n		earthworks for onsite retention and infiltration\n	\n		raingardens\n	\n		permeable pavement\n	\n		onsite or localized blackwater treatment\n	\n		compost toilets\n	\n		urine diversion for plant food\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;Where to find the information you need to match water supply sources with water end use:\n\n	Efficiency:\n\n	http://www.whollyh2o.org/efficiency.html\n\n	Rainwater Harvesting (RWH):\n\n	http://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater.html\n\n	Graywater:\n\n	http://www.oasisdesign.net/greywater/\n\n	http://www.greywateraction.org/greywater-recycling/\n\n	http://www.whollyh2o.org/graywater.html\n\n	Stormwater:\n\n	https://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater/overview.html\n\n	http://cfpub.epa.gov/npdes/home.cfm?program_id=6\n\n	Blackwater:\n\n	http://www.whollyh2o.org/blackwater.html\n\n	http://www.livingmachines.com/\n\n	Low Impact Development:\n\n	http://www.epa.gov/owow/NPS/lid/\n\n	Audits:\n\n	http://www.awwa.org/Resources/WaterLossControl.cfm?ItemNumber=48055\n\n	http://www.swfwmd.state.fl.us/conservation/audits/wateraudits.htm/\n\n	Water Budgets:\n\n	http://www.whollyh2o.org/rainwater/rainwater-res/item/66-water-budgeting.html/\n\n	http://waterbudget.sustainablesources.com/\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '15', NULL, 'topics/water/decentralized', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/15', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/15'),
(578, 'Conservation', ' By Mary Kean, EcoCloud Water Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Water conservation, which relies on a thorough cost-benefit analysis to develop program details and rebate levels, is widely considered the most cost-effective option in any water supply portfolio.\n\n	Water conservation programs reduce demand on existing water and energy supplies, helping to lessen the costs and environmental impacts of developing additional supplies. In addition to helping to meet long-term water reliability goals, the District’s programs also help meet short-term demands placed on supply during critical dry periods as well as during a regulatory drought. These programs also protect the South Bay salt-marsh habitat and the endangered species that live there by reducing freshwater effluent released from wastewater treatment facilities.\n\n	In November 2009, Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger signed the historic water conservation bill, S.B. 7, at the SCVWD campus. This bill mandates the long-term goals of reducing per-capita urban water use by 20 percent by the year 2020. SCVWD’s water conservation program resulted in nearly 50,600 acre-feet of water savings in FY 09/10. http://www.valleywater.org/EkContent.aspx?id=2991\n\n	Water Conservation Resources from Bay Area organizations\n\n	\n		Bay Area Green Business Program\n	\n		\n			The Bay Area Green Business Program is a partnership of environmental agencies and utilities that offers assistance and incentives to participating businesses to conserve energy and water, minimize waste, prevent pollution, and shrink their carbon footprints.\n	\n	\n		East Bay Municipal Utility District\n	\n		\n			WaterSmart Guidebook: Water Use Efficiency Plan and Review Guide for New Businesses . A 242 page guidebook in PDF format, providing information on water-saving technologies for the commercial, industrial and institutional sectors.\n		\n			www.ebmud.com/for-customers/conservation-rebates-and-services/commercial/watersmart-guidebook\n	\n	\n		Santa Clara Valley Water District http://www.valleywater.org/Programs/ConservationForBusinesses.aspx\n	\n		\n			Information on rebates and Water Conservation Programs in the Bay Area\n	\n	\n		Wholly H20\n	\n		\n			Wholly H2O - California''s Integrated Water Reuse Management Center is a catalyst for sustainable, integrated water management in California. Wholly H2O uses locally-adapted solutions for water efficiency, (re)use of rain, storm, gray, and black water.\n	\n\n\n	Other Water Conservation Resources\n\n	\n		California Urban Water Conservation Council (CUWCC)\n	\n		\n			CUWCC is a partnership of environmental agencies and utilities offering assistance and incentives that verifies participating businesses conserve energy and water, minimize waste, prevent pollution and shrink their carbon footprints.\n	\n	\n		StopWaste\n	\n		\n			A public agency serving Alameda County that offers programs, education and assistance on source reduction and recycling.\n	\n	\n		Bay Friendly Landscaping and Gardening\n	\n		\n			A program of StopWaste, Bay Friendly offers workshops, classes and resources for a sustainable approach to landscaping and gardening for residents, landscape professionals and public agencies.\n	\n\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '35', NULL, 'topics/water/con', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/35', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/35'),
