(683, 'Invitation to Enter Call for Solutions (closes 1/31/2013)', 'Collectively, human beings and our industrial society are destroying the life support systems of the planet. This is not inevitable. Human genius and creativity can be used to heal and repair and even strengthen these systems. Sustainable Silicon Valley and our partners, including NASA Ames Research Center, Silver Spring Networks and Microsoft are collaborating on a conference that will be held in Silicon Valley on May 23, 2013 to explore in-depth, solutions that can yield planetary sustainability. \n\nInvitation to Action \nWe invite you to share your solutions by Jan. 31, 2013 that can contribute to planetary sustainability. Do you have a technology, policy or behavior-changing proposal that is scalable and game-changing? If so, please enter the Call for Solutions. Your idea will be posted on the EcoCloud website to stimulate dialog with other concerned people around the world. The most promising solutions will be selected as finalists to be presented at the conference on May 23, 2013. Winners will be selected for special recognition by a panel of distinguished experts from a wide range of fields. We are especially interested in approaches that span domains (such as energy and water). The conference will include time for match-making among solution inventors and potential funders and integrators with the goal of creating ecosystems of solutions, and building momentum for implementation and action.\n\nWhat are Planetary Life Support Systems?\nPlanet Earth is made up of many interwoven systems that create an environment conducive to life. For example, rich soils, full of microorganisms and communities of insects and invertebrates, make it possible for trees, grasses and other plants to grow. The soil absorbs water and releases it slowly, to reduce floods and withstand dry seasons. Tree roots hold the soil in place to resist erosion from wind and rain. Larger animals graze on the plants and keep those populations in check. Predators and disease keep the plant-eating animals from over-grazing, yielding a dynamic equilibrium among species. \n\nThese systems affect each other. For example, plant canopies help keep the surface temperatures of the earth comfortable for living creatures. They serve as the lungs of the planet, breathing in carbon dioxide and breathing out oxygen. The atmosphere around the planet moderates storm intensity and precipitation patterns. As human industry burns forests to clear them for agriculture and burns fossil fuels for energy, we have changed the chemistry of the atmosphere, adding huge amounts of carbon dioxide, methane and other gases that create a green house effect, warming the surface temperature of the oceans and land and creating changes in precipitation and other weather patterns that have resulted in catastrophic storms, floods, droughts, heat waves, and wind that cause damage to crops, property and lives. \n\nThe chemistry of the oceans are changed as they absorb huge quantities of carbon dioxide, becoming more acidic and less hospitable to the microscopic life forms that are the base of the aquatic food chain. Over fishing and extensive pollution from plastic waste and toxic chemicals, such as agricultural run-off, also is threatening the health and productivity of the oceans.\n\nMany other systems allow the basis for human agriculture and civilization to exist and flourish. It is up to us to invest in the health and well-being of these systems over the long-term, and not just extract resources for short term use and profit. Self-restraint through social norms, the rule of law, taxes on “externalities”; technology that can reuse and recycle resources and generate energy from sun and wind; and, cultivation of a culture of conservation are some of the ways that humanity can shift towards truly sustainable civilization. Now is the time. Join us at WEST Summit 2013.', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '34', 9, 'blog2/view/34', 'admin/blog2/edit/34', 'admin/blog2/delete/34'),
(590, 'Bus Rapid Transit', ' \n	\n\n	Light Rail Without the Rails\n\n	Bus Rapid Transit (BRT) is a system of busing that in many ways emulates light rail, but without the expense or permanence of tracks.&nbsp; Features include dedicated lanes, priority crossing through lights, at-level boarding, pre-boarding ticket purchasing and, in some cases, on-board wi-fi.&nbsp; Curitiba, Brazil made the concept known, but many places in the U.S. (including Eugene, OR, Los Angeles, CA, Las Vegas, NV, and Boston, MA) have adopted it as well, with great success.&nbsp; Now the issue is front and center right here in Silicon Valley as communities along a proposed BRT line up El Camino Real from the HP Pavilion in San Jose to the Palo Alto Transit Center are considering whether to support the effort or not.\n\n	Here in Silicon Valley:&nbsp; Sunnyvale’s Choice--Rejected\n\n	On May 22, 2012, Sunnyvale City Council voted 4 to 3 not to go forward with pursuing BRT for El Camino Real. &nbsp;\n\n	Sunnyvale has long pursued more public transportation. When the light rail was being extended, downtown Sunnyvale lost out to Mountain View so that the rail lines brush through on the north side of the city before heading up to Moffet Field and on to Mountain View’s Castro St.&nbsp; The plan for the El Camino Corridor route (which is one of three routes planned by the Valley Transportation Association under the name “Valley Rapid”&nbsp; http://www.valleyrapid.org/what_is_valley_rapid/) would have offered service at 10 minute intervals and take many of the current 522 route buses off the streets (and out of the car lanes).&nbsp; It would also have taken away the parking lanes along El Camino and create bike lanes in order to make the space for the dedicated lanes in the middle of the roadway.&nbsp; This removal of parking space had some people and businesses worried, but there are only 300 spaces in Sunnyvale along El Camino as opposed to thousands of off-street spaces.&nbsp; The parking is in general underutilized anyway along El Camino, being a dangerous and undesirable place to park.&nbsp; Bicycle advocates welcomed the addition of the bike lanes along bicycle-unfriendly El Camino, and environmentally the plan could remove 4,555 metric tons of greenhouse gas annually.\n\n	While not as intensive as installing rails and electric overhead wires, the project would still have been a huge one.&nbsp; However, funding for the Valley Rapid projects is financed by the Santa Clara County Measure A half-cent sales tax and federal funds, so Sunnyvale would not have been paying for its development.&nbsp; As a comparison, light rail would cost $100 million per mile to build, whereas BRT rings in at $8-$13 million per mile and is expected to cost less to operate.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '56', NULL, 'topics/transportation/bus-rapid-transit', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/56', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/56'),
