(597, 'Sustainability Leaders Forum', ' \n	Sustainability Leaders Forum (SLF)\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	The&nbsp;Sustainability Leaders Forum, (formerly called the Sustainability Leaders Learning Exchange, which evolved from “Green Team Leaders”) meets quarterly to build the capacity and effectiveness of sustainability leaders by sharing best practices and presenting expert knowledge about sustainability. Justine Burt, Principal at Justine Burt and Associates says: "The Sustainable Leaders Forum is SSV at its best. This well organized program elevates regional sustainability efforts by giving sustainability change agents a forum to share their wisdom".\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Excited to sign up for a future SLF event?\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Design for Sustainability Workshop\n\n	\n		When: November 1st, 2012 3:00 PM – 6:00 PM\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				TOPIC:&nbsp;Designing for sustainability can be a powerful catalyst for innovation as products and processes are optimized or completely re-imagined. Learn how to use sustainability constraints to open new possibilities, using techniques such as biomimicry, cradle-to-cradle design and customer-centered design.\n			\n				This is a hands-on workshop. Please come with specific products or services on which to apply the methods presented. (Backup topics also available).&nbsp;Bring colleagues from design, engineering, sustainability, supply chain, manufacturing, operations and marketing. These tools can be applied for services, as well.\n			\n				&nbsp;Event Details\n			\n				Thursday, November 1, 2012\n				2:45 pm: Registration\n				3:00 pm - 6:00 pm: Workshop\n				Location: Silver Spring Networks\n			\n				Refreshments will be provided.\n			\n				Register Here\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Curious about what you’ve missed?&nbsp; Here is information about past SLF events:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Cradle-to-Cradle Materials Management\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	TOPIC:&nbsp;"Material flow in a cradle-to-cradle economy means that there is no "waste." Outputs from one process become inputs to another, by design. Come learn from expert practitioners from Cradle to Cradle Products Innovation Institute, Adobe, Speciality Solid Waste and US EPA on how Silicon Valley companies and cities are bringing this transformational (and profitable) vision to reality.\n\n	Bridgett Luther''s Cradle-2-Cradle PowerPoint\n\n	Shannon Davis'' EPA Materials Management PowerPoint\n\n	George Denise''s Adobe Facilities PowerPoint\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Green Data Centers: Economics and Operations (Silicon Valley''s Annual Earth Day Event): April 27, 2012\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Hosted by Vantage Data Centers and GE Intelligent Platforms at SAP\n\n	Data Centers represent a significant opportunity for companies (and all institutions) to save energy and costs, while achieving high performance. The life cycle of energy for high technology gear is greater than the cost of the equipment. The event addressed Data Center best practices from companies and experts that have achieved significant efficiencies and savings, resulting in strategic business impact. Presentations at the event also focused on how to achieve a 1.12 PUE without sacrificing reliability and quality.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Employee Engagement 2.0 - Success Stories and the way ahead: March 8, 2012 &nbsp;Hosted by and at eBay in San Jose\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Employees can be a powerful force to move the sustainability needle in companies and spread sustainability thinking in hard-to-reach functional areas of the company. The presentations at this event were the NEEF study on Employee Engagement 2.0, eBay success stories and future plans, Environmental Defense Fund’s energy treasure hunts as a way to engage employees and short Pecha-Kucha style presentations on commuting and other sustainability oriented employee programs.\n\n	Speakers:\n\n	\n		NEEF study presented by Suparna Vashisht: Presentation on highlights of the recently published NEEF White paper on Employee Engagement 2.0 which includes the results of the survey NEEF conducted of over 1300 business professionals.&nbsp;&nbsp;NEEF Study by Suparna (pdf)\n	\n		eBay, J.D. Norton: How to achieve sustained engagement (awaiting file from presenter)\n	\n		Environmental Defense Fund, Beth Trask: Case studies of companies that EDF has helped establish successful employee engagement program.&nbsp;(awaiting file from presenter)\n	\n		Pecha Kucha 5’ presentations:\n\n\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 511 Services:&nbsp;511 Employee Services (pdf)\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; RideSpring :&nbsp;Making alternative Commuting Easier and more Rewarding (pdf)\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Satellite Telework Centers :&nbsp;Work Anywhere (pdf)\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; SunShares:&nbsp;Silicon Valley Leadership Group Sunshares (pdf)\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Eco Cloud:&nbsp;EcoCloud and Employee Engagement (pdf)\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	"Unstuff Your Life" with organization expert&nbsp;Andrew Mellen: &nbsp;January 12, 2012&nbsp;Hosted by and at Net App in Sunnyvale.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	From hardcore hoarders to overwhelmed soccer moms, and from harried executives to exhausted small business owners, this workshop contains vital instruction for achieving a degree of efficiency, productivity and calmness that has previously eluded you. &nbsp;Join the "Unstuff" forum&nbsp;for a summary and a chance to join the discussion.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Water Infrastructure and CII Best Management Practices: November 3, 2012 Hosted by and at Intuit in Mountain View.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	SLF’s November event was on innovative ideas for Water Infrastructure and Water Best Management Practices in CII – Commercial, institutional and industrial.&nbsp; &nbsp;Attendees included water conservation managers from utilities, executives from commercial and high tech businesses, facility managers, and many others.&nbsp;&nbsp; Discussions on these issues occured.\n\n	The presentations included:\n\n	Introduction to Water Footprinting Tools and Frameworks (pdf)&nbsp; &nbsp;VIDEO!\n\n	Re-defining CA Urban Water Infrastructure (pdf)\n\n	CII Water Task Force Update (pdf)&nbsp; &nbsp;VIDEO!\n\n	Success Story: Dupont Fabros (pdf)&nbsp; &nbsp;VIDEO!\n\n	EcoCloud: An innovative, collaborative, Industrial Ecosystem for sustainable development (pdf)&nbsp; &nbsp;VIDEO!\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	See also EcoCloud Water Metrics and Tools for detailed analysis of over 75 water online and downloadable tools, standards, guidance, software, and certification schemes (many of which are free) for businesses, organizations, and utilities.\n\n	You can join the discussion groups on SSV’s EcoCloud on these two issues: CII High Tech-Sector Water Task Force Group and Wastewater as a Resource Forum.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Designing for Sustainability through Biomimicry: September 8, 2011, Hosted by and at Genetech.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	The meeting included presentations and discussions on:\n\n	\n		an overview of biomimicry\n	\n		Agua Via &nbsp;spoke about Water Filtration system based on how kidneys filter impurities\n	\n		Qualcomm spoke on technology for the next generation of mobil device screens which will leverages MEMS to create color using interference (similar to that found in butterfly wings)\n	\n		Discussion groups led by presenters to explore applications of biomimicry in product categories picked by audience.\n\n\n	This event was attended by sustainability leaders, designers, engineers, product marketing experts and others who wanted to learn about Biomimicry and an approach that can ignite your ingenuity and open new avenues for invention inspired by nature.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Implementing Sustainability: &nbsp;A solutions lab event hosted by NetApp,&nbsp;Wednesday, June 1 2011\n\n	\n	SSV’s Sustainability Leaders Forum Peer-to-Peer event hosted by NetApp on June 1st, received high marks from the attendees. Nearly 80% of the attendees said that they found the event “Very Useful”.\n\n	Six speakers made presentations regarding an experience related to implementing a sustainability initiative. The format for the meeting was patterned on Pecha Kucha or Ignite, with each speaker making a 5-6 minute presentation with slides that auto-advanced every 10-30 seconds. The audience then split into groups and discussed one of the six presentations with a view to learning from the experience or brainstorming solutions to the challenges/setbacks presented.&nbsp; Finally one person from each group shared the synopsis of the discussion with the rest of the audience. The issues discussed were:\n\n	\n		Spurring Energy Efficiency - Challenges and Opportunities: Rick Row, Energy Upgrade California\n	\n		Best Practices for Initiating and Establishing Sustainability Initiatives:&nbsp; Bruce England, Silver Springs Network\n	\n		Leveraging the VTA for Sustainability efforts: Mike Hursh, Santa Clara VTA\n	\n		Overcoming the challenge of being Green in a multi-tenant space: Danielle Bricker (Yahoo!), Frank Teng (Jones Lang LaSalle)\n	\n		Building Efficient Data Centers&nbsp;– lessons learned: Peter Perrault, NetApp\n	\n		Electronics Recycling and Recovery – the promise and the reality: Tom Hogye, ECS Refining\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	“Value Creation from Sustainability Best Practices” Panel Discussion February 18, 2010\n\n	Sustainability Best Practices Among Leading Companies. Article by Michal Lenchner\n\n	Key Takeaways from Panel Discussion. Article by Kanal Consulting\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '76', NULL, 'topics/systemic/sustainability-leaders-forum', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/76', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/76'),
(965, 'Green Teams', ' \n	Are you on a Green Team or do you want to start one?&nbsp; You are not alone.&nbsp; Here are some resources to give you ideas and encouragement, get you started, and help you succeed:\n\n\n	Why Green Teams are good, how they work, and how to get one started:\n\n	\n		Corporate Green Teams: Sustainable Business from the Bottom Up\n	\n		Forming the Green Team: Advice on forming a green team in an office or building\n	\n		Start a Green Team\n	\n		Leading from the Middle: The Power of Green Champions\n	\n		The Architecture of Green Teams\n	\n		Green Teams: Engaging Employees in Sustainability. Article by Deborah Fleischer\n	\n		Top 10 Tips to Green Your Workplace. Article by Justine Burt\n	\n		Bay Area Green Teams Top Challenges 2009 Notes from Green Team Leaders Meeting, Sept 2009. Top challenges facing Green Team Leaders among SSV Partners.\n	\n		Launching A Green Team Presentation on June 23, 2009 by Lorin May of eBay\n	\n		Facilities and Green Teams - Working Together Presentation on June 23, 2009 by Laurel Perry of Symantec\n	\n		How to Start a Green Team in Your Organization (book review) Review of Senge''s Book "The Necessary Revolution: How Individuals and Organizations are Working Together to Create a Sustainable World"\n	\n		Corporate Green Teams: A New Social Trend at Work? A Conference Report and Research Summary by Don Bray, AltaTerra Research\n	\n		Creating Evolutionary Learning Communities\n	\n		Sustainable Value Creation Excerpt from Peter Senge''s Book "The Necessary Revolution"\n\n\n	&nbsp;\nExisting Green Teams at the company level:\n\n	\n		eBay Green Team\n	\n		Genentech Green Team\n	\n		How to "Green" Your Intuit Office\n	\n		Green Teams at U.S. Department of Agriculture\n	\n		Burlingame: Citizens Environmental Council Burlingame\n	\n		Cupertino: South Bay/Peninsula Simplicity Circle\n	\n		Los Altos: Los Altos Green Ribbon Citizens Committee\n	\n		Menlo Park: Menlo Park Green Ribbon Citizens Committee\n	\n		Mountain View:\n		\n			\n				Green Mountain View\n			\n				Mountain View Coalition for Sustainable Planning\n			\n				Mountain View Cool Cities\n		\n	\n	\n		Palo Alto:Redwood City: Sustainable Redwood City\n		\n			\n				Community Environmental Action Partnership\n			\n				Acterra: Action for a Sustainable Earth\n		\n	\n	\n		San Jose: San Jose Cool Cities Team\n	\n		Sunnyvale: Sunnyvale Cool Cities\n\n\n	&nbsp;\nExisting Green Teams at the Community Level:\n\n	\n		Burlingame: Citizens Environmental Council Burlingame\n	\n		Cupertino: South Bay/Peninsula Simplicity Circle\n	\n		Los Altos: Los Altos Green Ribbon Citizens Committee\n	\n		Menlo Park: Menlo Park Green Ribbon Citizens Committee\n	\n		Mountain View:\n		\n			\n				Green Mountain View\n			\n				Mountain View Coalition for Sustainable Planning\n			\n				Mountain View Cool Cities\n		\n	\n	\n		Palo Alto:Redwood City: Sustainable Redwood City\n		\n			\n				Community Environmental Action Partnership\n			\n				Acterra: Action for a Sustainable Earth\n		\n	\n	\n		San Jose: San Jose Cool Cities Team\n	\n		Sunnyvale: Sunnyvale Cool Cities\n\n\n	&nbsp;\nExisting Green Teams at Schools:\n\n	\n		Gunn High School Green Team\n\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '77', NULL, 'topics/systemic/activities/green-teams', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/77', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/77'),
(599, 'Adaptation', ' \n	\n		\n			\n				\n				Adaptation in Response to Climate Change\nBy Ursula Syrova, EcoCloud Sustainability Lead\n				\n				Adapting to the effects of climate change is a hot topic now as efforts to mitigate against it are clearly not going fast enough. There is no exact picture of what the Bay Area in California will be facing, but the educated likely expectations are rising sea (and bay) levels, which will endanger development at the water''s edge, and decreased snow pack, which will endanger water supplies. More extreme weather also seems likely.\n				\n				The good news is that communities all around the bay are beginning to address these issues through development and land use policies, but these are big issues that effect everyone and there has to be collaboration and coordination.\n				\n				The Joint Policy Committee has provided the following two documents to highlight efforts currently underway:\n			\n				Bay Area Climate and Energy Resilience Project\n			\n				Bay Area Climate &amp; Energy Adaptation/Resilience Map\n			\n				&nbsp;\n		\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '78', NULL, 'topics/systemic/adaptation', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/78', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/78'),
(600, 'Holidays', ' \n\n	Thinking and Acting with Sustainability in Mind During the Holidays\n\n	In late December every year, MORE is the operative word for most of us and society in general it seems, and that includes creating a lot more waste (waste generation goes up at least 25% during this time of year). &nbsp;Resisting the siren call of advertising and cultural pressure can be challenging during the holidays, but making different choices as you go along is always worthwhile.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	For a super sustainable holiday gift idea, how about giving Sustainable Silicon Valley a donation? We have a wish list if you want ideas or have something you could re-gift to us. Tax-deductible, too!\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Some basic goals for the holidays:\n\n	Vote with your dollars: Think outside the big box store and look for something local, fair trade, sustainably produced. &nbsp;CalRecyle&nbsp;has some great items made with recycled content to get you thinking.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Wrap it with re-use: &nbsp;Use fabric, use decorative bags, use interesting boxes. &nbsp;RecycleWorks&nbsp;has many great ideas for gifts and wrapping.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Wrap it with recycling:&nbsp;That metallic wrapping paper sure is pretty, but it can''t be recycled. &nbsp;Let go of the glam when buying wrapping paper, and if you feel like it, try getting the paper off of gifts you receive somewhat intact so you can use it again. &nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	More inspiration for less-is-more holidays:\n\n	Make enjoying and honoring the world around you part of your holidays: The Wilderness Society&nbsp;has brought together many great ideas for gift giving, decorating and even eating during the holidays.\n\n	As the Sierra Club&nbsp;says, ''tis the season for consumption, and they have many ideas to help rein it all in, including a good one that is easy to forget--bring your own bag to every store, not just the grocery store.\n\n	Feeling economically constrained but still want to embrace your eco values? &nbsp;Here are some budget friendly tips&nbsp;for that, too.\n\n	If you are ready to think completely outside the box, there are many gifts that support worthy causes, such as the Natural Resources Defense Council, which offers gift-versions of support for various causes.\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '80', NULL, 'topics/systemic/holidays', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/80', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/80'),
(601, 'Videos', ' \n	\n\n	All Hands on Deck! 300 Years of Fossil Fuels in 300 Seconds\n	\n\n	Michael Killen Interviews Marianna Grossman, Ex. Dir. Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Michael Killen Interviews Eric Rosenblum, District Manager of South Bay Water Recycling\n\n	Let''s Keep It Simple: Climate Change and Risk Management Thinking in a 4-Part Grid.\n\n	Vote With Your Pedals: Bike to Work Day in Washington, D.C.\n\n	Why Aren''t You?: Promotional and inspirational video about Bike to Work Day in San Francisco.\n\n	Radical Simplicity: One family goes zero-waste. Is it too much? (Or too little?)\n\n	It''s a book! It''s a movie! It''s a short preview: No Impact Man: One man''s quest to have no impact on the environment, and how his family supported him in the experiment.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Our gadgets: we love them, but . . \n\n	.\n\n	The now-classic video that describes the problems created by all our "stuff." &nbsp;Why we want it, how&nbsp;it is made, what happens to it when we are done with it.\n\n	\n\n	If you are drinking bottled water, put it down, watch this video, get mad, and take back the tap!\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '81', NULL, 'topics/systemic/videos', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/81', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/81'),
(602, 'Success Stories', ' \n	Successes -&nbsp;Where Green Can Meet Green\n\n	Many companies are doing great work in their pursuit of ways to make operations more environmentally sustainable while also realizing financial benefit. &nbsp;Here we share some of those stories with you, while encouraging you to submit your own.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Case Studies:\n\n	\n		Akraya saves money and wins awards as a small green certified business\n	\n		Air Products makes use of recycled water&nbsp;in its Air Separation Unit in Santa Clara, realizing great savings in the process.\n	\n		San Jose State University saves money using recycled water in their cooling towers\n	\n		Santa Clara University created a micro-grid with on-site renewable energy production to realize significant energy cost savings and increased energy reliability.\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '87', NULL, 'topics/systemic/success-stories', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/87', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/87'),
(609, 'Case Studies', ' \n	Water Conservation Case Studies\n\n	Water Ownership\n\n	\n		Water Ownership and AquaJust™\n\n\n	Silicon Valley Water Award Winners Silicon Valley Water Conservation Awards are presented to organizations, agencies, businesses and individuals whose programs and leadership have advanced water conservation in Silicon Valley (San Mateo County, Santa Clara County and Alameda County from Hayward south). If you would like to apply for an award, go to www.waterawards.org\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	2011 Silicon Valley Water Awards Winners:\n\n	\n		BAWSCA Water Conservation Implementation Plan.pdf\n	\n		Brandenburg Mobile Home Submetering.pdf\n	\n		ET Water Systems Irrigation Management.pdf\n	\n		Hitachi GST Large Business Water Conservation.pdf\n	\n		Ken &amp; Sally Coverdell (individual).pdf\n	\n		Our City Forest (education).pdf\n	\n		San Jose State Water Conservation.pdf\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	2010 Silicon Valley Water Awards Winners:\n\n	\n		CA Landscape Assoc.pdf\n	\n		Campbell Union School District.pdf\n	\n		Cisco Systems Water Conservation.pdf\n	\n		City of Hayward Water Conservation program.pdf\n	\n		Humane Society Silicon Valley LEED Bldg.pdf\n	\n		Nurserymen''s Exchange Water Conservation.pdf\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	2009 Silicon Valley Water Awards Winners:\n\n	\n		Applied Materials.pdf\n	\n		California Native Plant Society.pdf\n	\n		First Community Housing.pdf\n	\n		John Laird.pdf\n	\n		Kirsch Center.pdf\n	\n		L-3 Process Water.pdf\n	\n		Montara Agency Conservation Plan.pdf\n	\n		Redwood City Water Conservation Program.pdf\n	\n		Stanford Water Conservation Master Plan.pdf\n	\n		ValleyCrest Landcaping.pdf\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '92', NULL, 'topics/water/con/case-studies', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/92', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/92');
