(611, 'Water Metrics and Tools', ' By Mary Kean, PE\n\n	January 2012\n\n	This "Water Metrics and Tool" section includes water metric guidelines, tools (excel, interactive maps, online tools), and reports about water accounting, risk evaluation, benchmarking, measuring and certification systems. See the section on Water Management Software / IT for specific software applications regarding water and energy.\n\n	For a more detailed &amp; up to date review of each item, refer to Water Metrics Report (pdf) and a quick reference on the tables accessible on EcoCloud Water Metrics\n\n	The Alliance for Water Stewardship (AWS) Certification Program\n\n	• Website: http://www.allianceforwaterstewardship.org/\n\n	• Tool or Metric: certification standard for water managers (under development)\n\n	• Description: AWS is working with water authorities, companies, local communities and environmentalists to establish a voluntary freshwater stewardship certification program; This program will include an "eco-label" and require quantification of water use, discharge, and impacts; Standard will based on: 1) International standards, 2) Verification to determine whether these standards have been met., 3) A global brand demonstrates compliance with or support for water stewardship.\n	• Target Audience (User): standard to apply to utilities and organizations (businesses, CII); Used by water managers companies, &amp; communities; international; North American Chapter started 2011\n\n	• Source: AWS; A non-profit; Board orgs include: The Nature Conservancy, The Water Stewardship Australia, Pacific Institute, WWF, Water Witness Int’l, European Water Partnership, Water Environment Federation, Int’l Water Mgmt Institute, UN CEO Water Mandate, CDP.\n	• Objective: promote responsible use that is both socially beneficial and environmentally sustainable\n\n	• Date: formed in 2008; working on certification program\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, certification\n\n	• Strengths: represents various stakeholders (as of July 2011: The Nature Conservancy, WWF, Water Stewardship Australia, Water Witness International, the Water Environment Federation, the Pacific Institute, the European Water Partnership, CDP, the International Water Management Institute (IWMI), UN’s CEO Water Mandate)\n\n	• Limitations: aims to reward water users/managers who "take significant steps to minimize their water use and impacts", but could lead to conflict of interest and bias; lacks specifics\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, certification\n\n	American Water Works Association (AWWA) Water Conservation Measurement Metrics Guidance Report\n\n	• Website: http://www.awwa.org/files/Publications/Streamlines/2010/030210/AWWA%20Metrics%20Guidance%20Report%20Jan-22-2010%20Final%20_3_.pdf\n\n	• Description: The purpose of the report is to identify and characterize a set of water use and conservation metrics for public water supply utilities. These metrics could be used as measurement tools to evaluate the effects of water efficiency programs over time in a single utility. Some metrics can also be used to compare water use and conservation effects across different utilities. This report provides guidance on standardized methods of calculating specific metrics and describes their advantages and limitations.\n\n	The report includes data from seven U.S. water utilities.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): public water supply utilities\n\n	• Source: AWWA\n\n	• Date: January 2010\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics, water-conservation\n\n	• Strengths: detailed water use accounting; methodology appears to be sound; metrics developed with conservation as end goal; provides pro and con of each selected metric\n\n	• Limitations: may need larger pilot study to further demonstrate metrics’ usefulness\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n\n	Energy Index Development for Benchmarking Water and Wastewater Utilities Report (AWWA Research Foundation)\n\n	• Website: http://www.waterrf.org/ProjectsReports/PublicReportLibrary/91201.pdf\n\n	• Description : This 190 page report sets out to review , assess, and develop energy metrics • that allow comparison of energy use among water and wastewater treatment plants through a scoring method.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): water utilities, wastewater treatment plant operators; water consultants\n\n	• Source: AWWA Research Foundation dedicated to drinking water research;\n	• Date: 2007\n	• Topic: water energy, benchmarking, wastewater, water-metric, energy-metric\n\n	• Strengths: well-researched, academic approach; applicable to existing plants\n\n	• Limitations: TBD\n\n	• Other Sustainable Programs: Over $460 million in research, more than 1000 projects in the health, infrastructure, management, treatment technologies, and water resources for water utilities\n\n	• Tags: water-energy, benchmarking, wastewater\n\n	(In Progress) Aquawareness – European Water Stewardship Program (EWS)\n\n	• Website: http://www.ewp.eu/activities/water-stewardship/\n\n	• Tool or Metric: Certification and Assessment framework using indicators to indentify risks/impacts to business and water ecosystem. The final system (expected 2013) will include the EWS standard (glossary and guidelines, case studies of best management practices), inspection and certification system (checklists, ranking system), and communication guidelines.\n\n	• Description: Voluntary system to assess/certify and communicate about Sustainable Water Management by an organization, industry, agricultural user, or urban area. The certification system will include assessing a water user’s performance on-site and within the referring river basin. The draft certification as of December 2011 consists of 4 sustainable water management principles and 53 indicators which are ranked. These 4 principles area: 1) achieve and maintain sustainable water quantity 2) biological/chemical sustainability (toxicity of chemicals), 3) restore/preserve "high conservation value areas" (sensitive ecosystems), 4) equitable/transparency water governance\n\n	• Target Audience (User): EWS System implementation pilot studies will include industries, agriculture, and urban areas to be used by CII, public authorities, agricultural users, &amp; inter-governmental agencies in Europe\n\n	• Source: EWP, a non-profit organization; structured to include cross-sectoral organizations to give water one common "voice" in Europe. Partners include government, innovators, water utilities, and researchers on multiple cross-collaboration projects.\n\n	• Objective: Water Stewardship Program objectives are to provide an evaluation of the strong/weak points of the water management on-site, and identify the response strategy that will have the highest impact on the referring watershed and to stimulate the reality of a third party certification system. EWP’s aquawareness objectives are (1) create a common vision for water in Europe with widely accepted principles for sustainable water management, (2) set sights on changing behavior and practices, (3) shape and integrates water into policy and strategy agendas, (4) create a water saving and efficiency culture among private, industrial, business and agricultural users, (5) support the shift from supply to demand management through information, education and training.\n\n	• Date: established in 2008; Developed draft indicators 2008-2011; Pilot Programs (2010-2012) and full implementation expected 2013.\n	• Topics: Best Management Practices, public policy, case studies\n\n	• Strengths: EWS good for identification of water strategies at the operational level; in line with and complementary to other environmental certification schemes, raise awareness;; unites various stakeholders across Europe; provides uniform framework and vision for many countries; supports education and training effort\n\n	• Limitations: EWS checklists &amp; list of indicators not available on website (Dec 2011); Vision 2030 may be too long-term to be effective for timely actions now\n\n	• Other Sustainable Programs: Includes a vision 2030 for Europe Water multiple public-private collaboration projects around sustainable water management Europeon Commission Environment’s water blueprint, INNOWATER (collaboration to identify and implement innovative water technology (3 year project 2010-2012), and STREAM project communication project between research and policy on Aquatic management research.\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, certification public-policy\n\n	Beverage Industry Environmental Roundtable (BIER)\n\n	• Website: http://bieroundtable.com/water_stewardship.html\n\n	• Tool or Metric: Sector specific water use guidelines; benchmarking; water footprinting guidelines (in development; Dec 2011)\n\n	• Description: The mission of the roundtable is to define a common framework for stewardship, drive continuous improvement practices and performance, and inform public policy in the areas of Water Conservation and Resource Protection, Energy Efficiency, and Climate Change Mitigation. Annual quantitative and qualitative benchmarking is completed on select aspects of the BIER-developed World Class Water Stewardship in the Beverage Industry. Results are consolidated, patterned, and collectively analyzed at Roundtable meetings. To date, the benchmarking has included data from over 1,100 beverage facilities, including breweries, distilleries, wineries, and bottling sites. A working group has been formulated to continually improve benchmarking processes and methodologies.\n\n	Current BIER members include: American Beverage Association, Anheuser-Busch InBev, Bacardi Limited, Beam Global Spirits &amp; Wine, Brown-Forman Corporation, Carlsberg Group, The Coca-Cola Company, Diageo, Diversey, Groupe Danone, Ecolab, Heineken, MillerCoors, Molson Coors Brewing Company, Nestlé Waters, New Belgium Brewing Company, Ocean Spray Cranberries, Pernod Ricard and PepsiCo.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): beverage industry companies and supporting partners\n\n	• Source: BIER\n\n	• Date: first convened in 2006\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: powerful coalition of companies may lead to significant changes; gov’t engagement\n\n	• Limitations: Trade group ploy or something "real"? Does not use LCA approach in water accounting\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n\n	CA Commercial, Institutional, and Industrial (CII) State Task Force Report including Case Studies, and Metrics\n\n	• Website: http://www.cuwcc.org/2column.aspx?id=16620\n	• Description: State Task force developing alternative best management practices (BMPs) for Commercial, Industrial, and Institutional (CII) water users include metrics, best management practices, case studies, and water saving potentials.\n	• Target Audience (User): Facility Managers, consultants, regulators, and anyone who is interested in water best management practices and possible reductions in water use in CII; will include actual case studies of success stories of CII that completed reductions in water use or potable water use and utilized innovative technologies\n\n	• Source: CII Task Force as appointed by the State Legislature; Coordinated by CA Department of Water Resources with input from multi-stakeholder group including regulators, utilities, researchers, consultants, and representatives from CII organizations\n	• Date: To be completed by April 2011 and presented to State Legislature\n	• Topics: CII, Best Management Practices, water metrics, water conservation, case studies\n\n	• Strengths: TBD\n\n	• Limitations: TBD\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-metrics, water-conservation, case-studies\n\n	The California Water Sustainability Indicators Framework\n\n	• Website: http://www.waterplan.water.ca.gov/docs/meeting_materials/workshop/08.24.11/CWP_SIF_Draft_Framework_Jul20_11.pdf\n\n	• Description: The Framework is composed of a cycle of process steps that build upon each other. The cycle begins with defining what is meant by sustainability and other terms and completes one cycle by informing policy and decision‐making. The process is intended to be part of a cycle of adaptive learning and action. The indicators and the process of developing, analyzing, and interpreting them are not intended to stand alone, so links are described with regional planning, ecosystem services, and water footprint. Process could be used by others to implement water sustainability initiatives and be used to guide public policy.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): water authorities, water managers and users, companies, communities\n\n	• Source: The California Water Plan, part of CA DWR; Participating stakeholders include: CA Dept of Water Resources, EPA, Water Plan’s Statewide Water Analysis Network, Sustainable Water Resources Roundtable, State Agency Steering Committee, Water Plan Public Advisory Committee, Regional Forums, Tribal Advisory Committee, and Federal Agency Network.\n\n	• Date: draft dated July 20, 2011\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, sustainability reporting, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: starts from fundamentals (e.g. definition of sustainability, etc.); detailed and summary reports; linked to ecological footprints; scenario planning\n\n	• Limitations: applicability to other regions; project scope too wide?\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics\n\n	Ceres Aqua Gauge\n\n	• Website: http://www.ceres.org/issues/water/aqua-gauge/aqua-gauge\n\n	• Description: The Ceres Aqua Gauge provides a framework and tool for assessing corporate water risk management. It is an Excel-based tool that "allows investors to scorecard a company''s water management activities against detailed definitions of leading practice. The tool also benefits companies by giving them a resource to inform and strengthen their own water management strategies."\n	• Target Audience (User): Investors (incl. 1) Portfolio managers and analysts, 2) governance specialists, and 3) financial and ESG data providers) and business organizations\n\n	• Source: Ceres\n	• Date: Released in October 2011\n	• Topic: Best Management Practices, benchmarking, financial, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: Flexible – Allows for both rapid and more comprehensive analysis; continuously updated to reflect advances in water management practices and ongoing stakeholder feedback; simple, clear one-page scorecard\n\n	• Limitations: Primary aim is to provide a quick guide to engage equity investors, which means the underlying methodology may not be as rigorous or comprehensive; mostly qualitative questions in assessment\n\n	• Tags: Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, financial, water-metrics\n\n	Corporate Water Gauge (CWG)\n\n	• Website: http://www.sustainableorganizations.org/Water-Gauge-FAQs.pdf\n\n	• Description: CWG is a context-based water metric that consists of (1) a spreadsheet-based measure of water use that compares the water consumption of an organization or facility with an allocation of available renewable water supplies relative to volume of water, per employee, or per revenue, (2) a GIS technique for measuring and allocating renewable water supplies in watersheds, and (3) a consulting service for teaching and/or assisting with the use of the whole package. A context-based metric expresses the sustainability performance in the form of numerical quotients; focus on site and enterprise level metric and reporting;\n	• Target Audience (User): Any organization with one or more sites that uses water and has data on their water sources; Corporate sustainability managers, plant or facility managers, environmental managers; Applicable globally and different industrial sectors\n\n	• Source: Center for Sustainable Organizations co-developed with Acer GeoAnalytics (Vermont)\n	• Date: v3.5 released in March 2011\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: Context-based metrics (Company’s impact on renewable water resources)\n\n	• Limitations: May not have data on related water sources and sinks and their respective volumes; Conflict of interest? It provides consulting service and fee-based workshops; seems to be more concerned with finding faults with GRI\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n\n	Global Environmental Management Initiative (GEMI) Water Sustainability Tool\n\n	• Website: http://www.gemi.org/water/overview.htm\n\n	• Tool or Metric: GEMI online water sustainability planner\n\n	• Description: GEMI’s free online Water Sustainability Tool contains five core analytical stages, or modules, all with a focus on a company’s value chain. These include:\n\n	Module 1: Water Use, Impact, and Source Assessment\n\n	Module 2: Business Risk Assessment\n\n	Module 3: Business Opportunity Assessment\n\n	Module 4: Strategic Direction and Goal Setting\n\n	Module 5: Strategy Development and Implementation\n\n	GEMI is currently developing the GEMI Local Water Tool that aims to be a follow-up tool to WBCSD’s Global Water Tool for action planning.\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations (corporate and operational staff)\n\n	• Source: GEMI including 30 companies from various sectors; chaired by WBCSD members and industries\n	• Objective: identify water risks; generate corporate/facility water strategy\n\n	• Date: Released in 2002\n	• Topic: Best Management Practices, water risks, water accounting\n\n	• Strengths: Roadmap for corporate strategy; case studies\n\n	• Limitations: Does not provide a method or calculator to measure or quantify water use, impacts, and risks (mostly qualitative questions)\n\n	online water calculators and rules of thumb that can be downloaded as excel spreadsheets (residential and fluid flow/; pump, etc); general GEMI online sustainability planner; The GEMI Solution Tools Matrix™ is an interactive, web solution for users around the world to access the +30 free, solutions-based tools for organizations/industry for EHS and sustainability\n\n	• Tags: Best-Management-Practices, water risks, water-accounting\n\n	GEMI Water Sustainability Planner\n\n	• Website: http://www.gemi.org/waterplanner/\n\n	• Tool or Metric: GEMI online water sustainability planner\n\n	• Description: GEMI’s Collecting the Drops: A Water Sustainability Planner is a free online calculator segregated into three Modules that guides a facility user through:\n\n	Module 1: preparing a facility water block diagram and water balance in comparison to the availability of water in the region;\n\n	Module 2: web based interactive water risk evaluation questionnaire (watershed, supply reliability, efficiency, compliance, supply economics, and social context) and the identification of factors that may pose a risk on the operation’s ability to produce.\n\n	Module 3: Case study examples of how GEMI members have identified opportunities to efficiently manage water resources are also provided.\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations (corporate and operational staff)\n\n	• Source: GEMI including 30 companies from various sectors; chaired by WBCSD members and industries\n	• Objective: Generate information that can be used to create short and long term water management strategies, identify water risks; output used to develop corporate/facility water strategy\n\n	• Date: Released in 2007\n	• Topic: Best Management Practices; water calculator, case studies\n	• Strengths: Roadmap for both long-term and short-term corporate strategy; can be used by specific facilities for information on water use needs/risks; case studies water management strategies; can create an account for specific facilities; some industries case studies same as San Francisco Bay Area industries\n	• Limitations: no mention of its relationship to GEMI’s other water tools; can’t add risk questions or modify; not many specific CA case studies (Dec 2011); no quantifiable results; rudimentary assessment of relative risks\n	• Other Sustainable Programs: online water calculators and rules of thumb that can be downloaded as excel spreadsheets (residential and fluid flow/; pump, etc); general GEMI online sustainability planner; The GEMI Solution Tools Matrix™ is an interactive, web solution for users around the world to access the +30 free, solutions-based tools for organizations/industry for EHS and sustainability. •\n	Tags: Best-Management-Practices, water-calculator, case-studies\n\n	Global Water Footprint Standard\n\n	• Website: http://www.waterfootprint.org/?page=files/home (main website)\n\n	• Description: The water footprint here is defined as "the amount of freshwater used in the goods and services consumed or used in production." The main website has pdf documents on how water footprints can be calculated for individual processes and products, as well as for consumers, nations and businesses; there is a water footprint calculator for individuals; actual examples of different kinds of water footprints; examples of measures that can contribute to water footprint reduction\n\n	• Target Audience (User): Water footprint accounting is targeted for the following groups of stakeholders:\n\n	A consumer or group of consumers (online calculator)\n\n	Province, river basin, i.e. a geographically delineated area\n\n	Nation\n\n	Business\n\n	• Source: Water Footprint Network; Founding partners include: WWF, UNESCO-IHE Institute for Water Education, WBCSD, Univ of Twente, Water Neutral Foundation, International Finance Corp., and the Netherlands Water Partnership\n	• Date: First published in November 2009 (131 page report). Current version came out in February 2011.\n	• Objective: The Global Water Footprint Standard aims to make all water footprints comparable in order to help relevant stakeholders improve water management.\n\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: Good tool for "big picture" strategic planning purposes; easily understood by non-technical audiences; Best for water use assessments, as opposed to water quality; identifies hotspots linking corporate water use and source water data\n\n	• Limitations: Generic, aggregated blue-green-grey water footring figures are misleading; Grey water footprint deemed ineffective by many companies\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-metrics\n\n	Global Water Tool (WBCSD)\n\n	• Website: http://www.wbcsd.org/work-program/sector-projects/water/global-water-tool.aspx\n\n	• Tool/Metric Description: Tool includes two parts: 1) Free, Excel-based tool for companies and organizations to map their water use and assess risks relative to their global operations and supply chains; 2) online and GIS mapping system that plots site location with external water datasets and special viewing via google earth interface.\n	Outputs include GRI water indicators, inventories of water consumption/efficiency; downloadable charts with company and watershed data and GSI geographic maps\n	• Target Audience (User): Companies and organizations operating in multiple countries who need to better understand the water issues in their operations and that of their extended supply chain; "More than 300 corporations have used the tool which has been regularly updated with improved datasets and functionalities."\n\n	• Source: World Business Council for Sustainable Development (WBCSD)\n	• Objective: , map water use at an industry and assess and communicate water risks relative to water availability in facility operations and supply chain\n\n	• Date: Launched in 2007, last updated in 2011\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices\n\n	• Strengths: free of charge; easy to use; Effective at identifying water risk "hot spots"; emphasis on geographic locations; Linked to GRI, CDP, Water, Bloomberg, and DJSI water reporting indicators; includes supply chain; rough measurement of water use and efficiency; can enter water related data for supplies and staff presence;\n\n	• Limitations: Does not assess water quality/discharge related risks; doesn’t assess impacts; only rough estimates of risk; must hand enter data into excel worksheet unless you write a macro to transfer data\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices\n\n	The Green Grid\n\n	• Website: http://www.greenbiz.com/news/2011/03/08/green-grid-rolls-out-data-center-metrics-water-energy-reuse\n\n	• Description: The Green Grid is an IT industry sustainability group that develops metrics to track data center sustainability efforts. The Green Grid also acts as a standards setting organization with tools such as the Data Center Maturity Model that helps determine how resource-efficient data centers are. Newly developed metrics in 2011 include:\n\n	(1) WUE, or Water Usage Effectiveness\n\n	(2) ERE, or Energy Reuse Effectiveness\n\n	(3) DCcE, or Data Center Compute Efficiency\n	• Target Audience (User): business orgs, data center sustainability managers\n\n	• Source: GreenBiz.com\n	• Date: March 08, 2011\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, water energy, benchmarking, water metrics, energy metrics, data center sustainability\n\n	• Strengths: Addresses important niche of data center operation, frequent updates, alliances with gov’t orgs, NGOs, and trade assoc\n\n	• Limitations: TBD\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-energy, benchmarking, water-metrics, energy-metrics, data- center-sustainability\n\n	Hospital Energy Benchmarking Guidance\n\n	• Website: http://hightech.lbl.gov/documents/healthcare/lbnl-2738e.pdf\n\n	• Description: Describes an energy benchmarking framework for hospitals.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): business orgs, hospital operation and building sustainability managers\n\n	• Source: Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL)\n	• Date: October 2009\n	• Topic: water energy, benchmarking, hospital energy benchmarking\n\n	• Strengths: Addresses energy benchmarking in hospitals, metrics address energy use through heating, cooling, water, air, and others.\n\n	• Limitations: TBD\n\n	• Tags: water-energy, benchmarking, hospital-energy-benchmarking\n\n	(In Progress) ISO 14046, Water footprint\n\n	• Website: http://www.iso.org/iso/isofocusplus_bonus_water-footprint\n\n	• Description: The proposed Standard will deliver principles, requirements, and guidelines for a water footprint metric of products, processes and organizations, based on the guidance of impact assessment as given in ISO 14044. It will develop a water accounting inventory methodology and requirements for impact assessment (for screening and detailed assessments). It will define how the different types of water sources (e.g. ground, surface, gray, etc.) should be considered, how the different types of water releases should be considered, and how the local environmental conditions (dry areas, wet areas) should be treated. For products, it will apply the life cycle approach and will be based on the same product system as specified in ISO 14040 and ISO 14044. At the organization level, it will consider the guidance given by ISO 14064 for GHG.\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations; use at multiple organizational levels from facility to regional\n\n	• Source: International Standard Organization\n	• Date: In development; at the stage of preliminary work item (Dec 2011)\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices\n\n	• Strengths: Addresses communication with respect to water footprinting\n\n	• Limitations: No methodology for calculating offsets or compensation\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, water-foot-print; water-metics\n\n	Life Cycle Analysis (LCA)\n\n	• Website: no one protocol/website has been adopted to complete a life cycle analysis; some information on life cycle assessment is available through UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative\n\n	• Description: An analytical method which measures the environmental sustainability of products (including water use/discharge and other environmental factors) through all parts of the value change\n\n	1) UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative, a global non-profit professional society has information on general life cycle assessments, methodologies, and lifecycle database registry; has a working group on resources LCA (including water)\n\n	2) Corporate Water Accounting, the CEO Mandate Report (2010) has a comparison of this method versus 3 other water accounting methods\n	• Target Audience (User): Businesses/organizations which use water; particularly those with long supply chains\n\n	• Source: UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative, a global non-profit professional society\n\n	• Objective: UNEP/SETAC life cycle initiative: provide industries with framework to measure and compare environmental products regarding freshwater use and depletion; develop a multi-criteria assessment scheme within the LCA framework that allows industries to benchmark performance of products, facilities, and processes on freshwater resources, human health, and biodiversity protection\n\n	• Date: UNEP/SETAC Life cycle initiative: August 2007 created\n	• Topic: Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics, database\n\n	• Strengths: well-suited to cross-media environmental assessments; mature science based assessing water quality impacts; starting point for assessing risks; situates water in a broader context of sustainability\n\n	• Limitations: no universally accepted method of water use impacts; data often not available; results difficult to communicate to stakeholders; doesn’t typically calculate impacts at local receiving water bodies\n\n	• Other Programs: LCA can be applied to water, energy, materials, GHG, and other sustainability areas\n\n	• Tags: Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics, life-cycle-assessment\n\n	Strategic Water Management in the Minerals Industry\n\n	• Website: http://www.minerals.org.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0009/17595/Water_strategy_book.pdf\n\n	• Description: strategic framework structured around 4 issues:\n\n	1) Water Value: guidance on how to reflect the true value on water in decision making\n\n	2) Strategic water planning guidance\n\n	3) Implementation: guidance on site water management plans and balances to improve operational performance\n\n	4) guidance on engaging stakeholders\n\n	Member companies produce up to 85 per cent of Australia''s mineral output including precious metals, base metals, light metals and iron ore, as well as energy materials such as coal.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): mining companies; corporate managers and planners; mine managers and environmental personnel that are responsible for water management\n\n	• Source: Australian Ministerial Council on Mineral and Petroleum Resources (MCMPR) and the Minerals Council of Australia (MCA).\n\n	• Objective: Aim is to promote a strategic approach to water management at mining and processing sites so that water is more efficiently managed and valued as a vital business, community and environmental asset.\n\n	• Date: framework development begun in 2005\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: coalition of companies may lead to significant changes; gov’t engagement; aligns with GRI\n\n	• Limitations: Trade group ploy – activities are entirely funded by MCA member companies? Mostly qualitative assessment and metrics\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n\n	UK Federation House Commitment to Water Efficiency\n\n	• Website: http://www.fdf.org.uk/waterefficiency.aspx\\#item1\n\n	• Description: Developed in partnership between FDF and former government-funded body Envirowise, the Federation House Commitment (FHC) sets out a process for food and drink manufacturing companies to work in a systematic way towards improving their water efficiency.\n\n	There are currently 54 active signatories across 245 sites in the UK.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): food and drink manufacturers\n\n	• Source: Food and Drink Federation\n\n	• Date: 2007, with annual progress report\n	• Topic: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: coalition of companies may lead to significant changes; gov’t engagement; strategic framework can be applied to other global companies\n\n	• Limitations: Trade group ploy or something "real"?; water use does not take into account water embedded in products\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n\n	UN Water Footprint, Neutrality and Efficiency (WaFNE) Umbrella Project\n\n	• Metric or Tool: building a website to host different tools &amp; methodologies\n\n	• Website: http://www.unep.fr/scp/water/WAFNE.htm\n\n	• Description: The Project aims to produce methodologies and guides through the refinement of water accounting/footprint and water neutrality management tools. It will apply the above concepts in selected industries and selected geographical locations. Includes Water Footprint and Corporate Water Accounting for Resource Efficiency Report (183 pgs)\n\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations, public authorities\n\n	• Source: UN Environment Programme\n	• Objective: enhance water efficiency and water quality management through the refinement and pilot testing of several accounting methods and supporting management tools\n\n	• Date: Timeframe = 10/2009 – 2012/2013\n	• Topics: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking\n\n	• Strengths: Partnerships with other UN water-related initiatives, Water Footprint Network, UNEP/SETAC Life Cycle Initiative, and GRI.\n\n	• Limitations: Only three years in project duration – limited impact (there is not even a dedicated website to the project)\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking\n\n	Veolia – Water Impact Index\n\n	• Website: http://www.veoliawaterna.com/north-america-water/ressources/documents/1/10975,Water_Impact_Index-White_Paper.pdf\n\n	• Description: According to Veolia, it is "the first indicator enabling a comprehensive assessment of the impact of human activity on water resources. It is a tool that can help cities and companies plan long-term projects and better understand sustainable approaches to ensure long-term water supplies and healthy water ecosystems."\n\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations, public authorities\n\n	• Source: Veolia Water North America\n	• Date: July 2010\n	• Topics: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: Index integrates other variables in addition to volume, including resource stress, water quality and competing consumption needs with existing volume-based water measurement tools; considers both direct and indirect influences of an activity; LCA approach\n\n	• Limitations: Developed by water utility – potential bias\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n\n	WaterSense Label and Certification\n\n	• Tool or Metric: Certification of Products\n\n	• Website: http://www.epa.gov/WaterSense/about_us/what_is_ws.html\n\n	• Description: The program seeks to help consumers make smart water choices that save money and maintain high environmental standards without compromising performance. Products and services that have earned the WaterSense label have been certified to be at least 20% more efficient without sacrificing performance. To date \\[2010 Report\\], WaterSense has helped consumers save a cumulative 125 billion gallons of water and over $2 billion in water and energy bills. By the end of 2010, reductions of 16.7 billion kWh of electricity and 6 million metric tons of carbon dioxide were achieved through the use of WaterSense labeled products.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): business organizations, consumers\n\n	• Source: US EPA\n\n	• Date: program created in June 2006\n	• Topic: Best Management Practices, policy, label\n\n	• Strengths: simple way to help consumer make informed decisions; independent certification ensures integrity\n\n	• Limitations: voluntary program on consumer products, could be looking into expanding program scope\n\n	• Tags: Best-Management-Practices, policy, label\n\n	Water Stewardship Australia\n\n	• Website: http://www.nwc.gov.au/publications/distilled-e-newsletter/2010/distilled-edition-51-june-2010/water-stewardship-australia\n\n	• Description: The organization leads the initiative to develop responsible water management standards for the largest of all Australian water users in the agribusiness, manufacturing, mining and infrastructure sectors.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations, public authorities, consumers\n\n	• Source: Australia’s National Water Commission\n	• Date: 2007\n	• Topics: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water policy planning, policy\n\n	• Strengths: various water tools available free of charge, publications on water research\n\n	• Limitations: water metrics and reporting would be the next step\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-policy-planning, policy\n\n	WWF/DEG Water Risk Filter\n\n	• Website: http://www.unglobalcompact.org/docs/issues_doc/Environment/ceo_water_mandate/7th_Working_Conference_Copenhagen_2011/Copenhagen-Verberne.pdf\n\n	• Description: The Water Risk Filter uses the newest available scientific data sets with global coverage and company specific information to quantify all relevant water risks (physical, regulatory and reputational). A mitigation toolbox, providing a well-structured overview of potential mitigation responses and related case studies, will also be part of the online tool.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): Business organizations, public authorities, consumers\n\n	• Source: Australia’s National Water Commission\n	• Date: anticipated early 2012\n	• Topics: CII, Best Management Practices, benchmarking, financial\n\n	• Strengths: input data seem comprehensive (GIS, WRI database, industry &amp; country data sets, etc.)\n\n	• Limitations: provides go/no-go investment decision, but does not seem to provide recommendations for action\n\n	• Tags: CII, Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, financial\n\n	(In Progress) World Resource Institute''s Aqueduct Alliance\n\n	• Website: http://insights.wri.org/aqueduct/how-it-works\n\n	• Description: Aqueduct "provides a comprehensive and credible metric for measuring geographic water risks. It consists of a global database and interactive mapping tool that enable companies to quantify and map water risks at a local scale, worldwide." 21 indicators in three categories (access &amp; growth constraints, cost risks, and disruption potential) are aggregated to determine the overall water risk.\n\n	Funders by invitation: Goldman Sachs, Bloomberg, Dow, Talisman Energy, United Technologies, Coca-Cola, Dutch gov’t\n	• Target Audience (User): Business and government\n\n	• Source:\n\n	Modeled data: hydrologic modeling by ISciences;\n\n	Spatial data: compiled by research or international organizations;\n\n	Observations: recorded from monitoring stations;\n\n	Official statistics reported by local and national governments;\n\n	Global water stress maps: provided by The Coca-Cola Company\n\n	• Date: Aqueduct Alliance launched in August 2011. In depth basin-level water risk mapping will be released in early fall 2011.\n	• Topic: Best Management Practices, benchmarking, water metrics\n\n	• Strengths: Flexible – Allows customization of Water Risk Atlas based on different sectors or risk profiles; periodic update of data sources; identifies increasingly water-stressed locations throughout the world\n\n	• Limitations: The success all hinges on Aqueduct’s global database of water risk information, which is highly dependent on data sources; data integrity and availability may vary greatly among regions\n\n	• Tags: Best-Management-Practices, benchmarking, water-metrics\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '62', NULL, 'topics/water/tools-metrics-reporting/water-metrics-and-tools', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/62', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/62'),
(612, 'Sustainability Reporting Tools', ' By Mary Kean and Carey Chen, EcoCloud Water Lead\n\n	January 2012\n\n	For a more detailed &amp; and up to date review of new metrics, refer to our Water Metrics Report and the tables on EcoCloud Water Metrics\n\n	Global Reporting Initiative (GRI) – Water Performance Indicators\n\n	• Website: https://www.globalreporting.org/Pages/default.aspx\n	• Description: GRI produces and continuously updates a "comprehensive sustainability reporting framework" that is one of the most used reporting framework in the world. The G3 Guidelines are made up of two parts. Part 1 features guidance on how to report. Part 2 features guidance on what should be reported, in the form of Disclosures on Management Approach and Performance Indicators. There are three water indicators:\n\n	1) Total water withdrawal by source\n\n	2) Water sources significantly affected by withdrawal of water\n\n	3) Percentage and total volume of water recycled and reused\n\n	As of early November 2011, 3000+ organizations around the world have adopted the GRI framework, resulting in 7,600+ GRI sustainability reports.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): For-profit corporations, NGOs, non-profit organizations, universities, gov’t agencies\n\n	• Source: GRI\n	• Objective: Standardized reporting format that gives guidelines and boundaries to the process of sustainability\n\n	• Date: first version of Sustainability Reporting Guidelines released in 2000 (currently in process of developing v.4)\n	• Topics: financial reporting, sustainability reporting, water metrics, water-performance indicators\n\n	• Strengths: Continuous update/refinement of framework, sector-specific metrics, combo of quantitative and qualitative metrics, standardized framework • improves caparability\n\n	• Limitations: Lengthy process to generate a report, leading to significant resource commitment and GRI report adopters tend to be larger corporations with sufficient financial and HR means; metrics beget metrics – reports often run hundreds of pages, making it difficult to summarize and parse info; annual reporting timeframe may be too long for timely decision-making; voluntary audit of reports.\n\n	• Other Sustainability Programs: The G3 sustainability Performance Indicators are organized into 3 categories: Economic, Environmental and Social ( Labor, Human Rights, Society and Product Responsibility subcategories)\n\n	• Tags: financial-reporting, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics, water-performance-indicators\n\n	CDP - Water Disclosure\n\n	• Website: https://www.cdproject.net/en-US/Programmes/Pages/water.aspx\n\n	• Description: "CDP Water Disclosure provides critical water-related data from the world’s largest corporations to inform the global market place on investment risk and commercial opportunity. Companies targeted are the:\n\n	largest 500 companies globally (the FTSE Global Equity Index Series)\n\n	largest 100 Australian companies (the ASX 100)\n\n	largest 100 South African companies (the JSE 100)\n\n	The 2011 report includes data from 354 financial institutions with assets of US$43T.\n\n	• Target Audience (User): business organizations, institutional investors, government\n\n	• Source: CDP, with companies disclosing relevant info on a voluntary basis.\n	• Date: report published every November\n	• Topics: financial reporting, sustainability reporting, water metrics, Best Management Practices , finance\n\n	• Strengths: Continuous refinement of water questionnaire; integration with GRI and GHG Protocol; combination of quantitative and qualitative metrics\n\n	• Limitations: Voluntary nature may skew resulting aggregate data; findings are only for the largest companies in the world or companies with the HR means to dedicate resources to project\n\n	• Other Sustainable Programs Carbon disclosure &amp; information on climate change for large investors, cities, corporations, public entities; Global Corporations climate change impacts within supply chain\n\n	• Tags: financial-reporting, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics, Best-Management-Practices, finance\n\n	Institute for Supply Management (ISM) Sustainability and Social Responsibility Metrics and Performance Criteria (Document)\n\n	• Website: http://www.ism.ws/Files/SR/Metrics.pdf\n\n	• Description: List of sustainability and CSR Metrics and performance criteria (5 pages) for "(1) supply organization, (2) entity and (3) supply base (e.g., first tier and beyond, transportation services, etc.)"; ISM website includes best practices, guides, "How-tos", and links to green purchasing websites about sustainability, energy, water, and CSR related to supply management\n\n	• Target Audience (User): supply professionals and management\n\n	• Source: Institute of Supply Management (ISM); "largest" supply management professional association; ISM''s mission is to lead the supply management profession through its standards of excellence, research, promotional activities, and education\n	• Date: last updated on February 16, 2011\n	• Topics: financial reporting, sustainability reporting, water metrics, Best Management Practices\n\n	• Strengths: emphasis on supply chain management; more resources maybe available to members only\n\n	• Limitations: criteria document list only; serves as guide only\n\n	• Tags: financial-reporting, sustainability-reporting, water-metrics, Best-Management-Practices\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '63', NULL, 'topics/water/tools-metrics-reporting/sustainability-reporting-tools', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/63', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/63'),
(613, 'Climate Change Tools', ' \n	by Mary Kean and Carey Chen\n\n	January 2012\n\n	For a more detailed &amp; and up to date review of new metrics, refer to our Water Metrics Report&nbsp;and&nbsp;the tables on EcoCloud Water Metrics\n\n	Climate Resilience Evaluation &amp; Awareness Tool (CREAT)\n\n	• Website: Climate Resilience Evaluation &amp; Awareness Tool (CREAT)\n	• Description: " EPA has developed CREAT, a software tool to assist drinking water and wastewater utility owners and operators in understanding potential climate change threats and in assessing the related risks at their individual utilities. CREAT provides users with access to the most recent national assessment of climate change impacts for use in considering how these changes will impact utility operations and missions"\n	• Target Audience (User): water/wastewater utility owners and operators\n\n	• Source: United States. Environmental Protection Agency\n	• Date: Dec 17, 2010\n	• Topics: Adaption, drought, rain, precipitation, flooding, water quality, water supply, changes in supply, snowpack, water utilities guidance, models and tools\n\n	• Strengths: Contains info at regional and local levels; provides suggested adaptation strategies\n\n	• Limitations: Too narrow in scope; CREAT is only for drinking water and wastewater utility owners and operators; meant to be a stand-alone risk assessment tool – does not allow integration with other tools\n\n	• Tags: Adaption, drought, rain, precipitation, flooding, water-quality, water-supply, changes-in-supply, snowpack, water-utilities-guidance, models-and-tools\n\n	For More Climate Change Resources Related to Water:\n\n	Santa Clara Valley Water District Climate Change Portal\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '70', NULL, 'topics/water/tools-metrics-reporting/climate-change-tools', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/70', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/70');
