(615, 'Green Building', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead &nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Green Data Centers\n\n	\n		Best Practices for Making the Data Center Energy Efficient\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		Data Centers can consume up to 100 to 200 times as much of electricity as standard office spaces and so are prime targets for energy efficient design.\n	\n		This article provides an overview of best practices for an energy-efficient data center design and walks through some of the strategies that can be deployed in Information Technology (IT) systems and their environment, data center air management, cooling and electric systems, on-site generation and heat recovery.\n	\n		Information Technology (IT) Systems\n	\n		In a typical data center, IT equipment load can account for over half of the facility’s energy use. Use of energy efficient equipment will significantly reduce the load, which will also downsize the equipment required to cool them.\n	\n		Efficient Servers\n	\n		Purchase servers equipped with energy-efficient processors and look for products that include variable fan speed. Servers that meet Energy Star efficiency requirements will be on average 30% more efficient than standard servers. Install power monitoring software on servers that can detect and direct certain servers to go idle or in low power.\n	\n		Storage Devices\n	\n		Upgrade from traditional methods to thin-provisioning which will maximize storage capacity utilization by drawing from a common pool of purchased storage on an as-need basis. It will also allow for extra physical capacity to be installed when data approaches capacity threshold. Take superfluous data offline and consolidate storage drives into a Storage Area Network.\n	\n		Network Equipment\n	\n		On newer generations of network equipment, look for active energy management measures like idle state logic, gate count optimizations and memory access algorithms to reduce energy usage based on variance of network demand. Ethernet network efficiency can also be substantially reduced by quickly switching the speed of network links to the amount of data that is currently transmitted.\n	\n		Power Supplies\n	\n		Consider one power supply per rack instead of one per server. Integrated rack mounted power supplies operate at higher load (70%) as compared to individual power supplies (20% - 25%) which vastly improves power supply efficiency. Today it is possible to find power supplies with 95% efficiency which can also help lower the data center’s electricity bill.\n	\n		Consolidation\n	\n		Consolidation happens through hardware-location and virtualization.\n	\n		Hardware Location – Equipments with similar heat load densities and temperature requirements should be grouped together. This allows cooling systems to be directed to the least energy-intensive set points on each location.\n	\n		Virtualization – Enable running multiple independent virtual operating systems on a single computer in order to drastically reduce the number of servers and thereby reduce the server power and size of necessary cooling equipment.\n	\n		Air Management\n	\n		Air management in a data center deals with things like minimizing or eliminating mixing between cool air supplied to equipment and hot air rejected from equipment. An effective air management system that minimizes bypass of cool air around rack intakes and recirculation of heat exhaust back into rack intakes can reduce operating costs, reduce heat related failures and increase the data center’s power density.\n	\n		Implement Cable Management\n	\n		A poorly laid out cable system will obstruct and interfere with the distribution of cooling air. A minimum effective height of 24 inches should be provided for raised floor installations. There should be a clear and persistent cable managing strategy employed in the center.\n	\n		Aisle Separation and Containment\n	\n		\n	\n		&nbsp;&nbsp;Data center equipment should be laid out in rows of racks with alternating cold (rack intake) and hot (rack exhaust) aisles as this increases the cooling capacity of the system. Equipment with non standard exhaust directions must be addressed in some way (shrouds, ducts etc) to achieve the designed front-to-back airflow. Cable openings in raised floors and ceilings should be sealed. The hot air does not mix with cold air as per design and this can allow reuse of the exhaust heat.\n	\n		Use flexible plastic barriers such as plastic supermarket refrigeration covers to seal the space between tops of the racks to greatly improve hot aisle/cold aisle isolation. Use VSD (Variable Speed Drives) or other speed-control based fans to take maximum advantage of this optimization.\n	\n		Use overhead or under-the-floor air distribution systems. For overhead systems, diffusers should be located directly in front of racks, above the cold aisle. Under-the-floor air distributions systems usually have maintenance issues when wanting to change wiring etc and so must be very carefully planned.\n	\n		Cooling Systems\n	\n		Cooling Systems should always keep in mind initial and future loads, and part and low-load conditions, as the need for digital data is always expanding.\n	\n		Direct Expansion (DX) Systems\n	\n		Use packaged DX air conditioners as cooling equipment for smaller data centers. Also look for packaged inexpensive rooftop units. Several manufacturers also offer units with multiple and/or variable speed compressors to improve part-load efficiency. Also investigate newer energy efficiency cooling options that are integrated within the CRAC.\n	\n		Air Handlers\n	\n		Better performance and efficiency can be achieved by utilizing specifically designed central air handler systems. Centralized systems today offer more advantages than traditional distributed systems. The following two pie charts elaborate on the differences between using centralized vs. distributed air handling systems in two fairly large data centers in terms of the electricity consumption distribution.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		\n	\n		Low Pressure Drop Air Delivery A low-pressure drop design (‘oversized’ ductwork or a generous under floor) is essential to optimizing energy efficiency by reducing fan energy and facilitates long-term build out flexibility. Ducts should be as short as possible in length and sized significantly larger than typical office systems, since 24-hour operation of the data center increases the value of energy use over time relative to first cost. Periodic manual air flow balancing is more cost effective than implementing an automated air flow balancing scheme.\n	\n		High Efficiency Chilled Water Systems\n	\n		Use high efficiency VFD equipped water cooled chillers with an appropriate condenser water reset. Condensed water and chilled water pumps should be selected for the highest pumping efficiency at typical operating conditions, rather than at full load condition.\n	\n		A medium-temperature, as opposed to low-temperature, chilled water loop design using a water supply temperature of 55°F or higher improves chiller efficiency and eliminates uncontrolled phantom dehumidification loads (refer to “Humidification” and “Controls” sections). Higher temperature chilled water also allows more water-side economizer hours, in which the cooling towers can serve some or the entire load directly, reducing or eliminating the load on the chillers.\n	\n		The condenser water loop should also be optimized; a 5°F to 7°F approach cooling tower plant with a condenser water temperature reset pairs nicely with a variable speed chiller to offer large energy savings.\n	\n		Free Cooling\n	\n		Most nights and during mild winter conditions, the lowest cost option to cool data centers is an air-side economizer; however, a proper engineering evaluation of the local climate conditions must be completed to evaluate whether this is the case for a specific data center.\n	\n		Due to the humidity and contamination concerns associated with data centers, careful control and design work may be required to ensure that cooling savings are not lost because of excessive humidification and filtration requirements, respectively.\n	\n		For data centers with active humidity control, a dew-point temperature lockout scheme should be used as part of the air-side economizer control strategy.\n	\n		Thermal Storage\n	\n		Thermal storage is a method of storing thermal energy in a reservoir for later use, and is particularly useful in facilities with particularly high cooling loads such as data centers.\n	\n		In climates with cool, dry nighttime conditions, cooling towers can directly charge a chilled water storage tank; using a small fraction of the energy otherwise required by chillers. A thermal storage tank can also be an economical alternative to additional mechanical cooling capacity.\n	\n		Humidification\n	\n		Low-energy humidification techniques can replace traditional electric resistance humidifiers with an adiabatic approach that uses the heat present in the air or recovered from the computer heat load for humidification. Ultrasonic humidifiers, evaporative wetted media and micro droplet spray are some examples of adiabatic humidifiers.\n	\n		Controls\n	\n		A center-wide control system should be programmed to maximize energy efficiency. VSD should be deployed on CRAC and CRAH units. For raised floor installations, fan speed should be controlled to maintain an under-floor pressure set point. Variable air volume delivery systems should be installed. There is no need to tightly control humidity (a legacy approach).\n	\n		On the chilled water plant side, variable flow pumping and chillers equipped with variable speed driven compressors should be installed to provide energy-efficient operation during low load conditions.\n	\n		Electrical Systems\n	\n		Like cooling systems, consider initial and future loads, and part and low-part conditions when designing and selecting equipment for data center’s electrical system.\n	\n		Power Distribution\n	\n		The electrical power distribution path consists of the utility service, switchboard, switchgear, alternate power sources (i.e. backup generator), paralleling equipment for redundancy (i.e. multiple UPS and PDU), and auxiliary conditioning equipment (i.e. line filters, capacitor bank).\n	\n		Operating efficiencies can be controlled and optimized through thoughtful selection of these components.\n	\n		Buy UPS systems for your data centers that have efficiency between 90% to 95%. Redundancy in particular requires design attention; operating a single large UPS in parallel with a 100% capacity identical redundant UPS unit (n+1 design redundancy) results in very low load factor operation.\n	\n		The following figure shows a typical UPS efficiency curve for 100 kVA capacity and greater.\n	\n		\n	\n		Line interactive systems often provide enough power conditioning for servers at a higher efficiency than typical double conversion UPS systems. New technologies currently being proven on the market, such as flywheel systems, should also be considered. Such systems eliminate replacement and disposal concerns associated with conventional lead-acid battery based UPS systems.\n	\n		DC Power\n	\n		One way to reduce the number of times power needs to be converted is by utilizing a DC power distribution. This has not yet become a common practice and, therefore, could carry significantly higher first costs, but it has been tested at several facilities.\n	\n		A study done by Lawrence Berkeley National Labs in 2007 compared the benefits of adopting a 380V DC power distribution for a data-com facility to a traditional 480V AC power distribution system. The results showed that the facility using the DC power had a 7% reduction in energy consumption compared to the typical facility with AC power distribution.\n	\n		Lighting\n	\n		Zone based occupancy sensors throughout a data center can have a significant impact on reducing the lighting electrical use. Careful selection of an efficient lighting layout (e.g. above aisles and not above the server racks), reduced lamps and ballasts will reduce not only the lighting electrical usage but also the load on the cooling system.\n	\n		Other opportunities\n	\n		On-Site Generation\n	\n		To reduce first costs, on-site generation equipment should replace the backup generator system. It provides both an alternative to grid power and waste heat that can be used to meet nearby heating needs or harvested to cool the data center through absorption or adsorption chiller technologies.\n	\n		An option is to use Co-generation plants, involving the use of a heat engine or power station to simultaneously produce electricity and useful heat. The waste heat produced by the generator can be used to run an absorption chiller which provides cooling to the data center.\n	\n		Use of Waste Heat\n	\n		Waste heat can be used directly or to supply cooling required by the data center through the use of absorption or adsorption chillers, reducing chilled water plant energy costs by well over 50%. Adsorption chillers generally restart more quickly and easily compared to absorption chillers. While adsorption chillers have been in production for more than 20 years, they have only recently been introduced in the U.S. market.\n	\n		The direct use of waste heat for low temperature heating applications such as preheating ventilation air for buildings or heating water will provide the greatest energy savings.\n	\n		Source: Best Practices Guide for Energy-Efficient Data Center Design, Revised March 2011 edition, U.S. Department of Energy, Federal Energy Management Program.\n\n\n	\n		Other Recent Topics:\n	\n		Benchmarking Energy for Buildings\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '57', NULL, 'topics/energy/efficiency/green-building', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/57', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/57'),
(616, 'Clean Vehicle Tech', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	2011 – The Year of Electric Cars\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		The year of the electric car has finally arrived. With manufacturers rushing to get their energy efficient vehicles out of production and into the hands of the customer this year, and with the Government offering compelling tax rebates on electric vehicles, there are many signs that indicate that this might turn out to be an year of extraordinary choices for a car buyer who is looking at saving energy, reducing cost, going green and helping the environment.\n	\n		\n			Lithium-ion battery,&nbsp;The New&nbsp;Electric &nbsp; Power Plant\n	\n	\n		Manufacturers like Nissan have already been gearing up for a mass introduction of electric vehicles by showing up models to the public in various Auto Expo shows last year, offering test drives, getting public feedback and advertising in media. All these activities will now culminate into an exciting launch as many of these new electric car models are expected to hit the showrooms this year. The new EVs start from a price of around $32,780 (the Leaf''s price) and go up to $87,400 (the Fisker Karma plug-in hybrid). The cost of these cars could be offset with federal and state rebates and tax credits. To find out more about what kinds of rebates apply to you locally, please visit the following resource:\n	\n		http://www.driveclean.ca.gov\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '59', NULL, 'topics/energy/efficiency/clean-vehicle-tech', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/59', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/59'),
(617, 'Case Studies', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Local Energy Efficiency Programs\n\n	San Jose’s Green Vision Clean Energy Showcase\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		San Jose is one of the 25 cities participating in DOE’s Solar America communities Program. San Jose’s vision over the next 15 years is to achieve the following goals and to reduce the carbon footprint in the city by more than half: create 25000 clean Tech jobs as the world center of Clean Tech innovation, reduce per capita Energy use by 50%, receive 100% of our electrical power from clean renewable sources, build or retrofit 50 million square feet of green buildings and replace 100% of our streetlights with smart zero-emission lighting.\n	\n		One of the special projects funded is the San Jose Clean Energy Showcase - a Green Vision Education and Demonstration Center that acts as the hub of providing information on solar technologies and innovative financing options and allows the community to gain hands-on experience with solar technologies.\n	\n		The San Jose Clean Energy Showcase brings cutting edge technologies and innovations in the area of renewable energy to the footsteps of residents, educating them about energy efficiency and use of renewable sources in their homes. The showcase is a live, hands-on, instructional experience for existing and potential home owners to learn about the benefits of using clean energy while experiencing and learning about various clean energy options available in the market today, and by directly talking to and learning more with company representatives available in the showcase.\n	\n		Participants in the clean energy showcase include various companies that are leaders in their renewable energy domains (example solar or wind technology companies). The clean energy showcase also brings together schools and colleges like SJSU School of Art and Design and the San Jose Public Art department.\n	\n		Following are some of the participants and the projects that are demonstrated to the public:\n	\n		\n			Windspire Energy – Off Grid vertical axis wind turbine.\n		\n			Schuco / Sunwater Solar – An off-grid roof-mounted Solar thermal system\n		\n			Sunpods – A factory built solar array utilized for both on and off-grid solar energy projects by Sunpods. Includes a turnkey electric vehicle charging station and car.\n		\n			Cool Roof Display – Lawrence Berkley National Lab Heat Island Group\n		\n			Silicon Valley Energy Watch and New Avenue Homes - New Avenue EcoHome featuring energy efficiency technologies\n		\n			City of San Jose Public Art Program/ San Jose State University/ Qcells - Off grid thin film photovoltaic shading structure with interactive elements\n		\n			Burnham Energy/ Stion/ Fresco - Grid-tied high-efficiency thin film array\n		\n			Nanaosolar/ Real Good Solar/ Sunlink&nbsp; - Grid-tied High efficiency thin-film photovoltaic array\n		\n			Cromasun – A high performance solar collector for powering industry and air conditioning systems\n		\n			Sopogy – Off-grid Micro Concentrating Solar Power Collector\n		\n			Akena solar (Westinghouse Solar)/ San Jose Fire department/ SMA America - Two grid tied systems side by side arrays demonstrating photovoltaic modules utilizing traditional inverters vs. micro inverters\n		\n			Armageddon Energy – Grid tied, light weight Solar Clover photovoltaic array\n		\n			Sunpower - Grid tied array showcasing Sunpower’s T5 photovoltaic commercial roof tiles.\n		\n			US Solar &amp; Wind Synergies – Off-grid LED streetlights with wind turbine, photovoltaic module and battery storage\n		\n			Off-grid photovoltaic modules with electric car plug-in capability and battery storage\n	\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Highlights from Solar Energy Efficiency Fair – April 30th\n	\n		Home efficiency through State rebates Energy Workshop by Solar City - This talk highlighted steps that homeowners can take to increase home energy efficiency before actually installing any solar PVs and also described preferred ways to get your home audited for energy efficiency. Solar City via an agency called BPI certifies houses and buildings by using a DOE certified software that simulates the energy utilized in a house using various factors like Latitude, Longitude, Air flows, etc, and calculates potential gains for homeowners in terms of energy savings as well as rebates upon installing energy efficient measures. For example, existing attic and crawl space leakages are detected, duct systems are inspected as potential leak sources, blower door tests are performed, and a 3 hour energy evaluation is done to determine the current energy efficiency of your home, followed by home energy improvement suggestions that a home owner may be interested in. After the workshop interested home-owners could enroll for discounted energy evaluation sessions with Solar City and BPI.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Go Solar and Save Workshop by Real Good Solar and Sunpower - This talk highlighted the rebates and incentives that homeowners are entitled to when they install Solar PVs in their homes. A representative from Freedom Solar, a vendor agency of Sunpower, spoke about how to decrease our energy bill, how to calculate payback times on installing a solar PV panel, how to get inspections done, permit conditions, how to get certified contractors, typical rates, and various other aspects of interest to home owners potentially seeking to install Solar PV panels. Various important trivia was shared. For example a $150 per month electricity bill means you will save by installing solar PV. &nbsp;Or that with the current AB 920 legislation, home owners can expect changing rates (12 cents per 2KwH from 8.5 cents per 2 KwH last year), pay off period on smaller systems is typically 25 years while larger system installations have faster payback rates.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Solar Hot Water Workshop by Schucco\n	\n		This workshop highlighted the benefits of using Solar Hot Water in homes. For example typical thermal collectors are at about 75 gallons capacity and save 70% of your energy. Schuco also had an actual exhibit and demonstration of their Solar Hot Water equipment installed in a model home and an expert was available to explain and answer any questions around the solar hot water equipment’s installation, use and maintenance. The equipment shown in the demo uses a Glycol Antifreeze that flows through the pump and heats up the water. Costing around $12,000, there is also a $3000 rebate and a 30% tax credit that can be claimed. Vendors like Apollo Systems support both Solar PV and Thermal installations, and provide a monitoring system to the home owner to detect that systems are working. An interesting use of this technology can be applied in your Pools by using a radiant system that costs $10,000 with a 30% rebate.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Workshop by Firefighters Association \n	\n		The workshop explained about “Setbacks” that are installed in the San Jose Fire code now so as to allow spaces in the roof of homes for fire-fighters to climb up and shut down any fires caused due to overheating of Solar PV panels. Around 600V of electricity continuously flows in a typical micro-inverter type PVs installed at the roof of your home, and an accidental fire caused due to a PV is harder to put out, simply because there is no wire that can be disconnected. There was a live demo by firefighters as they made people aware of precautions to take when installing or cleaning PVs on your rooftops.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		SJSU - Students showcasing college projects\n	\n		Finally, a lot of innovative real life projects in progress were showcased by students of SJSU. For example the picture illustrates the bike-bud project that uses solar panels in an innovative way, promoting not only solar panels but also the healthy activity of biking in the community.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		EcoCloud™ members: This is a collaborative site. Please add your own case studies here. When your page is ready, add a link to the list at left. All contributed content is subject to moderation. Get started\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '60', NULL, 'topics/energy/efficiency/case-studies', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/60', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/60'),
(241, 'November - Carbon Monoxide Awareness Month', 'Redwood City, CA - As the colder weather starts to settle in and the use of fossil fuel heating increases, the Redwood City Fire Department reminds residents that November is Carbon Monoxide Awareness month.\n\n\n Redwood City Fire Department Advisory - November is Carbon Monoxide Awareness Month&nbsp;\n\n Contact:\n Jim Palisi, Fire Marshal\n Redwood City Fire Department\n\n 650-740-0827\n\n &nbsp;\n Carbon monoxide (CO) is a colorless, odorless gas that is produced from heaters, fireplaces, furnaces, and many types of appliances and cooking devices. Each year, CO claims the lives of an average of 480 people, and sends more than 20,000 people to emergency rooms, nationwide. In Redwood City, there have been incidents of CO poisoning in recent years from in-house heating and furnaces, which have been life-threatening and nearly disastrous.&nbsp;\n &nbsp;\n The best way for homeowners to stay protected from CO is to have a carbon monoxide alarm installed on every floor and outside each sleeping area. A recent study found that nearly nine in 10 California households did not have a CO alarm. Combination CO/smoke alarms are available.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n &nbsp;\n As of July 1, 2011, state law requires owners of single family homes with attached garages or fossil fuel sources for heating to install carbon monoxide alarms in every California home.&nbsp; In addition, all other dwelling units, like apartments, are required to have an alarm by January 1, 2013.\n &nbsp;\n California''s Carbon Monoxide Month is intended to help educate homeowners about the law and to encourage them to install a carbon monoxide alarm. CAL FIRE / Office of the State Fire Marshal are teaming up with fire departments across the state, as well as other State agencies to spread the word about the dangers of CO and how to keep families and friends safe.&nbsp;&nbsp;\n &nbsp;\n For more information on carbon monoxide visit the CAL FIRE website at www.fire.ca.gov or visit the website for the California Department of Public Health at www.cdph.ca.gov. Visit the Redwood City Fire Department''s web page at www.redwoodcity.org/fire.&nbsp;\n &nbsp;', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '14', 27, 'blog2/view/14', 'admin/blog2/edit/14', 'admin/blog2/delete/14'),
(328, 'Holiday Book Talk: Gift Book Suggestions', '\n Learn about great new books for adults and kids!\n Date: 11/19/2012 6:30 PM - 7:45 PM\n Cost: Free\n Location: Central Park Library- Redwood Room\n 2635 Homestead Road\n Santa Clara, California 95051\n\n Jenn Ramage from Random House, Children''s Librarian Erin Ulrich, and Adult Services Librarian Mary Boyle, share their recommendations for new books to read and to gift this holiday season.\n There will be a free raffle - the prize is a bag of newly released books! Please provide your name and email address at the event to sign up for raffle.\n The event is free and open to the public.\n This event is presented by the Foundation and Friends of the Santa Clara Library in partnership with the Santa Clara City Library and Random House.\n Click here for the event flyer. http://santaclaraca.gov/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=8058\n\n (Sent by)\n\n Web Manager webmanager@santaclaraca.gov', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '16', 27, 'blog2/view/16', 'admin/blog2/edit/16', 'admin/blog2/delete/16'),
(318, 'Silicon Valley Water Awards', 'The application/nomination period for the 2013 Silicon Valley Water Conservation Awards is open until February 15, 2013.\n\nGo to www.waterawards.org for more details.\n\nRecognizing the primacy of water to the health and economic vitality of our region and the environment, the Silicon Valley Water Conservation Awards are presented to organizations, agencies, businesses and individuals whose programs and leadership have advanced water conservation in Silicon Valley (San Mateo County, Santa Clara County and Alameda County from Hayward South.) Our coalition of 20 organizations represents a diverse cross-section of respected parties concerned about water conservation and the need for a strategic response, both to droughts and to a new era of water scarcity. The goal of the Awards is to raise awareness and celebrate outstanding achievements in water conservation through best practices, efficiency and innovation.\n \nThis years award categories are:\nGovernment Agency / Water Utility\nBusiness\nOrganization\nGreenscape Management\nEducation\nWater Champion\n\nMark Your Calendars!\nThe 2013 Awards Ceremony will be held on World Water Day, March 22nd, 2013. Go to www.waterawards.org for more details.\n\nHosted by the Silicon Valley Water Conservation Coalition including the following organizations:\nActerra\nBay Area Water Supply and Conservation Agency\nCity of Cupertino\nCity of Hayward\nCity of Mountain View\nCity of Palo Alto\nCity of Redwood City\nCity of Sunnyvale\nClean Water Action\nCalifornia Native Plant Society\nJoint Venture: Silicon Valley Network\nPurissima Hills Water District\nSanta Clara County Creeks Coalition\nSanta Clara Valley Water District\nSierra Club Loma Prieta Chapter\nSilicon Valley Leadership Group\nSustainable San Mateo County\nSustainable Silicon Valley\nTuolumne River Trust\nWholly H2O', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '19', 11, 'blog2/view/19', 'admin/blog2/edit/19', 'admin/blog2/delete/19'),
