(325, 'Triton event - Fall Floral Festival', 'Join us for a beautiful night of flowers, art, music, fine hors d''oeuvres and wine!\n\n\n Where: Triton Museum of Art, 1505 Warburton Ave., Santa Clara, CA 95050\n\n When: Saturday, October 20, 2012, 6:30 pm - 8:30 pm\n\n Tickets: $50.00\n\n This year''s event will feature a special world premier performance by Alla Breve, Peninsula Women''s Chorus''s small ensemble, who will debut their own special interpretation of a work of visual fine art. Noted composer Frank Ferko was commissioned to write a composition based upon a painting by artist Ryan Reynolds: Alma Submerged. Reynolds is a professor of Art at Santa Clara University and one of the up and coming artists of our region. This is a special opportunity to hear a world premier performance that merges the talents of the artist, the composer, and the celebrated Alla Breve of the Peninsula Women''s Chorus.\n\n Can''t come Saturday night? Come Sunday, October 21 from 11:00 am to 5:00 pm to view the beauty for $5.00/person.\n For more information on the event or to buy tickets, visit the event website.\n\n \n Thank you to our in-kind catering sponsors:\n Catered Too!\n Parsley, Sage, Rosemary &amp; Thyme Catering&nbsp;\n the Party Helpers\n Restaurant O Catering', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '8', 27, 'blog2/view/8', 'admin/blog2/edit/8', 'admin/blog2/delete/8'),
(618, 'Benchmarking', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	Benchmarking Energy for Buildings\n\n	Jan 2nd 2012\n\n	Benchmarking energy means measuring the energy consumed by a building, using a standard set of tools like the Portfolio Manager, and comparing these measurements against a relevant set of energy consumption data using a program like Energy Star. Energy benchmarking in CA is currently mandated for certain non-residential buildings of size greater than 10,000 sq. ft. which are sold, leased or refinanced.\n\n	The legislation for energy benchmarking for CA buildings calls for a mandatory disclosure of energy benchmarking data by buildings within a certain timeframe. This is primarily enforced by AB 1103 – the Commercial Building Benchmarking Law that was signed by the Governor in 2009 and it currently applies to non-residential buildings. This bill is now regulated by the CEC and it mandates that by the end of 2011, CA based Utilities like PG&amp;E are able to provide energy consumption data per request from their customers as a first phase of implementation. The second phase for implementing the same law requires that by 2012, non-residential building owners will have to disclose benchmarking data for the refinancing, sale or lease to the market for an entire building.\n\n	The timeframes for implementing benchmarking criteria (as defined in AB 1103) are separately established by AB 531 which provides for the CEC to establish the schedule to implement AB 1103 through a CA non-residential building energy use disclosure program.\n\n	Accordingly the requirement for implementing AB 1103 is that by 2012 buildings with 50,000 square feet area should disclose their energy benchmarking data; that by Jan 2013 buildings with areas between 10,000 and 50,000 square feet should disclose their benchmark data, and that finally by July 2013 buildings with areas between 5,000 to 10,000 square feet should disclose their energy benchmark data. AB 1103 also mandates that buildings that are eligible to receive Energy Star scores from 1 – 100 must also disclose their final scores to the market.\n\n	The energy benchmarking process is itself carried out by following certain steps as outlined by the Portfolio Manager. The energy performance rating resulting from this process utilizes certain building variables affecting energy consumption like Building Size, Space Type, Weather, Hours of Operation, Occupancy and Plug Load. Once a building has its energy benchmarking data, it also sets itself up for periodic energy audits to measure changes in energy consumption patterns over periods of time.\n\n	Utilities like PG&amp;E now provide Automated Benchmarking Service (ABS) for their customers which create Portfolio Manager Accounts for users and allow them to view energy consumption data and benchmarking results online. Similarly the City of San Francisco is also active in disseminating information about energy benchmarking strategies that it plans to carry out through webinars in collaboration with Utilities like PG&amp;E, as well as by establishing detailed ordinances that describe the practicalities of dealing with benchmarking data from commercial buildings in San Francisco. The city’s goal is to reduce energy consumption by 50% over the next 20 years by identifying potential savings, engaging tenants, and leading by example in public facilities.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '100', NULL, 'topics/energy/efficiency/benchmarking', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/100', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/100'),
(565, 'Efficiency', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Energy efficiency can be improved by using less energy to accomplish a particular task. For example, insulating a home allows a building to use less energy to maintain a desired temperature. Another example is that compact fluorescent lights use two-thirds less energy and may last 6 to 10 times longer than incandescent lights.\n\n	Improvements in energy efficiency are most often achieved by incorporating a more efficient technology or production process.\n\n	\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Most Energy Used in Commercial Buildings goes to Space heating\n\n	\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Source: U.S. Energy Information Administration\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '38', NULL, 'topics/energy/efficiency', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/38', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/38'),
(626, 'CleanTech Open Global Forum 2011', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	CleanTech Open Global Forum 2011\n\n	Dec 18th 2011\n\n	CleanTech Open is the world’s largest clean technology business competition for clean tech entrepreneurs. This annual event in the U.S. that was started in 2006 seeks to discover, promote and reward the most promising and upcoming clean tech entrepreneur companies of today, by mentoring and training these companies and providing opportunities for Venture Capital fundingof up to $250,000. Since its inception, this program has resulted in the creation of more than $300 Million of private capital by its alumni companies and has led to more than 2500 clean tech jobs in the market.\n\n	The clean tech open business competition of 2011 focused on key clean tech innovation and business ideas in the areas of Renewable Energy, Energy Efficiency and Smart Power, Green Grid and Energy Storage among other clean tech categories. The participants for both the National Business Competition and the Global Ideas Competition included startups that had invested themselves in creating unique business opportunities in one of the key categories listed for the competition. After being evaluated all year long for their business viabilities and success probabilities, the 2011 event culminated into a 2 day Cleantech Open 2011 Global Forum event held in San Jose on November 15th and 16th 2011, where regional and category finalistshad to compete by pitching their ideas to the judges and where the final winners of the 2011 competition were announced.\n\n	The grand prize of $250,000 went to Atmosphere Recovery Inc, the winner of the Renewable Energy category, for developing unique laser-based gas analyzer systems that enables advanced energy process control and efficient manufacturing. The runners up included Indow Windows, the winner of Energy Efficiency category, which manufactures thermal-window inserts that press into place on insides of window frames and improve performance at fractional prices, and PK Clean, a company that incorporates a unique catalytic de-polymerization process that converts various forms of wastes into useful forms of energy.\n\n	National category winners also included GridMobility, the winner of Smart Power category, whose proprietary signal technology catalyses smart-grid growth by enabling business, industry and consumers to choose electricity sources based on personal preferences, and Whole Tree Structures, winner of the Green Building category, that manufactures structural building systems made from round timber which is the waste product of sustainably managed forests.\n\n	Other notable participants included ArticSand – an MIT spinout delivering power conversion with a 10X reduction in circuit size and cutting power losses by 75%, Enovative Kontrol Systems that develops patented controls for water heating efficiency systems, HM3 Energy that uses proprietary biomass torrefaction technology to convert woody biomass into energy-dense briquettes, Keystone Tower Systems that use on-site welded steel towers for next generation wind turbines, and Sheerwind Inc that uses proprietary technology to accelerate and concentrate wind to produce cheaper electricity than natural gas. A complete list of finalists can be found here.\n\n	Click here for a complete list of winners and announcements for the 2011 CleanTech Open competition. For general questions as a future participant to the CleanTech Open competition, check this link.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '102', NULL, 'topics/energy/events-archive/cleantech-open-global-forum-2011', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/102', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/102'),
(631, 'US Renewable Energy Usage and Production 2010', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	U.S. Renewable Energy Usage and Production 2010\n\n	Dec 10th 2011\n\n	Renewable Energy Usage and Consumption\n\n	In 2010, renewable energy consumption in the U.S. was 8.049 quadrillion Btu, which was slightly more than 8% of the total energy consumed by the nation. The largest contributions in this 8% share of renewable energy come from biomass energy (53%) followed by hydro energy (31%), wind energy (11%), geothermal energy (3%) and solar energy (1%), as shown in the figure below.\n\n	\n\n	Comparing Renewable Energy Consumption Trends with 2009\n\n	Renewable energy consumption in 2009was slightly less at 7.744 quadrillion Btu .The main drivers behind the increase in 2010 are consumption increases in biofuels and wind, of amounts of 288 trillion Btu and 203 trillion Btu respectively. These increases were partially offset by a decrease in conventional hydro-power by an amount of 160 trillion Btu. As a whole, renewable energy consumption rose by 6% from 2009 to over 8 quadrillion Btu in 2010, growing faster than the total energy consumption increase of 4% in the same period.\n\n	Comparing Renewable Energy Consumption Trends with 2006\n\n	From 2006, changes in renewable energy consumption and usage patterns in the U.S. have been significant, as depicted in the two figures shown below. Changes from 2006 to 2010 show an increase in wind power usage from 4% to 11%, an increase in biomass usage from 49% to 53%, and a decrease in the share of conventional hydroelectric from 43% to 31%. The figures also show that while both Geothermal and Solar have been growing quantitatively (in Btu usage) over this period, their shares have remained constant at 3% and 1% respectively. Overall, between 2006 and 2010, renewable energy consumption in the U.S. has quantitatively grown by more than 2000 quadrillion Btu, with increased share of wind energy and biomass energy consumption.\n\n	\n\n	Increase in Biofuel Consumption\n\n	Increases in Biofuel consumption from 2006 to 2010 are largely from ethanol consumption which has more than doubled to over 1 quadrillion Btu during this period. This increase has happened because of two Government regulations; First, in the Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007 (EISA)Clean Air Act section, the US EPA has issued an increase in demand target volume from 13.19 billion gallons to 13.95 billion ethanol equivalent gallons of bio-fuels in 2010, and secondly, the EPA has also now permitted the blending of motor gasoline with 15% ethanol (E15), raising this blending ratio from the recent 10% limit. The E15 blending is applicable to light-duty vehicles manufactured from 2001 and later. An 85% mix of ethanol (E85) also holds potential growth for the market. Biodiesel, on the other hand showed a decrease in consumption from 2009, due to the expiration of biodiesel blender tax credit and its late renewal in 2010.\n\n	Sector-wise Consumption of Renewable Energy\n\n	Interestingly, out of all the renewable energy consumed, only about half of the renewable consumption is for the electric power sector at 4000 trillion Btu. This market share has in fact decreased from 55% in 2006 to 50% in 2010, dropping by around 2% from 2009. This is followed by a steady share of 2249 Btu of consumption in industrial sector. Transportation sector’s consumption of renewable energy on the other hand has doubled during this period (from 475 trillion Btu in 2006 to 1098 trillion Btu in 2010, an increase from 7% to 14%) due to an expansion in biofuel consumption. Residential and commercial sectors had smaller but stable market shares.\n\n	Electricity Generation\n\n	Out of a total of 4,120 billion kWh of total energy produced in the U.S. in 2010, renewable energy generated 4425 billion kWh, or around 10% of the total energy produced. While total energy production increased by 4% between 2009 and 2010, renewable energy grew by only 2% in the same period, due to a net decrease of 16 billion kWh of conventional hydropower because of low water availability. With California’s exception, thirty seven U.S. states experienced losses in hydropower generation. The states of California, New York, Oregon, Texas and Washington provided more than half of the total renewable energy produced between 2009 and 2010.\n\n	Wind Generation\n\n	Wind generation increased by 21 billion kWh to 95 billion kWh from 2009 to 2010, providing 2% of total U.S. energy with the majority of increase of 6 billion kWh coming from Texas alone. Wind capacity expanded in 21 other states, while 2 states – Delaware and Maryland had wind capacity for the first time. Since 2006, wind generation has more than tripled, from 11,329 MW in 2006 to 37,889 MW in 2010.\n\n	Solar Generation\n\n	From 2006, when Solar had central station capacity in just 2 states, this sector has expanded to 15 states with capacity of 888 MW, with 4 new states in 2010. The largest share is from California (460 MW) followed by Nevada (137 MW), Florida (125 MW), Colorado (33 MW) and North Carolina (33 MW).\n\n	Growth Factors for Renewables\n\n	Factors contributing to the growth of renewables in the period from 2009 to 2010 were:\n\n	\n		The federal Production Tax Credit (PTC) provided a 2.2 cent/kWh credit for wind and 1.1 cent/kWh credit for all remaining technologies like biomass, geothermal and hydroelectric.\n	\n		The energy Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which is worth 30% of expenditures, was also available in lieu of PTC to eligible systems.\n	\n		The U.S. treasury grant program was also available under H.R.4853 providing a grant of 30 percent of the basis of property for wind, geothermal, biomass and other energy sources. The grant was 10 percent of the basis of property for geothermal heat pumps, micro turbines, and certain combined heat and power (CHP) facilities.\n	\n		Renewable Production Initiative (REPI) also provided a 2.2 cents/kWh incentive for new eligible facilities in operation.\n	\n		Renewable Portfolio Standards or mandates in 37 states.\n	\n		Lower cost of silicon used in crystalline silicon-PV installations.\n\n\n	Despite the effects of recession, competition from low natural gas prices and reluctance of utilities to enter Power Purchase Agreements (PPA) with wind, renewable capacity grew in 2010 by 3%, or 4,019 MW. These trends indicate that the generation and consumption of renewable energy will be on the growth path in the U.S. in the foreseeable future.\n\n	Source: http://www.eia.gov/renewable/annual/preliminary/\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '104', NULL, 'topics/energy/trends/us-renewable-energy-usage-and-production-2010', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/104', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/104'),
(632, 'US Renewable Energy Usage and Production 2009', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	U.S. Renewable Energy Production and Usage 2009\n\n	April 18th 2010\n\n	Renewable energy consumption for generating electricity in the U.S. stands at 8% of the total energy consumed. The largest contributions come from hydro (35%) followed by wood (24%), bio-fuels (20%) and wind (9%).\n\n	\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	U.S. is also one of the largest producers of renewable energy, closely following China. The largest production share comes from hydro (66%) followed by wind (17%), wood (9%), biomass waste (4%), geothermal (4%) and solar (0.2%). In 2009, the highest year over year growth in renewable energy was for Wind, up 28% from 2008.\n\n	Despite this growth in production, only 53% of this total renewable energy produced is actually consumed for generating electricity. A 66% contribution of Hydropower in renewable energy production for example translates only to 35% contribution towards electricity generation (53% usage of 66% production) as Hydropower gets diverted to other uses.\n\n	Overall, renewable energy production increases by around 8% yearly, contributing to around 8% of demand and around 10% of electricity generation in the U.S. This is an indication of the strong growth to be expected with using renewable sources.\n\n	According to US EIA, consumption of renewable sources for electricity will grow up to 17% of total electricity generation by 2035, in large part due to tax credits, policies like RPS (Renewable Portfolio Standards) and how RECs (Renewable Energy Certificates) are used between providers and different states. Any deterrents to this growth will come from the cost of building renewable energy power plants and infrastructural investment required to connect remotely based renewable power plants.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '105', NULL, 'topics/energy/trends/us-renewable-energy-usage-and-production-2009', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/105', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/105'),
(633, 'Solar PV Industry 2009', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	U.S. photovoltaic (PV) industry hits a record high in 2009\n\n	The U.S. Photovoltaic (P.V) industry has been hitting record highs. According to a US-EIA report released in Jan 2011, the PV industry shipped nearly 1.3 peak gigawatts of cells and modules, representing a 30 percent year to year growth from the previous year. A major factor for this is thought to be Federal Stimulus funding coupled with significant manufacturing cost reductions.\n\n	\n\n	While demand for solar cells/modules increased greatly, overall profit margins decreased significantly from the previous year. This is probably due to many new companies entering this market, and the diversification of activities of existing companies. For example, in 2009, 43 companies were involved in module and/or cell manufacturing, 49 designed modules or systems, 34 developed prototype modules, 26 developed prototype systems, 54 were involved in wholesale distribution, 23 were involved in retail distribution, while 42 installed PV systems. Innovation will clearly be a differentiator in the PV market.\n\n	All 3 forms of PVs (Crystalline Silicon, Thin-Film and Concentrator) show excellent growth, with PV cells and modules increasing for the 6th consecutive year and reaching a record of 1,282,560 peak kilowatts in 2009. Electricity generation, which consists of both grid-connected and remote or dispersed applications, continues to be the predominant end use for PV cells and modules. In 2009, PV cell and module shipments to the electricity generation market totaled 593,308 peak kilowatts, or nearly 99 percent of domestic shipments. At the same time, exports of PV cells have also shown a 47 percent growth in 2009 from the previous year, and exceeded domestic shipments in 2009, accounting for about 53 percent of total shipments. Thus PV demand continues to be on the rise both within and outside of the U.S.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '106', NULL, 'topics/energy/trends/solar-pv-industry-2009', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/106', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/106'),
(634, 'Wind Energy Trends in the US and Germany', ' \n	By Dominika Kurzeja, EcoCloud Energy Content Developer\n\n	Wind Energy Trends in the US and Germany \n\n	A Comparison of Key Elements\n\n	Dec 11th 2011\n\n	Germany is often called the wind energy kingdom; the country’s wind energy industry is one of the largest worldwide. In 2007 Germany was the largest wind power generator in the world and currently it stands at the number three position, exceeded by China and the U.S. But what exactly is the driving force behind its success? What is so different about Germany’s wind energy industry compared to the US?\n\n	The boom started in 1991 by the introduction of a law that committed electricity supply companies to purchase the produced wind energy for a defined price along with continuous Governmental support for research and development. As a result of this political decision, by the end of 2007 Germany had more than a third of total installed wind capacity worldwide[i]. In addition Germany was able to become a worldwide leader in wind power engineering.\n\n	Financials\n\n	The most obvious difference between Germany and the US is the pricing model. In Germany the price for energy is fixed by law. In this model, utilities are mandated by legislation to provide access and a fixed price for electricity that is normally based on cost plus normal profit margin. One major factor for determining the price is the year of installation. For example: a wind energy converter installed in 2009 shall receive 9.2 €ct/kWh for the first five years, and after that the tariff decreases to 5.02 €ct/kWh for the next 15 years[ii].\n\n	In the US the price for sale of power is negotiated through a Power Purchase Agreement (PPA) with a buyer (typically, a utility). Depending on various factors like location, capacity and duration of the PPA the sales price ranked between 3 $ct/kWh and 7.5 $ct/kWh in 2008[iii].\n\n	One major advantage of the German model is the high investment security for wind energy operators, which means lower risks and therefore more investments. On the other hand, the US model is more flexible as operators can choose between the duration of their PPA and taking the long-term development of the energy price into account.\n\n	Interconnection\n\n	Wind farms that deliver power into the grid are required to submit an interconnection request. This process includes a feasibility study, system impact study and a facility study.\n\n	Depending on the region, the generation queue is long and it occurs frequently that wind energy operators in the US need to wait couple of years in order to start delivering power. Moreover the wind farm owner is responsible for the cost of transmitting the energy from the wind farm to the interconnection point.\n\n	In Germany the system operator is mandated by legislation to interconnect any renewable energy source to his grid[iv]. This process only takes couple of weeks. Furthermore the system operator is responsible to provide an interconnection point directly to the wind farm, which means lower costs for the wind energy operator.\n\n	Infrastructure \n\n	Wind energy farms are often concentrated in areas with high wind energy. These areas are not attractive for people to live. So after the wind energy is harvested, it must be transported to the population centers. Since few people live in the high-wind areas, the electricity grid is weak. As a result of this there is a high supply of wind energy, but not sufficient capacity for incorporating the energy into the grid. This bottleneck-problem is more pronounced in the US. With over 312 Million[v] people and 9.83 million km2 the US[vi] is the third or fourth largest by total area. The density of population is 33.7/km2. In Germany the density of population stands at 230 inhabitants per square kilometer, with 82 Million[vii] people and 357.000 km2. Because of the higher density the infrastructure in Germany is more developed and the grid can incorporate more renewable energy.\n\n	Grants\n\n	In Germany there are several grants available on the national and European level. State-of-the-art projects can be eligible for low-interest financing. The development and demonstration of innovation is eligible for non-refundable grants up to 30% of the total investment costs. There are non-refundable grants available for research and development up to 50% of the total project costs. Furthermore the guaranteed Feed-in Tariff, which is financed by the German power consumer eventually, is a subsidy.\n\n	During the recession in 2009-2010 the US government initiated the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act 2009, which, among other things, extended the federal tax credit for the production of electricity from wind facility through the end of 2012. This Production Tax Credit (PTC) has been the major financial support mechanism for wind energy, which rewards the wind energy facility with 2.2 $ct per kWh for 10 years[viii]. In lieu of the PTC wind energy facilities could apply for a cash grant for 30% [ix]of the cost of the renewable energy facility, if the facility was placed in service in 2009 and 2010 or if construction began in 2009 or 2010 and it is placed in service before 2013. The application for the cash grants must have been submitted until the end of September 2011. That means that the primary financial support mechanisms for wind energy are going to expire by the end of next year.\n\n	IHS Emerging Energy Research forecasts, that without the PTC installations could collapse from an annual peak of 10.5 GW in 2012 to as low as 1.5 GW in 2013.\n\n	Conclusion\n\n	As of today Germany ranks third with more than 27 GW total installed capacity behind the leader China with 44 GW and the US with 40 GW[x], although China and the US are significantly larger countries than Germany. Consequent and reliable legislation, predictable financing and a developed infrastructure are the key to Germany''s successful and sustainable development of wind energy. Recently, the starting signal for commercial offshore wind energy farms has been given. It remains to be seen, which strategy will pay off.\n\n	References:\n\n	\n		\n			[i] GWEC: Global Wind 2007 Report\n		\n			[ii] Renewable Energy Sources Act (EEG) 2009, Section 29\n	\n	\n		\n			[iii] Pramod Jain, Wind Energy Engineering, The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc. 2011\n	\n	\n		\n			[iv] Renewable Energy Sources Act (EEG) 2009, Section 5\n	\n	\n		\n			[v] "U.S. POPClock Projection". U.S. Census Bureau.\n	\n	\n		\n			[vi] "United States". The World Factbook. CIA. 2009-09-30. Retrieved 2010-01-05\n	\n	\n		\n			[vii] Key Figures on Europe. Belgium: European Union. 2011. p. 37\n	\n	\n		\n			[viii] DSIRE – Renewable Energy Production Tax Credit (PTC)\n	\n	\n		\n			[ix] DSIRE – U.S. Department of Treasury – Renewable Energy Grants\n	\n	\n		\n			[x] Bundesverband Windenergie e.V.\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '107', NULL, 'topics/energy/trends/wind-energy-trends-in-the-us-and-germany', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/107', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/107');
