(625, 'Green Data Centers: Economics and Operations', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	May 1st 2012\n\n	At Silicon Valley’s annual Earth Day event on April 27th, Sustainable Silicon Valley presented the event “Green Data Centers: Economics and Operations” that was hosted by SAP and featured speakers from prominent companies like GE, SAP, Vantage Data Centers, Yahoo and LBNL. The two hour long program brought in data center expertise and experience from different perspectives and functionalities like engineering design, software and IT operations, environmental strategies, and energy management programs. The audience was treated to valuable insights in data center energy optimizations as the distinguished speakers described state of the art best practices for data centers that were being pursued by their companies, and explained various strategies that have resulted in considerable economic savings and highly efficient PUEs for their data centers.\n\n	The session started with the first speaker - Jonathan Koomey, consulting professor at Stanford University. Describing studies that were carried out in 2005 to measure how much of electricity was being used holistically in data centers in the U.S, the data revealed that data center electricity use had moved up to 1.5% of the total electricity consumed in the U.S. and had doubled in the last 5 years. A more recent analysis indicated a curb in this trend, as the electricity usage has not doubled recently, and is at 1.3% of the world and 2% of the U.S. electricity usage. From a high level perspective, key principles for ensuring energy efficiency in data centers were elucidated; Accurately evaluate your inventory like servers and other infrastructure, continuously measure and benchmark your energy usage, focus on the total cost by designing efficient management hierarchies that can combine diverse operations like IT and facilities under a common cost control scheme, and start with a clean approach of design principles whenever possible to create a highly efficient data center. Data centers can be categorized into three types for easier understanding – high performance computing centers, in house data centers for companies, and the efficient cloud computing centers. Download presentation here\n\n	The next speaker, Jennifer Fraser, Director of Engineering and Construction at Vantage Data Center, spoke from the perspective of client engagement in delivering a highly efficient data center designed upon sound engineering principles that achieve highly efficient PUEs. A key concept followed in Vantage Data Center is to understand the client’s requirements in terms of their IT, network infrastructure, engineering and cost requirements to come up with a more efficient design. Showing their LEED certified V2 facility in Santa Clara which has two 55MW substations allowing a client’s definition to be integrated at inception and the ability to expand from 9MW to 18MW in a very short time, Jennifer explained their emphasis on pre-engineered solutions and modular structures for clients. Techniques for managing density requirements (Watts/sq-foot) and utilizing outside air for cooling were described. Their critical mission is to keep everyone’s business online and a lot of infrastructure is in place to achieve this. A new tier 3 data center being designed by Vantage in Washington targets a PUE of 1.25 and will be capable of surviving natural disasters like earthquakes. All of their data centers are Platinum LEED certified and they report annualized PUEs of 1.12.\n\n	Next up was Brenda Riconscente, Regional Manager at GE representing mission critical applications. Brenda introduced and explained GE’s “ecoimagination” concept. Data centers today have individual control systems in different sections like power generation, power quality, electrical distribution, cooling, IT (AC systems) and facilities (lighting and security systems). GE’s ecoimagination solution combines all of these separate controls and integrates them into an easy to use front-end for efficiently managing data center operations. The architecture, design and resulting benefits of this system were then explained during this session. Check out GE presentation here.\n\n	Gil Perez, Global VP for Sustainability Management and Strategy at SAP, representing the IT/Software aspect of data center optimization next threw a unique perspective into the session series by explaining how software contributes to carbon emissions, and how SAP implements methodologies that reduce IT consumption, minimize e-waste, reduce software complexity and improve hardware efficiency. Entire SAP systems that include servers, storage and network are power benchmarked with solutions that SAP co-develops with their partners. Gil also explained how virtualization as a technique is very useful in achieving high efficiency and showcased SAP’s NetWeaver platform. Download presentation here.\n\n	The next speaker was Christina Page, Global Director, Energy and Sustainability Strategy at Yahoo. Introducing Yahoo’s busy cloud computing platform that manages millions of users, data and service requests continuously, Christina took the discussion to a broader perspective about climate change and investing in large scale values, directions and solutions that can influence energy usage in data centers. Starting with a clean sheet for new data center design a couple of years ago where it re-evaluated design and metrics, the company today looks towards addressing factors like volatility in electricity prices by engaging in creative solutions that look at alternative renewable sources of energy production that could be beneficial to data centers. Yahoo’s long term goal is to reduce their MMT CO2 levels by committing to a downward trend for CO2 emissions that continue till 2050. The presentation can be downloaded here. \n\n	The last speaker for the event was Dale Sartor, Head Building Technologies, Applications Team at Lawrence Berkeley National Labs (LBNL). Explaining how power is lost as it is carried forth in various stages from raw material to delivery resulting in just 15% of the actual energy utilized at a data center, he emphasized opportunities available at every stage of the transmission process that can be utilized to optimize the flow. We could have on site generation and reduce transmission losses, utilize waste heat for productive purposes, increase voltage distribution, use uninterruptable power supply systems, reduce the number of AC-DC-AC flows in the system, and use various retrofitting applications to improve the energy efficiency of data centers. Mentioning that many data centers are outdated today with some having PUEs of 4, he cited best practices deployed at LBNL to achieve high efficiencies. LBNL has improved PUEs of their super computer data center from 1.4 to 1.28, while their enterprise data center has shown improvements from 1.65 to a value between 1.42 and 1.49. More can be learnt by downloading the LBNL presentation here\n\n	The speaker sessions concluded with enough time for the audience and participants to exchange information and ideas. In all, the Green Data Center event hosted by Sustainable Silicon Valley was informative, educational and provided valuable insights to the audience from these distinguished speakers representing various departments of their companies.\n\n	About the Speakers\n\n	Event Agenda\n\n	Speaker Presentations\n\n	GE ecoimagination presentation by BrendaRiconscente\n\n	Green and Greener presentation by Christina Page Yahoo\n\n	Saving Energy in Dta Centers presentation by Dale Sartor LBNL\n\n	Capturing Efficiency in Data Center presentation by Jonathan Koomey Stanford\n\n	Sustainable IT Operations presentation by Gil Perez SAP\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '101', NULL, 'topics/energy/events-archive/green-data-centers-economics-and-operations', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/101', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/101'),
(568, 'Energy Tools Evaluation', ' \n	By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead and Cary Chen, EcoCloud Energy Content Developer\n\n	Energy Tools Evaluation Report\n\n	Feb 18th 2012&nbsp;\n\n	This section summarizes the evaluation of various Energy tools which are used today to manage energy demand, control energy cost and consumption, improve energy reliability and minimize environmental impacts.\n\n	Our methodology categorizes the energy tools in two categories:\n\n	By Audience\n\n	The basis of our categorization of energy tools by audience is the users of various energy performance metrics as defined by the Commercial Building Initiative run by the Office of Energy Efficiency &amp; Renewable Energy (EERE) and by the Building Energy Software Tools Directoryof the Department of Energy (DOE).\n\n	\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Tools - By&nbsp;Audience\n		\n		\n			\n				Architects and Builders\n		\n		\n			\n				Auditors\n		\n		\n			\n				Corporations\n		\n		\n			\n				Engineers and Energy Professionals\n		\n		\n			\n				Facility Managers\n		\n		\n			\n				Building and Residential Owners\n		\n		\n			\n				Researchers and Students\n		\n		\n			\n				Utilities\n		\n	\n\n\n	By Application\n\n	Application categories are listed separately for the three building types examined: Residential, Commercial, and Mixed-Use.&nbsp; The categories are derived from DOE’s Building Energy Software Tools Directory&nbsp;and represent the most frequently used applications for building performance.\n\n	\n		\n		\n		\n	\n	\n		\n			\n				Tools - By Application\n		\n		\n			\n				Commercial\n			\n				Residential\n			\n				Mixed Use\n		\n		\n			\n				Benchmarking\n			\n				Benchmarking\n			\n				Benchmarking\n		\n		\n			\n				Calculators\n			\n				Calculators\n			\n				Calculators\n		\n		\n			\n				Energy Simulation\n			\n				Energy Simulation\n			\n				Energy Simulation\n		\n		\n			\n				Green Buildings\n			\n				Green Buildings\n			\n				Green Buildings\n		\n		\n			\n				Performance\n			\n				Performance\n			\n				Performance\n		\n		\n			\n				Rebates\n			\n				Rebates\n			\n				Rebates\n		\n		\n			\n				Energy Water Conservation\n			\n				Energy Water Conservation\n			\n				Energy Water Conservation\n		\n		\n			\n				Energy Management\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Energy Management\n		\n		\n			\n				Renewables\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Renewables\n		\n		\n			\n				Life Cycle Analysis\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Life Cycle Analysis\n		\n		\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				&nbsp;\n			\n				Mobile Apps\n		\n	\n\n\n	Please click on&nbsp;links above to see the Energy Tools Evaluation Tables listing&nbsp;by categories.\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '51', NULL, 'topics/energy/energy-tools-evaluation', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/51', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/51'),
(572, 'Case Studies', ' By Anuradha Munshi, EcoCloud Energy Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Clean Energy Strategy Part of Santa Clara University’s Business Continuity Plan - Phase One of Smart Microgrid Project Complete&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	In 2006 Santa Clara University (SCU) conducted an energy strategy study as part of the university’s business continuity plan and its aim to become carbon-neutral by 2016.\n\n	“We looked at the next 20 years and what we needed to accomplish to ensure we had energy reliability,” said Joe Sugg, Assistant Vice President, University Operations at SCU. The university needed guaranteed energy reliability, some influence over the cost of energy, a move to green energy, and (to develop) the capability to operate with the grid down for extended periods of time.\n\n	Joe Sugg, Assistant VP Operations SCU with SSV Executive Director Marianna Grossman testing a new prototype wind generator\n\n	“We knew we would need distributed generation capability on campus and a way to control our demand on campus and when our distributed energy was used. We also needed to be able to maintain continuity with the grid when it was up so we could take advantage of it.”\n\n	A smart microgrid became the necessary infrastructure to make it possible. A smart box will instantaneously sense any drop in supply, such as when cloud cover affects solar generation, and react accordingly by automatically reducing demand to match available generation.\n\n	In 2010 - the first phase of the project, SCU installed sub-meters into 14 buildings and integrated the smart microgrid’s onsite alternative energy sources, including solar. Phase 2 will connect the entire campus to the campus microgrid, and is expected to be completed ahead of schedule in December 2011.\n\n	SCU is currently producing 1 Megawatt (MW) from solar, 2 MW from diesel as standby energy, and generating biogas using garden waste. The university is also testing a new wind generator sited on the same roof as the university’s bank of solar panels and is in a product queue for a Bloom fuel cell that will generate an additional 1 MW.\n\n	According to Joe Sugg, the wind generator operates efficiently at low wind speeds; starting production at 2 mph. Energy from the generator currently is fed into a battery that is used to charge the university’s electric vehicles, and is not part of the microgrid.\n\n	Monitoring the system and reviewing energy savings\n\n	While SCU expects to see savings of around 20% from on-campus energy generation and from reduced consumption, the real benefits are energy and cost reliability, simplified building management, and reduced CO2.\n\n	“We know the cost of solar electricity for the next 20 years, and we like the price,” said Joe Sugg.&nbsp;Distributed energy is not only the answer to SCU’s energy needs, but for the region overall, he says.\n\n	“I imagine our microgrid as one among hundreds. Our 3 MW generation capacity in combination with other smart microgrids becomes a powerful force in the Valley. “Silicon Valley Power” will be able to produce significant energy and carbon load savings.”\n\n	In 20-30 years from now, says Sugg, Long haul transmission of power from Nevada to California will be prohibitive. “It will not be an option.“\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		SCU’s current system allows it to control HVAC systems and temperatures. A Trane environmental control system in conjunction with an Energy Management System from Serious Energy, processes server information to automatically monitor and adjust the optimum server room temperature. As a result SCU’s server room now operates at 85 degrees compared with 65 degrees previously.\n	\n		The smart microgrid, when complete, will encompass the entire campus and enable the university to instantly turn off lights and equipment in any building, ration electricity during prolonged power outages all from one computer.\n	\n		SCU is collaborating with Sustainable Silicon Valley and SSV partners - Cisco and Serious Energy.\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '53', NULL, 'topics/energy/smart-grid/case-studies', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/53', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/53'),
(579, 'Energy / Water Connection', ' By Mary Kean, EcoCloud Water Lead\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	California’s water supply chain, or the route water follows as it is pumped and/or conveyed from its source, treated to drinking water standards, distributed, used, and treated to wastewater standards, is energy intensive. More specifically, water-related energy consumption in the state represents approximately 15%-20% of all energy consumed in California. For example, the State Water Project alone, a 444-mile long aqueduct transporting San Francisco Bay-San Joaquin Delta water to Southern California, consumes 2%-3% of all electricity in the state because of the high elevations and long distances over which water must be pumped and conveyed. Thus, a reduction in flow through the water supply chain brought about by an alternative water supply source/demand management tool such as water conservation or water recycling will decrease energy use.\n\n	See EcoCloud’s review of tools&nbsp;including water/energy for more info.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n\n	For more information on the Water/Energy Nexus, visit:\n\n	UC Davis Center for Water Energy Efficiency\n	Cal-Wec – CA Water Energy Coalition\n	The Climate Change Clearinghouse\n	CEC 2005- Calfornia''s Water Energy Relationship\n	NCSL - Summary of Water/Energy Nexus Statutes\n	Researchers to test renewable-energy system at local treatment plant \n	Northern California Water/Energy Summit Presentations\n	Water/Energy Issues Wiki\n	Link to WaterRF energy projects\n	https://www.whollyh2o.org/water-energy-nexus.html\n	\n	\n	Watts to Water Report by Santa Clara Valley Water District\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '36', NULL, 'topics/water/energy-water-connection', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/36', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/36'),
