(782, '3. The WBCSD Global Water Tool©', 'Water is recognized as a critical sustainable development challenge that has intrinsic links to energy, biodiversity, food security and climate change. It is predicted that by 2030, the world will need 30 percent more available fresh water and will need to produce 50 percent more food and energy, while mitigating and adapting to climate change. This threatens to create a ‘perfect storm’ of global events.\n\nCurrently, global per capita availability of freshwater is steadily decreasing and this trend will inevitably continue with population growth and increased consumption. In some parts of the world, locally available fresh water resources are already exceeded by local demand and we can anticipate increased competition and even conflict for freshwater resources. As a consequence, water availability, quality and security challenges are evident and visible on the full range of political and regulatory agendas.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '93', 665, 'solutions/view/93', 'admin/solutions/edit/93', 'admin/solutions/delete/93'),
(783, '4. Multi-Strain photobioreactors to produce ethanol and other compounds', 'There is a distinct need to find green chemistry alternatives to traditional chemical synthesis and fuel production. Traditional bioreactor approaches have focused on monocultures of engineered strains, or the utilization of a dominant strain when working with wastewater products. I believe we can generate synthetic ecosystems in order to harness the interaction between microbial populations.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '95', 667, 'solutions/view/95', 'admin/solutions/edit/95', 'admin/solutions/delete/95'),
(784, '5. Predicting Urban Irrigation Rates for Silicon Valley Using Satellite Remote Sensing', 'Urban irrigation can account for more than half of all municipal and industrial water demand in cities of the western United States (Western Resource Advocates, 2010).  Consequently, many municipalities have started to regulate the amount of irrigation water that can be applied to outdoor landscapes, due to rapid urban population growth, droughts, and inefficient application practices (Salamone, 2002).\n\nBecause water meters in urban areas do not generally track indoor and outdoor uses separately, the share of water used outdoors for irrigation can only be roughly approximated.  The 2005 California Water Plan estimated that the residential sector used roughly 2.3 million acre feet (maf) outdoors in 2000, or 42 percent of total residential demand. Parks, golf courses, and other “large landscapes” used another 0.7 maf.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '96', 668, 'solutions/view/96', 'admin/solutions/edit/96', 'admin/solutions/delete/96'),
(785, '6. EnergyPoints Analytics - "The world''s first true energy ERP"', 'There are five fundamental problems with methods used to measure environmental sustainability today: \n• Complex and non-intuitive units (mBTU, kWh, MtCO2e, Acre-feet) make resource management difficult to understand or act on\n• Resources are measured in silos and not comparable (electricity, water, waste, materials, travel)\n• Geographical context and time of use are ignored\n• Renewable energy is assumed to be an absolute benefit and measured separately\n• CO2 is used for reporting only', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '98', 21, 'solutions/view/98', 'admin/solutions/edit/98', 'admin/solutions/delete/98'),
(499, 'The Nature of Materials with the Northern California Recycling Association', 'Another very informative class put on by the Northern California Recycling Association.  This one-day class covered four major sectors in the recycling industry: plastic, paper, glass and metal.  Patty Moore from Moore Recycling Associates spoke on the recyclers’ viewpoint on plastics, covering the different types of plastics, expelling some common myths and presented some trends for the coming future in plastics recycling.  Susan Kinsella from Conservatree explored the manufacturing process and the properties of the many types of paper, the challenges facing the industry today and how the current paper recycling model isn’t the most effective for the varying paper sectors.  Phil Ross from Glass Industry Consulting Inc. presented glass from the manufacturing perspective, explaining the various types, their properties as well as highlighting the precise chemistry involved and how recycling adds to its complexity.  Scott Rubenstein from Alco Metals spoke on the business model they utilize in recycling metals, reviewing the metals they work with, the importance of understanding your markets and some issues that arise in their sector.  Like the Introduction to Recycling course put on by NCRA, this class provides a wealth of information from industry experts and is recommend for anyone from concerned citizens to business owners and career recyclers. Check out the Northern California Recycling Associations Website for their next great class.  www.ncrarecycles.org  \n\nHere are some interesting points to consider: \n\n• The plastic film recycling stations in front of grocery stores collects more then just plastic grocery bags; it is recycling for all Polyethylene (PE) plastic films.  Plastic film is not usually recycled from curbside but rather ends up in a landfill after more valuable materials are separated.  Collect your plastic film for the next trip to the store and get it back into the loop.  See plasticbagrecycling.org\n• The energy needed to produce a typical canvas bag is roughly equivalent to the energy needed to make 120 plastic bags, so you would need to re-use your canvas bags 120 times to start seeing a savings in energy.  With citywide bag bans, stores are no longer required to provide plastic film recycling to their customers, often taking away a main resource for plastic film recycling.  Are reusable bags and plastic bag bans a robust solution?  How many reusable bags do you have and are they all getting used?  What other considerations are there for the plastic ban?  How many bags actually get recycled and what is their downstream effect on the environment when they are not recycled?  \n• About 90% of manufactured office paper has no recycled content, yet its manufacturing is the hardest on the environment compared to other types of paper.  To make office paper from recycled content you need the left over scraps from its manufacturing (pre-consumer recycling) or segregated office paper of the same quality (post-consumer recycling).  Recycled office paper cannot be made from old corrugate cardboard, old newspaper and unlikely from shredded office paper due to contaminants that usually end up in the mix (e.g. staples, tape, plastics). For these reasons, office paper that is put in mixed paper recycling is essentially lost to office paper mills.  Even if offices were to keep their office paper separate, will their recycling service pick it up separately and then recycle it separately? Should offices plan recycling services accordingly?\n• Glass can theoretically be recycled an infinite number of times.  Manufactures want recycled glass but need consistent supply.  Precise measurements of glass components are needed to achieve desired product; making it difficult to recycle mixed color glass.  Color separated glass is a highly desirable feedstock for manufactures.', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '24', 695, 'blog2/view/24', 'admin/blog2/edit/24', 'admin/blog2/delete/24'),
(586, 'Measuring & Characterizing Waste', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n\n	MATERIALS RECYCLING&nbsp;is processing used&nbsp;materials&nbsp;into new products to prevent waste of potentially useful materials. Its purpose is to reduce the consumption of fresh raw materials, &nbsp;energy&nbsp;usage, air pollution (from&nbsp;incineration) and water pollution (from&nbsp;landfilling), by reducing the need for "conventional" waste disposal. This results in lower&nbsp;greenhouse gas&nbsp;emissions as compared to virgin production. Recycling is a key component of modern waste reduction. Recycling is the third component of the&nbsp;"Reduce,&nbsp;Reuse, Recycle"&nbsp;waste hierarchy.\n\n	\n\n	RECYCLABLE MATERIALS include many kinds of&nbsp;glass,&nbsp;paper,&nbsp;metal,&nbsp;plastic,&nbsp;textiles, and&nbsp;electronics. Although similar in effect, the&nbsp;composting&nbsp;or other reuse of&nbsp;biodegradable waste&nbsp;– such as&nbsp;food&nbsp;or&nbsp;garden waste&nbsp;– is not typically considered recycling.&nbsp;Materials to be recycled are either brought to a collection center or picked up from the curbside. They are then sorted, cleaned, and reprocessed into new materials bound for manufacturing.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	STATE OF CALIFORNIA MATERIALS&nbsp;RECYCLING RESOURCES&nbsp;\n\n	\n\n	The government offers grants, payments, and loans to assist private and public entities in&nbsp;the management of waste through the California Department of Resources Recycling and Recovery, also&nbsp;known as CalRecycle.&nbsp;The program will make sure that your methods are efficient and safe. The program covers many different types of waste, including beverage containers, used oil, solid waste, and old tires. The grant process is simple and straight forward. Apply now for help with managing the waste in your life.&nbsp;&nbsp;www.calrecycle.ca.gov/&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Recycling Market Development Zones:\n\n	The Recycling Market Development Zones (RMDZ) exist to create local markets for recyclables and products made from recycled materials. Low-cost loans and other incentives are available to eligible businesses that locate in designated areas throughout the State of California including the San Francisco, San Jose, and Oakland/Berkeley areas.&nbsp;The RMDZ program combines recycling with economic development to fuel new businesses, expand existing ones, create jobs, and divert waste from landfills.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	This program provides attractive loans, technical assistance, and free product marketing to businesses that use materials from the waste stream to manufacture their products and are located in a zone. The zones cover roughly 88,000 square miles of California from the Oregon border to San Diego. Assistance is provided by local zone administrators and CalRecycle''s Referral Team (R-Team). Local government incentives may include relaxed building codes and zoning laws, streamlined local permit processes, reduced taxes and licensing, and increased and consistent secondary material feedstock supply. Local incentives vary from jurisdiction to jurisdiction.California Assoc. of Recycling Market Development Zones.&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	The&nbsp;RMDZ CEQA Tool Kit&nbsp;is a series of web pages designed to guide a potential or existing zone through the CEQA process.\n\n	\n		The 2011 WRAP Application will be available on April 22, 2011.\n	\n		CalRecycle''s next “Zone Works” Training Workshop will be held in Sacramento, May 11-12, 2011. More information will be posted soon. Contact:&nbsp;Marshalle Graham.\n	\n		Learn about a number of resources for starting, growing, financing, expanding, or relocating a business in California through the&nbsp;California Economic Development Partnership.\n	\n		Loan Interest Rate: 4.0 percent.\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Who Are You?&nbsp;Choose a link below to find information most useful to you!\n\n	\n		Manufacturer\n	\n		Economic Developer\n	\n		Recycling Coordinator\n	\n		Zone Administrator\n\n\n	\n		San Jose Recycling Market&nbsp;Development Zone:\n	\n		\n			Incentives\n		\n			Target Materials\n		\n			Infrastructure\n		\n			Contact\n	\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Incentives\n	\n		San Jose offers the Special Tenant Improvement (STI) program to encourage occupancy of existing vacant building space. The STI program includes the suspension of the local Building &amp; Structures tax, a coordinated plan check review process, the deferral of plan check fees, and expedited permit processing. This program is designed to encourage tenant improvements on vacant buildings to make the space ready for earlier occupancy. In addition to the STI program, the city offers Industrial Development Bonds, loans and loan guarantees, and sales and use tax credits to those businesses located within the established 18-square-mile Enterprise Zone.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Target&nbsp;Materials\n	\n		Materials identified to provide businesses with continuous feedstock include mixed paper, glass, aluminum, plastics 1-7 (including film plastic), textiles; electronics, roofing materials (specifically asphalt shingles), and food waste.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Infrastructure\n	\n		San Jose has historically had a large processing and manufacturing base and the infrastructure necessary to support such industries. In addition, the Green Industry district is located near highways 101, 680, and 880 and all have direct rail access.\n	\n		&nbsp;\n	\n		Contact&nbsp;Information\n	\n		\n			\n				\n					\n						San Jose RMDZ\n						http://www.calrecycle.ca.gov/RMDZ/SanJose/Default.asp&nbsp;\n						Kristina Gallegos\n					\n						City of San Jose'' - ESD\n						County: Santa Clara\n						200 E Santa Clara St10th Floor\n						San Jose, CA 95113-1903\n						Phone: (408) 975-2520\n						Fax: (408) 292-6211\n						Email:&nbsp;Kristina.gallegos@sanjoseca.gov\n					\n						&nbsp;\n					\n						&nbsp;\n					\n						&nbsp;\n					\n						&nbsp;\n				\n			\n		\n	\n\n\n	California&nbsp;Materials Exchange\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	CalMAX’s mission is to build reuse markets for materials from businesses, organizations, industry, schools, and individuals, and to find markets for nonhazardous materials that may otherwise be discarded.\n\n	CalMAX is a simple idea: "One business'' trash is another business'' treasure." Businesses, industry, schools, and nonprofits can use CalMAX to search for available and wanted materials.\n\n	The commercial sector contributes 60 percent of the materials going to landfills. By reusing materials, the commercial sector conserves energy, resources, landfill space, and reduces disposal and purchasing costs. CalMAX is one tool to help jurisdictions, businesses, and organizations find alternatives to the disposal of valuable materials.\n\n	\n		In CalMAX, you can search for ads&nbsp;statewide&nbsp;or&nbsp;by region.\n	\n		To post an ad, you first need to&nbsp;establish an account.\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Interested in becoming a CalMAX partner?\n\n	Partnerships between State and local governments allow for more efficient use of funds, reuse efforts, and staff time.&nbsp;E-mail us&nbsp;to become a CalMAX partner.\n\n	\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		\n			\n				\n					California Recycled-Content Product Directory\n				\n					The&nbsp;Recycled-Content Product (RCP) Directory directory&nbsp;http://www1.calrecycle.ca.gov/RCP/&nbsp;\n				\n					has been set up to assist individuals, small business owners, state agencies, and corporate buyers in the commitment to buy recycled. The RCP Directory lists thousands of products containing recycled materials as well as information about the manufacturers, distributors and re-processors of these products.\n				\n					&nbsp;\n				\n					Although important, recycling is more than just dropping off cans, bottles and newspapers at the nearest recycling center. Diverting recyclables from the waste stream is the first of three steps in the recycling process. The second step occurs when companies use these recyclables to manufacture new products. Finally, the third step occurs when you, the consumer, purchase the products made from the recovered materials.\n				\n					&nbsp;\n				\n					In addition, buying recycled products results in many environmental benefits. It supports local recycling programs by creating markets for the collected materials that are processed and used to manufacture new products. In turn, this creates new jobs and helps strengthen the economy; conserves natural resources; saves energy; and reduces solid waste, air, and water pollutants, and greenhouse gases that contribute to global warming.&nbsp;\n			\n		\n	\n\n\n	Recycled Content Products Directory:&nbsp;Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)\n\n	ELECTRONICS RECYCLING RESOURCES:\n\n	RECYCLING IN THE NEWS:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	http://www.environmentalleader.com\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	April 13, 2011\n\n	Electronics Giants Pledge&nbsp;to Recycle a Billion Pounds&nbsp; Executives from Best Buy, Panasonic, Sony and Toshiba have helped to launch an industry-wide initiative to recycle one billion pounds of electronics a year by 2016, in a move they say will trump state-level recycling mandates.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	The&nbsp;eCycling Leadership Initiative, launched today by the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA), aims to more than triple the amount of e-waste recycled each year.\n\n	The initiative will support the voluntary use of third-party recycler certification systems, with the aim for the entire billion pounds to be recycled in certified facilities. That is enough electronics to fill a 71,000-seat NFL stadium, the CEA said.\n\n	(More)\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '64', NULL, 'topics/materials/measuring-characterizing-waste', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/64', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/64'),
(690, 'Applied Materials Increases Purchase of Clean Renewable Energy', 'Silicon Valley Power (SVP), the City of Santa Clara''s municipal electric utility, announced today that Applied Materials, Inc., the global leader in providing manufacturing solutions for the semiconductor, flat panel display and solar photovoltaic industries, will increase its purchase of clean renewable energy to match 100% of the electricity used at its Santa Clara headquarters. Applied Materials began purchasing green power in 2007 and is now SVP''s largest purchaser of Santa Clara Green Power, a renewable energy program that provides 100 percent clean wind and solar power resources.\n\nWith an annual renewable power commitment of 45 million kilowatt-hours, the company''s Santa Clara facility is now a Leadership Club member of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency''s (EPA) Green Power Partnership for its Santa Clara headquarters. Applied Materials'' green power commitment to 100% of its electricity use at its headquarters represents a five-fold increase over last year.\n\n"Applied Materials continues to demonstrate its leadership in sustainability, and we are proud to have the company as a long-term and active partner in the Santa Clara Green Power program," said Larry Owens, Division Manager of Silicon Valley Power.\n\nUsing EPA calculations, Applied Materials'' clean power commitment is projected to help avoid more than 31,132 metric tons of carbon dioxide-equivalent emissions, a key greenhouse gas, which is equal to the annual greenhouse gas emissions from 6,104 passenger cars, or the carbon sequestered annually by more than 6,638 acres of pine or fir forests. With its commitment, the company''s purchase of Santa Clara Green Power is now the equivalent of more than the annual output of 14 large-scale wind turbines.\n\n"Conventional electricity usage is the nation''s single largest industrial source of greenhouse gas emissions in the U.S.," said Blaine Collison, Director of EPA''s Green Power Partnership. "By increasing its commitment to purchase green power, Applied Materials will reduce its carbon footprint and help advance the market for cleaner, renewable resources."\n\n"Applied Materials is honored to be recognized as a corporate leader in using energy responsibly throughout our business to reduce impacts to the environment and in minimizing greenhouse gas emissions by giving preference to renewable energy sources," said Phil Naughton, Corporate Energy Manager at Applied Materials. "We are proud to be making this investment to help grow our business responsibly and in a sustainable fashion."\n\nAbout Applied Materials\nApplied Materials, Inc. (Nasdaq:AMAT) is the global leader in providing innovative equipment, services and software to enable the manufacture of advanced semiconductor, flat panel display and solar photovoltaic products. Our technologies help make innovations like smartphones, flat screen TVs and solar panels more affordable and accessible to consumers and businesses around the world. Learn more at www.appliedmaterials.com.\n\nAbout Silicon Valley Power\nSilicon Valley Power is the trademark adopted for use by the not-for-profit electric municipal utility of Santa Clara, CA serving residents and businesses for over 100 years. SVP provides power to more than 50,000 customers, including Applied Materials, Intel, Owens Corning and Yahoo!, at rates 15 to 45 percent below neighboring communities.\nVisit siliconvalleypower.com for more information.\n\nAbout Santa Clara Green Power\nSanta Clara Green Power is a voluntary renewable energy program offered by Silicon Valley Power to all of its residential, commercial and industrial customers as a way to support energy generated from 100 percent clean wind and solar power resources at a low additional cost of 1.5 cents per kilowatt-hour. Santa Clara utility customers can enroll in Santa Clara Green Power by signing up through the secure website at www.siliconvalleypower.com/green or by calling 408.244.SAVE (7283).\n\nContact:\nLarry Owens\nSilicon Valley Power\nPhone: 408.621.5873\nEmail: LOwens@SantaClaraCA.gov  \n\nDan Beerman\nCity of Santa Clara\nTel: 408.615.2228', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '35', 27, 'blog2/view/35', 'admin/blog2/edit/35', 'admin/blog2/delete/35'),
(692, 'City of Redwood City - Notice of Funding Availability and Request for Proposals', 'The City of Redwood City is pleased to announce the availability of the Request for Proposals (RFP) for eligible projects to be funded with Community Development Block Grant (CDBG) and Home Investment Partnership (HOME). These grant fund sources are available to organizations providing assistance to low and moderate income households residing within Redwood City that meet one or more of the City''s Consolidated Plan priorities relating to affordable housing, public facilities and economic development activities that create jobs for low income persons.\n\nComplete information and the full Notice of Funding Availability/Request for Proposals is available on the City''s Housing Services website at www.redwoodcity.org/cdd (click on "Grants and Loans" under "Housing").  All proposals must be submitted electronically by 5:00 pm on Friday, January 25, 2013.\n\nTechnical Assistance Workshops\n\nTechnical assistance workshops will be held on January 8, 2013 from 10 - 11 am and January 10, 2013 from 3 - 4 pm at City Hall, Council Chambers, 1017 Middlefield Road, Redwood City, 94063. Attendance at a workshop is mandatory for all new CDBG or HOME applicants.\n\nFor more information, contact Rhonda Coffman at 650.780.7299 or via email at rcoffman@redwoodcity.org.\n\n*************************\n(sent by)\nMalcolm Smith\nPublic Communications Manager\nCity of Redwood City, California\n~\nOffice:  650.780.7305\nCell:     408.472.8536\nEmail:   malcolm.smith@redwoodcity.org', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '37', 27, 'blog2/view/37', 'admin/blog2/edit/37', 'admin/blog2/delete/37'),
(694, 'Free Service to Reduce Junk Mail now Available', 'The San Jose Green Vision Resource Team will be teaming up with Catalog Choice on a campaign to reduce Junk Mail.\n\nCatalog Choice is a website that has a free service to opt out of catalogs, coupons, credit card offers, phone books, circulars and more in your mailbox. You can also sign up with them with a paid service where they contact companies for you to opt out of unwanted junk mail.\n\nThe campaign will be called Stop Junk Mail San Jose. I will post more information as it comes up, here and on Ecocloud. Feel free to go to the Catalog Choice website for more information as well.\n \nTo all a prosperous and rewarding 2013\n (Sent by)\nDave Lantz\nEmail: dlantz@sustainablesv.org', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '38', 27, 'blog2/view/38', 'admin/blog2/edit/38', 'admin/blog2/delete/38'),
(699, 'Great News! Fiscal Cliff Deal Includes Increase in Commuter Tax Benefit', 'Dear Employer,\n\nPlease see the announcement below.\n\nhttps://netforum.avectra.com/public/DocumentGenerate.aspx?Image=48189670-ce74-4de9-80b4-853b9b92d60c\n\nFiscal Cliff Deal Includes Increase in Transit Benefit\n \nLegislation averting the so-called ‘fiscal-cliff’ (HR 8) included a provision that will once again re-establish parity between the parking and transit benefits at $240/month. The provision is effective immediately and is set to expire at the end of 2013. ACT will immediately begin working to make the provision permanent.\n\nIf you have questions about the Commuter Tax Benefits Program please contact me at 510 541-8505 or send me an email at furnas@rideshare.511.org. I will be happy to help you set up a program or answer any questions.\n\nLinda Furnas\n\nEmployer Services Representative\n\n511\n\n408 321-5948 (Direct)\n\n510 541-8505 (Cell)\n\nfurnas@rideshare.511.org\n\n511.org', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '39', 27, 'blog2/view/39', 'admin/blog2/edit/39', 'admin/blog2/delete/39'),
(836, '35. Reducing Water in Consumer Products', 'Consumers buy and use many products for cleaning and eating with high water contents. This liquid is expensive to transport and requires costly and environmentally damaging packaging. Transportation of products is an ecological problem. If these products were packaged and shipped in smaller, lighter quantities this would cut down on pollution and plastic usage. Manufacturing, transportation and disposal of the containers would have a lighter ecological footprint.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '142', 759, 'solutions/view/142', 'admin/solutions/edit/142', 'admin/solutions/delete/142'),
(801, '18. Cool City Challenge', 'PROBLEM AND OPPORTUNITY: With international climate change legislation failing to get traction, a ticking clock, and the long timeframe required to scale up new technological solutions and renewable energy, the world is searching for feasible, scalable and high impact strategies to address global warming in the short-term while we still have the ability to take action. Since cities represent 70% of the planet’s carbon emissions and citizens’ daily lifestyle choices represent between 50 and 90% of these emissions, helping cities and their citizens reduce their carbon footprint provides the world with an unparalleled opportunity to address climate change. Further, engaging citizens can serve as a demand-side driver to increase the pace of renewable energy, energy efficiency and new technology adoption.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '118', 729, 'solutions/view/118', 'admin/solutions/edit/118', 'admin/solutions/delete/118');
