(713, 'ebay', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	EBAY Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	eBay is the world’s largest online marketplace (more than 100 million active users in 2011), connecting individual buyers and sellers, as well as small businesses. eBay had 27,770 employees end of 2011, including 18,720 in the USA, and facilities in 30 countries. eBay does not publish a sustainability report.\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments\n\n	Sustainability Awards:\n\n	National:\n\n	\n		2010: Social Innovator Award for Best Employee Engagement Strategy, given by Just Means and The Financial Times\n	\n		2010: Sustainable Design Award for the organizational design of the Green Team initiatives, given by Global Green USA\n	\n		2012: eBay and Dell have been selected to win a Green Enterprise IT award by Uptime Institute, a global organization that provides thought leadership, certification, education and professional services for the global data center industry\n\n\n	Local:\n\n	\n		2012: Modular Data Center Product Deployment award received jointly&nbsp; for Project Mercury data center in Phoenix, AZ\n	\n		The WPR team in San Jose recently received a BOMA (Building Owners and Managers Association) Emerald Award for Single Tenant Recycling as a result of the Zero Waste Program\n	\n		Bronze level for a bike-friendly business given by the League of American Bicyclists to the Omaha office, making it one of the first companies in Nebraska to receive this designation\n\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	\n		Calvert Social Index\n	\n		FTSE4Good\n	\n		Domini400\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		Ranked 104 in 2011 Newsweek’s Green Ranking of US companies (among first 100 in 2009)\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		2011 Carbon Disclosure Leadership Index: 63/100; Performance: C\n\n\n	 INSERT INTO `search_index` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `keywords`, `keyword_hash`, `module`, `entry_key`, `entry_plural`, `entry_id`, `created_by`, `uri`, `cp_edit_uri`, `cp_delete_uri`) VALUES
(715, 'Symantec', ' \n	Symantec Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Symantec is a global service provider in security, backup, and storage management. Symantec was founded in 1982 by visionary computer scientists.&nbsp; They have shown their commitment towards sustainability since the birth of the organization. They launched their ‘Environmental Stewardship Council’ in 2005 and published their first corporate sustainability report in September 2008. They have made constant efforts in reducing carbon emissions and energy consumption. They have 18,500 employees in more than 50 countries and for a $6,190,000,000 in revenues in 2011.\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012\n\n	Sustainability Awards\n\n	\n		Ethisphere Institute: 2011 World’s Most Ethical Companies (listed for the past four consecutive years)\n	\n		2011 Acterra Business Environmental Awards\n\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	\n		For the past two years, Symantec been selected for the Maplecroft Climate Innovation Index (CII) Leaders. The CII is the single most exhaustive study of how the United States'' top companies are managing and adapting to climate change\n	\n		Listed on the Dow Jones Sustainability Index (World since 2008 and North America since 2007); named Sustainability Leader in December 2010\n	\n		&nbsp;Listed on the FTSE4Good Index since 2007\n	\n		100% (perfect score) on the Human Rights Campaign’s Corporate Equality Index\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		Fortune Magazine’s World’s Most Admired Companies\n	\n		Newsweek Magazine’s 2010 Green Rankings&nbsp;\n	\n		CR Magazine’s 2011 100 Best Corporate Citizens\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		Symantec has been reporting the sustainability performance by filing an annual Carbon Disclosure Project submission\n	\n		Symantec has been publishing GRI certified CSR report since 2008, in FY2012, they obtained the B+ certification\n	\n		Symantec has been a signatory of the UNGC – United Nations Global Compact since 2006, and has reported annually on its 10 principles since then. They have participated in the Global Compact LEAD Initiative since it was launched in 2011. They pledged to implement the Blueprint for Corporate Sustainability Leadership and share their experience with other companies through UNGBC Local Network and other initiatives\n	\n		Symantec joined Business for Innovative Climate and Energy Policy (BICEP) in 2009\n	\n		Joined the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Climate Leaders program and started measuring and reporting on all three scopes of global GHG emissions\n\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	\n		Received LEED Certification for 9 buildings and ENERGY STAR ratings for 10 buildings globally\n	\n		Greening of Global Corporate Events: Sustainability is a corporate priority that is built into the firm’s strategies for executing large corporate events like Symantec’s Vision EMEA conference. They are working to lessen the impacts of corporate events by incorporating environmental and social considerations in a more methodical way. In FY12 they expanded their efforts to provide:\n		\n			\n				Well-marked recycling bins\n			\n				Water bottle refill stations\n			\n				Information on local transportation options\n			\n				Foods sourced within 500 miles of the venue\n			\n				Paperless conference materials\n			\n				Carbon footprint estimates from select eventCollecting and documenting the data from these efforts will help continually refine and standardize their processes for reducing the environmental and social impacts of large events\n		\n	\n\n\n	Water\n\n	Symantec strives to reduce water consumption at all its global sites and facilities. Programs they have begun implementing at various sites include:\n\n	\n		Water saving plumbing fixtures, including low flow toilets, low flow or waterless urinals, and motion sensor faucets and aerators\n	\n		Water-efficient landscaping&nbsp;\n	\n		Irrigation management\n	\n		Storm water management\n\n\n	They are working to raise participation rates and increase water conservation efforts worldwide. One area of focus is landscape design and irrigation under the LEED program. When possible, they plant native vegetation and design the landscape to capture rainwater and parking-lot runoff to prevent it from entering storm drains. They are also installing irrigation systems that reduce or stop unnecessary irrigation.\n\n	Energy\n\n	Symantec has set goals to reduce CO2 emissions company-wide by 15 percent by the end of FY12 from a FY08 baseline in May 2008 (FY09).&nbsp; They have developed enterprise-wide measurement tools to both track progress toward the goal and increase transparency. The strategies they intend to employ are:\n\n	\n		Extend energy savings to endpoints while improving workforce productivity, with a reduction in annual energy costs of US$25 to $75 per workstation\n	\n		Symantec has had an overall increase of 3% CO2 levels in F11 to F10 due to the expansion of their enterprise data centers. To combat this increase in CO2 levels, Symantec tracked 338 facilities in 49 countries accounting for 15 percent of Scope 2* and 2 percent of Scope 1* GHG emissions. Additionally, they have also developed the ability to track rental car emissions under Scope 3*\n\n\n	*Scope 1 (Source: Natural Gas, Diesel, Propane, Refrigerants, and Gasoline)\n\n	&nbsp;Scope 2 (Source: Electricity)\n\n	&nbsp;Scope 3 (Source: Air Travel and Rental Cars)\n\n	Materials\n\n	\n		Symantec made a mandatory inclusion in Global Supply Chain Manufacturing and Fulfillment of Conduct that all the suppliers have to be ISO14001-certified. In FY12, this will be added to all Symantec Tier 1 supply chain supplier contracts, and Symantec will begin to conduct supplier audits that will include environmental considerations\n	\n		Symantec integrated the concept of reduce/reuse/recycle into packaging design and implements ISO14001 manufacturing practices\n	\n		They deliver the majority of software products electronically in order to conserve materials and energy. For instance, they adopted a DVD case that uses 20 percent less plastic compared to a standard DVD case in the American region. In Asia, they replaced most plastic DVD packaging with an all-paper DVD sleeve, and are working towards printing with soy inks. They have also replaced plastic license-key cards with paper cards for most products. Transitioned to manuals made from recycled paper for all new product releases\n	\n		Symantec has also increased the density of units shipped per pallet, leading to fewer pallets used overall. They changed the box sizes for several products in 24 countries, resulting in savings of 102,270 kg of paper and 44,737 kg of wood along with overall reductions in the carbon footprint of packaging\n	\n		Symantec has been fully committed to understanding its waste stream and developing a global program of waste reduction. For example, they conducted a waste-audit in May of 2010 at the headquarters facility in Mountain View, California. They accomplish the waste reduction objectives, they have looked at several different technologies including vermiculture, onsite composting, dehydration practices, biodegradable products, restroom electric hand dryers to reduce usage of restroom paper towels, and onsite waste to energy generation systems, among others\n	\n		They increase the amount of paper being recycled by using paper shredding vendors at facilities around the world to shred and then recycle confidential documents\n	\n		They make efforts to refurbishment and reuse equipment, specifically electronics and other e-waste containing metals such as lead, mercury, cadmium, gold, and silver, with multiple significant environmental impacts. IT department assesses older equipment to determine if it can be productively reused.\n		\n			\n				For example, when consolidating data centers, they save servers and other devices, preventing the generation of e-waste and saving the costs of purchasing new equipment\n			\n				They donate still-functional equipment that is not sufficiently powerful for their use to nonprofit organizations and schools through&nbsp;Silicon Valley StRUT (Students Recycling Used Technology)&nbsp;and Microsoft Authorized Replicator Program; these donations avoid end-of-life recycling or disposal costs and help recipients maximize budgets and meet program objectives\n			\n				Equipment that has reached the end of its useful life is sent to third party vendors for proper recycling. When possible, they utilize local contractors or large companies that recycle locally in order to support community economies while reducing transportation costs and CO2 emissions. These vendors offer services such as hardware retrieval, asset tag and identifier removal, sorting, and environmentally responsible data wiping, cleaning, and destruction procedures\n		\n	\n\n\n	Transportation\n\n	Symantec is reducing global travel and using environmentally responsible providers when possible. Symantec''s supply chain group is also working to reduce its transportation carbon footprint\n\n	\n		For product transportation, use of environmentally preferable options when possible, including the "green" programs of DHL, UPS, and FedEx, and the use of rail transport vs. trucks and sea freight vs. air freight when feasible\n	\n		When travel is absolutely necessary, use of environmentally responsible service providers whenever feasible: preference for airlines with strong corporate responsibility strategies and airplanes that can use biofuels\n	\n		Preferred car rental vendors report on their CO2 emissions and include hybrid or bio-fueled vehicles in their fleet\n		\n			\n				Avis reports on CO2 emissions, offers carbon-neutral driving to customers, and has an “eco collection” group of vehicles that have emissions of less than 120 g CO2 /km\n			\n				To further educate employees about environmentally preferable travel options, Symantec posts articles and company travel facts on the internal Symantec Travel Blog\n		\n	\n\n\n	Symantec works on reducing employee commuting and business travel to reduce greenhouse gas emissions:\n\n	\n		Symantec launched the ‘Ways2Work’ program that supports U.S. and Canadian employees in setting up a flexible work arrangement that contributes to reduced carbon footprint. In FY12, they launched the program in other countries as well and provided technology solutions to support and enhance the Ways2Work experience\n	\n		Halo Studios Drive Face-to-Face Collaboration: In FY11, more employees were able to take advantage of collaborating with their colleagues face-to-face as Symantec added more high-definition video collaboration studios globally. In addition to the benefits of seeing co-workers “live” during a meeting, the studios also reduced overall travel-related costs and carbon emissions&nbsp;\n	\n		Symantec''s Commute Reduction Program is a suite of initiatives designed to reduce the environmental impacts of employees'' daily commutes at several sites in the United States. Efforts to encourage and facilitate the use of alternative transportation include:\n		\n			\n				Adding bike racks, locker rooms, and showers to facilities\n			\n				Hosting rideshare bulletin boards and/or commuter information kiosks\n			\n				Reserving priority parking spaces for drivers of carpools or alternative fuel vehicles\n			\n				Providing shuttle services at the company''s larger locations\n			\n				Commuter Spending Accounts (CSA) that allow eligible employees to set aside pre-tax funds to pay for certain commuting expenses\n		\n	\n	\n		Symantec collaborates with Smarter Travel Workplaces to offer the Smarter Travel Program in Dublin, Ireland. They also host a car sharing website, bicycle challenges and premium car parking spaces for those who carpool in various locations\n\n\n	Partnerships around sustainability\n\n	Symantec donates $15 for every hour of volunteer service (up to $1,000 per employee annually) that an employee contributes to a nonprofit through the Dollars for Doers program\n\n	Sustainability-related products and services\n\n	Developed software and services to optimize the efficiency of data center operations for both customers and company\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	\n		Symantec’s environmental strategy is set under four components:\n		\n			\n				Green IT: Includes practices to minimize energy use and optimize performance in our clients’ and our own data centers and beyond\n			\n				Resource Conservation: Symantec aims to conserve energy and materials and minimize waste at each of our locations. In May 2008, we adopted a goal to reduce CO2 emissions by 15 percent by the end of FY12, using FY08 as our baseline year. We will measure performance against this goal by pounds of CO2 emitted per square foot\n			\n				Responsible Software Packaging:&nbsp; We integrate the concept of reduce/reuse/recycle into packaging design and manufacture, and deliver the majority of our software products electronically which conserves materials and energy\n			\n				Transportation alternatives: Symantec works to reduce employee commuting and business travel to reduce our greenhouse gas emissions.\n		\n	\n	\n		Symantec established the Environment Stewardship Council in 2005 consisting of Green Teams. These Green Teams are based in 24 locations around the world and contribute to the firm’s environmental efforts. Green Teams identify and help implement:\n		\n			\n				Initiatives to support improved environmental performance at Symantec,\n			\n				Volunteer opportunities within the local community, and\n			\n				Programs that employees can implement in their own homes and with their families\n		\n	\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals INSERT INTO `search_index` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `keywords`, `keyword_hash`, `module`, `entry_key`, `entry_plural`, `entry_id`, `created_by`, `uri`, `cp_edit_uri`, `cp_delete_uri`) VALUES
(725, 'Coca-Cola', ' \n	The Coca-Cola Company’s Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction:\n\n	The Coca-Cola Company is the world’s largest non-alcoholic beverage producer and supplier.&nbsp; They have approximately 146,200 employees worldwide, distribute over 3,500 beverages, operate in over 200 countries, and maintain 275 bottlers worldwide.&nbsp; Their sustainability efforts are detailed in the “2011-2012 GRI Report” and a few external publications.\n\n	Awards, Frameworks, and Accomplishments:\n\n	Awards and Recognitions: \n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; July 2012: “Innovation in Small Projects Award”, the International Water Association, Asia Pacific Region. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; November 2010: Responsible CEO of the Year Award to Mubtar Kent, Corporate Responsibility Magazine. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; August 2010: Greener Package Award for Sustainable Innovation, PlantBottleä Packaging. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; August 2010: Environmental Certificate, Coca-Cola Brazil’s bottling partner Leão Junior, 9th Latin American Conference on the Preservation of the Environment. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; August 2010: Environmental Excellence Award 2010, The Coca-Cola Export Corporation Pakistan Branch, National Forum for Environment &amp; Health (NFEH). Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; July 2010: 2009 – 2010 Environmental Responsibility Award "Ghiis Jáa," Coca-Cola Peru. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; May 2010: Gold Award, PlantBottleä Packaging, DuPont Awards for Packaging Innovation. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; November 2009: 2009 CSR Award, Coca-Cola China, AmCham Shanghai Corporate Social Responsibility Conference and Awards\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; October 2009: Citizen of Gold Award, Learning to Achieve program with Junior Achievement