ficient Unit,” Coca-Cola India, Confederation of Indian Industry (CII).\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; December 2007: Named Strategic Partners in Poland’s Responsible Business Forum, Coca-Cola Poland Services (CCPS) and Coca-Cola HBC Polska (CCHBCP), Responsible Business Forum (FOB)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; November 2007: Asia Society Leadership Award\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; September 2007: Finalist, Water Stewardship Initiatives, Coca=Cola China, Secretary of State’s 2007 Award for Corporate Excellence (ACE)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; May 2007: Bronze Star for Best Use of Innovative Materials, Chaudfontaine 0.51 RGB environmental friendly transparent label (first time compatible with reusable bottle), Starpack Industry Awards\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; March 2007: Corporate Social Responsibility Award, Mexican America Legal Defense and Education Fund.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; February 2007: Bhagidari Award, Coca-Cola India water conservation and environmental management, Delhi government\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2007: Product Innovation Best Ideas on Social Responsibility Issues, Coca-Cola Spain, Actualidad Economica\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; CSR Excellence Awards for “Continuous Commitment”, “Environment” and “Human Resources,” Coca-Cola Greece. Learn more »\n\n	Listings/Index: \n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; July 2007: FTSE4Good Index of Socially Responsible Companies\n\n	Rankings: \n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; March 2010: 50 Most Admired Companies, FORTUNE. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; October 2009: 1s place, Corporate Reputation Ranking, Coca-Cola Chile, Hill and Knowlton-Captiva and La Tercera newspaper\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; October 2009: 2nd place, Corporate Responsibility, Coca-Cola Argentina, ComunicarSE NGO\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; October 2009: Best Reputation Company in Bolivia, Coca-Cola Bottling Partner Embol, Captura Consulting\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; September 2009: No. 2, Newsweek Green Rankings, Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; August 2008: Most Socially Responsible Company 2008, Coca-Cola Nigeria Limited, Social Enterprise Reports and Award (SERA)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; August 2008: Food and Beverages Most Socially Responsible Company in Nigeria 2008, Coca-Cola Nigeria Limited, Social Enterprise Reports and Award (SERA)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; June 2008: “Best Corporate Brand License of the Year” for innovative merchandise made from “reclaimed, recycled and repurposed” materials, The Coca-Cola Company, Licensing Industry Merchandisers’ Association (LIMA)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; February 2008: One of Ten “Most-Admired” Companies in Germany, The Coca-Cola Company, Manager Magazine\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; December 2007: Philanthropist of the Year, Coca-Cola Ukraine, World of Child, Ukrainian Fund of Philanthropists and Ukraine 3000\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; December 2007: World’ Most Accountable Corporations, One World Trust 2007 Global Accountability Report. Learn more »\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; December 2007: No. 2 2007 Corporate Responsibility Study, Coca-Cola Mexico, Excélsior, \n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; November 2007: No. 2 India’s Most Respected Fast Moving Consumer Goods Company, BusinessWorld in conjunction with the Indian Market Research Bureau\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; November 2007: No. 7 Most Respected Multinational Corporation in India, Coca-Cola India, BusinessWorld in conjunction with the Indian Market Research Bureau\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; September 2007: World’s Most Respected Companies Survey, Barron’s\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; July 2007: Food and Beverage Industry Category, Best EthicalQuote Progress and Best Reported Performance Categories\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; July 2007: No. 2 Leaders Across All Sectors for Best Reported Performance, EthicalQuote.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; April 2007: No. 4 Most Respected Companies, Coca-Cola India, Business World\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; March 2007: No. 8 America’s Most Responsible Companies Consumer Index\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; March 2007: Best Sustainability Initiative, eKOfreshment program, Zenith International Publishing Beverage Innovation Awards\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; March 2007: Green End User of the Year (small projects), eKOfreshment compression (used in coolers and vending machines), Cooling Industry Awards\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; March 2007: No. 3 Beverage Industry Category, America’s Most Admired Companies Survey, Fortune Magazine\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; February 2007: Ethical Brand Awards: No 1 in the United States, No. 3 in Spain, No. 8 in France, five-country study by market research group GfK NOP\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; January 2007: “Global 100,” unranked list of the world’s most sustainable corporations\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2007: Best Companies of the Year, Coca-Cola Spain, Dirigentes. \n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2007: Best Professional Ethics, 3rd Place, Coca-Cola Spain, Actualidad Economica\n\n	Frameworks: \n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Project\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Global Reporting Initiative\n\n	Sustainable Actions\n\n	Water (Reduce, Recycle, and Replenish)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company is becoming more efficient in their water use by reducing the amount they use per liter of product even as they increase their production volume\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Estimate they replenish (offset) approximately 23% of water used in their finished products\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, the company used 294.5 billion liters of water to make 130 billion liters of product, a water use ratio of 2.26 liters per liter of product (16% reduction from 2004)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company wants to treat all the wastewater from their manufacturing processes. By the end of 2010, they achieved a 93% alignment\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By the end of 2010, 100% of the 200 Company owned plants achieved compliance with their wastewater treatment and discharge standards and now use on-site, municipal or government approved wastewater treatment plants\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To date, 370/950 system-wide plants have completed source vulnerability assessments.&nbsp; And 269 of those plants have begun implementing source water protection plants based on those assessments.&nbsp; The assessments inventory risks to water resources that supply their facilities and the surrounding communities\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Assessments covered six main areas of potential water risk:\n\n	§&nbsp; Efficiency of water use\n\n	§&nbsp; Compliance with wastewater standards\n\n	§&nbsp; Watershed Sustainability\n\n	§&nbsp; Water Supply Reliability\n\n	§&nbsp; Social and Competitive Context\n\n	§&nbsp; Supply Economics\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; 2008 Risk Assessment Update:\n\n	§&nbsp; 44% of water-related risks were derived from growing and competing demands on water, coupled with inadequate government policy and action, which affected water quality and quantity\n\n	§&nbsp; 24% of their risks were economic and came from rising water acquisition and discharge fees\n\n	§&nbsp; 15% of their risks were due to a lack of full compliance with internal wastewater treatment requirements\n\n	§&nbsp; 17% of their risk were sociopolitical in nature and came from local government and community engagement around local/global water challenges\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prior to 2010 water use division: 78% municipal, 21% surface/ground, and 1% other water/rainwater\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 system: 52% ground/surface, 47% municipal, and practically no other water/rainwater is used\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company states that they were able to achieve their successes in water sustainability by:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Using ionized air instead of water to rinse product packages prior to filling.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reusing treated wastewater for landscape irrigation and truck washing.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Advanced monitoring of water use and efficiency.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company’s bottling partners have engaged in 320 community water projects in 86 countries, 96 of the projects are educational programs. The projects have 4 objectives:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Improve access to water and sanitation\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Protect watersheds\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Provide water for productive use\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Educate/Raise Awareness about water issues.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Water Footprinting\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; A product water footprint is the total volume of freshwater consumed, directly and indirectly, to produce a product\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The Coca-Cola Company is investing in water footprint assessments in order to have a better understanding how of they indirectly use water in their supply chain, particularly sustainable agriculture\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; They have partnered with the Water Footprint Network since 2008, supporting its development and methodology\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; For the past two years, they have collaborated with The Nature Conservancy on 3 water footprint studies:\n\n	§&nbsp; Coca-Cola in a 0.5-liter PET bottle produced by Coca-Cola Enterprises, Inc. in the Netherlands\n\n	§&nbsp; Beet sugar supplied to Coca-Cola bottling plants in Europe.\n\n	§&nbsp; Minute Maid orange juice and Simply Orange produced for North America\n\n	Energy\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company has developed several measures to reduce greenhouse gas emissions:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; With the help of their partnership with WWF and research within their company the company was able to develop 10 high-return, low-risk energy best practices for bottling partners to implement by 2012 and a site through which they can document their progress\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; At their Ireland-based concentrate manufacturing facility, Ballina Beverages, a new combined heat and power plant went online.&nbsp; The plan captures heat from electricity generation and diverts it to heating and hot water systems.&nbsp; The plant’s operation is showing 17% lower carbon dioxide emissions\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Investing in clean energy:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The company has installed solar panels at facilities in Macon, Georgia and Coachella, California.&nbsp; They are working on installing solar panels at 4 more North American facilities\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; They have begun construction on a landfill gas-powered co-generation system at their Atlanta syrup branch\n\n	§&nbsp; The 6.3 megawatt combined heat and power system will use biomethane from a nearby landfill as its primary fuel.&nbsp; They expect it to reduce Coca-Cola Refreshments carbon footprint by approximately 20,400 tons each year\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, they organized a Sustainable Refrigeration Summit, which brought together a variety of companies to explore a more rapid adoption of HFC-free refrigerants. This led to The Consumer Goods Forum’s pledge to start phasing our HFC refrigerants by 2015\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Along with World Climate Ltd., they co-organized a panel discussion on a carbon-free economy\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Increasing their energy efficiency:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Through their improvement of their energy efficiency ratio to 0.45 megajoules per liter in 2010 the company was able to avoid $163 million in energy costs for 2010. That is a 1% improvement over their 2009 ratio and 14% over their 2004 ratio\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Global manufacturing emissions in 2010 were 2% lower than 2009 while increasing unit case volume by 5%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, Coca-Cola reduced emissions in developed companies by 1% compared to 2009\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; More efficient cooling equipment:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Approximately 45% of their company-owned coolers now have energy management devices which results in an estimated 16% decrease in energy consumption by the cooler fleet\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By the end of 2010, 100% of their new glass-door coolers and 95% of their new vending and fountain machines were 40% more efficient\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By August 31, 2011 the company had installed around 400,000 HFC-free coolers\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, around 15% of their new cold-drink equipment purchases were HFC-free\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cutting emissions and energy use in developing countries:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The new facilities that the company builds in developing countries meet the energy efficiency standards that the company holds for the rest of the facilities.\n\n	§&nbsp; For example, their operations in Turkey are the most efficient in their system, with a ratio of 0.26 megajoules per liter\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; They have LEED certified facilities being build in Brazil and established in China\n\n	Materials (Sustainable Packaging)\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduced the weight of their 20-oz PET plastic bottle by more than 25%\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduced 30% of the weight of their 12-oz aluminum can\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduced the weight of their 8-oz glass bottle by more than 50%\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, the company saved $90 million through a reduction of packaging waste\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; As of 2011, the company recovers around 36% of the bottles and cans they have in market\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Developed the first-ever fully recyclable PET bottle made from plant based material, PlantBottleä\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca – Cola works towards a zero-waste vision by:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Designing resource efficient packaging\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Eliminating waste for landfills\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Using recycled and renewable materials.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 Coca-Cola System Global Packaging Mix:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; PET: 54%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Aluminum: 12%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Refillable Glass: 11%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Fountain: 11%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Refillable PET: 7%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Glass: 1%\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Other: 4%\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In developing markets, the company works with industry and government to advance informal collection systems to make them formal systems that recover packaging material and provide sustainable jobs\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In developed markets, the company supports ways to organize comprehensive material recovery systems through industry\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Support the market for RPET by supporting the creation of goods made from the material\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PlantBottleä Packaging:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; More than 50% of The Coca-Cola Company’s beverage volume is delivered in bottles made from PET\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; PlantBottleä is a fully recyclable PET bottle made partially from plant materials\n\n	§&nbsp; The company has discovered a way to manufacture one of the two primary ingredients in PET from plant-based material and is working on the other one\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company invested in 7 bottle-to-bottle facilities that strive to increase their capacity for using recycled material\n\n	Transportation\n\n	Developed a Climate Friendly Fleet:\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company powers the fleet with a mix of fuels that include electricity, natural gas, diesel-electric hybrids, bio-diesel, and conventional fuels\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The company believes that their electric hybrid fleet in North America, of 700 or more trucks, could potentially reduce greenhouse gas emissions by around 30%\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca-Cola Hellenic has avoided 954 tons of carbon dioxide emissions since 2009 through the employment of a Safe and Eco-Driving Program along with maximum fuel consumption, route management systems, trained drivers, and performance monitoring\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca – Cola Refreshments is working to increase the number of electric trucks they deploy. They currently have 2 operating in Bronx, NY and six Navistar eStar electric trucks in Los Angeles, New York City, San Francisco and Washington D.C.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Along with training drivers to use techniques that are more energy efficient and reduce emissions\n\n	Partnerships Around Sustainability\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Safe Water for Africa Program\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; As part of the Replenish Africa Initiative (RAIN), Coca-Cola’s 6 year $30 million commitment to provide access to safe drinking water for communities in Africa, the company joined Diageo plc, WaterHealth International and the International Finance Corporation in laundhcing the Safe Water for Africa Program in May 2011\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The program will bring WaterHealth International’s WaterHealth Centers to more communities in Africa.&nbsp; The centers treat locally available water in accordance with the World Health Organization’s standards.&nbsp; The water is then made available to residents for a nominal usage fee and eventually the fees cover the cost of the center and maintenance, making the community sustainable\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Latin America Water Fund Partnership\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; FEMSA Foundation, a partner of one of Coca=Cola’s largest bottlers in Latin America along with The Nature Conservancy and Inter-American Development Bank created this Partnership that will manage all water funds in Latin America\n\n	§&nbsp; The water funds are in essence trust funds dedicated to the conservation of watersheds\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; By achieving the stewardship of 32 water funds, the partnership intends to conserve at least 800,000 hectares of protected natural areas and an additional 20,000 hectares of key ecosystems\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; It is projected that by 2015, more than 12 million people will have better access to water and at least 1200 rural families will increase their annual income\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Partnership with the World Wildlife Fund (WWF)\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2007, The Coca-Cola Company launched a transformational partnership with WWF, which established a join commitment to conserve 7 of the most important river basins spanning Asia, Europe, Africa, and the Americas. In each basin they address 4 central challenges:\n\n	§&nbsp; 1. Better governance and management\n\n	§&nbsp; 2. Resource protection\n\n	§&nbsp; 3. Conservation in balance with development\n\n	§&nbsp; 4. Biodiversity Protection\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Partnership with the UNDP\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2006, the company joined the UNDP in launching Every Drop Mattersä, which is an effort to address water related challenges in communities across Eastern Europe and Eurasia.&nbsp; The program helps to improve sanitation and water quality, install rainwater-harvesting systems and educate residents about water stewardship. The company made a $23.75 million commitment to support the project through 2014\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2030 Water Resources Group (WRG)\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In partnership with other businesses and governmental organizations, The Coca – Cola Company helped from this group in 2007 to contribute new insights to the increasingly urgent issue of water scarcity\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; As a result of the group’s work, several governments facing water shortages (e.g. India, Jordan, and Mexico) have engaged in more dialogue on water security, water management, and policy reform\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Its new goal is to support governments as they engage in water analysis, convene multistakeholder collaborations and undertake public-private partnerships\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Aqueduct Alliance\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The Coca-Cola Company has joined this group, which is a group of leading water experts from the private and public sectors, NGOs and academia\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; This alliance is a program of the World Resources Institute seeking to measure, map, and report on global water risk in order to form a global database of water risk information\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The company will support this group by providing their own extensive global database of water risk information\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; National Clean Fleets Partnership\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In July 2011, Coca-Cola Refreshments (CCR), the North American owned bottling operations, announced a membership with the National Clean Fleets Partnership.&nbsp; The partnership intends to help large companies reduce diesel and gasoline use by incorporating alternative vehicles, alternative fuels, and other fuel-saving measures\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Partnership with Thailand’s Pathum Thani Province\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2010, the Thailand Institute of Packaging and Recycling Management for Sustainable Environment, an industry organization that Coca-Cola is part of, partnered with the Pathum Thani Province as part of a project that aims to develop a more effective integrated waste management program\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Partnership with The Regional Initiative for Inclusive Recycling (Brazil)\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; A 4-year effort to transform the recycling market in Latin America by improving the socioeconomic status of recyclers and their families; ensuring that recycling cooperatives thrive in a competitive market; supporting public policy that allows recycling cooperatives to become part of local waste management systems.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ocean Conservancy\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; The company has partnered with this group for 16 years and has supported them by providing funding, in-kind support, and volunteer assistance to help clean up the seas and investigate marine pollution\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Co-hosted a workshop that helped design the Fifth International Marine Debris Conference\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2011, helped the Ocean Conservancy launch Trash Free Seas Alliance – a cooperative group of businesses, NGO’s, and scientific institutions working toward a goal of eliminating ocean trash\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	The Board of Directors is elected by shareowners to oversee the long-term health and the success of the business. The Board serves as the ultimate decision-making body, except for matters reserved to the shareowners. There are seven standing committees under the direction of the Board of Directors (Audit, Compensation, Directors &amp; Corporate Governance, Executive, Finance,\n\n	Management Development, and Public Issues and Diversity Review). Currently there are seventeen serving members in the Board of Directors.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Board of Directors established the Public Issues and Diversity Review Committee to aid the Board in its responsibilities regarding Coca Cola’s positions on corporate social responsibility and public issues that affect the shareowners, the Company, business community, and the general public. The Committee shall consist of no fewer than three members of the Board of Directors, which it currently consists six members including the chairman\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Public Issues and Diversity Review Committee evaluates social, political and environmental trends, issues and concerns that could affect the Company’s business activities and performance\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Audit Committee has oversight of environmental policies and performance as well\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Office of Sustainability with Chief Sustainability Officer, Beatriz Perez\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; VP, Corporate Social Responsibility, John Reid\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Global Director, Women’s Economic Empowerment, Charlotte Oades\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; VP, Sustainability Strategy and Communication, Abby Rodgers\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; VP, Environment and Water, Jeff Seabright\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Group Director, Corporate External Affairs\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Under the Senior Management and Board of Directors, several organizations were implemented to address sustainability such as the Technical Stewardship Organization, the Environment and Water Resources Department, the Environmental Advisory Board (EAB), and the Coca-Cola Environmental Council (CCEC)\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Technical Stewardship Organization- is responsible for environmental matters, including water resources, as well as product quality, scientific and regulatory affairs and business process excellence\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Environment and Water Resources Department- resides in the Technical Stewardship Organization and it is responsible for setting environmental strategy across business operations, developing environmental standards and programs, and managing performance\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Environmental Advisory Board(EAB)- a panel of experts from government, nongovernmental organizations and academia provides counsel to management on environmental issues, the views of external stakeholders, and environmental policies, programs and performance\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Coca-Cola Environmental Council (CCEC)- the CCEC consists of senior representatives from the Company and bottling partners. The Council promotes environmental management across the business system by sharing best practices and developing and validating environmental standards\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Water\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: Assess the vulnerability of the quality and quantity of water sources for each of our bottling plants and implement a locally relevant water resource sustainability program by the end of 2012.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2012, improve water efficiency by 20% compared with a 2004 baseline.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2020, safely return to nature and to communities an amount of water equal to what we want to use in our finished beverages and their production.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Energy\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: Grow our business but not our system-wide carbon emissions in our manufacturing operations through 2015 compared with our 2004 baseline.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2015, reduce emissions from our manufacturing operations in developed countries by 5% compared to our 2004 baseline.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: As of 2015, all new cold-drink equipment will be HFC-free, with an interim goal of being 50% HFC-free by 2012.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sustainable Packaging\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2015, improve packaging material efficiency per liter of product sold by 7% compared with a 2008 baseline.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: By 2015, recover 50% of the equivalent bottles and cans’ used annually.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal: Source 25% of our PET plastic from recycled and renewable material by 2015.\n\n	Best Practices / Success Drivers\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PlantBottleä Packaging: PlantBottle Webpage\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ionized Air: Patent\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Compensation Tied to Company Performance: \n\n	The compensation programs are designed to reward employees for producing sustainable growth consistent with the Company’s 2020 Vision, to attract and retain world-class talent and to align compensation with the long-term interests of shareowners. The Coca-Cola Company believes that as an employee’s level or responsibility increases, so should the proportion of performance-based compensation. As a result, the executive compensation programs are closely tied to performance\n\n	Researched and Prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/TCCC_2010_2011_GRI_Report.pdf\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/sustainabilityreport/TCCC_2010_2011_GRI_Report.pdf\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; http://www.thecocacolacompany.com/ourcompany/awards_recognition.html?awardSection=corp_responsibility\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/dynamic/press_center/2011/05/new-chief-sustainability-officer.html\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/citizenship/plantbottle.html\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; http://www.google.com/patents/US5265298\n\n	For further information regarding compensation discussion and analysis can be found on the following link: http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/21344/000130817912000055/lcocacola_def14a.htm\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '135', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/coca-cola', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/135', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/135'),
(724, 'Patagonia', ' \n	Patagonia Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Patagonia, Inc. is a Ventura, California based clothing company, focusing mainly on high end outdoor clothing such as Alpine Climbing, Fly Fishing, Rock Climbing, Skiing, Surfing, Trail Running and Snowboarding. It was founded by Yvon Chouinards in 1972 in Ventura, California. It is a privately held retail company with retail stores in the USA and abroad and employing around 1,500 people. Patagonia’s founder is a green-living pioneer and his company’s strategy includes being one of the greenest/cleanest and environmentally savvy companies.\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012\n\n	Sustainability Awards\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Lifetime Achievement Award for leading sustainable businesses: The Sustainable Business Council\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010: "Gear of the Year" awards for its use of lightweight and recycled materials: National geographic adventure\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2008: ''Eco Brand of the Year'' award at the Volvo Ecodesign Forum during the ISPO Trade Show in Munich\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2008: 2nd Annual Rock/Creek Environmental Stewardship Award: Rock/Creek\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006: Patagonia, Environmental Sustainability: For its unique commitment to developing sustainable business practices: Business Ethics 18th Annual Awards\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; May 24, 2012: Los Angeles Times: Outdoor retailer Patagonia puts environment ahead of sales growth\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sustainability index: Patagonia is working with 40 clothing companies, such as Walmart, to put green buying directly into the hands of consumers\n\n	Rankings\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia was the first major clothier to make fleece jackets out of recycled bottles\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Nearly a third of the power for its headquarters and adjoining child-care center comes from solar\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia ranked 7.8/10 for its green cloth rating as the cotton used was sourced organically\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; By joining B Corporation, Patagonia is striving to build the best company by meeting&nbsp; “rigorous, independent, and transparent standards of social and environmental performance.”\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia also demonstrates their environmental consciousness in the design and construction of their facilities. An example is their Reno Nevada Service Center which employs green design and technologies to initially achieve a LEED Silver and then later Gold certification\n\n	Materials\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia commits to buy sustainable wool from Ovis XXI, while this organization certifies that the product comes from responsible producers that are keeping and restoring their natural grasslands, and keeps instructing them along with The Nature Conservancy\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2005, Patagonia launched a worldwide recycling initiative called the Common Threads Recycling Program. The Common Threads Recycling Program relies on both Patagonia and its customers to accomplish reducing, reusing and repairing, and recycling. It allows customers to bring back any Patagonia clothing with the special Common Threads label on it and put it into the store’s recycling bin. Patagonia then ships the clothing to refurbishment centers around the world where the fabric is processed and turned into a new Patagonia product. This reduces the amount of virgin material used for Patagonia’s products\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduce- Patagonia makes useful gear that lasts long, the consumer is asked not to buy what they don’t need.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Repair- The company helps repair the customers Patagonia gear, the consumer pledges to fix what is broken.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reuse- Patagonia helps find a home for gear that is no longer needed, the consumer sells it back to Patagonia through the Common Threads Initiative or passes it on to someone who does need it.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Recycle- Patagonia will take back gear that is worn out and recycle it into new fiber or fabric, the consumer pledges to keep stuff out of landfills.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Reimagine- together “reimagine a world where we take only what nature can replace.”&nbsp;\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia works with bluesign standard since 2000 to evaluate and to reduce resource consumption and to screen raw materials, including dyes and finishes, used in the supply chain. Bluesign Technologies, based in Switzerland, audits the energy, water and chemical usage of its system partners and helps them achieve continuous, long-term environmental improvement. This includes screening of chemicals, which are assigned to one of three categories: blue, safe to use; gray, special handling required; and black, forbidden under the standard. The bluesign standard helps factories eliminate black chemicals and find equivalent alternatives\n\n	Partnerships around sustainability (engaging suppliers)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia Inc. has teamed with The Nature Conservancy Argentina and Ovis XXI to promote the conservation of natural grasslands and their surrounding environment\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Organic Exchange is an organization that helps promote education about and use of organic materials in clothing and industry, primarily organic cotton. Patagonia has supported this organization since its establishment in 2002, and Patagonia was one of the first companies to switch to entirely organic cotton\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Founded in 1989 by Patagonia, the Conservation Alliance encourages outdoor sporting goods stores to contribute monetarily to environmental causes. With over 170 members, 100% of the proceeds go directly to environmental organizations\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia commits 1% of their total sales or 10% of their profits, whichever is more, to environmental groups. Since 1985, when the program was first started, Patagonia has donated $25 million to over 1,000 organizations\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia co-founded 1% for the planet, an alliance of businesses which, like Patagonia, commit at least 1% of their total sales to the environment.\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia often features their environmental campaigns in their catalogs and advertisements. Many of their recent campaigns include work with preventing oil drilling in the Alaska Wildlife Refuge, "Ocean As A Wilderness", and "Don''t Dam Patagonia"\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia is collaborating with Earth justice and renowned photographer Florian Schulz to protect the Arctic wilderness.\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia supports Oceans as Wilderness campaign to help to see what lives under the Earth''s seas, how the vast schools of tuna are like herds of buffalo, how bottom trawling is like clear-cutting an entire forest to get at a single tree\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In addition to large global initiatives, Patagonia also supports several smaller initiatives such as the World Trout Initiative, Environmental Internships, and the Organic Exchange:\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Developed in 2005, the World Trout Initiative works to protect the endangered fish of the world through grants to organizations that protect threatened fish. The mission of the World Trout Initiative is to “identify the individuals and groups that protect native fish, to tell their story and to support their conservation efforts by placing money into the hands of the actual groups protecting the fish”\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; A unique program that Patagonia started in 1993 is their Environmental Internships program. A Patagonia employee can take a leave of absence with full pay and benefits to volunteer within an environmental non-profit of their choice for up to two months. Employees can work anywhere in the country on any project they want\n\n	o&nbsp;&nbsp; Gulf Crisis Response- Patagonia’s Response to the Gulf Oil Spill in 2010. Patagonia''s employees, while working with the Louisiana Bucket Brigade, walked door-to-door in communities across southeastern Louisiana’s coastal parishes surveying residents about the public health, cultural and financial impacts they’d felt from BP’s April 2010 oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico. A total of 70 Employees, worked for 7 Weeks with 7 Communities\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Company has also paired up with several groups to address the challenges with sustainability and social responsibility. Some of those groups are the Outdoor Industry Association’s Eco-Index, the Corporate Responsibility Working Groups and the European Outdoor Group’s Social Responsibility Working Group\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Founded by Patagonia in 2007, Freedom to Roam is a self-supporting coalition of business, government, and conservation groups working together to conserve wildlife corridors across North America. Its goal is to create, restore and protect wild ways or corridors between habitats so animals can survive.\n\n	Sustainability-related products and services\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Footprint Chronicles: This interactive website lets a customer follow a specific piece of clothing through its entire journey from production to recycle. The website is meant to give customers a glimpse into what Patagonia is doing, and leaves an open forum for customers to comment and try to make the process even better. The point of the website is to show customers the good and the bad side of Patagonia, and open up to suggestions for how they can improve the processes that are still hurting the environment\n\n	Governance\n\n	As part of their Corporate Responsibility (CR) efforts, Patagonia takes responsibility for the impact of their activities on communities and the environment. Patagonia makes sure that their products are produced under safe and legal humane working conditions. The company itself does not make the products; it merely sells them through retail stores, but the products that are being sold are made from sustainable, organic materials from factories that efficaciously promote sustainability\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To ensure the sustainability of the goods they sell, Patagonia examines every factory that is used to make their products because they want to make sure the factories are aligned with their values, goals, and mission. Patagonia selects the factories based on four factors: quality, business factors, environment and social performance\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The Social/Environmental Responsibility team screens all new factories for social and environmental compliance with local law under the terms and conditions of the Patagonia Code of Conduct. The SER staff visits the factories regularly to assess compliance and follow up with training for specific concerns.\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The director of SER works with the Sourcing and Quality departments to determine where to place the products, and he has full veto power over the choosing of a new factory. The SER team not only works with the Quality and Sourcing departments, but with the Production Department as well. All three teams work together, and each team’s director has an equal say in sourcing decisions\n\n	·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Patagonia has yet to publish a Corporate Social Responsibility report or a Sustainability Report that follows the guidelines of the GRI. But Patagonia is committed to Corporate Responsibility by initiating their own reports and publishing them online. Some of those publications are the social audit report results and a list of factories, which are available online. The factory list reports all the factories that produce Patagonia’s products. The social audit report reports on the clothes produced through the Fair Labor Association\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals INSERT INTO `search_index` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `keywords`, `keyword_hash`, `module`, `entry_key`, `entry_plural`, `entry_id`, `created_by`, `uri`, `cp_edit_uri`, `cp_delete_uri`) VALUES
(726, 'IBM', ' \n	IBM Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Charles Ranlett Flint founded the International Business Machine Corporation, or IBM in 1911. With 433,362 employees, $116.4 billion in assets, and over 300 national and international locations IBM is a very large company that makes and applies technology to improve the world.&nbsp; Its employees create and integrate hardware, software, and services with the goal of creating a “smarter planet”.&nbsp; It established corporate policies of providing a safe and healthy workplace (1967), protecting the environment (1971), and conserving natural resources and energy (1974).&nbsp; From 2007-2011, IBM has spent $106.9 million in capital and $508.5 million in operating expenses to construct, maintain, and improve the infrastructure for environmental protection and to manage its worldwide environmental programs.\n\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012\n\n	Sustainability Awards\n\n	2012:\n\n	\n		European Union Code of Conduct for Data Centers Award: for technologies used to improve data center energy efficiency\n	\n		EPA Climate Leadership Award\n	\n		World Environment Center’s Gold Medal for International Corporate Achievement in Sustainable Development\n	\n		Vermont Governor’s Award for Environmental Excellence\n\n\n	2011:\n\n	\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (to IBM Global Real Estate Operations)\n	\n		Corporate Energy Management International Award from AEE (Association of Energy Engineers)\n	\n		Institute for Supply Management Awards for Excellence in Supply Management\n	\n		Business and The Environment Award (from DECISION magazine in the UK)\n	\n		China Sustainability Award\n	\n		Canadian Industry Program for Energy Conservation Leadership Award (IBM Canada)\n	\n		Distinction Award (in the category of Energy Efficiency)(IBM Canada)\n	\n		Vermont Governor’s Awards for Environmental Excellence (IBM Burlington)\n	\n		Best Overall Energy Project in New England Award (from the New England Chapter of the Association of Energy Engineers) (IBM Burlington)\n	\n		Excellence in Environmental Engineering Award (from the American Academy of Environmental Engineers)\n	\n		Smith Seal of North Carolina Sustainable Business award--Lifetime Achievement for Large Organization\n\n\n	2010:\n\n	\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (IBM Systems and Technology Group)\n	\n		Most Valuable Pollution Prevention Award (from National Pollution Prevention Roundtable)\n	\n		Class of Excellence Wastewi$e Label Award in the Hong Kong Awards for Environmental Excellence program (IBM Hong Kong)\n	\n		Excellence Award in the Environment Excellence category (IBM’s Corporate Service Corps)\n	\n		Vermont Governor’s Awards for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention\n\n\n	2009:\n\n	\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (IBM Research)\n	\n		Vermont Governor’s Awards for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention\n	\n		Sustainable Development Award (IBM Canada from the regional Chamber of Commerce)\n	\n		Industrial Energy Technology Conference Energy Awards\n	\n		Most Valuable Pollution Prevention Award (IBM Burlington, Vermont)\n\n\n	2008:\n\n	\n		ECOFIRA INNOVACION Award\n	\n		Environmental Affairs Excellence Award (IBM East Fishkill)\n	\n		Top Winner in the Green IT Report\n	\n		Gold Medal at the British Computer Society Project Excellence Awards in the IT Industry Awards category\n	\n		Vermont Governor’s Award for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention\n\n\n	2007:\n\n	\n		Chairman’s Environmental Award (IBM Systems and Technology Group)\n	\n		Environmental Excellence Award\n	\n		Green IT Initiative of the Year\n	\n		Technology Award (IBM Canada from American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-Conditioning Engineers)\n	\n		Most Outstanding Demonstration of Packaging Waste Management in Australia\n	\n		SmartWay Excellence Award (from US EPA)\n	\n		Most Valuable Pollution Prevention Award (IBM Burlington, Vermont)\n	\n		Vermont Governor’s Award for Environmental Excellence and Pollution Prevention (IBM Burlington)\n	\n		New York State Environmental Excellence Award (IBM East Fishkill)\n	\n		U.S. Environmental Protection Agency SmartWay Excellence Award\n\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	2012:\n\n	\n		Standard &amp; Poors list: AA-\n\n\n	2011:\n\n	\n		Dow Jones Sustainability Index (since 2005)\n\n\n	2008:\n\n	\n		Gold Rating under the Corporate Responsibility Index (from St. James Ethics Centre, Australia)\n	\n		Ranked AA+ from Climate Protection Office of the Tokyo Government\n\n\n	2007\n\n	\n		Silver Star rating in the Corporate Responsibility Index (submitted by IBMAustralia)\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	2012:\n\n	\n		Ranked #1 among US Companies in Newsweek’s Green Rankings\n	\n		Ranked #4 in the global ranking of Newsweek’s Green Rankings\n\n\n	2011:\n\n	\n		Ranked #1 in Newsweek’s Green Rankings\n	\n		Ranked #1 in the November 2011 Supercomputing Green500 List (from Green500.org)\n	\n		Ranked #6 in Computerworld’s Top 12 Green IT Vendors\n\n\n	2010:\n\n	\n		Ranked #1 in Newsweek’s Green Rankings\n	\n		Ranked #1 in the November 2010 Supercomputing Green 500 List (from Green500.org)\n	\n		Ranked #1 in all-around performance in Gartner/World Wildlife Fund’s “Low-Carbon and Environmental Leadership Findings Report”\n\n\n	2009:\n\n	\n		Ranked #1 in IDG’s Computerworld’s annual Top Green-IT Vendors ranking\n	\n		Ranked #1 Supercomputing Green 500 List\n	\n		Top 20 companies in the Sustainable Business 20 List: The World’s Top Sustainable Stocks\n	\n		Top 5 in Newsweek magazine’s Green Rankings\n	\n		Top Rating in Bank Sarasin’s sustainability analysis\n\n\n	2008:\n\n	\n		Ranked #1 on Climate Change Strategies in Ceres Report\n	\n		Gold level ranking in the Business in the Community Environment Index\n	\n		Ranked #1 in Best 50 Corporate Citizens in Canada\n	\n		Included in Sustainable Business 20 List: The World’s Top Sustainable Stocks\n\n\n	2007:\n\n	\n		Ranked #12 on US EPA’s Fortune 500 List of Green Power Partners for 2007\n	\n		Gold Rating in Corporate Responsibility Index (IBM Australia)\n	\n		Gold Rating U.K. Business in the Community\n	\n		Ranked #1 in the IT sector by the MERCO index (Spanish Corporate Responsibility Index)\n	\n		Ranked #4 on Climate Counts scorecard of corporate leadership on climate change\n	\n		Top Ten Best Green Outsourcers of 2007\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		LEED Gold Certification (Lab in Foster City, CA)\n	\n		Carbon Disclosure Project\n		\n			\n				Disclosure Rating = 83\n			\n				Highest Disclosure Rating within sector\n		\n	\n	\n		Global Reporting Initiative rating of A\n	\n		Using OneReport\n	\n		IBM’s Global Environmental Management System conforms to ISO 50001 Standard on Energy Management Systems\n\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	\n		IBM Smarter Building Software maximizes the energy and environmental performance of buildings.&nbsp; It monitors equipment that consumes energy, manages the maintenance activities, and then reports the data using IBM software\n	\n		Match building lighting and occupancy schedules and install more efficient lighting systems\n\n\n	Water\n\n	\n		2011: 646 TCMs of water were conserved through:\n		\n			\n				On-site water reuse\n			\n				Wastewater and groundwater recycling projects\n			\n				Groundwater monitoring at all manufacturing and development locations\n		\n	\n	\n		Goal: average annual water conservation savings equal to 2% IBM’s annual water use at microelectronics manufacturing operations\n\n\n	Energy\n\n	\n		Saved 523,000 MWh of electricity: 7.4% of total energy\n	\n		175,000 metric tons of CO2 avoided\n	\n		Doubled the computing capacity of its data centers in 3 years w/o increasing power consumption\n	\n		Use renewable energy\n		\n			\n				Working to further the availability and affordability of renewable energy\n			\n				Wind farm management\n		\n	\n\n\n	Materials\n\n	\n		Health Protection:\n		\n			\n				Prohibited CFCs, Class I and II ozone-depleting substances, Trichloroethylene, ethylene-based glycol ethers and dichloromethane\n			\n				Of 3,233 metric tons of EPCRA-listed chemicals, more than 84% was treated for recycling or for energy recovery\n		\n	\n	\n		Product Recycling:\n		\n			\n				35% total weight of plastic resins were resins that contained between 25 and 100% recycled materials\n			\n				Processed 37,950 metric tons of end-of-life products and product waste and send only 0.4% of total to landfills/incineration\n			\n				Offered product take-back programs in Europe since 1989\n			\n				Included product recovery in annual corporate environmental report since 1995\n			\n				78% nonhazardous waste recycled\n		\n	\n	\n		Product Packaging Design:\n		\n			\n				Saved 780 metric tons of packaging materials with their 24 packaging redesign projects\n			\n				IBM Packaging guidelines (developed in 1990) lay out the methods, processes, and designs that should be used in order to reduce packaging volume and to promote the use of packaging materials that are reusable, recyclable, and/or contain recycled materials&nbsp;\n			\n				Use corrugated cardboard box instead of outer wooden crates for shipment overseas\n			\n				Eliminated the individual corrugated carton packaging for each part of the option package of IBM System x server\n			\n				Past Power System server chassis packaging strengthened so it could be reused for final delivery of product\n		\n	\n	\n		Voluntary Environmental Goal for Packaging Materials:\n		\n			\n				Requirement for responsible sourcing of paper and paper/wood-based packaging in 2002--supplies must be procured from suppliers who sustainably manage their forests\n			\n				Investigated bio-based materials\n		\n	\n	\n		Hazardous Materials\n		\n			\n				Management program tracks the hazardous waste management performance of locations worldwide\n			\n				Voluntary environmental goal\n			\n				Recycle some of the hazardous waste: in 2011, IBM generated 7,700 metric tons of hazardous waste.&nbsp; 44% was recycled and 36% was sent to landfills.&nbsp; Of the waste sent to the landfills, 85% was sludge from industrial wastewater treatment plants which (by government regulations) needed to be disposed of in hazardous waste landfills\n			\n				In 5 years, the hazardous waste generation has decreased by 36%\n			\n				Report the releases of chemicals into the environment\n				\n					\n						0.4% chemicals released into the air\n					\n						Goal: year-to-year reduction in releases of EPCRA reportable chemicals to the environment\n				\n			\n		\n	\n\n\n	Transportation/Air Quality\n\n	\n		2011: conserved 6.4 million gallons of fuel\n	\n		Offers Cognos and Sterling Transportation Management Software Solutions to help companies optimize their transportation systems (increase container/truck capacity, optimize routing, improving timely deliveries, reduce fuel use, and decrease emissions)\n	\n		Electrical vehicles: integrating into electricity grid and battery development\n	\n		Flexible work programs (work-at-home and mobile employees)\n	\n		Support public transport (shuttles from locations to mass transit stations, and “loaner” cars for business trips during the workday &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\n	\n		Set guidelines for smaller engines with lower car emission levels\n	\n		Online meetings and instant messaging to cut down on traveling\n	\n		2011: conserved 6.4 million gallons of fuel\n\n\n	Partnerships around sustainability (engaging suppliers)\n\n	\n		Governmental:\n		\n			\n				United States Environmental Protection Agency’s ENERGY STAR, SmartWay, Design for Environment, and WasteWise programs\n			\n				European Union Code of Conduct for Energy Efficient Data Centers\n		\n	\n	\n		NGOs:\n		\n			\n				Charter membership in World Wildlife Fund’s Climate Savers program\n			\n				Membership in Center for Climate and Energy Solutions\n			\n				Work with and support The Conservation Fund, the Environmental Law Institute, and the World Environment Center\n		\n	\n	\n		Partnerships with other companies:\n		\n			\n				Founding member of the GridWise Alliance: organization representing a large range of the energy supply chain with the goal of making the electric grid more sustainable\n			\n				IBM and WEC formed the Innovation in Environmental Sustainability Council, which explores how changes in business process and technology can solve challenges to materials, energy, water, infrastructure, and logistics\n			\n				Eco-Patent Commons: allows for global businesses to share their innovations that support sustainable development\n		\n	\n\n\n	Sustainability-related products and services\n\n	\n		Designing energy-efficient products that use high-efficiency power supplies\n		\n			\n				Providing clients with energy-efficient solutions\n			\n				Offers Cognos and Sterling Transportation Management Software Solutions to help companies optimize their transportation systems (increase container/truck capacity, optimize routing, improving timely deliveries, reduce fuel use, and decrease emissions)\n		\n	\n\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	\n		IBM’s Board of Directors is responsible for supervising the overall company’s affairs: it usually consists of 10 to 14 directors and it currently stands at 14 members.\n	\n		It has delegated authority to four committees:\n		\n			\n				The Audit Committee\n			\n				The Executive Compensation and Management Resource Committee\n			\n				The Executive Committee\n			\n				The Directors and Corporate Governance Committee\n				\n					\n						The Directors and Corporate Governance Committee review IBM’s environmental programs and performance annually\n					\n						The Committee was formed in 1993 and it established responsibility for reviewing IBM’s position and practices on issues such as corporate responsibility and environmental protection\n				\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		The Corporate Environmental Affairs staff:\n		\n			\n				Establishes the company’s worldwide environmental affairs strategy, EMS requirements, and monitoring of its implementation\n			\n				Environmental programs are implemented by professionals at manufacturing, development, and research\n			\n				Environmental staff at headquarters of major IBM geographic organizations oversees local performance\n			\n				IBM employees within operating units serve as team leaders for environmental matters\n		\n	\n	\n		Mechanisms to measure effectiveness include:\n		\n			\n				Professional Self-Assessment Program\n			\n				Environmental Performance Database\n			\n				Corporate Internal Audits\n			\n				ISO 14001 surveillance audits\n		\n	\n	\n		IBM formalized corporate policies in 1967, 1971 and 1974 to provide a safe and healthful work place, protect the environment, and conserve energy and natural resources\n	\n		IBM established a strong worldwide Environmental Management System: EMS\n		\n			\n				IBM first established EMS in 1997 to identify and effectively manage the potential environmental impact of IBM’s operations\n			\n				It respects the standard ISO 14001\n			\n				The registration of EMS verifies that IBM executes the same EMS no matter where in the world it does business\n		\n	\n	\n		Over the past five years IBM has spent over $508.5 million in operating expenses for environmental protection and to manage its environmental programs. In 2011 IBM saved about $139.1 million worldwide in environmental costs\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals INSERT INTO `search_index` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `keywords`, `keyword_hash`, `module`, `entry_key`, `entry_plural`, `entry_id`, `created_by`, `uri`, `cp_edit_uri`, `cp_delete_uri`) VALUES
(770, 'Smart Grids and the future', ' \n	Smart Grids and the future\n\n	By Anuradha Munshi\n\n	A smart grid is an intelligent infrastructure of the electricity network that builds itself up in a bidirectional and decentralized manner, unlike the traditional centralized top down electricity network that is in place today.&nbsp; This modern electricity network offers the advantages of utilizing locally available Distributed Generation (DGs) (which could be driven by renewable sources of energy like Solar and Wind energy) coupled with a fast and modern bi-directional interconnection network that allows near real time fault tracking and control. The smart grid improves grid reliability and operational efficiency [1], and introduces a platform on which retailers can create and offer new products and services that give electricity consumers greater choice and flexibility in energy consumption and in creating value for end users.\n\n	Architecturally the smart grid can be constructed as a network of smaller units of smart grids called micro-grids, each of which consists of a local distributed generation source and transmission mechanisms that interconnect it to the network. In the event of a national emergency (like a natural disaster), these micro grids can decouple from the main grid and can act as self-sufficient sources of electricity for long periods of time.\n\n	In this article we look at a couple of specific applications of the smart grid. The first application allows the smart grid to act as a peer to peer electricity network and help facilitate transactions where the consumer turns into a prosumer (or a producer and consumer of electricity). The second application allows a smart grid cluster of micro-grids to decouple itself from the main network in times of emergency.\n\n	As a decentralized model, a smart grid allows two methods of prosumer participation. The first model assumes that the utility has higher prominence in deciding or controlling electricity transactions between buyer and seller. This is the principle behind net-metering or the feed-in-tarrif (FiT) model today. The second model is the true peer-to-peer model [3] where all participants have equal status and can deal directly with each other for electricity buying and selling. In this case, transactions, pricing, and demand response capability in the smart grid are implemented via specialized software and hardware that enable this peer to peer relationship to exist. This model represents how eBay or the stock market or any peer-to-peer transactional network works today.&nbsp;\n\n	There is an interesting pilot project called PowerMatchingCity [4] in Netherlands that explores this very concept with the smart grid. Working on a cluster of 25 sample homes that are equipped with communication devices that help facilitate peer to peer electricity transactions, this pilot project makes use of a technology called PowerMatcher, a real time software that uses the concepts of Smart Agents to balance and get real-time quotes on electricity pricing that buyers and sellers can then negotiate upon and trade surplus electricity with each other.\n\n	PowerMatcher uses the concepts of Agents to help facilitate prosumer electricity transactions in a decentralized manner [5]. The Auctioneer agent is the main entity responsible for the price forming process as it collects bids from buyers and prices from sellers. Concentrator agents represent other micro grids connections as a combined price-bid number to the concentrator agent.\n\n	A larger scale project called EcoGrid [6] has been implemented in Bornholm, a Danish island. This project covers about 28,000 customers and utilizes a peer to peer smart grid model that is based on 50% renewable mix. The results of this project [7] have been very positive in fine tuning algorithms to implement a functional peer to peer model and also in verifying grid stability – responses for smaller production/consumption units (micro grids) are much faster than traditional larger units.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n\n	The above figure is a representation of the EcoGrid microgrid implementation in Bornholm, taken from [7].\n\n	As a second application of the Smart Grid, consider Sandy – the well-known U.S. “superstorm” of 2012 that was known to have wreaked havoc on the entire North Eastern U.S. Utility infrastructure. What is perhaps not that known is that during this outage a couple of Universities like Princeton and New York Universities that had implemented micro-grids interconnected to the traditional grid were able to isolate themselves and independently survive for a couple of days [8]. Similarly the 9.0 magnitude earthquake that hit Japan in 2011 allowed the Sendai 1 MW Microgrid [9] at Tohoku Fukushi University to isolate and operate independently for a couple of days during this time. Both of these events bear testimony to the fact that a transition to micro grids will allow larger clusters to go independent during times of emergency. Micro grids are today largely implemented by the military and universities, which is quite like the pattern of how the Internet started.\n\n	Some states like Connecticut today have started policy programs to support micro grids as responses to major storms and outages that have affected them. Internationally, some countries are also promoting micro grid growth in countries where grid reliability is poor. For example Greenpeace [10] in India is extolling a bottoms-up distributed renewables strategy to export surplus solar energy via micro grids from the Indian state of Bihar. It is these countries that offer a very large market for micro grid growth and expansion. Another concept that is very applicable to developing nations is remote micro grids, or micro grids that operate when there is no utility grid. Such micro grids can serve as the baseline of a new scalable infrastructure that smartly delivers humanitarian services to the poor.\n\n	References:\n\n	[1] - http://www.cnt.org/news/media/isgi-summary-of-benefits-and-issues-6-08.pdf\n\n	[2] - http://www.geni.org/globalenergy/library/technical-articles/transmission/green.venturebeat.com/how-microgrids-will-change-the-way/index.shtml\n\n	[3]- http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/10/24/electricity-ebay-our-future\n\n	[4] - http://www.ecn.nl/docs/library/report/2011/m11002.pdf\n\n	[5] - http://www.powermatcher.net/get-technical/powermatcher-technology/basic-structure-and-agent-roles/\n\n	[6] - http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/\n\n	[7]- http://www.eu-ecogrid.net/images/Documents/121218ecogrid%20eu%20-%20guide%20to%20the%20large-scale%20project_dec_update.pdf\n\n	[8] - http://www.greenbiz.com/blog/2012/12/05/how-microgrids-build-resiliency-extreme-weather\n\n	[9] - http://systemstechnologies.wordpress.com/2011/11/12/a-microgrid-that-wouldn%E2%80%99t-quit/\n\n	[10] - http://www.renewable-energy-technology.net/grid-storage/greenpeace-india-unveils-report-create-microgrids-network\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '139', NULL, 'topics/energy/smart-grid/smart-grids-and-the-future', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/139', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/139'),
(773, 'Featured-case-studies', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	Adobe - Green Buildings and Sustainability Measures\n\n	Adobe has been innovating in the LEED green building movement for the past decade. It owns seven buildings in the U.S., all of which have achieved EPA Energy STAR label with an average rating of 99 out of a possible 100.Six of the seven buildings are LEED Platinum certified in the Existing Buildings category, while the seventh is LEED Platinum certified in the Commercial Interiors category.How has Adobe achieved and maintained this level of energy efficiency in its buildings? Described are some of the features that Adobe deploys for its green buildings, along with some key sustainability measures. Read full Adobe Case Study here\n\n	NetApp - Greening its Data Centers\n\n	In today’s world of high performance computing, servers and IT equipment are typically housed in data centers that are constantly consuming large amounts of electricity as they run in the background to provide processing power to companies. The high amounts of power consumed along with inefficiencies in data center designs leads to the overconsumption and the wastage of electricity as a resource.\n\n	To address these issues, leading data storage and solutions providers like NetApp have deployed various measures that help reduce power consumption and increase data center efficiencies. Many of NetApp’s solutions for greening their data centers and achieving high energy efficiencies and lower Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE) have today become industry best practices in the quest for sustainability.\n\n	How has NetApp achieved these low Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE) values in its data centers? What are some of the innovative features that are deployed to achieve high energy efficiencies in its data center operations? This case study from Sustainable Silicon Valley highlights NetApp’s solutions and best practices for achieving a high degree of efficiency in its data centers.&nbsp;Read full NetApp Case Study here\n\n	Green Programs and Initiatives by eBay\n\n	Sustainability as a goal demands that we maintain our natural environment and create conditions that permit the fulfilling of social, economic and other requirements of present and future generations. To environmentalists all over the world this concept is well understood. But what does sustainability mean to large corporations?\n\n	To a company like eBay which facilitates online transaction of goods, sustainability means different things at different levels. At an operations and business model level, it means introducing green programs in its model of online trading, partnering with green companies and so forth. At an infrastructural level, it means making its data centers more efficient and optimizing its offices and facilities. At a corporate level, it means lending voice to green movements.\n\n	How does eBay deploy strategies that help drive green programs in its operational, infrastructural and corporate levels? How does it blend these initiatives within its existing culture? This case study from Sustainable Silicon Valley holistically examines various methodologies that eBay has adopted which lead it on the path of sustainability.&nbsp;Read full eBay case study here\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '143', NULL, 'topics/energy/featured-case-studies', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/143', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/143'),
(769, 'Adobe-case-study-green-buildings', ' \n	Adobe – Green Buildings and Sustainability Measures&nbsp;\n\n	By Anuradha Munshi\n\n	Adobe has been innovating in the LEED green building movement for the past decade. It owns seven buildings in the U.S., all of which have achieved EPA Energy STAR label with an average rating of 99 out of a possible 100. Six of the seven buildings are LEED Platinum certified in the Existing Buildings category, while the seventh is LEED Platinum certified in the Commercial Interiors category.\n\n	How has Adobe achieved and maintained this level of energy efficiency in its buildings? Described below are some of the features that Adobe deploys for its green buildings, along with some key sustainability measures.\n\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lighting Upgrades - Adobe has continuously upgraded all lighting at its office buildings and garages as more efficient versions of lighting have become available in the industry. Starting with florescent lamps Adobe first upgraded its lighting infrastructure. Today as LEDs have decreased in cost with higher efficiency, the facilities crew has once again swapped all bulbs for LEDs. Adobe finds that this simple yet effective move helps achieve a high degree of energy efficiency.\n\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Intelligent Sensors – Efficiency by the lighting infrastructure is complimented by installing intelligent motion sensors, daylight sensors, and other controls to turn off lamps and VAV boxes in work spaces and to power down monitors, task lamps, and other accessories when they not in use. For example daylight controlled lighting and timer sensitive motion detectors are used to control and monitor lighting in offices, resulting in its optimum usage.\n\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Monitoring and Control – Lighting upgrades and sensor equipment are further accompanied by software based intelligent monitor and control systems that monitor and control the buildings’ electricity and gas use, CO2 emissions, water use, indoor climate (temperature, humidity and airflow). Energy use in Adobe is tracked by building, floor and even by individual clusters of desks called “neighborhoods”. This holistic measurement and control is critical for Adobe in maintaining desired levels of energy efficiency in its buildings.\n\n	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Commissioning – Once the infrastructures are in place, continuous tweaking and fine tuning follows. Commissioning, or the process of continuous monitoring, fine tuning and upgrading, has been addressed early on in Adobe by their Facilities team. For example their HVAC changed from basic hourly timing or current weather conditions to well-placed motion sensors tied to VAV boxes. Similarly tying motion sensors to HVAC alone saved 300,000 kWh per year for Adobe. Moving a thermostat from ceiling to head level in an IDC closet (intermediate distributed closet) yielded better efficiencies. The key point is the process of constant experimentation and improvisation.\n\n	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Open office space – Adobe adopts an open office design that eliminates hard walls and makes use of natural lighting wherever possible. This has resulted in lower energy usage. Two rows of lights closest to the windows are operated by daylight activated sensors.&nbsp; Also when no motion is detected for 15 minutes all the lights shut off, and switching them back on is a manual task that people avoid. This saves energy and also does not make them want to use light unnecessarily in the first place.\n\n	6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Energy Generation – The Company has delved into different ways of generating sustainable energy of its own. At its San Jose campus, 20 vertical axis wind turbines (called “Windspires”) on the 6th floor patio generate clean energy from the natural wind tunnel configuration provided by the Adobe Towers. Adobe has also installed 12 100 kW Fuel Cells by Bloom Energy on its 5th floor parking garage. The fuel cells deliver about 30% of the electricity used at Adobe’s headquarters. The fuel cells however create CO2 and Adobe purchases RECs (Renewable Energy Certificates) to achieve carbon neutrality.\n\n	7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Water Conservation – Adobe has installed low-flow showerheads, low-flow hands-free faucets, waterless urinals and dual high-efficiency flush models with devices that adjust the volume according to the length of the user’s stay. Additionally their landscaping features drought tolerant native plants. Evapotranspiration controllers are used to adjust the amount of water used for irrigation based on current precipitation, humidity, temperature and wind conditions as determined wirelessly from the local weather station.\n\n	8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Solid Waste and Recycling – Adobe achieves nearly zero waste diversion rates. The office discourages excess usage of paper and other materials. Printers default to 2-side copies.&nbsp; Paper purchases are down by 60%. Bathrooms use compostable roll-style paper towels, bottled water dispensers are no longer used, coffee machines use beans in bulk packaging, and recyclers have been installed for shrink wraps and disposable pens, while all electronic waste is recycled. Dual “side-saddle” waste baskets at every desk allow first pass separation of recyclables into compost and non-compost articles. Shipping, packaging and distribution are controlled and monitored.&nbsp; All such measures go a long way for Adobe in controlling its solid waste disposal and encouraging recycling.\n\n	9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Supporting Sustainable and Local Agriculture – Cafeterias use organically grown food from local regions, even including food from the offices’ owned edible terrace gardens. Wood and other materials for furniture and design come from approved sources by the Forest Stewardship Council.\n\n	10.&nbsp;&nbsp; Encouraging sustainable transportation - Adobe provides free Caltrain passes to its employees, thereby encouraging mass transit. Monthly vouchers for other transit systems are also offered. Bicycle commuting is encouraged by providing weather shelters bicycle racks inside the garage, with gear lockers and showers at each building, while Electric charging stations are available for guests and employees free of cost. As a result of these measures, 24% of the total Adobe population commutes on public transit (compared to 4% average for the county of Santa Clara).\n\n	For more information about Adobe’s sustainability measures please refer to the document here.\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '144', NULL, 'topics/energy/featured-case-studies/adobe-case-study-green-buildings', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/144', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/144'),
(758, 'NRG Energy Brings Innovative Solar Power to New Santa Clara Stadium', 'SANTA CLARA, Calif. - NRG Energy, (NYSE: NRG), the Santa Clara Stadium Authority and the San Francisco 49ers today announced an agreement to bring sustainable energy to the new Santa Clara Stadium. Through this unique partnership, NRG will help the new facility become the first professional football stadium to open with LEED certification, the recognized standard for measuring building sustainability.\n\nAs one of the first Founding Partners for the new stadium, and the exclusive sustainable energy provider of the 49ers, NRG will install a number of state-of-the-art solar elements, including three solar array-covered bridges, a solar canopy above the green roof on the suite tower portion of the stadium and solar panels over the 49ers training center.\n\nThe arrays will have a total peak capacity of about 400kW and will provide enough power over the course of a year to offset the power consumed at the stadium during 49ers home games. As a result the stadium will be the first professional sports venue in California to achieve net zero energy performance.\n\n"NRG is much more than a Founding Partner, they are providing the energy leadership, infrastructure and expertise to help us achieve the vision of making the new Santa Clara Stadium an economically and environmentally sustainable showcase for innovation," said Jed York, Chief Executive Officer, San Francisco 49ers. "As we strive to build a stadium that embodies all that is unique and special about both the Bay Area and Silicon Valley, this partnership with NRG will make very lofty goals become realities."\n\nThe new stadium in Santa Clara is the next generation of stadium design. One of the most unique features of the facility is the green roof atop the suite tower on the west side of the stadium. The three solar bridges, connecting the main parking area to the stadium, will include hundreds of solar panels. In keeping with NRG''s philosophy of creating iconic solar elements at NFL stadiums, the solar bridges will be the first in the NFL.\n"The 49ers are not only one of the leading and most successful franchises in the history of the NFL, they have also been for decades community leaders in the Bay Area and with the entire 49ers fan base. Today and going forward, we are honored to support the 49ers as they extend their off-the-field community leadership into the critically important arena of clean and sustainable energy," said David Crane, President and CEO of NRG Energy. "And NRG is proud to partner with the San Francisco 49ers and the Santa Clara Stadium Authority in the pursuit of another milestone, the LEED certification of their new stadium."\n\nIn addition to the solar array, the stadium''s green initiatives include public transit access, convenient bicycle parking, a walking path from the San Tomas Creek Trail, water-conserving plumbing fixtures, recycled materials and a long list of other sustainable design elements.\n\nAs the sustainable energy partner of the 49ers, NRG will continue to explore other opportunities to help enhance the stadium''s sustainability efforts such as installing electrical vehicle charging stations to the new stadium. NRG is currently building the nation''s first comprehensive, privately funded electric vehicle charging network.\n\nNRG, the nation''s largest competitive power generator is a leader in providing safe and reliable energy solutions in new and innovative ways to American businesses and consumers. It is also the largest solar power company in the United States with more than 900 megawatts of solar generation in operation.\n\nAbout the new Santa Clara Stadium\nThe Santa Clara stadium will not only be the new home to the San Francisco 49ers, but it will also serve as one of the world''s best outdoor sports and entertainment venues. It was designed by HNTB and is being built by Turner/Devcon. The $1.2 billion venue will have 1.85 million square feet, seat approximately 68,500 and will feature an expected 165 luxury suites and 9,000 club seats. It was designed to be a multi-purpose facility with the flexibility to host a wide range of events, including domestic and international soccer, college football, motocross, concerts and various civic events, and will be expandable for major events such as the Super Bowl. For more information, go to www.newsantaclarastadium.com.\n\nAbout NRG\nNRG is at the forefront of changing how people think about and use energy. We deliver cleaner and smarter energy choices for our customers, backed by the nation''s largest independent power generation portfolio of fossil fuel, nuclear, solar and wind facilities. A Fortune 300 company, NRG is challenging the U.S. energy industry by becoming the largest developer of solar power, building the first privately-funded electric vehicle charging infrastructure, and providing customers with the most advanced smart energy solutions to better manage their energy use. In addition to 47,000 megawatts of generation capacity, enough to supply nearly 40 million homes, our retail electricity providers - Reliant, Green Mountain Energy and Energy Plus - serve more than two million customers. More information is available at www.nrgenergy.com.  Connect with NRG Energy on Facebook and follow us on Twitter @nrgenergy.\n(sent by)\nWeb Manager ', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '40', 27, 'blog2/view/40', 'admin/blog2/edit/40', 'admin/blog2/delete/40'),
(920, 'Environmental Challenges for Sustainable Redevelopment Conference', '\n\nCome hear our very own, Marianna Grossman, Executive Director, Sustainable Silicon Valley, and other experts speak at the Environmental Challenges for Sustainable Redevelopment Conference.\n\nDATE:   February 28th, 2012 8:30 – 12:30pm (San Francisco)\n\nTITLE: Environmental Challenges for Sustainable Redevelopment\n\nTOPIC: The program will provide insights on sustainable redevelopment, intelligent integrated infrastructure, sustainable remediation, and how to successfully manage vapor intrusion, regulatory coordination, and sea level rise, and other issues that may complicate expedited property redevelopment, especially for residential reuse. \n\nLOCATION: SPUR, San Francisco Planning and Urban Research 654 Mission Street, San Francisco, CA 94105\n\nCOST: Free, breakfast will be provided\n\nRSVP: For more information and to reserve your seat  http://rsvp.langan.com/inviteITRC/ \nor\nContact Julie Frankel at jfrankel@langan.com\n\nWho should attend? \nThis program will be of interest to anyone interested in redevelopment including corporate and military environmental managers, lawyers, developers, realtors, city officials, and regulators.\n\nThis is a half day program. Presenters include Langan Engineering, US EPA, CalEPA, SF Bay Conservation and Development Commission (SFBCDC), and others.\nThe program will provide insights on sustainable redevelopment, smart intelligent infrastructure, sustainable remediation, and how to successfully manage vapor intrusion, regulatory coordination, and sea level rise, and other issues that may complicate expedited property redevelopment, especially for residential reuse.\nThe conference is presented by Langan Engineering and Treadwell&Rollo;, which are members of both the Sustainable remediation Forum (SURF), and the Interstate Technology and Regulatory Council (ITRC).\n\nTopics will include:\n          Current Trends in Green and Sustainable Redevelopment\n\n          Expedited Redevelopment and Sustainable Remediation Policy and Strategies\n\n            New Developments in Vapor Intrusion Policy and Mitigation\n\n           Sea Level Rise and Impacts on Redevelopment\n\n           Panel – Environmental Challenges for Silicon Valley Redevelopment – panelists will include Silicon Valley director of development, developer, US EPA regulator, and attorney\n\n  \nTags: sustainable development, sustainable redevelopment, brownfields, intelligent  integrated infrastructure, green building, regulation, vapor intrusion, environmental challenges, sea level rise,', NULL, NULL, 'blog2', 'blog2:post', 'blog2:posts', '41', 23, 'blog2/view/41', 'admin/blog2/edit/41', 'admin/blog2/delete/41'),
(763, 'Microsoft', ' \n	Microsoft Sustainability Review\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Microsoft Corporation is an American multinational corporation headquartered in Redmond, Washington that develops, manufactures, licenses and supports a wide range of products and services related to computing. Bill Gates and Paul Allen founded the company on April 4, 1975. It has around 94,000 employees today.\n\n	\n	Awards, frameworks and accomplishments as of Nov. 2012\n\n	Awards\n\n	\n		2012: Microsoft was honored for its investment in sustainable power by the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)&nbsp;\n	\n		2012: Microsoft India received the Environment Management Award at The Green IT Initiative and IT Excellence Awards\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		2012: #3 in the list of organizations using the larger amount of green power by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)&nbsp;\n	\n		2012: #17 in Greenpeace''s Guide to Greener Electronics for their policies on toxic chemicals, recycling and climate change&nbsp;\n	\n		2012: #47 in NEWSWEEK Global Green Ranking\n	\n		2012: #12 in NEWSWEEK U.S. Green Ranking\n	\n		2012: Third largest user of green power according to EPA’s Green Power Partnership ranking\n	\n		2012: Second for green power use for the first-time ranking of tech companies by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		Global Reporting Impact: citizenship report, G3, undeclared (since 2007)\n	\n		United Nations Global Compact (since 2006)\n	\n		Carbon Disclosure Project:\n		\n			\n				2012 global 500: Carbon Performance Score B\n			\n				2012 S&amp;P 500 USA: Carbon Disclosure Score 99 (highest score)\n		\n	\n	\n		2009: Microsoft topped Goldman Sach’s GS Sustain Framework for the global software and services sector. The GS SUSTAIN framework seeks to “identify companies best-positioned to sustain competitive advantage and superior returns through analysis of 1) return on capital, 2) industry positioning, and 3) management quality with respect to environmental, social &amp; governance (ESG) issues”\n\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	\n		World Dow Jones Sustainability Index (2012, 2010, 2009)&nbsp;\n	\n		USA Dow Jones Sustainability Index (2012, 2010, 2009)\n	\n		NASDAQ OMX CRD Global Sustainability 50 Index (2010)\n	\n		FTSE KLD Global Sustainability Index (2012, 2011, 2010, 2009, 2008, 2007)\n	\n		Calvert Social Index (2012, 2011, 2010, 2009)\n\n\n	Sustainable Actions/Initiatives\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	\n		Microsoft’s Real Estate &amp; Facilities organization led an evaluation of smart building applications from three vendors across 13 buildings on its main campus. This program consisted in adding an analytical layer on top of existing building management systems and did not change existing infrastructure. The program first addressed energy efficiency through:\n		\n			\n				​“Fault detection and diagnosis INSERT INTO `search_index` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `keywords`, `keyword_hash`, `module`, `entry_key`, `entry_plural`, `entry_id`, `created_by`, `uri`, `cp_edit_uri`, `cp_delete_uri`) VALUES
(787, '8. Bushman Rain Harvesting', 'Every winter, millions of gallons of rainwater falls on residential and commercial properties and is treated as waste-water. It is quickly dispelled from the property and begins a downhill journey towards the San Francisco Bay. Along the way this once clean rainwater travels over parking lots, through creeks and streams, collecting organic and inorganic materials until it reaches its final destination. In many Bay Area cities this stormwater can combine with sewage systems and cause environmental problems.\nEvery summer, cities and counties implore their residents to use less water. Precious treated water is used on thirsty lawns and gardens. Almost half of residential water consumption is used to irrigate landscapes in the dry summer months.\nBushman Rain Harvesting manufactures sturdy aboveground rain tanks that allow the safe collection and storage of clean winter rain to be used for irrigation in the summer. The collection of rainwater also reduces the volume of stormwater.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '102', 699, 'solutions/view/102', 'admin/solutions/edit/102', 'admin/solutions/delete/102'),
(788, '9. SupplyShift - The Internet for Supply Chain Sustainability', 'Enhancing supply chain sustainability for companies with many suppliers requires data collection and a mechanism to use information to encourage supplier sustainability improvements. Buyers are increasingly asking suppliers to fill out questionnaires either based on existing standards or their own priorities, but there is no system that effectively uses this information to incentivize supplier sustainability improvement. There are three barriers to effective use of supplier information: (1) Many buyers use spreadsheets to manage supplier information, which makes tracking, analyzing, and using information difficult. (2) The use of multiple standards and questionnaires is both a burden to suppliers and makes comparisons across buyers, sectors, and product categories difficult. (3) It is difficult for buyers to cost-effectively use information to motivate suppliers to improve sustainability performance, especially since suppliers cannot evaluate their position within their industry.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '104', 702, 'solutions/view/104', 'admin/solutions/edit/104', 'admin/solutions/delete/104'),
(789, '10. Low-Cost Long-Life High-Efficiency Solid-State LED Lamp Power Supply', 'LED lamps today cost too much and don’t last long enough. LED lighting is extremely efficient, using about 75% less power than incandescent.  Lighting consumes 22% of commercial electricity in the U.S., and this consumption will be slashed to 10% when lights convert to LED. Many countries are banning incandescent lighting, but widespread adoption of LEDs is slowed by cost, reliability, and lifetime. When LED lamps fail, the cause is often the driver. When the driver fails, the cause is often the capacitors. LED Drivers are extremely challenging to design, because the LED is not a constant load but varies with time and temperature. A few companies are developing “AC LED drivers” with no capacitors, but they have not yet been widely accepted.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '105', 705, 'solutions/view/105', 'admin/solutions/edit/105', 'admin/solutions/delete/105'),
(790, '12. Smart Energy Enterprise Development Zone', 'Smart energy technologies, such as solar panels, electric vehicles and fuel cells have great potential, but have only begun to deliver the broad-scale environmental and economic benefits needed in the world. Even in the Bay Area, fossil fuel energy use and GHG emissions continue to rise (BAAQMD 2011).\n\nAchieving results on a large scale will take a system-wide approach, technology integration, policies and practice, and customer engagement. For instance, integrated customer tools and electricity rate structure incentives are critical to realizing the benefits of smart meter investments.  And grid management, optimization and reliability enhancements are needed to incorporate expansion of distributed and renewable power sources. \n\nCustomer requirements vary widely, and new technology carries cost and risk.  Collaboration is essential in bringing the right parties together, and to serve as force-multiplier in confronting shared integration, process, and policy-related challenges.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '107', 712, 'solutions/view/107', 'admin/solutions/edit/107', 'admin/solutions/delete/107'),
(792, '14. Kinetic Energy Recovery from All Vehicles (KERAV)', 'Problem: Nearly all vehicles waste tremendous amounts of energy, kinetic energy to be specific, when decelerating (either slowing or stopping completely). The majority of this energy is lost to heat through the braking system, never to be used again.\n\nOpportunity: Capture this kinetic energy! Although hybrids are beginning to do this, it is not anywhere near being 100% efficient, and probably will never be. There is still ample opportunity from other vehicles such as trucks, cars, buses and trains.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '109', 717, 'solutions/view/109', 'admin/solutions/edit/109', 'admin/solutions/delete/109'),
(802, '19. Village Industrial Power Plant', '1.4 billion people worldwide do not have access to electricity. Energy poverty is a barrier to food security, nutrition, health, hygiene, opportunity and financial independence.  Rural exodus accounts for 14 million people a year leaving their villages with 70% ending up in the slums. The lack of appropriate agricultural processing technology results in significant post harvest losses in some cases as high as 80%.\nThe Better World Workshop (BWW) has 35 years experience developing and disseminating energy and crop processing technologies in Africa.  Gazogen’s Village Industrial Power (V.I.P.) plant is a carbon neutral, small-scale power plant fueled by biomass in the form of crop waste. Carl Bielenberg, MSc, M.E., M.I.T., founder of BWW and Gazogen, strives to create opportunity through a systems approach to problems. The V.I.P. technology provides opportunity in a number of critical areas including women''s empowerment, food security, hygiene, water, education, and economic opportunity.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '120', 731, 'solutions/view/120', 'admin/solutions/edit/120', 'admin/solutions/delete/120'),
(803, '20. Nautical Torque Technology', 'Renewable sources such as wind and solar are intermittent and need to be backed up by\nbaseload sources such as nuclear and fossil fuel. Because society demands 24 hour power, a 1000Mw solar plant must be backed up by 1000Mw of baseload energy. Society''s power demands don''t go away when the sun goes away.  Potential baseload renewables such as tidal and wave technologies face higher costs because they are offshore, submerged or in remote locations. A tremendous opportunity exists for a baseload renewable that can cost compete directly with fossil fuel and nuclear power generation. .  .  \nIf society had the ability to store a large amount of energy, then intermittency would not be such a large impediment to renewable power. Compressed air and pumped hydro storage are the only bulk storage technologies currently available, and their efficiency and availability are limited, which prevents society from a 100% clean energy portfolio.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '121', 726, 'solutions/view/121', 'admin/solutions/edit/121', 'admin/solutions/delete/121'),
(804, '21. re.source: sanitation service for urban slums', '2.6 billion people in the world do not have access to safe sanitation, causing diarrheal disease that is the second-leading global cause of child deaths. One billion people live in urban slums, and that number is growing. Slum residents currently have a lose-lose choice between overcrowded public toilets, open defecation, and private latrines that are expensive to build and maintain. Few squatters and renters can invest in an immobile asset like a latrine. Narrow alleys make it difficult and unhygienic to empty the latrines that do exist. This results in dangerous and undignified living conditions and significant environmental degradation.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '123', 195, 'solutions/view/123', 'admin/solutions/edit/123', 'admin/solutions/delete/123'),
(805, '22. Energy Storage System for High Penetration of Renewables and Decreased Use of Fossil Fuels', 'High penetration of renewables often creates grid issues, high costs, and even environmental issues.  Renewable facilities may be located in remote areas within a weak grid, requiring new transmission through sensitive areas.  They may be located in highly populated areas where distribution assets are already near full capacity.  The energy generated must be consumed instantaneously, so during periods of high wind, high solar insolation, or unforecasted generation, the energy from renewables must be curtailed.  Typically, renewables cannot be ''dispatched'' to meet the current energy demanded, so a high degree of conventional generation overcapacity is required.  Flexibility comes at a high cost, requiring transmission and distribution with capacities often exceeding twice their average loading, and requiring fossil fuel based generators such as natural gas peakers.  An alternative is needed to fulfill the vision of ubiquitous use of renewables and an efficient and reliable grid.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '124', 738, 'solutions/view/124', 'admin/solutions/edit/124', 'admin/solutions/delete/124'),
(806, '23. iSTAR Living Literature', 'The question to be asked is “why is it so hard to implement sustainability in today’s society?”  The next generation of leaders crawls among us.  To permeate sustainability throughout the world we must educate our children on what it means to be a global citizen: that our actions and inactions impact the people we love and the planet we inhabit.  We are all connected in a unique, beautiful, ever-changing world.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '125', 737, 'solutions/view/125', 'admin/solutions/edit/125', 'admin/solutions/delete/125'),
(807, '24. Create viable human social system.', 'Our current social mechanism is terminally dysfunctional.  A large majority sees it from inside the box or boxes, recognizing "systems" that do not qualify as valid constructs.  Fictitious business entities are given more rights than people and other forms of life.  The health of our supposed economical systems are given preference over our ecological system.  The information explosion accords ever more powerful abilities to humanity.  If we can find a way to tame that for our mutual benefit then we face an open ended future with vistas, liberties and options heretofore unforeseen.  Can a very large population of high potential information handling entities coordinate their activities for their mutual benefit or is the experiment called life a transient failing experiment?', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '126', 741, 'solutions/view/126', 'admin/solutions/edit/126', 'admin/solutions/delete/126'),
(827, '26. AERC|Com-Cycle: Sustainable electronics recycling', 'Each year millions of computers, monitors, storage devices, printers, televisions, and other electronic items become obsolete in the eyes of businesses and consumers.\nProcessors are most frequently out-dated (by software) and are more likely to become "e-waste", while display units are most often replaced while working without repair attempts, due to changes in wealthy nation appetites for new display technology.\nThe EPA estimates that in 2009, the US generated nearly 3.2 million TONS of e-waste. But only 18% of that was collected for recycling. The other 82% went to landfills and incinerators, despite the fact that hazardous chemicals in them can leach out of landfills into groundwater and streams.\nFrom 50 to 80% of e-waste that is collected for recycling is shipped overseas for dismantling.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '128', 743, 'solutions/view/128', 'admin/solutions/edit/128', 'admin/solutions/delete/128'),
(828, '27. Viable Living Inc.', 'Means for acquiring green house gas minimal living is greatly needed.  The danger appears to be more severe than the pronouncements of the IPCC as one of the points of the evidence of this extreme danger linked to in this report suggest IPCC''s inability to be accurate: http://www.transitiontownsca.org/forum/topics/how-serious-is-climate-change .  Can a functional business model be made and deployed that facilitates many coming to viable living quickly?', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '129', 741, 'solutions/view/129', 'admin/solutions/edit/129', 'admin/solutions/delete/129'),
(829, '28. Earthship Biotecture', 'Life existed for many millennia without an adverse affect on the Earth’s ability to support life.  There was no “economy”, they did not have “garbage”.\nModern humanity has quickly managed to have adverse effects on the ability of the Earth to support life.  Modern human economy has created a thing called garbage.\nThe modern world tries to sustain a monstrous and oppressive economy that is supposed to sustain the people.  A greater world would have a system made to provide for the people.  Economy should be an insignificant aspect of an independently healthy and secure human existence.  \nA greater world based on the needs of the people would transform and consume garbage. Sustain the people and you will transcend economy.  Transcend economy and you will transform and eliminate the garbage, poverty, war, etc.\nThe key to having a better life for all people is found in the sustenance for all people...not just some people, but all people.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '130', 744, 'solutions/view/130', 'admin/solutions/edit/130', 'admin/solutions/delete/130'),
(830, '29. The SpatioTemporal Epidemiological Modeler', 'What can public health officials and scientists possibly do to protect populations from emerging disease or to implement better response measures? The rise of global economies, the rapid international movement of people and products, and the increased reliance of developed countries on global trade, all greatly increase the potential threat from infectious and food borne disease. The near real-time monitoring made possible by an electronic health record will provide input for dynamic epidemiological models of diseases. The need to rapidly develop new models requires a community working to bring together data and models designed to assisting public health officials and scientists responsible for public health response and interventions. This community requires input from several scientific domains and should, therefore, be open and allow scientists to reuse, share, and extend, reference data and models, thus rapidly building upon each other’s work.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '132', 745, 'solutions/view/132', 'admin/solutions/edit/132', 'admin/solutions/delete/132'),
(831, '30. Water Conservation', 'Water shortage is a worldwide crisis. Today''s world faces a greater demand for water. The world population is growing and more and more rivers, lakes and streams are being polluted. Tomorrow’s challenges are already at our door and we must act now for our future. Intelligent Irrigation manufactures a Subsurface Pressurized Irrigation system that reduces watering by up to 80% over sprinklers and up to 30% over drip systems. It also reduces fertilizer use and eliminates water run-off and evaporation of surface water This system will change the way we water the world. You can grow more food deliver less fertilizer and aerate the root zone with the Aquajet irrigation system. Billions of gallons of water  can be saved by eliminating surface evaporation and water run-off. Growers, Cities and Municipalities, Residential and Commercial properties will all benefit cut cost and conserve water. When you water in the root zone the water gravitates down and recharges the water table and aquifers.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '133', 721, 'solutions/view/133', 'admin/solutions/edit/133', 'admin/solutions/delete/133'),
(832, '31. The Energy+ Household - the complete residential solution', 'The way consumers use energy today is unsustainable as we will run out of fossil fuels someday. Also uncontrolled burning  of fossil fuels is having a disastrous effect on our climate. Solutions to almost eliminate fossil fuel use in the residential sector are already in sight. It is not prohibitively expensive nor very difficult to introduce these solutions to a typical US home.  All it needs is a little bit of planning and education and gathering all the best working practices together under one roof.  This solution creates an Energy+ household - that is a household that creates more renewable energy in daily life than it consumes over the course of a year. A working prototype of this solution already exits and the payback for the whole solution is currently about 10 years which is projected to decrease with time.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '137', 749, 'solutions/view/137', 'admin/solutions/edit/137', 'admin/solutions/delete/137'),
(833, '32. MyVerdafero - Utility Optimization Platform', 'Problem – Commercial utility costs are a major expense, continue to rise and are difficult / impossible to pass on to customers. Companies are constantly striving to cut costs and increase profit. Operational savings directly increases NOI. To be more competitive businesses are being forced to better manage their overhead expenses and focus their attention on real cost saving solutions. No single solution exists today that allows a company to easily track, analyze and report key metrics on an entire organization’s utility data to drive cost savings across multiple facilities and locations. Verdafero now provides that solution – MyVerdafero.\n \nOpportunity – US TAM is in excess of $5.2bn/yr based solely on SaaS subscription fees for our target markets. Larger overseas markets are on target roadmap within the next 2 years. \nWith the continued rise in utility expenses and squeeze on corporate profits the market is seeking real software solutions that effect bottom line profit.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '138', 750, 'solutions/view/138', 'admin/solutions/edit/138', 'admin/solutions/delete/138'),
(834, '33. Global Energy Assessment for a Sustainable Future', 'The Global Energy Assessment (GEA) demonstrates that a major energy system transformation is the key to addressing and resolving the worldwide sustainability challenges. Energy systems are a crucial entry point for addressing the most pressing global challenges in the 21st Century. These include sustainable economic and social development, poverty eradication, climate protection, conservation of ecosystems, peace, security and health for all. Major changes are needed to establish a comprehensively sustainable planet for societies worldwide. The GEA identifies strategies that would help simultaneously resolve these multiple challenges and bring multiple global benefits. Their successful implementation requires determined, sustained, and immediate actions. This assessment provides policy-and business decision-makers worldwide with invaluable new knowledge to inform action and commitment to implementing these strategies, and thereby resolving the 21st Century’s greatest challenges.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '140', 653, 'solutions/view/140', 'admin/solutions/edit/140', 'admin/solutions/delete/140'),
(835, '34. Creating Manufacturing Efficiencies', 'As manufacturer of photovoltaic cells a high-quality solution to existing trace metal contamination problems in cleaning chemistry and processes is required. There is currently no commercially viable methodology in the PV manufacturing segment addressing this contamination. Overly complicated process sequences, unbalanced processes using unnecessary amounts of chemicals, excess of dangerous and poisonous chemicals entering the waste abatement system, and reduction chemical and water consumption and waste generation through chemical usage reduction, recovery, recycle, reuse, and substitution are of high interest. In addition to trace metal removal, biodegradable, alcohol free texturing solutions are sought for the mono-silicon cell process. Multi-silicon, being 70-80% of our production has marginal texturing and cleaning processes. Viable solutions are required to increase performance, yield and efficiency.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '141', 756, 'solutions/view/141', 'admin/solutions/edit/141', 'admin/solutions/delete/141'),
(837, '36. International Centre for Earth Simulation', 'Over specialization in both the natural sciences and the socioeconomic sciences - and the lack of an integrated holistic view of our planet and its complex interwoven processes - has caused cascading multiple synchronous collapse across vast domains of society due to cross-connections that spread risk from one domain to the next. In the Tohoku earthquake March 2011, for example, we saw a subduction zone megathrust, tsunami, onshore destruction, nuclear damage, food contamination, supply chain disruption, political upheaval, and a global retake of nuclear safety. Cascading collapses were also experienced after Hurricanes Katrina and Sandy, and during the Deepwater Horizon oilspill, respectively. In all, 200 years of scientific specialization has been valuable and no doubt will never cease, however at this point in time we need to re-integrate our approach to all of science and society, and put back the pieces together again!', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '143', 760, 'solutions/view/143', 'admin/solutions/edit/143', 'admin/solutions/delete/143'),
(838, '37. More Efficient Transformers to Improve Our World', 'A huge opportunity exists to save enormous amounts of energy throughout the world by improving the efficiency of electrical transformers; an essential part of the electrical grid.  The conventional transformer (the ugly garbage can-like device mounted on telephone poles all over the world) are incredibly inefficient devices.  As electric current gets passed through these devices a large percentage is wasted.  Even in a no-load state (idle) energy is being lost through the inefficient designs of these devices.  There is a technology using amorphous cores that will dramatically reduce this energy loss and save billions of barrels of oil worlwide.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '144', 762, 'solutions/view/144', 'admin/solutions/edit/144', 'admin/solutions/delete/144'),
(839, '38. Reclaimed Water Pasteurization and Energy Recovery', 'The process of heating water for disinfection has been proven effective for greater than 150 years. However, only within the last 8 years have engineers and scientists discovered how to capture waste heat and continuously utilize that waste heat to cost effectively disinfect water. In late 2011, the City of Ventura, working with the Pasteurization Technology Group and Carollo Engineers, constructed the world’s first demonstration scale reclaimed water pasteurization system. Sized at 350 gpm, the system uses full-scale components to demonstrate low energy sustainable disinfection meeting California’s Title 22 reclaimed water criteria. For Ventura, the pasteurization system is planned to:\nBurn a combination of natural gas and digester gas, \nUse the power to run the entire treatment plant, and \nUse the waste heat generated from the turbines to disinfect up to 21 mgd of effluent meeting Title 22 standards for unrestricted water reuse applications.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '146', 746, 'solutions/view/146', 'admin/solutions/edit/146', 'admin/solutions/delete/146'),
(840, '39. Clean Local Energy Accessible Now (CLEAN) Program', 'Today, the United States primarily relies on energy generation from large-scale, fossil fuel and nuclear power plants, located far from the communities where energy demand is greatest.  INSERT INTO `search_index` (`id`, `title`, `description`, `keywords`, `keyword_hash`, `module`, `entry_key`, `entry_plural`, `entry_id`, `created_by`, `uri`, `cp_edit_uri`, `cp_delete_uri`) VALUES
(864, '64. Single Wheel Small Footprint Electric Scooter', 'Target Markets: Our market includes people in urban settings that frequently find themselves walking long distances on foot because of traffic congestion on the roads, limited parking spaces, and inefficient public transportation. Ideally people want their own quiet, energy efficient and green transportation solution that allows them to move easily on sidewalks, city squares, pedestrian precincts, train stations and other public spaces. They prefer to interact and flow with other pedestrians as if they were walking in a crowd but they don’t like being confined in city buses and trains. If they have to use a train they want to take their personal transporter on the train with them, into lobbies and elevators, and at the end of the day, into their apartments or condos.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '182', 814, 'solutions/view/182', 'admin/solutions/edit/182', 'admin/solutions/delete/182'),
(865, '65. Sustainable Power System Design & Performance Assessment Program', 'The environmental and economic sustainability of the United States, and nations across the globe, is threatened by an obsolete electrical power system that is costly, dirty and vulnerable. The electricity supply industry is a major contributor of carbon emissions and the distribution system is extremely susceptible to the impact of severe weather – the recent Hurricane Sandy has resulted in an estimated $30 to $50 billion in economic damage. The analog electromechanical infrastructure of the US electricity system has been starved of innovation for decades.\n\nWhile the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009 has infused $27.2 billion into alternative and renewable energy projects, electric vehicles and efficiency programs, these initiatives lack a method to specify designs or evaluate projects that produce desired, and critically important, environmental or economic results.  This Solution provides the first comprehensive environmental and consumer-centered method.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '184', 816, 'solutions/view/184', 'admin/solutions/edit/184', 'admin/solutions/delete/184'),
(866, '66. Noyo Headlands: Opportunity for a Sustainable Future', 'In 2002, on the ruggedly beautiful Northern California Coast, the Fort Bragg lumber mill shut down, leaving behind a devastated local economy and community. After laying off the final 150 workers from the 430-acre, ocean-front Mill Site that once employed 2000 people, Georgia-Pacific (G-P) shut the mill down. Fort Bragg residents have spent a frustrating ten years working with G-P (now owned by Koch Industries) to redevelop the property in a way that reversed the problems of land stripped of its resources; a toxic mill site; and a community without a viable economy. Instead, G-P/Koch''s plans rely on developing expensive second homes and courting wealthy tourists. This fossil fuel-dependent solution will increase our climate change problems while segmenting the town into rich/poor and new/old. Meaningful job creation is forsaken. Fort Bragg is not alone in this predicament. Hundreds of abandoned mill towns have to create a sustainable economy and community while nourishing the planet.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '185', 664, 'solutions/view/185', 'admin/solutions/edit/185', 'admin/solutions/delete/185'),
(867, '67. Energy Saving Thermostat', 'As part of reducing overall energy consumption for a sustainable planet, our focus has been on residential energy usage. \n\nHeating and cooling systems are the largest single contributor to residential energy usage. According to the Department of Energy, heating and cooling (HVAC) contributes to over 50% of the annual energy consumption of a typical US home. Reducing HVAC energy usage can make the largest improvement in home energy efficiency. \n\nThere are two approaches to reducing HVAC energy usage; improve HVAC equipment efficiency or improve how it is used. \n\nMost new HVAC systems are already energy efficient (due to mandate).  The return on investment does not justify higher efficiency systems. \n\nOur approach is to improve how a thermostat manages the HVAC system without impacting desired comfort level.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '187', 820, 'solutions/view/187', 'admin/solutions/edit/187', 'admin/solutions/delete/187'),
(869, '69. A Bullet Resistant 32.0 kWhr .Battery  Saline Electrolyte with Ceramic Electrodes', 'Military Service batteries need to be relatively bullet proof, as they may stand exposed without any form of shielding.Our solution was complex bur rugged and reliable for 25,000 cycles at 85% capacity. We utilized the capabilities of early bulletproof armour plates as the supporting plates for the cathodes and anodes. Thereby limiting the amount of damage to be done to a battery that wes struck by three bullets.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '190', 822, 'solutions/view/190', 'admin/solutions/edit/190', 'admin/solutions/delete/190'),
(870, '70. Global Alert - Floating Trash', 'The United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) estimates that up to 80% of marine litter originates on land, the majority of which makes its way into waterways end eventually the ocean, causing negative social, environmental and economic impacts. A 2009 report titled, “Marine Litter: A Global Challenge,” prepared in partnership between Ocean Conservancy and UNEP Regional Seas Programme, identified the urgent need for the development of a system like Global Alert. Regional Seas participants identified the need for litter monitoring programs in most regions to help formulate management solutions. Participants emphasized the need for education and public awareness as key components of effective environmental protection. Additionally, analysis revealed a widespread lack of systematic knowledge on the amounts, sources, fates, trends and impacts (social, economic and environmental) of marine litter, which has hampered the development and implementation of effective mitigation actions.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '191', 747, 'solutions/view/191', 'admin/solutions/edit/191', 'admin/solutions/delete/191'),
(871, '71. Plastic Disclosure Project', 'Plastic is a wonderful and versatile resource, providing many possibilities and conveniences. However, it is often treated as disposable, even though it is a permanent material that does not easily degrade. Today plastic represents approximately 12% of global waste, but a relatively higher share of the environmental damage. The impacts cut across our communities and ecosystems in many ways, including health, tourism, fishing, agriculture, water supply, waste disposal and direct impact on wildlife (APEC estimates that the annual cost of plastic pollution to marine industry in the Pacific region alone is over US$1bn). Government programs, laws, bans, taxes and campaigns have their roles to play in minimizing plastic pollution.  However, a solution is needed that is quickly scalable across industries and territories, engages businesses and institutions in applying their ingenuity and competitive instinct to drive innovative solutions, tangibly felt by investors, governments and consumers.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '192', 824, 'solutions/view/192', 'admin/solutions/edit/192', 'admin/solutions/delete/192'),
(872, '72. Mosaic', 'With new advances in technology and financing models, solar is becoming an increasingly affordable way for Americans to increase energy independence, hedge against rising fuel costs, cut carbon emissions and create local jobs. At the same time, an estimated 75% of Americans can’t go solar on their homes due to structural, shading or ownership issues.\n\nThat’s where Mosaic comes in.\n\nThrough Mosaic’s marketplace, individuals come together to invest in solar projects that benefit communities and the investors. All of Mosaic’s solar investments are carefully vetted to minimize risk while maximizing return and impact. Along with earning a solid financial return, investors are helping to build the clean energy economy and benefit important community organizations.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '193', 825, 'solutions/view/193', 'admin/solutions/edit/193', 'admin/solutions/delete/193'),
(874, '74. TOTO Drake II 1G Ultra High-Efficiency Toilet', 'TOTO’s Drake II 1G ultra high-efficiency toilet (UHET) consumes a mere one-gallon per flush, offering consumers aggressive water-saving benefits by reducing their water consumption by more than 35% over 1.6-gallon toilets, a water savings of more than 5,000 gallons of water per toilet, per year.  \n\n\nThe gravity-fed, two-piece Drake II 1G Double Cyclone marries flawless performance and exceptional bowl cleansing action to ultra high-efficiency water-savings, creating a clean, green flushing system that saves homeowners money, water, and time.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '195', 748, 'solutions/view/195', 'admin/solutions/edit/195', 'admin/solutions/delete/195'),
(959, '75. TOTO EcoPower Technology', 'TOTO has harnessed the use of water as a power source with its revolutionary EcoPower technology, by converting potential energy into kinetic energy that is stored in a series of capacitors to power the system.  TOTO’s unique line of electronic EcoPower high-efficiency sensor faucets, high-efficiency sensor flushometer valves, and shower lighting systems use this patented, one-of-a-kind technology as their power source – greatly reducing maintenance costs and toxic battery waste, which helps protect the environment.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '196', 748, 'solutions/view/196', 'admin/solutions/edit/196', 'admin/solutions/delete/196'),
(876, '76. Business Intelligence for Sustainable Management', '“Most (companies) still take a fragmented reactive approach-- launching adhoc initiatives to enhance their “green” credentials, to comply with regulations, or to deal with emergencies…..That’s no longer enough”   ( McKinsey & Company, copyright 2011, The Business of Sustainability: Putting it into Practice  http://goo.gl/VXgsj)\nBusiness Intelligence for Sustainable Management offers corporations the opportunity to capitalize on new revenue opportunities, reduce costs, and manage risks.  Yet, while much is written about the critical need for sustainable management, little or nothing has been done to provide executives with effective systems to manage sustainably at scale. Existing approaches are spreadsheet based, manual, costly, and do not scale.  In summary, a critical need exists for a viable enterprise quality system for sustainable management.  Climate Earth has answered this critical need with a game changing solution that is proven with Fortune 100 clients.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '197', 670, 'solutions/view/197', 'admin/solutions/edit/197', 'admin/solutions/delete/197'),
(877, '77. The Bridge to the Vehicle-to-Grid Future, Starting Now', '1.  Need to Jumpstart and Accelerate the Vehicle-to-Grid Revolution.\nThe Vehicle-to-Grid revolution in electric power grids will save the planet if it happens soon enough, by allowing renewable energy to be stored in thousands of Electric Vehicle batteries and then fed back into the system when the sun and wind can''t help.  We need it soon, but creating the integrated smart grid with countless EVs presents huge challenges.  \n\n2.   Need for Power when There Is No Grid.\nAt the same time, we face a seemingly-unrelated problem of the need for backup power at government and corporate campuses when system grids fail in blackouts.  And as a major hospital in New York found out during Sandy, sometimes the backup generators also fail.\n\n3.  Need for Clean Air, Not Diesel Generator Emissions.\nThe blackout power problem gets compounded by California''s air quality problem and the use of polluting diesel generators to provide backup power, even for transient outages.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '200', 831, 'solutions/view/200', 'admin/solutions/edit/200', 'admin/solutions/delete/200'),
(878, '78. CarbonStory', 'There is growing awareness that climate change is a real threat and that something needs to be done to address the situation. Yet, to date it has been very difficult for people to do much about climate change without making radical back-to-nature changes to their lifestyles. We believe that there exists a significant proportion of people who would like to become part of the solution to climate change provided that they get an experience that is fun, engaging, affordable and socially rewarding. To address this situation, CarbonStory solves the below two problems for customers:\n   \n1) I want to do the right thing for future generations without having to compromise my current lifestyle. \n\n2) I want my efforts to be recognized by friends, family and people googling me on the web - I want to be seen as responsible and as someone who does the right thing.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '201', 833, 'solutions/view/201', 'admin/solutions/edit/201', 'admin/solutions/delete/201'),
(879, '79. Environmental Product Labels at Scale', 'In a sustainable economy all products will have environmental labels so that customers can learn to make sustainable choices and manufacturers can design and build sustainable products.  An Environmental Product Declaration (EPD) is a standardized (ISO 14025/TR) environmental label designed to meet this need.  EPDs mimic nutrition labels on food in that they provide the facts, but don’t offer any judgment as to the “greenness” of the product.  \nThe process for creating and verifying an EPD is manual, costly and not scalable. As a result industry leaders produce EPD’s at the product category level and not for individual products.  This is like giving the same nutrition label to all soft drinks or all laptop computers produced by a manufacturer.  Such labeling of product groups and not labeling individual products will ultimately render EPDs  ineffective for driving consumer choice and ultimately killing a foundation of the sustainable economy.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '202', 670, 'solutions/view/202', 'admin/solutions/edit/202', 'admin/solutions/delete/202'),
(881, '81. Beyond Sustainability—Regenerative Development', 'There is a growing movement of responsible world citizens who want to do more than simply “do less harm”. Sustainable development or ‘achieving a steady state’ is neutral or ‘100 per cent less bad’, is not good enough. We must do far more than limit the damage caused by our lives on this planet.\n\nThe World pop grew from 1.6 B in 1900, to 6 B by 2000. We need to think differently and plan intentionally for the next 100 years of human growth on this resilient planet, to assure that every person has access to the resources needed for work, play, shelter, energy, water, food, health and happiness.\n\nThe U.S. consumes enough natural resources to take up 4.1 Earths. The only reason we haven’t exceeded the Earth’s capacity to support its 7 B global pop is that the rest of the world is balancing out the U.S. by using a more sustainable percentage of the Earth’s resources. However, with the rise in population and the rapid industrialization of emerging countries that balance is in jeopardy.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '207', 810, 'solutions/view/207', 'admin/solutions/edit/207', 'admin/solutions/delete/207'),
(882, '82. Mountain View Cohousing Community', 'The aspirational housing of the U.S. is a single-family home that requires massive amounts of energy to build, maintain, and fill with furniture, appliances, and other lifestyle and status goods.   In the typical suburb, where the car is an extension of these houses, people must drive for business and social opportunities.  Worse, this “American dream” is being adopted globally as more people acquire the resources to duplicate it.\n\nIn addition to needing a more sustainable model for all, sustainable, healthy, and humanistic approaches are needed to house and support older adults, particularly in the U.S., where Baby Boomers are both aging and living longer than previous generations.  As we get older, the activities we once took for granted aren’t easy anymore: the house is too big to maintain; a grocery store or doctor visit is a major expedition; yet the alternative for many older adults is a facility that limits their independence, diminishing their mental health and quality of life.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '208', 829, 'solutions/view/208', 'admin/solutions/edit/208', 'admin/solutions/delete/208'),
(883, '83. Parking Charges + Incentives: Reduce Commuting by 23%', 'Solo drivers pay $2/day. Transit/carpool users receive $4/day. Solo commutes => 77% to 54%. Phased in gradually. \n******************  Leadership towards Kyoto targets requires US to implement serious transportation demand reduction policies. (CARB has no scenarios that meet 2035 reduction goals without demand reduction). European gas prices are roughly $8 per gallon. Per capita annual driving is one-third less than the US. The Moving Cooler Report agrees that a phased-in $5 per gallon gas tax increase will reduce US transportation GHG by 28%. No one contests that raising the cost of driving decreases the amount of driving. Politically, neither political party will suggest even a $0.05 gas tax increase.  Moving Cooler shows that expected increases in fuel economy cannot meet Kyoto objectives but must be combined with driving reduction. Proposed is a more politically palatable policy, implemented with cutting-edge technology.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '209', 819, 'solutions/view/209', 'admin/solutions/edit/209', 'admin/solutions/delete/209'),
(884, '84. Barrier-Crossing Transit for Cyclists and Pedestrians', 'Like many American cities, Milpitas is divided by physical barriers that make alternative transportation options challenging.  Cyclists, pedestrians, scooter kids, and others discover that railroad tracks, freeways and creeks are barriers to safe and convenient travel.  Spanning these barriers using standard steel-and-concrete bridges (known as Pedestrian Overcrossings or POCs) has become increasingly costly and difficult to site.  Finding an alternative, less expensive technology to bridge barriers will support all transportation alternatives.\n\nInstead of a static “dumb” bridge, try a “smart ferry” that could carry people and their stuff (bikes, wheelchairs, groceries, etc.) safely and conveniently over barriers.  People get on at one station and ride in a computer-controlled "podcar" to the station on the other side.  The “ferry” technology could be Personal Rapid Transit (PRT), a small, light-weight Disneyland-type of conveyance.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '210', 802, 'solutions/view/210', 'admin/solutions/edit/210', 'admin/solutions/delete/210'),
(885, '85. Energy-Saving of Office Building Lighting-orchestra (TM)', '21% of the total electric power consumed in buildings is consumed by lighting. When limited to working areas alone, this increases to 40%. Lighting is the single largest opportunity for improving energy efficiency in buildings. In addition, Japan’s plan to cut CO2 emissions by 2020 has an initial goal of reducing CO2 emissions from buildings by 31 million tons. Newly-constructed buildings are already equipped with energy-efficient air conditioners, elevators, escalators, and other energy efficient systems, so the immediate focus for this program is on how to expedite the renovation of existing structures and office buildings in particular.  This will be accomplished using Building Energy Management Systems (BEMS) that are designed to supervise the energy consumption of the entire building.  Our product, called Lighting Orchestra, is a powerful BEMS add-on that enables a dramatic reduction in lighting costs.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '211', 808, 'solutions/view/211', 'admin/solutions/edit/211', 'admin/solutions/delete/211'),
(886, '86. DIY Democracy--Key to a Sustainable Planet', 'The US Congress is failing to meet the challenges of 21st century democracy, including planetary sustainability.  In order to make policy on complex, "big picture" issues,  two oversight functions of the legislative process must be re-engineered: expertise and deliberation.  Our president has declared that we must do something about "the destructive power of a warming planet."  Realizing this priority on Capitol Hill, however, will require a new participatory approach that takes advantage of  big data, citizen science, network technology and recently mandated transparency requirements across government. Today,  knowledge management tasks critical for oversight in Congress can be distributed outside of Capitol Hill. This system wide realignment will modernize our democracy and create a powerful constituency  for evidence based decision making.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '212', 823, 'solutions/view/212', 'admin/solutions/edit/212', 'admin/solutions/delete/212'),
(887, '88. EV ARC™ (Electric Vehicle Autonomous Renewable Charger) Station', 'EV’s produce zero tail-pipe emissions, however, in regions that depend heavily on conventional fossil fuels for electricity generation, EV’s may not demonstrate a life cycle emissions benefit over conventional vehicles. There is a simple solution: solar energy generation. Solar energy is clean, free, and abundant. The drawback is that you need to build an infrastructure to capture and store the energy, so that EV’s can charge using this clean, renewable energy source. Typically building an infrastructure takes a lot of time, money, and maneuvering through bureaucratic roadblocks to accomplish. \nThe power grid isn’t the answer either. Street transformers are designed to cool down at night and if EV owners plug-in at the same time, these transformers won’t have a chance to cool. This can cause the transformer wires to melt, causing a short, and blacking out the local load it serves. We can anticipate these types of problems, but wouldn’t it be best to find a way to avoid them?', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '216', 713, 'solutions/view/216', 'admin/solutions/edit/216', 'admin/solutions/delete/216'),
(888, '89. Project ME4', 'Project ME4 addresses three problems:  gaps in emergency response infrastructure, gaps in education, and gaps in affordable enterprise.  \n     Project ME4 is designed to demonstrate the flexibility and capability of mobile solar generators in a program that uses the generator as an education and outreach vehicle that can literally be in several places each day of the week, performing in different capacities in each case.  \n     With one flexible platform, a 2.5kW mobile solar generator, Project ME4 addresses three distinct yet related areas.  Area 1 is disaster preparedness with a solar generator designed for rapid emergency response to provide the key critical services of power, water and communications when and where needed.  Area 2 is education and outreach for one or more groups for the majority of time when the system is not deployed for emergencies.  Area 3 is active development of enterprises based on mobile solar power generation.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '217', 577, 'solutions/view/217', 'admin/solutions/edit/217', 'admin/solutions/delete/217'),
(889, '90. StartupNectar, the Biomimicry Incubator', 'StartupNectar is a systemic solution solving multiple problems within our current systems - economic, ecological, and social. \n\nMuch of our current economic activity and market solutions produce a level of negative externalities that are at best affecting our health, shaping the global socio-economic landscape towards increasing inequity, having an impact on other species on our planet, and at worst threatening our existence due to climate change linked to standard practices within our current economy. By emulating nature''s strategies and 3.8 billion years of R&D, Biomimicry is a science-based resource for creating products and human systems in line with how all living systems on our planet function.\n\nProjected economic impact of biomimicry by 2025:\n$300 billion annually of U.S. gross domestic product\n1.6 million U.S. jobs \n$50 billion in mitigating natural resource depletion and reducing C02 pollution\n$1 trillion of global GDP', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '218', 407, 'solutions/view/218', 'admin/solutions/edit/218', 'admin/solutions/delete/218'),
(890, '91. ECOR® The intelligent use of cellulose fiber', 'The problem is that petroleum and wood resources are becoming scarce, more expensive, and the negative environmental effects of their acquisition and use are known to be extreme.  Particleboard, plywood and medium density fiberboard are used to create panel products used in the building, furniture and package markets.  These products use virgin lumber, wood byproduct raw materials, and their adhesives and binders are mostly petroleum-based.\n\nThe alternative is ECOR®, a material made of cellulose fibers from an almost infinite variety of sources including cardboard, paper, newsprint and agricultural fibers from anaerobic digesters, kenaf, hemp, wheat straw, sugarcane bagasse and many others.  ECOR® transforms this waste into a 100% bio-based material that can be used in building, furniture, packaging and many other markets, replacing the need to use virgin lumber and petroleum.  ECOR® is manufactured in a CLEAN facility using recycled water and no gas.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '219', 725, 'solutions/view/219', 'admin/solutions/edit/219', 'admin/solutions/delete/219'),
(891, '92. Patrizia''s Sustainability Synthesis- a sustainable decision-making framework', 'Teach individuals, business, corporations, and government officials how to make sustainable decisions using Patrizia''s Sustainability Synthesis', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '220', 834, 'solutions/view/220', 'admin/solutions/edit/220', 'admin/solutions/delete/220'),
(892, '93. Greening the Chambers Initiative', 'Local Chambers of Commerce are vital hubs for their local communities, and here in Silicon Valley they help power a global growth engine.  The green business revolution, however, is sadly lacking and in fact being actively harmed at the top by the US Chamber of Commerce, which has an anti-green business agenda due to the US Chamber''s rejection of basic climate science and of the need for climate solutions provided in part by green businesses.\n\nGreen businesses need to take greater involvement and leadership within local Chambers.  The local Chambers need to use their great influence and community respect for local environmental needs.  The US Chamber needs to learn, in ways that it will not forget, that it cannot continue its policy of harm to the green business sector.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '221', 831, 'solutions/view/221', 'admin/solutions/edit/221', 'admin/solutions/delete/221'),
(893, '94. Mission: Resiliency -- the Game That Grows in your Community', 'The New Language of Sustainability – Risk and Resilience, is the title of a keynote conversation at this year’s “GreenBiz Forum”.  Indeed, Hurricane Katrina and Superstorm Sandy have left a big mark on our coastal regions and our understanding of the dynamic disruptions caused by climate change. Extreme weather patterns quickly overwhelm our past engineering prowess and our physical and cultural infrastructures that were designed for a no-longer-valid set of assumptions. Communities will need to adapt to significant and unforeseen economic, environmental and social changes.  Our ability to survive and thrive will depend on our resilience and creativity. Collaborative innovation is not readily created or nurtured in a top-down only manner.  Government is frequently too slow and inflexible in the face of crisis while private sector entities are constrained by their business models.  We can help communities create a foundation for developing innovative resilience.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '222', 540, 'solutions/view/222', 'admin/solutions/edit/222', 'admin/solutions/delete/222'),
(894, '95. Envision Solar Tree® Structure', 'There are over 800 million parking spaces in the U.S. and enough solar energy strikes these parking lots each day to power U.S. transportation demands three times over! In just six hours, the world’s deserts receive more energy from the sun than humans consume in a year. The installation of Solar Tree® structures is a promising industry advance; however, getting projects through entitlement fast and efficiently provides a challenge. Additionally, the serious dearth of available EV Charging Infrastructure provides an opportunity for creative technology advancement. Innovative renewables storage solutions will allow for islanded EV charging stations to operate 24 hours a day without trenches, foundations, or grid connection. The electric grid in the US is already so strained that many of us experience black and brown outs regularly due to excessive loads; this is occurring before EV’s even hit the mainstream. Renewable Energy today powers less than 1% of the EV Charging Stations in use.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '223', 713, 'solutions/view/223', 'admin/solutions/edit/223', 'admin/solutions/delete/223'),
(895, '96. Net-Zero Non-Potable Water Strategy: On-Site Storm and Wastewater Treatment', 'As human population and industry have grown, so have demands on natural resources making water supply and water pollution issues one of the most critical environmental concerns for this generation.  Although treatment methods have improved, the standard model of collect-treat-discharge for wastewater has not changed in over 100 years. From a sustainability perspective, this status quo method for dealing with our ever-growing water problems cannot endure. \n\nThe nationâ€™s aging wastewater management systems discharge billions of gallons of untreated sewage in U.S. surface waters each year, disturbing aquatic habitats.  As our population grows, the facilities that treat this water will expand, intruding into natural areas.  And, 99% of potable water is over treated, contributing to a carbon footprint that is approximately 20% of national stationary energy use.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '228', 835, 'solutions/view/228', 'admin/solutions/edit/228', 'admin/solutions/delete/228'),
(896, '97. High performance shrouded wind turbine, "Wind-lens" turbine', 'The fraction of wind energy against the total of worldwide energy supply can grow up to 10 percent by 2050. To contribute a continuous and smooth transition without losing momentum, our research team at RIAM considers the following problems as the opportunities for the innovative solution we provide.\n\nProblem 1: Conventional wind power farms require strong wind (6 meter/second or greater) in order to economically provide stable supply of electricity.  And there are many areas in the world where the average annual wind speed is less than this.\n\nProblem 2: Wind turbine causes acoustic noise that is harmful to people and animals, especially when the generator is set up in or near the urban or the residential areas, or the farm areas near animals.\n\nProblem 3: Bird strikes.  Currently the number of birds killed by wind turbines is not huge.  But this is expected to grow as more wind power generators will be installed. Bird strikes may also damage the turbines.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '231', 836, 'solutions/view/231', 'admin/solutions/edit/231', 'admin/solutions/delete/231'),
(897, '98. The Green Ninja', 'Although climate change is one of the most important issues society faces today, most children know very little about the subject and their teachers are often underprepared to incorporate these topics into their classes. The soon to be adopted Next Generation Science Standards are a new framework that for the first time includes anthropogenic climate change topics at various grade levels.  The challenge remains that the teachers who will be asked to adopt these new standards will need additional professional development and appropriate learning materials to present these topics to their students.  Thus there is a pressing need to develop innovative and effective learning materials to bring climate change and sustainability topics to young children and their teachers.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '232', 800, 'solutions/view/232', 'admin/solutions/edit/232', 'admin/solutions/delete/232'),
(898, '99. A mobile biochar producing vehicle.', 'The problem is green house gas overload, depleted, overworked soil and dependence on dirty fossil fuels. Biochar and the by-products of its creation can help with all three. \n\nWith a mobile unit I hope to provide a service to farms, orchards, vineyards etc, that want to use  the biochar produced from what otherwise may be wasted cuttngs, brush etc. to amend their soil and increase fertility, thereby increasing crop yield. \n\nThe syngas and bio oil produced may also be used by the location as fuel to power equipment, and to produce heat for greenhouses, and barns.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '233', 313, 'solutions/view/233', 'admin/solutions/edit/233', 'admin/solutions/delete/233'),
(899, '100. Spaceship Earth Mission Control', 'Climate Change is under way bringing changing weather patterns, extreme weather events and sea level rise. A mass extinction of Earth’s plants and animals is ongoing due to climate change, habitat loss, invasive species and pollution.  The United Nations report GEO-5 Assessment of 2012 warns that “the earth''s environmental systems are being pushed towards their biophysical limits and that sudden, irreversible and potentially catastrophic changes are looming," a press release for the report states. (CBS/AP, Rio de Janeiro, June 6, 2012)  Consensus about climate change is building.    But now many people wonder “what can we do?”  Students face this dire news about the trend of their future environment on a daily basis.  We can provide them with information and knowledge and as many tools as possible to assist them in responding to this challenge.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '234', 804, 'solutions/view/234', 'admin/solutions/edit/234', 'admin/solutions/delete/234'),
(900, '101. Hastening Electric Vehicle Adoption Through Conversion', 'In California, motor vehicles account for about 40 percent of the state’s greenhouse gas emissions. Automobile manufacturers, both old and new, have been gearing up to produce hybrid, electric, and plug-in vehicles to try to address the problem. But what about the many people who cannot afford to upgrade to a hybrid, electric, or plug-in vehicle, or who simply do not want to buy a new car? What are their options?', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '235', 837, 'solutions/view/235', 'admin/solutions/edit/235', 'admin/solutions/delete/235'),
(901, '102. iAct Dialogues for Sustainability', 'A global and intergenerational approach to integrated online and in-person engagement that promotes discussion of and action on seemingly intractable sustainability challenges has not yet been leveraged to its fullest potential.  We see this as an unprecedented opportunity to bring people together to discuss conservation and development challenges and solutions, gain clarity and build capacity for action, and share successes to inspire further action.\n\nAs described below, the iAct Dialogues for Sustainability provide a dynamic platform and network that dovetails with Sustainable Silicon Valley’s (SSV’s) “Showcase of Solutions for Planetary Sustainability,” offering an avenue for identified solutions to be further discussed within a global network, and adapted and applied at regional and local scales.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '236', 769, 'solutions/view/236', 'admin/solutions/edit/236', 'admin/solutions/delete/236'),
(902, '103. Glass Bay - Mendocino', 'Fort Bragg (FB) in a coastal city in Mendocino county California, known for un spoilt natural beauty, which is why tourism is a major earner. However tourism is not enough.\nFort Bragg CA is a city in socio economic decline. Because of insufficient economic activity to create jobs, production and circulation of capital. \n\nProblem:  A major reason for the economic stagnation is due to closure of the largest employer and production giant, “The Lumber Mill”.  The Mill Site is 400 acres of prime sea front land incorporated in 1891. The mill was shut down in 2002 by Georgia Pacific (GP).\n\nOpportunity: The public of Fort Bragg has embraced the mill site as the future of Fort Bragg. The city has bought part of the land. City residents are congruent about seeing it develop into a “destination” for sustainable investors and organizations who develop these 400 acres of prime waterfront into a eco smart model of business and residence.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '237', 763, 'solutions/view/237', 'admin/solutions/edit/237', 'admin/solutions/delete/237'),
(903, '104. AstroSolar: Solar energy and science comes together', 'Imagine a small telescope that observes the sky at night and generates solar electric energy during the day more efficiently than most solar systems available on the market. This is AstroSolar!\n\nImagine children and adults observing, learning, and dreaming about the universe and other worlds around nearby stars, while at the same time watching and learning how the light from our own star can be used to generate solar energy with the same telescope. Isn’t it cool?\n\nI see this concept as an opportunity to motivate children and adults about science and engineering and to showcase the potential of technology to achieve more sustainable development. In particular, atomized energy generation solutions that aim for smaller personal carbon footprints are often not interesting for people. This project tackles this problem by converting advanced photovoltaic generation in a fun tool, allowing people to learn about science and see direct applications for sustainable energy.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '238', 781, 'solutions/view/238', 'admin/solutions/edit/238', 'admin/solutions/delete/238'),
(904, '105. Find most functional on-board generation of volatile gases for converting gas vehicles.', 'Hydrogen gas is a clean burning fuel but it has possible harmful environmental consequences if from the wrong source that involves releasing long-time stored greenhouse gases or even if generated on mass at centralized locations and then transported, leading to inadvertent release into the atmosphere where it could add to the threat of climate change by further increasing the already growing noctilucent clouds.  However, if hydrogen gas and/or other simple volatile gases could be generated from a water compound that could be stored as a liquid and then immediately burned to run an engine it could avoid much of the dangers.', NULL, NULL, 'solutions', 'solutions:solution', 'solutions:solutions', '240', 741, 'solutions/view/240', 'admin/solutions/edit/240', 'admin/solutions/delete/240'),
(944, 'Integrated Reporting', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	Transformational Results From Using Integrated Reporting\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	With the recent update of SAP’s preliminary sustainability results for 2012 and the impending release of their first ever Integrated Report&nbsp;for 2012,&nbsp;we sat down to speak with SAP’s Chief Sustainability Officer Dr. Peter Graf. Dr. Graf talks about how Integrated Reporting&nbsp;&lt;IR&gt;&nbsp;is transformational in driving integrated thinking not only for the company’s sustainability strategy but also for the overall corporate strategy. From his experience, he believes &lt;IR&gt;&nbsp;is important for any company interested in driving sustainability into the heart of their business.\n\n	\n\n	What would you like to tell us about &lt;IR&gt; and SAP’s sustainability strategy?\n\n	Peter Graf: Integrated Reporting &lt;IR&gt; needs to be seen as part of the wider strategy that SAP had embarked on when we made sustainability a strategic priority to the business back in 2009. At that point, we had separate strategies: A sustainability strategy, a product strategy, a go-to-market strategy, a people strategy, etc. It became clear that even if we executed our sustainability strategy very successfully we would still only represent one of the many different aspects of the business competing for attention from our senior management.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	So when the &lt;IR&gt; initiative started with the IIRC, we initially thought that an integrated report would be a great way to describe an integrated strategy -- once you have one. In other words, our belief was that we first had to put a lot of work into getting everyone on board and only then be able to articulate an integrated strategy, which would eventually lead to an integrated report.. We then recognized that we were wrong.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	How it works:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	PG:&nbsp;An integrated report combines elements of what you would put into an annual report with things you would put into a sustainability report. This combination is more than just the sum of the data in both reports: The real value of an integrated report is to actually explain the interdependencies between your financial performance indicators and your non-financial performance indicators.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Toward the middle of 2012, while talking to people who actually engage in &lt;IR&gt;,I learned that one shouldn’t wait until everyone is convinced of an integrated strategy that would flow into an integrated report. Instead, we recognized that the creation of the integrated report itself is the required catalyst to drive integrated thinking and an integrated strategy. That was an extremely valuable recognition.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Looking forward:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	PG:&nbsp;We are currently in the final preparations of our integrated report for 2012 which will be our first time ever. The expectations are high because SAP has always had so much recognition for its sustainability reports in the past. Our report has been acknowledged by readers at many different publications and we’ve received many awards as one of the top sustainability reports in the world. So we hope many people will take a look at our integrated report as well.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Impact of &lt;IR&gt; within the company:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	PG:&nbsp;The experience of creating an integrated report leads to a whole variety of different conversations throughout the company. In line with what &lt;IR&gt; is about, those conversations were about the long-term view of the business and how practicing sustainability and related non-financial indicators actually help us understand how we can be more financially successful in the future. This led to conversations with our investor relations team, with our finance and administration organizations, with HR and many other teams – conversations on a very different and more strategic level.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Recommendation for businesses setting up a sustainability strategy:\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	PG: I would recommend to anybody trying to move from having a sustainability strategy to a more sustainable corporate strategy to consider using the creation of an integrated report as the catalyst to drive integrated thinking. In other words, even if you don’t think your company is ready for an integrated report yet, I’d rather try it sooner than later because of the level of strategic engagement integrated reporting produces within your organization.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	(This interview has been edited to group together but is otherwise as-told-to Aswathy Dayanand)\n \n	&nbsp;\n\n	You might also want to read :\n\n	What is IIRC and &nbsp;&lt;Integrated Reporting&gt;?\n\n	What is Global Reporting Initiative?\n\n	Coca-Cola 2011/2012 GRI Report\n\n	Microsoft and GRI\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '146', NULL, 'topics/systemic/frameworks/integrated-reporting', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/146', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/146'),
(932, 'Materials', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	Welcome to the materials page. &nbsp;Our goal is to connect you with the knowledge &amp; resources you need to develop sustainable practices in your materials management. &nbsp;We are working to compile the best information available and describe our findings. &nbsp;Allowing you to focus on implementing the changes that will move your business, local government agency or community organization forward. &nbsp;\n\n	How our site works\n\n	Our team constantly researches topics regarding sustainable materials management giving you a head start in implementing change\n\n	We have organized our research into 6 sections to clarify our findings\n\n	The site is collaborative, we look forward to your questions and constructive feedback to increase the site''s effectiveness\n\n	Each section includes\n\n	\n		\n			core knowledge&nbsp;explaining fundamental principles&nbsp;\n	\n	\n		\n			success stories to inspire and foster innovation&nbsp;\n	\n	\n		\n			tools to help you get the job done&nbsp;\n	\n	\n		\n			news &amp; developments so you stay in the loop\n	\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	By reaching this site you are taking an important step towards sutainability. Just incase you need a little more of a push, here is a quick run down of reasons why you will want to move forward to develop a better understanding of your materials and processes.&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Save money&nbsp;\n\n	\n		More than $231 million back into Walmart U.S. in 2011 by increaseing recycling revenue and decreasing disposal expenses\n	\n		Research by consultancy McKinsey, found European manufacturers could save $630 billion a year by 2025 if they moved towards greater resource efficiency and reduced their reliance on increasingly rare and costly raw materials\n\n\n	Reduce Green House Gas Emmissions\n\n	\n		Safeway prevents the release of 37,518 metric tons of CO2&nbsp;in 2011 by shipping produce items from warehouses to stores in reusable plastic containers instead of cardboard boxes\n	\n		Apple reduced its iPhone packaging by 42%, allowing them to fit 80% more product into each airline shipping container to reduce air transportation\n\n\n	Brand Image &amp; Coporate Responsibility\n\n	\n		method ranked as the 7th fastest growing company in America by INC. 500 in 2006. &nbsp;Also one of the first companies to be cradle to cradle certified in 2009 with 37 certified products at launch. &nbsp;Coincidence?\n\n\n	Adapting to Legislation\n\n	\n		AB341 to reduce GHG emissions by diverting commercial solid waste to recycling efforts and to expand the opportunity for additional recycling services and recycling manufacturing facilities in California\n	\n		EPA workgroup writes paper "Sustainable Materials Management: The Road Ahead," presenting their ideas to move future legislation towards accelerating a life-cycle consideration of materials and more producer responsibility\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n		&nbsp;\n\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '22', NULL, 'topics/materials', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/22', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/22');
