(952, 'CISCO', ' \n	Cisco Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Founded in 1984, Cisco designs and sells networking solutions related to the information and communication technology industry to public sector organizations, enterprise business, commercial customers, and consumers. Cisco’s headquarters are located in San Jose, California and they have more than 475 offices in more than 165 countries and more than 66,000 employees globally. They state their mission as “To shape the future of the internet by creating unprecedented value and opportunity for customers, employees, investors, and partners.”&nbsp;&nbsp; They apply their goal of innovation and their mission to their sustainable practices and goals as well.\n\n	Awards, Listings, and Frameworks\n\n	Awards and Recognitions\n\n	\n		2012: Cool IT Challenge (#2), Greenpeace International\n	\n		2012: Best Corporate Citizenship Award to Cisco China, 21st Century Business Herald\n	\n		2012: Outstanding Corporate Citizenship Award to Cisco China, China Philanthropy Times under the Minister of Civil Affairs\n	\n		2012: Outstanding CSR Case Studies Award to Cisco China, China Philanthropy Times under the Minister of Civil Affairs\n	\n		2012: Outstanding Corporate Leader of 2012, Sustainability Roundtable, Inc.\n	\n		January 2011: Green Business Award, Cisco Lawrenceville, Gwinnett Clean and Beautiful\n	\n		2011: Silver “Green Binnie” Award, Cisco Boxborough, MassRecycle\n	\n		2010: Best Green Business Award, Gwinnett County\n	\n		2010: Greater Austin Business Award, for environmental responsibility, Austin Texas Chamber of Commerce\n	\n		2010: Best Green PR Campaign, PR News, Cisco Canada\n	\n		2010: Outstanding waste reduction efforts recognition, California Waste Reduction Awards Program (WRAP)\n	\n		2010: Silicon Valley Water Conservation Award, California\n	\n		2010: Gold LEED Certification, Cisco Building 14, Bangalore, India\n	\n		2010: Buildy Award, for smart building and connected infrastructure innovations,&nbsp;BuilConn\n	\n		2010: Best of Interop Green Award, for Cisco Energywise, Las Vegas Interop and Best of Interop Japan &nbsp;\n	\n		2010: Gold Quill Award, for video series that inspired employees to think and act in environmentally sustainable ways, International Association of Business Communicators.\n\n\n	Rankings\n\n	\n		2012: 50 Best Green Global Brands (#11), Interbrand\n	\n		2012: World’s Most Ethical Companies, Ethisphere Institute\n	\n		2012: Gartner Supply Chain 25 (#8), Gartner\n	\n		2011: America''s Top 10 Greenest Companies&nbsp;(#8), Forbes\n	\n		2010: One of America’s 10 Greenest Companies, Forbes\n	\n		2010: Green Power Purchasers (#6), US EPA List\n\n\n	Listings\n\n	\n		2012: Dow Jones Sustainability World and North America Indices, Dow Jones and SAM\n	\n		2012: FTSE4Good Index Series, FTSE International and Ethical Research Services\n\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	\n		2012: Global Reporting Initiative\n	\n		2012: Carbon Disclosure Project, Carbon Performance Leadership Index (CPLI)\n	\n		2010: Clinton Global Initiative\n	\n		2010: UN Global Compact\n	\n		2010: UN Millennium Development Goals\n	\n		2010: World Economic Forum\n\n\n	Sustainable Actions\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	\n		Cisco built new green data centers in the Research Triangle Park, North Carolina in early FY 2012\n	\n		By the end of FY 2012, 26 Cisco facilities had LEED certifications (17 are Gold or Platinum status)\n	\n		Cisco developed the “Cisco Connected Workplace”, a new space organization with mobile desktops to prevent the use of fix cubicles, which are vacant 35% of the time at Cisco. In a “Cisco Connected Workplace”, 140 employees work comfortably where 88 would work in a traditional workplace design. The goal is to improve productivity, employee satisfaction, increase user density in the building, and save real estate costs\n		\n			\n				By the end of FY12, Cisco Connected Workplace represented 19.5% of Cisco’s Total Office Space.\n		\n	\n	\n		Cisco has a 20.4 acre parcel of land that is a protected habitat for the burrowing owl and a rare plant species (Congdon’s Tarplant)\n		\n			\n				Cisco developed and implemented a wetland migration plan that created 0.77 acres of wetlands in the habitat preserve area and established a 5-year monitoring and maintenance program\n			\n				Implementing a burrowing owl mitigation plan that required preconstruction surveys and the installation of 12 artificial burrows in the habitat preserve\n				\n					\n						Locating grazing cattle in this habitat preserve as a method of weed abatement and soil compaction to help facilitate wetlands establishment.\n				\n			\n		\n	\n	\n		Partnered with Bon Appétit Management Company as their “Farm to Fork” program promotes local farming and supports sustainable farming and harvesting techniques\n\n\n	Water\n\n	\n		Cisco uses irrigation controllers at San Jose main campus, recycled water for irrigation, installed variable-frequency drives in their cooling towers and two way valves for bathroom fixtures, converted decorative fountains into landscaped beds for drought-resistant plants, utilized a water harvesting system at their Bangalore, India campus to capture rainwater for filtering and use, and replaced turf with planter beds that require little water\n	\n		In FY12 Cisco integrated a new Sustainability Information System that greatly improved their ability to track water consumption data for a majority of their real estate operations.\n		\n			\n				In FY 2012, Cisco was able to collect water use data for 71% of their total real estate portfolio by area\n		\n	\n\n\n	Energy\n\n	\n		100% of Cisco’s contract manufacturers, 93% of global transport providers, and 80% of their component suppliers responded to the CDP 2012 survey\n	\n		Cisco is phasing into the SIS (sustainability information system) and has incorporated Source 1 and Source 2 data and anticipates adding Scope 3 in the next phase\n	\n		Cisco has designed a way to use a company network as a center for energy intelligence: the Cisco EnergyWise System. Cisco has installed over 5,000 EnergyWise compliant power distribution units and has identified over $5 million energy savings potential\n	\n		Cisco’s average (gross) electricity emission factor for both its global facilities and data centers are 14% and 15% lower than the global average, respectively\n		\n			\n				Due to the fact that Cisco has located the majority of its facilities in grid locations where low-carbon to no-carbon grid electricity is available\n			\n				Through their energy reduction strategy Cisco estimates that in FY 2012 they conserved around 15.6 million kWh of energy and avoided 7,300 metric ton CO2 emissions through a $1.6 million investment in energy conservation projects\n		\n	\n	\n		In FY 2011 and 2012 Cisco installed solar PV systems at two data centers\n		\n			\n				These systems produced 270,000 kWh of electricity, saved Cisco $16,000 and avoided 170 metric ton of CO2e of GHG emissions\n		\n	\n	\n		In FY 2012, Cisco purchased 457 million kWh of Renewable Energy Certificates (RECs) by Green-e and 94 million kWh through various European green power suppliers\n	\n		Cisco is working to get its most efficient products qualified with the U.S. EPA Energy Star program\n	\n		In FY12, started a project to install a 425 kW cogeneration system on its campus in Bedfront Lakes, UK.\n		\n			\n				System is expected to reduce GHG emissions by more than 704 metric tonne of CO2 per year\n		\n	\n	\n		Cisco Green Data Center – Allen, Texas\n		\n			\n				Uninterruptable power supply (UPS) room uses rotary flywheels, which require little energy to be kept in motion\n			\n				Cooled by an air-side economizer design that reduces the need for mechanical chilling by using ambient air when the outside temperature is low\n			\n				A lagoon captures water to irrigate the drought-resistant landscape plants\n			\n				Solar cells on the roof generate 100 kW of power for the office spaces in the building\n			\n				LEED Gold certification renewed in FY 2012\n		\n	\n	\n		Cisco Green Data Center, Research Triangle Park, North Carolina\n		\n			\n				Select Features: Chimney rack hot-air isolation for improved cooling efficiency, 100kW solar photovoltaic cells on building roof, LED exterior lighting, reclaimed water use in cooling towers, occupancy sensors integrated with lighting and temperature controls, and landfill diversion during construction.\n			\n				Designed to achieve a Power Usage Effectiveness of 1.35 at full load\n			\n				Achieved a Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) – NC Gold Certification\n		\n	\n	\n		Cisco’s Bangalore data center has received one of the highest-rated Platinum LEED ID+C scores in the world (96 points)\n\n\n	Materials\n\n	\n		Deployed sustainability criteria in business scorecards for all contract manufacturers, logistic partners, and preferred component suppliers\n	\n		Provide sustainability training to supplier-facing employees\n	\n		Most of their documentation vendors are Forest Stewardship Council certified\n	\n		Cisco connects customers with their take-back suppliers who bring trade-in products back to Cisco where they can be refurbished, resold, or reused if possible\n	\n		More than 99% of the electronics sent to their e-scrap recyclers are recycled\n	\n		In their packaging initiatives, Cisco reduced 757,000 pounds of paper and plastic usage and increased the overall packaging efficiency rates for some of their Catalyst 3750 products by 6.7%\n		\n			\n				In total, reduced 466 metric ton of corrugated cardboard, plastic, and paper in their shipment in FY 2012\n			\n				Cisco products use recyclable polyethylene bags for protection and accessory kits subassembly consolidation\n			\n				All mechanical parts greater than 100 grams are made of one material, for ease of separation later on\n			\n				Plastic parts greater than 25 grams are designed with material coding so they can be easily identified at the recycler\n			\n				All plastic parts are free of metal inlays and can be separated with common tools, improving recyclability.\n		\n	\n	\n		Cisco Technical Migration and Exceptional Pick-Up Program: Cisco has trade-in programs where customers can bring back used technology to Cisco and will receive a discount on their new purchases in return\n		\n			\n				Customer can set up appointment with Cisco to have their old electronics picked up for recycling/reuse&nbsp;\n		\n	\n	\n		In FY 2012, Cisco reused over $286 million of Cisco equipment, calculated at standard cost\n	\n		Take-Back and Recycle program focuses on Cisco products that do not qualify for a trade-in program. Cisco also takes back competitor equipment that consumers have replaced with new Cisco products\n		\n			\n				These objects go to a Cisco-approved recycling site\n			\n				Cisco tries to use an “eco-pack” packaging solution for high-volume products that has been shown to reduce total packaging weight by up to 2% compared to single-packaging option, which makes a difference on high volume shipments\n		\n	\n	\n		Cisco has an internal waste program, eBin/Lab Scrap Program, at the San Jose campus\n		\n			\n				eBins’s are plastic rolling bins provided to employees in their lab where materials are collected for recycling.&nbsp; The employee makes an appointment with the recycler to have the waste picked up in exchange for a new bin\n			\n				Cisco Data Center Server Recycling Program serves data centers in 12 countries, when data is no longer needed at one center it is offered to other Cisco data centers for possible reuse\n			\n				San Jose campus diverted 713 metric tons of food waste that would have been sent to a landfill in FY 2012\n		\n	\n\n\n	Transportation\n\n	\n		Cisco encourages employees to use mass transit systems by allowing eligible employees to use pre-tax money to purchase their mass-transit passes\n	\n		By the end of 2011, Cisco had installed 23 EV charging stations\n	\n		Cisco is working towards replacing physical travel by using Cisco remote collaboration products such as TelePresence, WebEx, and MeetingPlace\n		\n			\n				Worldwide use of TelePresence has stayed steady at just under 50% based on an 8-hour day\n		\n	\n	\n		In FY 2012, air-travel emissions have dropped more than 30% compared to FY 2007\n	\n		Cisco has contributed towards saving 4415 gallons of fuel, $11,204 in fuel costs, and 23,622 pounds of CO2e in GHG emissions as a result of their EV stations\n	\n		In FY 2012, Cisco started a bike-sharing program at its Research Triangle Park location, North Carolina\n	\n		Cisco has provided employees with products such as Remote Collaboration and Cisco Virtual Office in order to reduce the amount of commuting they do\n\n\n	Partnerships Around Sustainability\n\n	\n		Planet Skin Institute (Cisco and NASA)\n		\n			\n				Global non-profit research and development organization that aims to improve the lives of people around the world by developing risk and resource management decision services\n		\n	\n	\n		U.S. EPA’s Green Power Partnership.\n		\n			\n				As of July 2012, Cisco was listed 16th among the National Top 50 and 11th among Fortune 500 companies\n		\n	\n	\n		Participated in the development of the Greenhouse Gas Protocol Scope 3 and GHGP Product accounting standards led by the World Resources Institute and the World Business Council for Sustainable Development\n\n\n	Sustainability-Related Services\n\n	\n		In FY 2012, about 96% of new products incorporated design-for-environment principles through the product requirements template\n	\n		Cisco has implemented company-wide information and training events such as Virtual Earth Day and video-on-demand classes\n	\n		Cisco has an internal, quarterly newsletter that summarizes Cisco’s environmental activities for their employees called Think Green\n	\n		Sponsors civil councils that allow employees to volunteer in their local communities on social or environmental related programs\n	\n		Once a year, Cisco employees can bring in used electronics to have them recycled using the same vendors and processes used in Cisco’s business\n	\n		Cisco is working to cut the power used by its Application-Specific Integrated Circuits (ASICs) used in most Cisco products. In lab tests, these modifications to the circuit have been shown to reduce energy consumption by 10 – 30%\n	\n		Cisco products such as TelePresence and Webex foster virtual communication and collaboration.\n	\n		Cisco data center virtualization technologies significantly reduce the number of data center components.\n	\n		Cisco has included a requirement that their power supplies be at least 85% efficient.\n\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	\n		Tae Yoo – Cisco’s Senior Vice President of Corporate Affairs\n		\n			\n				Handles business surrounding the CSR report\n		\n	\n	\n		Sustainable Business Practice Team\n	\n		Global Energy Management and Sustainability Team\n	\n		Eco-Board is an executive level forum to ratify strategy and goals, share best practices, and provide opportunities for employee education, awareness, and engagement\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals\n\n	\n		Goal: Partner with suppliers to identify and realize sustainability improvements in FY 2013\n	\n		Goal: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to complete Cisco’s supplier sustainability survey in FY 2013\n	\n		Goal: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to report their GHG emissions to the CDP in FY 2013\n	\n		Goal: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to have goals in place to reduce their GHG emissions and report their progress towards goals in FY 2015\n	\n		Goal: Get 100% of preferred suppliers to report Cisco’s share in their GHG emissions by end of FY 2015&nbsp;\n	\n		Goal: Get 100% of manufacturing partners to publish a CSR in FY 2013\n	\n		Goal: Get 75% of logistics providers to publish a CSR report in FY 2013\n	\n		Goal: 100% of Cisco’s supplier managers will complete web-based training on sustainability in FY 2013\n	\n		Goal: Roll out EnergyWise- enabled power distribution units in Cisco engineering labs worldwide\n	\n		Goal: Expand the quantity and usage of installed EV charging stations\n	\n		Goal: Incorporate Scope 3 (air travel data) data into the SIS system\n	\n		Goal: Move all GHG emissions, air travel, and sustainability data to a new, enterprise-wide sustainability information system (SIS)\n	\n		&nbsp;Challenge: Prevent electricity emission factors from increasing as Cisco grows in energy markets where low carbon and no-carbon electricity is not readily available\n\n\n	Best Practices/Success Drivers\n\n	\n		Cisco’s ISO 14001 certified cites are audited by an independent third party\n	\n		Cisco has used dematerialization projects to identify and remove unnecessary items associated with their shipment of products\n		\n			\n				Pointer card (directs people to web link) to replace accessory kits\n		\n	\n	\n		Getting suppliers engaged with sustainability practices (i.e. completing CSR, reporting to CDP)\n	\n		Cisco EnergyWise System\n	\n		Cisco Connected Workplace\n	\n		Cisco Virtual Office\n\n\n	Researched and Prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	References\n\n	http://www.cisco.com/web/about/citizenship/reports/pdfs/CSR-Report-2012-Full-Report.pdf\n\n	http://csr.cisco.com/pages/csr-awards-2012\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '148', NULL, 'topics/cisco', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/148', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/148'),
(953, 'Adobe', ' \n	&nbsp;\n\n	\n	ADOBE’s Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Adobe is a software company that specializes in digital marketing and digital media solutions that help businesses meet online publishing challenges. Adobe''s headquarter is located in San Jose, California.&nbsp;The company originated in Palo Alto, California in 1982. As of 2011, Adobe has 9,022 employees working in their offices around the world. 4,982 of those employees are located in the United States and Canada, and the other 4,040 are located in other countries. There are currently 26 Adobe offices in operation around the world. The company reports to the Carbon Disclosure Project and outlines their sustainability efforts in their Corporate Social Responsibility reports. According to their company website, their mission statement is:\n\n	“At Adobe, we believe a creative world sustains itself, we continue to strive to exceed industry certification standards and maximize efficiency with cutting-edge technology all while empowering employees to create a culture of environmental sustainability, it is adobe living its values”\n\n	Awards/Frameworks and Accomplishments\n\n	Awards\n\n	National:\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2005 Environmental Project of the Year Award, Association of Energy Engineers\n\n	Local:\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design– Existing Building Platinum certification, Adobe West Tower corporate headquarters, USGBC\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 First place award for Landscape Maintenance, Medium Commercial Maintenance Category, California Landscaping Contractors Association, San Francisco Bay Area Chapter\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Green Business of the Year, Santa Clara League of Conservation Voters\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Preservation Design Award in recognition of Outstanding Achievement in the Field of Historic Preservation for the Rehabilitation of the Baker and Hamilton Building in San Francisco, California Preservation Foundation\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2005 Best Overall, Comprehensive Energy Management, State of California, Flex Your Power\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Commendations for Green Business status, City of San Jose\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Green Building of the Year for Corporate Headquarters and International Earth Awards Silicon Valley Chapter, Building Owners and Managers Association\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2004 Building of the Year for Corporate Headquarters Buildings for Silicon Valley, BOMA Western Region\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Green Building Certification, Santa Clara County\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 Certified Green Business, Association of Bay Area Governments\n\n	Rankings\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012, 2011, 2010 World''s most ethical companies by Ethisphere – link\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Number 14 in 2011 and 2012 Newsweek Green rankings among US companies (Link 2012 – link2011) http://ethisphere.com/wme/\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 Number 20 on the Goodness 500 list in the area of Corporate Social Responsibility for donations, equality, and the environment – link\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 Ranked &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; number 20 on the Corporate Social Responsibility Index of the top 50 Socially Responsible Companies in the United States by the Boston College Center for Corporate Citizenship and Reputation Institute – link\n\n	Index\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Leadership Index S&amp;P 500, years 2011 (score 73) and 2012&nbsp; (score 93) - Link\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Project - http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html\n\n	Sustainable Activities\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Total of 10 LEED certified buildings\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Increase of about 4% since 2008\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Jose building matched the highest score from the United States Green Building Council in 2010\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012 CSR Report says that 45% of all Adobe buildings are LEED certified and 43% are Platinum certified\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; First to achieve 3 Platinum-Level Certifications for Energy and Environmental Design Excellence\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Retrofitting Adobe Offices with energy-efficient equipment and installing monitors that instantly meter power usage at all our sites around the globe\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; All janitorial products satisfy the American Society for Testing and Materials Cleaning Stewardship for Community Building Standards and meet the Green Seal Cleaning Products Standards &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Jose Location\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Waterless Urinals\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Garage Exhaust Fan\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Real-time electric meters\n\n	Water\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Per the 2012 CSR report, the San Jose Office reduced their domestic water use by 53% and irrigation water was reduced by 93%\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Francisco Location was able to reduce water by 48%\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Overall increase in water recycling\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reducing hours fountains on site are running\n\n	Energy\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wind turbines and Bloom energy fuel cells in California to power their offices and receive renewable energy credits\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bloom Boxes inexpensively convert natural, bio-gas into electricity and Adobe plans to reduce their carbon footprint by 121.5 million pounds over the\n	next ten years\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Verifiable emissions reduction credits from their use of Windspire wind turbines and biogas plants\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Jose Office has also installed IBIS smart floor technology, enabling a 35% reduction in energy use compared to other floors.\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From 2001 to 2010, the San Jose location was able to reduce their electricity by 27% and their natural gas by 16%\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The San Francisco office reduced electricity by 26% and natural gas by 29%\n\n	Materials\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal to increase the amount of digital downloads to decrease the need for packaging\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Goal to reduce the amount of packaging per unit that is sold in stores\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Have a greater influence on the manufacturing process, agreements with third parties in order to increase material efficiency\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Lean Print Software optimizes document layouts and manages toner output to reduce resource consumption\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; From 2008 to 2010, 5% decrease in the amount of software sold as hard goods and 5% increase in the amount sold electronically\n\n	Waste reduction:\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012 CSR report 98% of garbage was diverted from the landfill through recycling and composting\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; San Francisco diverted about 95% to be recycled\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe has agreements with their distributors to recycle\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In their offices in California, Adobe has switched paper dining and kitchen products to ones that are biodegradable\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kitchen grease is recycled and composting is a significant component in the kitchens\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The city of San Jose contributed to this effort when they switched to mixed recycling\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe calculates that their work to recycle saves about $198,000 in landfill fees after equipping office spaces with the appropriate supplies to effectively recycle\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Posters are located in break rooms to educate employees on their efforts so that everyone can benefit further from what is being done\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Accounts for e-waste and monitors it\n\n	Air Quality/Transportation\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012 CSR Report total business miles travelled per year increased to 79.3 million miles from about 48.8 million miles\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Purchased enough credits to offset all scope 1 and 2 emissions\n\n	Partnerships\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Electronics Industry Citizenship Coalition since 2006\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; UN Global Compact Ten Principles\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Follows the Code of Conduct and works with their suppliers to meet these standards and has begun using a Green Product Purchasing Policy. Adobe''s Supply Chains Operations Team participates in EICC working groups to continuously refine the codes.\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2006 exhibit in San Jose Tech Museum to teach about\n	environmental technology\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010 SIMS Recycling partnership to develop processes to recycle and dispose of technology-related software, ewaste\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cushman and Wakefield facilities management for world-scale energy monitoring and control\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PG&amp;E Energy Efficiency Programs\n\n	Sustainability Related Services\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Use of Adobe® Acrobat® and LiveCycle® software for electronic document exchange and electronic workflows helps companies cut paper use and significantly increase efficiencies\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe Connect™ software is used by companies and individuals to host live and interactive web meetings, virtual classes, and on-demand presentations. Adobe also makes an internal use this product\n\n	Governance\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Information available about Adobe''s sustainability efforts can be found in the Corporate Social Responsibility reports\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reports linked to the Carbon Disclosure Project\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Environmental Sustainability Council consisting of employees and experts that are representatives in areas such as facilities, operations, the supply chain,\n	and IT\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Report back to the CSR department to contribute to the overall sustainability goals of Adobe\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Green Team of employees began in 2008 and is used to educate and empower employees\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Organization of events throughout the month of April 2012 to celebrate Earth Day and sustainable lifestyles &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Opportunities for employees to learn about solar power and receive a discount on solar panels\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Developing an employee-run garden\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adobe plans to expand its Green Team to all 12 major\n	sites by 2015\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; “Create change” in the business, new software and pressing\n	environmental issues\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Achieve net zero energy consumption by 2015 in their owned facilities in\n	the United States\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reduce the amount of packaging used per unit by 40% by 2012 and 80%\n	by 2015\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Expand their employee-led green team to all of their 12 major sites by 2015\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ensure that third parties are sustainably minded\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Work on reducing emissions from travel of employees\n\n	Best Practices/Success Drivers\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Green Team driving employees\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Technology allowing Adobe to cut down on emissions\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Management of waste on site\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED certification at multiple locations\n\n	Proposed Case Studies Demonstrating Best Practices\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; IBIS Smartfloor Technology– link\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; LEED &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Certification– link\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Material Waste Management– link\n\n	Researched and Prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources\n\n	http://www.adobe.com/careers/awards.html\n\n	http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf\n\n	http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf\n\n	http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-platinum-certification.pdf\n\n	http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-facilities.html\n\n	http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-emissions.html\n\n	http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/environment-waste-management.html\n\n	http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/awards.html\n\n	http://www.adobe.com/corporate-responsibility/product-resource-reduction.html\n\n	http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/adobe-csr-brief-env-sust.pdf\n\n	http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/2011-adobe-csr-data-summary.pdf\n\n	http://wwwimages.adobe.com/www.adobe.com/content/dam/Adobe/en/corporate-responsibility/pdfs/2009-csr-summary.pdf\n\n	http://www.thedailybeast.com/topics/green-rankings.html\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '151', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/adobe', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/151', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/151');
