(954, 'HP', ' \n	\n	Hewlett Packard’s Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Hewlett Packard is an American, multinational information technology corporation.&nbsp; The company is composed of 349,600 employees worldwide and has six main office sites.&nbsp; Its sustainability efforts are compiled in their “Global Citizenship Report” that includes their GRI index and UN Compact report.&nbsp;\n\n	HP’s path to sustainability began in 1957, shortly after the company was founded.&nbsp; In the set of corporate objectives designed by the founders, the fifth objective, Citizenship, is defined as “meeting the obligations of good citizenship by making contributions to the community and to the institutions in our society which generate the environment in which we operate”.&nbsp; In 1970, HP named Glen Affleck to occupy the newly created position of environment control coordinator.&nbsp; HP has continued since to establish new positions and groups to help them achieve their sustainability and environmental goals.\n\n	Awards, Frameworks, and Accomplishments\n\n	Awards\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; GREENBEST Award 2012 – HP Brazil (May 2011, 2012)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Environmental Business Ripple Award – HP Fort Collins Area Chamber of Commerce (February 2012)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Greenpeace Guide to Greener Electronics (November 2011)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Top Green IT-Vendors (November 2010, 2011)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Mediacorp Canada – HP recognized as one of Canada’s Greenest Employers (2011)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP named one of China’s 50 Green Companies\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Low Carbon Champion 2010 – HP China (August 2010)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Green Enterprise IT Award 2010 – HP UK (May 2010)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PrintAction Magazine\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Gold Award for Carbon Footprint Calculator for Printing tool and Most Environmentally Progressive Technology Supplier in Canada. (April 2010)\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Bronze Award for its HP Designjet L25500 Printer Series technology (April 2010)\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Gold Award in the category of Environmental Community Involvement for partnership with Learning for a Sustainable Future (February 2008)\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Silver Award for Most Environmentally Progressive Vendor (February 2007)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Waste Reduction Awards Program (WRAP) (December 2006, 2009)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; AMR Research names HP for Sustainability and Innovation Award (May 2009)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Corporate Knights and Innovest – HP is on the Global 100 Most Sustainable Corporations in the World\n\n	Listings/Index\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon Disclosure Project’s Listing S&amp;P 500 2012 (score 92) and 2011 (score 84)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; FTSE4Good Index (May 2006, 2012)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dow Jones Sustainability Index – Computer Hardware and Electronic Office Equipment (September 2006, 2010)\n\n	Rankings\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; NEWSWEEK Green Rankings (October 2008 – 2012), #2 among US companies in 2012; #22 in the 2012 global ranking\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 50 Best Global Green Brands – Ranked first among technology companies and placed fifth overall (June 2011, 2012)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Climate Counts Company Scorecard – HP ranked #1 in electronics sector (December 2009, 2011)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Corporate Responsibility Magazine - #1 Best Corporate Citizens in Government Contracting (October 2010)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Corporate Responsibility Officer (CRO) – HP ranked #5 on CRO’s Best Corporate Citizens for 2009 (February 2009)\n\n	Frameworks\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Global Reporting Initiative\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Grade: B (self-reported)\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Using: 2001 - Present\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Third Party Certification: Bureau Veritas Certification, Environmental Resources Mangement (ERM), BSI Management Systems\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; UN Global Compact\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Joined: 2002\n\n	Sustainable Actions\n\n	Biodiversity/Site \n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP builds relatively few facilities relative to their size and growth and often uses previously developed land if they do expand\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Member of World Wildlife Fund’s Global Forest and Trade Network\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Where needed HP contributes to soil and groundwater remediation to clean up contaminated sites\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 18 sites where chemical releases from historical HP operations occurred\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 6 sites where HP’s wastes were managed by third parties and releases occurred\n\n	Water \n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2011, HP used just over 8 billion liters of water worldwide, predominantly for domestic use in buildings, cooling, and landscape irrigation. This represents a 1.4% decrease compared with 2010\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;HP plans to introduce 35 water-saving measures in 10 countries by 2015. Examples include flow restrictors, waterless urinals, and rainwater harvesting. They expect these measures to reduce freshwater use across those sites by 77.7 million liters, equivalent to 3% of 2011 consumption at those locations\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In 2011, their seven imaging and printing product-manufacturing facilities generated 1.296 billion liters of manufacturing wastewater. These effluents are discharged under a permit, and treated at a locally owned and operated treatment plant\n\n	Energy\n\n	Energy Efficiency of products and operations:\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thanks to energy-efficient products, HP saved customers 1.4 billion kWh through 2010\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP achieved a 50% reduction in energy consumption for all products by the end of 2011, and improved the energy efficiency of HP ink and laser printing products by 46% relative to 2005\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP operations consumed 4,122 million kilowatt hours (kWh) of energy in 2011, a small decrease from 4,140 million kWh in 2010. However, there was a 11% decrease in natural gas use and a 1% increase in electricity use in comparison to 2010\n\n	Use of renewable Energy\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Their award-winning Wynyard trade data center in the United Kingdom, which opened in January 2010, is 100% powered by renewable energy\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP purchased approximately 440 million kilowatt hours (kWh) of renewable energy worldwide in 2011, equivalent to more than 10% of the overall electricity use in their facilities and a 41% increase since 2010. This includes energy generated on-site and the renewable energy credits (RECs) they buy as part of electricity contracts in the United States. This is in addition to the renewable energy available by default in the power grid, and achieves their goal for 20121 ahead of time\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP installed more than 1,400 roof-top solar panels at their data center in Suwanee, Georgia, United States, which they estimate will generate approximately 450,000 kWh per year, enough to power the center’s noncritical facilities\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They estimate that the nearly 500 solar panels they installed at their facilities in Bad Homburg and Boblingen, Germany will generate approximately 170,000kWh of electricity per year\n\n	Materials\n\n	Working to increase both the percentage of post-consumer recycled fiber in HP-branded paper and use of pulp that is certified as sustainable by the Forest Stewardship Council. (Became FSC member in 2011)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Source paper from suppliers that demonstrate sustainable forestry and responsible manufacturing practices. Over 40% of HP branded paper is Forest Stewardship Council certified or has at least 30% post-consumer waste content by the end of 2011\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Environmentally Preferable Paper Policy sets out standards for buying, selling, and using paper and paper-based packaging\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Achieved 35% minimum recycled content for corrugate, globally\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Achieved 80% minimum recycled content for paperboard, globally\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Recycled plastic used in Original HP ink cartridges has up to a 33% smaller carbon footprint\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Achieved 67% of its goal to phase out BFR and PVC in newly introduced personal computing products in 2011\n\n	Waste and global recycling program\n\n	●&nbsp; In 2011, HP generated approximately 93,800 tons of waste. The vast majority, 92%, was nonhazardous consisting of solid waste\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;They recycle 82.2% of nonhazardous waste and aim to minimize the amount sent to landfill.\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;HP generated approximately 7,400 tons of hazardous waste in 2011, a 12% decrease compared with 2010\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Planet Partner Program, 1991\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; HP collects, sorts, and disassembles ink cartridges.&nbsp; Recovered plastic, metals, and other materials are recycled for reuse. Now serves 46 countries.\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Overall HP’s production of recycled plastic for use in manufacturing of HP ink cartridges had a lower environmental impact than producing virgin plastic. (Climate Change, Water Use, Fossil Fuel Depletion)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon footprint was up to 33% smaller\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Water use was up to 89% lower\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fossil fuel depletion was up to 62% lower using\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Total energy used for producing recycled plastic was 60% lower than virgin plastic\n\n	Transportation/Air Quality\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;In 2011 HP joined the Clinton Global Initiative’s Fleets for Change and committed to reduce GHG emissions from their U.S. auto fleet by 10% by 2015, compared with 2010 on a per unit basis\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;HP also launched an initiative in 2011 with Avis to reduce their U.S. rental car fuel consumption and related GHG emissions, with a targeted decrease of 15% per day driven by 2012, compared with 2011\n\n	●&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;In the United States, HP enables employees to take advantage of WageWorks and use pretax income to pay for public transport costs. They also encourage carpooling options, for example through a partnership with rideshare.org in the San Francisco Bay Area\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP products are designed and tested to reduce impact on indoor air quality\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 20% reduction in GHG emissions from operations between 2005 and 2011(not including employee travel)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 2011 they fully met and concluded their commitment under the US EPA – Semiconductor Industry Association PFC Emission Reduction Partnership.&nbsp; They had successfully cut their PFC related GHG emissions by 87$ since 1995.\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; They report their GHG emissions yearly through the Carbon Disclosure Project (CDP). In 2011 they were included in the CDP’s S&amp;P 500 Carbon Disclosure Leadership Index, and were still in the 2012 list\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Achieved reduction of 138,000 tons of carbon dioxide through various transportation projects in 2011\n\n	Partnerships \n\n	●&nbsp; BSR\n\n	●&nbsp; Center for Climate and Energy Solutions\n\n	●&nbsp; Center for Corporate Citizenship at Boston College\n\n	●&nbsp; The Climate Group\n\n	●&nbsp; Climate Savers Computing Initiative (CSCI)\n\n	●&nbsp; Clinton Global Initiative (CGI)\n\n	●&nbsp; Combat Climate Change (3C)\n\n	●&nbsp; Corporate Eco Forum\n\n	●&nbsp; CSR Asia\n\n	●&nbsp; CSR Europe\n\n	●&nbsp; Dutch Sustainable Trade Initative\n\n	●&nbsp; Electronic Industry Citizenship Coalition\n\n	●&nbsp; EPEAT\n\n	●&nbsp; Ethos Institute for Business and Social Responsibility\n\n	●&nbsp; European Recycling Platform (ERP)\n\n	●&nbsp; Forest Stewardship Council (FSC)\n\n	●&nbsp; Global Business Initiative on Human Rights (GBI)\n\n	●&nbsp; Global e-Sustainability Initiative (GeSI)\n\n	●&nbsp; Global Forest Trade Network (GFTN)\n\n	●&nbsp; Global Social Compliance Program\n\n	●&nbsp; The Green Grid Association\n\n	●&nbsp; International Climate Change Partnership (ICCP)\n\n	●&nbsp; National Association for Environmental Management (NAEM)\n\n	●&nbsp; The Sustainability Consortium\n\n	●&nbsp; Sustainable Silicon Valley (SSV)\n\n	●&nbsp; United Nations Global Compact\n\n	●&nbsp; U.S. Green Building Council\n\n	●&nbsp; World Resources Forum\n\n	●&nbsp; WWF Climate Savers\n\n	Sustainability Related Services\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Energy and Sustainability Discovery Workshop\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Energy and Sustainability Baselining Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Energy and Sustainability Roadmap Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Buildings Energy Efficiency Analysis Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Buildings Water Usage Analysis Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Critical Facility Sustainability Tradeoff Analysis Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Critical Facilities Energy Certification Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP IT Carbon Emissions Management Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Energy and Carbon Reporting Service\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; HP Resource Usage Monitoring Service\n\n	Sustainability in Management/Governance \n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2009: Created the HP Global Citizenship Council that retains overall responsibility for global citizenship as part of their business strategy.&nbsp; It meets at least quarterly to strategically promote and advance global citizenship through integrated risk and opportunity assessment, governance, and policy oversight.&nbsp;\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The council is composed of executives and subject matter experts from across HP and seeks input from other business groups and functions and external stakeholders.\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Councils, Committees, and Expert Advisors: Ethics and Compliance, Environmental Sustainability, Human Rights and Safety and Labor Practices, Privacy and Information Management, Supply Chain social and environmental sustainability and compliance, and Social Innovation.\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2010: HP formed the Executive Environmental Advisory Council, compromised of a group of high-profile business leaders who bring their unique perspective and insight on various aspects of the rapidly evolving field of environmental sustainability to the world’s largest IT company. Each council member has a minimum two year commitment and the council convenes in person every six months with virtual meetings in between.\n\n	Future Environmental Goals\n\n	To continue their positive impact HP desires to increase the efficiency of their portfolio, supply chain, and operations.&nbsp; They strive to create HP technology that will improve or replace current energy and resource intensive processes with more efficient alternatives.\n\n	Products and Solutions:\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Products and solutions:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Calculate and disclose product carbon footprint values using the Product Attribute to Impact Algorithm (PAIA), created in 2011, tool for new HP notebook, desktop, and monitor products\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Complete life cycle assessments on 20 additional HP LaserJet Printers, one HP scanner, and one book vs. e-reader\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Work with competitors to establish product category rules for printers\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Materials:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Complete the phase-out of bis (2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP), dibutyl phthalate (DBP), and butyl benzyl phthalate (BBP) in newly introduced personal computing products by the end of 2012\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2015: 50% or more of the HP-Branded paper will be FSC-certified or have at least 30% post-consumer waste content by end of 2015\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2015: Recycle 3.5 billions pounds of electric products and supplies by the end of 2015\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2015: Reuse 40 million electronic product and accessory units by the end of 2015 (since 2003)\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Supplier relationships:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Continue to promote supplier transparency in environmental performance and carbon emissions reduction by collecting carbon emissions data from suppliers representing 95% of first-tier manufacturing, material, and component supplier spend\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Facilitate supplier environmental performance improvements by tripling the number of HP supplier sites participating in the Energy Efficiency Partnership program compared with 2011 and sharing energy-saving best practices developed through the program to date\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Transportation/Air quality:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2013: Implement network enhancements, mode changes, and route optimization that decrease greenhouse gas emissions from product transport by 180,000 tonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2e) since 2008\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Progress: 138,000 tones by 2011\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2015: Reduce GHG emissions from HP’s U.S. auto fleet by 10% on a per unit basis, compared with 2010\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Energy:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Worldwide, new 2012 HP LaserJet and inkjet printers will use 13% less electricity annually than 2011 HP LaserJet and inkjet printers.\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Water:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2015: Reduce freshwater use at sites identified as water-stressed by 3%, compared with 2011 consumption at these locations.\n\n	Best Practices/Success Drivers\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; In 1991 HP began Planet Partners, a worldwide program to provide their customers with a free and convenient way to recycle their empty Original HP ink and LaserJet print cartridges. Beginning in 2005, HP began to use the collected PET plastic from this\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Program to manufacture new HP Original ink cartridges, resulting in a “closed loop” recycling program.\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Carbon footprint using recycled plastic was up to 33% smaller\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Waster use was up to 89% lower\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; Fossil Fuel Depletion was up to 62% lower using recycled plastic\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Case Study Planet Partners: http://h20195.www2.hp.com/v2/GetPDF.aspx/4AA3-1856ENUC.pdf\n\n	●&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Already met their energy goals for 2012 and 2013:\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2012: Double voluntary purchases of renewable energy to 8% of electricity use (in addition to renewable energy available by default in the power grid). GOAL MET.\n\n	○&nbsp;&nbsp; 2013: Reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions from HP-owned and HP-leased facilities by 20% relative to 2005 levels by the end of 2013 on an absolute basis. GOAL MET.\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	Researched and prepared by Natasha Patel for Sustainable Silicon Valley\n\n	Sources\n\n	http://h20195.www2.hp.com/v2/GetPDF.aspx/4AA3-1856ENUC.pdf\n\n	http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/newsroom/press_kits/environment/awards.html\n\n	http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/globalcitizenship/awards.html\n\n	http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/globalcitizenship/09gcreport/commitment/governance.html\n\n	http://www.hp.com/hpinfo/globalcitizenship/environment/executive_environmental_advisory_council.html\n\n	http://www8.hp.com/us/en/hp-information/facts.html\n\n	http://www8.hp.com/us/en/contact-hp/office-locations.html#2\n\n	http://www8.hp.com/us/en/business-solutions/solution.html?compURI=1079744#.UBgnmI4fkXc\n\n	http://h71028.www7.hp.com/enterprise/downloads/HP%20Photo%20Center%205%20Premier.pdf\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '152', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/hp', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/152', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/152'),
(955, 'Google', ' \n	Google Sustainability Review\n\n	November 2012\n\n	Introduction\n\n	Google is the creator of a popular link-based search engine and has also expanded into the arena of tech-based gadgets including tablets and mobile operating systems. The company has 34,111 employees as of Quarter 2 in 2012 and 70 offices in 40 countries. The company was created by two Stanford students in 2005 and strives to make the search process both smarter and faster to enhance consumer’s web experience, and to design internet tools helpful to businesses.&nbsp;\n\n	Sustainable Actions\n\n	Biodiversity/Site\n\n	Food-related actions:\n\n	\n		Google orders the food for their campuses from local sources that are within 200 miles of their offices\n		\n			\n				Purchase poultry and produce from small farms and work to educate rising farmers on how to grow their foods organically\n		\n	\n	\n		Community Supported Agriculture (CSA) program allows Google employees to buy fresh, seasonal produce that is delivered directly to a Google campus\n	\n		Google purchases coffee from four local roasters all of whom buy from Fair Trade certified growers\n	\n		Google Green Seafood program helps ensure that the company purchases species caught locally and through independently managed fisheries that use environmentally responsible catch practices\n	\n		Many campuses have edible gardens that allow employees to grow herbs for their own cooking\n	\n		20% of food waste from their cafes is recycled and in Europe, the Middle East, and Africa it is recycled to produce bio-diesel or electricity\n		\n			\n				The rest of the waste is composted\n		\n	\n\n\n	Waste reduction activities:\n\n	\n		Google recycles 100% of the electronic equipment that leaves their data centers\n	\n		Data Driven Purchasing: Google analyzes what is popular in their cafes and determines the amount of each ingredient to buy accordingly. This helps eliminate waste and provide a nice diverse variety of food at each meal\n	\n		Using Real Dishes and Silverware: In Cafes employees use non-disposable dishes and silverware.&nbsp; There are micro-kitchens throughout the campuses that provide a location for employees to drop off their dishes if they chose to eat in their office space\n	\n		Composting and Recycling: Throughout the campus there are marked recycling and compost bins and the to-go containers and utensils that are provided by Google are compostable as well\n	\n		Donating Unused Food: Any untouched, edible, and leftover food goes to local shelters in Google’s communities\n\n\n	Buildings construction and management:\n\n	\n		Only use building materials that have the lowest levels of VOCs and formaldehyde possible. Exclude any materials that contain mercury and lead\n		\n			\n				Require vendors to be transparent about their product ingredient information at every point in the supply chain\n			\n				In North America, require that vendors share their information through the Pharos Project, an open source materials evaluation system. This allows all other Pharos members to be informed on product choices&nbsp;\n		\n	\n	\n		Purchase EnergyStar-rated (or overseas equivalent) office equipment and use sophisticated building control technologies to ensure systems are only on when needed\n	\n		Use LEED certification program and Living Building Challenge as well as their own program creation of “Sustainable Pursuit” (based on LEED framework and popular board game, Trivial Pursuit) to guide their building performance\n	\n		Have 14 LEED certified projects and more in the works as well as one Green Start certification (Australia’s LEED equivalent).&nbsp; The SF office has made the HVAC system more efficient and this helped the office achieve the LEED Gold certification.\n		\n			\n				Received City of Mountain View’s first ever LEED platinum certification and first published LEED project certification for commercial interiors in Argentina\n		\n	\n	\n		Cradle to Cradle carpet usage: carpet Google uses is sent back to manufacturer where it is used in the supply stream so it does not end up in landfill\n\n\n	Sustainability Related Services\n\n	\n		To conduct a single search on Google their servers use about 1kJ of energy, resulting in the emission of 0.2g of CO2.&nbsp; To put this into context, 100 searches on Google have about the same carbon footprint as one hour on a laptop (assuming it’s a 30W laptop)\n	\n		One minute of streaming on YouTube emits 0.11g of carbon dioxide.&nbsp; To put this into context, the footprint of a DVD (manufactured, packaged, and delivered) has about the equivalent footprint of 72 hours on YouTube (assume footprint of DVD is 3kg CO2)\n	\n		The carbon impact of using Gmail for a year is about 1.2 kg CO2.&nbsp; To put this into context, drinking a 750 ml bottle of wine and then placing a note in it and tossing it into the ocean emits more carbon than using Gmail for a year (assumes the carbon footprint of wine is about 2 kg CO2 per liter)\n\n\n	Water\n\n	\n		Use recycled municipal wastewater for applications such as toilet flushing and landscape watering\n	\n		In Hyderabad, India and Sydney, Australia water recycling programs are implemented.&nbsp; In India, about 380,000 gallons of waste water are treated and reused annually in non-potable systems\n\n\n	Energy\n\n	In 2007, Google committed to being carbon neutral\n\n	\n		Purchase high-quality carbon offsets (entire operation is in-house)\n		\n			\n				Landfill gas capture: capture and destroy methane gas released from decomposing waste\n			\n				Agricultural methane capture: capture methane gas that is produced at farms from decomposing animal wastes and process it into usable products\n			\n				Forestry projects: Prevent the destruction of existing forests and develop new ones\n			\n				Reduce emissions from their operations\n				\n					\n						Brought the facility (data centers) overhead energy usage down from 1.4 to 0.5 per watt of IT computer energy\n					\n						In Zurich, Switzerland, a chilled beam heating, ventilation and cooling (HVAC) system uses significantly less energy to regulate building temperature while also occupying less space than conventional equipment\n				\n			\n			\n				Purchase renewable energy to power their operations\n				\n					\n						Power Purchase Agreements: Long-term, large-scale contracts to buy energy from renewable sources energy production site. The aim is to drive down the cost of clean power. 30% of energy used by Google is from renewable sources\n				\n			\n			\n				All carbon offset projects are third-party verified\n		\n	\n	\n		Total capacity of all Google’s renewable energy project investments is over 1.7GW.&nbsp; They are expected to generate 4.5 billion kWh annually – far more electricity than Google consumes\n	\n		Solar Power production in Mountain view: Google has installed 9,200 solar panels over its corporate headquarters in the last year. 1.7MW solar installation supplies approximately 30% of their peak energy consumption on the buildings it covers and Google has implemented a building management system that monitors and controls campus-wide energy use &nbsp;\n	\n		Set aside $10 million for a program to speed development of plug-in electric cars and $20 million for wind and solar companies (through Google.org)\n	\n		Google data centers use a very small portion of global energy, Stanford consulting professor Jonathan Koomey estimates that the data centers use between 1.1% and 1.5% of global electricity\n		\n			\n				Added temperature monitoring, optimized air vent tiles, increased temperature and humidity settings on CRAC’s, blocked off the ends of cold aisles with curtains, added 48” extensions to all CRAC air returns, added a new CRAC controller, and put blanking plates and side panels to block cold air passing through empty rack spaces.\n		\n	\n\n\n	Transportation\n\n	\n		Google has built a green transportation system composed of biodiesel shuttles and the largest corporate electric vehicle-charging infrastructure in the country\n		\n			\n				About 4500 Google employees who commute to the SF Bay Area office use the shuttle\n			\n				Shuttles include wifi\n			\n				Google is the first company with a corporate coach fleet to exceed the EPA’s 2010 bus emission standards; the fleet runs on 5% biodiesel and has filtration systems that eliminate many harmful emissions such as nitrogen oxide\n			\n				The biodiesel shuttles and GFleet result in a net annual savings of more than 5400 metric tons of CO2\n		\n	\n	\n		Google created a car-sharing program for the Google employees who commute to work called GFleet that also includes plug-in vehicles\n	\n		The GFleet is composed of Chevrolet Volts, Nissan LEAFs, Misubishi iMiEVs, Ford Focus Electrics, Ford Transit Connect Electrics, and a Honda Fit EV\n	\n		Google donates to an employee’s favorites charities based on how often they walk or bike to work. Each time an employee does so they receive a digital stamp that eventually translates to dollars that Google donates to the charity of the employee’s choosing. An employee can donate up to $140 a quarter and in 2011, 2000 employees took advantage of this opportunity\n\n\n	Partnerships Around Sustainability\n\n	\n		Google has collaboration with Coulumb Technologies to build the largest corporate EV charging infrastructure in the United States.&nbsp; They have over 400 vehicle chargers and the latest fast charging level 2 chargers\n	\n		Google has invested in:\n		\n			\n				Recurrent Energy: large scale photovoltaic projects in California\n			\n				Clean Power Finance: financing for rooftop solar\n			\n				SolarCity: solar for thousands of residential rooftops\n			\n				Brightsource: concentrated solar power at scale\n			\n				Atlantic Wind Connection: a superhighway for clean energy transmission\n			\n				Alta Wind Energy Center: harnessing winds of the Mojave\n			\n				Shepard’s Flat: one of the world’s largest wind farms\n			\n				Peace Garden Wind Farms: opening up more financing for wind\n			\n				Photovoltaics in Germany: investing in clean energy overseas\n		\n	\n\n\n	Sustainability Governance\n\n	\n		Google’s management team oversees the Company’s best interests and makes sure that sustainability in strongly implemented\n\n\n	The management team consists of:\n\n	\n		Executive Officers (6 members)\n	\n		Senior Leadership (15 members)\n	\n		Board of Directors (10 members). The Board of Directors establishes Corporate Governance guidelines to provide effective objectives for the business and stockholders. Under the Board of Directors,\n		\n			\n				The Leadership Development and Compensation Committee was established to oversee Google’s compensation programs, supports business objectives and incorporates the corporate governance principles\n		\n	\n\n\n	\n		Google believes that the Business Operations and Corporate Development team is at the heart of their business strategies. Under the Business Operations and Corporate Development team,\n		\n			\n				The Energy and Sustainability Team strives to make Google a leader in sustainability and clean energy by focusing on the Company’s operations system. The Energy and Sustainability Team implements sustainability by creating innovative technologies, and developing the best business practices\n		\n	\n	\n		Google’s Chief Sustainability Officer works closely with the Executive Officers to insure that the company focuses on the environmental aspect and reduction in energy costs. The Chief Sustainability Officer and the team focuses on the environmental impacts from Google, “greening offices” such as in “energy efficiency, sustainable design, healthy interiors, and on greening the electricity coming from their offices.”\n		\n			\n				Google has Real Estate &amp; Workplace Services Green Teams\n		\n	\n\n\n	Challenges and Future Goals\n\n	\n		Goal: Eliminate 100% of known toxins from Google’s buildings\n	\n		Goal: Pledged fifty megawatts of renewable energy by 2012\n	\n		Challenge: How to feasibly use only renewable energy for their data centers? Electric grid is currently the most feasible method for their needs\n\n\n	Best Practices/Success Drivers\n\n	\n		GFleet\n	\n		Data Driven Purchasing to reduce food waste\n	\n		Local engagement: purchase of local produce and work with farmers toward organic agriculture\n	\n		In North America, require their vendors to use Pharos Project, an open source materials evaluation system. This allows all other Pharos members to be informed on product choices\n	\n		Green Data Centers (lower temperature, new architecture, recycling of servers)\n\n\n	Researched and prepared by Caroline Nowacki and Natasha Patel\n\n	References\n\n	http://www.divinecaroline.com/22277/44799-meet-google-s-chief-sustainability-officer#ixzz21g3Q9PLt\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/#/datacenters/infographics\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/#/intro/infographics-1\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/bigpicture/references.html\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/energy/investments/\n\n	http://www.google.com/about/company/products/\n\n	http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/food-for-green-thought.html\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/efficiency/oncampus/#eating\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/efficiency/oncampus/#commuting\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/efficiency/oncampus/#building\n\n	http://static.googleusercontent.com/external_content/untrusted_dlcp/www.google.com/en/us/green/pdfs/google-carbon-offsets.pdf\n\n	http://static.googleusercontent.com/external_content/untrusted_dlcp/www.google.com/en/us/green/pdfs/renewable-energy.pdf\n\n	http://static.googleusercontent.com/external_content/untrusted_dlcp/www.google.com/en/us/corporate/datacenter/dc-best-practices-google.pdf\n\n	http://www.google.com/green/energy/\n\n	http://www.google.com/about/company/facts/management/#section-board\n\n	http://investor.google.com/corporate/board-committees.html\n\n	http://www.google.com/about/jobs/teams/business-strategy/\n\n	http://investor.google.com/corporate/board-committees-leadership.html\n\n	http://www.divinecaroline.com/32/44799-meet-google-s-chief-sustainability-officer\n\n	http://www.trilliuminvest.com/news-articles-category/advocacy-news-articles/the-importance-of-being-google%E2%80%99s-sustainability-report/\n\n	http://static.googleusercontent.com/external_content/untrusted_dlcp/www.google.com/en/us/green/pdfs/renewable-energy.pdf (Google’s Report on Green Computing)\n\n	&nbsp;\n\n	&nbsp;\n', NULL, NULL, 'pages', 'pages:page', 'pages:pages', '153', NULL, 'topics/systemic/compare-companies/google', 'admin/custom_pages/edit/153', 'admin/custom_pages/delete/153'),
